<HEADLINE>
LAKERS STILL IN SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The Lakers are seven weeks into Project Triangle,
but if the results on the floor still look a little less than
geometrical, there's good reason for it. Masked behind a surprising
8-4 record is a team still learning on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say we're at the fetus stage,'' guard Derek Fisher
said after practice Tuesday at the Forum. ``We've been going over
some things today, and even some of the things we've gone over a
number of times, we're still having a hard time being able to do in
a game-type setting, where it's intense and it's fierce, being able
to recall all these things mentally. That's why I would still say
we're in the very early stages of trying to get this thing down.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson has given the Lakers the basic form of the
triangle offense to run, but there are dozens and dozens of
variations he has yet to introduce. Fisher said the Lakers already
have all they can handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a plethora of things I know their champing at the
bit to throw in there, but they're scared it will blow us up
mentally,'' Fisher said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the basics, the Lakers too often are thinking through
the offense, rather than simply reacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's quite a bit of thinking going on,'' Fisher
said. ``Our coaches are doing the best job they can do of letting
us know to go out there and just play basketball, and this offense
is only a format to play within. . . . It's on us as players to
just continue to learn. And until you get down what you need to get
down, you can't start to become creative with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means the new offense often looks like the old one _ come
up the floor, throw the ball in to Shaquille O'Neal in the low
post, then cut and move and wait for O'Neal to pass or shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows some of our limitations mentally that we aren't ready
to go out there and play the game in a creative type of way,''
Fisher said. ``And it also kind of shows how far we have to go. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it will be the latter part of the season, where we
aren't even thinking about what's going on out there. That's when
the offense is most effective, when you just run down the court and
flow. It's almost like you don't even recognize that there's a
triangle being set up. Right now we run down and everybody's like,
`OK, I have to get over here and then this guy's got to get there
and now we're OK.' We're looking to see if a triangle is formed. We
have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the winning percentage looks comfortable, Fisher
insisted: ``There's really no level of comfort. We haven't played
well. We've won games, but that's because we have Shaquille O'Neal
and we have Glen Rice, we have Rick (Fox). We've got guys that can
play games. We've been lucky for the most part. . . . We want to be
the best, and right now we aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding pattern: Jackson has hinted at changes to the starting
lineup but said he's unlikely to make any change for tonight's game
against the Utah Jazz. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
