<HEADLINE>
GUN ATTACK AT SCHOOL IS THWARTED  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM WALSH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - In a case eerily reminiscent of the Columbine High
School massacre in Colorado, Phoenix police have thwarted what they
say was a plot by Moon Valley High School students to kill their
enemies during lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   An early-morning tip to police on Oct. 12 led to the arrests of
Christopher Michael Ciulla, and Matthew David Russ, both 16, on
charges of conspiracy to commit first-degree murder, said Sgt. Jeff
Halstead, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   When police confronted the teenagers on a northwest Phoenix
street, they found a backpack that contained a weapon, along with a
detailed map of a nearby house the students planned to burglarize
to obtain guns, Halstead said. The attack at the school was planned
for later that day during the first lunch period, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had missed them, they would have got the guns and been
on their way to school'' to carry out the shootings, Halstead said.
</P>
<P>
   Ciulla was spending the night at Russ' home when the tip came
in, Halstead said, and the suspects were arrested later that
morning a few blocks from Russ' home by officers who had them under
surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kaiser, an attorney for Russ, said that his client did
not realize he was carrying a .22-caliber handgun in his backpack
and that Ciulla had access to the backpack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our opinion that he (Russ) prevented this tragedy from
happening,'' Kaiser said. ``He prevented Chris from moving forward
with these alleged crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ does not have a criminal record, Kaiser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're behind our son 100 percent,'' said James Russ, Matthew's
father. ``We believe him. He's always told me the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   James Russ said Ciulla was a runaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had been sleeping at various houses,'' the father said.
``The first time I saw Chris was that morning.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the gun, James Russ said, police found a mask and
a set of gloves in Matthew's backpack. If both teenagers were going
to carry out the killings, he said, then why weren't there two
masks and two sets of gloves?
</P>
<P>
   Matthew ``had no notion that these items were in there,'' his
father said.
</P>
<P>
   Halstead said detectives do not know how many fellow students
were targeted, and they have no clear motive.
</P>
<P>
   Police only know that Ciulla and Russ were part of a clique that
had a conflict with another clique at the high school, but the
run-in was never reported to authorities, Halstead said.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy demonstrates a dangerous lack of communication
between students and their parents, Halstead said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other kids knew about this plan and never called police.
That's what they said at Columbine,'' he said. ``The kids knew
about it, and they were going to hang around and watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The April massacre at Columbine High in Littleton, Colo., left
15 people dead and nearly a dozen injured. The gunmen were members
of a clique known as the Trenchcoat Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Ciulla and Russ were suspended for two years from the Glendale
Union High School District and will never be allowed to attend Moon
Valley High again, said Carole Sabo, a district spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since Columbine, we've been pretty hyper across the
country,'' said Richard Stapley, a school board member who declined
to discuss the case in detail. ``We're trying to keep an eye on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several parents watching a soccer game at the school Tuesday
night, Nov. 23, were upset when they heard about the plot. They
also were concerned that the district didn't inform them. Late
Tuesday, Sabo said a letter will be sent home to parents notifying
them of the incident. Kevin Jones, 16, a junior at Moon Valley, was
told about the plot by a teacher during class shortly after it
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was crazy. I thought it was like Columbine. You
could just be sitting in class, and someone could just come in and
start shooting,'' he said. ``It's nuts. You don't know who can have
a gun anymore. Anyone can have a gun now.''
</P>
<P>
   The students who didn't report the plot probably thought that
the suspects were blowing hot air, Stapley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it was just like Columbine, that they didn't think
anything was going to happen,'' Stapley said.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Hugh, another school board member, praised the tipster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever picked up that phone and made that call apparently
saved someone's life,'' Hugh said. ``I hope that sets a good
example.''
</P>
<P>
   Halstead declined to identify the tipster who called police at 4
a.m. that morning, but Kaiser said it was a fellow student.
</P>
<P>
   Ciulla and Russ were indicted Nov. 12 on the conspiracy charges.
Ciulla, who has a record, was charged with illegally possessing a
gun. The teens were arraigned Monday, Nov. 22, on the charges.
</P>
<P>
   They are being held in lieu of $200,000 bail and face a Jan. 14
hearing before Judge Stephen Gerst of Maricopa County Superior
Court. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Beverly Ford contributed to this report.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
