<SLUG> BC-IND-TEEN-SLAYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 WHITE TEENS CHARGED WITH MURDERING BLACK YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JO THOMAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELKHART, Ind. _ Two white teen-agers were charged with murder on
Tuesday in what prosecutors say was the racially motivated random
shooting of a black teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   A local newspaper reported that one of the whites told friends
that he hoped the killing would win a membership for him in the
Aryan Brotherhood, a white supremacist prison gang, and the right
to wear its spider-web tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors brought the murder charges in Elkhart County Circuit
Court against Alex Witmer, 18, and his friend Jason Powell, 19, in
the killing of Sasezley Richardson, 19. Richardson was shot in the
head on Nov. 17 as he walked in a suburban residential area of this
blue-collar factory city in northern Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The police said he was returning on foot from a mall, where he
had bought diapers for his girlfriend's baby. He died on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a particularly heinous crime,'' said Mike Christofeno,
the chief deputy prosecutor in Elkhart County. ``This victim was
entirely random. It could have been any black person or any
minority person.''
</P>
<P>
   Christofeno read in court on Tuesday a police affidavit
reporting that Witmer and Powell had confessed to the crime. He
said the killing was racially motivated, but would not comment on
any possible connection with white supremacist groups.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was found bleeding on the side of the road by a
passer-by who has not been identified by the police. Witmer and
Powell were arrested on Saturday morning after a tip.
</P>
<P>
   The Elkhart County Branch of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People praised prosecutors on Tuesday for
identifying the killing as a ``true hate crime'' and called for
calm. They will sponsor a Thanksgiving Day prayer vigil at the site
of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was on foot because he had lost his driver's license
because of traffic fines, a friend, Tony Lewis, said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said Richardson had been working in a fast-food restaurant
to earn money to pay his fines and hoped to have his license
reinstated by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis bumped into Richardson a week ago, he said, and found his
friend happy and excited because he was turning his life around.
Richardson, who had dropped out of school, had been scheduled to
receive his high school equivalency certificate the day after he
was shot, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richardson was generous and quiet, Lewis said: ``If he had
it, you had it. If you needed it, you got it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his friend ``didn't bother anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis continued, ``He was the quiet type. He wouldn't say too
much. For someone just to shoot him out of nowhere _ that is just
wrong. In fact, he'd turn and walk the other way if someone tried
to pick a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials said that Witmer had served time at
Plainfield Juvenile Correctional Facility for a handgun offense and
had been released in June.
</P>
<P>
   Powell has no criminal record. A neighborhood friend, Caleb
Johnson, said that Powell ``liked everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter what people were like,'' Johnson continued.
``He just liked people for who they were. I didn't think he'd get
involved in something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Elkhart County police estimate that there are just under 100
members of the Aryan Brotherhood in the area. The local newspaper,
The Elkhart Truth, reported that Powell hoped to win a spider-web
tattoo that symbolizes that a member has killed a person of a
minority race. The paper reported that Witmer had told officers at
the county jail that he was a member of the brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   The Aryan Brotherhood, which began in the California prison
system in 1967, is ``the biggest and hardest-edged prison gang,''
said Mark Potok, a spokesman for the Southern Poverty Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   Most of its members are in state prisons, Potok said.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
