<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MOSQUE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFIANT MUSLIMS BEGIN BUILDING MOSQUE IN NAZARETH 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to change Vals to Valls in 5th graf.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZARETH, Israel _ Thousands of jubilant Muslims chanted prayers
to Allah, threw fists into the air and set off firecrackers Tuesday
as they defiantly laid the marble cornerstone of a mosque in the
shadow of the Basilica of the Annunciation.
</P>
<P>
   A nun in white, a monk in brown and a priest in black watched
the celebration glumly from the crenelated roof of the church,
which, like all the major churches in the Holy Land, had been
shuttered for two days in protest.
</P>
<P>
   The battle of the Muslim majority here to build a mosque
adjacent to a central Christian pilgrimage site has not only
divided the once harmonious Israeli Arab town but strained Israel's
relations with the Vatican as the millennium approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican on Tuesday issued a sharply worded criticism of the
Israeli government's decision to authorize the mosque in the
boyhood town of Jesus. But it did not mention any change in the
plans for Pope John Paul's visit to the Holy Land in March, a trip
that local Christian leaders here had said would be jeopardized if
the cornerstone were unveiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision of the Israeli government seems to lay the
groundwork for future contrasts and tensions between the two
religious communities, Christian and Islamic,'' said Joaquin
Navarro-Valls, the chief spokesman for the Vatican. ``I believe
that political authorities in this case have a great
responsibility, because instead of favoring unity, they created the
foundation to foment division.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's foreign ministry responded angrily later in the day,
saying, ``It's their unfortunate but time-honored habit of pointing
the finger of blame in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   At the eleventh hour before Tuesday's festivities, Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, worked unsuccessfully to dissuade
Muslim leaders from moving ahead with the project. It put him in an
unusual role, mediating not only between his fellow Muslims and the
Christian world, but between Israeli Arabs and Christians.
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat fears that the troubles in Nazareth could harm his
plans to attract thousands of pilgrims to Palestinian-governed
Bethlehem and could sow religious discord among Palestinians.
Muslim leaders in Jerusalem also called on their counterparts in
Nazareth to cancel their plans, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   The usually sleepy center of this northern Israeli town was
strung with balloons as a few thousand Muslim men filled the square
to pray and to bask in their accomplishment. With several of them
deliberately facing the church, they waved the green flags of the
Islamic Movement and released canisters of green smoke as speaker
after speaker heralded the day as a critical first step in
reclaiming Islamic land throughout Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's liberate al Aksa next,'' said Ahmed Abu Nawaf, who runs
the Islamic religious trust in Nazareth. He was referring to the
Jerusalem mosque that is one of Islam's holiest, and he held his
fingers aloft in a V.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of the unveiling, hundreds elbowed close to the
marble slab. When its textile cover, embroidered with verses from
the Koran, was lifted, the crowd went wild. They shouted ``Praise
to God,'' as the fireworks exploded so loudly that the nun on the
church roof covered her ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should anyone be upset with us?'' asked Salman Abu Ahmad,
a local councilman who rode on the shoulders of his supporters.
``We are not building a dance hall or a casino. We are building a
house of prayer next to another house of prayer. May our city be
filled with blessing upon blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   A man wearing a T-shirt that said ``Islam is the solution''
smiled broadly in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Israeli riot police officers, armed with truncheons,
tear-gas launchers and automatic rifles, were positioned around the
old city, but the celebration did not get out of hand. In fact,
many of the Christian-owned stores were shut and the Christians
stayed away from the old town center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the middle, because we are not Muslims and we are
not Christians,'' said an Israeli officer who would not give his
name. ``The Muslims are a lot stronger than the Christians, a lot
more deadly. Without the protection of the Jews, I don't think
there would be any Christians left here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a curious statement, given that Christian leaders accuse
the Israelis of disregarding Christians' interests because their
population is small. The leaders say that Israel gave in to the
demands of a small group of militant Muslims who were seen to
represent a large population of Israeli Arab voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dignity of man does not depend on numbers,'' said
Archbishop Michel Sabbah, the Latin patriarch, who is the
highest-ranking Roman Catholic cleric in Israel and the Palestinian
territories and who is from Nazareth. ``Because of neglect, we were
forgotten and put aside.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
