<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-MOSQUE-1STLD-W     11-24 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MOSQUE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NAZARETH, Israel: put aside.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The basilica is a modern building atop the ruins of a
12th-century Crusader Church, which sits on the site where
tradition says the angel Gabriel told Mary she was pregnant with
the child of God. On Tuesday its gates were locked, with a notice
posted explaining the conflict to ``all ambassadors, local
Christians, Christian pilgrims and travel agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the church's locked gate, a local Christian man said he
feared that things would never again be the same in Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind closed doors, everyone can express their feelings, but
not out here,'' he said, giving only his first name, Khameis.
``It's sad, though, shameful. We have the same language, the same
culture, the same foods. We grew up together, neighbors. That's
what hurts me, that these people I went to school with turned out
to be fundamentalists. What if we tried to put a church in Mecca,
their holy place?''
</P>
<P>
   A priest called the man away from the gates and cautioned him
not to talk. Any frank conversation was seen as inflaming tensions
in a city determined to proclaim to the world that nothing was
really wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Returning, the man called out to a friend passing by. ``See, he
is Muslim, he is my friend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the nearby marketplace, Hamed Bana, who owns a shoe
stall, pointed to Rima Bana, who runs the neighboring clothing
store and who shares his last name but is not related. ``I'm a
Muslim and she's a Christian and she's like my daughter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adnan Zoubi, another shopkeeper, said: ``It's important for the
leaders to start calming people down. What is done is done. Now we
will have a mosque and church side by side, just like in Jerusalem.
Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict here began as a very parochial issue at a very
scruffy site in the center of the largest Arab town in Israel,
where Muslims outnumber Christians about 42,000 to 18,000. Almost
two years ago, local leaders set out to build a millennial plaza in
the half-acre lot adjoining the basilica.
</P>
<P>
   They tore down a school, and then began to fight with local
Muslims over a tiny mosque that is believed to contain the holy
tomb of Shehab el-Din, who is venerated by association: His uncle
was Saladin, the Muslim hero who ousted the crusaders in the 12th
century.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslims erected a protest tent on the site, promised to
build a huge mosque, and a tug-of-war between religious and
political forces in the town ensued. It came to a boil last Easter
when an outburst of violence brought the friction between Muslims
and Christians to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government proposed _ and imposed _ a compromise to
build a small mosque, leaving some land for the intended plaza. The
compromise was initiated by the right-wing Likud government of
Benjamin Netanyahu and completed by the new centrist government of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak. But the compromise was not fully
accepted and led to the church protest. ``Each government erred out
of narrow party political interests,'' Ehud Olmert, the Likud mayor
of Jerusalem, said Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In protest, churches were closed for the second day Tuesday.
Tuesday morning, at the Church of the Holy Sepulcher in Jerusalem,
an elderly woman, dressed entirely in black, crossed herself,
kneeled and kissed the sun-drenched wooden door several times. A
group of Polish pilgrims prayed silently outside the locked
entrance. A Belgian, Daniel Verschoore, said, winking, ``Maybe I'll
become a Muslim.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nazareth, Santos Nery, a visitor from Guatemala, stood on the
outskirts of the Muslim gathering studying the event. He had
intended to visit the basilica Tuesday, but shrugged off the
disappointment. ``I'll come back in the morning,'' he said, adding
that he would not begin to pass judgment on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are different cultures, with different perspectives.
This country has its own way of doing things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
