r k BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      11-24 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AMERICA, EVERY DAY SHOULD BE A DAY TO GIVE THANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This one's for those for whom thanks is an alien concept, those
never able or willing to look or walk on life's brighter side.
</P>
<P>
   They live on the dark side, where no blessing is worth
acknowledgment. For them, no incidence of good fortune is ever as
good as they think it should be.
</P>
<P>
   It's the malcontents who are most in my thoughts at this time of
year. They strive so mightily to avoid introspective reveries about
what they might be grateful for during this time of Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a recent preoccupation. It first began to enter my
consciousness back at Thanksgiving time in 1970 after returning
from a 14-year stay in the Far East, first as a soldier and later
as a newspaper journalist. The return to America and the challenge
of restarting a life and career had been difficult, but the first
Thanksgiving back was a special time because the new adventure was
beginning to show promise.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a half a lifetime away from my native land, the
culture shock was a jarring experience. America not only was like a
foreign country compared with the one remembered, but it also was a
much better place. Prosperity was so widespread as to be
unremarkable, and most Americans took it for granted. Compared with
the mid-1950s America of West Virginia last known to me, America
seemed like the promised land when it came to material things.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, compared with many places of my acquaintance in Asia,
America was a paradise. What was shocking, however, was that so few
Americans seemed to appreciate how much better off they were than
whoever was in second place. Conversations with new colleagues and
friends were more likely to be dominated by complaints about how
lousy things were than how wonderful their life actually was
compared with anyone else's on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever this was pointed out, though, the reaction was
defensive. Well, yeah, the argument went, maybe so, but we're not
living in another country. We're living in America, and things
could be so much better than they are.
</P>
<P>
   Here it is 29 years later, and life is even better than it was
back then. The year 1970, as it turned out, ushered in a rough
decade no matter what economic role you happened to being playing
at any given time. Workers, investors and consumers all got
bulldozed by the triple whammy of bad economic times, bear markets
and hyperinflation.
</P>
<P>
   As usually happens in America, though, things got better. Lots
better. Since the early '80s no society in the history of human
existence has had a longer run of prosperity, by every measure of
such things.
</P>
<P>
   It was during those early months of rediscovering my homeland
that my Thanksgiving epiphany occurred. My personal pledge was that
no matter how tough things got, never to forget how the other half
lives based on remembered observations and experiences of those
years abroad.
</P>
<P>
   From these memories would come constant reminders of the
difference between bad and really bad. After you've seen really
bad, whatever economic misfortune America has to offer always seems
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving may be our national day of expressing gratitude for
life's blessings, but if you're lucky enough to live in America,
every day should be a day of thanksgiving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
