<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK REPORTS HIGHER SECOND-QUARTER LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   H&AMP;R Block Inc. said Tuesday that its second-quarter loss widened
43 percent to $44.7 million, or 46 cents a share, because of
changed expense patterns in its tax operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City company also reported a 145 percent increase in
revenue to $209.9 million during the three months that ended Oct.
31. That was largely because of its acquisition in August of much
of the business and accounting services of McGladrey &AMP; Pullen LLC,
which made Block the nation's sixth-largest accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Block reported a loss of $31.2 million, or 31 cents a share, on
$85.6 million in revenue for last year's second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Block often reports losses or small profits during its first
three quarters because those are slack times in the tax filing
season. The company is aggressively expanding beyond tax
preparation to even out that seasonal pattern, which affected the
results reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increased expenses from U.S. tax operations and a decrease in
investment income were the two primary reasons for a higher net
loss this quarter,'' said Frank L. Salizzoni, Block's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Tax service expenses rose because Block has begun paying its
field managers higher salaries instead of big season-end bonuses.
The company also has made other changes that spread many previous
fourth-quarter-only costs through the rest of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
