<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-MERGER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENEX MEMBERS TURN DOWN PROPOSED MERGER WITH FARMLAND INDUSTRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City-based Farmland Industries Inc. was left standing at
the merger altar Tuesday when the nation's second-largest farm
cooperative narrowly rejected a proposed union.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the surprising setback, Farmland's top officer vowed to
continue the courtship of Minnesota-based Cenex Harvest States
Cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too many economic benefits and market impact on our
owners to just give up at this point,'' said Harry Cleberg,
Farmland's president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   With about 2,000 area employees, Farmland is the nation's
largest farmer-owned cooperative and one of the few Fortune 500
companies based in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   The merger defeat comes as federal regulators are considering
whether to approve a $129 billion merger between Westwood-based
Sprint Corp. and MCI WorldCom Inc. Unlike the proposed Sprint
merger, under which the combined company would be based in Clinton,
Miss., the co-ops had planned to put their merged headquarters in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed by the vote,'' said Bob Marcusse,
president of the Kansas City Area Development Council. ``We hope
that whatever issues stood in the way are resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Each co-op needed support from two-thirds of its members to
merge. Although 89 percent of Farmland's members approved, only 64
percent of Cenex members voted to merge.
</P>
<P>
   Many opponents cited concerns about Farmland's financial
condition and large merger-related payments to both co-op's
managers.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would have combined the co-ops into United Country
Brands as of March 1. Management on each side had said the merger
would help them compete better against even larger corporate
agricultural giants.
</P>
<P>
   Both co-ops will hold their annual meetings early next month.
Their continuing pursuit of a merger may depend on what happens at
those separate events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we don't have an answer to what happens next,'' said
Lani Jordan, director of corporate communications at Cenex Harvest
States.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said Cenex President Noel Estenson was not available for
comment Tuesday afternoon. He was rewriting his speech for the
annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the Cenex vote made it clear that Cenex leaders
need to learn more about members' concerns before considering
future talks with Farmland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a slightly different message from our members. We need
to talk to them,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said 92 percent of Cenex's members cast votes. Only 70
percent had voted when the co-op was formed last year in a merger
between Cenex Inc. and Harvest States Cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg said the supporting vote from Farmland's members
validated management's pursuit of the merger. It also encouraged
him to seek whatever economic ties the two large co-ops can
accomplish even if a merger doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the merger plan included agreements to combine
parts of their operations as joint ventures. Cleberg said that
those deals will have to be re-evaluated but that he wants to
pursue them as well as a merger.
</P>
<P>
   His first objective, he said, is to ``bring these companies
closer together even if it is not through a full and complete
consolidation.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the merger focused largely on Farmland's
above-average use of debt financing, a large potential tax
liability at Farmland and multimillion-dollar merger-related
payments to the top executives of both co-ops.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether any of those factors might be altered to rekindle
interest in the merger, Cleberg said, ``Those are all
possibilities, and certainly everything will be explored.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the merger was intended to help the farmer-owned co-ops
compete globally, Cleberg said the defeat won't compromise either
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither organization is backed to the wall right now,'' he
said. ``We're not in a panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said they were as surprised as they were pleased by
the merger's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'm happy. I thought it would pass,'' said Steve
Carney, a Montana farmer and Cenex director who worked against the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Carney had sent a letter, without Cenex approval or assistance,
to Cenex members challenging and questioning the merger. He said
Tuesday he believed it made a difference in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize it ever would,'' Carney said. ``I didn't
think people would read it, but evidently they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Carney is scheduled to retire from the Cenex board at next
week's annual meeting. The vote, however, has him wondering whether
he should seek re-election through a floor nomination at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to give a guy a lot to think about,'' Carney said.
</P>
<P>
   Carney also said a future merger might work, especially if
Farmland reduces its reliance on debt.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, expressed continuing reasons to avoid a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``By not merging it will preserve some competition'' in local
farm supply markets, said Robert Taylor, an agricultural economist
at Auburn University in Alabama. Taylor studied the merger at the
request of the National Farmers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's report was critical of the merger and especially of
Farmland's financial condition and the merger-related payments to
managers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 0052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
