<SLUG> BC-Boats-Casinos </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATION CASINO REGAINS MARKET SHARE LEAD IN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five weekends in October helped boost Station Casino back into
Kansas City's market share lead, according to the Missouri Gaming
Commission's latest financial report.
</P>
<P>
   Station's second-largest revenue month in history, $14.88
million, topped the $14.08 million raked in by Harrah's North
Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel. That gave Station the market lead for
only the third time in nearly three years _ but the second time in
four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to think there's a trend there,'' said Station's
Midwest president, John V. Finamore, who discounted the effect of
October's extra weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``That used to be the case,'' he said. ``Weekends were our big
focus. But there have been other five-weekend months when we
haven't been the market leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Weekday business is steadily improving, Finamore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to think it's the maturity and the natural evolution of
the property,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's general manger, Michael St. Pierre, could not be
reached Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for market share between the twin-boat Station and
Harrah's properties could be over next Wednesday if the Gaming
Commission, as expected, approves Station's proposed purchase of
the Flamingo Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   That would give Station three Kansas City boats and almost 58
percent of the market's total gambling capacity _ or places for
players at the games.
</P>
<P>
   But Harrah's appears to get more out of its capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The two Harrah's boats represent 28 percent of market capacity,
but the company's vessels routinely capture around 34 percent of
the revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Station, on the other hand, owns almost 44 percent of the
market's slot machines, table games and other wagering devices.
Despite that edge, Station also captures around 34 percent of the
monthly revenue.
</P>
<P>
   With the Flamingo's 13.9 percent of capacity, Station would own
57.8 percent of the market's games, but last month, for instance,
would have taken in only 48.2 percent of the market's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The Argosy Riverside Casino, with 14.1 percent of capacity, has
been gradually increasing its share of market revenue, to a record
18.35 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
   The single-boat Argosy posted a $7.7 million month, its best
showing since Station Casino _ the market's newest _ opened in
January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Argosy's success rests in part on heavy marketing of its
``loosest slots'' title. The phrase is industry jargon for the
highest percentage of jackpot payouts to customers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gaming Commission financial records and six-month
average payouts calculated by The Kansas City Star, the Argosy has
held the coveted title for the most popular 25-cent games for more
than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Argosy also operates the loosest 5-cent and $1 games.
</P>
<P>
   But October's numbers suggest that Illinois-based Argosy may be
losing its grip on the quarter-slots title.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time this year the Flamingo posted the highest
25-cent monthly paybacks to players and now trails Argosy in The
Star's six-month average calculation by just .01 of a percentage
point.
</P>
<P>
   Argosy General Manager Larry Kinser is watching the Flamingo's
sale to Station with interest. ``I don't know what's going to
happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Station's 25-cent slots typically are the market's tightest.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, payouts at Kansas City's casinos are only
fractions apart and, according to Strictly Slots magazine, are
among the loosest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The November issue of the publication for casino players showed
that Missouri's best quarter-slot payback for July, 94.3 percent at
the Argosy, was the highest among all U.S. riverboats. It was more
than a full percentage point better than payouts on the Las Vegas
Strip and trailed only four of eight other regions in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also reported that the North Las Vegas region,
which includes Station's Texas Station Casino, is home to the
nation's loosest slots, with paybacks of 97.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The tightest quarter slots this summer were at tribal casinos in
Connecticut; several boardwalk casinos in Atlantic City, N.J.; and
the Aztar Casino in Caruthersville, Mo., where paybacks averaged
less than 91 percent, the magazine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
