<SLUG> BC-MEGA-THEATER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER COMPLEX BRACES FOR THOUSANDS OF CUSTOMERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- This morning is truly the calm before the storm
at the Winnetka 21 in the suburban San Fernando Valley section of
Los Angeles. Or more appropriately, the eye within the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few weeks, employees at one of the nation's largest
and busiest movie houses have been scurrying around like ants in
the moments before it rains. The five-day storm begins this
afternoon, when customers start showing up to eat tons of popcorn,
candy and hot dogs until the final curtain drops Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot like the L.A. rush hour,'' said manager John King
Jr. ``If you don't plan it out, you'll wind up stuck in the
Sepulveda Pass. The sheer numbers of people are astounding.''
</P>
<P>
   King and the other managers at the Winnetka 21 have been working
overtime for the last month preparing for this long holiday
weekend, shipping in and stacking hundreds of pounds of extra candy
and popcorn, hiring and training extra staff and plotting which
screens will show which movies at what time to maximize ticket
sales and minimize customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Although theaters across the country all had similar preholiday
strategies, few movie houses are as large or well-attended as the
Winnetka 21. Its more than 100 separate showtimes every day are
spread over 120,000 square feet supporting 5,900 seats. Its three
snack bars include a main one nearly 100 feet long. The main hall
runs the length of two football fields.
</P>
<P>
   Co-manager Gary Frost predicts the theater will sell three times
as much snack food as usual this week. The key numbers: thousands
of pounds of popcorn, weighing 1.5 tons before popping, to be
washed down by 1,500 gallons of soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started ordering extra heavy 2{ weeks ago so I wouldn't kill
my stock people in the last few days,'' Frost said. Both storerooms
_ the larger of which is as big as a theater auditorium _ are
nearly full.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had enough to take us through Thanksgiving weekend, but we
got in another shipment Monday to restock,'' Frost said. ``You
can't afford to run out of anything now.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach of Thanksgiving requires double-checking all
equipment and making certain that staff members _ up to 170 people
from 120 in the early fall _ know how to deal with holiday hordes.
</P>
<P>
   King and Frost say crowd control is the most crucial part of
keeping customers happy. With ``Toy Story 2,'' ``The World Is Not
Enough,'' ``Sleepy Hollow'' and ``End of Days'' all playing, there
will be lines to buy tickets and then lines for specific films once
customers have bought their tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth the extra effort to make sure there are lots of
people out there to answer questions and prevent people from
waiting an hour for the wrong movie,'' King said. ``Otherwise you
have chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Staffers at the Winnetka 21 receive a week of training before
being assigned to specific areas of the theater, and each new one
initially is paired with a more experienced employee. But at crunch
time, everyone is expected to do whatever's needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the employees are trained to handle any job, so we can
assign people to wherever the greatest need is at that moment,''
King said.
</P>
<P>
   The managers also place a premium on staffing the
guest-relations desk with employees who can quickly defuse
agitation. Those slots go to experienced workers with the knack for
dealing effectively with customers who wound up in the wrong
auditorium, were disappointed by the movie or had some other
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest complaint by far is that they didn't get a good
seat,'' King said. ``They either came late or took a long time at
the snack bar. No one likes to sit in the front rows except for
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``bad seat'' complaint can be resolved several ways. An
usher can be assigned to try to find a seat the customer likes
better, or the customer may be offered the choice of a different
movie or a later screening, a ``sorry'' pass for re-admission later
or a cash refund.
</P>
<P>
   King and Frost admit that the most difficult part of their job
recently has been maintaining staffing levels for mostly
minimum-wage jobs requiring work on weekends and holidays. In a
tight job market, finding qualified employees has become
problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a lot harder to get workers, particularly since a
lot of new stores opened at Northridge Fashion Center,'' King said.
``That really hurt us. A lot of people will show up for the
interview with torn clothes and green hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Job perks include free popcorn on the job and a once-a-week
family pass to the theater. Over the past week, eight new employees
have been hired, far short of the goal of 20 to 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of new hires was not what we wanted, but every
single one of them helps,'' Frost said. ``The job requirements are
pretty basic. You have to act like you want to work here.''
</P>
<P>
   The managers insist that dealing with behavior problems at the
Winnetka 21 has not been a major burden for the staff. ``We really
do have a very good clientele here,'' King said. ``They tend to be
very well-behaved.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pressures will intensify this afternoon as customers
begin to celebrate what to most of them is a four-day weekend.
Forget that the calendar says it's Wednesday. Tonight will resemble
a busy Friday night for theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanksgiving Day starts really busy and then slows down a bit
in the middle of the afternoon,'' King said. ``Then it really picks
up in late afternoon once people have gotten tired of seeing their
relatives. And on the day after, it's crazy from opening to
closing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has unholstered four major guns for this prime-time
period: ``The World Is Not Enough,'' which opened last weekend with
$35.5 million; ``Sleepy Hollow,'' which followed with $30 million;
Walt Disney Co.'s ``Toy Story 2'' and Arnold Schwarzenegger's ``End
of Days.'' Each has a shot at matching the $45.7 million
Thanksgiving record set by ``A Bug's Life'' last year. Exhibitor
Relations Co. has predicted the five-day total could top $200
million, far above last year's record of $182.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Winnetka will allocate nine screens collectively to
``World,'' ``Sleepy'' and ``End of Days.'' In one of the
auditoriums assigned to each title, customers will see the film on
a 70-feet-wide screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big screens have really become our signature,'' King said.
``We get people coming all the way from Palmdale and Lancaster to
see them. This is really the crown jewel of the Pacific chain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Winnetka's 10-screen sister complex at the remade Northridge
Fashion Center will probably attract the region's
kiddie-and-parents crowd with ``Toy Story 2'' and ``Pokemon: The
First Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Both complexes are owned by the Los Angeles-based Pacific chain.
On the day after Thanksgiving last year, when the Northridge
complex was still under construction, the Winnetka 21 set its
all-time attendance record.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 17,404 admissions,'' Frost recalled. ``There are a
lot of towns that aren't that big. We had `A Bug's Life,' `Enemy of
the State' and `Rugrats,' and it was extremely busy, with lots of
sell-outs. We probably won't ever match that again because back
then we got all the major movies, and now we split them with
Northridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Pacific's headquarters staff deals with studios in
booking the films a week at a time, managers like King and Frost
are point men in executing strategy. For example, if a film in a
big auditorium isn't drawing customers, it may be shifted into a
smaller space at midday.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the right movie in the right auditorium is a
still-developing art since megaplexes _ theaters with 16 or more
screens _ have been on the scene only a few years. At the Winnetka,
there are 2,000 seats collectively in the three theaters with
70-feet-wide screens, while the small halls only have about 200
seats, so managers need to guess just how much demand there will be
for each film and allocate space accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Timing poses another tricky calculation. Even though the most
popular starting time is between 7 and 7:45 p.m., operators have
found it makes more sense to stagger the showings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're showing the Bond movie in three auditoriums starting
at 7, 7:15 and 7:30, then you could have close to 2,000 people at
once and that's a lot of traffic,'' King said. ``The idea is that
you spread them out and open one big auditorium on one side at the
same time that you open a small one on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their preparations, King and Frost face the prospect of
18-hour workdays back to back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like Thanksgiving and the day after,'' King
said. ``Gary and I will arrive at 9 a.m., take separate breaks for
dinner and go home at 3 in the morning. This will be my 23rd year
of working on Thanksgiving, so I can't believe I'm smiling as I'm
telling you this.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
