<HEADLINE>
FORMER PATIENT DONATES $18,000 TO HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Jack Wilkinson recalls vividly the needles
that doctors at Children's Mercy Hospital used to drain fluid from
his lungs. That was in 1937. Wilkinson was 4 years old and had
double pneumonia. Survival was far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saved my bacon,'' he said. ``They knew my dad didn't have
any money, so they didn't even send him a bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Wilkinson, 66, of Springfield, Va., is repaying Children's
Mercy. He retired recently as vice president of the Laborers'
International Union and donated to the hospital the $18,000 he
received in retirement gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The money will go toward a whirlpool for arthritis patients in
physical therapy. On Tuesday, Wilkinson visited Children's Mercy to
see where it would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of love for that hospital,'' he said. ``I
wouldn't be here without them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
