<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOND-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF MISSOURI NURSING HOMES CITED FOR INFRACTIONS SKYROCKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ The number of Missouri nursing homes cited
for problems that endangered residents more than quadrupled in the
last year, new federal statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   The likely reason for the increase, state and federal officials
said Tuesday, was a combination of factors, including more vigorous
enforcement of regulations and the increasing difficulty nursing
homes face in hiring adequate staff.
</P>
<P>
   But inspectors also may be grading nursing homes more harshly
now for violations that were not considered as serious in the past,
a spokesman for the nursing-home industry said.
</P>
<P>
   In their most recent inspections, 26 Missouri nursing homes _
4.6 percent of the state's total _ had violations that placed
residents' health or safety in immediate jeopardy. Missouri has
about 560 nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Just six nursing homes, or 1.1 percent of the total, had such
violations in their previous inspections, conducted annually by the
state.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, 1.5 percent of the state's 399 nursing homes had such
serious violations in their most recent inspections, compared with
3 percent in their previous inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics were released Tuesday by U.S. Sen. Kit Bond, a
Missouri Republican, following a meeting in Kansas City with
officials from the federal Health Care Financing Administration,
which oversees nursing-home quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a disturbing spike up in the number of deficiencies
found in Missouri nursing homes,'' Bond said. He said he had asked
the federal agency to give him monthly reports on Missouri nursing
homes that had chronic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said his office has been contacted in recent months by
family members of many Missouri nursing-home residents who ``give
us tales of very serious problems...not getting adequate care, not
getting the treatment they think they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems cited in the federal agency's statistics were not
trivial violations but involved such serious issues as inadequately
treated bedsores, medication errors and patients who were able to
wander away from their nursing homes unattended, said Thomas Lenz,
the agency's associate regional administrator.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that the increasing numbers of Missouri nursing
homes with violations can be attributed to a single cause, Lenz
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to look for the one thing. I don't think
there's one thing. It's a bushel basket of things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 1998, the federal agency has been under presidential
orders to step up enforcement of nursing-home regulations, Lenz
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have emphasized states must follow our protocols'' for
doing inspections, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the increasing number of violations is that
nursing homes are having a hard time maintaining adequate staffing
levels, Lenz said. Nursing-home work is often difficult and poorly
paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average pay for a nurse's assistant is what they pay at
Burger King,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri officials acknowledge that nursing homes are having a
hard time attracting workers, said Bryan Forbis, acting deputy
director for institutional services of the Missouri Division of
Aging.
</P>
<P>
   The division is seeking an increase in the budget next year for
Medicaid, the state program that pays for most nursing-home care,
so that nursing homes can better recruit and maintain their work
forces, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical they have sufficient numbers of adequately
trained staff,'' Forbis said. ``We want there to be a high quality
of care.''
</P>
<P>
   While a budget increase next year will help nursing homes,
higher Medicaid payments are needed right away, said Earl Carlson,
executive director of the Missouri Health Care Association, which
represents the nursing-home industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a crisis in staffing today that needs to be addressed
today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of Missouri nursing-home patients are
covered by Medicaid, Carlson said. ``We just can't go out and raise
prices because it's government reimbursement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While inadequate staffing may account for some nursing-home
problems, the increased violations found in the federal agency's
data may be inflated, Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing-home inspectors are grading problems more severely than
they used to, and some violations now are being counted twice, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, being found at fault for allowing a nursing-home
resident to wander away will also trigger a citation for inadequate
staffing, Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't happen before,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
