<SLUG> BC-PLAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REJECTS STATE'S BID TO DELAY HALTING OF PLANNED PARENTHOOD
FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ A circuit judge Tuesday rejected the
state's attempt to delay his decision halting state funds for
Planned Parenthood offices in Kansas City and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Cole County Circuit Judge Byron Kinder rejected the state's
request despite predictions that the ruling would force Missouri's
entire family planning program to close for up to one month,
temporarily denying services to 3,000 women and men.
</P>
<P>
   State attorneys said they would appeal Kinder's decision to the
Western District Court of Appeals in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The latest order stems from a Kinder ruling last week that
ordered a halt to state family planning money for Planned
Parenthood offices in Kansas City and St. Louis. Kinder said the
groups failed to comply with a new anti-abortion law, and he
ordered them to repay the state $105,750 they had received since
July 1, with interest. The law is designed to make sure that state
tax dollars do not subsidize Planned Parenthood's abortion
services. Kinder said the two Planned Parenthood offices violated
the statute by directly referring patients to abortion providers,
distributing marketing materials about abortion services and in
other ways.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday attorneys for the state asked Kinder to delay his
ruling while they appealed the decision. They said his order would
damage all 96 hospitals, local health departments and others that
supply state-funded family planning services, not just the two
Planned Parenthood offices.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dempsey, state health director, told the court in an
affidavit last week that clients would temporarily lose access to
tests or screening for pregnancy, cancer, sexually transmitted
diseases and sexual abuse while contracts were rewritten.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Cherrick, a special assistant attorney general who filed
the lawsuit, praised Kinder's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Cherrick, who was hired solely to defend two anti-abortion laws,
says there is no reason to interrupt state funds to nearly 100
family planning offices just because tax money was halted for
Planned Parenthood offices in Kansas City and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased that the court has refused to accept the
director of health's attempt to hold hostage the recipients of
family planning funds not affected by this court order,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey said the monthlong shutdown remained possible because
all of the state's family planning agreements were covered by the
same state contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that contract is at issue, then everyone's contract is at
issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey said that, if Kinder's ruling was not delayed, health
officials would ``have to issue contract amendments to assure
compliance'' with his order, and that would take up to one month.
</P>
<P>
   Family planning services are still being offered at Planned
Parenthood offices in the Kansas City area, said Peter Brownlie,
president and chief executive officer for Planned Parenthood of
Kansas and Mid-Missouri. Brownlie said his group was seeking
donations of about $300,000 to offset the possible loss of $628,000
in state family planning money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
