<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-COACH-TEX </SLUG>
 
Clemson assistant coach might visit Texas Tech again 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clemson offensive coordinator Rich Rodriguez said yesterday that
he and his wife, Rita, are considering going to Lubbock, Texas,
this weekend as speculation continues to point to him as a top
contender to succeed Spike Dykes as head football coach at Texas
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about doing that just to look around and get the
feel from her perspective,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez interviewed with Tech officials, met chancellor John
T. Montford and toured university facilities Monday. He said the
fact that he made the initial trip indicated his interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have gotten on the plane if I wasn't interested,''
Rodriguez said. ``I think the future looks bright there whether I'm
the next coach or not. Spike Dykes laid a great foundation and did
a great job while he was there.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Rodriguez and Oklahoma offensive coordinator Mike
Leach run wide-open offensive attacks make them both attractive
candidates, Tech athletic director Gerald Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are other people that we are interested in talking
to,'' he added. ``We want to talk to some people that we haven't
talked to yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers indicated that the process would intensify next week.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said his first impressions of the situation and the
university were good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed my visit and I think things went really
well,'' he said. ``Everything has been positive. It's my impression
that \RTech\S is committed to doing what is necessary facility-wise
to keeping up. And the Big 12 is one of the top conferences in the
country. Look at the top 10 right now.'' / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
