<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-ROCKETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS CAUGHT SHORT BY ROCKETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Rudy Tomjanovich, who turns 51 today, might want to
put two extra candles on his birthday cake.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Tomjanovich's Houston Rockets blow away the
stubborn Mavericks, 119-99, last night. They also said goodbye to
the longest losing streak ever to open a season at the 25-year-old
Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   The frustrated Rockets captured their first home victory of the
season _ in seven tries _ as they zipped by a road-weary and
short-handed Mavericks team that suited up only eight players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them before the game that fatigue might be a factor,
and it was,'' Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson said. ``We
were running on empty.''
</P>
<P>
   With Robert Pack, Cedric Ceballos and Gary Trent back in Dallas,
and Steve Nash and Randell Jackson on the bench in street clothes,
the Mavericks' gas tank quickly ran low in the second half. Pack
(hamstring), Trent (hamstring) and Jackson (thigh) will also miss
tonight's game at Orlando, while Ceballos is doubtful with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Nash, meanwhile, will have his sore right ankle examined this
morning to determine if he'll be available to play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   After a solid 24 minutes that saw them trailing only 57-54 at
intermission, the Mavericks couldn't keep pace with the quicker and
more athletic Rockets in the second half. With rookie point guard
Steve Francis accounting for 11 of his 17 points and three of his
seven assists, the Rockets outscored the Mavericks, 37-25, in the
third period en route to snapping a five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just outmanned,'' said point guard Hubert Davis, who
made his first start of the season and finished with 14 points and
six assists. ``We played real hard, but things didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seemed tired in the third quarter, and we made some runs.
But it wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough, because the Rockets had almost as many players
in double-figure scoring (seven) as the Mavericks had players in
uniform (eight).
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough, because future Hall of Fame forward Charles
Barkley played lights-out. Barkley produced a season-high 26 points
and 14 rebounds as the Rockets improved to 3-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very frustrating and disappointing season thus
far,'' Barkley said. ``Tonight was the first night this year that I
played up to my ability.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks (4-8) dropped their fourth consecutive game after
starting the season 4-4. Not even a career-high 31 points from Dirk
Nowitzki could save the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had a good game offensively, and tonight most of my
shots were going down,'' Nowitzki said. ``I'm always running on the
break, and Charles wasn't picking me up. I just had a good game,
and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Finley (29 points, eight rebounds, six assists) and Rick
Hughes (11 points) were the only other Mavericks players who
performed admirably. Erick Strickland struggled through a 2-of-12
shooting night, and Shawn Bradley was scoreless in 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, because I think we made it tough,'' Finley said.
``I think the first half we put ourselves in a good position to win
the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we came out in the second half, they started the
third quarter real strong and we never recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being short on players, Finley steadfastly refused to
use that as an excuse for losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to strap it up and do it again,'' Finley said,
adding that he hoped some of his teammates were upset about the
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has to be our attitude to go in there and get a win.
Hopefully this won't happen again.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
