<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-KINGS-NYT &LR;      11-24 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS TOP NETS, 105-92 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ There would be no therapeutic victory to restore
the New Jersey Nets to wholeness, no strong, unified performance to
serve as a balm for a team as sore as a fresh wound. The
cross-country plane ride and public airing of their locker-room
grievances did nothing to heal what ails the Nets. They left
Sacramento as they entered it on Tuesday night: wounded, fractured
and with one victory to their name.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, that youthful and exciting team that is all the Nets
were supposed to be, beat their guests soundly, 105-92, before
17,021 delighted fans at Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing their record to 8-1, the best start in franchise
history, the Kings proved to be all the Nets (1-10) are not. In
concert like a jazz band, they found teammates with behind-the-back
passes and finished uncanny feeds with alley-oop dunks that left
the Nets staring at the soles of their shoes.
</P>
<P>
   While the Nets were the Stephon Marbury show, the Kings had a
starting five and bench full of contributors. There was Chris
Webber gripping the rim and posing after dunks, grabbing every
rebound in sight and giving fascinating dishes to teammates in
recording a monstrous triple-double of 26 points, 22 rebounds and
10 assists. It was the ninth triple-double of Webber's career.
</P>
<P>
   There was the dazzling point guard Jason Williams gliding in the
lane for loping finger-roll layups, and the reserve energizer
Lawrence Funderburke providing a tour-de-force performance of 18
points and 9 rebounds off the bench. Ten Kings scored in all,
including four with 13 or more points.
</P>
<P>
   It was too much for Marbury, who played splendidly in recording
31 points and 7 assists on 12-of-27 shooting, to beat by himself.
Sherman Douglas added 13 points, and Keith Van Horn scored 12 and
grabbed 17 rebounds but missed a horrific 16 of 22 shots.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that Jim McIlvaine was poked in the eye in the second
quarter by his teammate Sherman Douglas and did not return, Kendall
Gill was accidentally hit in the face by Corliss Williamson and
received 4 stitches above his left eye and Douglas tweaked his left
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets will hope for a better result Wednesday night in
Oakland, home of the Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   After letting the Nets hang for a quarter and a half, the Kings
blew the game open with a slam-dunk competition's worth of jams
late in the second quarter. Webber seemed to score on nothing but
dunks, and Funderburke hung from the rim like a net after vicious
alley oops.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, the Nets, who led by as many as 8 points in the
first quarter, trailed, 60-50. It only grew worse in the third, as
the Kings came out with a barrage of 3-pointers to bury the Nets'
already fleeting hopes and increase the lead to 18 points midway
through the period.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento wanted to run from the tip-off, and initially the
Nets were game. With Marbury playing shooting guard alongside
Douglas, the Nets were able to keep up with the speed game and take
a 30-26 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, free to concentrate on scoring, was too much for
Williams. Effective from the perimeter as well as driving to the
basket, he made 5 of 8 shots in scoring 12 first-quarter points.
</P>
<P>
   He was so hot that late in the quarter he pulled up from behind
the left hash mark with the shot clock running down and sank a
30-footer.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the Marbury-Douglas backcourt seemed to be a
great find, as Marbury, like Philadelphia's Allen Iverson, thrived
without the responsibility of running the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the best of both worlds,'' Casey said before the
game. ``Having Sherman handle the ball more takes some of the
burden of setting up things for Stephon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' downfall had nothing to do with their backcourt. Van
Horn, who entered the game shooting 38.4 percent from the floor,
continued to struggle offensively and proved to be a microcosm of
the Nets' entire team in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 6 points on 3-of-8 shooting in the first, Van Horn
missed 7 of 8 shots in the second. The Nets, who shot 48 percent in
the first, fell flat, hitting just 7 of 26 shots for 26.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With the Nets stone cold, Sacramento took control midway through
the period and gained the lead for good, 42-41, on a basket by
Predrag Stojakovic. The hoop began a 20-7 run that ended with the
Kings ahead by 60-48 moments before intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Injury was added to the embarrassing situation when McIlvaine
was poked in the eye by his teammate Douglas while both were
scrambling for a loose ball with 1 minute 58 seconds remaining in
the half. McIlvaine did not return to compete, and in a way,
neither did the Nets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
