r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     11-24 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS WIN, STORR LOSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Kings were pounding the Colorado Avalanche on
Tuesday night, but things rarely have looked worse.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Storr was gone after one period with the goaltender's
biggest fear _ a badly strained right groin _ just two weeks after
the Kings lost Stephane Fiset with a deep bone bruise in his right
hand.
</P>
<P>
   And though the team rallied around Storr's replacement Marcel
Cousineau by ending a two-game slide with a 6-2 victory, it was
hard to tell the winners from the losers in front of 18,004 at the
new Pepsi Center that included Kings owner Phillip Anschutz.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into tonight's game against the struggling but still
defending Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars, the Kings have been
struck with their fourth potentially major injury this month that
began with Luc Robitaille's broken left foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the game,'' said captain Rob Blake, who scored
two goals. ``You aren't going to replace the guys we've lost, but
now is the time when you put faith in your system. Last year, we
lost guys and it killed us. But we weren't a playoff team. Now we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Kings looked like they might be able to absorb the
loss of Robitaille and center Jozef Stumpel, who will miss at least
the six weeks due to abdominal surgery. But after an early surge
this season, their power play continues to disintegrate, going 0
for 3 against Colorado and scoreless in the last 24 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   But the loss of their second goalie in two weeks truly stings.
Last year, the Kings lost Storr and Fiset seven minutes apart
during the season's fourth game, lost 14 of their next 16 and were
never heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   This year's team is much better, but Fiset is expected to miss
two more weeks. Cousineau was brought in when Fiset went down Nov.
6 but didn't play until Tuesday. Storr, who has a history of groin
problems, was 4-2-1 in Fiset's absence and was named NHL Player of
the Week in early November.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mike O'Neill, Cousineau's backup at minor league Long
Beach, will fly to Dallas today to be the Kings No.2 goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through this before,'' said Cousineau, who started
the second period with just 21 games of NHL experience. ``It's
tough to play back-to-back on the road, but with Long Beach I
played three games back-to-back in three different cities.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is certain Brett Hull, the Stars' biggest star, did not
play in any of them.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-6-4 Kings, though, made it look easy for Cousineau. The
beat up Colorado, which was coming off a tough overtime victory on
Monday against Dallas. For the first six minutes of the second
period, the Avs did not get a shot off against Cousineau.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the Kings got goals from Vladimir Tsyplakov and
Blake to make it a 3-1 game. The first shot Cousineau faced was a
goal by Dave Reid, but the Kings wore down the tired Avs and scored
three more times against goalie Marc Denis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were tired, but you have to make sure they play
tired,'' said Blake, who also assisted on Jason Blake's first goal
this season. ``That could be us against Dallas, but I think we'll
have something in reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that Kings coach Andy Murray rested Blake and
Ziggy Palffy for much of the third period in preparation for
tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   But the big ice pack of Storr's right groin in the post-game
locker room was a reminder that the Kings won at a price.
</P>
<P>
   Storr was injured attempting to stop a first-period breakaway by
Avs center Joe Sakic, who was back after missing nearly two weeks
with a rib injury.
</P>
<P>
   Sakic already had scored a power-play goal. As he came in on the
Kings' net, Sakic had a chance for his 1,000 career point. He
didn't get off the shot, but Storr stuck out his right leg and felt
more than a tweak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have stayed in, but I might have injured it more,''
Storr said. ``We'll have to see tomorrow just how bad it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said the strength in Storr's leg was down to 20 percent
between the first and second periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time when we find out about ourselves and our
system,'' Murray said. ``We have confidence in the guy we are
bringing up. We will get through this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
