<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CLIPPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS DEFEAT KNICKS, 100-95 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The New York Knicks hauled their frontline of
spare parts onto the showroom floor of the Staples Center on
Tuesday night and were faced with the forgotten team off the back
lot of Hollywood, the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Something had to give, and it was the Knicks. They were unable
to make up for the absences of the injured Marcus Camby, Larry
Johnson and Patrick Ewing against a lively Clippers team that was
led by the youth of the Queens prodigy Lamar Odom and the savvy of
Derek Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, zipping in and around a variety of Knicks defenders,
scored 24 points in the Clippers' 100-95 victory, a performance
that included a driving layup with 2 minutes 12 seconds left to put
his team up by 7 points. Until then, the Knicks had a chance
despite their lethargic beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Down by as many as 28 points in the second quarter, they blew
four opportunities to tie the game in the fourth quarter and wasted
an energetic effort by Latrell Sprewell, who finished with 32
points. The Knicks missed two 3-pointers that would have tied the
game in the waning seconds; one by Charlie Ward with 16.9 seconds
left and one by Sprewell with 1.4 seconds left. When it was over,
the Knicks' five-game swing out west ended 2-3 and left the team at
6-7.
</P>
<P>
   It was a miserable night for Allan Houston. Often double-teamed
and turnover prone, Houston scored 11 points on a 4-for-11 effort.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell and Kurt Thomas (18 points) kept hope alive. In the
fourth quarter, the Knicks were down, 85-74, when Sprewell, Andrew
Lang and John Wallace alternated scores to get the team within 2
points with eight minutes left. The Knicks had a chance to tie it
at 87 but a pull-up jumper by Sprewell bounded off the rim before
falling to the side.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks would have another chance to tie with 4:40 left but
Chris Childs missed a short jumper. Each failure opened up a chance
for Tyrone Nesby to hurt the Knicks. After scoring four points in a
row for the Clippers, Nesby launched a 3-pointer over Wallace with
4:11 left to give his team a 94-89 lead. Odom took over from there
on a difficult night to swallow for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-day break in the California sun and some time to
relax, the Knicks approached their last night of a five-game road
trip as uninspired as beach bums. After all, these were the
Clippers, not the Warriors. No big deal. After their controversial,
Sprewell-charged romp in Oakland, the Knicks had a laid-back look
about them.
</P>
<P>
   Injury-depleted or not, there was little excuse for a casual
defense that allowed the Clippers amazing opportunities to look
like an elite team. If Anderson was not slipping by Houston or
Sprewell, Odom was twisting past Sprewell, Thomas and Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who were down by as many as 28 points in the first
half, were a stunned group on the sidelines. An exasperated Coach
Jeff Van Gundy tried everything, even playing a four-guard lineup,
and nothing was working until Sprewell opened up as suddenly as a
pop-up book to give the Knicks a chance with a 17-point second
quarter. He was the inspiration behind the Knicks' third-quarter
surge that helped them trim a 16-point halftime deficit to 6 after
a 12-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   But after a couple of botched possessions, the Clippers held a
84-74 lead entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was actually an uneasy lead for the Clippers, who started out
clicking so well against a Knicks team that was oozing apathy.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, Anderson had 17 points in the first quarter and
the versatile Odom flashed moves as if he was ruling the
playgrounds of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   And it got a lot worse before Sprewell seemed to get a whiff of
smelling salts when the Knicks bottomed out, down by 60-32 with
four minutes left in the second quarter. As usual, Sprewell didn't
ease into his game, he barged into it aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Driving to the basket and pulling up to hit his jumper, Sprewell
scored 15 of his 21 first-half points during a 17-5 run to get the
Knicks back to respectability at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting just two of his first five shots, Sprewell hit six
in a row in the second quarter to lead the Knicks back into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the way Van Gundy wanted to end this trip.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the injuries and energy-draining week on the road, he
was looking for a big finishing kick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
