r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN     11-24 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE UPSETS FRESNO STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO _ There was no way Tezale Archie was going to pass on an
opportunity to be a hero in his long-awaited homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   So Archie, on a play designed for him, let the shot fly, and
watched as the ball never got close to the rim. And then Archie, a
senior point guard at Pepperdine, celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Fresno State's Melvin Ely was called for
goaltending on Archie's game-winning shot attempt with less than a
second left, and the Waves upset the Bulldogs 70-68 in a men's
basketball game Tuesday night before a sellout crowd of 10,220.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a storybook ending,'' said Archie, who starred at
Fresno's Hoover High in the early '90s and grew up rooting for the
Bulldogs. ``I've been coming here (Selland Arena) since I was a
kid. I couldn't have written it any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Archie, who scored 13 points, doesn't care to think about a
scenario not entailing Ely getting called for goaltending. He drove
the length of the court after Ely's free throw tied the game at 68
with 8.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The shot) looked good to me,'' he said. ``A goaltend is a
goaltend.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a gutsy call, but the right one by the officials. The
ball was on a downward trajectory when Ely swatted it against the
backboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was up there for a long time,'' said Jan van Breda
Kolff, Pepperdine's first-year head coach who has guided the Waves
to a 2-0 start. ``It was the correct call.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves surprised the favored Bulldogs (1-1), who played
without All-American candidate Courtney Alexander who has a stress
fracture in his foot, with a tenacious pressing and trapping
defense. Pepperdine won despite shooting 36 percent (27-of-75).
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State committed 24 turnovers and blew a 65-60 lead with
3:25 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players believe, if we get down, we can come back because
of the press,'' van Breda Kolff said.
</P>
<P>
   Ely also was at the center of another crucial sequence with
three minutes left that helped the Waves score six points on a
single trip.
</P>
<P>
   After Nick Sheppard made a basket for the Waves, Ely was called
for a technical foul. Archie made both free throws, and with 2:38
left, Brandon Armstrong made a layup to give Pepperdine a 66-65
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves trailed most of the first half, but went on an 11-3
run in the final three minutes to cut the Bulldogs' lead to 40-37
at halftime. Pepperdine shot just 28 percent in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to try and find different ways to win the game,''
van Breda Kolff said. ``You can't always win with your shooting.
You have to make big plays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
