<HEADLINE>
CUSTER TRAIL LEADS TRAVELERS TO HISTORY, HEIGHTS OF THE
IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My best trip ever?
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. That's a tough call.
</P>
<P>
   Most of my travels have been themed. Sports-focused holidays
have revolved around soccer in San Francisco and baseball in St.
Louis; historical jaunts have led to castles in Germany and pueblos
in New Mexico; musically tuned vacations have culminated in
concerts in Orlando, Chicago and New Orleans. On other dedicated
trips, I have hiked in Turkey, roller-skated in Minnesota and skied
in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   But the all-time best?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ireland's Donegal had fabulous scenery, terrific soccer and
good beer, but it was so cold that I didn't feel my toes for the
entire two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ I wept for joy the first time I saw Mickey's Magic Kingdom.
Too bad I was 20; it caused quite a scene.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bustling Bangkok with its temples and temptations was
fascinating, but a lost passport sapped the fun of that exotic
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   _ For days I marveled at the palpable power of Washington, D.C.,
but I dreaded the nights at a cheap motel where most guests paid by
the hour and bat-wielding teens tortured rats in the alley.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps my most loosely themed trip was my best. My favorite
traveling companion and I spent a week on the trail of George
Armstrong Custer, the controversial yellow-haired general who met
his Waterloo at Little Bighorn.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trip marked not as much by what we saw as by what we
imagined:
</P>
<P>
   _ The sky slicing open and spilling stars onto the forest during
a violent thunderstorm at Custer State Park near Rapid City, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gutzon Borglum's disappointment of not seeing his monumental
salute to democracy, Mount Rushmore, completed before he died. Work
commenced in 1927, and while it took only 6{ years to carve the
four presidents' faces, the plagued project wasn't finished until
1941, eight months after the sculptor's death at age 74.
</P>
<P>
   _ The force of a vision such as sculptor Korczak Ziolkowski's
tribute to American Indians. His Crazy Horse would be 563 feet high
and 641 feet long. Compare that to nearby Mount Rushmore, where
George Washington's face is 60 feet tall. The sculptor began his
project more than 50 years ago, armed with a jackhammer, explosives
and $174. He died in 1982, and Crazy Horse is still a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Along the trail, we rediscovered the power of storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Before white settlers came to what is now northeastern Wyoming,
the unique geological formation currently known as Devils Tower was
called Mateo Tepee, or Bear Lodge. The story: Chased by a fierce
bear, seven sisters take refuge in a great tree. The bear's huge
claws scrape the tree as the girls climb higher and higher to
safety. Eventually the sisters are lifted to the sky, where they
become the seven stars of the Big Dipper.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of years later, Steven Spielberg told quite a different
story in his film ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind.'' The 1977
hit depicted the formation as a magical welcome mat for visiting
aliens. While Devils Tower became a national monument in 1906, it
is Spielberg's story that lures hundreds of thousands of visitors
to the park each year.
</P>
<P>
   Moving westward through Wyoming, we contemplated the perils of
life on the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   At the site of Fort Phil Kearny, we imagined the life of the
soldier sent to battle many foes: isolation, extreme weather,
rattlesnakes and a hostile people with more at stake than a young
infantry soldier. We spent hours walking the site of the
short-lived fort, constructed along the Bozeman Trail in 1866 to
protect westbound travelers from Indian attacks. Thousands of logs
were used to build the fort, which boasted 8-foot walls and
enclosed more than 17 acres. Two years later, it was abandoned by
the Army. Soon after that, Cheyenne Indians burned it.
</P>
<P>
   The fort's most famous soldier is remembered for a gaffe, not
greatness. Capt. William Fetterman disobeyed orders and was led
into a trap near the fort. He and his 81 men were killed. We walked
around the well-marked battleground, dodging rattlesnakes and
imaginary enemies on a lonely, windblown ridge.
</P>
<P>
   The week climaxed at Little Bighorn Battlefield in southeast
Montana. The national monument marks the site where Custer and more
than 200 members of the 7th Cavalry were killed in a battle with
Sioux and Cheyenne forces in 1876. Led by Sitting Bull and Crazy
Horse, the Indians claimed their most dramatic victory in a doomed
quest to preserve their way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Like generations of history buffs, we were drawn to the
battlefield by its myths, its mysteries and its momentousness in
American history. While the Indians won the battle, Little Bighorn
lost them the war by bolstering the U.S. government's commitment to
their domination.
</P>
<P>
   My companion was eager to walk the entire battlefield, to decide
for himself where errors were made and comrades were betrayed.
Well-versed in Custer lore, he walked along the ridge, imagining
troop movements and second-guessing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly aware that I should have beefed up on American history
before the trip, I became engrossed in the many ranger talks,
historic films and tours offered at the visitors center. Much of
the information dealt with the archaeological research done at the
battlefield and the site's importance to American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   That evening at dinner, with ``Garryowen'' echoing in our heads,
my companion presented his latest theories, and I shared my
conversations with the park's American Indian rangers.
</P>
<P>
   We agreed it had been the best day ever. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
