<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 03:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9807 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-24 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG RED BOAT TEXAS-BOUND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven months before its debut, Premier Cruise Lines is making a
significant change in its product targeted for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Good-bye, IslandBreeze. Hello, Big Red Boat III.
</P>
<P>
   Same ship. New name. New concept. Well, actually a familiar
concept in Florida, soon to be expanded all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Facing potentially strong competition at the Port of Houston
from the newer, bigger and already established Norwegian Sea, and
with industry giant Carnival primed to inaugurate sailings from
Galveston next fall, Premier will attempt to carve a niche by
focusing on family cruising during weekly voyages to three ports in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids will have their own dining area and dinner hour (5 p.m.),
their own menu, their own activities, even shore excursions geared
to young people,'' Premier president Bruce Nierenberg says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have separate facilities and counselors for kids ages
2-4, 5-8, 9-12 and teens. And because parents will know their kids
are well taken care of, they'll be able to fully enjoy all the
other services we offer. We won't be cutting back, either, on any
of our standard activities and entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT'S NEW? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the question is: What's so radically different
about Premier's approach?
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line, which pioneered weeklong ``Texaribbean''
sailings from the Port of Houston to Mexico and Honduras in May
1997, also offers a variety of kids' programs (and menus) aboard
its Norwegian Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival, whose Celebration will operate four- and five-day
itineraries from Galveston beginning Oct. 5, sponsors a year-round
supervised Camp Carnival for passengers ages 2-15.
</P>
<P>
   But Nierenberg, previously with NCL and largely responsible for
that line's initial presence here, says Premier has some
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ship coming to Houston has a lot of larger staterooms
equipped to handle third and fourth beds,'' he says. ``We can
easily accommodate 500-600 kids above our normal adult capacity.
The Sea is a great ship, but she's totally different. Most cabins
are small. She's limited in the number of kids she can carry.''
</P>
<P>
   Won't some travelers be put off at the prospect of 500 children
_ plus as many as 1,146 adults _ vying for space on a ship that, at
31,000 tons, is much smaller than the Norwegian Sea or Celebration?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because if you know what you're doing, 500 kids can seem
like less of a distraction than 100 kids on other ships,''
Nierenberg says. ``And we know how to do this right; it's been our
focus for many years. We'll have separate areas of the ship
dedicated to kids.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
APPEALING NOT JUST TO KIDS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Big Red Boat family concept goes beyond kids, Nierenberg
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year alone, 93 million adults will take a family trip,''
he says. ``But what constitutes a family? It is parents with kids.
But it's also honeymooners, single parents, extended families,
grandparents and couples without children.''
</P>
<P>
   Dare I say he's covered the waterfront there? Wait: ``We'll have
a lot of family reunions aboard the Big Red Boats, too,''
Nierenberg says.
</P>
<P>
   Premier claims to have pioneered the concept of the family
cruise vacation in 1983. For 10 years it was ``the Official Cruise
Line of Walt Disney World,'' specializing in land-sea packages. One
Big Red Boat remains a fixture at Port Canaveral, Fla., with
packages that include Universal Studios Escape.
</P>
<P>
   But, says Nierenberg, ``Now, we are bringing our Big Red Boat to
where the people live.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be four Big Red Boats in all.
</P>
<P>
   Big Red Boat I will continue to offer three- and four-night
cruises from Port Canaveral, combined with land packages at
Orlando-area resorts (but struggling for market share since the
debut of two newer and larger Disney Cruise Line vessels over the
past two years).
</P>
<P>
   Big Red Boat II, the recently chartered Edinburgh Castle, will
operate New England/Canada itineraries from New York next summer,
then switch to the Caribbean in the fall. Big Red Boat IV, now
known as the Rembrandt, will be based in Los Angeles beginning next
November.
</P>
<P>
   Big Red Boat III will sail from the Port of Houston to Vera
Cruz, Cozumel and Playa del Carmen starting in June.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts see this and other recent strategies as Premier
grasping for any edge with an older fleet (including the 1961
vessel bound for Houston) in an increasingly competitive business.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Nierenberg, a co-founder of Premier and a longtime
industry leader, proclaimed the company ``the cruise line of the
individual.'' Then he announced a focus on ``Seven-Star Service'' _
an obvious takeoff on ship ratings by ``Fielding's Worldwide
Cruises,''an annual guide whose highest designation has progressed
from five-star to five-star-plus to six-star in recent editions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll definitely still have our Seven-Star Service aboard the
Big Red Boats,'' Nierenberg says. Amenities will range from
complimentary evening shoeshine service to tableside cooking.
``Chocolate-ship cookies'' will be awaiting kids at bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   Premier has firmed itineraries and is accepting reservations for
its first Houston venture, which will offer departures each
Saturday and feature at least 10 hours in each Mexican port.
</P>
<P>
   Brochure prices are $1,369-$2,269 per person, with third and
fourth guests in a stateroom _ read kids _ paying $569 each (or
$469 for ages 2-9).
</P>
<P>
   Consult a travel agent about significant discounts (but don't
expect bargains quite as extreme as a current $996 family-of-four
rate for land-sea packages on Big Red Boat I in Florida).
</P>
<P>
   Carnival also has announced Galveston-based itineraries through
2001. Brochure rates are $699-$1,229 per person for a four-night
sailing.
</P>
<P>
   A travel agent can provide brochures and discuss special fares
for these and Norwegian Sea departures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
