<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 03:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-TRIPS-90S-2TAK     11-24 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TRIPS-90S-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUN-FILLED WINTER VACATION TO ENGLAND AND SWITZERLAND TOPS LIST OF
FAVORITES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Questions in Switzerland:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Why did the housekeeper place earplugs, not chocolates, on
the pillows tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Are we allowed to play the harp in our hotel room?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Will you summon our waiter? The tablecloth is on fire!''
</P>
<P>
   Surprises in London:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What do you mean all this formal wear spread over the bed is
for my wedding? I'm already married!''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Can you believe our good fortune in seeing three icons of
the British theater _ Sir John Gielgud, Dame Maggie Smith and Koo
Stark?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Is that tall man bumping us from our flight home Tommy
Tune?''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge today: determining my best travel experience ever.
Not necessarily the most exotic itinerary, the most daring
adventure or the most enriching odyssey. Just one favorite trip _
even a flawed favorite, though fun-filled _ to commemorate the
impending conclusion of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the memory bank of my travels overflows, how is it
that I've come to choose a rather uncomplicated (or so wife and I
envisioned) three-week vacation in Switzerland and England during
the dead of winter almost 12 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   I begin the process of elimination:
</P>
<P>
   There was the spring when, as a sportswriter, I proposed
visiting 26 major-league baseball training camps in 26 days _ and
almost fainted when the boss took me up on the idea. For sheer
endurance, that one ranks high. Alas, the boss also expected 26
stories in 26 days, detracting a wee bit from the enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you imagine I learned my lesson, several years later, after
I had assumed my current position, came a 17-day whirlwind tour of
Wales, Scotland and England that included 15 hotels in 15 cities
and towns.
</P>
<P>
   The pace does occasionally slow. Indeed, I'll always cherish
living like a local for the better part of a month in a Barcelona
apartment during the 1992 Olympics. Lingering over a bottle of fine
wine on the terrace of a 10th-century German castle overlooking the
Rhine River. Leisurely exploring the Natchez Trace, the Oregon
coast, Wisconsin farm lands and so many Texas treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Some snapshots are permanently etched in the mind: singing
around a campfire beneath twinkling stars in Yellowstone National
Park; Mozart chamber music resonating within a fortress overlooking
Salzburg, Austria; parasailing above Acapulco Bay, losing my
glasses and not being able to see how scared I was; and struggling
with chopsticks _ the most effective diet procedure I've undertaken
_ for meal after meal in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the foods of the world: feasting on foie gras in Provence,
kim chi in Seoul, Jagerschnitzel in Vienna and Jack Daniels Pie in
Lynchburg, Tenn. Hey, cut me some slack: I need fuel to fulfill
this task. And I did resist a kangaroo burger in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   It's also tempting to revisit the beginning _ the morning my
father and I embarked from our home on the Mississippi Gulf Coast
for my first real trip, to Rocky Mountain National Park in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   I can still see the horror on Daddy's face when I lost my
breakfast peering down as we crossed the old Mississippi River
bridge in Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure you can handle heights?'' he said. ``Maybe this
trip isn't such a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   I was 9 years old. What if he'd turned the car around? Would I
never have developed an addiction to travel?
</P>
<P>
   Never discovered earplugs on my pillow?
</P>
<P>
   February 1988:
</P>
<P>
   OK, so maybe this seems a strange time of year to vacation in
Switzerland, considering that the wife and I don't ski. But we are
reasonably polished at apres-skiing. And once I'd witnessed the
grandeur of the snowcapped Rockies, and later the Alps, I was
magnetized.
</P>
<P>
   So I wrote about the Super Bowl from balmy San Diego on a
Sunday, flew home on Monday, packed on Tuesday and headed back to
Houston Intercontinental Airport on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``London. Flight 4. Canceled.'' We stared at the words on the
monitor. ``No, that was last night's flight; we're just delayed
tonight,'' an attendant reassured us.
</P>
<P>
   This was the old Continental. The bad Continental. Not the
reinvented good Continental of today. But as a frequent flyer in
the era of ``triple-mile promotions,'' I had earned two free
first-class tickets, and we weren't about to let a minor
inconvenience spoil the rare treat of crossing the pond in luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret to announce that it will take several hours to
repair the aircraft,'' the attendant was now saying. ``Please
collect meal vouchers at the gate, and we'll keep you informed of
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a pause. Maybe 10 seconds. ``Wait!'' she shouted, halting
the stampede. ``I've just been told the airplane is fixed. We'll
board momentarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to fret. This was devised as a relaxing trip: a break
between hectic work assignments. We would spend nine nights in
``Zimmer 29,'' a cozy but comfortable and familiar room at the
Wilden Mann Hotel in Lucerne, and nine nights at the London
Marriott. (Yes, I'm cheap; this was a frequent-traveler award,
too.)
</P>
<P>
   The prime objectives:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make Lucerne a base for scampering all about Switzerland,
using Swiss Passes for unlimited travel on trains and buses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forget Buckingham Palace, Westminster Abbey and the Tower of
London _ each fascinates, but we'd seen them several times _ and
instead savor as many musicals and plays (and as much Indian and
Thai cuisine) as possible during our stay in London.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sleep until noon if the spirit moved.
</P>
<P>
   Noon, hah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earplugs? We've left them for all our guests tonight
because Carnival starts at 4 a.m.,'' the Wilden Mann receptionist
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 4 a.m. where?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Right outside your window. The Carnival king gets to select
the headquarters. He chose us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was our second surprise in as many days. ``Zimmer 29 is under
repair; we must give you alternative accommodations,'' the manager
had informed at check-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Zimmer 29 is the only reason we're here,'' I pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you accept our penthouse apartment instead for the entire
length of your stay?'' the manager asked.
</P>
<P>
   If you must be awakened at 4 a.m., you may as well rise in
style.
</P>
<P>
   Two features of that vast apartment stand out in my memory: (1)
The beamed ceiling beside my bed was 5 feet, 6 inches above the
floor; I know because I stand 5 feet, 7 inches. (2) There really
was a harp _ an enormous harp _ in the dining room. And, yes, as
one who toys with the piano, I couldn't resist gingerly tickling
the strings.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the harp could be heard above the pulsating sounds of
kettles, drums and trumpets in the streets below. In terms of
revelry, the Lucerne Carnival would do New Orleans and Rio de
Janeiro proud. The Swiss manage to cram two months' worth of
celebration into about 36 hours, with kids and grandparents alike
decked out in blindingly bright colors _ many wearing masks 2-4
feet tall, masks towering toward the sky and all but defying
description other than to say that political correctness is not an
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Once celebrants wear out the streets, they parade into
restaurants and taverns, instruments in hand, serenading each table
of diners. Then they move on to Basel or another town and begin the
fun anew.
</P>
<P>
   Partied out, we took a different path, or paths: a marathon rail
odyssey in the Swiss Alps on a gloriously snowy, sunny day,
changing trains at Zug, Goschenen, Andermatt, Disentis,
Reichenau-Tamins, Filisur, Davos Platz, Landquart and _ how did
this one get in here? _ Zurich during one 14-hour period. We even
arranged time for walking tours during stopovers.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, as we followed the route of the Glacier Express,
the blizzard was so intense that we were in white-out conditions;
at other points we donned sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any shock that the Dole wine tasted better with every leg?
</P>
<P>
   Next day, we rode six trains to and from Zermatt, my favorite
village in the whole world _ a town where cars are banned and
visitors are greeted at the station by horse-drawn sleighs, a
winter wonderland in the shadow of the spectacular Matterhorn.
</P>
<P>
   If only they'll let us back now that we've almost burned down a
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   You're familiar with two-alarm chili? This was four-alarm beef
fondue. We were about three bites into a delectable repast
(self-cooked, Swiss-style) when the Sterno _ the fuel beneath the
fondue pot _ escaped its container and began spreading fire across
our table.
</P>
<P>
   As we panicked and fellow diners shrieked, the waiter calmly
capped the Sterno, doused the flames and said, ``Care for
seconds?''
</P>
<P>
   That bit of drama set the stage for London.
</P>
<P>
   Including matinees and allowing for theaters being dark on
Sundays, the maximum number of performances we figured we could see
was nine. We saw nine.
</P>
<P>
   Three consecutive evenings were reserved for the musicals ``The
Phantom of the Opera,'' ``Les Miserables'' and ``Chess,'' each
still featuring part of its original cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hankie packs, 2 pounds each,'' an usher barked in the lobby
before the curtain opened for Les Miz. ``Better buy one, luv,'' a
woman advised, wisely (but then we teared up when we saw Fantine
and Eponine perish in Munich two years later, too, and we didn't
understand a word of the German lyrics).
</P>
<P>
   The highlight was a Saturday ``double-header,'' Maggie Smith and
Margaret Tyzack in ``Lettice and Lovage'' in the afternoon and John
Gielgud and Rosemary Harris in ``The Best of Friends`` at night.
Try sleeping after that combination.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Koo. Starring in Agatha Christie's ``And Then
There Were None.'' This was Koo Stark's West End debut, but she was
familiar _ all of her _ to many Londoners via some (how do we say
this gently?) modeling and film endeavors. Thanks to the British
tabloids, she also was familiar as a former companion of Prince
Andrew's. Before Fergie came and went.
</P>
<P>
   Theatrical talent? Suffice it to say that in this particular
mystery she rated higher only than the troupe of Brits we watched
impersonate Puerto Rican singers and dancers in a revival of ``West
Side Story.'' (Try mixing those accents.) Koo, I understand, now
focuses on free-lance photography _ behind the lens.
</P>
<P>
   There was more suspense at our hotel when we returned from 14
hours of theater-hopping, shopping and dining (on mee krob and
chicken tikka) to find wedding attire pressed and cleaned and
draped over chairs, hanging in the closet and laid neatly on the
bed, ready for wearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that the ceremony wasn't planned for today,'' a
typically unfluttered British concierge said when I explained the
mistaken delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, room service brought flowers and champagne _
whether as an apology or as congratulations on my nuptials I'm
still not certain.
</P>
<P>
   One last adventure awaited at Gatwick Airport on the morning of
our return. Our flight to Houston was canceled, for real this time.
But as freeloading first-class passengers, we'd rate priority _ we
would, wouldn't we? _ and as we reached the front of the line, two
seats remained on a painless connection through New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me,'' a harried man in a rush elbowed us aside and
pointed to a dapper, gangling fellow standing nearby. ``We've got
to get Tommy Tune on this flight to New York. It's important.''
</P>
<P>
   So Tommy Tune whistled his way to New York. ``And I can get you
and your companion on the next connection to Houston via Denver,''
the ticket agent offered consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Denver is two hours beyond Houston,'' I argued. ``And
there is a snowstorm in Denver. We'll get stranded.''
</P>
<P>
   What the hay. On a subsequent theater pilgrimage, I'd see
Tune-directed ``Grand Hotel'' and ``The Will Rogers Follies.''
Loved both. And we got in and out of Denver. Eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, almost 12 years later, rekindling memories is almost as
much fun as life on the road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
