 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; IS FBI LEAKING IRRESPONSIBLE THEORIES ON EGYPTAIR CRASH? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Note last graf) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANDREW MARSHALL, The Independent, London &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The mystery of what happened to the Egyptair Boeing
767 which crashed off the U.S. coast two weeks ago may finally be
solved this week, as the tape from the cockpit voice recorder is
painstakingly transcribed and analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation in British and American media has so far blamed
mechanical failure, a struggle between the crew, a bomb, a hijack
and a suicidal crew member _ without any evidence whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   But the nationality of the crew and the plane have apparently
encouraged reporters to make irresponsible guesses at what went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Also, anonymous sources from one U.S. agency have repeatedly
leaked their views to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the leaks may be coming from the FBI, which would take
over the investigation if there was a strong presumption of
criminal activity. The FBI has been heavily criticized for a number
of investigations recently, and is seeking extra funds for an
expansion and reorganization of its activities _ including a new
counter-terrorism unit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (1,000 words) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-RECKLESS-RUMORS-EGYPTAIR-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICANIZED INTERNET TRASHES `BRITISH' ENGLISH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CHARLES ARTHUR, The Independent, London &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The change seemed to be a small one. British people buying the
new version of Apple Computer's operating system, OS9, noticed the
icon for deleting files wasn't called the Wastebasket anymore. It
was called the Trash.
</P>
<P>
   The result was uproar last week: for British users, accustomed
to having an English name for something, this was seen as part of a
creeping _ or possibly rampant _ change worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Around the world, British spellings such as ``colour'' and
``favour'' are being overwhelmed by the American versions _ color,
favor and so on.
</P>
<P>
   American culture, exported in TV series, the Internet and the
language of computers, is overwhelming ``British English'' so fast
that it may not be a question of if, but when, our spellings and
colloquial uses are forgotten. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (600 words) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-NET-KILLS-LANGUAGE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
