<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY ON TAPE: GOOD THINGS IN SMALL PACKAGES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds: See optional trims, optional ending) 
 
By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's beginning to look a lot like Christmas. Let it snow, let it
snow, let it snow.
</P>
<P>
   Just so long as that ``snow'' isn't visual drop-outs on a
defective VHS tape. That could turn someone's holiday gift into
slush.
</P>
<P>
   More often, our December tidings come with comfort, joy and _
boy _ lots of videos. While rentals drive the couch-potato market
month in and month out, year's end is the living end for video
sales.
</P>
<P>
   That means sleighs full of boxed sets, special editions and
holiday-themed videos are dropping into stores like snowflakes on a
reindeer's hide _ not to mention all those spiffy new DVDs that are
taking the United States by storm.
</P>
<P>
   So here's an overview and a guide to home entertainment's annual
gift-grabber campaign. Hopefully there's something here for
everyone _ just hold the snow, please.
</P>
<P>
   (Prices are suggested by the manufacturers. Prices are for VHS
tapes only, unless noted. Some stores and Internet outlets may sell
for less.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHILDREN _ HOLIDAY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disney has issued two new animated movies made especially for
video, each with gift-giving themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey's Once Upon a Christmas'': This entwines three tales
featuring Mickey and Minnie Mouse, Goofy and son Max, Donald and
nephews Huey, Duey and Louie _ and even pets Pluto and Figaro.
Their stories offer music, humor, fun and feeling, as the nephews
experience a spin on ``Groundhog Day'' (it's Christmas every day)
and Mickey and Minnie update O. Henry's classic 1906 short story,
``Gift of the Magi.'' Kelsey Grammer narrates. (VHS $22.99, DVD
$39.99)
</P>
<P>
   ``Winnie the Pooh: Seasons of Giving'': Pooh Bear adds his honey
flavor with five new songs. This film, too, stitches together three
tales. Featured in each are the fun-loving critter pals of Hundred
Acre Wood, from Pooh and Rabbit to Tigger and Piglet. ($22.99)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll Be Home for Christmas'': Disney also has issued the video
premiere of last year's live-action comedy-adventure starring
Jonathan Taylor Thomas. He plays a college student who must cross
America to get home by Christmas Eve. (VHS $22.99, DVD $29.99).
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer'': Golden Books is marking the
35th anniversary of the stop-motion animated title, featuring music
by Burl Ives. The disc includes an interactive trivia game and
video clips of other holiday classics. (DVD debut, $19.98; tape
reissue, $9.98.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
From Nickelodeon come ``Doug: Christmas Story,'' ``Rocko's Modern
Christmas'' and ``Ren &AMP; Stimpy: Have Yourself a Stinky Little
Christmas'' (all $9.95) as well as ``Hey Arnold!: Arnold's
Christmas'' ($12.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seasonal Peanuts videos include the classic ``A Charlie Brown
Christmas''; ``Happy New Year, Charlie Brown'' (both $12.95) and
``It's Christmastime Again, Charlie Brown'' ($9.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Teletubbies get into the spirit with ``Merry Christmas,
Teletubbies!'' ($29.98), a two-tape set with more than 90 minutes
of Teletubbies holiday festivities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a video first, Columbia says its ``The Nuttiest Nutcracker''
is the first computer-animated movie for direct-to-video release.
Featuring the voices of Jim Belushi, Cheech Marin and Phyllis
Diller, on tape it's $14.95 and on disc $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   Barney is back, too. Having sold almost 5 million copies of
``Barney _ Waiting for Santa'' since its release nine years ago,
the purple dinosaur returns with the new ``Barney's Night Before
Christmas.'' Never shown on TV, it's offered as an ambitious DVD
title, with DVD-ROM extras, costing $24.99, or on tape for $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   Still more holiday kidvid titles include Warner's ``How the
Grinch Stole Christmas,'' ``A Christmas Story'' and the
``claymation'' chestnut ``The Year Without a Santa Claus,'' each
$14.95. The first two are on DVD for $19.98 each.
</P>
<P>
   Also offered are ``Miracle on 34th Street'' (both the 1947 and
1994 versions), ``Story of Santa Claus,'' ``A Christmas Carol''
(both animated and the 1984 version starring George C. Scott) and
``Jingle All the Way,'' all for $14.98 each, as well as ``An All
Dogs Christmas Carol'' and ``Prancer'' for $14.95 each, and ``A
Pink Panther Christmas'' for $9.94.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Very Merry Casper Christmas'' features four Casper shorts
for $9.98.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MORE HOLIDAY FILMS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bing Crosby and Fred Astaire star in ``Holiday Inn,'' the 1942
musical featuring the classic song ``White Christmas,'' for $9.98.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, you can't escape perhaps the most popular Christmas
picture ever, ``It's a Wonderful Life.'' The heartwarming
adventures of Jimmy Stewart's George Bailey are on tape for $19.98
and on DVD for $24.98.
</P>
<P>
   But if you prefer a less reverent spin, try ``National Lampoon's
Christmas Vacation'' for $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHILDREN _ NONHOLIDAY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Classic cartoons abound from Bugs Bunny, Tweety Bird and Foghorn
Leghorn in ``Looney Tunes: The Collectors Edition,'' sent from
