<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ANESTHESIA-WAR1128-CO     11-24 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANESTHESIA-WAR1128-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PHYSICIANS AND NURSES WAR OVER THE BUSINESS OF PUTTING YOU TO
SLEEP
 &HT;    Advance for Sunday, Nov. 28
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The next time they lay you on an operating table
and tell you to count to ten backwards, who's going to open that
little valve on the side of the clear tube running down to your
arm?
</P>
<P>
   Will a physician, an anesthesiologist, put you to sleep?
</P>
<P>
   Or will it be a certified registered nurse anesthetist, a
``CRNA,'' the kind of nurse whose profession has been giving
patients anesthesia since before there were any anesthesiologists?
</P>
<P>
   A big time struggle is underway over the answer to those
questions. It has about as many twists and subplots as an episode
of ``ER.'' But between patients, the anesthesiologists and the
CRNAs are not groping it up in the linen closet. This is an angry
row.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it erupted into public view two weeks ago at the
National Naval Medical Center in Bethesda, Md., when the hospital's
top anesthesiologist was sacked for refusing to carry out orders
giving CRNAs unsupervised authority to administer anesthesia to
certain healthy and moderately ill patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alvin Manalaysay, a Navy captain, was relieved of his
command as chief of anesthesiology at the hospital where
presidents, Supreme Court justices and members of Congress are
treated, along with sailors and
</P>
<P>
   admirals.
</P>
<P>
   The action touched off an uproar among Manalaysay's fellow
military and private practice anesthesiologists. For the past week
they have been filling up each other's computer screens with
indignant e-mail about what one called the ``dumbing down'' of
anesthesiology and medicine in general.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Anesthesiologists called for a
congressional investigation and Rep. Dave Weldon, R-Fla., a
physician, said he was talking with members of the Armed Services
Committee about having one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something goes wrong in an operating room, it can be
horrible,'' said Weldon, a Melbourne, Fla., internist. ``The
patient's heart may stop beating. He or she may have a stroke.
Blood pressure may drop to zero. He may start inhaling his own
vomit. It's usually an absolutely catastrophic situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Such circumstances require the presence of a physician,
preferably an anesthesiologist, who has spent years in post-medical
school specialty training, Weldon believes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Carolyn Bannister, an Atlanta anesthesiologist and former
CRNA, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the training is for both professions,'' said
Bannister, who practices pediatric anesthesiology at Children's
Health Care. ``In nurse anesthetist school, you hear about a lot of
diseases very broadly, in very little depth. You get very little
detail about the disease process. You get that training only in
medical school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a nurse anesthetist, I knew there was a lot I
didn't know, but I didn't now how much I didn't know,'' she added.
``It's kind of scary to think about what I was doing and how little
I knew about it.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, anesthesiologists and nurse anesthetists deal with
some pretty scary stuff _ operating room drugs that put a patient
to sleep, block pain and even induce paralysis so that surgeons or
other specialists can work.
</P>
<P>
   But the recovery rate from anesthesia in America is incredibly
good _ something like one death for every 250,000 patients who are
anesthetized. Both professions claim credit for that and the
Bethesda affair is only part of a much larger struggle over whether
doctors or nurses will be in charge of anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Health Care Financing Administration requires
hospitals receiving Medicare reimbursement to provide physician
supervision of nurses who administer anesthesia. The supervising
physician does not have to be an anesthesiologist and may be a
surgeon, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the government proposed removing the requirement.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Nurse Anesthetists and the American
Society of Anesthesiology went to war, with each side whipping
together the customary public opinion polls, scientific surveys of
operating room
</P>
<P>
   survival rates and other ``facts'' that make up the raw material
of a national public policy debate. Comments were submitted to the
proposed rule change. Congressional testimony was drafted and
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   The health financing agency received ``tens of thousands'' of
comments, said spokesman Chris Peacock, and decided to postpone
action.
</P>
<P>
   The federal budget which Congress passed recently contained
language prohibiting any change in the Medicare regulation until a
``study'' has been conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``CRNAs administer anesthesia for all types of surgical cases,
from the simplest to the most complex,'' declares the American
Association of Nurse Anesthetists. CRNAs are the sole anesthesia
providers in
</P>
<P>
   two-thirds of rural hospitals in the United States, the
association's literature points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that means is the operating surgeon often becomes the
supervisor,'' Jan Stewart, a Chicago CRNA and president of the
nurse anesthetist group, said in a telephone interview. ``But their
input is often minimal-to-none, because they know much less about
anesthesia than does the nurse anesthetist.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said that her members are ``highly trained and qualified
professionals who are competent to do all the steps of
anesthesia.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta considered doing a national survey of
anesthesia outcomes but dropped the idea because poor anesthesia
outcomes are so rare, ``it would
</P>
<P>
   be a waste of government money to study it,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that as a nurse anesthetist, she can submit a bill to
Medicare under the plan's Part B, which pays fees to care
providers, and will be paid, with or without supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Part A, which pays for hospitalization, ``still contains the
original language from when Medicare was created in 1964''
requiring hospitals to provide physician supervision, she said.
</P>
<P>
   When a CRNA is supervised by an anesthesiologist, the two
professionals typically split the Medicare fee 50-50. But one
anesthesiologist can supervise up to four nurse-anesthetists
simultaneously. Of the four fees generated in such a case, the
anesthesiologist winds up with two and the four nurses split the
other two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work with nurse anesthetists every day, and I would never do
anything to demean or degrade them as individuals or as a group or
a specialty in nursing,'' said Dr. James McMichael, an Austin,
Texas,
</P>
<P>
   anesthesiologist. ``They have not only a reasonable role but an
absolutely necessary role in the delivery of care, but I think the
public is best served when a nurse anesthetist works under the
direct supervision of an anesthesiologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Neeld of Atlanta, immediate past president of the
American Society of Anesthesiologists, said the debate between the
two professions needs to be toned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to take the rhetoric off the table,'' he said. ``We,
the physicians, need to say that nurse anesthetists are indeed
skilled medical professionals who do a good job at what they are
educated to do. Our professions complement each other and we take
care of patients better when we work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we fight, the only people who do well are our
lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   Weldon believes pressure from nurse anesthetists for
unsupervised privileges in military operating rooms and full
Medicare reimbursement for providing anesthetics in civilian
hospitals is part of a struggle ``that is old as the hills.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of people who want to practice medicine who
aren't doctors,'' he said. ``Optometrists want to do laser surgery.
Psychologists want to prescribe psychiatric drugs. Nurse
practitioners and physician
</P>
<P>
   assistants want to open clinics and see patients.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about an issue of patient safety,'' Weldon
added. ``We are talking about people dying if we let this camel get
his nose in the tent.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
