<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 10:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9915 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: This is the column that ordinarily moves on Thursday. It is
being sent a day early because of the Thanksgiving holiday.
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Jackson right on all counts in Illinois case
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson is taking a lambasting for his trouble on behalf
of seven unruly high school kids in Decatur, Illinois, but he
appears to be right on the merits of the instant case and even more
right against the larger background of worsening racial disparities
in the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   For arguing that the crime (a student brawl in the stands at a
football game) didn't fit the punishment (two-year suspensions from
school), Jackson is denounced, falsely, as wanting to give
out-of-control kids carte blanche.
</P>
<P>
   The Decatur school board scaled the suspensions down to a year,
with the students permitted to study at an alternative school, but
then four suspended students were charged with felonies, as if to
show Jackson a thing or two for butting in. Long suspensions and
criminal charges are heavy wages for a fight in which no one was
seriously hurt and was of a kind that unfortunately is far from
unheard of at high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   The anger of Decatur's black community and Jackson's mediation
are best read against growing black distress at the compounding
inequities in criminal justice, which have reached levels that are
devastating African-American life _ undermining family formation,
seeding unemployment and underemployment and disenfranchising
hundreds of thousands by creating a huge caste of men branded by
criminal records and embittered and socially lamed by imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern is consistent: At every step, blacks are more likely
than whites to get the short end of the stick in comparable
circumstances. More likely in close calls to be charged, more
likely to be tried if charged, more likely to be convicted, to be
imprisoned _ and, on average, likely to be imprisoned longer.
</P>
<P>
   Take kids. According to the U.S. Department of Justice, black
youths between 10 and 17 account for 26 percent of arrests but 32
percent of juvenile court referrals, 41 percent of kids detained,
46 percent of juveniles sent to correctional facilities and finally
52 percent of youths transferred to adult courts _ at the end,
nearly double their in-take proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Or look at drugs. The U.S. Public Health Service found that 14
percent of drug users are black, but African-Americans account for
35 percent of drug arrests, 55 percent of convictions, 74 percent
of prison sentences. Some 65 percent of crack users are white, but
a 1992 study found 93 percent of crack convictions were of
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on. And on, with toxic outfall. In parts of South
Central Los Angeles, 70 percent of the young men are under court
control of one sort or another. And do we expect stable family
lives there?
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson, in Decatur, is not asking us to shrug off
misbehavior. He has made that clear. He is asking us to recognize
that law-and-order overkill against teens virtually assures us not
better adults but dysfunctional adults, the more so when the
excesses heedlessly _ or might it be malignly? _ compound an
already gross and damaging racial inequity.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
