<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-CO     11-24 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Another stay-at-home New Year's Eve
 &HT;    For release, SUNDAY, Nov. 28, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ During my most recent visits to the super market, I have
paused at the section that displays champagne. It is stocked
heavily this year to meet our needs not only for a traditional New
Year's Eve but for the ersatz end of the century and new millennium
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   (I strongly suspect that those entrepreneurs, propelling their
sales toward a century and millennium culmination will, sometime
around mid-2000, admit they were wrong and that the new century and
millennium really starts on Jan. 1, 2001_ to be celebrated with
their champagne and ocean cruises and lots of chicken wings all
over again.)
</P>
<P>
   There have been several times when I was tempted to reach for
the super market champagne, afraid in October and November that if
I really wanted it for Dec. 31, it would be gone by then.
</P>
<P>
   No bottle of bubbly made it into the shopping cart, however.
</P>
<P>
   This old fool plans to watch the clock turn midnight within the
confines of his own house. If any champagne is poured, it will be
there. Likely, I will put down a Diet Dr. Pepper. More likely, I
will be asleep at the celebrating moment, as I was last year.
</P>
<P>
   This can be chalked up to age, but not in the way that you might
think. Indeed, I am aging, but that's not why I became disenchanted
with New Year's Eve. It's just that, through experience, I tired of
the silly hats and horns, of all the tossed away money and of all
the booze so many of us sloshed down even before the champagne was
poured _ not to mention the hefty ransom I had to pay the
babysitter.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I tired of those awful hangover head and eyeball aches
that made watching bowl games on TV the next day an unbearable
chore.
</P>
<P>
   (This counsel is not aimed at young couples _ or singles _ as
they are daily in combat with their demanding jobs, their jumbo
bills and their merciless children. Many have earned the right to
turn loose, if for one night. Celebrate it, guys, but be heedful.
You'll be yearning to stay home in just a few years.)
</P>
<P>
   Supplemented by the century and millennium frenzy, this coming
celebration is beyond bounds. I say ``frenzy'' but I am beginning
to wonder if it is.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami Herald story last week uncovered that many of the major
events across the country as well as hotels and cruise ships have
not yet sold out for the millennium weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Likely, they won't for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One is the inflated cost of tickets and room rates to these
venues. As evidence was the cancellation announced last week of a
$1,000 to $2,500 per ticket New Year's Eve gala in New York City
that featured Aretha Franklin, Andrea Bocelli, Sting, Enrique
Iglesias and Tom Jones. Slow ticket sales were cited for the
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   The other reason is shown in a study by the Travel Industry
Association of America that says 76 percent of Americans likely
will not travel more than 100 miles from home that night. People
simply want to avoid potential chaos; even augured danger.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the premature centennial and millennium
mileposts, even more would be staying home _ not tempted to party
just a couple of weeks in front of Super Bowl, when the parties
seemingly are bigger and more widespread.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, I likely will go to the Orange Bowl Parade early in
the evening then get out of the downtown area and well within the
walls of my home before 10 p.m., as that is when what is attributed
to the cultures of the city's Hispanic population, guns are fired
into the air to welcome the new year. (What goes up, must come
down; but where?)
</P>
<P>
   The century/millennium hubbub is a well-done strategy of the
business world. We need to keep inventing things to celebrate, at
least one a month. But if there is anything to celebrate this time,
it would be that the clock clicks past midnight throughout the
world and the Y2K bug turns out to be nothing more than yet another
overstated anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
