<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9922 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA1125-C     11-24 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA1125-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA1125: Pilgrims to Christ statue are united in
prayer, faith on annual ascent
 &HT;    By Suzanne Gamboa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNLAND PARK, N.M. _ So many arduous steps taken. So little
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed by unwavering faith, beckoned by the spirit of previous
generations, a people separated by the borders of three states and
two countries drew on their common belief that a journey to a
mountain peak on a Sunday might deliver answers to their humble
prayers.
</P>
<P>
   They drew deep breaths and stepped up steep paths, pushed aside
the pain of tired muscles to arrive atop Mount Cristo Rey, where
4,576 feet above sea level an opened-armed statue of Christ
welcomes them, their worries, their pleas, their gratefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask for peace in the world, for all the world's needs, for
what is happening to our brothers and for all who need the love of
God,'' said Maria Consuelo Cordova, 78, one of the thousands who
made the trek.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova's voice boomed atop the summit, where she stood, arms
stretched to the face of Christ looming above her, as she sang in
Spanish the song, ``Cristo Rey'' _ ``Christ the King.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd that formed behind her joined in on the chorus and
followed along as she recited the rosary.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years have passed since the first pilgrimage to the
32-foot-high statue of a robed Jesus Christ and the 40-foot cross
behind him. In those years, the statue has become a thread through
generations of families, as children and grandchildren take up the
tradition of preparing the path to the top, maintaining the statue
and organizing the annual pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration for building the icon is attributed to Monsignor
Lourdes Acosta, the parish priest of the extinct village of
Smeltertown, home to Mexican Americans who worked in the nearby
smelters. A short history book written in 1989 says Acosta
envisioned the mountaintop sanctuary on Oct. 25, 1933.
</P>
<P>
   He went to his parishioners with his vision about the desert
mountain that some knew then as Cerro de Muleros, Mule Drivers
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our parents in Smeltertown, Father Acosta had a meeting
before the monument was completed, and he asked the parents if they
would make a promise that they and their children and their
children's children would continue to maintain the monument and the
road and the pilgrimages,'' said Felix Vasquez Jr., president of
the volunteer Mount Cristo Rey Restoration Committee, which is
funded through donations.
</P>
<P>
   Like other members of the committee, Vasquez's parents helped
build the statue with white limestone from Austin quarries. The
statue faces east, capturing the dawn's light. Despite the years,
the faith and the rituals persevere. People come from throughout
the area, with congestion forming on the paths. A recent Mass was
said by the bishops of El Paso, Las Cruces, N.M., and Ciudad
Juarez, Chihuahua. The readings were lessons on humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like nature, the land. I like to see the faith of the
Catholic people. I like seeing that all the people have faith,
belief and feel good,'' said Jesus Maldonado, 75, of Anthony, N.M.
``I like to see that people will take the time to make a sacrifice
to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of votive candles brought up the dusty paths in plastic
grocery bags were placed at the statue's base, each holding a
personal invocation. A few bouquets of roses were squeezed between
the candles. But much of what comes along with the people is their
deep faith. Guadalupe Villeja, 37, walked barefoot up the sandy
switchbacks that cut through the rugged desert mountain. She held
her year-old daughter Emily in her arms, wrapped in a green
blanket. Three months into her pregnancy with Emily, a doctor had
told her that her daughter had died in her womb, she said. He
recommended the fetus be removed. But she said she visited another
doctor who found Emily's heartbeat, and when the girl was born at 7
pounds, Villeja promised the Virgin de Guadalupe that she would
make the Cristo Rey pilgrimage in her bare feet to give thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My baby's heavy,'' she said in Spanish as she neared the
trail's end, ``but it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosalinda Armendariz was in her 25th year of ascending the
mountain. This year she went barefoot to thank God for the miracle
of her grandchild. Doctors told her daughter her son had spina
bifida, a congenital defect that causes paralysis and other
problems. Armendariz said she asked for divine intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked God for the miracle he created, and two weeks later,
he came out OK,'' said Armendariz, 47, of El Paso. ``If you see him
now, he's perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Some come for the fellowship, for the chance for a Sunday walk
with family and friends. Maria Teresa Loera, 53, of Sunland Park
and her friend Ricarda Santiago, 54, of Ciudad Juarez started early
and said they ran into people they'd met the year before along the
trail.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cristo Rey monument was built, the world was at war.
The statue, designed by Spanish sculptor Urbici Soler, was meant to
be a symbol of peace. Its purpose seems understood by the people
who come. Loera shook her head at the suggestion that she might
pray to win the lottery or for wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ask Christ for riches,'' Loera said in Spanish. ``The
only thing I ask of Christ is he give tranquility to me and my
family and to my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Such religious treks may become more popular as the turn of the
century looms, but most here said they would simply ask that all
goes well in the year 2000. None interviewed said they believed the
end of time approached, although some said that just to be sure,
they'd confess their sins and ask for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Ochoa, the El Paso bishop, said, ``We shouldn't have to wait for
the millennium. We don't have to wait for Christmas Eve or New
Year's Eve. We should live every day as if it's the last day of our
life, ready and willing to be accountable to the Lord Jesus as
Christ the King.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Suzanne Gamboa at sgamboa(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Photos by Deborah Cannon / Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Susan Deltoro puts her arm around her husband, Oscar, as they
pray Sunday in front of the statue at Mount Cristo Rey in Sunland
Park, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   The cliff at the top of Mount Cristo Rey in Sunland Park, N.M.,
is lined with people making their way to the cross at the summit.
The pilgrims come to the Christ the King statue from three counties
and two countries, for different reasons, but in shared fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
