<HEADER>
A9924 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A museum college kids could relish
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Since University of Texas regents want a
building design that will be familiar to Texans for their $60
million to $70 million Jack S. Blanton Museum of Art, why don't
they build an art museum that looks like a Dairy Queen?
</P>
<P>
   When you're talking about Texas architecture, it just doesn't
get much more familiar than DQ. Everybody in Texas knows what a
Dairy Queen looks like. Van Gogh. To go. What's the difference?
I'll have the Picasso -- asket. Mr. Matisse, would you like fries
with that?
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to get a swelled head, but this is a darned good
idea on my part. UT regents were at loggerheads with the heralded
Swiss architectural firm of Herzog &AMP; de Meuron. The regents didn't
like the unusual one-story building with the undulating roof
proposed by the architects. It's a real mess. After the architects
quit the project in frustration, UT Architecture Dean Larry Speck
resigned, saying the Swiss architects were treated badly.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the regents want an art museum with a more
traditional look. What could possibly be more traditional in Texas
than an art museum that looks like the home of the Hungr-Buster?
With 722 DQs, the Lone Star State has more DQs than any other
state.
</P>
<P>
   Just think how much money UT would save if it built a Dairy
Queen-look-alike art museum. Heck, the regents could put the extra
loot into additional luxury boxes at Royal-Memorial Stadium. What
Texan in his right mind wouldn't trade a couple of Renoirs for a
Yugoslavian place-kicker who can knock them home from 60 yards and
a running back to be named later?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, DQs are as much a part of Texas culture as football, a
bowl of red and the smog drifting in from Houston. Everybody who
was raised in a small Texas town has seen the building with the
familiar red mansard roof.
</P>
<P>
   And you didn't think I knew anything about architecture. I'll
bet Rita Clements, wife of former Gov. Bill Clements; retired Tyler
financier Dub Riter; Laredo oilman Tony Sanchez; and Houston
businessman Raul Romero didn't know DQs have a mansard roof.
</P>
<P>
   These four UT regents make up the Facilities Planning and
Construction Committee, the group that scrutinized the undulating
roof building design the Swiss architects presented.
</P>
<P>
   What do these people know about architecture? On Sanchez's
resume, it says he is ``an avid fisherman.'' Great. Just what we
need. An art museum that looks like Roy Bob's Bait &AMP; Tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's this business of having a man called Dub helping
pick out the architectural design. At this rate, UT could become
the only university in the country that has an art museum with
liquid propane on the side of the building.
</P>
<P>
   If the regents don't like my DQ suggestion, why not go with a
Taco Bell design? Taco Bell has that faux-Alamo facade on the
front, which is very Texan. Besides, the university advertises the
fast-food chain every football game at Royal-Memorial Stadium with
an annoying loud BONG sound emanating from the JumboTron video
display board.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, the Taco Bell building plan blends in well with
the Southwestern architecture of many of the buildings on campus.
</P>
<P>
   So what if it has a drive-up window? Maybe Jack S. Blanton likes
burritos.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
