<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9925 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thankful the big people's table got everything wrong
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I have a near-superstitious reluctance to
count my blessings. Even on Thanksgiving. Particularly on
Thanksgiving. I am thankful when we don't get around to the topic.
</P>
<P>
   Blessings, real blessings, don't announce themselves.
Enumerating them in a blessing census seems to endanger them, even
cheapen them. But sometimes you can't escape the topic.
</P>
<P>
   When cornered, I will admit one of the big things I'm thankful
for is that nearly everything wise grownups told me when I was a
kid about the way the world would be right now, at the turn of the
millennium, was just plain wrong.
</P>
<P>
   First some chronology: I was among the last group of American
first graders to be marched into a school cafeteria and told to
practice cowering under tables in preparation for nuclear war.
Being a little kid, I just assumed world wars were things that
break out
</P>
<P>
   from time to time and that crouching under a table could help.
</P>
<P>
   And even if a half-inch of varnished pine offered minimal
protection from atomic fallout, it did get across the idea that
this was a bad, dangerous world we were heading toward, walking
single-file into the future with no talking or cutting up in back.
</P>
<P>
   I tell all this to my kids and they roll their eyes. But they
are 14 and do that no matter what I say.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when I think about the how 20th century was supposed to
end, and I compare it to the world this Thanksgiving, the contrast
is striking and beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: The Soviets will expand into a divided free
world. Stay under the table.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: McDonalds expanded into Russia.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: Motorists will be enraged as the global oil
supply begins running dry. We will face high prices, long lines,
rationing and dinky cars.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: Motorists are enraged after gasoline prices clib
from 99 cents a gallon to $1.40 a gallon in less than year. Car
commercials mention built-in cup holders but not miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: Congress will be locked in battle and unable
to react to the depression caused by our insurmountable budget
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: Congress is locked in battle and fortunately
unable to jeopardize the national economic expansion helped along
by a budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: Computerization will cause widespread
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: The computer industry worries about finding
enough employees.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: We'll all end up working for the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: We'll end up working for Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: Information will be more controlled as
newspapers are replaced by a few centralized television networks.
People will think more alike as a result.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: Television networks are being replaced by cable
and the Internet. I turn off The Coleslaw Wrestling Channel and
check out the Web site of the Southern Red-haired Dyslexic League.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: World famine will break out as population
outstrips farm production.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: Farmers are threatened by depressed prices
because of a worldwide grain glut.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: Florida will be invaded by Cuban communists.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: Florida was invaded by Cuban capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: Global warming will melt the ice caps in
another 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: Global warming will melt the ice caps in yet
another 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   What we were told: We're on the verge of nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: We're on the verge of figuring out how to dispose
of outdated nuclear missile parts.
</P>
<P>
   What I was told: You will grow up, straighten out and lead a
normal life.
</P>
<P>
   What happened: I became a newspaper columnist.
</P>
<P>
   So this Thanksgiving, I look across the table, joyful that I
wheedled my way into the house of someone who can cook. I wish upon
my children a continuation of these blessings continue and that
everything I warn them about is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane writes for The Daytona Beach News-Journal, Daytona,
Fla. E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
