<HEADER>
A9926 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In America people can speak their minds no matter how narrow
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The Ku Klux Klan, in all it slimy variations, is a
despicable organization with un-American views.
</P>
<P>
   That's my view. I have a constitutional right to express my
views on the Ku Klux Klan, which is the American way.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, Klan members have a constitutional right to
express their views, which also is the American way.
</P>
<P>
   While their ability to express their views may be the American
way, I believe the Klan's views of white supremacy, racial
divisiveness, intolerance and bigotry oppose the American way.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month about a dozen hooded members of a Ku Klux
Klan faction from Indiana came to Waco. Oh, happy day.
</P>
<P>
   The masked bigots held a rally on the courthouse steps to
express their views on the government's actions at the Branch
Davidian compound in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A follow-up letter to the editor from Waco's Katie Mayfield
expressed the opinion that McLennan County Commissioner Lester
Gibson's proposal to require a five-day notice for people who want
to speak on county property should have been given more
consideration by the other commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   She said it cost thousands of dollars for extra police and
security during the Klan's courthouse rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it would have been all right if they would have burned
a cross on the courthouse lawn,'' Mayfield concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield evidently feels the same way I do about the Klan. But
there is a difference between the Klan's right to express their
views and burning a cross on the courthouse lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The Klan's views are protected by the First Amendment.
``Congress shall make no law ... abridging the freedom of speech
... or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to
petition the Government for redress of grievances.''
</P>
<P>
   The Klan has just as much right to make a speech on the
courthouse steps as does the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Burning a cross on the courthouse lawn, however, likely would
get them arrested. There are laws against the destruction of public
property. Besides, the county has a burn ban in effect due to our
prolonged drought.
</P>
<P>
   Besides harming property, there also are laws against harming
people _ or even making imminent threats to harm people.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have a right to express their views, but they do not
have a right to act on those views if their actions violate
existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Klan members expressed their views on the courthouse steps
and slimed their way back home again to Indiana where I hope they
stay.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks earlier, Ku Klux Klan members met at Foley Square in
New York City. They had been denied sound equipment by the courts.
They also had been denied the ability to wear masks. Supreme Court
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg upheld an old New York state law that
prohibits masks at public demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the Washington Post, constitutional expert Nat
Hentoff said the children brought by their parents to the rally to
see the bigots ``got a vivid First Amendment lesson when a young
woman in the crowd said of the Klan members, `This is America. They
have a right to speak.'''
</P>
<P>
   For expressing that view, Hentoff said a mob of
counter-demonstrators surrounded the woman, kicked and spat at her
and, according to the New York Times, beat her on the head with
flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they didn't burn the flags,'' Hentoff wrote. After being
pummelled to the ground, the woman finally escaped into the
Municipal Building.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the woman who defended free speech was
un-American.
</P>
<P>
   For America to remain free, free speech must be preserved, even
for repulsive Ku Klux Klan members.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
