<HEADER>
A9927 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kicking out a laminated window impossible
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The National Highway Safety
Transportation Administration is trying to drown sports-utility
vehicle drivers, and I guess it's up to me to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   But before I save our government from folly, a bit of good news:
Judith Silverman of Flushing, N.Y., writes to say that where
decades of quality nagging failed to get her husband to wear his
seat belt, one of my columns turned him around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been living with a man for 34 years, and for those 34
years he has refused to wear a seat belt. He has maintained that he
would rather rely on his reflexes than be trapped by a seat belt in
a crash.''
</P>
<P>
   That changed this summer during the Silvermans' annual visit.
``You wrote your article and John has been wearing his seat belt
ever since.... Thank you, thank you, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   When I went back to the article to see what thunderclap of logic
won the former knucklehead over, I was somewhat deflated to see
that all credit goes to members of West Palm Beach Fire Department
No. 5. Turns out it was their vivid accounts of attending hundreds
of ``ejection'' crash scenes that proved so _ well, instructive.
Typical was fireman Jim Harmon's explanation of how passengers
manage to leave a side window.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people go out a side window, it's usually only half way,
and then the car crushes them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers agreed that when most passengers leave the car,
it's face first through the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   The exception seems to be SUVs, which according to the NHTSA,
tend to roll because of their high centers of gravity, and fling
passengers out side windows, which are designed to shatter into
harmless pebbles. According to The Washington Post, NHTSA is
proposing to replace the disintegrating glass with a laminated
glass. Laminated glass, the kind in your windshield, is super tough
and designed to crack and sag, but not shatter.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's good when it keeps arms and heads inside the SUV.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not so good when a car goes into a canal or a lake or a
river.
</P>
<P>
   To escape a submerged car, it is often necessary to break out a
side window, especially if the doors are stuck and the power
windows have shorted out.
</P>
<P>
   I know whereof I speak. A few years ago after a spate of local
canal drownings, I did some field work in the desperate art of
breaking out of an automobile with inoperable windows and learned
some things that could save your life:
</P>
<P>
   _ Never mind what you may have seen in the movies: A windshield
cannot be kicked out or broken by the strongest man. I swung a
sledge hammer against the windshield of a junkyard car and with
repeated hard blows, could make it only crack and sag. You must go
out a side window or the back window.
</P>
<P>
   _ One of the easiest ways to break a side window is to rap it
smartly with a heavy metal tool. The metal end of a large
flashlight battery will do the job splendidly. But can you keep a
battery where you can find it in pitch darkness while you are
fighting panic?
</P>
<P>
   _ A heavy slot screwdriver will shatter a window if you force it
into the top edge, pry and twist. It works like magic. Again, do
you keep a heavy screwdriver in the front seat with you?
</P>
<P>
   _ Other than a hammer, the best tool for breaking out of a car
is a spring center-punch, available for under $10 at most hardware
stores. With this device, you jam the pointed end of the tool
against the glass, causing a spring to retract and deploy with
shattering force.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's say the NHTSA at some future date does mandate
laminated side glass for SUVs. This may save some unbelted nitwits
from ejection, but it's going to be a death sentence to those who
end up in a canal. Why? Because when side windows become as tough
as windshields, no screwdriver or spring center punch is going to
save you in 15 feet of water with three minutes of air.
</P>
<P>
   Just to let NHTSA know what I think of their unbreakable side
glass idea, I called up the agency and told crash research engineer
Stephen Summers, and he said that I was right, that if future
automobiles have unbreakable side glass and people can't get their
doors open in deep water, they're going to have to wait until
somebody can cut them out. That, he conceded, can get tedious when
you're holding your breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our studies show that only 0.3 percent of auto fatalities
involve entrapment,'' Summers said. ``It just doesn't happen as
often as people think.''
</P>
<P>
   In the brutal numbers game of crash deaths, the crash specialist
said, for every person who perishes from fire or drowning, 300 are
killed by ejection through a side window. ``Crime prevention is
another concern,'' he added. ``With laminated side windows, smash
and grab thefts are prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in all probability according to the researcher, all cars
will come equipped with tough glass all around. And when that day
comes and you find yourself at the bottom of a canal with your
doors stuck, as for all the break-out advice given above:
</P>
<P>
   Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   RON WIGGINS writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: ronwiggins(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
