<HEADER>
A9928 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traffic incivility is scary
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The unopened beer can hit the side of our car
with all the force of irrational hatred.
</P>
<P>
   A van passenger in the left lane shouted at us, his face
contorted with rage.
</P>
<P>
   It was, we assumed, a bad review of Jim's driving, though we
were mystified as to the exact nature of our breach in highway
etiquette. Driving the speed limit, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   The van sped away before we could get a license plate number. We
thought about reporting the incident, but never got around to it.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to hear about road rage, and another to see its
face.
</P>
<P>
   The stranger in the van didn't know whether that beer can would
smash our window and cause injury or an accident. He didn't stop to
think whether there was a child in the car seat.
</P>
<P>
   The beer can left only a slight nick in our Saturn _ and a far
greater dent in our psyches. It made me feel less secure, knowing,
in such a visceral way, that there are folks out there who could
turn murderous for no reason.
</P>
<P>
   In Rochester, N.Y., Monday, John Creel, 29, was convicted of
assault in the beating of retiree Ross Sperring, 79. Creel
apparently became so enraged by the older man's slow driving that
he jumped out at a red light and beat Sperring severely.
</P>
<P>
   Sperring died of complications from pneumonia two months after
the July 1998 beating. Just a coincidence, probably. Authorities
were unable to establish a link.
</P>
<P>
   But a part of me can't help wondering if the old man just didn't
give up. If he grew weary of a society in which such incivility
could take place. In which a young man, instead of helping his
elder across the street, beats him up for not moving it along fast
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, car ads glorify highway chauvinism. A current
Mitsubishi ad mocks the concept of good sportsmanship: No matter
how gracious a winner you are on the surface, deep inside you're
crowing: ``Nah nah nah nah nah, I'm better than you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, folks are driving Humvees, and SUVs are getting
bigger and bigger, with more and more testosterone-dripping names.
Can the Intimidator or the Devastator be too far in our future?
</P>
<P>
   There's no real way of tracking whether highway barbarity is on
the rise or not, said Lt. John Born, spokesman for the Ohio Highway
Patrol: ``There is no scientific formula for determining a road
rage incident, other than aggressive or violent driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Are such incidents on the rise? Born can only offer anecdotal
evidence: In Mansfield, a motorist throws a cast-iron bottle jack
into a car, injuring another motorist in the face. In Madison
County, an off-duty police officer is shot at random, with his
entire family in the car. He survived.
</P>
<P>
   Highway Patrol officials can't quantify or explain the problem.
They can only work toward solving it.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Highway Patrol established a program known as
TRIAD (Targeting Reckless Intimidating and Aggressive Driving).
Working with local agencies, the Highway Patrol sends up 12
aircraft in heavily congested areas to monitor aggressive driving.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists should report incidents such as ours, Born said. If
patrol officials receive several calls on the same incident, they
may be able to nab a suspect. The Highway Patrol has recently
established its toll-free I-877-7PATROL number for motorists who
need help with emergency or non-emergency situations. ``Many people
are hesitant to call if it's not an emergency,'' Born said.
</P>
<P>
   I know what he meant.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't call. In 1999, we knew, that would never qualify as an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
