<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9936 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-TAKE     11-24 1832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: What connection, if any, did presidential candidate George W.
Bush have to the failed savings and loan institution and subsequent
bailout by the U.S. government?
</P>
<P>
   A: We've answered this question before, but since there seems to
be continuing interest, let's give it another shot in hopes it will
put the matter to rest.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush had no connection to the case you're asking
about. It was Neil Bush, one of George W.'s brothers, who was a
figure in the Silverado Banking, Savings and Loan Association in
Colorado. Silverado failed in 1988, costing taxpayers an estimated
$1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Although Neil Bush never was charged with criminal wrongdoing,
he agreed to pay $50,000 in 1992 to settle a civil lawsuit lodged
two years earlier by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recent articles about British Home Secretary Jack Straw raise
a question I've always wondered about. What does Britain's Home
Office do? What is the equivalent in the U.S. government?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Home Office is the department of the British government
responsible for internal affairs in England and Wales. As its
Internet site states, the office's principal goal is ``to build a
safe, just and tolerant society in which the rights and
responsibilities of individuals, families and communities are
properly balanced and the protection and security of the public are
maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, the Home Office says its aims are the
reduction of crime and the fear of crime; the maintenance of public
safety; the delivery of justice through effective and efficient
investigation, prosecution, trial and sentencing, and through
support for victims of crime; the prevention of terrorism and
protection against threats to national security; the regulation of
the entry of non-citizens into the United Kingdom; and the
maintenance of the safety of the public through civil protection.
</P>
<P>
   There's no exact equivalent in this country. Gillian Cooper of
the British Consulate in Atlanta said that what the Home Office
does is ``a bit of a mixture of the duties and responsibilities of
several agencies at both the federal and state levels'' in the
United States. Think of the FBI, State Department, the Immigration
and Naturalization Service and state-level secretaries of state,
and you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about a Seabee museum that is
being built somewhere in the East? My uncle was a Seabee in World
War II and I inherited many souvenir objects from him. Perhaps a
museum would be interested in the memorabilia. Who can I contact?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Navy Seabee Veterans of America is in the beginning
stages of creating its new museum in Rhode Island. Ed Turner,
former Seabee who is coordinating the project, said it will be part
of the U.S. Navy Seabees Memorial Park, on a 6-acre site at what
used to be the Seabee Center at Davisville, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said the veterans' group, ranging in age ``up to
85-plus,'' is very enthusiastic about the museum, and indeed does
welcome donations of memorabilia as well as money. Some items
already donated include uniforms and medals as well as a large
Quonset hut to house the museum.
</P>
<P>
   When completed, the park will have several more Quonset huts and
other buildings, Turner said, including the restored Chapel in the
Pines. Construction is expected to take several more years. ``We're
moving along a little at a time,'' he added. ``Most of us are from
World War II and Korea, so we're along in age. Things don't move as
fast as they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   For information about donating items, call Turner at
401-732-4565. Checks can be made out to Seabee Memorial Park Fund
and mailed to: Seabee Memorial Park, P.O. Box 646, North Kingstown
02852. Information online can be viewed at www.nsva.org and click
on Davisville Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you clarify Adolf Hitler's last name for me? I thought he
was born with the surname Schicklgruber. If that's the case, why
did he change it to Hitler?
</P>
<P>
   A: Adolf Hitler was the Nazi dictator's birth name. He never
used any other. Born on April 20, 1889, he was the fourth child of
the third marriage of Alois Hitler, a customs official, and Klara
Polzl Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   It was Alois Hitler's mother whose surname was Schicklgruber
(first names: Maria Anna). She was unmarried when Alois was born,
but about five years later she married Johann Georg Hiedler, a
wandering miller. Some sources say Hiedler may have been Alois
Hitler's father.
</P>
<P>
   Hiedler died in 1856, when Alois was 20, never having officially
recognized Alois as his child. In 1877, Hiedler's brother arranged
for Alois to be registered as the legitimate son of Johann Georg
and Maria Hiedler. World Book Encyclopedia theorizes that the
priest who made the official entry misspelled the name as
``Hitler.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, before he came to power, some of Adolf Hitler's
political opponents in Germany and Austria called him
Schicklgruber, intending it as an insult. That may be the source of
your confusion over his birth name.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Considering the recent earthquakes all over the world, can
you give us any tips on what we should do if we're inside a
building when an earthquake strikes?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Federal Emergency Management Agency advises taking cover
under a piece of heavy furniture or against an inside wall. It
warns that the most dangerous thing to do during the shaking is
attempting to leave the building, because objects can fall on you.
So stay inside.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross gives similar pointers, adding that you
should stay away from windows and, in a high-rise building, be
prepared for the fire alarms and sprinklers to go off.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will you settle a bet? A friend swears that Leonardo DiCaprio
got his start on a TV program when he was a teenager. I think his
show business career is based entirely on his movies. Who's right?
</P>
<P>
   A: Chalk this one up for your friend. As a teen, DiCaprio landed
a successful, regular role as Luke Brower, a homeless youngster in
ABC's teen sitcom, ``Growing Pains.'' It was a small part that
lasted only for the program's 1991 season, but Leo-watchers say his
performance proved that he had great potential, outshining the rest
of the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, he had done some minor TV work in commercials and
educational programs such as ``How to Deal With a Parent Who Takes
Drugs'' and ``Mickey's Safety Club.'' He appeared in more than 30
commercials and made guest appearances on such TV shows as
``Lassie,'' ``The Outsiders,'' ``Roseanne'' and ``Parenthood.''
</P>
<P>
   His big break on the silver screen was his leading role as Toby
in ``This Boy's Life.'' But he'll always be known worldwide for his
role as Jack Dawson in ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Ted Turner once managed the Atlanta Braves
for one game. What was that all about?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was in May 1977. The Braves were in the midst of a 16-game
losing streak, and the Pittsburgh Pirates were on an 11-game
winning streak. In one of the most hilarious chapters in Braves
history, Turner decided to take over the duties of then-manager
Dave Bristol, giving Bristol a short sabbatical.
</P>
<P>
   Turner sensed trouble looming with the National League offices
and even attempted _ and failed _ to reach Chub Feeney, the league
president, for clearance before the game. After Cito Gaston showed
him how to put on his socks, Turner called the staff together and
realigned their responsibilities. The upshot was that the Braves
lost again, 2-1. The next day, Feeney banished Turner from the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is ``racketeering'' defined?
</P>
<P>
   A: The simple definition is ``the practice of conducting or
engaging in a racket, such as extortion or bootlegging.'' Black's
Law Dictionary explains further that racketeering is an organized
conspiracy to commit the crimes of extortion and coercion. From the
standpoint of extortion, the dictionary continues, it's the
obtaining of money or property from another, without his consent,
induced by the wrongful use of force or fears. The fear which
constitutes the legally necessary element in extortion is induced
by verbal or written threats of bodily or property harm, it adds.
</P>
<P>
   Racketeering activity, according to the U.S. Code, is organized
criminal activity to commit certain offenses, which include credit
card fraud, loan sharking, money laundering, police corruption and
interstate prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A Medal of Honor recipient who was protesting the School of
the Americas at Fort Benning, Ga., was quoted as saying he
``renounced the special privileges the medal brought: a lifetime
job with the Veterans Administration and a $600-a-month pension.''
Is that correct? I was under the impression that Medal of Honor
winners received a $200-a-month pension, and that was all.
</P>
<P>
   A: Medal of Honor recipients are entitled to a $600-a-month
stipend from the Department of Veterans Affairs, said VA spokesman
Tom Thomas, ``and that's it,'' unless there's some additional VA
compensation they would be entitled to for disability. Thomas added
that he isn't aware of any kind of federal employment benefits to
which Medal of Honor recipients are entitled through VA programs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Charlton Heston, a leading proponent of the right to bear
arms for the purpose of having a ready militia, ever serve in the
military? Or is he strictly a ``silver screen'' veteran?
</P>
<P>
   A: During World War II, Heston served with the 11th Army Air
Force in Alaska's Aleutian Islands. He was an aircraft radio gunner
there for most of his three-year tour, according to Current
Biography Yearbook. He was discharged in early 1947.
</P>
<P>
   As you say, Heston, president of the National Rifle Association,
is outspoken about his belief in the right of citizens to own guns.
He was in the news earlier this month when he spoke before the
House Government Reform Committee's panel on criminal justice, drug
policy and human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that in order for a department store's huge Christmas
tree to stay healthy, it needed 300 gallons of water and 200
aspirin tablets. What would the aspirin have been for?
</P>
<P>
   A: Aspirin helps suppress bacteria and micro-organisms that
might clog the cells that transport the water to the top of the
tree. The leaves (or needles) are still pulling water from the base
of the tree, and if micro-organisms plug those cells the tree can't
get any water and will dry out.
</P>
<P>
   The same theory holds true for cut flowers, so if someone gives
you a dozen roses, pop an aspirin or two into their water and trim
their stems to make them last longer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
