<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9940 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-TAKE     11-24 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2 takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The fight and subsequent expulsion from school of several
black students in Decatur, Ill., has received extensive news
coverage. But I don't remember seeing any reports at the time it
happened in September. What was the background?
</P>
<P>
   A: Described variously as a riot, a grandstand-clearing brawl or
a simple fistfight, the incident occurred Sept. 17 at a football
game between the Eisenhower High School Panthers and the MacArthur
High School Generals. It appears to have been preceded by a fight
that same day between students at the two schools.
</P>
<P>
   As the Chicago Sun-Times reported, the football teams at both
schools were having a dismal season, so city bragging rights were
at stake. The Panthers, who had lost every game before this one,
were leading at the half. At the start of the third quarter,
screams were heard erupting from the stands when the fighting broke
out. It isn't known who started it, but the scene was partially
captured by a spectator's video camera, so some of those involved
could be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Four youths were charged with mob action, a felony. One also was
charged with felony aggravated battery and resisting a police
officer, a misdemeanor. Ed Boehm, the MacArthur principal, said his
school received seven injury reports after the fight, mostly for
bruises and abrasions.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, who is leading an effort in support of
the expelled students, pointed out that no bullets were fired and
no bones broken. ``We see more violence than this at a hockey
match,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about Dahlonega, Ga., made me wonder about the
discovery of gold in Charlotte, N.C., many years earlier. Can you
refresh my memory about the time lines of gold in both places?
</P>
<P>
   A: You may be thinking of the Reed gold mind, now a North
Carolina state historic site, about 30 miles east of Charlotte. It
was the site in 1799 of one of the earliest discoveries of gold in
America. Charlotte's gold discovery came in 1825 when Samuel McComb
found gold at Irwin Creek. The ``rush'' to Charlotte's mines
followed, circa 1830. The Charlotte branch of the U.S. Mint opened
in 1838 and closed in 1861.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlonega historians say that in 1828, Benjamin Parks was deer
hunting when he overturned a rock and discovered it to be laced
with gold. In 1838, the Dahlonega branch of the U.S. Mint opened;
it closed, never to reopen, in 1861 at the outbreak of the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   In 1849, the California gold rush drew most miners west, with
promises of far more gold than could be found in North Carolina or
Georgia. By 1906, the last large Dahlonega mining company,
Consolidated Mining, closed its operation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did the EgyptAir crash occur in international waters? Why
don't we hear much about Egypt's involvement in the investigation?
</P>
<P>
   A: The site of the Oct. 31 crash _ which occurred in the
Atlantic Ocean about 60 miles south of Nantucket Island, Mass. _ is
indeed international waters. Under the International Civil Aviation
Organization treaty, the investigation of a plane crash in
international waters is under the jurisdiction of the country of
registry of the aircraft. However, the U.S. National Transportation
Safety Board said the Egyptian government requested that it take
the lead in this investigation, which it initially did. The FBI
took over the investigation later when there was an indication of a
criminal act.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Egyptian representatives have helped review cockpit
voice recordings. Other agencies and organizations involved in the
early stages included the Federal Aviation Administration, Defense
Department, Coast Guard, National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, Boeing Co., EgyptAir and Pratt &AMP; Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Soon after the crash of EgyptAir flight 990, I heard that
after the plane took off from Los Angeles, it landed at Edwards Air
Force Base in California before continuing to New York. I haven't
seen or heard anything more about that. What can you tell me?
</P>
<P>
   A: National Transportation Safety Board records show no such
thing, said NTSB spokesman Keith Holloway. Flight 990 left Los
Angeles at 4:30 p.m. local time (7:30 p.m. EDT) Oct. 30. It landed
at Kennedy Airport in New York just over five hours later, at 12:48
a.m. EDT Oct. 31. There was no stop anywhere in between, Holloway
stated.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Early reports after the crash of EgyptAir 990 stated that one
body had been recovered. Was that person ever identified?
</P>
<P>
   A: National Transportation Safety Board spokesman Keith Holloway
in Washington said the NTSB ``heard that initial report'' about a
body being recovered, but it was false. ``We never stated that we
found a body,'' he addded.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The language difficulties encountered with the crash of
EgyptAir flight 990 prompt my question: How do pilots of foreign
airlines communicate with English-speaking people in control
towers?
</P>
<P>
   A: Even those pilots whose first language isn't English are
required to communicate in English with traffic controllers. In
other words, English is the universal language in this situation. A
spokeswoman for the Federal Aviation Administration said, however,
that the language spoken in the cockpit among pilots and crew is
totally up to them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Of all the known meteors in space, are there any that
actually could break the Earth apart in the event of a collision?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Most of the objects we see as meteors are about the size
of a grain of sand. J. Scott Shaw, professor of astronomy at the
University of Georgia, explains that larger objects, such as small
asteroids _ ranging in diameter from hundreds of feet up to a few
miles _ have hit the Earth over its 4.5-billion-year history and
have been very devastating, forming craters many miles in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, the only object that even came close to
splitting the Earth apart was the collision with an object about
the size of Mars soon after the Earth formed. This collision
produced the debris that formed the moon. ``We know where all the
Mars-sized objects are in the solar system,'' Shaw said. ``They are
the planets, and they're not going to collide with the Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: A museum exhibit of Norman Rockwell's paintings includes many
years' worth of Saturday Evening Post covers using his artwork.
They appear to have been collected by someone from Burlington,
Iowa, whose name is on the address labels. Do you know anything
about that person, and how he happened to collect them all?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Norman Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge, Mass., has no
information about the person, or couple, who subscribed to the
Saturday Evening Post and saved all the issues whose covers are on
display.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Rawson of the Rockwell Museum said all that is known is
that the collection was donated in memory of G. Robert Rapp by his
family after his death. It appears that Rapp had purchased the
covers from the original collector, but other than that, she had no
details about the original collector or about Rapp himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockwell Museum, incidentally, says its reference center
welcomes donations to its collections relating to Rockwell's life
and work. The collection presently includes first uses of
Rockwell's artwork, such as magazine covers, and correspondence,
photographs, negatives, slides, films, recordings and original
prints.
</P>
<P>
   Information is available online at www.nrm.org or from the
Norman Rockwell Museum at Stockbridge, P.O. Box 308/Route 183,
Stockbridge, MA 01262 (413-298-4100).
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Baby Sitter with Screaming Infant,'' one of Norman
Rockwell's paintings, has an actual diaper pin embedded through the
canvas. Who put it there, and why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rockwell himself gets the credit. ``He was a very funny man
who often included that kind of playful, funny gesture in his
art,'' said Ann Knutson, curator of the Rockwell exhibit at
Atlanta's High Museum of Art. He also did it to add texture and
three dimensions. Rockwell thought that if he simply painted the
pin, and then it was photographed for a Saturday Evening Post
cover, it might not reproduce well. Hence, the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One of Norman Rockwell's paintings depicts Rosie the Riveter
of World War II fame. Someone told me there was a real Rosie, but I
never heard that before. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rose Will Monroe, a United Auto Workers riveter in an
aircraft plant in Ypsilanti, Mich., is the real-life person behind
the famous poster character. Her image was created to celebrate the
dedication and resourcefulness of millions of American women who
worked in factories to produce armaments for the United States and
the Allies during the war. The National World War II Memorial
Campaign, which is raising money for a memorial in Washington,
formed the Rose Monroe Society in her name to honor the sacrifice
and effort of those pioneering women. Information: 1-800-639-4992.
</P>
</TEXT>
