<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-COOK25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memories fresh from the oven
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Holidays are for making memories.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the holidays can be memorable as well. Just ask
Jane Breskin Zalben.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holidays bring families and friends together to share special
times, special traditions and special foods,'' writes the popular
author-illustrator in the introduction to her recently published
book, ``To Every Season: A Family Holiday Cookbook'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``When children work alongside adults to help prepare these
special dishes, cooking becomes fun,'' she adds. ``By sharing love,
family histories and dreams while we cook, we turn an ordinary task
into something meaningful.''
</P>
<P>
   Zalben, who has written and illustrated a number of children's
books featuring lovable animal characters and charming watercolor
paintings, is perhaps best-known for her Jewish holiday series
featuring Pearl the lamb. She has also written novels for older
readers.
</P>
<P>
   Zalben said families become close emotionally and physically
when they cook together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives everyone a sense of accomplishment,'' she adds.
``You're taking different ingredients, putting them together and
getting something tangible at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking is a way for generations to connect. It is a time to
talk, to teach customs and values, to allow children to take
chances and to get close.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids learn practical skills as well: math when they measure,
chemistry when they see things rise and fall, and art when they
decorate a cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   Concludes Zalben: ``And nothing can top the moment when a
special treat comes to the table, the child says, `I made it!' and
everyone sighs `ooh!' and `aah!'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
