<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9942 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TURKEY-PRIMER25-COX     11-24 2392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-PRIMER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everything you need to know to make a great holiday meal
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Maybe it's the first Thanksgiving dinner
you've ever cooked, or maybe it's been a while since you've done
one. Let's say you have 12 people coming over, and you need some
help.
</P>
<P>
   Sit down and read our instructions for the basic turkey dinner.
If you follow our advice, you should be able to pull it off with
few mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   MENU
</P>
<P>
   Roast turkey
</P>
<P>
   Herb stuffing with mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Giblet gravy
</P>
<P>
   Perfect mashed potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry-orange relish
</P>
<P>
   Traditional pumpkin pie
</P>
<P>
   THE TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Picking the right size: Buying the right size turkey is your
first hurdle. If you're planning on a big bird, you must have a big
refrigerator-freezer. Turkeys must stay frozen and be thawed in
cool temperatures to prevent food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Plan on serving 1/2 pound to 3/4 pound of turkey meat per
person, but consider the other foods on the menu, kids' appetites
and whether you want leftovers. Remember that only about 50 percent
to 58 percent of a whole turkey is edible.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you have 12 guests, you'd need 6 to 9 pounds of meat,
which you would find on a 12- to 18-pound turkey. (If you want
leftovers, go for the 18-pounder.)
</P>
<P>
   How to store the turkey: Store the turkey in the freezer, and
allow 5 hours per pound to thaw in the refrigerator, or 1/2 hour
per pound in cold water. So an 18-pound bird would take 90 hours to
thaw in the fridge; 9 hours in cold water. If using cold water,
change it every half hour. The thawed turkey will keep in the
refrigerator, wrapped, until Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Never thaw the turkey on the counter, and do not stuff the
turkey in advance, because bacteria may grow. U.S. Department of
Agriculture suggests you not stuff it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing the bird: In a clean sink, unwrap the turkey and wash
skin well. Unhook the legs from the leg clamp and remove the bags
of giblets and neck from the cavity. Set these aside for making
gravy or stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Wash the inside of the bird, and cut off the fatty knob of skin
at the rear of the bird. Season the inside and skin of bird with
salt and pepper; set on a tray. Wrap in plastic and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   How to roast the turkey: For open-pan roasting, preheat the oven
to 325 degrees. Put the bird in a roasting pan large enough to hold
the drippings. Sturdy, disposable aluminum pans are fine for this.
If you decide to stuff the bird, stuff it from the back cavity
first, then from the front. Important: The stuffing should be
packed loosely so that it will cook through.
</P>
<P>
   Sew up the front of the bird; put the legs back in the leg-lock
to hold the rear cavity closed. Sew the rear cavity if it gapes.
</P>
<P>
   Spread butter or oil and seasonings, such as poultry seasoning,
thyme or sage, over the skin of the turkey. Use a loose tent of
aluminum foil (shiny side down) over the bird during the first 2
hours of roasting to keep it from overbrowning.
</P>
<P>
   Baste the turkey with pan drippings, or use flavored liquids
such as fruit juice, honey-mustard or bourbon.
</P>
<P>
   The turkey will continue to cook once it's removed from the
oven, so take care not to overcook. After 2 hours in the oven,
check it with a meat thermometer. Cook it to 180 degrees on a
thermometer stuck in the thickest part of the thigh meat _ don't
let the thermometer touch a bone. Juices should run clear. Check
the stuffing also with the thermometer _ it should read 165
degrees. (See chart below for approximate roasting times.) Let the
turkey sit at least 30 minutes on the counter after it's cooked for
perfect slicing.
</P>
<P>
   CRANBERRY-ORANGE RELISH
</P>
<P>
   1 (12-ounce) bag fresh cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1 orange, washed, cut in quarters, seeded
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, washed, cut in quarters, seeded
</P>
<P>
   1 lime, washed, cut in quarters, seeded
</P>
<P>
   Sugar to taste
</P>
<P>
   Wash berries and pick out the bad ones. Place berries in food
processor or blender container and pulse until very coarsely
chopped.
</P>
<P>
   Put orange, lemon and lime in container (note: do not peel).
Process until all are chopped finely, and the mixture is of relish
consistency. Sprinkle with sugar to taste; blend a few seconds
more. Adjust sweetness, and store in refrigerator until ready to
use.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   HERB STUFFING WITH MUSHROOMS
</P>
<P>
   8 cups toasted bread cubes _ white,
</P>
<P>
   rye or cornbread
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 stalks celery, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mushrooms, trimmed and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cream sherry
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground sage
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   bunch parsley, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken or turkey broth
</P>
<P>
   (use broth from cooking giblets)
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter over medium heat in large skillet. Add onion, garlic
and celery and saute for 10 minutes. Stir in mushrooms and sherry
and continue to cook for another 10 minutes, stirring frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Add vegetables, liquid and all, to cubed bread and mix well. Mix
in seasonings. If stuffing seems dry, moisten with broth.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking stuffing outside the bird is recommended. But if you are
stuffing the turkey, stuff cavities immediately before roasting _
not any earlier. Otherwise, place stuffing in a buttered casserole
and bake at 325 degrees until golden brown, 45 to 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for a 16- to 20-pound turkey.
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT MASHED POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   8 pounds potatoes
</P>
<P>
   (about 16 medium potatoes)
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons butter, more if desired
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups milk or half-and-half, slightly heated
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Parsley for garnish, as desired
</P>
<P>
   Scrub potatoes; peel and cube. Put in a large pot, cover with
cold water and bring to a boil. Reduce heat to a firm simmer, and
cook until potatoes are tender when pierced with fork; about 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, preheat oven to 350 degrees. Drain potatoes; spread
them on a pan and heat in oven for 10 minutes. (Note: This helps
remove moisture and makes for the fluffiest mashed potatoes.)
</P>
<P>
   Put potatoes in large bowl. Mash potatoes slightly with mixer
before beginning; add a fourth of the milk. Beat on medium speed
until mixture begins to turn smooth; add remaining milk and other
ingredients; beat on high to whip. Scrape bowl frequently to assure
there are no solids left.
</P>
<P>
   Stop and taste; adjust seasonings and milk.
</P>
<P>
   Place potatoes in buttered bowl; set in oven that has been
turned off to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: For garlic mashed potatoes, add 2 tablespoons (or to
taste), roasted garlic puree to the potatoes after whipping; whip
again to mix.
</P>
<P>
   GIBLET GRAVY
</P>
<P>
   1 package turkey giblets and neck
</P>
<P>
   1 celery heart
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1/4 onion, peeled
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon poultry seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, cover giblets and turkey neck with water.
Add celery heart, onion and seasoning. Bring to a boil, cover and
simmer 45 minutes to 1 hour, or until meats are tender. Strain into
bowl; set bowl of broth aside.
</P>
<P>
   Remove all meats from neck bone; discard bones. Coarsely chop
all giblets and place in small bowl in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   When turkey is done, pour drippings from roasting pan into a
large measuring cup or bowl (reserve roasting pan for later use);
allow drippings to stand for a moment _ the fat will come to the
surface. Skim off 1/3 cup fat into a 2-quart saucepan; set saucepan
aside. Skim and discard remaining fat from measuring bowl of
drippings.
</P>
<P>
   Add reserved giblet broth in bowl to roasting pan; stir to
remove browned bits on bottom of pan. Add contents of roasting pan
to bowl of drippings. Add enough water to measure 4 cups liquid.
</P>
<P>
   In saucepan with the 1/3 cup fat, stir flour and 1 teaspoon salt
until blended. Gradually stir in meat juice mixture. Cook, stirring
constantly, until mixture thickens.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in reserved giblets and neck meat; cook 2 more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into gravy boat.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 18.
</P>
<P>
   TRADITIONAL PUMPKIN PIE
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cooked pumpkin, fresh or canned
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup dark brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Unbaked pie crust for 9-inch pie, chilled
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In large mixing bowl, beat together pumpkin, eggs and brown
sugar. Add flour and spices and mix well. Beat in corn syrup and
cream, beating until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the filling into the chilled pie shell; put on cookie sheet
for easy handling.
</P>
<P>
   Place on bottom rack of oven and bake for 15 minutes. Reduce
oven temperature to 325 degrees and continue to bake until the
filling is set and the center no longer looks wet, about 45 to 50
minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   (Tip: Insert a table knife carefully into center of pie,
straight down. Pull straight up. The knife should be clean, not
smeared, if the filling is set.)
</P>
<P>
   Carefully remove pie from oven, and cool on a wire rack. Chill
or serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   THE COUNTDOWN
</P>
<P>
   By planning and working in advance, you can get it all done by
the big day and have time to relax with guests. Ask for help
whenever possible _ guests can bring dishes or help assemble them.
</P>
<P>
   Make your own checklist and timetable based on ours. You can add
or delete items to match your tastes. Stay flexible and work within
your limitations.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday before Thanksgiving
</P>
<P>
   _ Plan and write out your food menu. Attach recipes to this
list; check your pantry and circle the items you do not have. Write
out the beverage menu. Don't forget extra ice.
</P>
<P>
   _ List items for your table setting, including linens,
centerpieces, candles, glassware, flatware, serving pieces and
coffee service.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday
</P>
<P>
   _ Shop for food, beverages, centerpieces.
</P>
<P>
   _ Things you're likely to forget: Pie spices, pickles or
condiments, coffee cream, candles, silver polish, extra food
storage containers, disposable turkey roasting pan, pie pans, gravy
or stuffing ingredients, rolls, extra ice, foam ice chests, trash
bags.
</P>
<P>
   _ Are you buying a frozen turkey? Don't forget to start thawing
at the appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   _ Launder or iron table linens.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wash and polish silver, glassware and serving pieces.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clean refrigerator to make storage space.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   9:30-10 a.m.: Go over your checklists; see that you have
everything you need.
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.: Get turkey ready for cooking, but do not stuff.
</P>
<P>
   10:30 a.m.: Make turkey stuffing and refrigerate separately.
</P>
<P>
   11:15 a.m.: Clean fresh vegetables, refrigerate in separate
containers.
</P>
<P>
   noon: Make cranberry relish. Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   12:15 p.m.: Make pie fillings and refrigerate. Whip cream for
the pies; refrigerate separately. Make pie crusts and freeze (if
you're not using ready-made).
</P>
<P>
   1-3 p.m.: Arrange flowers, cut garnishes, make butter pats, take
care of last-minute dusting or cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving Day
</P>
<P>
   These times are planned for a 5 p.m. dinner for 12. Guests
should plan to arrive by 4 p.m. The timetable is only a guide; try
to remain flexible.
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.: Set table and get room ready.
</P>
<P>
   9:30 a.m.: Check the cooking chart on this page to see when you
need to start cooking the turkey. Allow an extra 15 minutes for
prep work. Remember that you need to take the turkey out of the
oven at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.: Peel potatoes for mashed potatoes, put in water to
soak.
</P>
<P>
   10:40 a.m.: Put together any casseroles or vegetable dishes and
put in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   noon: Thaw pie crusts (if needed). Arrange hors d'oeuvres or
vegetable trays with dips.
</P>
<P>
   1 p.m.: Get coffee ready to brew. Put fillings in pies,
refrigerate. Fill relish dishes, butter dishes, creamer and sugar
bowl. Line bread baskets with napkins.
</P>
<P>
   2 p.m.: Begin cooking potatoes. Whip cream for pies.
</P>
<P>
   2:30 p.m.: Put casseroles and stuffing in oven. Get dressed for
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   3:30 p.m.: Put pies in oven to bake. Bring out cranberry relish
and other relishes. Begin cooking fresh vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   4 p.m.: Guests arrive. Serve finger foods and vegetable trays.
Remove turkey from oven and let sit. Put stuffing in bowl; keep
warm. Check casseroles and remove if done.
</P>
<P>
   4:15 p.m.: Make gravy; check casseroles and pies if not removed
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   4:20 p.m.: Heat rolls.
</P>
<P>
   4:30 p.m.: Mash potatoes; keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   4:45 p.m.: Have turkey carved and on platter; set on stove and
cover with roaster lid to keep it warm. Have someone fill wine and
beverage glasses.
</P>
<P>
   4:50 p.m.: Take rolls out of oven; arrange them in baskets.
Bring out vegetables, gravy. Turn coffee pot on to brew. Pies
should be cooling.
</P>
<P>
   5 p.m.: Seat guests, serve dinner.
</P>
<P>
   How much to allow per person
</P>
<P>
   These are approximate amounts.
</P>
