<HEADER>
A9943 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TURKEY-SIDES25-COX     11-24 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-SIDES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At meal where bird is the star,
 &HT;    make sides stand out, too
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ That darned turkey. Probably because of
its size alone, the bird steals the show no matter how much work
goes into the side dishes. Yet they're the foods that make the meal
stellar.
</P>
<P>
   Where would the big bird be without the supporting cast of
stuffing, candied yams or the ubiquitous green bean casserole? Just
another fowl centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Not content with mere roasting, today's cooks are trying new
tricks with turkey. But why not work on the side dishes?
</P>
<P>
   Turn the vegetables and soups into delicious foods that can
stand on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Stuffed onions and caramelized Brussels sprouts put some zip in
the otherwise bland meal. Take the cranberries out of the relish
and put them into the stuffing. Here are other ideas for making
stars out of sides.
</P>
<P>
   STUFFED ONIONS
</P>
<P>
   1pound bulk sausage, hot or mild, or a mix of both
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground sage (if sausage has sage, omit)
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon olive oil or butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup finely chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup grated carrots
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup finely chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   1cup seasoned breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   Parmesan cheese for topping
</P>
<P>
   8large sweet onions, peeled and cored to 1/2-inch shells (save
inner onion for other dishes)
</P>
<P>
   12ounces vegetable or chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   In nonstick skillet, lightly saute sausage until no pink
remains. Drain well; place in mixing bowl. Sprinkle with ground
sage.
</P>
<P>
   In same skillet, add butter or oil; saute onion, celery, carrots
and green onions until just tender. Pour over sausage; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Mix in bread crumbs, tossing well.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon mixture lightly into onions; sprinkle with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Place onions in large baking dish, pour broth into pan. Cover
lightly with foil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 375 degrees until onions are just softened, about 25
minutes. Remove foil and allow to brown lightly on top.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 large or 16 half servings.
</P>
<P>
   CARAMELIZED BRUSSELS SPROUTS
</P>
<P>
   Roasting brings out the natural sugars in any vegetable;
Brussels sprouts are no exception. Add to that a syrup made from
balsamic vinegar, and you've got a winning dish. Best part for the
cook: They can be in the oven with the turkey.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds Brussels sprouts for every six people
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil for baking sheet
</P>
<P>
   1cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Wash Brussels sprouts and trim ends. Cut larger ones in half,
leave small ones whole. Roll until coated with oil on an oiled,
foil-lined cookie sheet or roasting pan; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, heat vinegar to boiling, and reduce heat.
Allow to simmer about 30 minutes to reduce volume by half. At this
point it should be of syrup consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle vinegar syrup over Brussels sprouts and roast, at 375
degrees for 20 minutes or until lightly browned and done.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from Mollie Katzen's ``Vegetable Heaven'' 1997,
Hyperion Books.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
