A9944 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WILD-TURKEY25-COX     11-24 0236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILD-TURKEY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turkeys surviving better in wild than on your table
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Nov. 25.
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happy Thanksgiving. This is the day when the turkey is the most
celebrated bird in America. The turkey you munch today most
probably was raised by commercial growers in turkey houses strictly
controlled for temperature, humidity, water and food supply. But in
the wild, the wild turkey is one of Georgia's greatest examples of
a successful wildliflly sound hunting seasons, and enhancing the
turkeys' habitat, such as deciduous woodlands and wooded
bottomlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``A healthy habitat is the most important aspect of turkey
populations,'' says WRD biologist Reggie Thackston. Turkeys were
trapped in various parts of the state and relocated to establish
new breeding populations. More than 4,000 of them were relocated to
over 400 areas. Private landowners, hunting organizations and cone
spring and early summer of 1997 resulted in poor reproduction rates
for wild turkeys in Georgia. But their reproduction rates were high
in 1998 and this year.
</P>
<P>
   Long may the turkey gobble!
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes on nature and the environment for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution. His column appears weekly. E-mail him
at cseabrook(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
