r e BC-HOLIDAY-COOKTIPS25-CO     11-24 0181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-COOKTIPS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recipe for success
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Tips for cooking with the kids from cookbook
author/illustrator Jane Breskin Zalben:
</P>
<P>
   _ READ RECIPES carefully with your children and make list of
ingredients you don't have.
</P>
<P>
   _ TAKE YOUR LIST _ and the kids _ with you to the store.
</P>
<P>
   _ BE ORGANIZED. Line up ingredients in order of use.
</P>
<P>
   _ WASH HANDS and wear comfortable clothing you don't mind
getting messy.
</P>
<P>
   _ DECIDE WHICH tasks are suitable for the child. Some kitchen
equipment such as knives, graters, scissors, beaters, mixers, food
processors, ovens and stoves should only be used with adult
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   _ OVEN MITTS, pot holders and aprons should be used every time
you cook.
</P>
<P>
   _ FOLLOW THE recipe, cleaning up along the way.
</P>
<P>
   _ HAVE FUN! Enjoy the wonderful smells wafting through the
house. Says Zalben: ``I don't own a microwave because I love the
aromas of good food cooking or baking!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
