<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLIDAY-COOKRECIPES25     11-24 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-COOKRECIPES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cooking up a special holiday
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In her recently published book ``To Every Season:
A Family Holiday Cookbook'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $19.95), Jane
Breskin Zalben describes the origins of 16 holidays and offers
recipes for families to cook together.
</P>
<P>
   CRANBERRY-ORANGE RELISH (THANKSGIVING)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 portions
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fresh cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons orange zest
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   8-10 canned mandarin orange sections
</P>
<P>
   Boil cranberries in water with orange zest, sugar, and maple
syrup for 10 minutes over medium flame. Stir frequently until
liquid boils off and the berries are soft and mushy. Cover pot with
lid. Simmer on low for another 3-5 minutes. Remove from stove. Put
in serving bowl and mix in mandarin oranges. Serve at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   PEARL'S POTATO LATKES (HANUKKAH)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16-18 latkes, approximately 3 inches round.
</P>
<P>
   5 large potatoes, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup matzoh meal
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   vegetable oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   Grate peeled potatoes and onion by hand or in food processor. In
a large bowl, combine eggs, potatoes and onion. Blend in matzoh
meal, salt, and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In a large frying pan over a medium flame, heat a 1-inch layer
of oil. Drop in 1 heaping tablespoon of mixture for each latke. A
few latkes (about 5) can cook at a time. Turn over when crisp and
golden.
</P>
<P>
   Drain on double layer of paper towels over a thick paper
shopping bag. Serve piping hot with sour cream or applesauce.
</P>
<P>
   Cajun latkes: Add a pinch of cayenne pepper or a chopped
jalapeno. Serve with a sweet salsa on the side. Mix together three
kiwi fruits or a large peach, peeled and finely chopped, a small
red onion, peeled and chopped, a handful of chopped cilantro and
apple cider vinegar to taste.
</P>
<P>
   SWEET POTATO PUDDING (KWANZAA)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10-12 servings
</P>
<P>
   4 large sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 sweet apples, peeled and cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pineapple chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ginger
</P>
<P>
   8 large walnuts, shelled
</P>
<P>
   2 pats of butter
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Boil sweet potatoes in large
covered pot about 1 hour or until tender. Remove. Cool. Peel. Mash
in large bowl with a fork or use mixer. Gently stir together
apples, pineapple, maple syrup and spices. Fold into sweet potato
mixture with spatula. Pour mixture into approximately 7
1/2-by-12-inch baking dish. Smooth surface with spatula. Dot with
walnuts and butter. Cover pan with aluminum foil to prevent drying,
Bake 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Remove foil from pudding last 15 minutes. Serve steaming hot.
</P>
<P>
   SANTA'S ELVES EGGLESS EGGNOG (CHRISTMAS)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings (double recipe as needed for a large punch
bowl).
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   6 teaspoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of nutmeg or mace
</P>
<P>
   Cracked ice or ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   Put evaporated milk, sugar, and vanilla in blender. Whip 2
minutes. Set aside. Use whisk or electric mixer to whip heavy cream
until peaks form. Fold into evaporated milk mixture. Sprinkle with
nutmeg or mace (they come from the same fruit). Serve chilled with
cracked ice or ice cubes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
