<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9948 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-NUHN-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NUHN-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walking parity line is boring
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARITYVILLE, USA _ Well, here we are in the National Even-Steven
League, where every team _ with a couple of exceptions from Ohio _
can beat any other team on any given Sunday, Monday and, on
occasion, Thursday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League has reached its nirvana, and it is
not a pretty sight.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has managed, through legislation, injury, substance
abuse and bad luck to produce 31 teams and one flavor _ vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   There is nobody to love, nobody to hate, nobody to root for or
against.
</P>
<P>
   No excellence. Just rampant balance, which also goes by the
names equality, similarity and, unfortunately, mediocrity. I look
at the league on a weekly basis, and there are no more must-see
games.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, there are 18 teams that are unwatchable. Look at the
standings. That 18 number is negotiable _ you might find more; you
won't find fewer.
</P>
<P>
   To bring this as close to home as possible, check the dearly
beloved AFC Central, but only if you haven't eaten in the last
hour. From the bottom up, Bengals, Browns, Ravens, Steelers,
Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Unwatchable, unwatchable, unwatchable, unwatchable, unwatchable.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Titans are 8-2. But they are as tasteless as grits.
</P>
<P>
   But even with five of six AFC Central teams on the endangered
species list, we don't hold title to the worst division in
football.
</P>
<P>
   No, that surely goes to the NFC East. Find a team among these
worth even 10 minutes of your time on a Sunday afternoon: Redskins,
Cowboys, Giants, Cards, Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   That's the entire NFC East. They go 5-for-5 on the
sadsackometer.
</P>
<P>
   I long for those old Cowboy-Redskin-Cardinal games when the
teams actually had personalities. It was Staubach, Jurgensen and
Jim Hart playing 35-34 games that weren't decided until the last
ambulance had left the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders-Chiefs used to be an event. Now, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Browns-Bengals; Steelers-Browns; Steelers-Bengals once raised a
clamor. Now, those games are as interesting as the production of
porridge.
</P>
<P>
   And what has the NFL found to replace those rivalries?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the league is a victim of its own plan. Unlike
baseball, it wanted equality, and it got it. Unfortunately, the
price of equality has been the loss of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   The league's onetime headline quarterbacks are either sitting
home in Barcaloungers _ John Elway, Jim Kelly, Joe Montana _ or
trying to recover from injuries _ Steve Young, Dan Marino, Brett
Favre, Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one good, young quarterback who has had more than
six good games _ Peyton Manning _ and a few others the league is
praying for because they're so badly needed.
</P>
<P>
   The teams with the best records are frail imitations of the old
Steelers, 49ers or Bears. Two weeks ago, the supposed best team in
the league, Jacksonville, won a game 6-3 against a team with Hansel
and Gretel at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the NFL has achieved what it wanted _ 25 of its 31
lambs are still in contention for the playoffs. As they stuff their
faces with cranberry sauce on Thursday, fans in those cities can
raise a turkey leg to their teams.
</P>
<P>
   Not around here, of course. Here we're afraid to raise a turkey
leg to our two powerhouses because it might be part of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: gnuhn(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
