</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, November 25, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Jesse Jackson is taking a lambasting for his
trouble on behalf of seven unruly high school kids in Decatur,
Illinois, but he appears to be right on the merits of the instant
case and even more right against the larger background of worsening
racial disparities in the criminal justice system. (Teepen, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA, Fla. _ Blessings, real blessings, don't
announce themselves. Enumerating them in a blessing census seems to
endanger them, even cheapen them. But sometimes you can't escape
the topic. When cornered, I will admit one of the big things I'm
thankful for is that nearly everything wise grownups told me when I
was a kid about the way the world would be right now, at the turn
of the millennium, was just plain wrong. (Lane, Daytona Beach
News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ First Thanksgivings always seem to make a
lasting impression. Here are three stories I've collected from
friends of Thanksgivings that will never be forgotten. (Ernest
Murray, Cox News Service). MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ It's one thing to hear about
road rage, and another to see its face. (McCarty, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Earlier this month about a dozen
hooded members of a Ku Klux Klan faction from Indiana came to Waco.
Oh, happy day. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Since University of Texas regents
want a building design that will be familiar to Texans for their
$60 million to $70 million Jack S. Blanton Museum of Art, why don't
they build an art museum that looks like a Dairy Queen? When you're
talking about Texas architecture, it just doesn't get much more
familiar than DQ. Everybody in Texas knows what a Dairy Queen looks
like. Van Gogh. To go. What's the difference? I'll have the Picasso
-- asket. Mr. Matisse, would you like fries with that? (Kelso,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WIGGINS-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The National Highway
Safety Transportation Administration is trying to drown
sports-utility vehicle drivers, and I guess it's up to me to stop
them. (Wiggins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
