<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA1125: Pilgrims to Christ statue are united in
prayer, faith on annual ascent
</P>
<P>
   SUNLAND PARK, N.M. _ So many arduous steps taken. So little
asked. Pushed by unwavering faith, beckoned by the spirit of
previous generations, a people separated by the borders of three
states and two countries drew on their common belief that a journey
to a mountain peak on a Sunday might deliver answers to their
humble prayers. They drew deep breaths and stepped up steep paths,
pushed aside the pain of tired muscles to arrive atop Mount Cristo
Rey, where 4,576 feet above sea level an opened-armed statue of
Christ welcomes them, their worries, their pleas, their
gratefulness. (Gamboa, Austin American-Statesman) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   XMAS-LIGHTS _ A few years ago, strings of Christmas lights that
could be hung in a pattern mimicking icicles first started showing
up on store shelves. Now icicle lights are becoming dominant in
outdoor home Christmas decorations. And because the lights have
changed, the rules for hanging them have changed a bit as well.
(Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 27.
</P>
<P>
   WILD-TURKEYS _ Thanksgiving is the day when the turkey is the
most celebrated bird in America. The turkey you munch today most
probably was raised by commercial growers. But in the wild, the
wild turkey is one of Georgia's greatest examples of a successful
wildlife comeback. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
