<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-$ADV2     11-24 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN RUSSIA, CRIME AND NO PUNISHMENT FOR POLITICAL CANDIDATES
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Nov. 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Murder, arson and jail time. These are
not the sort of credentials that make for a promising political
career.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Russia and, more specifically St. Petersburg, where
the politics are not just bare-knuckled; sometimes they're deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Yuri Shutov, a member of the local city council, wants to be
elected to the national lower house of parliament, the Duma, in the
Dec. 19 elections. He's running for office from a grim prison cell,
and his aides have collected enough signatures to place his name on
the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   A popular political maverick, Shutov was arrested last February
on charges of arranging at least three contract murders of
businessmen and politicians. Shutov claims that political enemies
have framed him. Until he is formally charged and a trial date has
been set, he's free to hold his local office and run for a national
seat in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia votes for a new parliament next month, it will
determine the future of the troubled nation, and signal the
political mood in advance of a more critical choice next summer _
the election to replace President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   But the elections to fill the Duma's 450 seats also are burdened
by a faulty political system and a cast of colorful and dubious
characters that make Russia's experiment with democracy look at
times like mad science.
</P>
<P>
   Perks and power _ not public service _ provide the motivation
for most candidates, political analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Russian election system, voters will cast two votes _
one for a candidate from the local district and one for a political
party and its list of candidates. So, for example, while popular
and respected politicians like former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov will head the list and attract votes to his Fatherland-All
of Russia party, he'll also carry with him into office lesser-known
candidates down the party list.
</P>
<P>
   The lists drawn up by eligible political parties will fill half
the Duma seats, and those lists are riddled with candidates
currently under criminal investigation or with people alleged to
have paid large sums _ in the millions of dollars _ to become
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who are criminals, or accused of crimes, or simply
fearful that they may face criminal charges sometime in the future,
are seeking seats in the Duma because it provides limited, yet
substantial, immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinary Russians are very disillusioned with politics and
politicians of all kinds,'' said Sergei Markov, of the Moscow-based
Institute of Political Studies, a think tank. ``They have been
deceived many times in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law enforcement officials have sought and failed over
the years to push legislation to eliminate the immunity benefit.
Russia's interior ministry estimates that there are about four
million current and former elected officials, judges and
prosecutors at the federal and regional level who enjoy immunity
from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is nothing to prevent Shutov or others from
running for office from jail _ and avoiding imprisonment once
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Shutov, 53, insists he is not in this category. He wants to
serve the people, not use the office to evade prison, said his
lawyer. Yet, he is no stranger to the penitentiary. In Soviet
times, he served five years for forgery and embezzlement. He served
another 18-month stint earlier in this decade awaiting trial on
charges of arson, extortion and smuggling until winning acquittal
from a local court.
</P>
<P>
   Now he faces charges that he was part of a ring that ordered up
the executions of prominent businessmen and politicians in St.
Petersburg, a city that has been plagued by sensational mob-style
hits since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Shutov's lawyer claims it is a smear campaign and that his
client continues to be among the city's more effective lawmakers,
not a lawbreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is still involved in making daily decisions (on the city
council) through his assistants and his lawyers,'' said Andrei
Pelevin, who says his client should be freed while awaiting trial.
``It seems to me that now he is more active than other council
members.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities rejected Cox Newspapers' request to interview Shutov
at the Vyborg prison, a two-hour drive northwest of St. Petersburg.
Pelevin said authorities did not want to allow Shutov to talk to
journalists and that Russian newspapers were being pressured not to
publish Shutov's commentaries written from prison.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia's young democracy, where competing political parties
are still a new phenomenon, there is little party loyalty _ aside
from the Communist Party, which opinion polls show has the support
of about 20 percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Voters tend to be attracted to nationally known politicians.
Political alliances are forged not so much along ideological lines,
but with business ties and power-sharing pacts.
</P>
<P>
   In Shutov's case, he is a political ally of powerful St.
Petersburg Gov. Vladimir Yakovlev, but essentially running as an
independent. He failed in a bid for the Duma in 1995, but won
election to the city council in 1998 with 60 percent of the vote in
his district.
</P>
<P>
   Could he be elected this time from prison? The odds are against
him, particularly since he was re-arrested and allegedly beaten up
by security forces in a bizarre episode earlier this month after
briefly getting out on bail.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one independent political analyst in St. Petersburg
says Shutov has an allure that others in the race for the Duma may
not possess: At least voters will know whom they would be getting.
And since the public perceives government as corrupt and
untrustworthy, prosecution could be a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prison _ this is not a condition that makes a person less
attractive,'' said analyst Leonid Kesselman. ``We have our own
value system in Russia and in the old (Soviet) days, nearly every
Russian knew someone or had a member of their family in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
