<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Richard Paul Evans talks about his new book, ``The
Looking Glass,'' and how his debut novel, ``The Christmas Box''
changed his life. Also, Amazon.com lists readers' choices of books
of the millennium and Talk Magazine lists the most-talked-about
books of the century. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA:
6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEWS _ Short reviews on recently-released books. This
week: ``Remembering Walt,'' ``Michelangelo: The Pietas''. (Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EVEREST-BOOKREVIEW _ George Mallory was last seen alive on June
8, 1924. He and Andrew Irvine were at 27,000 feet and moving over a
ridge, about three hours from their goal, the summit of Mount
Everest. For more than 75 years, that has been the sum total of
knowledge about Mallory's last day. He and Irvine never returned,
and whether they made it to the top before dying (a full 29 years
before Sir Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay conclusively conquered
Everest) has been the subject of many books and much speculation in
the climbing subculture. Their story unfolds in ``Ghosts of
Everest,'' and we review the book. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HITLERS-NIECE _ In Mel Brooks' classic movie ``The Producers,''
Zero Mostel deliberately produces a musical called ``Springtime for
Hitler,'' thinking it will be a huge flop on Broadway and he can
make off with the investors' money. Ron Hansen, I'm afraid, has
written ``Springtime for Hitler'' by accident. A review.
(Blackburn, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
