<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNWITTING HERO VS. NET CLODS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody wants a piece of Mahir Cagri.
</P>
<P>
   There's the designer in Dallas who is showing movies featuring
Cagri on his Web site and who plans to sell T-shirts and ads soon.
There's the guy in Toronto who designed the Mahir Cagri Ping-Pong
game who readily admits he's driven by ``shameless
self-promotion.'' There's the guy in England hawking Mahir coffee
mugs and mouse pads who claims that the proceeds will go to the Red
Cross in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the columnists sending frantic e-mail to the
overnight cultural icon, assembling pathetically urgent missives
from a dogeared Berlitz phrasebook: ``Merhaba. I am gazeteci. I
want bilmek. Lutfen.'' (``Hello. I am journalist. I want speak.
Please.'')
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Cagri ignored that poignant plea.
</P>
<P>
   For folks who haven't been on line recently, Cagri is reportedly
an ordinary Turkish fellow who awoke one day to find himself an
Internet superstar, the central character in a Kafkaesque tale. The
story goes something like this: About a year ago, Cagri set up a
home page describing his hobbies and interests in fractured
English. Apparently, someone in Turkey doctored the page (which
began ``I kiss you!!!!!''), adding such sentiments as ``I like
sex'' and ``I like to take foto-camera . . . nice nude models and
peoples.'' That page found its way to Netizens at the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund, who circulated the Web address
to colleagues worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, Cagri was bombarded with e-mail and phone calls and
requests for interviews (``Lutfen!!''). Parodies sprouted all over,
with one page substituting President Clinton for the Turkish
lothario and another combining images of Cagri with the infamous
(and annoying) Hamster Dance. Cagri found himself on the front page
of the Turkish dailies, proving he exists.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually posted his own explanation of the purloined page
with an impassioned appeal for racial and religious tolerance.
``Everthing is for peace, friendship, huminity and love,'' he
wrote. ``As a world's citizen, I love all of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the earnest world citizen's page was inspiring
parodies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   And in the twisted and complex spirit of the Internet, some
folks were having good-natured fun with the existential hero of the
moment while others were trying to make a quick buck or garner good
PR. The original site was posted on Xoom.com, an on-line community
that offers free home pages. ``We tried to send him a digital
camera so he can use his Xoom membership,'' says Stacey Irvine,
senior director at Xoom. She skirted questions about the identity
of the person who posted the first phony page, answering every
query with a pitch for Xoom.
</P>
<P>
   By now, it doesn't matter how much of the story is true, since
Cagri doesn't own his identity any more. He's part Peter Sellers in
``Being There,'' part Jamaican bobsled team, and part Eddie Edwards
(the British ski jumper whose ineptitude brought instant fame).
He's the guy who makes us all feel a little bit superior because
he's so touchingly naive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something deeply endearing about the combination of
earnestness and cheesiness,'' says Jacob Park, a specialist at the
Lawyer's Committee for Human Rights in New York, who runs a site
called Mahir Central. ``Most people think he's charming and cute,
but certainly there were snide comments from people who say, `He
can't speak English good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There is an element of imperialism to all the parodies: None of
this would be funny if it weren't assumed that English is the
language of cyberspace. Just who is making fun of whom?
</P>
<P>
   Park has many human-rights colleagues in Turkey, and he says
that the phrase ``I kiss you'' is the Turkish equivalent of ``Hi''
or ``Ciao.'' By the way, Park now signs his e-mails with kisses,
too.
</P>
<P>
   So do the rest of the Mahir maniacs _ profiteers and fans alike.
Michael Simpson created an interactive game that uses Mahir's head
as a torpedo. So much for Cagri's message of peace. ``There isn't
anything productive or virtuous about it,'' says Simpson, a Web
content developer who lives in Toronto. ``It's a way of shamelessly
promoting myself, like spray-painting your name on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Stachowski, a Web designer in Dallas, is obsessed with the
cult hero, but he also wouldn't mind making a little money off his
Web page, which features animated movies starring Cagri. He is
selling ads on the page and says T-shirts will be available soon.
``I've gotten a couple of leads, but nothing serious,'' he says. So
why has he been spending so much time on the craze? He pauses, as
if in disbelief. ``Because,'' he says, exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that explains it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cagri promises to post another update to the page in
the next few days. According to on-line reports, he has asked CNN
to pay him $50,000 for an interview, but a CNN spokesperson said
those reports were false. ``He never asked to be paid,'' the
spokesperson said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Cagri comes out looking classier than the folks who are
having so much fun with his image and Mediterranean stereotypes. He
seems to lack the cynicism of most opportunists: If he were in
Hollywood, he would already have ``peoples,'' from agents to
publicists to personal assistants. And he'd be sure to have a movie
deal and a book contract.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, he's not answering e-mails from unsophisticated
scribes who contact him in fractured Turk-glish. ``I want bilmek.
Lutfen.'' Maybe we should have tried, ``I kiss you. Ciao.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mahir's updated page is
http://members.xoom.com/_XOOM/primall/mahir/index.html. For links
to parodies, see Mahir Central at
http://www.geocities.com/Athens/Ithaca/4637/mahircentral.html)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-18-99 1340EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
