<HEADLINE>
SMALL DEVICES WON'T REPLACE PCS SOON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Twenty years ago, the Computer Dealers Exposition
hosted a mere 4,000 visitors who came to this ultra-tacky city in
the desert to make deals with each other. The IBM personal computer
was two years away.
</P>
<P>
   The PC not only changed Comdex, as the event became known, but
it also changed modern society. Personal computers are now on
nearly every white-collar desktop in America and in more than 50
percent of all homes. Connecting these machines is the Internet,
which is creating further astounding change in our day-to-day
lives.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's particularly interesting at the 20th anniversary of
Comdex that so many people here are ready to say the PC's time has
passed. The buzz among the 200,000-plus who have gathered this week
is that we are either moving into the post-PC era or the PC-plus
era.
</P>
<P>
   The former argument says the PC has outlived its usefulness, and
that a new generation of smaller, cheaper, easier-to-use
information appliances will take its place. The latter decrees that
these devices will indeed flourish and become more popular but will
serve to supplement the PC, which will remain the central
information manager in homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The official theme of this year's Comdex is ``Beyond the PC,''
with a heavy emphasis on these small, single-focus devices.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts and pundits have been falling all over themselves
to tout the coming of information appliances for several years,
I've been dubious. And after spending a few days wandering the
crowded booths on what is supposed to be the dawn of the
info-appliance age, I've not seen much to change my mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WRESTLING WITH DEVICES' LIMITATIONS
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there won't be _ or that there aren't already
_ useful information appliances. But it doesn't make sense that
these devices will overwhelm, supplant and become more popular than
the PC. The very thing that is supposed to be attractive about them
leads to their biggest downfall _ they have built-in limitations.
And when it comes to information, users hate limits.
</P>
<P>
   One of the products shown here this week is something called a
``Web companion,'' a type of small terminal used primarily to surf
the Web and send and receive e-mail. Houston's own Compaq Computer
Corp. was showing one of these at an event called Showstopper, and
branded the brief exhibition as a ``technology demonstration.''
</P>
<P>
   It uses a small passive-matrix, flat-panel display propped up on
a base, with a nifty wireless keyboard. The keyboard has buttons _
similar in design to the Internet keyboard found on Compaq's
Presario desktops _ that can do specific tasks, such as launching
Web pages or an e-mail program.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect to find this device, which is still in search of a
name, on store shelves anytime soon. Once it's ready, Compaq plans
to sell it to companies who either offer Net access or services
over the Web, such as an online merchant, a bank or a stock trading
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The business would then resell the devices to its customers, or
even give them away. The business could then control what customers
see on the screen, essentially creating a window to the Web viewed
only through that business' brand.
</P>
<P>
   This is a smart move. By having other companies subsidize the
cost of the device when they make it available to their customers,
they get around a big problem with these information appliances _
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PRICES COMPETE WITH DESKTOPS
</P>
<P>
   Most of the single-purpose devices I've seen here are going to
be selling in the $200 to $500 price range. The ones that are
capable of Web surfing are usually at the higher end of the
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   But at that point, they start competing in price with the
low-cost PCs that are out there. Why buy a device that will limit
your capabilities for $500 when you can get a device with no limits
for the same price or a little more?
</P>
<P>
   Information appliance boosters claim the PC isn't easy or
reliable enough for those who are not technically savvy. But given
the exploding consumer market for PCs _ and the fact that nearly
everyone who buys one gets onto the Net _ this seems to be a
specious argument. Certainly, people are figuring out PCs and
making them work.
</P>
<P>
   The whole concept of the information appliance is, I think,
flawed. Their proponents use the toaster analogy, saying you don't
need a commercial kitchen just to make toast.
</P>
<P>
   But information isn't like toast. Most people, when they are
getting information, like to do something with it. They want to
change it, share it, create it. These devices, by and large, do not
allow that. You can look at the information, maybe print it out,
maybe forward it via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   (To Compaq's credit, its device has several Universal Serial Bus
ports and an Ethernet network connection. That means you will be
able to connect printers, scanners and external drives to it _ but
only if Compaq provides the support for them. You'll also be able
to hook it up to a home network, and receive from and send
information to _ you guessed _ a real PC.)
</P>
<P>
   I frequently get mail from frustrated users of Microsoft's WebTV
device who buy the television-based Web terminal for its
simplicity. But suddenly they discover that they can't see some of
the fancier features on Web pages, can't chat online with their
friends and can't do any of the myriad of things that their
PC-owning friends can do.
</P>
<P>
   I guess if you insisted on carrying the toast analogy forward,
you could say that very few people eat their toast plain. They like
a little jelly on it.
</P>
<P>
   These information appliances don't have jelly. They're a bit
dry. And that's why I think the reports of the death of the PC are
greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-19-99 1555EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
