<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-DIGITAL-MUSIC-MAR     11-24 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGITAL-MUSIC-MARKETING-1000&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC INDUSTRY FAILS TO MEET TARGET FOR START OF ONLINE SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (js) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After scrambling to adopt a technical standard for sales of
music online, record companies and hardware makers last summer said
they had paved the way for Christmas sales of portable digital
players. But the holidays are ringing in a reality: neither the
tunes nor the players will be in place to make this the first big
digital music Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the delay, Sony Electronics, a consumer electronics
bellwether, last week introduced its digital music player, the
Memory Stick Walkman, but said that it would not be for sale until
January. Meanwhile, major music companies say that the delay in
adopting standards _ along with logistical challenges _ has forced
them to abandon their one-time goal of making much of their music
available over the Internet by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The delays suggest the complexity of the still evolving
technical standards being developed by the recording industry's
Secure Digital Music Initiative, and they hint at continued
uncertainty for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   They also reflect competing interests. The music companies fear
that insecure digital players will lead to rampant piracy of music
downloaded from the Internet, while the consumer electronics
industry sees the digital players merely as heir to the portable
cassette and compact disc player.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a final agreement on the first phase of the
specifications being developed by the Secure Digital Music
Initiative, or SDMI, is not even scheduled to be signed until next
week. Initiative officials plan to meet in Maui, Hawaii, on Dec. 1
to sign a contract with Aris Technologies Inc., which makes a key
screening technology for the portable devices.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Hardware vendors have sought to play down the delay, suggesting
that a single holiday shopping season lost will make little
difference in a still-nascent market. At the same time, some say
they are disappointed that they were pushed to adopt and comply
with standards but will not reap the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   This delay hurts the ``credibility of SDMI,'' said Chris Smith,
portable audio program manager for Creative Labs. His company makes
the Nomad II, a portable player initially due out by Christmas but
now scheduled for distribution in the first quarter. When SDMI was
formed, he said, ``our stated goal was to have specifications by
June 30 so we could create products for Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   The consumer electronics manufacturers said their concern had
been mitigated by the fact that their competitors' digital players
would not be on the shelves either. ``Our goal was Christmas,'' a
spokeswoman for Sony said, ``but in the grand scope of things,
missing one Christmas isn't going to make or break us.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen portable digital players that record music
on tiny hard drives are already on the market. But those players
are not yet fully compatible with the technical standards, and it
is unclear how many of them will be able to be upgraded once the
new standards are in place. If they ultimately cannot meet SDMI
specifications, they would not be able to play the newest music _
either downloaded from the Internet or ``ripped'' from compact
discs.
</P>
<P>
   What has made the issue so pressing from a music industry
perspective is that the downloading of music from the Internet has
gathered momentum. College students in particular, a huge music
audience, have taken advantage of the Internet to trade, download
and listen to music online in a format called MP3, opening both a
massive opportunity and a potential Achilles' heel for music
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The great fear of the music industry _ and of some musicians _
is that the existing MP3 technology makes it possible for people to
trade and distribute music freely, in blatant violation of
copyright laws and possibly costing the companies tens of millions
of dollars in lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   The industry in turn regards the portable players as the
paraphernalia of music piracy because people will theoretically
have even more incentive to pirate music if they can copy, store
and play it on easy-to-use portable devices.
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry's trump card is its vast catalogs of
popular music. Its promise to make this content available over the
Internet is what has lured the device manufacturers to cooperate in
SDMI. Without the content, the conventional wisdom goes, the market
for the devices will not thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Both the recording and consumer electronics industries expressed
optimism in June that they would meet the Christmas target. At the
time, a coalition of more than 100 companies from the two
industries agreed to the first SDMI specifications, which were
designed to eventually preclude the portable devices from playing
pirated music in the MP3 format. That first specification, called
Phase I, stopped short of preventing piracy but would have enabled
the players to be upgraded once the record industry settled on a
secure format for the delivery of music.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, these Phase I compatible players would screen
incoming music and prevent the devices from playing illegally
obtained songs. But despite the agreement in principle to Phase I
specifications, SDMI did not settle on the Aris screening
technology until Nov. 12. And, in fact, the final contract is not
slated to be signed with Aris until the Dec. 1 meeting in Maui.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The delays were so great that when Creative Labs begins selling
its Nomad II sometime in the first quarter next year, it will not
initially be Phase I compatible. To make it compatible, consumers
will eventually need to download software from the Internet, though
it is not entirely clear what incentive consumers will have to
download the software. The same is true of players expected from
Sanyo, Toshiba and Sharp, among others.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, opponents of SDMI, which has been criticized as a
record industry initiative to maintain control of music
distribution, contend that the latest delays underscore much larger
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``SDMI is dead _ it's dead as a door nail,'' said Robert Kohn,
chairman and cofounder of emusic.com, an online music site that
sells songs in MP3 format. ``There's no document from which any of
these companies can develop specifications. They've developed a
framework, not specifications.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The music companies themselves are facing delays, partly because
of SDMI delays and partly because of technical logistics in
preparing their music for online distribution. Laurie Jakobsen, a
spokeswoman for Sony Music Entertainment, which now offers limited
downloads of music for promotional purposes, said that Sony would
be pushing back commercial distribution of music online ``because
of SDMI.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do more as soon as there are players out there,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Samit, senior vice president for new media for EMI Records,
said there were also simple, practical matters to contend with.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, the record companies have discovered that
they must explore how and whether each artist contract permits the
distribution of music over the Internet. ``We're going as fast we
can,'' he said. ``We are moving through mounds of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-21-99 1706EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
