<SLUG> BC-CPT-Y2K-PREPARATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL GRADES ARE READY ON YEAR 2000 READINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government is going to get a respectable report
card, with plenty of A's, when the House subcommittee tracking Year
2000 preparations issues what it calls its final grades Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But one reason things look so rosy is that the subcommittee has
decided not to issue grades for more than 40 vital government
programs, including Medicaid and Medicare. As the committee sees
it, many programs dependent on the states and private organizations
are not completely ready for the transition to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the kind of programs that affect everyone,'' said
Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif., chairman of the House Subcommittee on
Government Management, Information and Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Horn, who was president of California State University at Long
Beach and then a professor there before running for Congress,
instituted the grading system to draw attention to the potential
disaster facing many government agencies when he first began
investigating Year 2000 computer concerns in 1996. Many agencies
had no plan for dealing with potential problems. In fact, two
cabinet heads had never even heard of the issue, according to Horn.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a year ago, the government's overall grade was a
D. But the grades rose steadily as agency after agency reported
completion of its repair work, testing and development of
contingency plans. As the A's began to pile up, the subcommittee
shifted some of its focus to a gaping hole in its oversight effort:
the preparedness of state governments and private organizations
that the federal government relies on to provide federal money,
services and regulatory enforcement to the public.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the subcommittee issued separate grades for the
first time to the agencies for the readiness of 43 programs
designated ``high impact'' by the Office of Management and Budget.
Suddenly, agencies sporting A and B ratings for their own work
found themselves on the defensive about state or private programs
rated D or F with only a few months left until the Year 2000
rollover. The fact that the problems were not at the federal level
was not considered an acceptable excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's report will make it clear, though, that the expanded
grading proved to be more trouble than it was worth. Often, the
poor grade reflected incomplete readiness around the country where
services are delivered rather than substantial evidence of actual
Year 2000 vulnerabilities.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the subcommittee is simply classifying
programs as ready or not, Horn said. The subcommittee report will
point out some worries that were not highlighted three months ago,
including concern about the readiness of owners of public housing
raised by a recent survey by the Department of Housing and Urban
Development.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-21-99 1713EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1153EST &QL; 
