 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Microsoft continues innovative streak with new real-time game 
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about Microsoft _ it continues to
revolutionize gaming with its quality peripherals and great games.
So what if its latest, Age of Empires II ($50 for the PC), is yet
another in a long line of real-time strategy games? The company
gets it right, improving upon a great product and introducing
compelling campaigns, including a brilliant William Wallace
training scenario and the rise of Joan of Arc. While Age of Empires
took you through the beginnings of civilization, Age of Empires II
propels you from the fall of Rome to the Middle Ages. The game's
got better intelligence, more tactical options and better stories.
One of the truly best empire-building games around.
(www.microsoft.com/games/age2/)
</P>
<P>
   _ Madden football is like Thanksgiving leftovers. No matter what
you do, you know it's coming, and you know there's nothing you'll
be able to do about it. For the past few years, PC football games
have improved dramatically in graphics and game-play, led by folks
like EA Sports. This year's Madden 2000 ($40) is graphics- and
feature-rich, but unfortunately it just can't compete with the
intuitiveness and game-play of some of its console brethren.
Multiplayer and updated stats are standard fare for Madden games,
but 2000 has a few new features, such as an arcade mode that
emulates NFL Blitz. Harder hits and tired ``edgy'' commentary,
however, don't add up to Blitz's fun. And the game is glitchy,
causing strange crashes and errors on some 3dfx graphics cards and
often inexplicably starting the game with teams different than
those you selected. The graphics are ho-hum and the game-play
hasn't advanced much from last year. With games like Sega's amazing
NFL2K blazing trails on the console side, this may not be the best
year for Madden pound cake.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Just so you know, the first Nyko Scorpion Playstation controller
($30) I was sent had a screw missing in the handle. The apologies
were profuse and I was immediately sent another one (they assured
me it was an anomaly). Workmanship aside, this is an amazing
controller. If you're like me, you've been complaining about the
size of the Playstation controller since it came out. The Sony dual
shock controller added some heft, but it was still pretty small in
the hand. Nyko has worked to eradicate that with the Scorpion. The
controller is wider (looking like a cross between a stingray and
Klingon battle cruiser) and fits in the hand better. Also, the
controller puts those hard-to-reach R2, L2 buttons within reach,
which really helps on the sports games. The controller also comes
with turbo (speeds things up) and slow (exactly what it sounds
like) modes for the cheater in you. (www.nyko.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-22-99 1115EST &QL;
</P>
