<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-KIDGEAR23-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Barney gets in on bongo act 
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's amazing that anything with Barney's mug on
it still exists. There was a time where the purple dinosaur
inspired rage and social backlash. Now, it's the opposite. Barney
is back in favor, in part because of cool toys such as Barney's
Song Magic Bongos ($30). The Magic Bongos play 11 songs on five
different instruments. All kids have to do is pick their song (i.e.
``Farmer in the Dell'' among others) and an instrument, ranging
from a steel drum to a hooting organ sound, and start bonging away.
Each hit yields a note and, following that principle, a bunch of
notes/hits play a song. This toy is great for those creative kids
just starting to attain their dexterity, and is also good for
celebrities who insist on dancing around their homes naked.
(1-800-PLAYSKL)
</P>
<P>
   EHH, WHAT'S UP, CLOCK?
</P>
<P>
   Bugs Bunny has a problem. On the way to Albuquerque he finds a
time machine. That's not the bad part. The bad part is that he
tries to use it and gets lost in time. In Infogrames' Bugs Bunny:
Lost in Time ($30, for the Playstation), that wascaly wabbit must
travel through five different eras in order to get back to the
present. Along the way, he meets up with favorites such as Elmer
Fudd, Witch Hazel, Yosemite Sam and Marvin the Martian. If nothing
else, this game teaches the kiddies that you shouldn't play with
time machines.
</P>
<P>
   SAY 'UNCLE'
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Albert is a little touched in the head (we'll just
euphemistically call him ``eccentric''), but boy is it fun to poke
around in his stuff! In Uncle Albert's Magical Album ($30, PC and
Mac), you can look through Albert's scrapbook and piece together an
assortment of puzzles by flipping through pages and putting items
in the right places; if you find a key you can unlock the
rocketship game and go on a space journey. Find the picture of the
champ and you can play in the stadium. The game, a best-seller in
France, is handily adapted to the U.S. and runs on Windows PCs and
Macs. It features many small films, eight individual games and a
host of animal friends to play with. (www.vtechsoft.com/album.html)
</P>
<P>
   BRAINS, TRAINS AND AUTOMOBILES
</P>
<P>
   Do you remember those family vacations when mom and dad would
pack up the kids and a Styrofoam cooler full of bologna sandwiches
and store-brand cola, heading off at 5 a.m. for parts unknown? Do
you fondly recall pelting your parents with countless questions en
route to your destination?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Brain Quest series ($30, PC and Mac) lets your own
kids take that trip, albeit virtually, as tagalongs with the
Perdido family in its brain-powered vacation van. Better the
Perdido's than you, eh? ``Alas,'' you think, ``my kids are getting
their question-and-answer fix somewhere else. Our trips to the
grocery store will be peaceful and question-free.''
</P>
<P>
   And the computerized queries go well beyond the classic, ``Are
we there yet?'' In fact, the engaging program quizzes kids with
thousands of puzzlers in math, science, language arts and social
studies, each grade-tailored correct answer moving the van forward
toward their reward: a postcard of the Perdidos at their vacation
destination.
</P>
<P>
   With an Internet connection, Brain Quest variations include
multiplayer game modes and help with answers via the World Book
online encyclopedia. For a fee, extra game packs with more
questions can be downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, beware: Each Brain Quest title includes a booklet of
bound cards with trivia questions on all 50 states, meaning the
Q-and-A can continue far away from the keyboard. Better brush up on
your U.S. trivia _ looks like those shopping trips won't be so
peaceful after all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
