<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITIES CAUGHT UP IN NET PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is not about trashing celebrities. It's about celebrity
trash _ as in Gary Coleman's bowling shoes and Drew Barrymore's
baby clothes, the sort of stuff that mere humans usually cart off
to the thrift shop or consign to sleep with the mothballs.
</P>
<P>
   These and other sundries are available for auction on the Web,
part of the latest ``dot com'' craze. Haunted by debts and/or
parole officers, onetime celebrities (or, in some cases, their
mothers) are flocking to the Internet to raise money or to
resurrect flagging careers. Hollywood madam Heidi Fleiss, fresh
from her stay in a West Coast penitentiary, is selling it on line;
this time around, though, she's peddling sportswear and autographed
photos. Monica Lewinsky has an on-line boutique, and Drew
Barrymore's mother, Jaid Barrymore, is auctioning off her estranged
daughter's clothing and other items at www.gavelnet.com.
</P>
<P>
   But Coleman, whose claim to fame was his role in the '78-85
sitcom ``Diff'rent Strokes,'' is probably the only former child
star to be the centerpiece of his very own Web-a-thon, a new
concept in self-promotion. The site is the brainchild of UGO
Networks, a New York-based Web company that runs sites geared at
18- to 34-year-old males. UGO Staffers read about Coleman's
financial woes and decided to raise money for the actor on line.
</P>
<P>
   The Coleman site, at http://webathon.ugo.com, is a sort of mock
tribute to the 4-foot-8-inch actor. A timeline details his trials
and tribulations, including his lawsuit against his parents, his
recent arrest for an altercation with a fan, and his declaration of
bankruptcy in August.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who was once worth $18 million, smiles cheerfully on
the site, imploring visitors to ``Save me.'' Folks can either
donate money to help the financially strapped actor or bid on his
leather couch (current bid, $307.50), his bowling ball ($86), and
his ice scraper (a steal at $25.50). The site features ``Gary
Grooves,'' a variation on the Dancing Baby, and offers a contest in
which users can win a $1,000 shopping spree with ``Gary as your
shopping elf.'' There are also ``audition tapes'' and recordings of
Coleman allegedly practicing phone sex in an earlier career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's all scripted,'' a breathless Coleman said, during a
cell-phone conversation as he boarded a plane in New York. ``Don't
take any of that seriously. Jesus, what has happened to people's
funny bones these days?''
</P>
<P>
   In a game that turns Coleman into a virtual pet, users can feed,
punish, or heal the troubled star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the site is absolutely wonderful,'' Coleman said.
``It's going to be nice to make money, but I am also interested in
breaking into the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Robinson, chairman of UGO Networks, insists that Coleman
will receive every single penny raised on the site. ``It's not a
moneymaking venture. It's not a scam,'' Robinson said. ``Gary has
been working in a video store, and this is getting him some
exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also garnering publicity for UGO Networks, Robinson admits.
``It's good for everyone,'' he said. ``It's not as if we're doing
this for Donald Trump.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's an idea: If the trend continues, it's only a matter
of time before one or more of the Donald's exes start auctioning
off his stuff on line. Barrymore's mother, after all, doesn't have
any problem selling off her daughter's stuff, including the red
cowboy hat that Drew, then 6, wore in ``E.T.'' The bidding on the
hat hit $49,500 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Why sell this stuff? ``Drew is such a special, amazing person,''
Jaid Barrymore told the Associated Press. ``I decided to put some
of her things up on the Web to allow people to be part of Drew's
life.'' How sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Web users can also be a part of the lives of other former
celebrities who have turned to the Net. In a way, Fleiss and
Lewinsky are selling the same thing _ products made under duress.
At www.heidifleiss.com, the former madam is auctioning mugs she
made in prison to calm her nerves because ``the day-to-day
lifestyle was so stressful and hectic.'' The former intern is
selling hand-knit purses and totes at www.therealmonica.com:
Learning to knit, she says on the site, was a big ``help in getting
through a time of high anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp, apparently, didn't take up a craft to relieve
stress. But that hasn't stopped her from starting a Web site to
raise money for her legal defense fund. She's shamelessly
soliciting donations at www.lindatripp.com.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Coleman is turning himself into an on-line poster
child. ``It's not demeaning,'' says Robinson. ``He's poking fun of
the media. Look at what he's done. He's got the whole nation
watching now, so who is winning? Who is poking fun of whom?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-23-99 1409EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
