u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-SHOPPING     11-24 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-SHOPPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE SHOPPING GROWS, BUT CATALOGS STILL RULE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PAUL GRONDAHL   
 c.1999 Albany Times Union   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has got a high gee-whiz factor, the stores never close and
you can shop till your browser crashes.
</P>
<P>
   But is on-line shopping for the holidays an easier, better,
safer alternative to schlepping to a mall or ordering from that
stack of catalogs overflowing your mailbox this time of year?
</P>
<P>
   Depends on what you seek from a ``dot com'' experience. Choice
is not an issue. There are thousands of companies selling
merchandise online _ type in the name of your favorite store
followed by .com and voila! _ and the temptation to buy can be
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   American consumers are expected to spend a record $9.5 billion
by shopping on the Internet this holiday season, according to
industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Consumer Reports concluded in a 13-page ``Holiday.shop''
special report in its November issue that on-line shopping Web
sites have a downside. They can be vague when it comes to security
and shipping costs; inventory can be thin; navigating page after
page of items can be exhausting; and ordering procedures can be
Byzantine.
</P>
<P>
   Is it better to thumb through catalogs or to click your mouse on
the buy icon? Consumer Reports' staff members gave mail-order
catalog shopping the edge over cyber shopping in a head-to-head
competition from 25 companies across a variety of categories: ease
of use, content, shipping and others.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to hold a piece of merchandise in your hands _ and
not just view it on a computer screen _ before you buy it, nothing
can compare with reality-based shopping in an actual store.
</P>
<P>
   Although you will pay in time and transportation costs, you will
be spared the high fees for shipping and handling of goods
purchased on line _ quite often 30 to 50 percent of the cost of the
product tacked on.
</P>
<P>
   And for conspiracy theorists or the merely moderately paranoid,
cyber shopping is fraught with privacy issues. Web merchants
routinely track a consumer's movements across a site, time spent on
each page, which photos are viewed, buying patterns and other
nuances.
</P>
<P>
   The data are analyzed, sold or swapped with other companies for
solicitation opportunities via e-mail advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce companies are clearly concerned about a backlash over
privacy and security. The Goliath Amazon.com, for instance, has a
three-page statement about its complex and confusing privacy
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Let the merchants beware. Consumers are keeping their critical
eyes open.
</P>
<P>
   BizRate.com rates e-business and claims to be objective (on-line
companies can't pay to be listed or featured on its Web site).
Founded in 1996, BizRate.com arrives at its ratings by asking tens
of thousands of consumers to report on their on-line shopping
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer complaints about on-line shopping _ particularly
on-line auctions involving a third party _ have risen sharply in
the past year, according to Joe Mahoney, a spokesman for the New
York Consumer Protection Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because an entity has its own Web site does not mean it
has been checked for consumer reliability,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   And in terms of aesthetics, is the on-line shopping experience
as meaningful, as, say, fueling up first with a double latte amid
fresh-baked chocolate chip cookies before strolling the aisles of
your favorite bookstore or clothing boutique and sampling a product
in a tactile way before purchase?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, for millions of e-shoppers, for whom time and
geography are problematic, buying through the Internet is an
efficient alternative.
</P>
<P>
   On-line shopping taken to the next level involves
price-comparison services called bots (short for robots).
Essentially, they level the playing field between buyers and
sellers by offering lightning-quick price comparisons for a product
among dozens of merchants around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Some bots specialize in a certain product, such as computers or
foodstuff.
</P>
<P>
   The only certainty is that online shopping is a growth business.
New companies, bots and ranking services are coming on line daily.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever form you choose _ digital, catalog mail-order or live
and in-person _ happy shopping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-22-99 1314EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
