<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Luxury inn has a special touch: It's all in the details
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 28.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Anne Landers was horrified.
</P>
<P>
   The innkeeper of the Gastonian _ one of the finest lodgings in
this gracious coastal city _ had attempted to turn on a lamp in the
parlor only to find the bulb shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``No big deal,'' said a guest, sipping wine and relaxing after a
long day of shopping and sight-seeing, ``light bulbs burn out all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at four-diamond inns, they don't,'' Landers said.
</P>
<P>
   In minutes, the lamp was glowing.
</P>
<P>
   Landers' attention to detail is what distinguishes this
luxurious inn on East Gaston Street, two blocks from sprawling
Forsyth Park. That, along with handsomely decorated rooms with
working fireplaces and luxurious baths, gourmet Southern breakfasts
and one of the most attractive afternoon teas anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Special touches include fresh flowers, bottled water, handmade
pralines on turned-down beds at night and exquisitely soft bed
linens.
</P>
<P>
   The inn's 17 rooms and suites, filled with mostly English
antiques, are in two Regency Italianate mansions built in 1868. A
shared landscaped courtyard connects the two. Inside, the floors
are heart pine, the walls plaster and the woodwork finely wrought.
</P>
<P>
   An elegant Waterford crystal chandelier hangs in the parlor of
the Main House. Here also is a portrait of a pretty young woman of
16 whom Landers identifies as Eileen Richardson. The Englishwoman
was in her 80s when she agreed to sell the portrait of herself to
the inn's former owners with the stipulation that it be prominently
displayed in a grand home.
</P>
<P>
   When Landers purchased the inn in 1996, she says she ``had to
promise that the portrait would always stay in a place of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Guests hear this story as we nibble on the tasty goodies
prepared by pastry chef Laura Steele, a Culinary Institute of
America graduate who joined the Gastonian staff three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon the dining room table held sun-dried tomato and
basil tea sandwiches, Vidalia onion bites, chocolate truffle-filled
phyllo cups, orange madeleines and strawberry meringues. The next
day, the spread included chocolate chip pecan scones, sun-dried
tomato, basil and ham scones, cucumber sandwiches, lemon tarts and
lime cornmeal cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Even as we indulge ourselves with these tempting tidbits, we
pore over menus and confer with Landers to decide where we'll have
dinner. The concierge calls for reservations, and soon everyone is
out eating again.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, we leave room for the praline.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Rates are $190-$350. Two-night minimum on
weekends. No children under 12. The inn is at 220 E. Gaston St. (at
Lincoln Street). 1-800-322-6603 and on the Web at
www.gastonian.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
