<SLUG> BC-SAVANNAH-SAMPLE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Homes, history are highlights of holiday season in Savannah
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 28.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the stylish lady that she is, Savannah celebrates the
season with panache, offering a variety of festive doings from
holiday dinner cruises aboard the Savannah River Queen to a
Colonial Christmas at Wormsloe Historic Site.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling of some of the activities.
</P>
<P>
   TOURS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Humane Society Holiday House Tour. This tour promises to
take guests inside some of the most spectacular homes and romantic
inns in the historic district. A candlelight tour will be 5-9 p.m.
Friday. A daylight tour is scheduled 1-5 p.m. Saturday. $23.
912-236-7674.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Tybee Arts Association presents a Progressive Art Studio
Tour. The studios of eight of Tybee Island's most prominent artists
will be featured on this holiday tour 1-5 p.m. Dec. 5. Tickets, $6
or $10 for two, available at the Association Gallery, 1606 Butler
Ave., Tybee Island. 912-786-5920.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  12th annual Holiday Tour of Historic Inns. Savannah is known
for its elegant bed-and-breakfast inns. This self-guided walking
tour features 13 of the inns decorated for the holidays Dec. 11-12.
Guests enjoy refreshments in parlors as hosts share the history of
the inns. Included on the tour are Bed &AMP; Breakfast Inn, 117 W.
Gordon St.; Eliza Thompson House, 5 W. Jones St.; Foley House, 14
W. Hull St.; Gaston Street Gallery, 211 E. Gaston St.; The
Gastonian, 220 E. Gaston St.; Hamilton Turner Inn, 330 Abercorn
St.; Magnolia Place Inn, 503 Whitaker St.; Manor House, 201 W.
Liberty St.; Olde Harbor Inn, 508 E. Factors Walk; Planters Inn, 29
Abercorn St.; Presidents' Quarters, 225 E. President St.;
17Hundred90, 307 E. President St.; and Joan's on Jones, 17 W. Jones
St. Tickets are $17, available on tour days at all participating
inns. Hours are 1-5 p.m. both days. 912-232-5678.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  25th annual Holiday Tour of Homes. If you've ever wanted to
get a peek inside some of Savannah's most sumptuous homes, this is
your chance. The Downtown Neighborhood Association opens the doors
to 25 Colonial, antebellum and Victorian homes in the historic
district. Three self-guided tours _ each featuring a different
group of homes _ are scheduled for 1-5 p.m. ($25) and 5-8 p.m.
($15) Dec. 18 and 1-5 p.m. Dec. 19 ($25). A ticket for all three
tours is $60. Proceeds will be used to restore the Winged Lion
monument and fountain at Savannah's Cotton Exchange Building.
Tickets: 912-233-0220.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Christmas 1864 _ Evacuation of Old Fort Jackson. Several
re-enactment units will bring to life the final hours of the
evacuation of Confederate troops from the fort. Three 30-minute
programs will be presented. 6, 6:45 and 7:30 p.m. Saturday. Free. 1
Old Fort Jackson Road. 912-232-3945.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Winter Muster. Gen. William Tecumseh Sherman's capture and
occupation of Fort McAllister at the end of his famous March to the
Sea is recalled during this annual re-enactment. Catch the action
11 a.m.-4 p.m. Dec. 11 and 11 a.m.-3 p.m. Dec. 12. $2, $1 children
5 and younger. 3894 Fort McAllister Road at Spur 144 off Ga. 144.
912-727-2339.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Colonial Christmas. Traditional carols, plum pudding, the
burning of a yule log and living history demonstrations are among
the festivities at Wormsloe Historic Site, where volunteers dress
in period costume. 2-5 p.m. Dec. 12. $1-$2. 7601 Skidaway Road.
912-353-3023.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Christmas Candlelantern Tours. Tickets go quickly for this
popular event at Fort Pulaski, 10 miles east of Savannah on U.S.
80. Costumed volunteers and employees of Fort Pulaski National
Monument show ``visitors from the city'' through the fort. The
hourlong tour re-creates the Confederate Nog Party of 1861, when
the garrison celebrated the season with food, drink and
merrymaking. Guests enjoy cookies and mulled cider by candlelight
while listening to period music. $2; 16 and under free, but
everyone needs a ticket. 6:30, 7:30 and 8:30 p.m. Dec. 18-19.
Reservations, which are required, are taken 1-4:30 p.m. weekdays.
912-786-5787.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Holiday Shoppe at Ex Libris. The Savannah College of Art and
Design sponsors this special shop featuring gifts, pastries and
coffees from around the world. Throughout December, there will be
children's story hours Saturdays, performances and holiday
seminars. 228 Martin Luther King Jr. Blvd. 912-525-5225.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Christmas Market Open House. The City Market will glow with
the light from 500 luminaria that will line courtyards and streets
Friday night. Shops will offer late shopping and complimentary
goodies. Seasonal music will be offered by strolling minstrels and
the Holiday Harmonies, and Father Christmas will make his first
appearance of the season. 912-232-4903.
</P>
<P>
   JUST FOR FUN
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Festival of Trees &AMP; Lights. More than 75 decorated
Christmas trees and wreaths, along with sections for menorahs and
Kwanzaa displays, will fill the Savannah Civic Center lobbychard.
While you're there be sure to check out ``The Bird Girl''
sculpture, whose image appears on the cover of the book ``Midnight
in the Garden of Good and Evil.'' 2-5 p.m. Dec. 12. Free. 121
Barnard St. 912-232-1177.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lollipops II Christmas Concert. The Savannah Symphony presents
an afternoon of holiday music and family fun at the Johnny Mercer
Theatre. 3 p.m. Dec. 12. $9, $5 children general admission.
912-236-9536.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Holiday Pops Concert. The annual Holiday Pops concert with
conductor Skitch Henderson is 8 p.m. Dec. 18 at the Johnny Mercer
Theatre. $17.50-$48.50, reserved seating. 912-236-9536.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From Atlanta, take I-75 south to I-16. Travel
east on I-16 into downtown Savannah. It's about a four-hour drive.
Or fly Delta or AirTran for $39 each way with a 14-day advance
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accommodations: Though chain hotels are reasonably well
represented, it's hard to resist Savannah's inns _ of which there
are more than 30 in the historic district. Expect to pay at least
$80 a night; some tariffs run considerably higher. For a selection,
call for a Simply Savannah Visitor's Guide at 1-877-728-2662 or on
the Web at www.savannahvisit.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining: Finding a great place to eat in Savannah is like
shooting fish in a barrel. Our current favorites are the trendy
bistro Sapphire Grill (110 W. Congress St., 912-443-9962); the
artsy Northern Italian Il Pasticcio (2 E. Broughton St.,
912-231-8888); the Southwestern flair of Tuscon Grill, which offers
killer margaritas and guacamole made tableside (113 E. Broughton
St., 912-233-9669); and updated coastal cuisine in the historic
setting of The Olde Pink House (23 Abercorn St., 912-232-4286).
Lunch surrounded by art and antiques at newcomer Soho South Cafe
(12 W. Liberty St., 912-233-1633).
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth on 37th (105 E. 37th St., 912-236-5547) remains the
queen of Savannah restaurants with Elizabeth Terry's innovative
regional cuisine. And the home cooking at Mrs. Wilkes Dining Room
(107 W. Jones St., 912-232-5997) and The Lady and Sons (311 W.
Congress St., 912-233-2600) still draws queues of hungry diners.
</P>
<P>
   For afternoon tea, try the new Tea Room of Savannah (7 E.
Broughton St., 912-239-9690), which evokes the Charles Rennie
McIntosh-designed Willow Tea Room in Glasgow, Scotland, and Gryphon
Tea Room, which serves afternoon and children's themed teas as well
as an extensive dinner menu (337 Bull St., 912-525-5225).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-877-728-2662 or on the Web at
www.savannahvisit.com (Savannah Area Convention and Visitors
Bureau). The Savannah Scene Web site is also helpful:
www.savannah.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
