<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SAVANNAH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A gift you owe yourself: The gracious coastal city of Savannah
dresses up in holiday finery and gets in the yuletide spirit with a
rousing roster of events
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 28.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Forget chestnuts roasting on an open fire, Jack
Frost nipping at your nose. And don't even think about folks
dressed up like Eskimos.
</P>
<P>
   In this historic coastal city, signs that the holidays have
arrived are a bit more subtle.
</P>
<P>
   A festive wreath hangs from the outstretched hand of the statue
of stern-faced Colonial evangelist John Wesley in Reynolds Square.
The stone swans in Forsyth Square fountain sport jolly red bows
around their slender necks. The Savannah River Queen paddle wheeler
is draped in garlands of greenery. And horse and carriage drivers
don jaunty Santa caps.
</P>
<P>
   Not icicles but Spanish moss drips from ancient live oaks, and
the city's version of the Rockefeller Center ice rink is inside. At
the Savannah Civic Center's exhibition hall, people in jeans and
T-shirts gamely lace up skates and wobble out onto the ice under a
canopy of lights and flanked by a forest of gaily decorated
Christmas trees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Savannah seems a fine place to find some holiday spirit.
</P>
<P>
   We are here the weekend before Christmas last December to take
in the annual Holiday Tour of Historic Inns and Candlelantern Tours
at Civil War-era Fort Pulaski.
</P>
<P>
   It is unseasonably warm, and we swelter in our holiday sweaters
as we stroll among the 22 squares Saturday afternoon to visit
19th-century inns filled with period and antique furnishings and
lavishly adorned in seasonal finery.
</P>
<P>
   Elegant mansions _ once home to the city's rich and powerful _
and converted cotton warehouses now invite overnight guests to
experience the charms of ``The Hostess City of the South.'' Many
boast ornate fireplaces, heart pine floors and secluded courtyards
where breakfast is served when the weather is nice.
</P>
<P>
   There's a welcome chill in the air Saturday night as we drive
out U.S. 80 east to Fort Pulaski, where it's Dec. 26, 1861. The
spirits of the Confederates are high _ despite trading sporadic
fire with the Yankees at Tybee Island. The war is expected to be
over before these men get a real fight going. Food sent to the
garrison from Savannah is good and plentiful. The fiddle music is
lively, and eager young soldiers still move with spring in their
steps.
</P>
<P>
   We follow lantern-toting guides across the moat into the fort,
where a cannon blast booms through the night. Our Confederate
escort tells us he and his comrades drank eggnog the night before
and ``got tangle-footed.'' We sip mulled cider and nibble cookies
as we sing carols to fiddle and flute accompaniment. The dank rooms
of the fort are prettied up with greenery and fruits. Candles
flicker and a fire burns orange in the hearth.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, there's peace in this winter (if not wintry)
wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   Back in town Sunday morning, worshippers flock to services at
city churches, many founded in the 18th century. Our family climbs
the steps of the circa-1890, twin-spired Wesley Monumental United
Methodist Church on Abercorn Street, around the corner from the
Gastonian inn, where we are staying.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of poinsettias grace the sanctuary. Handbells ring out,
acolytes light the candles, and the choir proceeds down the aisles
singing ``Once in Royal David's City.'' Today's service is the
joyous Festival of Nine Lessons and Carols, a series of Scripture
readings interspersed with Advent hymns.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the church, we pause for a moment as brilliant noon
sunlight floods lush Calhoun Square. Another glorious day for
drinking in Savannah's many charms.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, a city so beautiful that even match-happy
Gen. Sherman didn't have the heart to torch it. Instead, he
presented it to President Lincoln in 1864 as a Christmas gift.
</P>
<P>
   No finer one could be had.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
