<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0109 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FIREHOUSE-SALSA-HNS &LR;      11-24 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREHOUSE-SALSA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS ARE RINGING ALARM BELLS IN THE KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARO ROBBINS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Call it fighting fire with fire. Before crew
members on the C shift at Fire Station 44 put out any blazes, they
light a few in their bellies.
</P>
<P>
   The shift starts every third afternoon with a firefighter at the
blender. In goes a can of peeled whole tomatoes, a quarter-onion,
lemon juice, cilantro and two jalapeno peppers. Out comes the hot
sauce _ a fitting food for the people who do a hot job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a tradition to make your own salsa at fire
stations,'' said Capt. Thomas Bullock, the shift supervisor at the
San Antonio station and a 30-year veteran of the fire service.
</P>
<P>
   Besides making generations of firefighters into fire-eaters, the
ritual has inspired a cookbook. A portion of the profits from the
book will benefit victims of fires through the Burned Out Survivors
fund and the University of Texas McDonald Observatory.
</P>
<P>
   The author, Sharee Willis, a St. Mary's University law student,
got the idea for ``San Antonio Firehouse Salsa'' from her
boyfriend, a firefighter who repeatedly returned from work still
raving about the daily dish and the variety available in stations
around town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really at first thought there can't be that many different
salsas,'' Willis said.
</P>
<P>
   But after visiting nearly half of the city's 47 fire stations,
she had sampled about a dozen dishes and collected more than 40
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hottest is the one prepared by firefighter Brandon
Davis at Station 17 on the city's north side. When a batch goes
into the refrigerator, it has, he said, sometimes been marked with
the warning ``liquid hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The recipe, developed with trial, error and the station's spice
rack, calls for 20 serrano peppers. Eating it, Davis said, is not
unlike playing Russian roulette. Depending on the individual
serranos, it can be harmless one time and overpowering the next _
as when it ambushed Davis while he was home watching a ballgame
with some buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us could eat it,'' he said. ``We just poured it down
the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the recipes create subtle variations on similar
ingredients. Improvisers who stray far from tradition are
remembered with a scornful chuckle, as when Bob West, a firefighter
in Station 1, recalled a colleague dumping sour cream into the
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a milkshake,'' West said. ``He took a lot of
ribbing for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although salsa is like humidity, a staple in this South Texas
city of 1 million, most firefighters said they first learned to
concoct the condiment in firehouse kitchens, not at home.
</P>
<P>
   They cook regularly during shifts that last 24 hours. Some
results are swapped and passed down for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   About three decades ago, when he joined the department, Bullock
knew little about the kitchen and less about the differences
between peppers. Now he talks about how subtle markings on a
jalapeno reveal its hidden heat, like notches on a thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people are from Alabama,'' he said. ``We didn't know about
this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, the refrigerators at downtown Station 1
held steak sauce, mustard, ham glaze, all bearing bright brand-name
labels. Only the pulpy red salsa, left half-eaten in a bowl, was
homemade.
</P>
<P>
   Department veteran Juan Herrera explained that, more than a
meal, the salsa is a binding ingredient in the station, a
centerpiece at sit-downs that begin most of his shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a quilting club,'' he said. ``But instead we have a
salsa club.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
