<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0119 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-MICHEL-NY     11-24 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-MICHEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY THANKSGIVING? A NATIVE-AMERICAN PERSPECTIVE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate's NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE is for use only by arrangement
with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For purchase
information, see end of text.) 
 &HT;    
 By KAREN LINCOLN MICHEL 
 &HT;    November is known as ``Deer Mating Month'' among my Ho-Chunk
people. My ancestors had a rare gift for defining the world with
insightful simplicity. Had they lived today they might have called
it ``Indians Are Popular Month.''
 &HT;    This month, images of American Indians are as seasonal as fallen
leaves. From grade-school teachers asking their students to draw
``The First Thanksgiving'' to college professors offering Indian
heritage lectures, educators save their lessons on Native-American
history until November.
 &HT;    It's also one of the only times that local TV anchors actually
utter the words ``Native Americans'' in stories with no connection
to casino gambling.
 &HT;    The natural flow between Thanksgiving and Native-Americans has
prompted some U.S. presidents in my lifetime _ including Bill
Clinton _ to designate November ``National American Indian Heritage
Month.'' A proclamation signed by Clinton said, ``The framers of
our Constitution incorporated Indian nations into the political and
legal framework of this country, forever joining the destiny of the
tribal nations with that of the American people.''
 &HT;    It's great to receive the recognition. But he forgot to mention
another destiny _ choosing this particular month forever links us
to Pilgrims and pumpkin pie.
 &HT;    Despite the holiday connection, Native-Americans in communities
nationwide have found ways to fashion the designated month to their
advantage. Universities and American Indian civic groups probably
are the most skillful at drawing media coverage of native issues by
hosting events and activities that celebrate Native-America.
 &HT;    On its Web site last year, PBS used Indian Heritage Month to
showcase its programming on contemporary Indian life.
Unfortunately, such forward-looking perspectives on native people
are as fleeting as autumn color.
 &HT;    Perennial media coverage of American Indians places tribes in
the context most familiar and comfortable to the average American:
the context of history. Sure, some news reporters try to update
their stories by interviewing Native Americans with a pulse. But
the result is what I call ``covering diversity through event
journalism.''
 &HT;    People of color know what I mean. The media's view of us is
cyclical. It starts with Chinese New Year and ends with Kwanzaa. My
husband has to wait until spring to see his Hispanic culture come
alive in the media. His shot at seeing his people reflected in
local TV news comes on Cinco de Mayo.
 &HT;    On these occasions our cultures are reduced to featherweight
features to which many editors assign interns _ or lackluster
reporters. Our heritage gets summed up in a few quotes and a splash
of festive color. Then when readers and viewers ask editors why
their news organization neglects their racial or ethnic community,
the response is: ``We just covered your parade and festival a while
back.''
 &HT;    But for all the flaws of event journalism, I have to admit that
I look forward to November. Anticipation builds knowing that
finally we'll get noticed in a somewhat positive light.
 &HT;    Maybe this is how some African-American elementary teachers feel
on Jan. 31, the eve of Black History Month. It's bad timing,
though, that the recognition for Native-Americans and
African-Americans comes in the months with the fewest days. A
couple more features could get squeezed in, if only the events
occurred in the months immediately preceding or following February
and November.
 &HT;    Like it or not, American Indians are forever tied to the
Thanksgiving holiday. Never mind that it is Squanto who deserves
credit for educating the Pilgrims on life skills.
 &HT;    Squanto, the lone survivor of the Patuxet Indians who were wiped
out by sickness, broke bread with his white friends after havingtheir Puritan hides from starvation. His friends from the
Wampanoag tribal village also joined in that first celebration of
thanks and eating to excess.
 &HT;    But now, even I am the beneficiary of the 17th-century Indian's
goodwill. Occasionally, around this time of year, some non-Indian
will smile at me and say something like: ``There would be no
Thanksgiving if it wasn't for your people.''
 &HT;    That's right. If tribes hadn't shown white folks the ropes, we'd
probably give thanks each day that we still had our land.
 &HT;    I know of some Native-Americans who ignore the holiday
altogether. A college professor who is Lakota told me she thinks
setting aside only one day a year for thanksgiving runs counter to
her cultural beliefs. Many _ if not all _ tribes believe human
beings should pay homage to the Creator every day and offer prayers
of thanks. The Lakota educator said she'd sooner stick to her own
traditions rather than follow someone else's.
 &HT;    Some might say that I'm nitpicking, and that Native-Americans
should seize the opportunity to educate the public on who they are
today. But this stigma of Indians as Thanksgiving characters has me
wishing for simpler times of autumns past _ when the most notable
event was listening to the sounds of deer mating.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Karen Lincoln Michel, past president of the Native-American
Journalists Association, is co-owner of News from Indian Country.) 
 &HT;    -----
 c. 1999 Karen Lincoln Michel 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC; 
 &UR; To purchase this material contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) &QL;
</TEXT>
