<P>
   ARTICLES FROM LSAT WEEK'S TRANSMISSION:
</P>
<P>
   CRITICS OF JACKSON AT DECATUR IGNORE ONE CENTRAL POINT.
Eisenhower High School in Decatur, Ill., was recently catapulted
into national focus when it expelled seven black male students for
two years because of their involvement in a brawl during a
nighttime football game at the school. The Rev. Jackson deemed the
punishment too harsh and went to Decatur to seek reconsideration _
a much lighter sentence for the youths based upon the absence of
weapons, bloodshed and injury. In this commentary, columnist Vernon
Jarrett supports Jackson's appearance and ponders what might have
happened to these teens had Jackson not gotten involved. ``If
Jackson had not journeyed to Decatur, seven youths, who were never
tried with respect for due process, would have been cut from the
educational process _ maybe permanently,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   A DISGRACEFUL USE OF AN APACHE LEADER. Geronimo, the great
Chiricahua Apache warrior and leader, would spin in his grave if he
knew the U.S. Census Bureau was using his portrait in an
advertising campaign aimed at American Indians, writes columnist
Tim Giago. U.S. Census 2000 hopes to make up for the shortcomings
of the 1990 Census that missed so many people, particularly
minorities. American Indians were among the minority groups that
were miscounted. In this commentary, Giago recounts the life of
Goyathlay (One Who Yawns) _ known to the white man as Geronimo _
who was taken frhomeland in chains because he stood up as a
patriot to defend his people and who died in exile far from his
beloved mountains of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   TRANSLATING TECHNOLOGY. Since the '60s, the demand for more
sophisticated hardware and efficient software has grown faster than
one can say ``DSL,'' writes Benjamin Sun in this excerpt from A.
magazine. New millionaires emerge every day as new technology
companies are launched, bought and sold. For Asian-Americans, this
new environment provides a win-win situation. Asian-American
engineers, programmers and tech wizards alike have been stepping
out of back rooms and into the spotlight. Yahoo!'s Jerry Yang and
Hotmail creator Sabeer Bhatia revolutionized the Internet. Former
Intel vice president Vinod Dham developed the ``pentium'' which
shook technology geeks and Wall Street. Sun is the president and
CEO of CommunityConnect.com, parent company of the interactive
online community, AsianAvenue.com.
</P>
<P>
   PRO-GAY CATHOLICS &AMP; ALLIES CALL FOR JUSTICE AT HOME. When the
U.S. Catholic bishops meet this week in Washington, D.C., one topic
that probably won't be on their agenda is the outrage over the
Vatican's barring an American nun and priest from continuing their
nearly three-decade-long ministry to gay Catholics. Many outraged
Catholics do not intend to let the controversy be swept aside. A
six-page public statement _ with more than 4,000 signatures,
printed this week as a signature ad in the National Catholic
Reporter _ calls on the bishops to appeal the Vatican's decision
and reinstate the gay-affirming clergy. Columnist Chuck Colbert
comments on this historic event.
</P>
