<HEADER>
A0128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-SATURDAYS-HNS &LR;      11-24 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SATURDAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATURDAYS NOT ALWAYS A GRAVEYARD ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC has made a very smart move by rescuing ``Freaks and Geeks''
from the exile that is Saturday night and moving the excellent but
struggling freshman drama to Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Saturday night has been the Elba where new
shows die in anonymity (remember last year's ``Cupid''?). For every
successful ``Walker, Texas Ranger'' on Saturdays, there are several
shows that toil in obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Freaks ...'' moving to Mondays at 8 p.m. in January, at
least it will get a fighting chance to succeed. Earlier this month
the program ranked 97th, the lowest-rated show among the Big Four
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night was once a programming jewel, the home of
``Gunsmoke'' and ``The Honeymooners,'' ``Bonanza'' and ``Perry
Mason'' (all of which were moved around the schedule), and the
powerhouse ABC tandem of ``Love Boat'' and ``Fantasy Island.'' It
was a time when families could still gather and watch the same
shows from a three-channel universe, pre-cable.
</P>
<P>
   The best night of programming ever presented by a single network
aired on a Saturday night. The year was 1973, the network CBS, and
the shows, all five of 'em, are Hall of Famers: ``All in the
Family'' at 8 p.m.; ``MASH'' at 8:30; ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show''
at 9; ``The Bob Newhart Show'' at 9:30, and ``The Carol Burnett
Show'' at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The first four finished in the Top 12 that year, and Carol
Burnett's status as a legend was already secure.
</P>
<P>
   The next season CBS moved the shows around to plant seeds of
success in other nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only one year,'' said Robert Thompson, director of the
Center for the Study of Popular Television at Syracuse University
in Syracuse, N.Y. ``Nothing comes close to that one.''
</P>
<P>
   While the No. 1 all-time lineup is set, there are certainly some
other challengers. Many come from NBC's famed Thursday night
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these lineups were pre-ordained to be hits; other times
the networks just lucked into pay dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you give us more credit than we deserve,'' said
Preston Beckman, the NBC executive vice president for scheduling.
``A lot of the great scheduling moves are made out of desperation.
A lot of it is luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the quality of shows top-to-bottom, here is my take
of the other best single-night prime-time lineups offered by the
networks (years denote the fall start of seasons):
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Thursdays, 1994: ``Mad About You,'' ``Friends,''
``Seinfeld,'' ``Madman of the People'' and ``ER.'' The rookie
season for ``ER'' was ground-breaking.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Mondays, 1953: ``The George Burns and Gracie Allen Show,''
``Arthur Godfrey's Talent Scouts,'' ``I Love Lucy,'' ``The Red
Buttons Show'' and ``Studio One.'' Lucille Ball's show garnered a
59 rating _ which was a steep drop from the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Thursdays, 1984-86: ``The Cosby Show,'' ``Family Ties,''
``Cheers,'' ``Night Court'' and ``Hill Street Blues.'' Must-See TV
before the phrase was coined.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Fridays, 1971-72: ``The Brady Bunch,'' ``The Partridge
Family, ``Room 222,'' ``The Odd Couple'' and ``Love: American
Style.'' Cutting-edge cultural schlock (``Odd Couple'' excluded). A
perfect time capsule.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Sundays, 1967-68: ``Lassie,'' ``Gentle Ben'' ``Ed
Sullivan'' ``Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' and ``Mission:
Impossible.'' Smooth transition that had outdoors, variety and
intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Thursdays, 1993: ``Mad About You,'' ``Wings,''
``Seinfeld,'' ``Frasier'' and ``L.A. Law.'' NBC lucked into this by
slotting ``Mad About You'' in at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Thursdays, 1979: ``Laverne &AMP; Shirley,'' ``Benson,''
``Barney Miller,'' ``Soap'' and ``20/20.'' News magazines were once
unique.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Mondays, 1979: ``The White Shadow,'' ``MASH,'' ``WKRP in
Cincinnati'' and ``Lou Grant.'' Going against ``Monday Night
Football'' obscured this lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Tuesdays, 1965: ``Combat,'' ``McHale's Navy,'' ``F Troop,''
``Peyton Place'' and ``The Fugitive.'' What was ``Peyton Place''
doing in this tube of testosterone?
</P>
<P>
   Honorable mention: ABC, Tuesdays, 1998: ``Home Improvement,''
``The Hughleys, ``Spin City,'' ``Sports Night'' and ``NYPD Blue.''
Only ``Sports Night'' remains in its time slot, although ``NYPD
Blue'' returns in January.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no list would be complete without the three worst
network-programmed nights:
</P>
<P>
   UPN, Mondays, 1998: ``Guys Like Us,'' ``DiResta,'' ``The Secret
Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer'' and ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie.'' Sure it was
recent, but it will live long in the memories of all (well, the
few) who have seen each of those shows.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, Saturdays, 1987: ``Mr. President,'' ``Women in Prison''
(believe it or not, a comedy), ``The New Adventures of Beans
Baxter'' and ``Second Chance.'' To think Fox survived that first
season.
</P>
<P>
   And the worst:
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Fridays, 1983: ``Mr. Smith,'' ``Jennifer Slept Here,''
``Manimal'' and ``For Love and Honor.'' An orangutan, an actress'
ghost, a cop who could turn into animals and a soap opera about
paratroopers. This couldn't even look good on paper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
