<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0133 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-MACHO-COX     11-24 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-MACHO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Much ado about Macho
 &HT;    By Brad Mayhar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Tickets have just gone on sale for WCW's Dec. 27
edition of ``Monday Nitro'' at the Astrodome, and one of the
industry's all-time most popular superstars ``Macho Man'' Randy
Savage has come to town to celebrate the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a table outside of a grocery store, Savage is wearing
his trademark dark sunglasses and signing autographs for hundreds
of fans who have come to buy their tickets for WCW's last Monday
night broadcast of the millennium, appropriately titled ``New
Year's Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   To the general public, he may be known merely as the man in the
Slim Jim beef stick commercials, but to wrestling fans, Savage can
still draw a crowd and fill up seats after 26 years in the
business. This Friday afternoon crowd in the autograph line
consists of fans who've followed him throughout his career, and
school children who skipped class to come meet one of their heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you go `Macho Man,' if you have any needs,'' a local
pastor says, handing Savage a business card to his church.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right man, thanks,'' Savage says in his distinct voice.
</P>
<P>
   Savage who turned 47 on Nov. 15 _ according to ``Pro Wrestling
Illustrated's 1999 Almanac'' _ doesn't show any signs of slowing
down. This year, he's engaged in violent matches with ``Big Sexy''
Kevin Nash and Dennis Rodman, and can still execute his signature
high-flying elbow off the top rope with the same finesse today that
he did 15 years ago - if not better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely harder,'' Savage said, comparing the
competition and the demands on his body in 1999 to 1989. ``There's
no doubt about it, but I'll never admit it (laughing). Actually I'm
in better shape than I've ever been in my whole life if you know
what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that 10 zillion people can't be wrong that the older
you get, the more you're going to feel the injuries, and I've been
through a sawmill. But I've got a real positive attitude, and I
feel like I'm still the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Savage's path to stardom on the mat could have potentially
veered off to a successful career on the diamond. He boasted a .500
batting average at his Chicago area high school and maintained an
above .300 batting average during his tenure as a catcher and first
baseman on minor league clubs for the Chicago White Sox, Cincinnati
Reds and St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his knack for baseball, Savage wanted to follow in the
footsteps of his father, wrestling legend Angelo Poffo. Savage made
his pro wrestling debut during the 1973 off season as the ``Masked
Spider,'' and soon found himself making a living as a wrestler on a
full-time basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a fan of my dad,'' Savage said between autographs.
``I've always loved wrestling since I was a baby _ since I was a
Macho Baby!''
</P>
<P>
   Savage continued wrestling for various organizations throughout
the southern states until the mid-1980s when he joined the WWF,
where he immediately made a name for himself by winning the
Intercontinental title from Tito Santana.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he made the move to WCW, where he has since become one
of five wrestlers to hold both the WWF and WCW world titles (the
others being Hulk Hogan, Ric Flair, Kevin Nash and most recently
Bret Hart.) Savage has enjoyed two title reigns in WWF and three
for WCW and remains a contender for another shot at the title.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Savage has managed to pursue other avenues such
as acting. He has appeared on Nickelodeon and recently duked it out
with Chuck Norris on an episode of ``Walker: Texas Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck Norris is a cool guy, and he's a hero of mine now,''
Savage said. ``I've always liked Chuck Norris. When I saw what kind
of shape he was in, his work ethic and how he was nice to people
and everything, I just totally thought he was a cool guy.''
</P>
<P>
   For now it appears Savage will keep his day (and night) job. His
blonde voluptuous manager Gorgeous George, who is sitting at the
table with Savage smiles when he jokes about wrestling for ``about
122 more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Although, he will not say how long he realistically plans to
continue wrestling, Savage hinted at his possible plans after his
days in the squared circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking of doing something politically or doing my own
radio show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's for certain, with Savage's flamboyant ways and
charismatic personality, ``Macho Madness'' in some form or fashion
will likely continue to run rampant for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
