<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-LAURA-INGRAHAM-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULTIPLYING THE POLITICS OF DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Campaign
Countdown commentary column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MS-NBC host Laura Ingraham.)
 By LAURA INGRAHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Early this fall, Al Gore's campaign was wilting. The vice
president was dogged by widespread Clinton fatigue and the
perception that he was taking the nomination for granted.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, Bill Bradley was wowing the Manhattan financial crowd
_ and also reaching out to the black community, proclaiming,
``Racial unity is who I am.''
 &HT;    To secure his increasingly fragile base, Gore decided he needed
to go ``back to basics'' on the campaign trail. We are now
beginning to see what this cover-your-base strategy means _
treating the American people as a collection of Democratic Party
interest groups.
 &HT;    The Washington Post dubbed it a Gore ``constituency tour.'' I
think a more accurate description would be the ``Divide and Conquer
Tour.''
 &HT;    Gore's campaign manager, Donna Brazile, got specific after the
vice president's campaign stops in California, Tennessee and Iowa.
 &HT;    ``The four pillars of the Democratic Party are
African-Americans, labor, women and what I call other ethnic
minorities,'' she said.
 &HT;    What a cynical view! Far from saying ``bring us together,''
here's a campaign that thinks it's a winning strategy to dice the
country up by color, gender and whatever other demographic traits
the pollsters select.
 &HT;    Set aside the fact that the so-called ``gender gap'' _ Texas
Gov. George Bush actually runs evenly with Gore among women _ is
really more of a gap between married and single women: Married
women tend to vote Republican, singles tend to vote Democratic.
Never mind that most Americans could claim to be ``ethnic
minorities.''
 &HT;    Even so, the Divide and Conquer Tour reflects a poisonous view
of the American people _ group-think is in, independent thought is
out.
 &HT;    Brazile told reporters that Gore also would focus on ``emerging
constituencies.''
 &HT;    ``Great,'' I thought. ``Maybe Gore is reaching beyond arbitrary
classifications of race and gender toward groups that identify with
issues Gore cares about.''
 &HT;    But here's how Brazile defined that outreach: ``The emerging
constituencies are environmentalists, gays and lesbians and those
with physical disabilities.''
 &HT;    When I asked my gay brother whether the Gore camp could safely
count gays as part of the Democratic base, he laughed.
 &HT;    ``Yeah,'' he said, ``and we all listen to Barbra Streisand,
too.''
 &HT;    He considered Brazile's comments ``incredibly patronizing.''
Other gay friends were also not amused _ even those who are
politically liberal warned that politicians who try to pander to
the gay ``community'' could find themselves alienating as many gays
as they rally to their cause.
 &HT;    The Gore campaign's decision to target the disabled vote made
even a high-ranking Democratic senator wince. What the party should
be chasing now, this senator told me privately, are Reagan
democrats and the ``techno-generation.''
 &HT;    And by the way, just what kind of a disability president will
you be, Mr. Gore? The Charles Krauthammer type? The Max Cleland
type? Or will you play it safe and proclaim yourself a Christopher
Reeve Democrat?
 &HT;    The notion that people with disabilities should think alike is _
let's just say it _ outrageous!
 &HT;    Unfortunately, in recent years Democrats have become addicted to
this sort of identity politics. It was Gore, let's not forget, who
first introduced Willie Horton to the American people, attacking
former Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis during the 1988
Democratic primaries. Vice President George Bush was later
denounced for using this divisive symbol of black crime against
Dukakis in the general election, but Horton was a Democratic
invention.
 &HT;    Gore and his mentor, Bill Clinton, claimed to have transcended
the old politics of fragmentation when they ran as New Democrats in
1992. Clinton's famous criticism of rapper Sister Souljah, in the
presence of civil-rights leader Jesse Jackson, supposedly
symbolized their break with political group-think.
 &HT;    The fact that Gore is now embracing the politics of division is
a sign of how worried he is about Bradley. He wants to scare the
core Democratic constituencies back into line before the challenger
gains any more ground.
 &HT;    I'd like to think that Gore's cynical strategy will backfire.
Already his likely Republican opponent is speaking out against this
type of divisive politics.
 &HT;    ``I don't believe in group thought _ pitting one group of people
against another. All that does is create kind of a huge political
... nightmare,'' Gov. George W. Bush said on last Sunday's ``Meet
the Press,'' explaining why he won't hold a special meeting with a
gay Republican group.
 &HT;    Even if Gore's Divide and Conquer strategy turns out to be good
primary-election politics, it's bad for the country. It will make
it harder for Gore to campaign as candidate of the people in the
general election, and harder still to govern if he wins.
 &HT;    As Gore himself says, ``a president is the only one empowered to
fight for all of the people.''
 &HT;    That's some political advice Al Gore should take.
 c.1999 Laura Ingraham  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Laura Ingraham is a lawyer and the host of the MS-NBC daily
program ``Watch It! With Laura Ingraham.'' She is the author of the
upcoming book, ``The Hillary Trap: Looking for Power in All the
Right Places,'' due from Hyperion in 2000.)
 &UR; EDITORS: To subscribe to Campaign Countdown, a rotating
campaign-commentary column written by former Democratic
vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by MS-NBC host
Laura Ingraham, contact Bob Farnell at (800) 535-4425, or e-mail
him at farnellb &LR; nytimes.com. &QL; 
