<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE PRIMED FOR VIRGINIA TECH GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is that cute TV phrase? Oh, right. ``Appointment
Television.'' That's what the network pooh-bahs call shows such as
``ER'' and ``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, the Boston College Eagles will be involved
in a sporting version of ``Appointment Television.'' Anyone in
America who cares about college football will be in front of his or
her TV set at 2:30 p.m. EST when undefeated Virginia Tech takes the
field in the hopes of nailing down a berth in the Jan. 4 Sugar Bowl
against Florida State, the winner to be crowned national champion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a lot of those viewers think the game is over
already. Virginia Tech is, at last look, a 24-point favorite. The
average fan regards BC as a bug on the Hokie windshield, which, as
you might surmise, is just fine with the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard people describe us as a `soft' 8-2,'' says
quarterback Tim Hasselbeck. ``But, you know what? That's the way
it's been all year. We were 10-point underdogs at Notre Dame. This
gets us motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to it,'' says defensive lineman Mike Willetts,
whose tipped extra point played a huge role in last Saturday's
31-29 victory over Notre Dame. ``I think it's kind of funny. The
underdog role has worked pretty well for us this year.'
</P>
<P>
   Second-ranked Virginia Tech will really be playing two games on
Friday. The immediate opponent is BC. The other opponent is the BCS
computer. In order to stay ahead of Nebraska in that all-important
rating, Virginia Tech must do more than merely defeat BC. It must
punish BC. In the really big scheme of things, anything under a
10-point victory (perhaps even as many as 14) is a loss.
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much answers the question as to which team will be
playing under more pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure's on them,'' maintains senior safety Pedro
Cirino. ``Definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   According to coach Tom O'Brien, BC has been playing
pressure-free for the past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said the front part of the schedule was the easy
part,'' he points out. ``So those were the difficult games, the
ones we had to win. In the past five weeks we've been able to play
with a nothing-to-lose, chip-on-the-shoulder attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Candor is a refreshing part of the O'Brien package. You've got
to like a coach who admits on the eve of the biggest game of the
season that he never thought it would come to this.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a tremendous group of overachievers,'' he says.
``I thought 6-5 would have been a very good year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the season, O'Brien was looking at four new
assistant coaches. He had real questions about his offense. The
idea that BC could provide legitimate opposition for an undefeated
Virginia Tech team on the day after Thanksgiving was a fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the case. It is, in fact, an ideal coaching
circumstance in that Tom O'Brien has a team that is as ready as it
can possibly be to play the Big Game. Playing a team as imposing as
the Hokies in Week 2, 5, 7, or 9 would have been pointless. But
playing them with the team he has now, well, he's very happy to
take his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told the team that the first 10 games are warmups for
this one,'' he says. ``We've talked all year about getting better
week by week, and we have. So are we as ready to play as I could
ever ask? Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'd say this is the perfect time,'' says
Hasselbeck, ``but it's pretty good. When I look back at how we
played (on Opening Day) against Baylor, it's like night and day.
The way our defense has come along, and with the big wins we've
had, it's a really good time for us to go down there.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an especially satisfying moment for seniors such as
Chris Hovan and Cirino, who have lived through some bad times at BC
and who now are being rewarded by getting a national Appointment
Television showcase in the autumn of their collegiate careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered at times if we'd ever turn this thing around,''
says Cirino, the ferocious hitter from Jersey City. ``But so many
of the games we lost in past years were close. We're finally
getting the breaks, like Notre Dame not getting the extra point, so
later on they'd have to go for 2. It's our turn now. Things are
working out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was more representative of BC's resolve against Notre
Dame than Cirino, whose interception stopped the final Notre Dame
drive. He was actually carrying in his pants the by-now-famous
photo of Notre Dame stopping Mike Cloud last year. Coach O'Brien
didn't have to do anything to get his team up for Notre Dame, and
he isn't going to need any Rockne speeches on Friday afternoon,
either. With leaders such as Cirino and Hovan, the psych-up thing
is already taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing the No. 2 team in the country is enough inspiration,''
says Hovan, the superb nose guard. ``It's the only game on TV.
Everybody will be watching. Don't worry; I refueled my tank on
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   All anyone can ever ask for in life is an opportunity to pursue
one's dreams and one's goals. Fate and a fascinating convergence of
circumstance have placed Tom O'Brien, his staff and his team in a
situation that will have the entire college football community
watching them play a highly important game on Friday in Blacksburg,
Va. That's as good as it gets, and BC is not about to apologize for
being there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've earned this,'' asserts Cirino, a born football player if
ever there was one. ``There's no doubt about it. We've earned
this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
