<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATES'S TIME WAS WELL-SPENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ He has been told countless times by the coaching
staff that when he gets his ice time, he should make the most of
it.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, when that opportunity is only a few minutes a
game, it becomes a chicken-and-egg scenario. If you log only a
small amount of time, it's difficult to produce, and if you don't
produce, you won't be given an increase in ice time.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Carolina Hurricanes Monday, Shawn Bates was pressed
into duty by the center-poor Bruins with Joe Thornton sidelined by
a knee injury. Bates had to play a lot _ 16 minutes and 31 seconds
over 25 shifts _ on a line with Dave Andreychuk and Steve Heinze.
He finished with a team-high four shots on net, was a plus-1, won
more faceoffs than he lost, and assisted on a goal by Andreychuk in
Boston's 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played really well,'' said coach Pat Burns, not one to
praise players lightly. ``Andreychuk kept on talking to him the
whole game, which helped us for sure. There was a little bit more
confidence in him. He's got to have that, be first on the puck to
make things happen. That's how Andreychuk scored his goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates, who is in his third year of pro hockey after a standout
career under Jack Parker at Boston University, said he couldn't
swear it was the most ice he'd ever had in his young NHL career,
but it seemed so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty tired,'' said Bates. ``I know I had a lot more fun
out there. I want to show (Burns) that I can play in this league.
Playing 17 minutes with guys like that, that's going to help me
out.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that he was teamed with a sniper in Andreychuk
and an up-and-down wing in Heinze. Heinze, who has been on the
downswing recently, played significantly better and generated a
couple of excellent scoring chances, including doing the dirty work
that led to Andreychuk's score that tied the game, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with two experienced guys and that made my job
easier,'' said Bates. ``Once you get out there a little bit more,
you get a little bit more confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity is there with Joe being out and me being a
centerman. I played a lot of minutes and I think I did a pretty
good job. I almost had a couple of goals out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates wasn't shy about playing student to Andreychuk's teacher.
Part of Andreychuk's credibility comes from his patience, his
class, and his experience. The rest comes from his credentials as a
goal scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been around for so long,'' said Bates. ``I go to him
first for advice, like where I am supposed to be in terms of
position. I ask him if I'm out of position and what can I do to
help us out. He talked to me through the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a lecture; a word here, a phrase there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like if I'm out of position on the trap or
forechecking,'' said Bates. ``If I'm funneling the wrong way, like
I should be forcing them up the boards instead of behind the net.
Things like that, things that might go over my head that he
notices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a whole bunch of things. I just want to know if I did
something wrong after every shift. He comes up and tells me. It's
no big thing but he's trying to help me out and make me a better
player. He knows the game as well as anyone in the league. I'll
take advice from him any day.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk said it's helpful for everyone on the line if there
is better communication, and he found Bates to be a willing pupil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's one of those guys who is willing to learn,'' said
Andreychuk. ``He wants to be better and that's going to help him.
You could see as the game went on, he got better. We were able to
create more chances. He was using his speed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Bates has to rely on himself _ on his
instincts, his speed, his determination to make it difficult for
the coaches to keep him off the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around long enough to know that when the opportunity
comes around, you've got to produce,'' he said, ``and that's what
I'm trying to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
