<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS IN NEED OF A COUNTERATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ After the Dolphins lost in Buffalo two weeks
ago, their preparation for the subsequent Patriots game was
described by one player as ``hell on Earth.'' When the Jets lost in
Oakland in the last moments earlier this season, Bill Parcells's
next practice was so tough that one player vomited several times.
</P>
<P>
   After two lackluster performances against key divisional rivals,
the Patriots will trudge back to the practice field Wednesday. If
ever there was a time the Patriots needed a little misery on the
practice field, it's now.
</P>
<P>
   Will they get it?
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, Sunday's game in Buffalo may go like the last
two. The Jets came up with a defensive scheme that was designed to
bully Drew Bledsoe. Miami mimicked that, but added more force. The
Bills likely will continue the trend.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots don't counter what the Bills throw at them, Pete
Carroll may indict himself forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the talent here to run the table,'' said Shawn
Jefferson, whose 68-yard touchown reception proved to be the New
England highlight of a 27-17 loss to the Dolphins. ``But we have to
straighten some things out in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as frustrating to us as it is to everybody else because
we know we're better than this. We've got to find a way to pull it
together and play football like one of the best teams in the
league. It's not too late for anything. We still have a chance to
achieve all of our goals, and that's the attitude everybody _ the
coaches, players, front office people _ have to take.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus surely will be on offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese,
who started the season looking like a genius but recently has led
many to scratch their heads over the play-calling.
</P>
<P>
   This is not new for Zampese and quarterbacks coach Jack Reilly;
three years ago, the same charges were brought against them in
Dallas: The offense was too predictable and very unproductive.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese and Reilly were dismissed from Dallas when head coach
Barry Switzer was fired by owner Jerry Jones. The more
offensive-minded Chan Gailey was brought in to run the show.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese quickly found a home in New England after the Patriots
fired Larry Kennan, making him the scapegoat of the 1997 season.
Offensive line coach Paul Boudreau was scapegoated last season,
even though Robert Edwards ran for almost 1,200 yards as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are unlikely to have a 1,000-yard rusher this
season, which is part of the problem with the offense. At times the
Patriots haven't been able to run. But even when they've shown
signs that they can run _ such as Sunday vs. Miami, against a tough
defense _ they have elected not to. It is this inconsistency that
has put the offense in a critical state.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, again in the line of fire of fans and media, said last
week that he would not take a greater role in the offense. Carroll
is primarily a defensive coach. But he is the head coach, and what
he says must be adhered to. The powerful coaches eventually take
control when there are problems areas on a team, but so far Carroll
has stopped short of that with the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest concern for Carroll at the moment is getting Bledsoe
out of his funk.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots talk about getting him back into a rhythm, but
there are concerns that perhaps the timing offense isn't right for
him. One player said this week that he feels Bledsoe is at his best
when he can take a seven-step drop, survey the field, then
distribute the ball _ as he did in the Parcells system.
</P>
<P>
   The Zampese system was supposed to be designed to protect the
quarterback more from hits, yet Bledsoe has been hit more than
anyone in the league. His interception rate is also alarming.
</P>
<P>
   In their six wins, the Patriots have turned the ball over five
times; in the four losses, they've committed 14 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The defense shouldn't get off the hook, either. The Patriots are
the only team in the AFC East to have allowed more than 200 points
(201).
</P>
<P>
   They should receive an emotional boost this week when Ted
Johnson begins practicing in pads. He is not expected to do 100
percent of the reps, but the Patriots are hoping to gradually build
him up and are still eyeing a very optimistic Dec. 5 return. But
just Johnson's presence in a uniform could be enough to spark the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   A strange aspect of the season is that, other than Johnson, the
Patriots have not had major problems with injuries. Their key
players _ Bledsoe, Terry Glenn, Troy Brown, Ben Coates, Jefferson,
Willie McGinest, Ty Law, Lawyer Milloy, Chris Slade _ all remain on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Health was supposed to be the key factor in the Patriots'
hanging in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, we have our players in good health and I think if
we can get back on the winning trail, that has to be an issue the
rest of the season,'' said Jefferson. ``There are a lot of good
players here and they have pride. They don't want to go out there
and get beaten like that. This isn't on any of the coaches. This is
on us. If we're as good as we say we are, we have to go out and
prove it this week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
