<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MERRYMOUNT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE OTHER EARLY SETTLERS: MORTON AND HIS MERRY BAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUINCY, Mass. _ Down the coast at Plymouth, in the image so
deeply etched in the national memory, the Pilgrims would be seated
at a long harvest-laden table, faces solemn and heads bowed in a
prayer of thanksgiving, with a few equally grave Indians among
them.
</P>
<P>
   But here, on a hillock now called Merrymount, a rival group of
colonizers could be found reveling around a maypole, perhaps arm in
arm with their Indian trade partners (and sometimes bed partners).
</P>
<P>
   It was the Pilgrims who triumphed in the New World, as is
abundantly clear this Thanksgiving week. Rival leader Thomas Morton
and his Merrymount revelers are as forgotten as the Pilgrims are
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   But Jack Dempsey, who has produced a new edition of Morton's
account of the land and its native people, `New English Canaan,''
believes that Merrymount is as much a part of the American
experience as Plymouth is.
</P>
<P>
   And by dealing with the Indians as economic _ and social _
partners, Dempsey suggests, Morton may be even more relevant to an
increasingly multicultural world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nub of the problem,'' says Dempsey, is that Europeans who
visited New England periodically in the years before the Pilgrims
settled in Plymouth in 1620 ``were trading with the Native
Americans in the way they wanted.'' They gave them guns in trade
for furs _ and they intermarried. ``When Morton comes to town'' in
1624 and sets up a trading post _ with a maypole decorated with
stag's antlers as a kind of billboard _ ``he's willing to give the
locals whatever they want for their furs and he gets what he
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton realized ``that if you gave the Indians what they wanted,
they'd take you upcountry where the furs were,'' Dempsey says.
Thus, Morton became ``an economic threat to Plymouth _ not a
cultural one, even with his maypole _ and had to be suppressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey, 44, has been studying Morton for 15 years. Morton had
been a lawyer back in England and was an associate of Ben Jonson
and other English Renaissance poets. In 1624, he came to New
England and took over a failed settlement _ known as Wollaston for
its original settler _ naming it Ma-re Mount in a play on the Latin
word for ``ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey sees Morton as both pragmatist and visionary, dealing
with the Indians on mutually beneficial terms and writing of their
common intertwined existence in a new biblical land of milk and
honey. At Ma-re Mount, Dempsey writes, Morton was ``surrounded by
extremes of hardship and free-wheeling atmosphere, by a crowd of
many different cultures, working together in secular
self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey talks of Morton and his followers ``feasting on venison
steaks while rival colonists in Boston and Weymouth were
starving.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey says that Morton would have seen maypoles attracting
crowds to market fairs in England and cleverly adopted one as
``literal staging'' for his New England business operations.
</P>
<P>
   Plymouth Colony, its essence founded on conservative religious
teachings, sent Myles Standish, its military leader, to arrest
Morton four years after Ma-Re Mount's settling. A few months later,
Governor John Endicott of the new Massachusetts Bay Colony moved on
Ma-re Mount to disband the trading post and chop down the maypole _
an incident that became the basis for a short story by Nathaniel
Hawthorne and later for Robert Lowell's verse play, ``Endicott and
the Red Cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton was marooned on the Isles of Shoals off New Hampshire and
eventually made his way back to England. He returned to Ma-re Mount
a year later, but was again arrested and exiled to England. There
he wrote the ``New English Canaan,'' originally as a legal brief
but interspersed with poems in its final form. In 1643, close to
70, Morton returned again to New England, only to be jailed as a
suspected ``royalist agitator.'' Freed in 1645, after the royalists
were defeated in the English Civil War, he made his way to what is
now York, Maine, where he died.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey who teaches composition at Wheaton College, views
Morton's poetry as a manifesto for what the trader saw as an
essential cultural condition for successful colonizing _ evident in
the posting of a poem on the Ma-re Mount maypole.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey's edition of ``New English Canaan,'' which includes a
biography of Morton, is the first since one edited by Charles
Francis Adams Jr. for the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1893.
It is published locally by DSI, a digital scanning company in
Scituate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
