<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-END-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`END OF DAYS' FILLED WITH ENDLESS DRIVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
END OF DAYS 
Directed by: Peter Hyams 
Screenplay by: Andrew W. Marlowe 
Starring: Arnold Schwarzenegger, Gabriel Byrne, Kevin Pollak, Robin
Tunney, CCH Pounder, Rod Steiger, Derrick O'Connor, Miriam
Margolyes 
Running time: 122 minutes 
Rated: R (intense violence and gore, a strong sex scene and
language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add to the list of Y2K nuisances the new Arnold Schwarzenegger
movie ``End of Days.'' It seems endless. It's also unusually crude
and stupid, even for an Arnold Schwarzenegger movie. Having
presumably exhausted the list of possible earthly adversaries, it
sends him up against the devil, who, as played by Gabriel Byrne,
seems to have all the fun here. Coyly called The Man (a bid to
avoid offending devil-worshipers?), he coolly strolls through
Manhattan in the borrowed body of an investment banker, wreaking,
as they say, havoc. The way it works is he smirks and something
explodes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not all fun and games for the devil. Before the
stroke of the new millennium he's got to find and impregnate a
certain woman in order to climb out from under a heavenly curse as
spelled out in the Book of Revelations. Only Schwarzenegger's cop
attached to an anti-terrorist unit can stop him. First, though,
there's the question of whether the cop is going to stop himself as
he sits in his seedy bedroom with a pistol in his hand,
contemplating suicide because he feels guilty about having left his
murdered wife and child unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the suicidal feeling passes, and the cop gets down to
business. But because he's supposed to be depressed, he keeps the
unshaven bummed-out look. He gets to Robin Tunney's unlucky
designated mother one step ahead of the devil, but it takes him an
inordinately long time and many shootings later to realize that
bullets don't do it when it comes to taking out the devil. Not that
the devil even does much of his own dirty work. It doesn't take
much for him to bend this or that human to his will. There is one
fringe benefit. His henchmen are endowed with super strength and
the ability to come back from the dead.
</P>
<P>
   This plot twist peaks when roly-poly Miriam Margolyes, as one of
the unholy acolytes, wipes the floor with Schwarzenegger's cop. Not
that everybody is against him. Kevin Pollak, his police partner,
provides comic relief. And Rod Steiger turns up as a priest who
knows the score and just might be trustworthy. But as the body
count and decibel level climb, one's involvement plummets. The film
is so preoccupied with technical logistics, so busy administering
sensory jolts, that it leaves no room for anything like character
or even impulse, let alone feeling. Think of ``End of Days'' as
Hollywood's own Y2K bug, at a multiplex near you. As for
Schwarzenegger, he'll be back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
