<SLUG> BC-ESHOP-SUPPORT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT SEEN KEY TO WINNING E-COMMERCE CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDFORD, Mass. _ There is an eerie silence here among the
cubicles at ESupportNow, as 35 men and women, mostly in their
mid-20s, chat with customers, answering routine questions about
products and services.
</P>
<P>
   But this chat is different. Instead of talking on the telephone,
most are tapping out responses on a computer keyboard to help
Priceline.com customers with hotel reservations and respond to
floral-arrangement concerns and delivery issues sent from customers
at the Web site of KaBloom Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   These workers are ``nowreps,'' such as Jason Taglieri, whose
flying fingers allow him to reply to as many as five e-mail
messages in a matter of minutes. Nearby, Frank Figueroa and Deisy
Nobles respond in Spanish or English to messages from users of
Espanol.com who are buying Latin music CDs and Spanish-speaking
Sesame Street videos, as well as jewelry, spiritual items,
fragrances, and sporting goods.
</P>
<P>
   With Forrester Research forecasting $4 billion to be spent on
line between Thanksgiving and Christmas _ double last year's volume
_ customer support services will play a big role in completing
sales transactions and retaining customers into next year.
</P>
<P>
   And while some e-commerce companies have their own in-house
support staffs to handle buyer concerns, many others, including
Priceline.com, which receives more than 4,000 e-mail messages per
day, want to outsource part or all of their customer support.
</P>
<P>
   So far, two independent companies have sprung up to address this
growing need. ESupportNow and PeopleSupport of Los Angeles both
devote themselves exclusively to providing e-commerce companies
with the Web equivalent of a call center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten questions asking if I have any suggestions for
buying a gift for a grandmother, and we respond by asking about the
recipient's interests and how much the buyer wants to spend, and
direct them to the gift center on the Web site,'' said Amy O'Neil,
a nowrep for ESupportNow who handles some of the 100 daily chats
for Shopnow.com, a Seattle-based on-line retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike going to a shopping mall and seeking help from a sales
clerk, or calling a bank's telemarketing representative about a
credit card bill, logging on for instant advice presents a bigger
challenge for ``dot-com'' companies to keep customers satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   There is a natural tendency to pick up the phone to get answers
to a problem rather than going back to the Web site, clicking on
customer support, and bantering by e-mail hoping to get answers
relatively quickly. And with so many places to shop on the Web,
small e-commerce companies don't have the back-office support to
handle many queries, leaving customers frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ESupportNow and PeopleSupport were each launched barely a year
ago, and are a tiny fraction of the overall telephone-based
customer support market. They compete with telephone call centers
that are now scrambling to offer on-line support. ESupportNow
charges its client companies $2.50 to $7.50 per call, depending on
the volume _ far less than the $8 to $10 it costs for telephone
support offered by independent call centers, said Renan Levy, the
Israeli-born founder and chief executive of ESupportNow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes young people who not only know the Internet but can
also think and learn fast to juggle a lot of incoming messages _
skills that are different from telephone call center personnel,''
said Levy, who previously ran a 1,500-person telephone call center
for Cross Country Group Inc. in Medford, which also financed his
year-old company.
</P>
<P>
   His secret for bringing telephone etiquette to the keyboard?
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell our staff to smile when they chat and to Spellcheck
before they send anything,'' said Levy, who claims finding nowreps,
who are paid $10 to $14 an hour, has not been a problem, as most
new hires are employee referrals.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, business is brisk. The company added 10 more workers
just last week to reach 110 employees, mostly nowreps, up from five
in January. It now has 26 clients, up from just one in January.
Revenues have climbed from $2,000 at the beginning of the year to
$100,000 in July, and are expected to surpass $400,000 this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shopping on the Web will get its real test between now and the
end of the year, as customers decide which companies they will
continue to buy from based on their customer service,'' said Cormac
Foster, an analyst at Jupiter Communications Inc., a New York
Internet market research firm. ``Many of the e-commerce firms that
don't respond quickly to buyer concerns _ which we saw last
Christmas _ may not be around next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Both ESupportNow and PeopleSupport say they are prepared for the
big holiday rush, each estimating that between 5 and 10 percent of
customers who buy on the Web will seek on-line help. Each
guarantees to respond to e-mail in less than three hours. Both also
offer ``chat,'' which enables the customers to send and receive
messages with an immediacy that helps complete a sale _ a key
selling point. Forrester Reseach says that at more than two-thirds
of all Web retail sites, only two visitors per 100 buy anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``On-line companies are looking to close sales, and they're
spending 5 to 7 percent of their revenues on customer support,''
said Lance Rosenzweig, founder and chief executive of
PeopleSupport, whose clients include Reel.com, which sells videos;
clothing site Armani Exchange; and Carparts.com.
</P>
<P>
   For customers who after chatting still have questions only an
on-line company official can answer, ESupportNow can link the
customer to the appropriate person along with a transcript of the
dialog. This saves everyone time: The customer does not have to
start all over explaining the problem, and the manager can scan
what's been said and respond more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ESupportNow's nowreps can help on-line customers
locate a particular page on a client's Web site _ for example, one
containing specific financial policies _ without the customer using
the keyboard. They can also assist shoppers over the phone and the
Web at the same time, provided the caller has two lines.
</P>
<P>
   And for Web surfers who linger at a particular client's site but
do not buy anything _ akin to circling the same racks at Macy's for
20 minutes before a sales clerk offers to help _ ESupportNow can
jump in and provide assistance. However, on the Web, that strategy
is used sparingly, Levy and his staff acknowledge, because it can
be jolting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people can't believe there is a live person out there on
the Web,'' said Susan Macri, ESupportNow's vice president of client
services, adding that the company's nowreps routinely work for
several clients at once, answering a question or two about flowers,
then helping a customer of a relocation marketing firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
