</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 230 or 227.
PLEASE NOTE: THERE IS NO ATTENDANCE CHART WASHINGTON, Nov. 24 --
The following chart shows how senators and representatives voted on
key bills and amendments within the last week. A ``Y'' means the
member voted for the measure; an ``N'' means the member voted
against the measure; a ``?'' means the member did not vote; and a
``P'' means the member voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Nov. 19 approved, 74 to 24, a final catch-all
spending bill that provides more funds for education and health
programs, restores $12 billion of previously cut funds to Medicare
and provides funds for the U.S. to repay debts to the United
Nations. The consolidated spending bill also gives $435.8 million
to the District of Columbia, and includes a plan to allow satellite
companies to provide local broadcast service to customers.
Supporters said the $385 billion bill gives more money to key
programs without dipping into the Social Security surplus.
Opponents said the bill represented bad budgeting practices by
including too many last-minute provisions. They were also concerned
that most members did not have time to read the 2000-page document
before voting. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   THERE ARE NO HOUSE VOTES THIS WEEK.
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The attendance record is not part of the
current vote chart because the company that supplied us with the
information is no longer in service. We are looking for a new
source.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   keyword(s) state(s)pa
</P>
</TEXT>
