<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FEAR INVESTORS ARE IGNORING DANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the stock market shot higher last week after the Federal
Reserve hiked interest rates, David Wyss was baffled.
</P>
<P>
   The chief economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI couldn't figure
out why investors were so excited. A week later _ with stock prices
even higher _ he still can't. ``It doesn't make any sense,'' says
Wyss, who is not the only one around scratching his head.
</P>
<P>
   A number of forecasters and money managers insist that investors
either didn't read what the Fed had to say or that they were
wearing rose-colored reading glasses at the time. A careful look at
the Fed's words suggests that the central bank may not be finished
hiking interest rates and that the next increase could come as
early as March.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the laws of economics have been repealed, higher interest
rates are still bad for stocks. Says Mark Zandi, chief economist at
RFA Dismal Sciences, ``The market is at risk and the higher it
rises, the more at risk it becomes.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, there were some soothing words in the statement the
Fed released last Tuesday to explain its 1/4 percent hike in rates.
The central bank said inflation is ``contained,'' and productivity
is ``accelerating.'' The Fed went on to say that as a result of its
three rate hikes since June, the risk of inflation going forward is
diminished markedly.
</P>
<P>
   So far so good.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in another paragraph, the message was not so encouraging.
According to the statement, ``The expansion of activity continues
in excess of the economy's growth potential. As a consequence the
pool of available workers willing to take jobs has been drawn down
further in recent months, a trend that must eventually be contained
if inflationary imbalances are to remain in check and economic
expansion continue.''
</P>
<P>
   In English, the Fed is saying this: We think the economy is
growing too fast and the unemployment rate is too low. We want to
see the economy slow down and the jobless rate stabilize, at the
very least.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed would like to orchestrate a soft landing,'' says Fred
Breimyer, chief economist at State Street Bank.
</P>
<P>
   To date, there is precious little evidence the economy is doing
anything but soaring. When the government reports on growth this
morning, the numbers are expected to show the gross domestic
product expanded at a 5 percent annual clip in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters expect another robust performance in the fourth
quarter. At 4.1 percent, the jobless rate is near a 30-year low and
every survey of employers shows that workers are hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market's strength is contributing to the problem, says
Zandi. The higher stock prices rise, the more confident consumers
will be and the more they will spend. If that trend continues,
warns Zandi, ``the Fed will have no choice but to raise rates
further.''
</P>
<P>
   So why are investors ignoring the danger?
</P>
<P>
   There are a few possible explanations. Investors may believe
that the economy will slow down on its own over the next few
months. Interest rates are higher than they were, and with a bit of
lag time, they may begin to act as a brake on growth.
</P>
<P>
   An alternate explanation concerns the new economy. The market
may believe that today's premier companies _ Cisco Systems, EMC,
Dell Computer _ are going to grow like gangbusters in any kind of
economic environment.
</P>
<P>
   Obstacles such as higher interest rates and higher oil prices
might slow these companies down some, but not enough to make a real
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the stock market may be convinced things are going to
work out perfectly, just as they have for the past four years. Over
that time, economists and other assorted pessimists have warned
repeatedly that the economy could not keep growing at a breakneck
pace without triggering inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? The economists have consistently been wrong. The
United States has been growing at a 4 percent clip since 1996 and
prices have barely moved in response. Maybe it's technology. Maybe
it's just good luck. Whatever the reason, the market's faith in the
future has been justified time and again.
</P>
<P>
   Why assume the traditional gloom and doomers are right now?
</P>
<P>
   The next few months will see whose view of the world prevails.
It is generally agreed that the Fed won't do anything about rates
in December and February because the central bank wants to wait for
more information before acting. By March, however, the Fed may be
ready to move, says Wyss, who thinks the chances for another rate
hike are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is running too hot and the Fed is going to want to
put on some more ice cubes to cool it off,'' he says. And why does
the stock market reject that view? Says Wyss, ``The stock market
doesn't want to pay any attention to bad news.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' public Pension Reserves Investment Management
Board Tuesday selected J.P. Morgan and Legg Mason Inc. to join
Fidelity Investments in managing $1.8 billion earmarked for
large-company stocks. The money directed to Legg Mason will be run
by William Miller. Beth Terrana invests the funds turned over to
Fidelity. An investment team will manage the account at J.P.
Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
