<SLUG> BC-IVOR-HANK-AZARIA-IN-TUESDAYS-WITH-MORRIE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANK AZARIA'S RED-LETTER `TUESDAYS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Hank Azaria
with Jack Lemmon in a scene from ``Tuesdays With Morrie'' and by
himself in a scene from ``Cradle Will Rock.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Fans of ``The Simpsons'' know him by his voices.
 &HT;    Think Moe the Bartender, Police Chief Wiggum, Apu, the boss of
Qwik-E-Mart, Professor Frink and an assortment of others, including
Lou, Dr. Nick, Riviera, Carl Smith and Jail Bird.
 &HT;    For those who aren't fans of ``The Simpsons'' _ and I suppose
there are such people _ the man behind the voices is 35-year-old
Hank Azaria, also known as dogwalker Nat in the recently ended
sitcom ``Mad About You.'' Or perhaps he's best known as the
husband, since last July, of ``Mad About You'' star and
Oscar-winning actress Helen Hunt.
 &HT;    The master of many voices _ ``I watched a lot of TV as a kid,''
he explains, ``and found I could imitate everyone from Bugs Bunny
to Robert De Niro'' _ is no stranger to the movies, either. That
was him in a wig and French maid's outfit as the Guatemalan house
boy in Mike Nichols' ``The Birdcage'' (1996). He also played a
television producer in Robert Redford's ``Quiz Show'' (l994) and
was Gwyneth Paltrow's straitlaced fiance in ``Great Expectations''
(l997).
 &HT;    More recently, he's used his real voice and face as the
cameraman in ``Godzilla'' (l998), and in David E. Kelley's hockey
saga ``Mystery, Alaska'' (1999) as a sportswriter who helps arrange
a hockey match between the New York Rangers and a small Alaskan
town's local team.
 &HT;    In December, Azaria will appear in two very different roles, in
the process considerably upping the profile of this most underrated
performer.
 &HT;    The first is ``Tuesdays With Morrie,'' airing Dec. 5 on ABC,
which the actor calls ``the best work I've done'' _ which, given
his extensive credits, is saying a lot.
 &HT;    Based on Mitch Albom's book of the same name, which has been a
fixture on best-seller lists for almost two years, the telefilm _
an entry in the ``Oprah Winfrey Presents'' series _ casts Jack
Lemmon as Morrie Schwartz, a retired Brandeis University sociology
professor, with Azaria as Detroit sportswriter Albom, one of
Schwartz's former students.
 &HT;    After seeing his old mentor talking with Ted Koppel on
``Nightline'' about his imminent death from ALS, better known as
Lou Gehrig's Disease, the cell-phone-addicted, overprogrammed Albom
flies to Boston for his first meeting in 16 years with his old
friend and teacher.
 &HT;    It is a visit which changes his life, as his professor sets up a
regular Tuesday meeting. It's an extension of their university
tutorials, but this time the subject is life and how to live it.
 &HT;    Albom is a stressed mess, too caught up in his career to be in
touch with his own emotions, too busy to make time for a
relationship, too scared to commit to the woman he loves ... until
he starts listening to Schwartz.
 &HT;    ``Work, money, ambition _ we bury ourselves in these things,''
his terminally ill teacher tells him.
 &HT;    Schwartz instructs Albom to listen to the bird on his shoulder
and ask himself daily, ``Is today the day that I die? Am I ready?
Am I living the life I want to live? Am I being the person I want
to be?''
 &HT;    The moving story, directed by Mick Jackson _ best known for
``The Bodyguard'' (l992) _ has ``Emmy nominations'' written all
over it for both actors. Azaria is every bit as impressive as
Lemmon, for the first time letting the public see the limitless
potential that so many of his co-workers have spoken of for years.
 &HT;    Azaria appears to climb into the skin of Mitch Albom
effortlessly, even though he admits that he isn't at all like
Albom.
 &HT;    ``I'm interested in philosophical and spiritual things,'' he
says, ``while Mitch is not a particularly spiritual guy and did not
willingly go to this kind of place.
 &HT;    ``But Morrie's gift was making this stuff very practical,''
Azaria adds. ``It wasn't like, `Maybe this would be good' or `Try
that.' It was `I'm dying. Here's what's important in life.'
 &HT;    ``Let me tell you, it's very stark and very real, and I think
that's why it moved so many people.''
 &HT;    The film is a duet, and the veteran Lemmon, whom Azaria hugs,
kisses and physically carries around for much of the film, dragged
more out of him than he's ever given, the actor says.
 &HT;    In fact, it sounds as if Lemmon was to Azaria much as Schwartz
was to Albom.
 &HT;    ``I've never been more intimate with another actor,'' Azaria
says. ``I spent the whole time six inches from his face. He's
incredible _ I learned a lot about acting just watching him. And
what he shared with me is all about giving up more and being more
open to what's going to happen to the other actor that day _ taking
a risk.
 &HT;    ``The whole thing was amazing,'' he says. ``It was an incredible
life experience for me.''
 &HT;    Azaria will show up again on Dec. 15 in Tim Robbins' new film,
``Cradle Will Rock,'' as composer Marc Blitzstein, who in 1937
defied government censorship and a court order to perform his
controversial musical, ``The Cradle Will Rock.'' The play was
directed by a 22-year-old wunderkind named Orson Welles (Angus
Macfadyen)
 &HT;    Azaria admits that, when he first read the ``Cradle'' script he
thought it was fiction. Despite an education at New York's American
Academy of Dramatic Arts and at Tufts University in Medford, Mass.,
he'd never heard the story of ``The Cradle Will Rock,'' which went
on to become a Broadway hit.
 &HT;    ``I thought Tim made it up,'' he says. ``I had studied the
history of theater, and this period is not taught _ I never heard
about it. Maybe in New York theater circles it was handed down.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, it's ``Tuesdays With Morrie'' that is most
important to him right now _ not only as a plum role or a chance to
work with the legendary Lemmon, but for the story it tells.
 &HT;    ``It's hard for me to articulate what's so special about this
book,'' Azaria says. ``But I can say that everyone showed up on the
set really wanting to do it justice.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Tuesdays With Morrie,''
consult the official Website at www.abc.go.com/primetime/movies.
And don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
