<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-WALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELFAST WALLS REINFORCE A BITTER DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Geraldine McIlwaine chuckled
ruefully when she watched televised scenes of Germans gathering at
the Brandenburg Gate this month to celebrate the 10th anniversary
of the collapse of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Belfast,'' she said, standing in her doorway, stroking her
8-year-old daughter Katie's hair, ``we want our wall higher.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Irish Republican Army has been willing to discuss
turning in its weapons, no one who lives on Geraldine McIlwaine's
street in West Belfast wants the IRA to give up its guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the IRA decommissions,'' she said, ``we'll be all alone
again.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the progress made on the political front last week,
barriers real and imagined remain in Northern Ireland, especially
on the meanest streets of this old Victorian city.
</P>
<P>
   The most imposing of these barriers are the walls separating
Catholic nationalist and Protestant loyalist neighborhoods, walls
known here euphemistically as peace lines. There are 15 of them
throughout the city, all but one in North and West Belfast, two
neighborhoods where more than one-third of the approximately 3,500
victims of the Troubles have died over the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   With the main paramilitary groups observing cease-fires for most
of the last five years, bloodshed has been dramatically reduced.
Since August 1998, when 29 people were killed by a bomb in Omagh,
the worst single atrocity of the Troubles, only a dozen people have
died in violence linked to the political situation.
</P>
<P>
   But those in poor neighborhoods like the Falls, a Catholic
enclave, and the neighboring Shankill, home to working-class
Protestants, continue to live segregated from each other, their
interaction in many cases limited to the projectiles and verbal
abuse hurled over the walls that separate them.
</P>
<P>
   Since the cease-fires of 1994, not only have none of the peace
lines been torn down, several new ones have gone up.
</P>
<P>
   After the cease-fires were announced, the European Union offered
about $350 million to tear the peace lines down. There were no
takers. If EU leaders in Brussels see the walls as anathema to the
ideal of a Europe without borders, those who live in the toughest
neighborhoods in Belfast see them as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The peace lines are immune to the peace process. To bigots and
drunken teenagers, they are like a red flag. In what has become a
childhood ritual in parts of Belfast, youths routinely gather at
the walls to hurl stones and epithets at unseen enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the older peace lines, like those separating parts of
the Falls from the Shankill in West Belfast, are graffiti-stained
concrete walls topped with army-green corrugated steel. More
recently, the British government has tried to make some peace lines
more aesthetically pleasing. A 10-foot-high wall of brick and
wrought iron built on Duncairn Gardens last year looks nice, but
has done nothing to lessen animosities between the Protestant
loyalists in Tigers Bay and Catholic nationalists in New Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the celebrations in Berlin nor the conciliatory
statements by longstanding enemies in Belfast inspire much hope
here that walls long thought to be permanent could someday come
down. Instead, those who live in the shadows of the peace lines say
life here has not changed much for the better, despite the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Along Bombay Street, a Catholic enclave that was burned down by
loyalist mobs in 1969, residents are demanding that local
authorities raise the fencing that tops the wall, which runs as
high as 30 feet in some areas. Hardly a week goes by that the wall
isn't breached by stones, golf balls, and paint bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never sleep in peace here,'' said Patsy Canavan, 43, who
vividly remembers the night her father and mother led her and her
five brothers and sisters to safety down the burning street 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Canavans moved back a year later, when residents rebuilt
their homes, and have refused to be driven out again. They and
their neighbors endure regular showers of rocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, go on the Protestant side and they'll tell you the same
thing. They don't want the wall down any more than we do,'' Canavan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The children grow up knowing, and living, the history.
Eight-year-old Katie McIlwaine was an infant when a stone came
crashing through the window, showering her bassinet with glass. Her
next-door playmate, Gerard Mullan, fell and seriously damaged his
eye while fleeing golf balls that rained down on his street two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The walls here are daubed with murals that recall the burning of
Bombay Street, along with exhortations that the IRA never disarm.
Catholics on Bombay Street, and Protestants on the opposite side of
the wall, are convinced that they would be overrun and burned out
if the wall came down.
</P>
<P>
   Canavan says her experience has hardened her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never live with them,'' she said of Protestants. ``I
still have friends who are Protestant, but I would never trust
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire Murphy, a Catholic, raised 11 children in a house that
sits hard by the wall. Her backyard is covered by a mesh wire
barrier. Rocks and other objects hurled over the wall are snagged
by the barrier, like nuggets in a prospector's pan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear people go on about the peace process, I say, `What
peace process?' There's no peace for us,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Canavan, the 75-year-old matriarch of the Canavan family,
said the wall will never come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know why?'' she asks. ``Because there's bigots on the
other side of that wall.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also victims on the other side of the wall, like Lily
McCurry. She has lived her whole life on the Protestant side of the
peace line, which could not save her father, Alec Andrews, who was
killed in 1971 when an IRA snuck across and put a bomb in his
local, The Four Steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just having a wee drink with his friends,'' McCurry
recalled, pausing as she swept her driveway in a new housing
development in the Shankill. ``My father was just one of the many
innocents. He survived the battle of Dunkirk, only to die in a pub
up the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Lily McCurry is 60 now. She raised four children on Battenberg
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them got in trouble, please God,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes the walls come down, but doesn't expect to live to see
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked in Mackeys, the factory, with a Catholic girl. She
lived on one side of the peace line, and I was on the other. We got
on well, but at night after work she'd go home to her side and I'd
go home to mine.''
</P>
<P>
   She says that while the drop in paramilitary violence is an
improvement, the segregation that helps breed prejudice on both
sides remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think that the new generation would see to it that
these walls come down, but the young people have a lot of hatred in
them.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry looked at the wall and sighed wistfully, recalling the
early 1960s when she was young and there were no walls and she
thought Belfast was the best wee place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what those walls are,'' she said, sweeping again, this
time harder. ``Monuments to hate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
