<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MAYORALTY RACE IS TAKING ON THE LOOK OF `ROCKY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- When a candidate persuades 48,000 voters to
write in his name, spending only $20,000 against richer rivals, he
evokes the chap who slew a Philistine giant in the Old Testament's
Book of Samuel. But in this city, far from the Bible Belt, the tale
of David and Goliath is a less apt metaphor for the Dec. 14 mayoral
election between Tom Ammiano and Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   A stronger parallel in drama and ideology is ``Rocky,'' a
low-budget film from 1976 in which Sylvester Stallone played the
title role, a boxer offered a fluke chance to battle the
heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky was from Philadelphia. Ammiano is from New Jersey. In the
movie and in this city, Rocky's foe is a citizen of the world, at
ease among bright lights, high fashion, and self-confidence. Mayor
Brown resembles the character played by Carl Weathers, Apollo
Creed, an accomplished, elegant and genial braggart who laughingly
condescends to his opponent until a handler hears that Rocky is a
southpaw.
</P>
<P>
   Hey champ, we don't want you fightin' no lefty, says the worried
trainer, echoing current concerns in the Brown entourage. Ammiano,
58, is chairman of the board of supervisors, the equivalent of city
council president. He champions a living wage of $11 per hour and
has in the past urged a tax on stock transfers, plus an income tax
on salaries of more than $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   The city Republican committee has endorsed Brown, 65, stunning
many California Republicans, bedeviled by Brown in his 15 years as
Assembly speaker and unable to imagine any room to the left of
their nemesis. Brown had expected a rematch against Frank Jordan, a
former mayor and police chief, considered a conservative. But in
the Nov. 2 preliminary election, Ammiano's write-in campaign won 25
percent, ahead of Jordan's 17 and behind Brown's 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is the first black elected mayor here. If elected, Ammiano
would be the first gay mayor. But race and sexual orientation
matter less than ideology, which defines and envelopes San
Francisco more powerfully than any metropolis west of Havana.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco voters favor socialist politics and capitalist
aesthetics. Residents of this urbane city react to change like
skittish suburbanites. They may growl at or weep for the homeless,
but build a shelter for panhandlers? Not in my neighborhood. Rents
are rising rapidly, so how about building more housing? Not in my
neighborhood. In the annals of NIMBYism, the liberal lamb is as
ferocious as the conservative lion in defending the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   In Sacramento, Brown filed a gay rights bill every year from
1969 until it became law in 1975. But in this city, the question
politicians hear is ``What have you done for me lately?''
</P>
<P>
   San Franciscans value humility and insist on it. Although the
charter limits mayors to two terms, the voters rejected the last
two incumbents after one term. At a Monday night debate, Brown
conceded mistakes ``of style rather than substance.'' Ammiano
accused Brown of ``sweetheart deals'' and ``letting developers into
the driver's seat.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenger scored points by saying, ``I take the Muni every
day,'' referring to the city's burdened transit system. The mayor,
who rides in limousines, said he was ``responsive and accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Nov. 2 preliminary election, Brown was first in 19 of the
city's 25 neighborhoods and second in six. Ammiano was first in
six, but third or fourth in 11 other areas. Ammiano ran poorly in
the western part of the city among the Chinese-, Irish-, and
Italian-Americans who voted against Brown in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   John V. Lindsay, elected mayor of New York as a conservative in
1965, returned to office as a liberal in 1969. Winning reelection
with a new constituency is a heroic feat, but Brown is confident,
while wary of Ammiano. The mayor, a major movie buff, remembers
that in 1977 ``Rocky'' won the Oscar for best picture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
