<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0206 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV26-H     11-24 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Friday, Nov. 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's working for Arizona Sen. John McCain. Why not
for New Jersey former Sen. Bill Bradley? Why not, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about campaign finance reform. For openers, it's
an issue voters have never cared a lot about. And it's been around
so long that it is encumbered by a monster sense of futility. All
words and no action.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has actually been trying in the Senate to do something
about it, not only sponsoring a sensible bipartisan bill but
fighting hard for several years to get it past the opposition of
the Republican congressional leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The sincerity of his crusade is taken so seriously it has put
him on the national map as the only viable alternative to Texas
Gov. George W. Bush for the GOP presidential nomination. Prospects
for a successful McCain candidacy, in fact, are brighter than the
prospects for passage of his cherished campaign finance changes,
which have repeatedly been blocked in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley has no similar credentials as a leader of campaign
finance reform. When he attacked Vice President Al Gore the other
day as a symbol of a corrupt, money-driven political system, he
raised a subject that he has never given a high priority to. In
July, he spelled out proposals to change the money chase, including
endorsing the politically unrealistic notion of public funding for
congressional races. Since then, however, he has mostly talked
about other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has returned to campaign finance reform now because he
seems to be losing the early momentum that had made him an
unexpectedly strong contender for the Democratic presidential
nomination. He is trying to draw a contrast between his own
supposedly superior status as a Washington outsider and Gore's
well-known history of dogged fund-raising among the rich and
famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to put an end to big money in politics,'' Bradley said
piously. ``Politicians believe you don't really care about this
issue. They don't respect you enough to even hide their actions or
pretend.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current campaign, Bradley had raised more than $19
million for his presidential bid by Sept. 30, and he flies around
on corporate planes, for which he makes no public financial
accounting.
</P>
<P>
   By raising the issue, he hopes to remind voters of the
Democratic scandals of the last presidential campaign, which were
exploited by Republican congressional probes that focused on White
House fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's extensive dialing for dollars was widely criticized, but
unproved GOP charges of illegal activity were rebuffed by Attorney
General Janet Reno, who refused to name a special counsel to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore may not be as vulnerable in this area as Bradley
thinks. Voters in New Hampshire, the first primary state, are
notoriously reform-minded, which accounts in part for McCain's
strong showing in polls there. But the rest of the country is
ambivalent. Campaign finance abuses do not rank high on the
national scale of voter concerns. The public attitude is: Everybody
does it; so what?
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Gore and the Clinton administration are solidly on
record as supporting McCain's bill, which would limit legal
contributions in ``soft money'' technically given to a political
party rather than an individual candidate, and several other
campaign finance changes. They have not, however, spent much time
doing anything about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast, opposes McCain's crusade and essentially
favors the status quo, which has served him well. He had raised
more than $58 million for his campaign as of his Sept.30 filing
with the Federal Election Commission, more than twice as much as
Gore's $27 million. Bush is awash in so much money he is refusing
to take federal matching funds, which would mean limiting the
amount he could legally spend in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans benefit the most from the open-ended ``soft money''
contribution system and have been at the core of resistance to
reform, although they have had some Democratic help. As president,
Bush's father vetoed campaign reform in 1992,and congressional
Republicans have blocked it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   On this issue, it is easy for McCain to draw the contrast
between himself and Bush.They are both incumbent office-holders,
but McCain wants to shake things up and Bush wants to stand pat.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley cannot make a similar contrast between himself and Gore,
beyond the obvious fact that Gore still holds elective office and
he does not. When Bradley retired from the Senate in 1996, he
complained that the system was ``broken'' but he did not stay
around to try to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democrats are for reform, although Bradley's support for
public financing of congressional elections goes where most
politicians dare not tread. Asking taxpayers to subsidize the
campaigns of a bunch of people they don't think much of anyway has
never been a popular idea. It won't do much for Bradley either.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
