<SLUG> BC-CALIF-MAYOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMIC TRANSFORMS THE MAYOR'S RACE IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The primary election results surprised everyone,
especially the last-minute, write-in candidate and his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mood in the cabaret-turned-campaign headquarters is
ebullient if unpolished. Volunteers walk in off the street and slap
on homemade ``I AM A TOMBOY'' pins. The worker behind the reception
desk signed on four hours ago. Cardboard boxes double as filing
cabinets, and messages are scrawled on sheets of paper taped to the
wall. The hand-drawn thermometer with the number of registered
voters represented in red is lopsided.
</P>
<P>
   But the underground feel isn't fooling anyone this time around.
Tom Ammiano _ gay stand-up comedian, anti-establishment activist
and president of the Board of Supervisors _ could best Mayor Willie
Brown in the Dec. 14 runoff. Although polls still show Brown in the
lead, a large portion of the electorate remains undecided, with
less than a month to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``All bets are off,'' said Richard DeLeon, chairman of the
political science department at San Francisco State University.
``Mayor Brown still has the edge, but we've already been
flabbergasted once. The passion pouring into the Ammiano campaign
can offset a lot of advantages that come with being the incumbent.
He could pull it out.''
</P>
<P>
   That prospect has turned a city known for its left-of-center
political traditions topsy turvy. While San Francisco has come to
define liberalism in the national psyche, the term has become
relative in a race that pits an established big-city black mayor
against a candidate who prides himself on radical rhetoric. With
numerous overlapping constituencies, the matchup is forcing
longtime friends, as well as enemies, to choose sides.
</P>
<P>
   As Ken Garcia, a columnist with the San Francisco Chronicle, put
it: ``The politics in this city have gone off the axis. Which side
is up is the question. The town is nuts now.''
</P>
<P>
   The fault lines are most evident in the gay and lesbian
community, although they are also noticeable in minority
communities. Jesse Jackson went so far as to urge Ammiano not to
run against Brown. While many of the city's gay power brokers have
stuck with Brown, recent polls show Ammiano leading among
homosexual voters. It's a discrepancy that some view as a setback;
others as a sign of progress.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano supporters say he has rallied gays and lesbians, an
established political force in San Francisco, to turn their
attention to the same issues that concern everyone else, such as
crime and getting the buses to run on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supporting gays is just one part of being mayor of San
Francisco,'' said John Burket, a florist who is volunteering for
Ammiano. ``It's political suicide for any politician not to do
that. But there are other things that matter, like making this a
city people can live in again and caring about people who have
less.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Brown, a longtime advocate of gay rights, counter
that coalitions cannot be built if friends are so easily abandoned.
Beyond appreciating what he has done for the city, they say they
owe him for what he has done for them over the years, from
repealing anti-sodomy laws as a state legislator to pushing for
domestic partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't send the right message to other communities, that
you can support us and then we'll run a candidate against you,''
said Robert Barnes, a local political consultant and gay activist
who backs Brown. ``You don't reward someone who has been on your
side by defeating them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some unexpected groups have sided with Brown.
Against Ammiano, he suddenly finds himself the conservatives'
candidate. The county Republican Central Commission recently
gritted its teeth and endorsed the longtime advocate of organized
labor and affirmative action. The Chinese-American community is
with him. Not surprisingly, given Ammiano's desire to tax high
incomes and stock transactions, business groups are also mobilizing
behind Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say businesses are going to leave town if
Ammiano wins, but some businesses might rethink their investments
in the city,'' said Mark Mosher, executive director of the
Committee on Jobs, an organization of 35 San Francisco-based
employers. ``His record is astoundingly antibusiness. Mayor Brown
believes in social spending, but he believes the way to pay for it
is economic growth.''ill, as political observers noted, Ammiano has undeniably
invigorated younger voters, as well the middle and lower classes
who increasingly find themselves unable to afford San Francisco's
overheated housing market. His campaign is intent on registering as
many homeless people to vote as possible. Tenants-rights
organizations are pitching in.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that Brown has brought fiscal health to San
Francisco since he was swept into office in 1996. During his first
term, the booming economy helped quell many of the political
rivalries now surfacing.
</P>
<P>
   Then Amminano's write-in campaign, launched just three weeks
before the Nov. 4 primary and costing less than $25,000, tapped
into an unsuspected level of discontent with city services and
discord over the city's vision of itself. In a four-way race, he
took 25 percent of the vote. His base of support also helped pass
ballot measures to provide greater access to public meetings and
ban fees banks charge noncustomers for using their ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we got in the race, it just really took off,'' said
Ammianno, a former schoolteacher who hopes to raise $250,000 for
the race, against Brown's millions. ``It's clear we really hit a
nerve.''
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks, the candidates will engage in a series of
debates to differentiate their styles of leadership and outline
their plans for redistributing the prosperity. For now, though, the
candidates appear to be busy one-upping each other's liberal
credentials, even as Brown paints himself as the more moderate,
practical one in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to co-opt one of Ammiano's centerpiece campaign issues,
Brown recently indicated that he would support a more extensive
living-wage law, even as he stressed the importance of job growth.
Campaign spokesman P.J. Johnston, however, said Brown does not care
who he is running against, because the message remains the same.
``The person who champions domestic partnerships, same-sex
marriages, and a living wage but is also fiscally responsible so we
can pay for everything we do is the candidate for the city,''
Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, whose last-minute campaign enabled him to avoid
significant public scrutiny or debates, attacked the mayor as a
backroom wheeler and dealer who has raised millions of dollars and
has little interest in campaign-finance reform or the plight of the
minimum-wage worker. One of Ammiano's goals is to weaken the
mayor's office, perhaps in part because Brown helped prevent
passage of most of the legislation Ammiano has championed as a
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My San Francisco is about a shift in the balance of power,
from city hall back to the neighborhoods,'' he said. ``It's about
not being so cavalier about granting carte blanche to the chain
stores, about retarding gentrification, about stopping the erosion
of neighborhood characters. Hopefully we won't be such a cash cow
for the big bucks lobbyist.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano insists that his administration would not be
antibusiness, that both corporate needs and the needs of the less
fortunate can be met simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   But on the streets of San Francisco, the divisions are expected
to widen in the coming weeks. Few feel comfortable making
predictions anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Ammiano came in, he rode a tidal wave,'' said veteran
pollster David Binder. ``It became a cause, the in thing, to go
write in his name. The odds are against him now, but he could win.
It's about how political figures who have been viewed as liberal
their whole life make others think about them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
