<HEADER>
A0216 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-POLL-GAP-BOS &LR;      11-24 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-GAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME MAY ERODE LARGER GAPS SEEN IN NATIONAL POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In New Hampshire, both the Democratic and
Republican presidential races seem too close to call. But
nationally, the race at this point seems like a blowout, with Vice
President Al Gore and Governor George W. Bush of Texas easily
leading their respective contests.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Campaign 2000 is a race that needs two scorecards. But
which one is right?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that both are accurate in their own way, which is
why the Democratic and Republican front-runners _ while smoothly
sailing on national waters _ are pouring huge resources into New
Hampshire and the first-caucus state of Iowa to prevent a possible
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason it is so close in New Hampshire is not that New
Hampshire voters are so different, but that they have been exposed
to the candidates more,'' said Tami Buhr, who has worked on a New
Hampshire poll for Dartmouth College and a national survey
associated with Harvard University. ``If (all) voters are given
that opportunity, we might see something similar nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while the polls make it seem that Bush and Gore are
far ahead nationally, an unusual new survey has found that the vast
majority of people are undecided. The Vanishing Voter Project at
Harvard's Kennedy School of Government recently asked voters to
name their favorite candidate, but, unlike typical surveys, the
poll did not supply any names.
</P>
<P>
   The result: 64 percent said they did not support any candidate,
16 percent named Bush, 6 percent said Gore, 5 percent said Bill
Bradley, and 2 percent said John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most preelection polls give a false impression that voters are
strongly supporting a candidate by reading a long list of names and
encouraging respondents to make a choice that they often have not
made,'' Buhr said.
</P>
<P>
   With such a large undecided base of voters, the underdogs are
counting on a strong showing in Iowa and New Hampshire in hope that
national support will follow. If the national front-runners slip up
in New Hampshire, the complexion of the campaign could change
overnight across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Republican race as it looks under the usual polling
method, in which candidates' names are supplied. Nationally, Bush
leads with 59 percent, followed by McCain with 13 percent and Steve
Forbes with 5 percent, according to a recent Los Angeles Times
poll. But in New Hampshire, a variety of polls show a close contest
between Bush and McCain, prompting a huge dose of media attention
to McCain, the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   A similar scene is unfolding between Gore and Bradley. Gore
leads Bradley by 20 points in national polls, but the two are even
in most New Hampshire surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Gore knows well the importance of New Hampshire. In 1988, he
paid little attention to New Hampshire during his first
presidential campaign, thinking he could make up for a defeat by
sweeping the South. But after Gore lost in New Hampshire, winner
Michael Dukakis capitalized on his victory by winning the large
electoral states of Texas and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Gore said in a recent interview, he is taking nothing
for granted in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write this down,'' Gore said. ``I'm running in New Hampshire.
I'm not picking out some contingency path. I'm giving everything
I've got in New Hampshire. I'm competing with everything I possibly
can in New Hampshire. I'm spending more time there than anywhere
else, devoting more people there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser said the former New Jersey senator
is doing well in New Hampshire but trails in the national polls
because ``this is where we have campaigned and are getting better
known.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president is better known (nationally), and he has
been vice president for seven years,'' Hauser said. But as
Bradley's national campaigning increases, his national poll numbers
will pick up, Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   The first-caucus state of Iowa is also the focus of intense
campaigning, but so far the races there are not as competitive,
especially with McCain not actively participating on the GOP side.
</P>
<P>
   For years, New Hampshire has had a reputation of being out of
synch with the country because it is a mostly white, conservative
state. While the once-rural state is still overwhelmingly white,
its diversified economy and bugeoning suburbs have made it more
like the rest of the country in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire voters do have more contact with candidates than
people elsewhere. Six percent of people nationwide have some direct
contact with a candidate, compared to 20 percent in New Hampshire,
according to Dartmouth government professor Dean Spiliotes. But he
said the importance of personal exposure to the candidates has been
exaggerated, because most New Hampshirites, like most voters
elsewhere, get their information through the media.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshirites are exposed to far more political advertising
and news coverage than people in most other states.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Bush emerged as the front-runner, not because
he was ahead in a particular state, but because he became the top
choice of Republican Party leaders. That, in turn, led to massive
news coverage of him, which helped boost his fund-raising and his
standing as the front-runner. That, in turn, prompted several
candidates _ such as Lamar Alexander, Dan Quayle and Elizabeth Dole
_ to drop out before a single vote was cast.
</P>
<P>
   But New Hampshire voters, who are accustomed to scrutinizing the
candidates, essentially said: Not so fast. In response, Bush
recently has stepped up his appearances in the state and has agreed
to participate in his first debate, a Dec. 2 forum in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Bush well remembers that his father was weakened nationally in
the 1992 contest when conservative commentator Patrick J. Buchanan
came in a surprisingly strong second in New Hampshire. Similarly,
Bob Dole in 1996 was wounded politically when Buchanan won the New
Hampshire primary. While Bush and Dole both went on to win the GOP
nomination, their difficulties in New Hampshire played a role in
their eventual defeats in the general election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
