<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING ON LINE FOR OFF-THE-RACK FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friday, the busiest shopping day of the year, are you going to
be: a) stalled in traffic and waiting in lines at a mall, or b)
liberated as you shop on line at home in your pajamas? This holiday
season, 24 percent of Internet users plan to buy clothing on line,
up from 15 percent last year, according to a survey by the NPD
Group Inc., a marketing information company. And no wonder.
Cybershopping has never been better. Department stores, catalogs,
chain stores, boutiques, and discount malls are all on line. We've
put together a random sampling of sites, many claiming to be ``the
biggest'' or ``the best.'' We haven't ordered from them, so we
can't vouch for service, quality, or delivery. Here is a list of
the sites we cruised:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nordstromshoes.com
</P>
<P>
   Claim to fame: Calls itself ``the world's biggest shoe store.''
</P>
<P>
   Pairs of shoes: 20 million _ for men, women, and children.
(They're not all in stock, of course, but can be ordered quickly,
directly from manufacturers.)
</P>
<P>
   Prices: $30 to about $300.
</P>
<P>
   Styles: Includes loafers, oxfords, sneakers, sandals, slippers,
wingtips, boots, pumps, flats, and Mary Janes.
</P>
<P>
   Designer names: 30, including Kenneth Cole, Cole-Haan, Johnston
&AMP; Murphy, BCBG Max Azria, Stuart Weitzman, and Via Spiga.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Displays top recommendations for every shoe
category, just as a salesperson would; the search mechanism allows
users to narrow their search by typing in categories such as
business, casual, nightclubbing, comfort, or special occasion. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sephora.com
</P>
<P>
   The hook: Says it's ``the world's largest fragrance and
cosmetics retailer'' (also sells skin-care and bath products).
</P>
<P>
   The numbers: 365 shades of lipstick, 183 shades of nail polish,
and more than 140 shades of eye pencil.
</P>
<P>
   The smells: 93 fragrance brands for men and women, including
such brands as Dolce &AMP; Gabbana and Gucci;. 65 bath and skin-care
brands, like Ellen Lange and DDF EPF.
</P>
<P>
   The names: 19 cosmetic brands including Bourjois and Anna Sui.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: 50 cents to $150.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: A monthly magazine called Beauty Cyber-Space
spotlights new trends, hot looks, and products its editors
recommend. An interactive celebrity makeup lesson allows readers to
click on a celebrity's eyes, for example, and receive information
on the products the star used and how she created the look. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bluefly.com
</P>
<P>
   What: A discount outlet site offering designer apparel for men,
women, and children, as well as home accessories and gifts from
about 250 designers.
</P>
<P>
   Discounts: Says it offers 25 percent to 75 percent off retail
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Designer names: Includes Calvin Klein, Donna Karan, Gucci, and
Prada.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: $10 to $700.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel: Includes blazers, shirts, dresses, and bathing suits.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Allows users to create a personalized catalog. You
select your favorite brands, apparel categories, and sizes; the
site will display photos of all such items available every time you
log on. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Allejewelry.com
</P>
<P>
   What: An on-line jewelry store for men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry available: More than 3,000 pieces, including gold,
diamonds, rubies, platinum, pearls, and watches.
</P>
<P>
   How you shop: Choose a category such as bracelets, earrings,
necklaces, or engagement rings; pictures appear that users can
enlarge.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: $29 to $10,000
</P>
<P>
   Authenticity: Any item that costs more than $1,000 comes with an
appraisal that is independent of allejewelry.com and the
manufacturer. Jewelry under $1,000 comes with a certificate of
authenticity; all have a 30-day money-back guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: A gemologist is available to answer questions by
phone. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boo.com
</P>
<P>
   Niche: Sportswear, footwear, and accessory retailer with brands
from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Designers: About 20 brands, including Acupuncture of Britain,
Royal Elastics of Australia, Final Home of Japan, as well as the
US-based FUBU and DKNY.
</P>
<P>
   How you shop: Users can shop by designer name; there are
microsites displaying what's available in each brand. Users can
also type in apparel category or activity (such as jogging) and a
list of available options appears.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: $10 to $350.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping companion: Miss Boo, a virtual character who helps
users through the site and explains what they're looking at.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: A virtual dressing room where users can place
selected items on a mannequin that spins, mixing and matching
apparel any way they want; Boom magazine, a monthly with stories on
culture, style, and sports. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sydandsam.com
</P>
<P>
   What: Calls itself the ``first on-line retailer to feature
brand-name apparel in special sizes.'' The site also sells
footwear.
</P>
<P>
   The sizes: Plus (12 and up); plus plus (26W and up and 4X to
9X); junior plus (12 and up); petite (2P to 14P); petite plus (12
and up); tall (10T to 20T). Footwear is 10 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Audience: Women and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Brand names: 50, including Eileen Fisher, Gianni, and Josephine
Chaus Woman.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel: Casual, career, evening, and outerwear.
</P>
<P>
   Price range: $25 to $300.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Allows users to create a customized catalog where
the site will display all preferred brands, styles, and sizes in
stock, every time the user logs on. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alloy.com
</P>
<P>
   Niche: Apparel and entertainment site geared toward teenage boys
and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Brand names: Includes Roxy, O'Neill, Rusty, Billabong, Fresh
Jive, and Vans.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: $8 to $175.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel: Includes sweaters, jeans, pants, T-shirts, and sweat
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   How you shop: Users type in what they're looking for (such as
girls' apparel or accessories) and a list appears (for example,
tops and tanks, pants, or hats and bags). Users select a category,
and a listing and pictures appear of the products available. Users
can also type in a product number from the Alloy catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Alloy.com is like a magazine. There are four daily
advice columns about girls, boys, sex, and fashion. There is daily
celebrity news, music industry news, TV show updates, horoscopes,
movie clips and reviews, a chat room, and weekly poetry
competitions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guyshop.com and Girlshop.com
</P>
<P>
   Audience: Fashion addicts in their 20s and 30s.
</P>
<P>
   The goods: Boutique-style fashions from about 40 up-and-coming
designers. Some items have been featured in magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Style: Trendy dresses, suits, jackets, and other apparel as well
as accessories like pony-skin handbags and diamond toe rings.
Clothing ranges from casual to dressy.
</P>
<P>
   How you shop: Each designer has a boutique; choose a designer
and then browse the selections.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: $20 to $650.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: A gift registry you can e-mail to friends and
family. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Designeroutlet.com
</P>
<P>
   What: Discount brand-name clothing and accessories for men,
women, and children.
</P>
<P>
   Brand names: 300 manufacturers, designers, and retailers,
including Ralph Lauren, French Connection, and Ocean Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Items: Includes coats, accessories, and dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Discounts available: 35 percent to 75 percent off retail, the
site says.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: $5 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Users can e-mail questions to a personal shopper,
such as what they should wear to an event. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DoughNET.com
</P>
<P>
   What: A money-management Web site for teenagers. Teens set up
spending and savings accounts with a participating bank to purchase
clothing and other goods on the site. Kids can buy products using
money only from these accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The point: To teach kids to be financially savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers: 59 on-line merchants, including JCrew.com,
Esprit.com, Levi.com, and Delias.com.
</P>
<P>
   Prices: $10 to $300.
</P>
<P>
   How it works: Teens need parental permission to sign up. Parents
are e-mailed a form to fill out and can then place money in their
child's new accounts or grant use of a credit card. Teens are
encouraged to send in their own money.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Teens can donate money to six nonprofits associated
with the site.
</P>
</TEXT>
