<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. FUSSY   HIDES FROM THE TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanksgiving, Mr. Fussy mused. Is that the one with the turkey,
or the one with the goose?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, he knew it was one of The Big Three, along with
Christmas and New Year's Eve. These events loom at the end of the
calendar like Everest, K-2, and Annapurna, insuperable obstacles
separating mankind from the Promised Land of normal life. You're
living normally when you don't have to act thankful to be eating
dry turkey and frozen peas, or pretend that anyone could possibly
want those horrid, sticky gloves that Dan Marino models on TV, or
blubber hopelessly about auld lang syne.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Three aren't regular, pleasant holidays, like Columbus
Day or Labor Day, when you can switch off the answering machine and
watch television for 72 hours. Mr. Fussy once spent an entire Labor
Day weekend at home, drinking beer and watching videos of Krzysztof
Kieslowski's indecipherable movie trilogy ``Red,'' ``White,'' and
``Blue'' over and over. When people asked, he said he had spent the
weekend sailing. It was bliss.
</P>
<P>
   That couldn't happen now. There are no ``optional'' activities
on the Thanksgiving-New Year's Trail of Tears. Christmas concerts,
office parties, relatives phoning across time zones to wake you up
with unwanted cheer. For years, Mr. Fussy dreamed of hiding at a
homeless shelter during Thanksgiving, doling out food to the less
fortunate as a family-avoidance stratagem. Then he read a newspaper
article saying the shelters would prefer that people not come on
Thanksgiving or Christmas, but some other day of the year. Yeton
the other days of the year, there's no reason to hide . . .
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving was like a kidney stone; it would pass. But then
comes Christmas. Mr. Fussy once tried to sell a book called ``Is
Christmas Necessary?'' There were no takers, which should have
showed him just how out of step he was with modern civilization.
Christmas, of course, is necessary, even if its only apparent
reason for being is to drive Mr. Fussy bonkers.
</P>
<P>
   The great David Owen _ not the British diplomat who looks like
Dirk Bogarde, the New Yorker writer _ once floated the idea of a
``golfastery,'' a quiet place to which fanatics could repair and
golf all day long. Mr. Fussy wondered: How about a
``Christmastery''? It could be located in a large self-storage
facility outside of Lowell, where all the interstates meet. Or if
more space is needed, just take a large, uninhabited part of the
country, such as Death Valley, and hand it over to the revelers. A
special church-government council would surround the area with
those awful year-round Christmas shops, liberating the rest of the
country from their yoke.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, gifts. It's true that men and women in Mr. Fussy's
demographic wanted less and less _ they had acquired pretty much
everything there was to acquire during the decade-long stock market
binge _ so there was more pressure than ever to find just the right
gift. Mrs. Fussy would probably settle for something small, like a
Faberge Easter egg. The older Fussy children would be easy; they
told Santa they wanted Cisco Systems Class A warrants redeemable in
case of a ``special event.'' The youngest Fussy presented no
problem. A $10,000 gift certificate to buy Pokemon would suffice.
Whatever happened to fire trucks?
</P>
<P>
   And for himself? A few weeks ago, Mr. Fussy made a list: pants
clips for bicycling, those lovely brass book darts that cling to
the side of the page and mark a passage, opera glasses for his
failing eyesight, silk undersocks _ an absolute necessity for the
winter. More dental floss, of course. But then Mr. Fussy realized
that this list made him seem like a bit of a fuddy-duddy. So when
he finds a necktie, or the latest Grisham under the tree, he will
manage a smile and a half-sincere thank you.
</P>
<P>
   What does Mr. Fussy really want? Mr. Fussy really just wants it
all to be over.
</P>
<P>
   (With gratitude and apologies to the late Roger Hargreaves,
creator of the wonderful children's book character Mr. Fussy.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
