<HEADER>
A0230 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-AHAB-BOS &LR;      11-24 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AHAB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEMINIST HEROINE WITH A WHALE OF A TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
AHAB'S WIFE 
By Sena Jeter Naslund 
Morrow, 668 pp., illustrated, $28 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't let the precedent fool you: Like ``Moby-Dick,'' Sena Jeter
Naslund's ``Ahab's Wife'' is a whale of a book, 668 pages of grand
sea-centered adventure. Like ``Moby-Dick,'' it plays on the mores
of the period and questions the nature of God, love, and justice.
But unlike Melville's 1851 classic, Naslund's first novel is a
grand romance, designed more for wintry firesides than for
literature classes.
</P>
<P>
   The romance of ``Ahab's Wife'' is not only of the simplistic
modern definition, though in Naslund's hands the mad captain of the
title is merely intense, at first, and dashing in a tall, scarred,
and handsome way. But the men in this book _ and the title
character, Una Spenser, ends up with three husbands by the time
this involving adventure winds to a close _ are secondary. This is
Una's story, and in her the author has created a distinctly
Romantic heroine, a character for whom emotion and humanism reign
over scriptural morality. ``Moby-Dick'' set Captain Ahab against a
white whale, a creature of overwhelming strength and seeming
malevolence, in a struggle that, in most interpretations, pitted
the captain against divine will. Una's conflicts are more varied,
her enemies usually some manifestation of social custom, but her
battles are often as dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   That the two books run along parallel courses highlights their
differences: Where Ahab's hubris was punished, Una's is celebrated.
Ahab's 19th-century Nantucket still teeters on the edge of
Puritanism; his ``savage'' Native American and South Pacific
sailors alert readers that their captain puts himself outside
society's code. In Una's world it is the young white men who come
to replace a lighthouse lens (and the young woman who accompanies
them to sea) who turn cannibal.
</P>
<P>
   On land, Una's world often seems too good to be true. Like some
seaside Lake Wobegon, her Nantucket is populated by supremely
intelligent and liberal individuals, literate free-thinkers who
embrace all forms of tolerance. Una may only have a passing
interaction with ``Mr. Hawthorne'' and ``Mr. Emerson,'' but she
lives in the world of literature and philosophy, and corresponds
regularly with the feminist writer Margaret Fuller. If all her
neighbors are not so well-read, they are at least pragmatically
liberated: When Ahab goes to sea, a nearby widow casually offers
her ``an array of porcelain devices'' to relieve sexual tension.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, these people (and these devices) existed, but Naslund
brings them together in a feminist utopia that doesn't always ring
true. What discrimination there is, such as the brutal intolerance
of Una's father, is long over when the story opens. Or it is once
removed _ in the slavery that the runaway Susan describes and which
Una's cousin fights as an abolitionist.
</P>
<P>
   Such forced enlightenment is a bit off-putting, and on land
Naslund's rich, descriptive prose can become overripe, as when her
benevolent uncle attempts to teach her about seashells: ``As I
touched their whorls and knobs and spines and admired their spots
and shadings of brown, pink, purple, he described to me what oceans
the shells had lived in, distant places, and what the people wore
and ate.''
</P>
<P>
   But civilization and its contentments fade away _ much as they
do in Melville's original _ whenever Una leaves home. Una's desire
for adventure brings her through some tough times. As the book
opens, for example, she is about to give birth alone in a freezing
cabin in the woods. And when she runs away to sea, she discovers
nothing is unthinkable. Rapes occur between friends; the civilized
turn cannibal. Even the business of the ship _ hunting whales _
takes on a decidedly contemporary but believable tone of horror
when the boat kills a mother whale and Una sees its orphaned calf
slip away, lost and scared. For Una, whaling conjures up a vision
of hell: ``Oil poured in fountains and . . . dripped all over the
deck. . . . We were all so covered in grease and blood and dirt
that I recognized men only by their voices.''
</P>
<P>
   Freed from the prim proprieties of land, however, Naslund's lush
language blossoms. In short passages, interspersed with various
character's monologues, the religious echoes of Melville's book
come back loud and clear. Simple humanity becomes a sacrament, as
one character tries for justice in the face of starvation. ``This
is the last biscuit,'' he says to the hungry inhabitants of a
lifeboat. ``I divide it equally among us, regardless of our size or
condition.'' Horror becomes poetry: ``My lips are at the veins. Not
his, her, your, their veins. Just the veins.''
</P>
<P>
   In such a world, freed from even the most supportive society,
Una's spirit is tried. Unlike her colleagues, or her noteworthy
predecessor, she survives. `` `I will never give up my arrogance,'
I said. `I want to live.' '' The moral may be contemporary, perhaps
even inappropriate for the setting, but the spirit is timeless _
and a great companion for the reader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
