<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0233 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      11-24 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALE OF A SIREN SONG; A LOOK AT ANDY KAUFMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vanity Fair for December offers a juicy story begging to be
turned into a movie. Called ``The Miranda Obsession,'' it
investigates the tale of the phone phony that has been in the
Hollywood rumor mill for years. Apparently, in the 1980s, a
Louisiana woman named Whitney Walton used only the telephone, her
most seductive voice, and the name Miranda Grosvenor to ingratiate
herself to a host of male entertainment hotshots, including Billy
Joel, Buck Henry, Art Garfunkel, Paul Schrader, Quincy Jones,
Richard Perry, Eric Clapton, Sting, and Robert De Niro. Indeed, a
number of these men became quite smitten with the mysterious lady,
without ever seeing her in the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda had the numbers of these famous men, both literally and
psychologically. Saying she was a gorgeous blond model and the
daughter of a wealthy New Yorker, she would hook them into
conversation with ego-massaging comments and insider information
that she had learned from her other dupes. They weren't sex calls,
exactly, just flirtatious chats in which she offered support, safe
companionship, and gossip. Billy Joel, who tells VF, ``A lot of
nights she was my only friend,'' would try out new songs on her
answering machine. Generally, when one of the men insisted on
meeting Miranda in person, she would put on the dodge, making dates
and then not showing up.
</P>
<P>
   In VF, record producer Richard Perry talks at length about his
obsession with her, after she reached him at home in 1982. For
Perry, she called herself Ariana, and after a while they began
talking three and four times a day. He would schedule his life
around her calls, and in the evening he would eat dinner with her
on the speakerphone. She made excuses about meeting him in person,
but she sent him a magazine photo and claimed she was the pretty
model in it. Meanwhile, Perry shared his story with a few friends,
one of whom, Buck Henry, had already had a phone relationship with
her and had found out she was a fraud. A shaken Perry confronted
her with Henry's information, but when she finally admitted her
game, he only fell further in love with her. Or at least, until he
finally met her at the Park Lane hotel in New York. A short, frumpy
woman about 30 pounds overweight, Walton told him she loved him,
and Perry recoiled. He felt angry that she had lied so thoroughly
about her appearance, saying to her, ``I can't really trust you
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanity Fair reporter Bryan Burrough tracks Walton down in Baton
Rouge, but the social worker quickly denies any knowledge of
Miranda Grosvenor. Her former co-workers, however, do recall
Walton's heady ride as caller to the stars, and they remember
Walton playing them phone messages from Peter Wolf, Henry,
Garfunkel, and others. What Burrough doesn't get into is the nature
of the mindset of these men, who were able to project their
fantasies all over this lone, mysterious voice. Also, what kind of
fame-aholism or neediness drove Miranda to pursue them so
wholeheartedly? Surely it won't be long before Miranda is the
subject of an ``E! True Hollywood Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in VF, the 1999 Hall of Fame pictures include a
classic Annie Leibovitz foldout shot of the cast of ``The
Sopranos'' having the last supper. This one's a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've never quite understood why the late comedian Andy
Kaufman has been hailed as a comic genius, you might want to check
out Rolling Stone for Dec. 9. The story, by Bill Zehme, gives a
good sense of why Kaufman has become so legendary, as well as the
subject of Jim Carrey's forthcoming ``Man on the Moon,'' which is
named after R.E.M.'s tribute song. In an uncommonly committed,
gonzo fashion, Kaufman took an un-standup approach and believed
fully in the separateness of the characters he created, including
Latka on ``Taxi'' and Tony Clifton, the slimy lounge singer. Zehme
talks to ``Taxi'' cast members, some of whom resented Kaufman for
his theater-of-life tricks, which included an afternoon watching
studio cops remove a deranged Clifton from the set. (It didn't help
that he was always late for rehearsals.) Kaufman, of course, has
already been the subject of an ``E! True Hollywood Story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
