<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MANSFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER AUSTEN WINNER IN `MANSFIELD PARK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MANSFIELD PARK 
Written and directed by: Patricia Rozema (based on Jane Austen's
novel) 
Starring: Embeth Davidtz, Jonny Lee Miller, Alessandro Nivola,
Frances O'Connor, Harold Pinter, Lindsay Duncan, Sheila Gish, James
Purefoy, Hugh Bonneville, Justine Waddell, Victoria Hamilton,
Sophia Myles, Hannah Taylor Gordon 
Running time: 110 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (brief violent images, sexual content and drug use) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patricia Rozema's ``Mansfield Park'' continues Jane Austen's
winning streak on film, although in slightly different fashion than
any of the previous entries. What makes Austen's novels so resonant
today is their quite modern fix on love and money, and their
heroines' way, when the chips are down, of betting on love.
Rozema's reworking of Austen's third novel stems, I think, from the
fact that its heroine, Fanny Price, is so unfailingly virtuous that
her apparent lack of faceting poses a challenge. In the end, of
course, we are left with Austen's intended irony that the poor
relation, Fanny, living in a rich house, treated as little better
than a servant, should be the grave repository of the integrity
that keeps the place together as the various weaknesses of its sons
and daughters surface.
</P>
<P>
   Although its stature is the equal of any Austen novel, it hasn't
the sparkle of, say, ``Pride and Prejudice.'' It is, in short, a
bit of a problem novel, and Rozema's tweakings smartly, although
not always successfully, address this. To liberate Fanny from mousy
rectitude, Rozema has made her a writer, as the novel does not. In
other words, a Jane Austen surrogate. It turns her silence and her
imposed meekness into an alert, keen-eyed gathering of impressions
for, presumably, novels to come. And Rozema throws into high relief
the underpinnings of the tranquility of Mansfield Park _ slave
labor on a plantation in Antigua.
</P>
<P>
   It also supplies a possible source for the brooding demeanor of
Fanny's real soulmate at Mansfield Park _ not the sensitive but
wishy-washy second son, Edmund, but the patriarch of Mansfield Park
himself, Sir Thomas Bertram, played, in an inspired piece of
casting, by Harold Pinter, who certainly knows how to suggest
darkness lapping around the edges of anything. Here his gravity is
plausibly fed by a troubled conscience over the fact that he and
his family are living off slaves. Just as Fanny is made more
attractive by exhibiting a sprightly sentience and curiosity it's
easy to attribute to this more Austenized version of her, so it's
easier to like Sir Thomas if we can feel that his forbidding
glumness stems from the depressing contemplation of children who
are turning out to be lightweights and a wife befogged in her
addiction to laudanum.
</P>
<P>
   In short, while it's easy to understand the controversy aroused
by Rozema's rewrite, the question must be asked: To what end? The
ends here are, on the whole, dramatically, psychologically, and
philosophically sound. Either way, ``Mansfield Park'' must be
centered dramatically by its moral anchor, Fanny, and Australian
actress Frances O'Connor is superb as Lady Bertram's poor niece,
tenuously attached to a moneyed family that can offer her not only
stability but a serenity unavailable to her in her crude, dirty,
chaotic family digs in Portsmouth. Like ``Persuasion'' _ my
favorite among the recent Austen-derived films _ ``Mansfield Park''
spends no small amount of time in Portsmouth, to which Fanny is
exiled for refusing to obey Sir Thomas and marry a charming
newcomer, Alessandro Nivola's Henry Crawford, whose essential
shallowness she correctly discerns.
</P>
<P>
   The byplay in ``Mansfield Park'' is stylish and arrives at a
satisfying cumulative weight, even if it isn't Austen pure. Rozema
says she knew she was taking a chance extrapolating from Austen's
letters and other material in departing from a straight transfer.
But it's intelligent chance-taking that pays off in terms of
shoring up the context while leaving Austen's brilliant dialogue
virtually intact. It took me a while to warm to Rozema's structural
gambles, and I didn't warm to all of them _ especially some
un-Austen-like overt sexuality, including Embeth Davidtz's silken
adventuress Mary Crawford's lesbian flirting with Fanny. And at
first, I found myself frowning at what was initially an episodic
vignette style. But as we get to know the characters, Rozema's
takes on them grow longer and our involvement grows deeper, aided
by a raw and slightly seedy look to the world of the film that make
it seem less a period theme park and more rife with existential
immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   The acting is juicy, too. Austen's usual sisterly triumvirate
has a complicated twist here in that Fanny has sisters at home, but
also occupies the position of ideal sister to the disappointing
biological daughters of Sir Thomas. Justine Waddell and Victoria
Hamilton are allowed to remain sympathetic while being foolish.
Even the horrid Aunt Norris (played by Lindsay Duncan, who doubles
as Fanny's mother), is mitigated by our awareness of how she, too,
is a poor relation whose insecurity forces her to scramble for
position and status. Sensitive Edmund could easily have been a
washout, but Jonny Lee Miller keeps him sympathetic, too. But
``Mansfield Park'' rides the twin gravities of Pinter's troubled
patriarch and O'Connor's bright, graceful, steadfast Fanny. Against
the stony gloom of the stately home, her emotional and moral
integrity glows like Liberty's torch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
