<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOY' 2: MORE ANIMATED THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TOY STORY 2 
Directed by: John Lasseter 
Screenplay by: Andrew Stanton, Rita Hsiao, Doug Chamberlin, Chris
Webb 
With the voices of: Tom Hanks, Tim Allen, Joan Cusack, Kelsey
Grammer, Don Rickles, Jim Varney, Wallace Shawn, John Ratzenberger,
Annie Potts, Wayne Knight 
Running time: 98 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2'' is everything you could want in a sequel. It
satisfyingly regenerates the characters and qualities that made the
first film so popular. And then it moves them forward into newer,
fresher, more elaborate, more involving territory. Trailblazing
though ``Toy Story'' may haveMovie Review
</P>
<P>
   been in 1995, its creators can simply do a lot more at their
keyboards today. Four years is a geologic era in computer capacity,
and the Pixar wizards build on what they learned making the first
``Toy Story'' and ``A Bug's Life.'' Some of their new capacities
are quite subtle, such as the ability to do more with the corners
of characters' mouths and eyes. This doesn't sound like a lot, but
it makes available a far greater range of expression, which means
more close-ups are possible, which means the new film achieves a
much richer emotional dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ``Toy Story 2'' is about to depart from its central
relationship, the friendship between old-style Woody the Cowboy and
souped-up new plastic Buzz Lightyear, the space hero. But John
Lasseter and his Pixar crew deepen and broaden the canvas by almost
immediately moving the story out of Andy's room. When Andy goes off
to summer camp, Woody winds up in a yard sale, and is stolen by the
greedy collector and owner of Al's Toy Barn. It has hundreds of
Buzz figures for sale, but Woody, who dates from pre-Sputnik TV, is
a collectible, worth big bucks or, rather, big yen, since the
thief's plan is to unite Woody with the other puppets on the old
``Woody's Roundup'' show and sell them to a Japanese museum. Woody
had no idea he was a collectible, or even what a collectible is,
but old stirrings surface when he's reunited with the adorably
rambunctious Cowgirl Jessie; his faithful horse, Bullseye; and a
sneaky prospector, Stinky Pete.
</P>
<P>
   For a toy, Woody is given some pretty heavy thinking to do. Not
only must he confront his mortality as a discarded doll with an arm
that needs to be sewn back on; he's also torn by conflicting
loyalties to his old TV puppet pals and his family of toys from
Andy's room. The latter, of course, form a search party under
Buzz's leadership to track down and rescue Woody. This takes them
into a much more elaborate version of the outside world than the
suburban street in ``Toy Story.'' They cover many busy city blocks,
the vast shelf-lined Toy Barn, Al's art deco penthouse, and a
mazelike roller-coaster world of airport baggage ramps. Not only
are the animators up to the task; they seem to revel in doing
things they couldn't do the first time, including the inclusion of
foliage and a windblown leafy tree they learned to do in ``A Bug's
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's the writing, the characterizations, and the dynamic
story line that drive ``Toy Story 2'' as much as the unique look
and enhancement of its animation. The voices of Tom Hanks and Tim
Allen instantly plunge us back into the world of the toys who speak
and come to life when humans are out of sight. ``Toy Story 2'' is
packed with new humor as well as new characters. And without going
off on tangents, even the vignettes add to the fun, sometimes with
in-jokes. This time we see the evil Emperor Zurg, Buzz's mortal
enemy, who not surprisingly turns out to bear a more than passing
resemblance to Darth Vader. Barbie turns up this time, too, after
having rejected a cameo in the original. And Pixar aficionados will
smile at the presence of the old man from the Oscar-winning short
``Geri's Game,'' who plays a toy restorer here. While most sequels
are pale carbon copies of the original, ``Toy Story 2'' is more
than a match for ``Toy Story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
