<HEADER>
A0245 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-FLAWLESS-BOS &LR;      11-24 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FLAWLESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMACHER AND DE NIRO DELIVER NEAR-PERFECT `FLAWLESS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FLAWLESS 
Written and directed by: Joel Schumacher 
Starring: Robert De Niro, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Barry Miller,
Chris Bauer, Skipp Sudduth, Wanda De Jesus, Daphne Rubin-Vega,
Wilson Jermaine Heredia, Nashom Benjamin, Scott Allen Cooper, Rory
Cochrane 
Running time: 111 minutes 
Rated: R (pervasive language and strong violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joel Schumacher's ``Flawless'' is a smartly crafted throwback to
the gritty Manhattan crime melodramas of the '40s _ with one big
difference. Given a freedom unavailable to those old genre
pictures, this update is driven by the enforced closeness between
Robert De Niro's brave, proud bank guard who has suffered a stroke
and Philip Seymour Hoffman's transvestite club emcee living in the
same seedy residential hotel, to whom De Niro turns for singing
lessons as therapy. The enormous gulf between them is narrowed, but
never easily, and never is it closed entirely, which makes the film
a lot easier to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The question is to what degree each can inhabit the other's
world, even provisionally, when each regards the other's world as
anathema. The big plus, as the film works its way toward an answer,
is the way each maintains a certain dignity and toughness and never
yields to easy sentimentality to move things along. The closest De
Niro's Walt and Hoffman's Rusty come to a matchmaker is a homicidal
drug dealer who drives them closer than they otherwise would get,
when Rusty is suspected of having stolen some money the dealer had
killed to get and would kill for again. If this sounds a bit
contrived, it is, but it plays better than it sounds, for three big
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The first two, of course, are De Niro and Hoffman. It is to be
expected that De Niro, whose painstaking preparation for roles is
legendary, would be convincing as the recovering stroke victim.
Master actor that he is, De Niro manages to seem simultaneously
imploded and intense. He makes us feel what his character is
feeling, but isn't saying, and since his character is as stubborn
as he is proud, we feel him feeling a lot beneath his largely
frozen exterior. Schumacher the screenwriter gives him much more
than a string of Archie Bunker numbers to reel off. He and De Niro
make us feel Walt's integrity. Walt's capacity for emotion is
conveyed in his relations with two women at a tango palace he
frequented before his stroke: Wanda De Jesus's exploitative beauty
and Daphne Rubin-Vega's sympathetic one.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Seymour Hoffman is the surprise here, but only to those
who haven't seen his extraordinary performances as the schleppy
porn movie gofer in ``Boogie Nights'' or clammy obscene phoner in
``Happiness.'' Resourcefully and movingly, he, too, avoids
caricature as the character called Busty Rusty, even when doing a
Sophie Tucker nightclub parody. Hoffman's Rusty is a creature of
strong feelings, unafraid to express them, wanting to please, yet
tough as cement and street smart. Rusty, in short, is a vivid
survivor, convincing when bonding with fellow drag queens, but
touchingly vulnerable in the decidedly emotional clinches when he's
at the piano, working with his reluctant but determined new client.
</P>
<P>
   The third, but no less important, element in the film's success
is its street feel and the degree of conviction brought to this
project by Schumacher. He's from New York, and although he hasn't
lived there for a couple of decades, he remembers its sights and
textures from the days when he himself led a marginal existence. In
short, this is a New Yorker's New York, not a Los Angelino's, and
it makes a difference. And Schumacher surprises us by making Rusty
the hard-boiled one and Walt the one who's afraid to acknowledge _
and deal with _ his own sensitive side. ``Flawless'' rides an
understated gutsiness and tenacity which is the stuff of life if
you're going to have a life in New York. Atmosphere, perfectly
inflected supporting performances from Rusty's and Walt's very
different social circles, and those sizzling characterizations from
De Niro and Hoffman make ``Flawless'' a down-and-dirty winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
