<HEADER>
A0291 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-PHILIP-HOFFMAN-P     11-24 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PHILIP-HOFFMAN-PROFILE-LADN </SLUG>
  
Indie actor hits the big time with 3 new films  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Not for use before Friday, Nov. 26) 
By Bob Strauss 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You really wonder how weird the guy's going to be.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice surprise then _ actually, more of a relief _ when
Philip Seymour Hoffman shows up happy, full of good humor and
apparently well-adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   A rising sensation in the indie film world for the past several
years, the sandy-haired 32-year-old actor made memorable
appearances as insidious or deeply damaged characters in Paul
Thomas Anderson's ``Hard Eight'' and ``Boogie Nights,' the Coen
Brothers' `Big Lebowski'' and, most alarmingly, Todd Solondz's
controversial ``Happiness,'' in which his alienated young loner
could barely muster a face-to-face conversation but was a real
raconteur when making obscene phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   There have been more conventional roles, such as ``Twister's''
goofy guy in the back of the truck and the skeptical roommate who
came around to recognizing the silly saintliness of ``Patch
Adams.'' But it's Hoffman's willingness to go to behavioral
extremes with uncommon sensitivity that is really defining his
increasingly remarkable career.
</P>
<P>
   ``You explore, but you're also paying homage to a type of human
being,'' says Hoffman, wearing thick, black-rimmed glasses, a dark
blue suit and black shirt. ``If you respect that you're playing a
certain kind of person that is on the Earth _ and any well-written
part usually is that _ then you must, with care, be accurate and
honest and beautiful. If you're not, then ... give up, because
acting's too tough, and that's just the way it should be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, three wildly different roles in equally disparate year-end
feature films showcase a versatility that confirms Hoffman as one
of the most gifted young actors in movies today.
</P>
<P>
   In the just-released ``Flawless,'' he plays a flamboyant New
York drag queen who unexpectedly bonds with his homophobic
neighbor, a conservative security guard played by Robert De Niro,
when the latter suffers a stroke and comes to him for
singing-lesson speech therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's multicharacter ``Magnolia,'' which opens Dec. 17,
presents Hoffman as a visiting nurse whose remarkable day with a
dying television producer played by Jason Robards forces him to
plumb reserves of compassion and quiet heroism he did not know he
possessed.
</P>
<P>
   And in the big-budget period thriller ``The Talented Mr.
Ripley,'' Hoffman plays a wealthy young American having a high old
time in 1950s Italy opposite Gwyneth Paltrow, Matt Damon and Jude
Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flawless'' was the brainchild of Joel Schumacher, the director
of such big-budget extravaganzas as the last two Batman movies and
the John Grisham adaptations ``A Time to Kill'' and ``The Client.''
Schumacher wanted to make a smaller scale, more character-based
drama for a change, and ``Flawless'' was inspired by a friend whose
stroke recovery involved extensive singing lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman doesn't know where the drag portion of the scenario came
from. He just knows Schumacher chose him over a number of
professional transvestites to play tough-but-tender Rusty _ and
that playing a man who prefers being a girl was an awful lot of
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched videos and documentaries _ and went to drag clubs to
see what my character would do at work,'' Hoffman explains. ``I
discovered that these guys are very affected fellows, especially if
they're living in the drag-queen world, which is quite a flamboyant
and colorful society.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I had to decide where I wanted to place Rusty in all of
this. Practicing behaviorally and vocally took about an hour and a
half every day for three months, just preparing myself so that when
I got to the production it would be kind of second nature. He
pretty much lives his life like a woman, and the biggest challenge
was to do all of this stuff that I prepared to do with this guy and
make it as if it was just me. It was tough to have the left side of
the brain going while the right side was churning, keeping all of
that stuff you practiced alive while doing all of the stuff from
moment to moment that's supposed to be very spontaneous.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a general sense of intimidation that comes from
working opposite the greatest actor in American film, and it's no
wonder that Hoffman was in quite a state while making ``Flawless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a basket case,'' he admits. ``A lot of the movie was
just me and Bob, and I can't imagine what I would have done if
somebody who was a jerk played that part. I'd never had a lead in a
movie, and here I had one in that part? I was out of my tree,
going, `Man, I'm going down in flames!'
</P>
<P>
   ``But Bob and Joel both, I could tell that they were like, `God
bless him. This is not easy for this kid, just give him all the
support he needs to let him do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reassuring. But Paul Thomas Anderson arguably gave Hoffman an
even greater gift when he wrote a ``Magnolia'' role specifically
for one of his favorite actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil's character's name is Phil in the movie, and you can
decipher that as I wrote Phil,'' says Anderson. ``He's been getting
all these parts where he plays characters, drag queens and
whatever, and he's so great at it. But I was kind of sick of seeing
him do that and thought, what if Phil had to play himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``So I wrote Phil, who is that compassionate and that wonderful
and that clear. I didn't let him have any tricks in this movie: no
accent, no props, no weird schtick. So that's Phil Hoffman.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not entirely. Hoffman says the giving, empathetic side of
Phil's nature is probably there in him _ but then, who wouldn't cop
to such flattering traits? But where it comes to Phil's complete
dedication to his job at the expense, apparently, of his personal
life, Hoffman says the guy may as well be from another planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy doesn't go out, does he?'' Hoffman says. ``He's weird;
he's, like, 28 years old, and he's `I don't want to go out, I want
to take care of dying people and cry about it and stuff.' I mean,
how many 28-year-old men do you know like that? He's as odd a
character as I've played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there are people who are devoting their lives to
this work, and it's really honorable stuff. But this guy I play
doesn't even have a girlfriend (I know Paul loved every moment of
writing that part). I think about sex 24-7, I've got a definite
scope on what that's about in my life, and this guy's putting it on
hold because he knows that there's something more important. That's
a very odd person to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is one of Hoffman's more accessible roles. While
admitting that he's been without a serious girlfriend for a few
years, the actor bristles at the suggestion that he's becoming
typecast as the movies' signature lonely guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really reachin', don't you think?'' he says. ``No, I
don't think it's like that at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is the way it is,'' he does concede, ``and what're
you going to do? Me and Brad Pitt in the movie, who gets the girl?
But I'm not saying that to be self-effacing; in fact, I just made a
David Mamet movie (`State and Main,' opening next year) in which
I'm the romantic lead and get the girl at the end. I'm glad I did
it, and that's really good, but that's not going to be my career,
and I don't want it to be my career. Most guys don't end up with
the girl, they have problems with relationships. I want to be in
the movies that deal with the real things.''
</P>
<P>
   But a little fantasy doesn't hurt now and then.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy I play in `Ripley,' he's having a great time,''
Hoffman says of the year-end thriller, which is set among young
jet-setters in the 1950s. ``He's rich, drunk and with a girl every
night!''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman grew up in the Rochester, N.Y., suburb of Fairport. A
sports enthusiast for most of his youth, he got into acting after a
wrestling injury, and attended a summer program in nearby Saratoga
Springs sponsored by the famous Circle Repertory Company. He moved
on to study acting at New York University (his brother, Gordy
Hoffman, became a playwright) and, soon after, established an
impressive stage career.
</P>
<P>
   A good background for the movies, yes. But it is Hoffman's
singular ability to invest the most peculiar individuals with
sympathetic understanding that has enabled him to transcend the
category of character actor and, at least so far, come up with
something unique and original each time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have good empathy for people, and it does help my
acting,'' Hoffman says. ``It's just fascinating to me to understand
people's struggles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
