<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE _ Eric Etheridge climbed off the towering wooden
structure, looked up and noticed a slight tilt. From his perch on
the fourth stack, Derek Woodley's swing dipped suddenly. Both heard
an ear-splintering crack and nightmarish chaos ensued as they and
dozens of their Texas A&AMP;M University classmates tumbled to the
ground along with hundreds of tree trunks. No one can say for sure
what caused the Aggie Bonfire to collapse a week ago, killing 12
students and injuring 27. University President Robert Bowen's
special task force is only now beginning the arduous and
months-long task of interviewing witnesses like Etheridge and
Woodley, and sifting through the rumors, photographs, and piles of
lumber in search of answers. However, interviews with a dozen
students working on the bonfire that night suggest a number of
consistencies. (Copelin/Spencer, Austin American-Statesman). 40.
WITH GRAPHICS AND FILE PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   THEORIES _ Experts suggest possible ways the Texas A&AMP;M bonfire
could have collapsed. (Haurwitz/Phillips, Austin
American-Statesman). 20.
</P>
<P>
   ETA: 7 p.m. EST Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   SULLIVAN-REVERSAL _ Tallahassee, Fla. _ The Florida Supreme
Court reversed itself Wednesday and ruled that it should not have
tossed out a $4 million wrongful death verdict in a case involving
a Palm Beach millionaire and his murdered suburban Atlanta wife.
The justices ruled that the verdict against James Sullivan, long
suspected in the murder of his wife, Lita McClintock Sullivan,
should be reconsidered by the trial court even though the
</P>
<P>
   wrongful death statute of limitations had expired. The justices
ruled that Sullivan conspired to cover up his role in the death and
thus should not
</P>
<P>
   be protected by the statute of limitations. (Date, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   PINETOPS _ PINETOPS, N.C. _ A local ministers' group in charge
of relief efforts in this flood-stricken town has scheduled a
Thanksgiving service for Tuesday night, two days before
Thanksgiving. An update on this community. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ETA: 2 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-PIRATES _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Welcome to a 21st century
headache for college administrators. Schools have invested millions
to create cutting-edge computer infrastructures, opening new
frontiers of research and learning. However, those same networks
have made it easy for students to trample copyright protection
laws. Thousands of digital, CD-quality music files are floating
across the World Wide Web. Some are offered by their creators, who
hope to spur interest in their work by giving away a sample. But
many are copied and traded illegally, depriving musicians and
record companies of money that, in all likelihood, is exponentially
greater than the $1 million a day lost from bootleg tapes and CDs,
according to the Recording Industry Association of America.
(Keilman, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CHRISTIANS _ JERUSALEM _ Going into a last effort at
negotiations with contentious church leaders, an Israeli official
said Wednesday that the police may restrict access to the Church of
the Holy Sepulchre if an emergency exit cannot be installed by the
time millennium pilgrims flock to the shrine. The church, thought
to be the site of Christ's crucifixion, is governed by
centuries-old regulations and six different turf-conscious
denominations. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE _ Staff members at the Atlanta-based Carter Center
hope Mozambique's general elections Dec. 3-4 will run even more
smoothly than the African nation's first national multiparty
elections five years ago. The 1994 elections, just two years after
the end of a 16-year civil war, were heavily monitored by U.N.
observers. This year it will be observed prinicipally by a
50-member team from the Atlanta-based center, including former
President Carter and his wife, and a group of about equal size from
the European Union. (Graham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 11.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBALGREEN _ A look at Global Green, the U.S. affiliate of the
international environmental organization Mikhail Gorbachev heads.
The former Soviet leader will speak at the upcoming Global Green
conference in Atlanta. (Graham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KHRIPUNOV _ Igor Khripunov is looking forward to Mikhail
Gorbachev's speech in Athens next week. But it won't be the first
time Khripunov has heard the former Soviet leader. Khripunov served
as Gorbachev's interpreter during a summit with Maggie Thatcher and
later worked with him during a visit to Washington. A former
Communist diplomat himself, Khripunov is now the associate director
of the University of Georgia's Center for International Trade and
Security. He says Gorbachev is the greatest global leader of the
century. (Graham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-JOURNAL _ ORISSA, India _ I had been to Orissa before,
lured by its ancient Hindu temples and pristine beaches. This time,
I was not a tourist. I was there to witness a tragedy of enormous
proportions. A ``super cyclone'' had visited the state just days
before my trip. And it had changed the face of Orissa. A foreign
journal. (Basu, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Political column: Setting a tone for the
politics of abundance. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
