</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CHRISTIANS-1125-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LACKING AGREEMENT ON EXIT, ISRAEL MIGHT LIMIT CHRISTIANS ACCESS
TO CHURCH
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Worried about a millennium year disaster, an Israeli
official Wednesday said police may limit access in peak times at
one of Christianity's holiest sites, the Church of the Holy
Sepulcher.
</P>
<P>
   The cavernous stone church, believed by Roman Catholic and
Orthodox Christians to be the site of Christ's crucifixion, expects
hundreds of thousands of pilgrims next year to mark the 2000 years
since Christ's birth.
</P>
<P>
   The church only has one exit from its main chambers. Already, as
the swell of millennial tourists begins, the church is hosting
10,000 visitors on some days. They pack shoulder-to-shoulder crowds
in some of the passages between its shrines and chapels.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have tried for more than a year to win
approval from church leaders to install an emergency exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not open an emergency gate, then maybe the police
will have to limit the number of people who can enter,'' said
Israel's Christian Communities Department Director Uri Mor.
</P>
<P>
   Mor singled out for special concern the Holy Saturday services
of Greek Orthodox worshippers. A day before Easter, the ceremony
usually packs the church with more than 15,000 people holding lit
candles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will not be much choice but to limit the number,'' Mor
said. ``It is a very, very, very, dangerous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said police may also have to set quotas on other days, which
would be the first time Israel has done that.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders could not be reached after Mor's remarks
Wednesday, but they have been reticent to make any changes to the
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``With deep faith, we believe that God will protect all these
pilgrims. All the pilgrims believe that,'' Metropolitan Timothy, a
leading local bishop with the Greek Orthodox Church, said earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israeli officials fear a repeat of a 19th century fire that
killed several hundred worshippers.
</P>
<P>
   Mor said he is about to enter another round of negotiations with
church leaders, but he was not optimistic about the emergency exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it coming close to reality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments Wednesday came amid several incidents of religious
acrimony in the approach to the year 2000, when the Jewish state is
to host millions of pilgrims at Christian sites.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in memory and possibly centuries, the Church
of the Holy Sepulcher and other shrines closed their doors to
visitors for two days earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders were protesting Israel's permitting the
construction of a mosque near the Basilica of the Annunciation in
Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders wanted to use the space for a visitors plaza.
They accused the Israeli government of creating bitterness between
Christians and Muslims by encouraging militant Muslims who wanted
the mosque. A visitors plaza will still be constructed on
two-thirds of the area.
</P>
<P>
   But, dissatisfied with the compromise proposals, a
representative of the Vatican criticized Israel saying it was
``instigating division'' between religions.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy lashed back at the statement
Wednesday, calling it ``the opposite of the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, Israeli police arrested a Jewish man and
accused him of trying set fire to a Russian Orthodox Church in the
city of Tiberias.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of the Holy Sepulcher, in Jerusalem's Old City, is
governed mainly by Roman Catholic, Greek Orthodox and Armenian
churches. Syrian Orthodox, Coptic and Ethiopian churches also pray
there.
</P>
<P>
   For 147 years, the church has been governed by a ``status quo''
agreement that dictates exactly which areas the different churches
control. Battles have broken out over who would clean a single
step, since caring for an area is taken to signify ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the church is the rocky alter where Christ is believed to
have been crucified, the stone slab on which his body was prepared
for entombment, and the tomb from which he is believed to have
risen.
</P>
<P>
   Mor said church leaders have agreed in concept to the emergency
door, but not agreed on where it should be placed. They also have
disputed who should control the keys to the door. Some want only
the denomination that owns the space where the door is placed to
hold the key, while others want all denominations to have keys.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
