<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcome to Walt's world - the real one
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disneyphiles of all ages are going to want ``Remembering Walt''
(Hyperion, $29.95), an enchanting oral history of Walt Disney as
remembered by everyone from such trusted animators as Frank Thomas
and Ollie Johnston to actors like Kurt Russell to the pilot of his
private plane.
</P>
<P>
   Authors Howard Green and Amy Boothe Green made wise use of
material from the Disney archives, so we get to hear Walt's late
wife Lillian, as well as others who have gone to the big
Cinderella's Castle in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The book is full of previously unpublished art. I particularly
enjoyed the family snapshots _ the Disneys at their wedding
anniversary, their kids' birthdays, etc., which were found in
Disney's desk after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Michelangelo for the holidays
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine a more meaningful book for the holiday season
than ``Michelangelo: The Pietas'' (Abbeville) a slipcased volume
that covers, in exhausting detail, the three sculptures in which
the soul of his age struggled with the idea of the Madonna and her
dead child.
</P>
<P>
   Most people prefer the Pieta in the Vatican, but I like the
unfinished one in Florence (The third, in Milan, was the piece he
was working on when he died; I've never seen it.) I have no idea
how he made the one in the Vatican, but the unfinished state of the
Florentine Pieta, the leg he struck off in a fit of rage, the
chisel marks still on most of the marble, give us a vision of the
artist's struggles that make the perfection he achieved elsewhere
even more poignant.
</P>
<P>
   Last night I dreamt I went to Manderley . . .
</P>
<P>
   Although Daphne du Maurier was one of the most popular authors
of her time, the reality of this ever-speeding-up culture is that
no one is more than two generations from obscurity. Other than the
perennial Rebecca, perhaps the most imitated book of the century,
du Maurier has been completely out of print.
</P>
<P>
   But the University of Pennsylvania Press is reprinting several
Du Maurier titles: ``The Scapegoat'' (1957) and ``The House on the
Strand'' (1969). Should these titles do well, the Press stands
ready to reprint more, such as ``The Birds,'' from which Hitchcock
made his fine 1963 film, or the swashbuckler ``Frenchman's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Quote Unquote . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a good thing for an artist to marry. As the ancients
used to say, if you serve a Muse, you must serve her and no one
else. An unhappy marriage may perhaps contribute to the development
of talent, but a happy one is no good at all.'' _ Ivan Turgenev
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
