<HEADER>
A0345 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-END-OF-DAYS-REVIEW26-     11-24 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-END-OF-DAYS-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOVIE REVIEW: End of Days
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five weeks and counting until the new millennium, when doomsday
thrillers such as ``End of Days'' will thankfully be things of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Schwarzenegger's first film since 1997's frostily
received ``Batman &AMP; Robin'' preys on premillennial fears by staging
the biblical book of Revelation as an abhorrently violent action
flick, in which Satan assumes human form to take a bride in the
hour before midnight on New Year's Eve 1999. To vanquish his foe,
Arnie must put his faith in God, not a grenade launcher, but he
blows up a lot of stuff before coming to that realization.
</P>
<P>
   ``End of Days'' recalls the recent and similarly awful religious
thriller, ``The Omega Code,'' albeit with a much bigger budget and
considerably more bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Peter Hyams (''The Relic''), the film is a seriously
disturbing orgy of carnage and computer-generated effects. Though
we expect a fair amount of mayhem from Schwarzenegger movies, ``End
of Days'' is awash in gratuitous violence, pointless explosions and
more gore than most folks probably can stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The story is as subtle as a sledgehammer, pitting
Schwarzenegger's gritty lost soul, Jericho Cane, against the Prince
of Darkness (Gabriel Byrne) to protect the latter's chosen bride,
Christine York (Robin Tunney), and prevent the end of the world.
Cane is a hard-drinking ex-cop who lost his faith after his family
was brutally murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``End of Days'' holds some initial intrigue as Cane and his
comic-relief sidekick, Chicago (Kevin Pollack), are caught unaware
between a rogue sect of Vatican assassins and a ``Rosemary's
Baby''-like cabal of Satanists. However, the film quickly dissolves
into a dull, gruesome game of cat-and-mouse that just gets worse as
it goes.
</P>
<P>
   Satan first rises up from the New York City sewers in
transparent form, looking much like Schwarzenegger's adversary in
``Predator.'' Setting the ridiculous tone of the film, he randomly
takes the form of a darkly handsome Wall Street banker (Byrne), who
returns to his restaurant table and forcibly gropes his companion's
wife. He then exits the restaurant, which promptly explodes for no
apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   Plot holes abound, such as why Satan hires Cane and Chicago as
his bodyguards, when his bullet wounds heal themselves. The bigger
question is why aren't religious groups protesting the film, as
they did with Kevin Smith's smart apocalyptic comedy, ``Dogma?''
</P>
<P>
   Hyams' mind-numbing horror show features scenes of a priest
being gored through his skull with a crucifix and Cane being
crucified above the entrance of a Catholic church, to name but two
offensive images. Revolting close-ups of a mutilated corpse and
countless shots of mangled living flesh make the film tougher to
watch than ``Fight Club.''
</P>
<P>
   ``End of Days'' is Schwarzenegger's first film since his two
life-threatening open-heart operations in April 1997 to fix a
congenitally defective heart valve. The action star looks as strong
as ever and performs a number of impressive but ludicrous stunts,
such as chasing a hit man across a roof top while suspended on a
rope ladder from a helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzenegger keeps the quips to a bare minimum, but he mauls
much of his dialogue, especially when he snaps at Satan: ``You're a
choir boy compared to me!''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack (A Few Good Men) gets in a few good lines before his
character is killed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``End of Days'' features some stylish visuals, but like the evil
spirit in ``The Haunting,'' Satan ultimately proves to be a big,
disappointing special effect.
</P>
<P>
   The end of this short-lived genre can't come soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   Director: PETER HYAMS; Starring: ARNOLD SCHWARZENEGGER, GABRIEL
BYRNE, ROBIN TUNNEY, KEVIN POLLACK; 118 minutes; Intense violence
and gore, a strong sex scene and profanity
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: D
</P>
<P>
   A _ Excellent
</P>
<P>
   B _ Good
</P>
<P>
   C _ Fair
</P>
<P>
   D _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   F _ Abysmal
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: davelarsen(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
