<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0346 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-EVEREST-BOOKREVIEW26-     11-24 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVEREST-BOOKREVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mountain mystery: The Mallory and Irvine story told in ``Ghosts
of Everest''
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Mallory was last seen alive on June 8, 1924. He and
Andrew Irvine were at 27,000 feet and moving over a ridge, about
three hours from their goal, the summit of Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 75 years, that has been the sum total of knowledge
about Mallory's last day. He and Irvine never returned, and whether
they made it to the top before dying (a full 29 years before Sir
Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay conclusively conquered Everest)
has been the subject of many books and much speculation in the
climbing subculture.
</P>
<P>
   George Leigh Mallory was one of those strange, obsessive,
severely handsome Englishmen _ T.E. Lawrence was another
contemporaneous example _ capable of capturing the world's
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lawrence, nothing in Mallory's life prepared him for what
he was determined to be. He had been an indifferent schoolmaster, a
lecturer, and at the time of his last expedition was the assistant
secretary of the Board of Extra-Mural Studies at Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   But all who knew him agreed that he was an extraordinary
climber, with a strange, unorthodox style that enabled him to give
the impression of gliding up a mountain. If anybody could have
climbed Everest, given the primitive equipment and clothing of the
time, it was Mallory.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, an expedition formed solely to search for the
bodies of Mallory and Irvine achieved half their goal by finding
Mallory. A bare five months later, the first of what will be many
books on the subject has appeared.
</P>
<P>
   There weren't a lot of clues to enable them in their search. For
their reference point, the expedition decided to use the camp of a
Chinese expedition of some 30 years ago that had reported finding
``English dead'' very nearby.
</P>
<P>
   It was, for the most part, guesswork; the expedition's
braintrust, one Jochen Hemmler, was a young amateur climbing
historian who was himself only a nominal climber. He studied photos
of the Chinese expedition and found reference points on the
mountain that told the expedition where to look for the
long-abandoned Chinese camp, hence the ``English dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The spot was on the North Ridge, and as the expedition began
fanning out from the site of the Chinese camp, they stumbled across
a virtual graveyard of abandoned bodies (it's a practical
impossibility to bring a dead body down from Everest, so people are
left where they drop).
</P>
<P>
   The tangled bodies disabused the expedition about the cause of
death of most Everest casualties _ not exhaustion and exposure, but
a misstep and a drop of thousands of feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ghosts of Everest'' spends too much time on the makeup and
details of Mallory's ascent, and too little about the men who found
his body. We learn that there were great tensions between the
sponsors and the team; that the BBC, which was financing part of
the expedition in return for video rights, was untrustworthy at
best and dishonest at worst.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the most part, the authors keep their eye on the ball
and don't let the narrative bog down in accounts of internecine
warfare.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Mallory's body was found without too much
trouble, and, despite his paltry clothing _ George Bernard Shaw
said that men like Mallory dressed as if they were going to a
picnic in the Connemaras _ in amazingly good condition because of
the permafrost.
</P>
<P>
   Mallory had fallen and broken a leg and, probably, some ribs,
and had suffered a bad wound to the forehead that was probably the
immediate cause of death. Irvine presumably met the same fate at
the same time _ the two men had been tethered together _ but the
whereabouts of his body remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The expedition was hoping for a conclusive answer to the
ultimate question, but it didn't get it. Mallory had been carrying
a collapsible Kodak camera so he could memorialize a successful
ascent, but it wasn't found on his body.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing the expedition found invalidates the possibility that
Mallory and Irvine made it to the top, but nothing proves it,
either. One teasing thing: Mallory always said that if he made it,
he was going to put a picture of his beloved wife at the top of the
mountain. There was no picture of Ruth Mallory found on his body.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not lose our heads. Mallory might have made it, but
someone killed by Everest can hardly be said to have conquered the
mountain. What is clear is that they were coming down after dark _
Mallory wasn't wearing his sungoggles _ and that the two men had
climbed higher than anybody else ever had.
</P>
<P>
   After examining Mallory's body, and removing the contents of his
pockets, the expedition gave him the best burial they could,
covering him with a cairn of rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments will continue, of course, but ``Ghosts of
Everest'' adds a great deal of knowledge that helps add some facts
to a romantic historical legend, as well as serving as a spur for a
continued search for the body of Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   The book features a touching introduction by Mallory's daughter
and the best definition of why men climb mountains I've ever read.
</P>
<P>
   It comes from Jochen Hemmler, who says that ``during a couple of
hours of climbing, you can experience more than you would in a week
elsewhere. Your senses are completely alert when you're climbing _
hearing, breathing, smelling, everything _ and you begin to get a
glimpse of how deep the feeling of being alive can really become.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think climbers climb to risk death; I think they climb
to prove to themselves that they are not already dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1446EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0347 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HITLERS-NIECE-REVIEW2     11-24 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITLERS-NIECE-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Hitler's Niece' makes you want to cry 'uncle'
 &HT;    By Tom Blackburn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Mel Brooks' classic movie ``The Producers,'' Zero Mostel
deliberately produces a musical called ``Springtime for Hitler,''
thinking it will be a huge flop on Broadway and he can make off
with the investors' money. Ron Hansen, I'm afraid, has written
``Springtime for Hitler'' by accident.
</P>
<P>
   That's not his intention, and, indeed, Hitler commits murder at
the end of his novel. But for the long trudge to the end, Hansen
has to describe the domestic life of a Fuhrer. Hitler is a doting
uncle. He picnics in the Alps. He plays with his doggy. He attends
the opera. He nibbles sweets.
</P>
<P>
   His half-sister, Angela, and her daughter, Geli, come from
not-so-genteel poverty in Austria to do his cooking and cleaning.
But the work is done in half a day, and then it's time for play.
Uncle Adolf lavishes gifts on his niece, has his chauffeur take her
motoring and praises her limited accomplishments. It's gemutlich.
</P>
<P>
   As time goes on, a) Hitler becomes sexually obsessed with his
niece, and b) she finds out about his mistress, Eva Braun. Besides
Eva and consanguinity, there are other problems with his love for
Geli. For one thing, he has odd ways of performing sex. For
another, he is 34, she is 15 when they meet. She's 23 when his
jealous possessiveness drives him to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is more or less documented. When Geli Raubal's death
was ruled a suicide after a less-than-zealous investigation,
anti-Nazi newspapers doubted it. Hitler's alleged preference for
sex as a non-contact sport found its way into a psychological
profile of him written for the Office of Strategic Services during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Rosenbaum, in his recent ``Explaining Hitler,'' traced the
sex tales to Hitler's enemies, who didn't have firsthand
information (who before Ken Starr ever did?). Rosenbaum doubted
this version of the Geli saga, but the folklore is out there to be
exploited by a novelist.
</P>
<P>
   But is it worth exploiting?
</P>
<P>
   Start with the title character. About all we know about her
personality is that many Nazis found her charming. How expert about
charm were Nazis? Hansen makes her a liberated woman with a sharp
eye for phoniness and a healthy (considering her associates)
cynicism whose put-downs exude irony.
</P>
<P>
   I find her irony unlikely, given the era and her small-town
background.
</P>
<P>
   Other personalities in the story come straight from standard
reference works: ``She did not meet Hermann Goering until May 1928,
but she'd heard a great deal about him, for, next to her uncle, he
was the most famous Nazi in Germany. She was told by Putzi
Hanfstaengl _ whose job as foreign press officer obligated him to
know _ that Goering's father, the first governor of West Africa and
a former consul general in Haiti, had been 64 years old when
Hermann was born in 1893, and had named his son after a friend who
was . . .'' etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   But you know what? As Hansen portrays her, Geli wouldn't have
paid attention to a single word Hanfstaengl said on the subject.
And she's the viewpoint character. If she wouldn't care, why should
we?
</P>
<P>
   Because it's history as fiction, and the reason for caring about
the history is that Uncle Adolf launched the mother of all European
bloodbaths and went on to have Jews murdered because they were
Jews, Russians murdered because they were communists, homosexuals
murdered because they reminded him of the mentally retarded whom he
was also having murdered, and Poles murdered because he just didn't
like Poles.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing all that, to picture him murdering his niece doesn't
really take the skills of such a highly regarded novelist as Ron
Hansen. Hitler doesn't wave a gun until Page 179. Until then, the
most important thing about that character has been simply omitted,
and anybody's bachelor uncle could be substituted for him.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Blackburn writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
