<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0348 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TOY-STORY2-REVIEW26-C     11-24 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOY-STORY2-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A shiny new `TOY': Sequel is season's must-have ticket
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like G.I. Joe with lifelike hair or bendable Barbie, ``Toy Story
2'' is a rare sequel that's better than the original.
</P>
<P>
   The wildly imaginative follow-up to the 1995 computer-animated
blockbuster improves with more realistic animation and a
surprisingly deep and poignant storyline. The delightful
comedy-adventure also introduces a marvelous array of new
characters, including Woody's Roundup Gang and Buzz Lightyear's
arch nemesis, Emperor Zurg.
</P>
<P>
   The film's humor, which includes hilarious riffs on ``Star
Wars,'' ``James Bond'' and ``Lassie,'' works on multiple levels and
will have viewers of all ages roaring with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   The action-packed plot, which sends Buzz (voiced by Tim Allen)
to the rescue when Woody (Tom Hanks) is stolen by an obsessive toy
collector, is fraught with edge-of-your-seat peril.
</P>
<P>
   The thrilling climax, which pays homage to Hollywood westerns,
is as exciting as an Indiana Jones movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2'' picks up with Andy heading off to Cowboy Camp.
His favorite toy, Woody, is left behind because of a torn arm and
inadvertently winds up as part of a yard sale. There he is snatched
away by Al McWhiggin (Wayne Knight), owner of Al's Toy Barn.
</P>
<P>
   At Al's apartment, Woody learns he is a highly valued
collectible from a Howdy Doody-style 1950s television show called
``Woody's Roundup.'' The show was a pop-culture phenomenon, but was
canceled because of the sudden demand for spaceman toys following
the launch of Sputnik _ echoing the Woody-Buzz rivalry of the first
film.
</P>
<P>
   Woody completes a prized collection that also includes cowgirl
Jessie (Joan Cusack), Bullseye the horse and Stinky Pete the
Prospector (Kelsey Grammer), which Al plans to sell for big bucks
to a Japanese toy museum.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz mobilizes Mr. Potato Head (Don Rickles), Slinky Dog (Jim
Varney), Rex (Wallace Shawn) and Hamm (John Ratzenberger) for a
daring crosstown rescue mission. But Woody is torn between his old
friends and new, who will wind up back in a dark storage box
without him, and he must decide if he wants to be a child's
plaything or a museum piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2'' is more emotionally involving than the first
film, centering on what happens when children outgrow their toys.
It's also more consistently funny, thanks to tons of great gags
involving such new recruits as Barbie and the Rock'em Sock'em
Robots.
</P>
<P>
   Director John Lasseter uses the technological advancements
developed for ``A Bug's Life'' and Pixar's 1997 Oscar-winning
short, ``Geri's Game,'' to enhance the look of the film. The
outdoor settings appear much more realistic than in the original
``Toy Story,'' thanks to the grass-and-tree software from ``A Bug's
Life.'' The humans are less synthetic-looking, with ``Geri'' making
a cameo appearance as The Cleaner (Jonathan Harris).
</P>
<P>
   The use of live-action-style camera angles and updated lighting
and depth-of-field techniques makes the world of Andy's toys come
alive, so that you forget you're watching an animated film.
Remarkable attention is paid to detail, from dust bunnies on a
shelf to the toys' reflections in the polished hardwood floor of
Andy's bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack whoops it up as Jessie, who is resentful of Woody, while
Grammer lends his resonant tones to the sage Prospector, who has
never been out of his box.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks provides a wealth of emotion. Allen gets big laughs in the
dual role of the old and new-and-improved Buzz dolls.
</P>
<P>
   To spell it out like A-B-C blocks, ``Toy Story 2'' is one of the
year's best films.
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: A
</P>
<P>
   Toy Story 2
</P>
<P>
   Director: JOHN LASSETER; Starring: THE VOICES OF TOM HANKS, TIM
ALLEN, JOAN CUSACK, KELSEY GRAMMER; 85 minutes; Nothing
objectionable
</P>
<P>
   A _ Excellent
</P>
<P>
   B _ Good
</P>
<P>
   C _ Fair
</P>
<P>
   D _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   F _ Abysmal
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: davelarsen(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
