<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONESOME-CLINTON-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL CLINTON CUTS A LONELY, SAD FIGURE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 875-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House has abandoned efforts to attract
international leaders to next week's World Trade Organization
summit in Seattle, a decision that leaves one of the biggest
international gatherings of recent years at its planned ministerial
level.
</P>
<P>
   However, this failure also deprives President Bill Clinton of an
opportunity to appear in the role of world leader at one of the
last big set piece events of his presidency on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   While the diplomatic significance of this setback is small _ the
WTO meeting was always planned as a ministerial meeting and the
White House began only late in the day to try to make it something
more _ it underlines the diminishing power of a U.S. president as
his second term draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of President Clinton, the seeping away of his power
is compounded by the growing distance between himself and his two
closest lieutenants: his wife and his vice-president.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fact of presidential life that senior members of the
administration, however loyal, start to depart in pursuit of their
own interests as their president's time runs out.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, however, Clinton has had to stand back as
first his vice-president and this week his wife stated publicly
that they were putting their own careers above their official
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Vice-President Al Gore has now given two newspaper interviews in
which he has not only distanced himself from the president, but
effectively downgraded his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running for President of this country,'' he told the
Washington Post last weekend, ``is far more important than being
the best vice-president I can possibly be.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose close association with Clinton is widely _ though
perhaps wrongly _ seen as the chief obstacle to his winning the
presidency in a year's time, has increasingly tried to distance
himself from the president.
</P>
<P>
   He told the same Washington Post correspondent that he had
``zero involvement'' with Clinton's controversial decision to grant
clemency to a group of Puerto Rican nationalists, and is now rarely
seen in public side by side with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Gore will accept campaign help from Clinton, however, is
still moot. Having said three months ago that he did not want
Clinton to campaign for him, he then retreated to the point of
suggesting that this was not his position.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to escape the impression that he wanted the money
that Clinton, still the Democratic Party's most effective
fund-raiser, could raise for him, but not the ethical baggage that
inevitably accompanies the president.
</P>
<P>
   With Mrs. Clinton's announcement on Tuesday that she was
``scaling back'' her official duties as first lady in order to
campaign full time for a U.S. Senate seat, Clinton was given formal
notice that he had lost _ at least temporarily _ his most trusted
adviser, and consort, as well.
</P>
<P>
   She will move to the couple's new house at Chappaqua, north of
New York City, as soon as it has been adapted for security, and
launch her official campaign from there.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first time for 80 years that a president has
lived at the White House without a full-time first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clintons insist that they will see each other at weekends _
presenting the arrangement as a ``commuter'' marriage, no different
from that of thousands of American couples separated by their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's office also moved quickly to quash any new
speculation about the state of the marriage. Her spokeswoman,
Marsha Berry, also denied categorically that the Clintons'
daughter, Chelsea, had any plans to interrupt her studies at
Stanford University to stand in for her mother as first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a full-time student and will remain one,'' she said
when the question was put.
</P>
<P>
   It remains, however, that President Clinton and his wife have
spent very little time together in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   On their latest foreign travels, they flew out and back
separately, linking up only for a few days in Turkey, Greece and
the weekend meeting in Florence where Mrs. Clinton was a speaker.
Mrs. Clinton returned two days earlier than her husband, in part it
seemed, to stem speculation about her Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, still the abjectly contrite spouse, uses
every opportunity to stress his support for his wife's Senate bid,
and is expected to campaign on her behalf. Given the surge in her
popularity when she emerged as a wronged wife any reminder of that
period will probably help rather than hinder her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife and vice-president increasingly absent, though,
Clinton has started to cut a lonely and somewhat sad figure.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, he was reported to have spent an
afternoon playing golf by himself, in the rain. Earlier this week,
there were poignant photographs of him, with Chelsea, in Athens,
visiting an otherwise deserted Parthenon.
</P>
<P>
   At home, not even his dog, Buddy, has been much in evidence of
late.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the questions are being asked: is the presidency a
job that can be done alone? And how will a man who so clearly
thrives on company adjust to his new isolation?
</P>
<P>
   Both he, and America, are about to find out. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 875-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1521EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0391 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-ROSETTA-REVIEW-L     11-24 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ROSETTA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
  
On strength of star and script, `Rosetta' commands attention  
(For use by  LANG Group)  
Our rating:  3 stars  
(Eds: Not for use before Friday, Nov. 26) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By Bob Strauss, Film Critic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Rosetta'' won the best picture prize at the Cannes Film
Festival, and its amateur star, 18-year-old Emilie Dequenne, copped
the fest's best actress award. This uncompromising Belgian drama
certainly earned its accolades _ it's raw and exquisitely
controlled at the same time, and Dequenne's fierce, focused energy
is a relentless marvel.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this means that the film is anything akin to a
pleasant experience.
</P>
<P>
   With a frenzied, tightly framed hand-held camera that quickly
achieves that delightful ``Blair Witch'' nausea effect, directors
Luc and Jean-Pierre Dardenne plunge us into the desperate world of
Dequenne's Rosetta. A rough-edged adolescent who lives in a grimy
trailer with her near-catatonically alcoholic mom (Anne Yernaux),
Rosetta longs for the consistency that a job _ any job _ would
bring to her life.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, no matter how hard she works, she can't keep one. We
initially see her charging frantically through a factory, running
from the supervisor who wants to lay her off. She hides and fights
him tooth and nail, as if he were trying to steal her soul (which,
by her reckoning, he is).
</P>
<P>
   Wandering the streets of a grubby industrial town, she gets
brief work from a waffle stand entrepreneur who then has to replace
her with his no-account son. One of the guy's clerks, Riquet
(Fabrizio Rongione), takes a shine to Rosetta, but she's more
interested in appropriating his job than responding to his
affection. In one remarkable scene, Riquet falls into a muddy
canal, and she seriously contemplates letting him drown for the
outside hope of a minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Rosetta herself had been flung into the same slippery
muck by a mother who didn't wish to visit a rehab facility.
Flopping about and crying ``I can't get out'' as the older woman
disappears in search of her next bottle, the moment pretty much
sums up the girl's life in one vivid, resonant symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Furious as Dequenne's performance often is, it is also marked by
steadying (yet heartbreaking) periods of self-made busywork.
Rosetta trolls for fish she throws back, obsesses over boots she
hides in wooded dugouts and tries to do anything else that can seem
like work, or can at least momentarily distract her from the
awfulness she otherwise breathes. It's an impressively complete and
modulated performance, one of the few marked by emotional outbursts
that is actually enriched by quieter moments.
</P>
<P>
   The Dardenne brothers, whose last film was the impressive ``La
Promesse,'' continue their startlingly moral, uncondescending
fascination with contemporary capitalism's born rejects here. They
never ask us to cry for Rosetta _ she's too obnoxious for that _
yet there's narry a second when she doesn't earn our sympathy. You
wish that she could earn a decent living with similar efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   And many will wish that they'd never been exposed to such a
convincingly dire life. There is a flurry of
irresponsible-mom/practical-daughter movies out at the moment.
``Anywhere But Here'' is pure Hollywood fakery, and
``Tumbleweeds,'' though more honest, lets actresses indulge wayward
theatricality far too often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rosetta'' is far and away the most truthful, unflinching and
creative of the three _ the idea that Rosetta's overdeveloped sense
of responsibility is a form of pathology is, in and of itself, a
brilliant notion. The film deserves nothing but praise for these
qualities. Sitting through it, of course, is another matter
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The stars: Emilie Dequenne, Fabrizio Rongione, Anne Yernaux,
Olivier Gourmet.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Luc and Jean-Pierre
Dardenne. Produced by the Dardennes and Michele and Laurent Petin.
Released by USA Films.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: One hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Playing: Nuart, West L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating:3 stars
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
