<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OPERATION-SMILE-II (Beijing) _ In recent months, Operation Smile
has been the recipient of coveted awards for assisting poor
children, as well as the target of increasingly loud criticism
about its shoddy medical practices. Last August, at the Plastic
Surgery Hospital on the outskirts of Beijing, the organization
clearly showed its potential to temper its good work with bad. A
Special Report, the second of two parts, by Elisabeth Rosenthal and
Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-TREASON (Jerusalem) _ A newspaper's publication of
partial transcripts from the treason trial of Mordechai Vanunu,
arrested in 1986 for alleged disclosures of Israel's nuclear
program, is reopening the debate on the country's policy of nuclear
ambiguity. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-TUDJMAN (Zagreb, Croatia) _ The parliament considers
transferring some powers of the country's ailing president, Franjo
Tudjman. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ASSISI-BASILICA (Assisi, Italy) _ Three years after a
devastating earthquake, Assisi's famous basilica is to reopen on
Sunday. But new housing for the thousands left homeless has yet to
materialize. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-GYPSIES (Usti Nad Labem, Czech Republic) _ This Czech
city, bending to pressure, pulls down a wall blocking off gypsy
housing.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-OIL (Nis, Yugoslavia) _ The first fuel and heating
oil from the European Union arrives in opposition-controlled
Serbian cities. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-MISSILES (Beijing) _ China's chief of arms control
issued a new warning today that American plans for a national
missile defense system, even if intended to stop attacks from rogue
states like North Korea and Iraq, would set off a global arms race
and cause more countries to develop nuclear weapons. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
