   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-RITALIN-SCHOOLS (Denver) _ The Colorado Board of Education
has become the first in the nation to adopt a policy against
teachers urging parents to put their children on behavior
controlling drugs like Ritalin and Luvox, rekindling a national
debate over the growing use of such drugs by school children. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-TRAVEL (Undated) _ On our congested roads and airports
as we gather together. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THANKSGIVING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GIVING-THANKS-I (New York) _ A factory worker walked by a
homeless man near the Port Authority for years; once, he tossed a
couple of quarters his way. Thus is set in motion a remarkable
story of charity, kinship, coincidence and reunion. The worker
befriended the homeless man, cleaned him up, discovered he was from
same part of Virginia and vowed to take him home to his mother,
whose church had been praying for him for three years. Now back
home, the homeless man, Raymond, is playing the organ for the
church choir. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GIVING-THANKS-II (New York) _ Our Thanksgiving miracle story: a
police officer who is shot, but saved by cellphone. By Jason Blair.
</P>
<P>
   GIVING-THANKS-III (New York) _ Ten Thanksgivings ago, Iris
Sanchez, on strike from a low-paying job, made 30 turkey sandwiches
and gave them to the homeless in her Brooklyn neighborhood. Now she
feeds 1,000 hungry, often homeless people each week, and organizes
language classes and health exams for them. For her it's about
gratitude: on successive Thanksgivings, years earlier, her
ex-husband almost succeeded in murdering her. By Jan Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   THANKSGIVING-BAND (New York) _ The Athens, Texas, high school
band is marching in the Thanksgiving Day Parade. We see how they
like New York. Athens is the hometown of Nicole Barrett, the woman
who is hospitalized in New York after being attacked last week on
the street by a man with a paving stone. By Winnie Hu.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TOYS (Undated) _ The toy craze of the holiday shopping season?
It must be Pokemon. As many as 1 in 5 of the toys, games and books
given to children this season will have a Pokemon theme, said Chris
Byrne, the editor of The Toy Report, a weekly newsletter. ``Kids
can't seem to get enough of it,'' said a spokeswoman for Toys ``R''
Us, But they may not get exactly what they want. Some of the the
most popular Pokemon items, like trading cards and cuddly Pikachu
dolls that also say their name, are in short supply. Stung by last
year's disappointing holiday season, toy manufacturers expect sales
to rebound this year. The other big sellers are expected to include
some familiar names in new incarnations: Rock and Roll Elmo and
Rock and Roll Ernie from ``Sesame Street` and Flight Control Buzz
Lightyear and Strumming' Singing' Woody from ``Toy Story 2.'' By
Terry Pristin.
</P>
<P>
   MANNESMANN-VODAFONE (Hong Kong) _ As Mannesmann and Vodafone
AirTouch roll out the heavy artillery for their bitter takeover
battle, there is already one undisputed victor: Li Ka-shing, the
billionaire developer and chairman of Hutchison Whampoa. No matter
who wins, he stands to make a multi-billion dollar profit. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-FRANCE (Undated) _ The French government, for a second
time, blocks the $733 million sale of Orangina to Coca-Cola on
antitrust grounds, another setback in Coke's efforts to build up
its European business. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Economic growth was substantially
stronger in the third quarter than previously thought, powered by
rising inventories, vigorous consumption and an improved trade
performance, the Commerce Department says in revising an earlier
estimate. The gross domestic product rose at a steep 5.5 percent
annual rate in the third quarter, higher than the 4.8 percent
originally reported, and above Wall Street economists' expectations
for an annual rate of growth of 5 to 5.2 percent. By Robert D.
Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-AIRLINE (Mexico City) _ The Mexican airline Taesa,
accused of shoddy maintenance practices by its former flight
attendants, has been grounded by Mexican authorities two weeks
after the crash of one of its DC-9's killed 18 people. By Sam
Dillon.
</P>
