<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FOX-$ADV27-COX     11-24 1771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHARISMA, MARKETING FUEL CANDIDATE'S QUEST TO END ONE-PARTY RULE
IN MEXICO
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    EDs: Vital stats on Vicente Fox attached to end of story.
 &HT;    For Sat., Nov. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ With his six-feet, four-inch frame, basso profundo
voice and gleaming black cowboy boots, Vicente Fox could be the
star of a Mexican western.
</P>
<P>
   The charismatic politician is, in fact, playing a lead role in
this country's transition to greater democracy. A farmer and a
former executive for Coca-Cola Co. in Mexico, Fox wants desperately
to smash 70 years of one-party presidency in Mexico. He campaigns
daily with relish, visiting poor and rich, eagerly trying to
convince Mexicans to make him the first president since 1929 to not
belong to Mexico's omnipresent Institutional Revolutionary Party,
or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corrupt,'' ``deceitful'' and ``dictatorial'' are a few choice
words Fox employs to trash the PRI in interviews or before
delighted campaign crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're terrified of an honest person will get to the
presidency here,'' Fox says in an interview, lambasting the PRI and
sliding easily between Spanish and English. ``All the jails in
Mexico, the United States and Europe wouldn't be enough to hold all
the criminals here.''
</P>
<P>
   As Mexico gears up for its July 2, 2000, presidential election,
Fox is said to be the opposition politician with the best chance
ever to wrestle the presidency away from the PRI. For more than two
years, while he was governor of Mexico's Guanajuato state, Fox
campaigned openly for the presidency on his own. He refused to
succumb to the dictates of old-fashioned politics here and quietly
wait to be anointed by his party _ the National Action Party, or
PAN _ as its candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where half the population lives in poverty, the
pro-business PAN suffers from a reputation for being controlled by
wealthy, socially conservative Catholics. Selected by convention in
September as the party's candidate, Fox is portraying himself as
more of a man of the people. Building on his image as an able
governor who has stood up to the PRI and corruption, Fox is
enhancing his profile with frequent appearances on television talk
shows and near-daily briefings with the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm a businessman,'' he says, talking about his party's
stuffy image. ``I was in Coca-Cola and in my family business. But
I'm also a human being filled with a clear feeling and commitment .
. . to creating equal opportunities for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's talk about ``opportunities'' and his relentless
self-promotion as a distinguished governor who boosted jobs and
investment in Guanajuato touches a nerve in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not for any party, but of the top candidates Fox is the
one I like the best. He works hard and talks about what really
bothers Mexicans,'' said Brenda de la O, 27, a Mexico City nursing
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI still controls millions of voters, Fox admits, but polls
and a number of state election results show that 60 percent of
Mexican voters tend to reject the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Fox is the country's opposition is fragmented
into left- and right-wing camps and other splinter movements. To
win, Fox has to tap into the non-PAN vote and capture at least 20
million voters _ 51 percent of the expected electorate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He's had some setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's opposition parties failed to unite this year in an
alliance that would have presented a ``guaranteed way into the
presidency,'' Fox said. The two main parties, the PAN and the
leftist Democratic Revolution Party managed to overcome their
ideological differences and create a platform.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiations fizzled when Fox and the PAN rejected a
proposal to hold a primary election to pick a single candidate. Fox
feared that the PRD might rig the election to impose their own
candidate, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the former mayor of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Now Fox _ largely because of his own paranoia, critics say _
must compete against the PRI's candidate, former interior secretary
Francisco Labastida, as well as against Cardenas and three other
opposition candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Minimizing the damage, Fox says polls give him hope. A Nov. 3
poll in El Universal newspaper showed Labastida with a 42 percent
preference rate compared to Fox with 41 percent. Cardenas was way
behind at 13 percent. A Green Party candidate was preferred by 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electorate is mature and doesn't want to waste its vote,''
Fox said, predicting that by election day in 2000, voters will
flock to him because he will represent the only hope of defeating
the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now our strategy is to be very universal,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding more like a social democrat than a conservative, Fox
told a group of foreign reporters: ``In Mexico it's more important
to distribute income than to create wealth. And our philosophy in
that area is we need to make sure we distribute opportunities.
We'll have precise, specific, detailed government actions to make
sure we distribute income.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fox also connects with business crowds by sharing the
travails of his family business and his experiences at
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Lately Fox has also appealed to the PAN's ranks by suggesting
that ``moral'' or religious education should be allowed in public
schools, a sensitive topic in Mexico, where civil war was fought
over the power of the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems contradictory and diffuse much of the time,'' said
University of Guanajuato political analyst Luis Miguel Rionda, who
has followed Fox's career. ``But that's what has worked for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox left the governorship earlier this year relatively popular.
Unemployment seems to have declined and investment in the state is
up. It's still too early to measure the impact of Fox's attempts to
boost education in the state from very low levels, according to
Rionda. And Fox's programs to increase farm credit, Rionda added,
appear to have benefited the state's booming export farmers more
than poor farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Rionda said, Fox as governor was adept at wooing
support from all quarters, including local PRI leaders and PRD
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have to count on his personal charm and charisma'' to
repeat that in 2000, Rionda said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the presidential campaign next year will be
publicly financed, raising additional private money to augment
campaign coffers is an Achilles' heel for Fox, said Adolfo Aguilar
Zinser, an independent senator and sometimes Fox advisor.
</P>
<P>
   To conduct the expensive media campaign he plans, Fox has to
compete for donations from business people who are often
intimidated by the PRI, Aguilar said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has consulted with American campaign strategist Dick Morris,
Aguilar added, but after running Coca-Cola Fox is himself ``an
expert at marketing. That's the big difference between him and all
the other candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox admits that he lost at least four or five percentage points
recently in public opinion because of the PRI's first-ever primary
election on Nov. 7. Fox credited the PRI with ``perverse
intelligence'' for holding the primary, which received ample
publicity even though it was self-supervised and riddled with
allegations that the party elite engineered a victory for Labastida
over three other contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons of the PRI's primary, Fox said, are that the ruling
party's political machine is still effective at organizing votes,
whether they are bought with gifts of food or other supplies,
coerced or delivered out of habit. Fox joined Labastida's opponents
in accusing the party of allowing government-controlled union
leaders and party functionaries to steer minions into voting for
Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   The day of the primary, the PAN aired a Fox-inspired television
spot appealing to Mexicans' widespread skepticism of the primary.
</P>
<P>
   After alluding to repeated failed promises of PRI presidents, a
voice asks, ``Do they think that we have no memory? That we could
swallow . . .the same medicine that has hurt us so much? . . . No,
because the majority of Mexicans has woken up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said his aim is to reach Mexico's poor and poorly educated
voters, to convince them to shed their fear of voting for change.
His message, he said, is ``it's better to have a future for them
and their kids . . . than to have a ``torta'' (a sandwich) or a
``dispensa'' (a food package) for their vote in the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, always the pragmatist, noted that in the PRI's primary
about one-third of the nearly 10 million who the party claims voted
cast ballots for Roberto Madrazo, who campaigned for change. Fox
immediately visited Madrazo's home state of Tabasco after the
election, seeking support from those disgruntled voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to line up the popular vote in a massive way,''
Aguilar said. But what's still missing, Aguilar added, is strong
support from the 2 million to 3 million highly educated Mexicans
who shape public opinion and tend to be liberal opposition voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He speaks with a language these people consider frivolous and
unpresidential,'' Aguilar said. ``He is remarkably isolated from
those people.''
</P>
<P>
   VICENTE FOX QUESADA, MEXICAN PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   AGE: 57
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Guanajuato, Mexico; where he was raised on his family
ranch. His English surname comes from an American grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION: Business administration degree from Iberoamericana
University, Mexico City. Management degree from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   PROFESSIONAL: Rose from route supervisor to president of
Coca-Cola in Mexico and Latin America between 1975 and 1979. After
that, ran his family's vegetable export and shoe business.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS: Joined the conservative National Action Party, PAN, in
1988 and elected a federal deputy. Ran for Guanajuato governor in
1991 but lost in an election clouded by fraud. Joined forces with
left opposition to force the election to be annulled and an interim
governor to be appointed. Elected Guanajuato governor in 1995.
Resigned this year to run for president. He was the only candidate
to seek the PAN's nomination at a convention.
</P>
<P>
   PROPOSALS:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Double Mexico's education budget using oil income.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Increase tax revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Negotiate new phase of North American Free Trade Agreement to
include select labor movement.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Increase exports.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Expand credit to entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
