<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0402 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-NAFTA-TRUCKING-HNS &LR;      11-24 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAFTA-TRUCKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN TRUCKS STILL NOT FREE TO TRAVEL U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENALIA MORENO 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ By Jan. 1 Mexican cargo trucks carrying auto parts
were supposed to be traveling as easily between Puebla, Mexico, and
Pontiac, Mich., as U.S. trucks moving plastic pellets from Houston
to Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   But by all indications, such free trade will remain a dream of
NAFTA's framers.
</P>
<P>
   The seamless international border touted during NAFTA
negotiations seems nothing more than rhetoric now as that deadline
opening the border looms just more than a month away and another
deadline has passed us by.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six years after the North American Free Trade Agreement
took effect, international trucking remains the most contentious
promise made by the deal to lower trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   North of the international border with Mexico, Teamsters and
politicians accuse Mexican trucks and their drivers of being
unsafe. Some say they have witnessed Mexican trucks illegally
barreling across U.S. highways as far away as Florida.
</P>
<P>
   South of the border, Mexican truck drivers and politicians
accuse the United States of reneging on its end of the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   International trucking, as proposed by NAFTA drafters, was to
happen in two stages.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1995, Mexican trucks would have been able to travel
within the four border states of Texas, New Mexico, Arizona and
California. Then in 2000, they were to be allowed to bring a
shipment of goods from a point in Mexico to a destination in the
United States, where they would pick up cargo and return to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from Teamsters and citing safety concerns,
President Clinton refused to give Mexican trucking companies
permission to travel within the border states in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to political pressure from Teamsters and other unions,
Clinton likely will not follow through with the second deadline,
continuing to cite safety as a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blatant violation of NAFTA,'' said Ken Hoffman, an
Austin, Texas-based attorney who represents transportation clients
on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico agreed. Politicians there reacted by not allowing
truckers from the United States to travel through its six border
states. Fed up with the lack of response by the United States,
Mexico filed a complaint with a NAFTA dispute resolution panel two
years ago but the panelists have yet to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, international shipments move like this: American
companies deliver their cargo to a warehouse in a U.S. border
community.
</P>
<P>
   Another truck, commonly called a drayage truck, hauls that cargo
to a warehouse on the Mexican side of the border. Then a Mexican
truck hauls those goods south. The drayage truck typically returns
to the United States empty. In Laredo alone, 1.3 million trucks
make that trek annually.
</P>
<P>
   The routine is the same for cargo moving north from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole industry has been built on interchanging loads at the
border,'' said Bill Webb, president of the Texas Motor
Transportation, which represents 1,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Such inefficient movement of goods creates traffic snarls in
border communities such as Laredo, ground zero for the
international border logjam.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA framers hoped to alleviate this traffic tie-up, speed up
the movement of cargo and save shippers millions of dollars a year
in drayage costs by loosening some of the trucking rules.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, the issue has pitted one government against another
and U.S. unions against trucking associations on both sides of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters officials, who did not respond to calls, have cited
recent reports by the U.S. Department of Transportation that
Mexican trucks are unsafe as reasons for their opposition to
opening the border.
</P>
<P>
   The agency reported that more than 250 trucks were found
illegally traveling throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised by the few carriers that they found,'' said
Martin Rojas, director of cross border operations for the
Washington-based American Trucking Association, which represents
3,000 members. ``I would expect that there would be more.''
</P>
<P>
   Other studies conducted by the Transportation Department found
that a shortage of inspectors meant too few Mexican trucks were
inspected and that more than one-third of the trucks that were
inspected at the border were taken out of service due to safety
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of opening the border said these studies look at
drayage trucks, the dreg vehicles of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   If the border were to open, Mexican carriers would send their
best trucks to the United States, said Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in the industry wants to be the one to have a problem
because it's going to get a lot of attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican trucking companies, anticipating the opening of the
border, made significant investments in their fleet but still need
to invest millions of dollars more to bring their trucks up to U.S.
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican trucking officials admit that their fleet of trucks is
inferior to that of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of a Mexican truck is 15 years compared to 5
years for a U.S. truck, said Antonio Vazquez, spokesman for the
Mexican trucking association known by its acronym CANACAR.
</P>
<P>
   The United States ``knew that before they signed NAFTA,'' said
Vazquez. ``They knew the conditions of the Mexican trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as the two sides debate the issue, it's tough to find
someone who said they will take advantage of an open border. Even
CANACAR opposes opening the border because Mexican truck drivers
simply cannot compete with the U.S. industry, which has better
equipment and earns a lower profit margin.
</P>
<P>
   Truckers in the United States are also divided on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``About half of my members would like for (the border) to open
and the other half would like a 60-foot wall to be built around
it,'' said Webb of the Austin-based trucking group.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. trucking companies don't want to send their equipment
farther south than the industrial city of Monterrey because of the
poor road conditions in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``One trip to the lower part of Mexico and back would probably
shake your truck apart,'' said Charlie Alexander, general manager
of International Trucking Co. in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A shortage of truck drivers in the United States also makes
companies wary of sending their workers down to Mexico for even a
few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the border opens tomorrow, nothing is changing tomorrow,''
said James Giermanski, regents professor for Texas A&AMP;M
International University in Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   Giermanski predicts that ongoing negotiations between the two
countries will eventually result in an open border, but he said it
may take years before that will make a significant difference in
the movement of goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will eventually change because there's no excuse for delay
at the border,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1527EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
