<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0404 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-TOY2-HNS &LR;      11-24 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TOY2-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOY STORY 2' IS A MUST-SEE FOR KIDS OF ALL AGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a cynic would say that ``Toy Story 2'' is a mere marketing
tool, an excuse for all the Woodys and Buzzes already rubbing
elbows in toy-store holiday displays across the land. Only a cynic
would question the wisdom of making a sequel to the Pixar company's
ebullient, computer-animated blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   Only a cynic would complain that there's nothing too original in
the sequel, that the characters are familiar, that Randy Newman
didn't write much new music or that the film borrows openly from
``Star Wars'' and ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' and ``Watership Down.''
Only a cynic would get all cranky over the lack of a really foul
villain, or the dearth of True Dramatic Tension.
</P>
<P>
   Ahhh, shuddup already. Let's trash the cynicism, shall we? This
isn't the Brooklyn Museum we're talking about. It's a movie about
playthings _ as Woody says to Buzz in the first film and Buzz says
to Woody in the second, ``You ... are ... a ... TOY!''
</P>
<P>
   He is. They are. And for 83 minutes of ticklish diversion, it's
fun to imagine that a motley roomful of games and dolls could be as
intrepid, and as charming, as this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2'' proves itself as that rare beast of a movie, a
sequel that defies all naysayers. Delightful, funny, warm, less
scary than the original and stuffed with genuinely moving
heart-tuggers, it's simply too sweet a confection to resist.
Grown-ups, take the kids. Kids, take the grown-ups. Grown-ups, take
the grown-ups, or the cockatoo, or something. See it.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the stars of the show are Woody the cowboy (Hanks) and
Buzz Lightyear, the stentorian-voiced space explorer (Tim Allen).
As usual, they while away their days in Andy's bedroom alongside
Mr. Potato Head (Don Rickles), Rex the dinosaur (Wallace Shawn),
Slinky Dog (Jim Varney), Bo Peep (Annie Potts) and Hamm the
loquacious piggy bank (John Ratzenberger).
</P>
<P>
   And, as usual, a malevolent outside force intervenes to separate
the clan, requiring much swashbuckling and plucky innovation before
order is restored.
</P>
<P>
   Last time around the malevolent outside force was Sid, the kid
with the mutant toys. This time it's a nerdish toy collector, a
squishy round man (voiced by Wayne Knight) with a crisp Van Dyke
who snatches Woody and imprisons him behind a Plexiglas display
case in an anonymous urban high-rise. Here Woody learns the truth
about himself.
</P>
<P>
   He's not just a toy but a (gasp) collector's item, a remnant of
a giant Woody craze that swept America in the 1950s. What kitsch
accompanied his rise to fame: the radio! the collector's plates!
the mechanical bank! the yo-yo!
</P>
<P>
   Agog with his own importance, Woody meets his fellow tchotchkes
_ Jessie the Cowgirl (Joan Cusack), Stinky Pete the Prospector
(Kelsey Grammer), Bullseye the Horse _ and bones up on videotapes
of his old Saturday morning television show. But before long he
discovers the dark side to fame, and it takes some heavy
soul-searching before he's back to his usual chipper self.
</P>
<P>
   It also takes some gymnastic bluster on the part of Buzz, who
leads a fivesome of plucky toys on an obstacle-fraught urban rescue
mission. Some of this involves elevators; some of it involves
jaywalking; some of it involves motoring down the aisles of a
massive toy store, where grooving Barbies party to surf rock and
Buzz encounters shelf after shelf of doppelgangers (``Am I really
that fat?'' he asks).
</P>
<P>
   Not to spoil any of this, but the climax is a winner _ exciting
without resorting to the let's-explode-Planet-Earth cliches of
rampant overproduction. Despite the detailed computer animation,
``Toy Story 2,'' like ``Toy Story'' and Pixar's interim feature,
``A Bug's Life,'' is more dependent on story and character than on
filmic gimmickry. (The film credits numerous writers and directors,
including John Lasseter, who directed the original.)
</P>
<P>
   It works because it is, ultimately, a film about the perils and
joys of friendship. As Stinky Pete says, ``It's a dangerous world
out there for a toy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
