<HEADER>
A0407 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GIANT-MARTINI-HNS &LR;      11-24 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANT-MARTINI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS LEADERS ARE SHAKEN BY GIANT MARTINI AT NEW YEAR SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RYAN KIM  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As thousands of worshipers gather on New Year's
Eve in Union Square to sing songs, recite poetry and welcome the
new millennium with piety and reflection, a seven-story martini
glass will tower above them, ready to drop an enormous olive at the
stroke of midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Although this pairing of the secular and the spiritual has some
leaders of the interfaith worship shaken and stirred, organizers of
each event are unwilling to change their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope we wouldn't have that type of a distraction,''
the Rev. Cecil Williams of Glide Memorial Church said of the
martini glass. ``It is not consistent with what we're trying to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, contend that the two events are a perfect
example of San Francisco's eccentricities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time San Francisco got some positive attention for our
lifestyle, which is diversity, and if that includes martinis, so be
it,'' said Marsha Monro, director of marketing and communications
for the Westin St. Francis Hotel, where the martini glass will be
installed. ``This is an `only in San Francisco' thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Union Square spiritual celebration is one of two
city-organized New Year's Eve events.
</P>
<P>
   The martini glass will sit atop the 13th floor of the St.
Francis, which fronts the west side of Union Square. The glass will
be an inflatable light blue structure constructed around one of the
hotel flagpoles.
</P>
<P>
   Protruding out of the glass will be a swizzle stick with a
10-foot olive, which will slide down at midnight. The drop of the
olive will be accompanied by a pyrotechnic and fireworks. Monro
said the $250,000 display will be San Francisco's answer to New
York's Times Square celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our entire intent is to promote the West Coast'' Monro said.
``If New York can be known as the Big Apple, why can't we be called
the Big Olive?''
</P>
<P>
   The martini drink, according to legend, was created in Martinez
about 150 years ago during the California Gold Rush. But some
insist it was San Francisco that popularized the aperitif. For
years, the 98-year-old St. Francis has been home to the city's
largest martini, and the hotel plans to serve a 48-ounce millennium
martini.
</P>
<P>
   The interfaith peace service is being produced by the mayor's
office, members of religious groups and merchants.
</P>
<P>
   The event will begin at 10 p.m. with drummers and includes
poetry readings, moments of prayer, words from clergy and a
performance by 110-voice musical ensemble of the Glide Memorial
Church, a United Methodist congregation. Williams is scheduled to
lead the crowd in ``Auld Lang Syne'' at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Semel, executive vice chairwoman of San Francisco's
Interfaith Council, said that if she had her way, the martini glass
would be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service is more of a looking forward to next year in a
more spiritual and thoughtful way,'' Semel said. ``I don't think
the martini glass will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some religious leaders have questioned what kind of reception
the martini glass will receive.
</P>
<P>
   The peace service will require tickets, which are free and will
be distributed through churches and stores. Williams expects that
most of the people on the square will be there to worship, not
party. He said he would urge people to focus their attention and
not be distracted by the olive.
</P>
<P>
   Monro admits that not all those on the square will turn their
gaze to the hotel rooftop. But she said the olive drop and
fireworks will be there for anyone who chooses to look up and will
be designed to not overpower the proceedings below.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials are downplaying potential conflicts, saying the
two events are in keeping with San Francisco's eclectic reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is a very diverse community,'' said Martha
Cohen, special assistant to Mayor Willie Brown Cohen. ``We can work
with whatever happens in Union Square.''
</P>
<P>
   The martini glass will be erected during the two weeks leading
up to New Year's Eve. Hotel officials say they expect to make the
martini glass a tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the West Coast deserves some notoriety,'' Monro said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
