<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0413 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BAXTER25-COLUMN-COX     11-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER25-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abundance vs. need is next big moral issue
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a benchmark for the unfolding presidential race, the most
interesting speech delivered during this Thanksgiving season was
not by any of the candidates but a utility executive, J. Wayne
Leonard, CEO of New Orleans-based Entergy Corp.
</P>
<P>
   His company, which provides electricity to parts of Louisiana,
Mississippi, Arkansas and Texas, has been ``insensitive, if not
harsh'' in its bill collecting and shut-off policies, Leonard said
Friday at a ``Low Income Summit'' organized by the utility.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are now past, he declared. This Christmas, if
customers can't buy their children presents and pay their electric
bill, they can just call in and the company will work things out
after the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The poor are more numerous than the government admits, he said,
and worse off than they were 20 years ago. And a mean-spirited
society is ``demonizing the poor in the most shameless way
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fighting a war we claim to be on the undeserving, the
lazy, the immoral. But, fact is, it's largely a war fought against
children and the disabled,'' said Leonard, who announced a list of
company initiatives to help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard became more interested in the plight of his poorer
customers after accompanying President Clinton on his New Market
Initiatives tour of the Delta region last July, according to
company spokeswoman Carol Clawson.
</P>
<P>
   There's a man-bites-dog quality to a utility executive telling
people not to worry overmuch about their bills, but there may also
be some business logic at play as well.
</P>
<P>
   Texas and Arkansas have already passed legislation opening
electric utilities to competition, and some of the areas served by
Entergy are among the poorest in the country. In the company's
service area, residential customers who struggle to pay their bills
may be a more enduring base than industries that move away.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not Leonard's motives that are important here, but the
way his remarks frame the political debate that begins in earnest
after the cranberry sauce is put away.
</P>
<P>
   This presidential campaign is about the politics of abundance _
both our impatience to share in it and our nervousness about what
it masks.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard would have no basis for his comments if the plight of
low-income citizens weren't a lot worse than portrayed this year on
the presidential campaign trail _ and in his service area, it is.
But it's also likely he wouldn't be able to cut his customers such
slack were it not for the era of falling costs and rising profits
American business has been enjoying.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the candidates attempt in one way or another to address
how to use the current largess to rectify our shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time, when the sun is shining, to fix our roof, not
to wait until a rainy day,'' former Sen. Bill Bradley told voters
last week at the United Jewish Federations conference in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk about divvying up the budget surplus,
Republican Gary Bauer said Tuesday, ``I'm not sure that's getting
at what most people are worried about. They want to know why so
many terrible things seem to be happening in a country that has so
much wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later the poor have to pay their electric bills, but
they don't have to vote. None of the candidates would address the
country's problems in the stark terms Leonard did. But the
conditions that make such a remarkable speech possible set the
terms for the race ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
