A0414 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-PINETOPS-COX     11-24 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINETOPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thanksgiving a mixed blessing in flood-ravaged North Carolina.
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINETOPS, N.C. _ Hip deep in Hurricane Floyd's flood waters
surging through her living room, Rosa Dickens got scared when she
saw a pallet of hay floating down the street. Next came metal gas
tanks, refrigerators and hot water heaters bobbing along in the
stinky black swell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have been floating, too,'' said Dickens, 59. ``I thank
God for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months after the state's worst natural disaster killed 51
people, including seven here in Pinetops, Thanksgiving comes as a
mixed blessing across flood-ravaged eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Thankful to be alive, tens of thousands who were displaced from
their homes are still grappling with the tedious, heart-wrenching
rebuilding of lives, forever changed by Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The rising waters washed away homes, cars and keepsakes passed
from generation to generation. The recovery is testing the resolve
and patience of people who had expected, as they always had, to
gather with kinfolk around the table for Thanksgiving meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am taking one day at a time,'' Dickens told nearly 400
people who gathered Tuesday night in a Pinetops schoolhouse for a
Thanksgiving service. Preachers reading from Lamentations and
Romans spoke of hope amid the misery. Testimonials from victims
offered thanks for donations and volunteer work crews who've helped
in several neighborhoods washed over by Town Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it takes a crisis to bring us together,'' said the
Rev. Robert Williams, 49, pastor of two local Baptist churches, St.
Luke and Washington Branch Missionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I lost everything_my cars, my house_I did not lose
my life,'' he told the crowd offering ``amens'' in approval. ``I
did not lose my soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the stress brought by Floyd's deluge in mid-September is
hard for many to shake.
</P>
<P>
   Across this hardscrabble region where farming communities have
struggled for years, people are trying to recover from devastation
few ever imagined. Despite the flood of government, church and
charitable aid, expected to top $6 billion, people are missing the
familiar rhythms of the holidays, something money can't buy.
</P>
<P>
   In community after community, from Conetoe to Comfort to
Chinquapin, residents are months from returning to homes they built
decades ago. The few who've had the energy to strip their houses
down to the bare wooden studs can't yet rebuild because of
lingering moisture and mold.
</P>
<P>
   In Princeville, a town founded by freed slaves after the Civil
War, a flood-ruined mobile home collapsed recently as it was being
hauled away on a tractor trailer.
</P>
<P>
   It was a symbolic mishap for North Carolina's tattered eastern
half, where the receding waters left behind debris hanging on limbs
and fences. Uprooted trees point in the direction of the deadly
currents of the Tar, Neuse and Cape Fear rivers and their hundreds
of tributaries, which turned the swampy coastal plain into a lake.
</P>
<P>
   A muddy residue clings to the walls of abandoned houses and
buildings, marking the seemingly unfathomable levels to which the
water rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still living in holy hell,'' said Marie Randolph, 54,
of Pinetops, a two-stoplight town of 1,500 people 60 miles east of
Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Many victims are living temporarily with relatives and friends,
in apartments and motels, and in camper trailers where today's
Thanksgiving meals of cooked turkey and canned cranberry sauce will
be delivered in cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   People are wearing clothes they didn't own just weeks ago,
hand-me-downs or new garments among the tons of donations from
across America. The generosity is wearing thin, though, among
people frustrated by the slow pace of government loans and grants,
money that will provide only part of what they need to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a whole lot of turn-downs and a whole lot of nos
and a whole lot of false hopes,'' said Maryanne Staton, 36, an
evacuee from flood-ruined Princeville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't describe it,'' said Staton, now living in Rocky Mount,
in a government camper park dubbed Camp Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to Princeville Tuesday to pick up a free turkey
from a truck stop parking lot where Princeville officials are
distributing canned food and toiletries and baby food from under
two green military tents.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for a free turkey, William Henry Bridges drove down from
nearby Oak City. But because he doesn't live in Princeville, he
wasn't eligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``As old as I am and as hard as I worked, it's a pity I can't
even get a turkey,'' said the 84-year-old farmer, sorting through
clothing piled in the truck stop's muddy parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina suffered its own setback this week. Congress
adjourned for the year Monday, after approving less than half the
$1.9 billion in federal aid sought by Gov. Jim Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The new appropriation is on top of $500 million the government
has already sent to North Carolina, aid that Hunt called a ``real
step forward,'' but not enough to rebuild the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on Congress,'' North Carolina Agriculture Commissioner
Jim Graham said. ``The monies they seem to be offering are a
Band-Aid, when we need transplant surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   But here in Pinetops, a fellowship of black and white ministers
has taken on the task of providing relief. It organized Tuesday
night's religious service, part of efforts to provide spiritual
help to victims along with the canned goods, clothing and shoes
dispensed from the old F&AMP;T hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Owens, who pastors three Presbyterian church with his wife,
Peggy, travels frequently back into the flooded neighborhoods of
Dodge City and Bynum Park. Ghost towns, the subdivisions are slowly
coming back to life as residents rip out water-soaked cabinets and
carpet and pile it on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, 43, listens more than he talks in visits with victims.
They need help contacting federal agencies, buying used cars,
arranging for volunteers to help rip out their houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being there with words of compassion and expressions of
sympathy,'' Owens said. ``These people need the strength to move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1533EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0415 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-GLOBALGREEN-COX     11-24 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBALGREEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Green' allies aim to topple walls between humans, environment
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The names might not be household words.
</P>
<P>
   But the leadership of Green Cross International and its American
affiliate, Global Green USA, seems determined that the
organizations will be real players in enhancing the world's
environment.
</P>
<P>
   The most important of those leaders is the founder, Mikhail
Gorbachev, the 68-year-old former leader of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are we mutually interdependent with others _ no one
nation alone can tackle pollution in the seas or warming of the
atmosphere _ but future generations are dependent on how we use the
planet today,'' Gorbachev said in a recent interview, posted on the
GCI Web site.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of desertification taking over vital farmlands, a
looming fresh water crisis, air pollution threatening the health of
billions in megacities, among other problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``To meet that challenge, we need to change our mentality just
as we did to end the Cold War,'' Gorbachev said. ``We need to take
down the wall that separates the future from the present.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev probably will reiterate those themes when he speaks
Dec. 3 at the University of Georgia. He is sure to stress them when
he speaks at Global Green USA's annual Legacy Forum at Georgia
State University the following day.
</P>
<P>
   The former Soviet president's commitment to the environment is
the principal inspiration behind the founding of GCI. And,
according to Matt Petersen, executive director of Global Green,
Gorbachev is ``absolutely'' sincere on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen first met Gorbachev in 1994 and ``was immediately blown
away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Gorbachev was that this man's soul comes
through his eyes,'' Petersen said. ``I think that's what makes him
such a forceful presence.''
</P>
<P>
   However, inspired leadership is one thing. Practical building of
programs is another. Petersen said the progress of the organization
on that score has been incremental.
</P>
<P>
   GCI was founded in 1993 to build on goals established at the
1992 Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. Its mission broadly is
to ``help create a sustainable future by cultivating harmonious
relationships between humans and the environment'' and to ``promote
a significant change in human values leading to greater respect and
care for Earth's community of life in all its diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples of ways the group is trying to accomplish that mission
include:
</P>
<P>
   Helping draft an Earth Charter, intended to serve as a universal
code of conduct on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Examining the environmental legacy of wars and advocating
solutions to lingering problems, including clean-up of former
military bases and environmentally responsible destruction of
chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting informed decision making on water management.
</P>
<P>
   Disseminating information about ways to design energy-efficient
housing and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Developing educational materials on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding, the Swiss-based organization has developed
country affiliates in 21 nations, including Global Green in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Global Green's programs parallel the international
organization's and focus on cleaning up the environmental damage of
the Cold War, fostering the design of energy-efficient housing and
advocating alternative energy development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't litigate and we don't protest. Those are important
things that environmental organizations do,'' Petersen said. But
Global Green's mission is more of being a ``mediator and
catalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We bring people together,'' the executive director explained.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has deliberately taken its programs ``outside
the Beltway'' of Washington by establishing its headquarters in
Santa Monica, Calif., and sponsoring events in such cities as
Atlanta and Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda for the forum at GSU, on the theme ``Sustainability
in the Southeast,'' reflects the group's aims. Guests from the
military, business and government agencies as well as environmental
activists will come together to discuss such topics as renewable
energy, ``smart growth'' and the destruction of chemical weapons in
the United States and Russia. Georgia State's J. Mack Robinson
School of Business is the official host for the event, and the U.S.
Army's Environmental Policy Institute is a co-organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen expects 150 to 250 people to attend the two-day
conference, which also will feature Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson, but the crowd could more than double when Gorbachev
speaks to an afternoon session Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Others will come to hear the man whose efforts led to a new era
of freedom for people behind the Iron Curtain later that evening
when he speaks at Global Green's Founder's Award dinner at the Ritz
Carlton Buckhead. Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes is to introduce
Gorbachev, and Sen. Max Cleland also is expected to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The event will pay tribute to Pat Mitchell, president of CNN
Productions/Time Inc. Television.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's presence in Atlanta is the most important reason
Gorbachev is making both the Athens and Atlanta appearances. She is
a University of Georgia graduate and won a Peabody award for an
acclaimed television series on the Cold War. She also is president
of Global Green and has overseen production of nearly 200 hours of
environmental programming for the Turner networks.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen said Gorbachev and Mitchell have worked closely
together, and that the former Soviet leader was especially touched
when Mitchell came to the funeral of his wife, Raisa, in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really meant a lot to him that she came,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
