<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT 103 VICTIMS ARE HONORED IN NATIONAL CEMETERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Who put up the monument erected for victims of Pan Am Flight
103, which crashed in Lockerbie, Scotland? _ J.F.G., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: A memorial cairn honoring the 270 victims of the Flight 103
bombing was placed at Arlington National Cemetery by order of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   After Scotland donated the stone cairn to the United States,
Senate Joint Resolution 129 in 1993 placed it at a spot that
couldn't be used for grave sites. Some military organizations
opposed the use of Arlington to honor non-veterans and
non-Americans, but the bill passed both houses on voice votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terrorist bombing of Flight 103 was unquestionably an
attack on the United States,'' SJR 129 states.
</P>
<P>
   Libyan intelligence officers Abdelbaset Ali Mohmed al-Megrahi
and Al-Amin Khalifah Fhimah have been indicted on charges of murder
and conspiracy in the Dec. 21, 1988, bombing. Their trial, which
will be conducted by Scotland at a Dutch military base, is expected
to begin in February.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My 73-year-old mother is an avid fan of Stevie Ray Vaughan.
Her birthday is coming up. Where can I find a source of Vaughan
T-shirts and other memorabilia? _ H.W., Crowley, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: You can find Vaughan memorabilia at Pepperland, a Grapevine
Mills Mall store that also has a shop on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperland sells nine Vaughan T-shirts and hats, jackets, CDs,
autographs and other items. A catalog is available on the World
Wide Web at www.srvcatalog.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Grapevine Mills store also sells memorabilia devoted to the
Beatles, the Grateful Dead, Jimi Hendrix, Led Zeppelin and other
musicians. For more information, call (972) 724-3399.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the name of the movie where Robert Reed played a
businessman who had a sick urge to call Arlene Golonka and say foul
and obscene words? _ J.C.B., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: That's the 1975 made-for-TV movie ``Secret Night Caller,''
which also starred Hope Lange and Robin Mattson.
</P>
<P>
   No video copies turned up for ``Caller,'' one of many TV films
produced by Charles Fries during the '70s and '80s.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
