<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0424 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-KHRIPUNOV-COX     11-24 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KHRIPUNOV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Soviet diplomat idolizes Gorbachev
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Igor Khripunov has great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev is coming to Athens
next week, and Khripunov looks forward to hearing a man he respects
deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the audience for the Dec. 3 speech at the University of
Georgia will be hearing Gorbachev for the first time. Not
Khripunov. The associate director of the university's Center for
International Trade and Security is a Moscow native. He's also a
former Soviet diplomat. And he vividly remembers the occasions when
his work brought him into close contact with the leader who did
more than anyone to end totalitarianism in the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gorbachev was quite a different breed of person,'' the UGA
political scientist said. ``His biggest contribution was to say no
to the Cold War and to open up the country to democratic reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Khripunov worked as an interpreter at the United
Nations in New York, a taste of America that introduced him to a
more open society. He returned to the Soviet Union in 1976 to earn
a doctorate in a topic some of his friends still find puzzling,
Canadian foreign policy. But Khripunov, now 53, soon found a niche
he thought might be more useful. He sold all his books on Canada
and began transforming himself into an expert on a new topic: arms
control.
</P>
<P>
   He was working on arms issues for the Soviet Ministry of Foreign
Affairs when he first met Gorbachev, then the second ranking person
in the Communist Party. The year was 1984. And the rising young
diplomat had been picked to accompany Gorbachev and his wife,
Raisa, on a trip to Maggie Thatcher's London.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met him, that was a couple of days before this
delegation left for London,'' recalled Khripunov.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the meeting vividly: ``Gorbachev was technically in
charge of agriculture, but when we arrived at his office, in the
headquarters of the Communist Party, for the briefing before
departure, he talked without any notes for an hour about his vision
of Soviet foreign policy relationships and the world situation. I
was amazed by his intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   During the trip, Gorbachev was armed with written comments, even
for the toasts he was to make, but he didn't use them, impressing
not only the young diplomat accompanying him but also his British
hosts with his spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   Khripunov met Gorbachev on other occasions over the years, but
the most memorable came in 1987, when the Gorbachevs made a
historic visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Khripunov was working at the Soviet Union's U.S.
Embassy and had gained even deeper respect for Gorbachev as a
leader who was committed to the idea of a world free of nuclear
weapons. On that visit, Gorbachev again demonstrated that he was a
new kind of Soviet leader, stopping his car and getting out to
shake hands with Americans on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   But the trip was not just about style. There was also substance,
as Gorbachev and President Ronald Reagan signed a treaty
eliminating intermediate range nuclear missiles from Europe.
Khripunov had been involved in negotiating the agreement, and he
was later assigned to help implement it.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, of course, went on to implement something else, major
democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, Khripunov applauded those reforms. That's not to
say the transition has been easy.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet Embassy where Khripunov worked evolved into a Russian
Embassy, and the diplomats there felt rudderless as the old empire
disintegrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly speaking, losing a country to which you are supposed
to be loyal and which you served throughout all your career is
destabilizing,'' Khripunov admitted.
</P>
<P>
   But he also recalled the great hopes of the era: ``There was a
lot of enthusiasm that democracy and the end of communism may
really spell new prosperity and a new future.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for Russians, the prosperity has not
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   As an arms control expert, Khripunov frets about the weapons and
other dangerous materials still found in the old Soviet empire. He
came to the University of Georgia largely because its Center for
International Trade and Security was working on nonproliferation
issues. And he has been involved in the center's programs including
one recently started to train managers of nuclear facilities in the
old Soviet Union to protect and control potentially dangerous
materials. But the struggle to ensure that the proper procedures
are used is thorny. Corruption in Russia and the disastrous
economic situation are major complicating factors.
</P>
<P>
   Had the West lived up to Gorbachev's expectations as communism
was collapsing, the situation might be better.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev had ``expected deep in his mind a kind of second
Marshall Plan for Russia,'' Khripunov explained.
</P>
<P>
   The West has poured a lot of money into the Soviet republics but
has not put in place the hands-on programs that might have been
more help
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
