<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0433 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CHECHNYA-TANKS-YELTSI     11-24 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-TANKS-YELTSIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN NEEDS TO DO MORE THAN `STAND UP ON THAT TANK' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By PAVEL PALAZCHENKO  
 c.1999 Metro International, Helsinki  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   What an unenviable task for President Clinton and his policy
planners _ to assess the West's options for responding to Russia's
relentless military campaign in Chechnya. It is as if all the
contradictions and inconsistencies of Western and particularly U.S.
post-Cold War policies have merged into one big international
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the scale of the tragedy unfolding in Northern
Caucasus, the loss of life and destruction, is similar to if not
worse than what happened in Bosnia and, more recently, in Kosovo.
Yet the West's outrage is muted and its morality-driven willingness
to act, so evident in Kosovo, is now absent.
</P>
<P>
   The military option, which the United States and NATO used so
willingly against Yugoslavia, is simply out of the question when
dealing with Russia, a nuclear power. Thus, ``the Clinton doctrine
of humanitarian intervention,'' tentatively proclaimed during the
Kosovo crisis, has been shown to be at best selective _ a policy
that can be modified opportunistically depending on other
priorities and on U.S. military capabilities vis-a-vis the current
transgressor.
</P>
<P>
   Economic or financial penalties do not fare much better.
Although Russia would like to get some money from the International
Monetary Fund _ whose lending decisions take account of political,
military and economic travails _ the West is reluctant even to call
for the IMF to withhold the next tranche of its Russian loan.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the loan is meant to repay previous IMF handouts.
What is more, failure to provide it could upset the entire
structure of delicate debt rescheduling compromises between Russia
and Western public and private financial institutions _ something
the West clearly does not want.
</P>
<P>
   Given the anti-Western sentiment now prevailing in Russian
politics and, increasingly, among the people, economic sanctions
would be counterproductive. With its oil and gas prices to foreign
clients at their highest level in years, Russia could for a while
do without the IMF money, and many Russians would just say good
riddance.
</P>
<P>
   And as for longer-term consequences, people don't think about
them in the heat of recriminations that are, more and more,
beginning to resemble the time of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia's offensive in Chechnya was just beginning, there
was talk in the West of using the summit of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe, held last week in Istanbul, to
call Russia to account and make it change its behavior. But both
before and during the summit, it became increasingly clear that
little could be achieved there.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Yeltsin's sharp rebuttal of any attempt to ``interfere in
Russia's internal affairs'' was to be expected. Perhaps Bill
Clinton had hoped that praising the Russian president, for the
umpteenth time, for ``standing on that tank'' and thus thwarting
the hard-line coup in August 1991 would sway him in the right
direction. But this is a situation where a compliment is as
ineffective as a threat would be. To some, it looked awkward; to
others, pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the OSCE is a weak organization and thus not the
best vehicle for meaningful policy initiatives. Even if better
avenues were available for the West's pressure tactics, though, the
result would likely be the same. For Russia can only be influenced
by countries it sees as friendly and that it feels treat it with
respect. And that is where the problem lies.
</P>
<P>
   It is amazing how quickly the reservoir of good will and
apparent mutual respect that Russia and the United States shared in
the early '90s disappeared during the past few years. It takes two
to tango, and it takes at least two to break up the dance _ so, of
course, Moscow should take part of the blame for the relationship
turning sour. But try to look at it from Russia's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus there is that for years America was rather
cynically using Russia for its own political purposes. A recent
indiscretion _ remarks by a ``senior administration official''
reported by Jane Perlez in The New York Times _ illustrates just
the sort of attitude Russians dread _ and why that may be more than
just paranoia. As regards NATO expansion and Kosovo, the U.S.
official rather arrogantly staid, ``we knew what the Russians ought
to do and, by the way, they did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they ``did it'' _ Russia had to put up both with NATO's
enlargement and the bombing of Yugoslavia, but only a very naive
person could think that such humiliation would leave no scars. For
the Russians, the bottom line is that they ``got no respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Russians generals and politicians keep pointing out that what
the United States and NATO did in a foreign country, Russia has a
right to do in its own Chechen territory. They invoke the pretext
of fighting international terrorism, reminding the world of U.S.
cruise-missile attacks on Osama bin Laden's ``terrorist camps'' in
Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   There is much self-serving hypocrisy in these arguments but it
cannot be denied that Clinton's administration has been much more
willing than some of its predecessors to use force abroad under
very flimsy pretexts and without much regard for international law.
</P>
<P>
   The administration should therefore not be surprised that it has
lost credibility in Moscow and that many people there and elsewhere
see much of its foreign policy as based on a cynical double
standard. In fact, both Russia, a former superpower, and the United
States, the sole remaining superpower, are arguably guilty of what
that famous Communist icon Karl Marx called ``the greatest of human
vices, hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a good basis on which to build a new world order _ or even a
good bilateral partnership.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Pavel Palazchenko is the author of ``My Years With Gorbachev
and Shevardnadze: The Memoir of a Soviet Interpreter'' (1997). His
columns have appeared in Moscow News; Metro International,
Helsinki, and other publications. During the Cold War, he published
commentary under the pen name, ``P. Vorobyev.'' He currently
teaches Russian language and contemporary politics at Colgate
University; he has also taught at Moscow Linguistic University.
From 1980 to 1991 he served in the Russian Foreign Ministry, before
which he was an interpreter with the United Nations in New York. He
is still the chief translator and personal adviser to Mikhail
Gorbachev, the last president of the Soviet Union.) &LR;
</P>
