<HEADER>
A0435 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-OVERSEAS-SHOPPING     11-24 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-OVERSEAS-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING CARE (USE PLASTIC) OF FOREIGN SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are a few things I know about the raw-milk camembert cheese
that a French company called Fromages.com sells online. First, milk
is ladled carefully into vats. Then it matures into creamy yellow
rounds that get coddled, like newborns in a hospital nursery, until
at the age of 21 days they reach the peak of taste.
</P>
<P>
   Now we get to one important thing I do not know: how that peak
tastes. That is because raw-milk cheeses that mature in less than
60 days may harbor dangerous bacteria; they are illegal in the
United States. So American shoppers who arrive at www.fromages.com
are steered instead to a truncated list of federally approved
cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   As for the list, the Roquefort, the Saint-Marcellin and the
Reblochon sounded fine _ like the camemberts, they are stored in a
temperature-controlled cellar until ready to eat, then shipped
overnight to customers around the world. But the site's soulful
descriptions of 116 cheeses convinced me that I wanted nothing less
than the distinctively runny camembert, ripened ``to the very
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   So I phoned Marc Refabert, the director of Fromages.com. But he
said, quite simply: ``I am very sad that I cannot send it. To my
point of view, for the person who does not have the chance to have
this cheese, it's a pity.''
</P>
<P>
   If he had not rubbed it in like that, my initial response might
have been more graceful. In any case, I would like the record to
show that any subsequent comments I might have made along the lines
of ``Listen, Refabert, who would it hurt if you just shipped me one
little bite?'' were entirely in jest.
</P>
<P>
   I changed my mind anyway, after I phoned the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration, where a spokesman told me that the listeria
bacteria in contaminated raw-milk products kills 425 people a year
in the United States. Resigned to a healthy fate, I returned to
Fromages.com to instead order a (legal) camembert made from
pasteurized milk.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for my cheese, I had time to reflect on the fact that
this is just one of the many compromises that American shoppers are
going to have to make as a growing number of overseas merchants go
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of countries are rushing to catch up to where the United
States is in e-commerce, and that means that shoppers are going to
run into this more and more,'' said Bob Laity, an Andersen
Consulting managing partner who advises overseas Web sites. ``If
you saw a nice ivory bracelet on a French Web site, would you know
that it is illegal to import? What about a product that is
classified as food in one country, but as drugs in another?''
</P>
<P>
   The simplest answer is that if you question a product's
legality, don't buy it. While government officials acknowledged in
interviews last week that they simply cannot inspect every single
parcel, the last thing you want is to be the unlucky shopper whose
shipment of fresh meat or endangered species of plants or Cuban
cigars is seized on the docks. I cannot even begin to contemplate
the headache involved with trying to get a refund for that.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you need any sort of customer service _ if you want
to return a damaged item, if you have questions about shipping or
import tariffs _ you can expect problems, Laity said. ``The United
States as a country is way ahead on customer service, so if you are
buying overseas, anticipate difficulties if everything is not all
right with the purchase. How do you straighten it out, when the
dot-coms in Europe don't come from an environment where customer
service is as widely considered important?''
</P>
<P>
   One way to protect yourself is to pay by credit card; you can
always dispute the charge. Even better, some overseas Web sites
will calculate your credit card payment in United States dollars.
For instance, at www.chinesejade.com (a jeweler headquartered in
Hong Kong), www.aviapress.com (a Russian seller of aviation-related
books) and www.indiagiftcenter.com (in India), buyers make credit
card payments through CCNow of Delaware, which processes credit
card transactions for about 7,000 merchants, 30 percent of whom are
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   That method worked well for me when I recently bought a poster
from a Hong Kong art dealer who happened to be a CCNow client. The
seller calculated a final price (including shipping costs) in
dollars and informed me that no duty was owed. (A U.S. Customs
spokesman told me that duty is assessed on purchases over $100
unless they fall into such duty-free categories as books, antiques
or paintings.) As soon as CCNow processed the $15 transaction, the
seller mailed me the poster.
</P>
<P>
   I still do not know how much my cheese will cost me, however.
Fromages.com estimated that the total, 455 francs, would be about
$63. However, when I phoned American Express two days later to find
out how much my account actually was charged (currency exchange
rates can fluctuate several times in the course of a single day), I
learned the transaction had not been posted _ and might not be for
up to 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the cheese itself arrived much sooner, lovingly wrapped
in protective silver foil and nestled in a bed of torn paper
strips. The camembert was delicious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
