<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR THANKSGIVING DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (A graphic of these matchups has been sent electronically to NYT
graphics clients. Call 888-603-1036 for information.) 
(jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago (5-6) vs. Detroit (6-4) (12 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that Chicago leads the NFC in passing offense,
averaging 263.9 yards per game? The Bears use multiple
wide-receiver sets but most frequently gets the ball into the hands
of Bobby Engram, who has caught 56 passes. Quarterback Jim Miller
owns an 82.3 passer rating for the season and in his last two games
a 107.7 rating, both overtime affairs that the Bears split. Charlie
Batch returns at quarterback for Detroit and expect him to shine.
Look for receiver Germane Crowell (16.8 average yards gained per
catch) to make big plays. And the Detroit defense, allowing an
average of only 87.7 rushing yards per game, will control the
Bears. Detroit has lost two straight but rights itself for a sprint
toward the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Lions, 26-10.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (8-2) vs. Dallas (5-5) (4 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Here comes Jimmy Johnson back to Texas Stadium for the first
time in six years. He left in a huff, wound up in Miami and now
faces many of the players he drafted and coached. Dallas expects an
intense fight from Johnson and his new players. And the Cowboys
will be prepared. Watch Emmitt Smith. He needs 125 rushing yards to
join Barry Sanders as the only players in league history to rush
for nine consecutive 1,000-yard seasons (Sanders had 10 seasons).
Miami enters with the better defense, Dallas with the better
offense. Dan Marino hopes to play, Troy Aikman will. It will be a
festive game full of big hits and big plays but Dallas will make
more of them.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys, 19-17.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
