<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-200125-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dr. Dre's latest a welcome return but no landmark
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The much-reported story goes something like this: Prolific rap
producer Dr. Dre was sitting around the manse one day when his wife
just got tired of seeing him sit there. Get up and do something,
she insisted, and make sure it's not some record you're dancing in
tuxedos to, like in that corny ``Been There, Done That'' video.
</P>
<P>
   So being the obedient husband that he is, the architect of some
of the most offensive music made, obliged. The result is his
anticipated follow-up to the best gangster rap album ever, 1992's
``The Chronic.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife should be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chronic 2001'' soundly repositions Dr. Dre as one of the
music's most inventive producers with a keyboard. Profanities and
graphic depictions of sex (``(Expletive) You'') and violence (``The
Car Bomb'') are, once again, made as innocuous and melodic as a
jingle for a cereal commercial. And the starched khakis and tennis
shoes are back on one of the best offerings here, ``Still D.R.E.''
</P>
<P>
   Rap fans, however, may not be pacified. Unlike ``The Chronic''_
a project on which Dr. Dre created tracks for then-newcomers such
as Snoop Doggy Dogg _ on this album Dre takes the microphone a lot
more. And while he's a better writer offering a believable
perspective of life as an aging ``gangster,'' he's only
occasionally compelling. ``Chronic 2001'' isn't the singular,
cohesive pronouncement of gangster rap's merit that ``The Chronic''
was. It's just a welcome comeback with some good singles.
</P>
<P>
   RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Chronic 2001''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dre. Aftermath /Interscope Records. 22 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
