<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BECK25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Superb weirdness from a pop savant
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It must be beautiful and frightening inside Beck Hansen's head.
What sort of twisted psyche drives this 29-year-old pop savant, who
alchemizes seemingly incompatible musical references into groove
collages that are at once hilarious, seductive and deeply weird?
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Sexx Laws,'' the first track on the ``official''
follow-up to his groundbreaking 1996 release ``Odelay.'' (Last
year's slight, stripped-down ``Mutations'' was deemed a career
sidestep.) The song hits the ground swinging to a horn-driven,
``Austin Powers'' beat, only to be rudely interrupted by a banjo
solo.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Deliverance'' interlude is just the first of myriad
funhouse surprises. More down-and-dirty than ``Odelay,'' both in
subject matter and groove execution, ``Midnite Vultures'' gives
props to a host of funk and pop icons in its scattershot search for
the perfect sex beat. ``Nicotine &AMP; Gravy'' evokes Sly Stone by way
of Parliament. ``Get Real Paid'' pits Prince against Kraftwerk in a
bloodless death match.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the lyrics are a white-water ride through the
subconscious. ``People look so snooty/Take pills make them
moody/Automatic bzooty/Zero to tutti frutti,'' Beck raps on
``Hollywood Freaks,'' conjuring, in his patented wacked-out way,
the vivid surreality of La-La Land.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end, ``Midnite Vultures'' temporarily abandons its
transcendental funk-party vibe, retreating into the
modified-Beatles musings heard on ``Mutations.'' But Beck dons the
velvet soul-man suit one more time on the final track. ``Debra'' is
a dead-on, between-the-sheets '70s R&AMP;B number that finds the singer
crooning _ in perfect falsetto _ to a would-be lover: ``I want to
get with you/and your sister/I think her name's Debra.'' Like all
of Beck's best work, it's so good it's scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midnite Vultures''
</P>
<P>
   Beck. DGC.
</P>
<P>
   11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
