<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONBOARD MODEMS WILL LET FANS TRACK RACE ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By CATBHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Armchair sailors will be able to follow the America's Cup
yachting race from both their TV sets and their computers, thanks
to a new system that receives data from wireless modems aboard the
yachts.
</P>
<P>
   The system, developed by the Electronic Co. of New Zealand and
Telecom New Zealand, is in place now and broadcasting the Louis
Vuitton Cup, in which 11 teams participate in a series of round
robin races for the chance to compete against Team New Zealand, the
Cup defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Each yacht in the race carries a global positioning satellite
device, which constantly monitors its position in terms of latitude
and longitude. A Sierra Wireless MP200 cellular modem, built to
withstand heavy vibration, is also mounted on each yacht. Similar
modems are zipped into inflatable pouches on marker buoys along the
18.5 nautical mile course.
</P>
<P>
   As the yachts move through the course, the modems transmit
multiple streams of information _ GPS location data as well as data
on wind speed and direction _ to Animation Research, a New Zealand
graphics company. The transmissions will occur two times each
second during the qualifying races, and five times each second
during the America's Cup. The information is then translated into
an animated simulation of the yachts at sea on a TV or computer
screen.
</P>
<P>
   The animation program, which will be featured on ESPN, was
originally developed to give TV viewers a better perception of the
yachts' progress, said Tony Thomas, chief executive of the
America's Cup. For $70, America's Cup fans who visit
www.americascup.org can purchase the Virtual Spectator animation CD
package, and use it to translate race updates as they are
transmitted over the Internet. They can also download and watch
races that already occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's often difficult to tell which yacht is ahead by watching
video footage,'' he said. ``We wanted to educate the viewers as to
exactly where the yacht is in relation to the finish mark.'' Dotted
lines and flowing arrows on the screen also indicate the distances
between two yachts, their trails, which direction they are moving
in relation to the finish mark, the distance to the finish mark,
and the wind direction.
</P>
<P>
   When the Young America yacht split in half on Nov. 9th while
racing Nippon of Japan, for example, a dot flashed in place while
the dot representing Nippon moved up the screen. Running commentary
in the lower right hand corner describes wind and current
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   There was some initial concern among race participants when the
modems were installed that another team could use some of the
transmitted information. If one yacht were able to learn of another
yacht's speed during its trajectory into and away from the wind
toward the final mark, (which is known as optimum velocity made
good), it could develop its own course based on that information.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't want another yacht to know what speed you're
going for,'' said Dawn Riley, captain of America True, the coed
team representing the San Francisco Yacht Club. ``It's kind of like
stealing a playbook.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, slight distortions are created in the information
that's relayed from the yachts. If the GPS data, for example,
relays a yacht traversing an ocean swell, the program might depict
it moving across a flat surface. The effect is an accurate enough
simulation for racing fans, but the graphics are not technical
enough to reveal anything significant to a competing team.
</P>
<P>
   But even with distortions, some of the teams view and rehash the
recorded races after they are over. ``We use it to analyze our
tactics,'' Ms. Riley said. ``It gives us an idea of when we were
doing well against the other yachts, and when we weren't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1557EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0442 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS25-COX     11-24 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini music reviews
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Northern Star''
</P>
<P>
   Melanie C. Virgin. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Frequently voted the Spice Girl most likely to succeed as a solo
artist, Melanie C. (the artist formerly known as Sporty Spice)
takes her shot with this sometimes ambitious, sometimes
underwhelming collection of rock, pop and dance-oriented tunes. Her
voice isn't bad, and her sun-bleached image makeover makes as much
as possible of her muscular body tone and tattooed midriff. But,
musically, ``Northern Star'' is only consistent in its
inconsistency. Working with producers William Orbit (''Ray of
Light'') and Rick Rubin (Red Hot Chili Peppers), she samples grunge
and techno-inspired approaches but is never fully convincing as a
surrogate Bjork or Breeder. She's most effective when she sticks to
acoustic-tinted ballads that give her vocals the most room to
breathe. Look out, Jewel!
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``End of Days''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Geffen. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Oooh, the heavy-osity! The soundtrack to the most blockbusterish
of current end-of-the-world movies is as bruisingly hard-core as
you'd expect, given it's the backdrop for Arnold Schwarzenegger's
doomsday battle with the devil. Of course, it's hard to know if
these bands _ a ``parental advisory'' hit parade that includes
Korn, Limp Bizkit, Eminem and comeback kid Axl Rose, with his first
new tune in seven years _ are truly down with the Terminator or
merely pawns of Satan. What's obvious, however, is that most of
these tracks sound like reruns. Prodigy and Rob Zombie provide the
usual mindless fun, though, and Sonic Youth's vintage ``Sugar
Kane'' offers some historical context for how real noise edged its
way into the rock mainstream. As for Guns N' Roses, the histrionic
``Oh My God'' suggests Rose is trying too hard to make a point
that's already irrelevant. But with a new album due soon, he's got
plenty more opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
