NYT-11-24-99 1558EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0444 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS25-COX     11-24 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' (R) _ It offers what
you expect: crude animation, cruder humor. It's probably the most
offensive (and also funniest) bit of celluloid to ever make
moviegoers shell out $7 at theaters. But in its timely, sly,
self-referential way, the movie is more than that. It's a witty
cultural artifact that captures the here and now of American media
obsessions, circa 1999. It should be put inside a time capsule.
Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Entrapment'' (PG-13) _ A thriller with no thrills. A he/she
sexual pas de deux with little chemistry. Sean Connery plays Max, a
dapper thief swiping priceless works of art and computer chips. A
shapely insurance agent (Catherine Zeta-Jones) slinks into the
picture, and ``Entrapment'' becomes a cat-and-mouse game with lots
of twists and turns. Sadly, it's almost always a bore.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Haunting'' (PG-13) _ Scary in all the worst ways. ``The
Haunting'' is a Hollywood debacle, an overpriced mess with only one
scare in it. That scare is of the old-fashioned ``boo'' variety. It
has nothing to do with the over-the-top computer effects that make
this less a remake of the 1963 classic than a theme park in search
of a script. The unlucky actors include Liam Neeson, Catherine
Zeta-Jones and Lili Taylor. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Limbo'' (R) _ Independent filmmaker John Sayles is at his
most independent-minded in this intriguing and inherently honorable
movie whose parts don't add up to a satisfying whole. It's as if he
set out to make one film _ a tender, middle-aged romance told
against the backdrop of encroaching tourism in Alaska _ and then
got interested in something totally different: an unsettling
metaphysical survival tale. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Love Letter'' (PG-13) _ Not lovable, but generally
likable. An anonymous love letter circulates among the residents of
a small New England town setting off enough rendezvous, revelations
and romantic misunderstandings to fill a Shakespeare comedy. The
film has two problems: It flirts with a serious case of the cutes,
and Kate Capshaw, while sexually appealing and adorably flustered,
never quite takes over her own star vehicle. Still, it generates
enough low-key charm to keep you interested. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Autumn Tale'' (unrated) _ Magali (Beatrice Romand), a
long-widowed Frenchwoman in her mid-40s, becomes the object of some
strenuous matchmaking by her longtime best friend (Marie Riviere)
and by the young woman (Alexia Portal) who's dating Magali's son.
The film is overflowing with generosity, humor and insight. By
being both sympathetic to and ironic about the simple fact that the
prospect of seeking out romance reduces us all to cringing
adolescents, master director Eric Rohmer, now almost 80, imparts
wisdom that's aged to perfection. Subtitles. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes
for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
