<HEADER>
A0463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-UNDERINSURE-HEALTH-HN     11-24 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERINSURE-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH INSURANCE IS NOT ALWAYS A CURE-ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: For release anytime over the Thanksgiving period.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kate and Brian Stenz were devastated in 1996 to
learn their newborn son Zachary had hemophilia, which robs the body
of its blood-clotting function.
</P>
<P>
   They were confident that Brian's health insurance would cover at
least the first 10 years of the expensive medical treatment he
would need. But this June, with insurance picking up as much as
$35,000 a month for medication, the Stenzes learned they had
``capped out'' on the policy's $1 million lifetime limit.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent $8,000 out of pocket and facing medical bills of
$100,000 a year in a best-case scenario, the young Columbus, Ohio,
couple found themselves staring into a financial abyss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the cap was going to be increased, but that didn't
happen, and the bills continued to mount,'' said Brian, a salesman
of industrial products.
</P>
<P>
   Although they found alternative insurance coverage, the Stenzes
live under the shadow of abruptly losing it. ``It's a ticking time
bomb,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stenzes are among an estimated 31 million people who are
underinsured, people who risk spending more than 10 percent of
their own annual income in the event of a catastrophic illness,
according to Consumers Union, the non-profit organization that
publishes Consumer Reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have a false sense of security about their
insurance,'' said Gail Shearer, the organization's director of
health policy analysis. ``A financial crisis situation can sneak up
on people unexpectedly.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1998 Consumers Union report, the number of
underinsured had risen 40 percent in the previous 15 years. The 31
million people in that category comprise close to 16 percent of the
195 million Americans under age 65 with health insurance.
Approximately 44 million under 65 have no health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the largest concentration of the underinsured are
those with the greatest need for health care and the least ability
to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care has gotten so expensive relative to what people
make that neither employer nor consumer can afford to buy insurance
that covers everything,'' said Pam Farley Short, who heads
Pennsylvania State University's Center for Health Policy Research
and who has studied the underinsured for 15 years. Many people, she
added, ``could wake up and find they weren't as insured as they
thought they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Short said that to be safe, people should have insurance with a
lifetime cap of $10 million or more for catastrophic illness. The
typical $1 million cap, which dates to the 1970s, may not be
sufficient in an era where the cost of new treatments is
skyrocketing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   People also should have a cap on maximum out-of-pocket
expenditures of $1,500 for an individual and $3,000 for a family,
Short added. Without a cap of some kind, a person with serious
cancer whose plan pays, say, 90 percent of the treatment costs, can
be out $20,000 if the treatment bills hit $200,000, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Policies should cover outpatient prescription drugs and at least
30 days of inpatient mental health services and 30 outpatient
visits, Short suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. James Jeffords, R-Vt., chairman of the Senate Health,
Education, Labor and Pensions Committee, and John D. (Jay)
Rockefeller, D-W.Va. have fought for legislation that would phase
in a $5 million catastrophic illness cap, with a $10 million cap
following that. The bill has gone nowhere, but Jeffords plans to
reintroduce it when Congress reconvenes next year, a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Christopher Reeve, paralyzed from the neck down after a
horse-riding accident in 1995, has lobbied for passage of the
legislation. At the time the cost of Reeve's medical treatment was
estimated at $400,000 a year. Reeve has reached the $1.2 million
cap on one insurance policy and is close to the limit on a second
policy, according to a spokesperson for the actor.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesperson declined to disclose details on the second
policy or on a third policy that Reeve carries.
</P>
<P>
   Among the presidential candidates, only former Sen. Bill
Bradley, D-N.J., has focused on the underinsured. In his health
care proposal, Bradley said that ``no American should have to worry
about being one serious illness or injury away from financial
ruin.'' Bradley also called for a special insurance fund to help
those with major health needs.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say that increasingly people in managed care plans
who have trouble getting approval for certain treatments find
themselves in the same fix as the underinsured.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, your plan may look like a great plan,'' said Gail
Jensen, an economist who studies health care at Wayne State
University in Detroit. ``But when you need it the most, you may
find you have less than you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Jensen knows the pitfalls from first-hand experience. Two years
ago, her 13-year-old daughter attempted suicide. Jensen battled her
managed care plan to get continuous treatment for the girl at a
mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen's plan refused to cover more than a week at the hospital
at a time. Her daughter was released still threatening to kill
herself and was readmitted twice after two more failed attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very frightening,'' Jensen said. Her daughter is now
doing better even though she is still on medication, Jensen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something you don't discover about you plan until it
is too late,'' Jensen said. ``You may conclude, as I did, that you
don't have enough insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1617EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0467 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-SOUTH-TEXAS-JOBS-HNS &LR;      11-24 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-TEXAS-JOBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKILLED WORKERS LEAVING SOUTH TEXAS DESPITE BOOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys' spring training camp, a
citrus-lined water park and a tire plant all share a kindred
purpose in the lower Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   They are economic development ventures launched by various
Valley cities to lure jobs and improve the image of a rapidly
developing corridor on the Texas-Mexico border, an area enjoying
new opportunities but hobbled by old problems.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the Valley has occupied the dead-last position on
most state economic charts. So it is not surprising that city
leaders, faced with chronically high rates of unemployment in a
region where 45 percent of residents live below the poverty level
and educational attainment is low, are desperate to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   And, in recent months, there are indications of a ``brain
drain'' as skilled workers take their talents to Houston, Dallas,
San Antonio and Fort Worth, where higher-paying jobs abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see people going to other areas of the state, they are
people with skills,'' laments Perry Vaughn, director of the
Associated General Contractors in Harlingen, who is working with
other groups to expand skilled training in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But some community leaders have begun to question the wisdom of
recruiting corporations with publicly funded incentives _ including
large tax abatements, free land and free training for new employees
_ if the jobs created only pay minimum wage or slightly better.
</P>
<P>
   They are referred to as poverty wages, paying $7.50 an hour or
less, putting a family of four with one wage-earner below the
poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the kind of economic development that is going to
bring the Valley into the 21st century,'' insists Sister Judy
Donovan, an organizer with Valley Interfaith, a community
betterment group drawing membership from Catholic parishes. ``It's
going to put the Valley in first place on a race to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to change the culture of poverty wages, the
thinking that any job is a good job, especially when it comes to
utilizing public dollars (to attract them),'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   City officials in McAllen spend half a million dollars annually
in sales tax revenues to operate the McAllen Economic Development
Corp. Over the last dozen years the corporation's staff has
recruited 152 companies to McAllen and 189 to Reynosa, McAllen's
Mexican sister city across the Rio Grande. In all, the companies
have created 9,893 jobs on the U.S. side and 46,988 in Mexico,
according to a recent tally by the city agency.
</P>
<P>
   But development officials say they are only now completing an
analysis of how much these jobs pay local residents.
</P>
<P>
   However, one clue can be found in the 4,107 new jobs created by
10 companies that recently moved to McAllen, according to a Nov. 8
status report prepared for the McAllen City Commission. Only 127
jobs of those jobs pay $10 per hour or more.
</P>
<P>
   And while the 10 companies are projected to provide a yearly
payroll of $93.6 million and spend $53 million on capital
expenditures, about 1,500 jobs will pay $7.50 per hour or lower _
including 300 part-time telemarketing jobs paying $6.50 per hour
without benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Allen, the director of McAllen's development agency, said
low-paying employers are not given incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we don't recruit companies that pay only $6.50 (per
hour) or something like that,'' he said. ``We're going after
companies that will pay better wages than that _ $7.50 is our
bottom. But if they come, they come, but we don't provide them any
financial incentives.''
</P>
<P>
   Some elected officials are concerned that the new jobs are not
always as advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're creating the largest population of uninsured people in
the history of the Valley, whether we realize it or not,'' warns
Paul Cowan, the chief aide to St. Sen. Eddie Lucio, D-Brownsville.
``It's because we're moving people from welfare to work, and work
doesn't have full medical benefits. Some of these polices have high
deductible and co-payments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At least on welfare, they have it (medical coverage). But
you're not insured if you have to make a $1,000 co-payment,'' Cowan
said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, negotiations have advanced to bring the Dallas
Cowboys' spring training camp to a new sports complex under
construction in Mission, part of a sprawling industrial and
residential development being built by Dallas developer Ray Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The cities of Mission and McAllen and the Hidalgo County
government have agreed to pay the Cowboys $1 million over three
years to move their training to the Valley from Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got chambers of commerce and development corporations
all over the Valley who are spending literally hundreds of
thousands of dollars advertising the Valley as place to do
business, a place to take vacations, a place to live,'' notes Randy
Whittington, a Harlingen attorney who chairs the Rio Grande Valley
Sports Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about free advertising that is worth many
multiples of that. It literally puts the Valley on the map, on
national TV, any number of times a day while they are in training
camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Whittington said a university analysis estimated the Cowboys
training camp generated $6 million in direct revenue to Wichita
Falls, after hotel, meal and other expenses were computed for the
football team, a pack of 400 to 500 journalists from around the
world and thousands of fans who attended the daily practice
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboy owner Jerry Jones has said he would make a decision on
the camp in December. ``The champagne is chilled, but we haven't
popped the cork yet,'' Whittington said.
</P>
<P>
   In Edinburg, city leaders loaned $600,000 from a city garbage
collection fund to cover budget shortfalls at a 35-acre water park
financed by $21.3 million in revenue bonds sold by the Edinburg
Industrial Development Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   SuperSplash! Adventure Waterpark, which was supposed to turn a
profit, instead has lost nearly $900,000 since opening in July
1998. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The water park is part of a family entertainment complex that
city officials are developing, which includes a public golf course,
a city park and a $10 million movie complex. Officials still say
the expect the development to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   In Brownsville, local officials expressed confidence that a huge
tire plant will eventually live up to earlier expectations. The
Titan Tire Corp. plant moved to$ 9kkW-[e
</P>
</TEXT>
