<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKEN-TREASURES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TELLS HOW TO REPAIR THE IRREPLACABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY FRIAUF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your mom has good taste, so over the years she's acquired some
beautiful things in addition to her children. A number of those
things have gotten broken. The favorite vase (cracked), the
heirloom string of pearls (unstrung) have been pushed to the back
of the cabinet and the jewelry box.
</P>
<P>
   So this Christmas, why not fix something Mom loves?
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at ``Care and Repair of Everyday Treasures'' by
Judith Miller (Reader's Digest, $29.95 hardcover), a step-by-step
for fixing all of those favorite things.
</P>
<P>
   If this klutz can do it _ and I once Superglued fingers on
different hands together _ you can, too. And if you become
proficient, think of all the broken garage-sale treasures you can
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some repairs I attempted, and the results:
</P>
<P>
   The vintage champagne glasses _ chipped
</P>
<P>
   Not the currently fashionable flutes, these resembled delicate,
etched custard dishes on 6-inch stems. They were a set of four, all
dangerously nicked around the rim.
</P>
<P>
   As directed in ``Care and Repair,'' I started with a wooden
dowel and wrapped it in a strip of fine-grit silicon-carbide paper.
This is also known as wet-dry paper, as I would have known had I
read the resource directory at the back of the book.
</P>
<P>
   I filled a bowl, larger than the glass, half-full of water, so I
could use one hand to rewet the rim repeatedly while holding a
grit-wrapped dowel in the other hand. After a moderate application
of elbow grease, it was gratifying to see the nicks disappear.
Results: Excellent
</P>
<P>
   Cost: I found the tapered dowel in the garage, so the whole
operation cost the price of grit paper: 79 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The cracked and stained teapot
</P>
<P>
   This small Blue Willow-ish pot, an anniversary gift, had a long,
deep and aged crack, and the surrounding area was badly stained.
The borax-followed-by-bleach treatment recommended in ``Care and
Repair'' brightened the piece considerably. (I remembered to clean
the lid so it would match the pot.) But hours of soaking didn't
touch the stain that had seeped in via the crack. Time to get
messy.
</P>
<P>
   I ordered the whitening agent titanium dioxide from an
old-fashioned pharmacy. ``Care and Repair'' vows that it prevents
glue from yellowing. I mixed the powder (about $1 an ounce, and a
teeny bit goes a very long way) into Superglue, between sneezing
fits. Handling titanium dioxide, a gritty powder, calls for a
respirator mask; the label cautions that it is an irritant. Also
advisable are thin latex gloves, because all adhesives are hard on
the skin.
</P>
<P>
   I spread my concoction over the crack with a tiny wooden
spatula, then nestled the teapot in a basket lined with dish towels
to keep the repaired side up. I let it dry a couple of days, then
sanded away the excess with wet-dry grit paper.
</P>
<P>
   Along the repair line, the pattern was obscured. I used a 3/0
liner paintbrush, $2 at a craft store, and dabs of blue, black and
white acrylic paint from my children's art supplies, to fill in the
pattern. I started over a couple of times, but I just don't have
the skill to paint a subtle pattern whose color varies several
shades along 5 inches. ``Brave'' was my kind co-worker's
description of my efforts. I'll be easy on myself and call it folk
art.
</P>
<P>
   Results: Disappointing
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $5
</P>
<P>
   The broken bracelet
</P>
<P>
   Grandma's mother-of-pearl bracelet had cracked, predictably on
the link that once had the closure. I'd always imagined a young man
risking loss of a digit to scoop it from the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   My attempts at repair were less romantic. The broken-off
filigree piece was about 1/16 by 1/2 inch. I chose clear glass
adhesive (about $3). Suffice it to say that impatience was the
major obstacle. Minute repairs such as this are best attacked with
plenty of time, a mounted magnifying glass in excellent light and
the finest, tiniest tweezers you can find.
</P>
<P>
   I found it was helpful to mount the bracelet on a small ball of
modeling clay to hold it steady during repair and curing. I got in
a hurry the first go-round and broke the bond. The second time was
the charm. I finished the project with a 99-cent clasp and links
cadged from other broken jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Results: Excellent
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $4
</P>
<P>
   The favorite mug with broken handle
</P>
<P>
   Dad's best mug had lost its handle.
</P>
<P>
   The titanium dioxide-epoxy mixture cemented it perfectly, and as
``Care and Repair'' recommends, I used a long strip of masking tape
to secure it, then set it, handle-up, to cure overnight in a basket
lined with crumpled paper towels. The little gaps were filled with
epoxy putty, allowed to dry, sanded and lightly lacquered. Dad's
back in business, although the epoxy didn't quite fill the chinks.
</P>
<P>
   Results: Serviceable though short of excellent
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $2
</P>
<P>
   A different approach
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the home of someone you care about, there's a piece
of art or memorabilia that deserves to be seen. And before it can
be seen, and subjected to sunlight, dust, rampaging kids and New
Year's Eve beverages held aloft, it needs proper framing.
</P>
<P>
   Among my family's Christmas decorations is a spirit-of-Christmas
editorial my father wrote more than 25 years ago. My aunt had it
framed with red and green matting, and we've treasured it ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   William Campbell, who has kept a gallery in Fort Worth for a
quarter-century, says the important thing in framing archival
material is protection from sunlight and avoidance of acidic mats
and frames. ``Take care of all the safeguards if it's really worth
something to you,'' he said. Allow two weeks. Expect to pay about
$60-$200.
</P>
<P>
   Or be cheap, like me. I found a big box of filthy, banged-up
5-by-7-inch picture frames at a garage sale in southwest Fort
Worth. Nice molding, with an elegant bead. Some had glass, too.
They were 10 cents each.
</P>
<P>
   A friend says they're maple, circa 1935. I sanded off the grime,
Windexed the glass. On a shelf in my garage, I found little dabs of
leftover paint: sky blue, ivory, metallic gold. Bought a $3 can of
varnish and slapped it on. All this made the frame look too new, so
I cut up an emery board and sanded off itsy bits of the ivory paint
and blended the blue into it. Dug up a family photo from 1901. Oh,
what luck; it fit. With 25 cents' worth of picture wire, it'll be
ready to wrap and put under the tree. Except I don't want to part
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Results: Excellent
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $3.25
</P>
<P>
   What you can fix
</P>
<P>
   ``Care and Repair of Everyday Treasures'' walks the reader
through projects covering everything in your mom's house, plus your
great-aunt's attic. Each section details cleaning, plus more
elaborate work. Examples:
</P>
<P>
   Furniture: From removal of water rings to structural repairs. Go
ahead, reassemble a chair.
</P>
<P>
   Canework: Strengthen worn examples of this elegant use of
rattan. Or, if you're a weaver, recane an entire seat.
</P>
<P>
   Upholstery: Stitch up a small tear, reupholster a button-back
chair or anything in between. It helps if you're a seamstress.
</P>
<P>
   Leather: Patch a tear. Replace a desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Textiles: Dry-clean an antique doily. Fix moth-eaten
needlepoint.
</P>
<P>
   Rugs and carpets: Repair small tears, or reweave. .MDUL/.MDNM/
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
