<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0475 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     11-24 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T CALL 911 FOR `ER' _ ITS VITAL SIGNS ARE GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All this talk of ``ER'' having lost a step or two is nonsense.
Knee-jerk reaction, I'd say, to a sleek and sly series that no
longer tries to keep up its former frenetic pace yet still manages
to remain remarkably consistent, despite this season's risky
personnel changes and big-star drive-bys.
</P>
<P>
   How good is ``ER,'' still? Unlike a drama such as ``Law &AMP;
Order,'' where because of its
half-cop-chase/half-courtroom-showdown formula the characters are a
distant second to story, ``ER'' continues to reinvent itself _ to
go under its own knife in an attempt to look fresher, leaner,
meaner.
</P>
<P>
   When people say that ``ER'' isn't what it used to be _ well,
they're absolutely right. But what is? What should be? And in a
season that is, night for night, show for show, the best I've
witnessed in some time, could it also be that once you take in
something as uniquely appealing as, say, ``Now &AMP; Again,'' wouldn't
a 6-year-old drama pale a bit when examined under the same
lighting?
</P>
<P>
   But why take my word? A new episode is offered up tonight, on
Thanksgiving, at 9 p.m., the time at which you'll be fat and happy
and barely moving from the couch. Watch it, digest it, give another
shot to a series that has taken great pains to maintain its
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Thank sweeps and gumption for the new episodes. Usually on this
holiday, the networks pull out reruns or call it a night by pulling
out blockbuster theatrical films. (Fox is going with ``Home Alone
2,'' while ABC counters with ``Forrest Gump.'') Although the
feeling in Hollywood is that people don't sit in front of the tube
on Thanksgiving, my thinking has always been: Where else can they
wobble off to? To play a board game?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``ER'' is part of a strong, all-new episode night that
I highly recommend as a package deal. It includes regulars like
``Friends'' (Chandler meets Monica's parents) and ``Frasier''
(Lilith's back) but with ``Just Shoot Me'' and ``Will &AMP; Grace''
(the series that should have been on this day anyhow, not ``Stark
Raving Mad,'' although my neighbor would feverishly disagree; Neil
Patrick Harris seems to crack him up) creeping over from its
Tuesday night perch.
</P>
<P>
   As for tonight's ``ER,'' surely you've seen the promos where
Nurse Hathaway (Julianna Margulies) goes into labor on the subway.
Because I've been sworn to secrecy as to the outcome, let's move on
to the story line involving the return of John Cullum as Dr.
Greene's (Anthony Edwards) ill-natured father. Along with Greene's
daughter, (Yvonne Zima) who thinks quite lowly of his new love, Dr.
Elizabeth Corday (British actress Alex Kingston), Cullum comes with
both barrels firing. The relationship between Cullum's character
and Dr. Greene is, with the exception of the hot-cold entanglement
of Annie Potts and Lorraine Toussaint on Lifetime's ``Any Day
Now,'' the most prickly and strained and realistic pairing in prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, though, Dr. Greene is called away from their uneasy
Thanksgiving dinner to assist with Hathaway's difficult delivery
(did I say difficult?) leaving Dr. Corday to deal with a couple of
medical surprises. Funny how ``ER's'' most promoted episodes (and
usually its best efforts) are those that take place outside the
hospital, from Dr. Peter Benton's (Eriq LaSalle) trip to the Deep
South to George Clooney's renegade life-saving maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably because without knowing it, we, too, need a
break from the dizzying number of medical cases; to turn away, at
least for a while, from the blood and gore and medical jargon
flying over our heads _ though there's a lot of all that sprouting
about tonight. And for all its emergency-room razzle-dazzle,
stories about where these people go and what they do after leaving
the hospital makes for intoxicating drama.
</P>
<P>
   The terrific thing about the new season is that it's not only
Dr. Greene's personal life that has become complicated and messy
and therefore enjoyable. Thankfully Dr. Kerry Weaver (Laura Innes)
has returned to cranky form; for a minute there, the writers were
sucking the life out of her character by softening her edges, by
making her care.
</P>
<P>
   Benton is still reeling from the possibility of losing his son
to out-of-the-country relocation by the boy's mother and new hubby,
and who knows what will happen with Hathaway, last seen tonight
with a look of terror painted on her face. (Did I say terror?)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Romano (Paul McCrane) made quite an impression over
the past few seasons in a recurring role as a malicious schemer who
matches Dr. Weaver in back-stabbing, political maneuvering and
withering deadpan cracks. (His too-brief comments last week
concerning Dr. Carter's presence in an administrative services
meeting were priceless.) Why he hasn't gotten more screen time as
of late is something of a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for Michael Michele, one of the new cast
members who has been seen mostly swooping in to interject her
medical passions on others, mostly to Lucy (Kellie Martin) and
exercising _ running, doing push-ups, sit-ups. Tonight she's
jumping rope in the snow, prompting Hathaway to quip, ``I remember
when I was that skinny.''
</P>
<P>
   And I remember when Lucy was trumpeted as The Young Savior of a
drama that feared getting stale. Either Martin's college work is
preventing her character from being fully developed or the writers
have already lost interest and moved on to the ongoing search for a
hunk equivalent of Clooney. (It's obvious that Noah Wyle is too
lightweight for the job; Goran Visnjic as Dr. Kovac is getting a
tryout.)
</P>
<P>
   If anything pained me this season it was the disrespectful
shoo-away of physician's assistant Jeanie Boulet (Gloria Reuben),
who left the series two episodes back. The writers apparently
having done all they could with her AIDS story line, her presence
there had dwindled. A shame, considering that Boulet's acting at
the end of last season was some of the best stuff from anyone on
any series. Having her merely walk into the emergency room and tell
Dr. Weaver that she was quitting to stay at home with her new baby
and husband wasn't a sign-off worthy of a star to whom we've become
emotionally attached.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. At least my anger was tempered somewhat when Reuben
told David Letterman the other night that her next gig was as
backup dancer on Tina Turner's tour beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
   Because I can no longer afford the exorbitant concert ticket
prices, my only hope of getting a Reuben fix is that she'll slip
off the stage and end up being wheeled into ``ER.'' Sounds like a
nice story line to me.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
