<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EMAIL-VOLUNTEERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLACE TO REACH OUT, VIRTUALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Texas)   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By REBECCA FAIRLEY RANEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Bonnie Frascatore was confined to bed for seven months
during a high-risk pregnancy, the high point of each day came when
she switched on her computer. There, every day, she received e-mail
from a woman who had experienced a pregnancy just as difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Through the e-mail, she found compassion that wasn't always
available at home _ and she did not have to contend with making her
house or herself presentable for a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to write what I wanted to write without having a
family member say, `Oh, get over it,''' said Ms. Frascatore, who is
36 and lives in upstate New York. In fact, when she went into labor
in March, she insisted that her family send e-mail to the woman, a
volunteer with a nationwide support group, to let her know.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the hospital, the first thing I said to my husband was, `I
forgot to e-mail!''' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ms. Frascatore has become a volunteer with the same
online support group, the Sidelines National Support Network
(www.sidelines.org), and sends e-mail each day to other women with
high-risk pregnancies. Her experience as a ``virtual volunteer'' is
becoming more common as nonprofit groups learn to organize helpers
who want to contribute to society from their keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne Cravens, manager of the Virtual Volunteering Project
(www.serviceleader.org/vv) at the University of Texas at Austin,
has identified more than 250 organizations nationwide that have
started such programs. They range from small grass-roots
environmental groups to large educational organizations that
coordinate online mentoring of students.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `I want to help, but I want to do it by
computer,''' Ms. Cravens said. Her project tracks groups that allow
volunteers to work via computer and also provides training in
setting up programs.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when the program started, the nonprofit world
was resistant to the notion of using the Internet. ``The idea of
working with unseen volunteers _ people think, `I'm never going to
see these people, and the Internet is crawling with pedophiles,'''
Ms. Cravens said. With time, she said, as perceptions of the
Internet matured, organizations became more open to the concept.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, outreach would not be possible without the
Internet. Last year, the San Jose Children's Musical Theater
created a production called ``Pulse: The Rhythm of Life'' by
drawing disabled and seriously ill children into the process online
as volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Tegan McLane, director of the Theater as Digital Activity
program (www.sjcmt.com/TADA!), created characters based on
composites of the children who volunteered as online consultants.
</P>
<P>
   For example, producers asked the children what kinds of
challenges an 11-year-old character named Thomas with bone cancer
would face, what episodes would unfold in his life and what his
dreams and fears would be. When the songs and dialogue for the
production were written, they were posted on a Web page for the
children to critique.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cravens is compiling more examples like that every day. She
sees the Internet as an important catalyst for getting people
involved in causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick to death of stories about how the Internet is making
people lonely and cranky,'' she said. ``If anything, I've noticed
the Internet is getting people out more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
