<HEADER>
A0480 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-GAME-FESTIVAL-NYT     11-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GAME-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENTS OFFER UP DREAMS ON DEMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, a congregation of programmers, animators and
designers assembles in San Jose, Calif., for the Game Developers
Conference, a techie jamboree dedicated to the art and science of
video games. In the spirit of innovation, last year the conference
featured a festival for independently developed games, along the
lines of Sundance or the South by Southwest conference in Austin,
Texas. The winners are announced in March, but collecting and
culling the entries takes the better part of a year.
</P>
<P>
   The process also requires people willing to install buggy alpha
versions of games with questionable artistic merit (and face the
technological consequences) in order to find the pearls.
Invariably, multiple demos bring your computer to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   But even though my PC, and my psyche, still bear the scars of
last year's balloting, I agreed to do it again this year because,
as the conference organizers reminded me (in successive e-mail
messages), I am the sort of person who supports independent
developers. So here I am again, loading labors of love onto my hard
drive with a mixture of hope and trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   The entries come from all over the world, from Silicon Valley to
Eastern Europe and Asia. As usual, it's interesting to see the way
culture maps onto game design. A posse of programmers in Texas puts
the player in the middle of an extraterrestrial invasion with guns
blazing. A studio in New York takes its inspiration from techno
music and rave graphics. A team of programmers in Russia has
somehow managed to convert a car race into chess. You place markers
along the track and specify what the car will do at those
positions. The idea of drag racing while taking turns never
occurred to me, but somehow it works.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the voices that seem to spring not from a
particular region, but rather from their own passionate and highly
colorful universe.
</P>
<P>
   Witness Azura: Amazon Avatar.
</P>
<P>
   Azura's back story alone is a testament to the fervor of the
unsung game designer: ``Azura stood like a goddess on the high
castle balcony. Casting her eyes down upon the ocean of her people,
the Amazons, she sovereignly declared war. In response, the mass of
people shouting in unison, War! drowned out all other sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Azura quickly turned on her heels into the Throne Room and
from its royal resting place, slowly and with great serenity, she
lifted the Sacred Scimmeron. From its small cylinder shape, the
true form of the Sacred Scimmeron remained hidden. When activated,
it would morph into the fastest and most destructive weapon: The
Death Sled.''
</P>
<P>
   Azura: Amazon Avatar, the entry form promises, has the following
features: ``Nonstop action and excitement! Battle hordes of
Titanaras as they try to take over your home planet of Terran and
enslave your people. Advanced Magick System: Small Fireball,
Freeze, Large Fireball, Summon Drakan and Hellfire! As you advance
in levels, your power grows. Start with the Small Fireball spell
and work your way up to the ultimate destructive spell, Hellfire!''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, after several hours of installation migraines and
a dozen crashes, I was not actually able to experience this
interactive tour de force. Azura's adventures with the Death Sled
and the Sacred Scimmeron must, alas, play out in my imagination.
But perhaps that is for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Plowing through a six-inch stack of demo discs, it's easy to
adopt a hard-boiled ``Gong Show'' mentality. But every once in a
while, you find things that are made with so much generosity that
no matter how rough they are, they force you to acknowledge their
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   In response to an entry form question (``What do you hope to
achieve personally or professionally by creating this game?''), a
team of Web designers in South Korea wrote: ``Obviously, our
primary concern is that our creditors are paid, our families are
fed, and our children are clothed. We refuse to advertise on our
Web site and within our game, and we allow our customers to pay us
for increments as brief as one month.
</P>
<P>
   ``These decisions were made to guarantee that our motivation
would always be to ensure the happiness of our customers. That in
itself is a great reward.''
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make even the most hard-boiled game maven pine
for the days of home-brewed Commodore 64 demos and floppy-disk
role-playing adventures. Who knows, maybe some of these contest
submissions will turn into commercial products.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, most of them will never make it onto a store
shelf _ nor should they. But they need to exist, if only to remind
big-budget game producers that they were once novice programmers
whose dream was to design video games. People are still cobbling
together those dreams with the bolts and scraps of technology
available to them, and it's important that they have a place to
showcase their handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   So, long live indie games. Long live Azura: Amazon Avatar. May
she attain the power of successful installation. And when that
comes to pass, may the Death Sled spare my hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address: Herz(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
