<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0481 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-HEISMAN-COX     11-24 1729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HEISMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heisman fervor evident on Georgia Tech campus:
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech bookstore fairly bristled the morning of Oct.
30. That afternoon, the Yellow Jackets, once-beaten and ranked No.
7, would trample poor N.C. State, thanks largely to their
undersized quarterback. The very same QB who was the impetus for
new T-shirts on sale that day. Which read, in part:
</P>
<P>
   1999 Heisman Candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Below was an outline of the state of Georgia, with the
stiff-arming Heisman Trophy superimposed on it and a large No. 14
off to the left.
</P>
<P>
   The T-shirts ($14.95 plus tax) were going as fast as Dez White
on a streak pattern. On that day, all things seemed possible _ even
that the school where John Heisman once coached finally might have
its own Heisman Trophy winner.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Heisman was, or is, Joe Hamilton's motivation.
''No, I don't play for that,'' he said. ''I go out and try to play
to win. Who knows? It's out of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   And on the ballots of the Heisman electorate _ at least those
voters who haven't already made up their minds and mailed the
ballots to the Downtown Athletic Club in New York. There, the
Heisman will be presented on Dec. 11. Yet when Georgia Tech and
Georgia _ two 7-3 teams who just don't dislike each other but
loathe each other _ meet Saturday in Bobby Dodd Stadium, it will be
more than Joe Hamilton's last home game and last shot at the Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   It's also his last chance to make a lasting Heisman impression.
To convince voters that he, Little Joe _ who weighs 189 pounds and
is listed at 5 feet 10 but actually stands about 5-8 1/2 _ is
worthy of the Heisman. Not Ron Dayne, Wisconsin's 255-pound
fullback who earlier this month became college football's Division
1-A career rushing leader and the Heisman front-runner. Rather, the
little big man from the hamlet of Alvin, S.C., who literally put
his hometown on the South Carolina state map this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The closest Georgia Tech has come to producing a Heisman winner
was in 1963. Another versatile quarterback, Billy Lothridge _ who
passed with his left arm, did all of Tech's punting and
placekicking and played with one kidney _ finished a distant second
in the voting to a scrambling Navy junior named Roger Staubach.
Tech's highest Heisman finish since then: 1978, when tailback Eddie
Lee Ivery was eighth the year Billy Sims ran away with it.
</P>
<P>
   In '63, while the Heisman was still one of sport's most
cherished awards, the selection process was less complicated, the
media scrutiny almost non-existent, the hype almost hushed and the
winner relatively anonymous. The year before, Johnny Gresham _ who
played at Tech 1962-64 and captained the '64 team _ picked up the
newspaper one Sunday morning to find a story about the 1962 Heisman
Trophy winner. ''I said, 'Who is Terry Baker?' '' Gresham said.
Baker was Oregon State's versatile, left-handed quarterback, whose
707 votes edged LSU halfback Jerry Stovall's 618. ''I'd literally
never heard of Terry Baker. I didn't even know he was in the
running for the Heisman Trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   No one ran for the Heisman back then. Not as the players, their
schools and sports-information offices do now _ helped,
intentionally or not, by television networks, newspapers and
magazines that can't help hyping that Heisman thing, no matter how
prematurely. This year, as in many years, the Heisman voters decide
early and mail their ballots. Even back on Oct. 30, Dayne the
senior whom Sports Illustrated already had called one of college
football's 10 biggest disappointments was making a huge comeback.
He was closing in on the all-time rushing record of '98 Heisman
winner Ricky Williams, which Dayne broke two weeks later in his
last home game.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Virginia's Thomas Jones is this year's leading
1-A rusher and that the Heisman is awarded to the best player of
that year. Never mind that some peole view Alabama's Shaun
Alexander as a superior running back to Dayne. The Badger bulldozed
to the top of those weekly Heisman race charts that run all season,
and he did it largely on the strength of his life's body of work,
not this season's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like the rules (for the Heisman) change every year,''
said Malcom Moran, who covers Notre Dame for the Chicago Tribune.
''It's like, 2,000 yards (rushing) was a lock, or, the 2,000 means
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Colorado's Rashaan Salaam rushed for the first 2,000
season, he won the 1994 Heisman. When Iowa State's Troy Davis ran
for more than 2,000 the next year, he wasn't even invited to New
York as a Heisman finalist. When Davis did it again in '96, he made
it to the ceremony but was a distant second in the voting to
Florida's Danny Wuerffel.
</P>
<P>
   While Wuerffel would then lead Florida to the national
championship, he already had benefited from another factor in the
Heisman race: television. So has Dayne. ESPN's Lee Corso and ABC's
Terry Bowden for months have been promoting Dayne as the Heisman
choice. On Nov. 7, the day the Heisman race probably turned in
Dayne's favor, ESPN promoted the Wisconsin-Purdue game ''almost as
a Heisman showdown'' between Dayne and Purdue quarterback Drew
Brees, Moran said. ''And Tech-Virginia (later that day on ABC)
almost as an afterthought. Here you have (ESPN), who's probably the
most influential (Heisman) factor presenting their opinions. . . .
I remember thinking, 'Thomas Jones and Joe Hamilton are pretty good
players, and they're not getting anywhere near the attention the
other two guys are.' ''
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, Dayne had rushed for 222 more yards and was the
No. 2 career rusher; Hamilton and Tech, meanwhile, were upset by
Jones and Virginia's furious comeback, 45-38. When Hamilton threw
for five touchdown passes to beat Clemson the next weekend,
however, he said of the Heisman, ''It ain't over.'' Then came last
Saturday in Winston-Salem.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Hamilton was right on track 'til then,'' Mark
Blaudschun of the Boston Globe said. ''I convinced people to hold
off (voting) and wait. But now he's dead. You can't lose to Wake
Forest and expect to win the Heisman. He'll get first-team
All-American quarterback, and that'll be his consolation prize.
That's pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no Heisman, however.
</P>
<P>
   The fervor is evident everywhere on the Tech campus:
</P>
<P>
   The bronze statue of John Heisman himself, megaphone on his
right hip, stands in Callaway Plaza beyond the north end of the
stadium; several weeks ago, some students painted a 14 on Heisman's
chest. Last week, Heisman wore a white No. 14 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   For each home game, ten Tech student paint themselves yellow,don
yellow fright wigs and yellow tutus and paint blue letters on their
chests so they spell out J-O-E-H-E-I-S-M-A-N
</P>
<P>
   From the Rambling Wreck Club, the booster organization that
distributes ''Hamilton for Heisman'' buttons at home games.
</P>
<P>
   Late the night before the Oct. 9 homecoming game against North
Carolina, the good brothers of Theta Chi fraternity moved couches
out into the street in front of their abode, the better to, uh,
stop traffic while painting a large white rectangle across the
street. In gold letters, they painted: HAMILTON FOR HEISMAN. Tech
never has had a Heisman autumn like this one. There was the
preseason ''Hamilton for Heisman'' CD-ROM the sports information
office mailed to Heisman voters, followed by a computer mouse pad.
Hamilton has gone on to become Tech's all-time passing leader and
the first ACC player to amass 10,000 total yards while directing
the nation's most prolific offense.
</P>
<P>
   The SID office recently got two Heisman-related requests: An
elderly gentleman who said he was calling on behalf of Dick
Kazmaier, who won the 1951 Heisman as a Princeton tailback, for
information about Hamilton's academic credentials and off-the-field
charitable works; and sportswriter Jack Ebling of the Lansing State
Journal, state chairman of the Michigan Heisman voters, who
requested a tape of Tech's 41-35 loss at No. 1 FSU _ in which
Hamilton passed for 387 yards and four touchdowns and ran for a
fifth TD _ because ''four or five of us around here are considering
him as our No. 1 pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech head coach George O'Leary was an assistant at Syracuse when
diminutive Boston College quarterback Doug Flutie won the 1984
Heisman. Flutie, now starring with the Buffalo Bills was ''very
similar to Joe,'' O'Leary said. ``Joe's probably a little bit
niftier. Flutie's probably faster. Both have the same arm
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet unlike Hamilton, Flutie was the late-season Heisman
frontrunner even before he launched the last-second Hail Mary pass
that beat Miami and clinched the Heisman. ''It's like anything
else,'' O'Leary said of the Heisman. ''When that award's given,
it's who's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's first lasting Heisman memory was 1987, when he was 10
and Notre Dame receiver/returner Tim Brown won the Heisman. ''He
did a lot of good things, exciting things,'' Hamilton recalled.
''He scored, he did everything to put his team in position to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was surprised when Salaam prevailed in '94 (''I didn't
think he'd win it''); loved Michigan's Desmond Howard when he
struck the Heisman pose in the end zone in '91; said about the '92
honoree, ''I really didn't think Gino Torretta was a Heisman Trophy
winner;'' and advised people aboard the Peyton Manning bandwagon in
'97, ''Don't count out Charles Woodson.''
</P>
<P>
   And this time? ''You never know what they're looking for in a
player, what they want,'' Hamilton said. ''They might be looking
for a Ron Dayne-type player, or a Drew Brees. I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dayne has done great things. To his record, I say
congratulations. But the only I thing I say is, how many people
could do that, do what Dayne did? That's a big question. Maybe some
college athletes could go to Wisconsin and do what he did? I don't
know. But he's a great back.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also apparently at the head of this Heisman class.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Hamilton will join Dayne and the other
finalists in New York for the Heisman presentation. ''It's just an
award,'' said Hamilton, who has played down the Heisman all fall
but knows it's more than just an award. ''Sometimes, you dream
about being in their shoes. What would I do? How would I react?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
