<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0482 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-BOBBYROSS-COX     11-24 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BOBBYROSS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Relaxed Ross wins over players
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Thanksgiving Day 1998, Detroit Lions running back Barry
Sanders already had rushed for 1,192 yards in 11 games. Yet the
Lions were 4-7 and seemed to be in disarray under coach Bobby Ross.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lions host the Chicago Bears today in the Pontiac
Silverdome, Ross won't have Sanders, who abruptly retired before
training camp started in July. Without Sanders in the backfield,
the Lions are 6-4 and tied with Tampa Bay and Minnesota for first
place in the NFC Central, even thought they lost their past two
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is we're still in it,'' said Ross, who guided
Georgia Tech to a share of the national championship in 1990. ``We
still have a chance. I'm not saying we dug ourselves a hole, but
now it's a competitive thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Lions are competitive at all says a lot about Ross, who
spent five seasons with the San Diego Chargers after leaving Tech
and took them to Super Bowl XXIX in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit limped to a 5-11 record last season, the worst finish in
Ross' seven seasons in the NFL. Ross seemed to have lost control of
his team. Bill Ford Jr., vice chairman of the team, wanted to hire
television commentator Matt Millen to run football operations, even
if it meant losing Ross. Millen later backed out.
</P>
<P>
   But so did Sanders, who was on the verge of breaking Walter
Payton's all-time rushing record. Sanders quit two days before
training camp because,he said, he thought the team was going
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things went on last year, and if you want to perceive it
a certain way, fine,'' Ross said. ``I spent the offseason taking a
good look at myself, but I also think that was true of everybody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's players were greeted by a friendlier and gentler Ross
this season. The former U.S. Army first lieutenant showed his
players that he was willing to bend. The team now provides
breakfast every day and gives each player his own hotel room for
road games. The little things have started adding up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time during a team meeting this year where he came
in wearing this awful-looking tie,'' Lions defensive tackle Luther
Ellis said. ``We kidded him about it, and he laughed right along. A
year ago, nobody would even try to joke about something like that,
because you weren't sure what his response would be. Would he blow
up or something?''
</P>
<P>
   Ross also is seeking more input from his players. Last season,
Sanders and other veterans reportedly were upset when Ross benched
quarterback Scott Mitchell after only two games. Ross replaced
Mitchell with rookie Charlie Batch, who went 3-9 in 12 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing and probably the biggest change is that he's
more willing to listen to us than he did last year,'' Ellis said.
``He's open to suggestions, and you have no idea what that does to
the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lions have overcome a rash of injuries to remain in
contention this year. At least one-third of their starters have
missed one game or more. Running back Ron Rivers, who expected to
replace Sanders, broke his ankle against Carolina in the sixth game
and was lost for the season. Wide receiver Herman Moore, who
started the last three Pro Bowls, doesn't have a catch because of
injuries to both knees. Batch has missed the past two games and
parts of two others because of a bruised thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Lions seem less predictable on offense. While Sanders
was often the first _ and sometimes only _ option on offense in
seasons past, several players have emerged in 1999. Wide receiver
Germane Crowell, of Virginia, has blossomed into a star in his
second season. In his last three games, Crowell has 21 catches for
427 yards. Johnnie Morton has 41 receptions for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' running ``was something that always came up and
probably this year was going to be a tremendous topic of discussion
each week,'' Ross said. ``We haven't had to deal with that.
Obviously, our running game isn't what it used to be. So we've gone
to more throwing, probably more than even I like to do. But it's
where we get our playmaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the surprising start, Ross hasn't escaped criticism.
Against Arizona on Nov. 14, the Lions had just scored a touchdown
and trailed 23-19 late in the game. Instead of kicking an extra
point and hoping for a game-tying field goal later, Ross elected to
try a two-point conversion. It failed. With less than two minutes
left, Detroit faced fourth down deep in Cardinals territory. The
Lions had to go for a touchdown and missed.
</P>
<P>
   The loss seemed to stick with the Lions. They lost 26-17 at
Green Bay last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ever going to look back on it,'' Ross said. ``I'm
going to look ahead. The decision wasn't spontaneous. It was
thought out _ right or wrong. This team needs to take the risks. A
part of why we are where we are is because we have taken some
risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
