<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CIR-XMAS-LIGHTS-ART-N     11-24 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-XMAS-LIGHTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW IT WORKS: HOLIDAY LIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SALLY McGRANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The city of Taylor, Texas, started its holiday lighting display
five years ago. More than 130,000 lights later, downtown Taylor is
ablaze beginning on Thanksgiving weekend with brightly lighted
Christmas trees, characters from nursery rhymes, a wagon train,
teepees, a 20-foot sailing ship, a Santa Claus with his sleigh and
eight reindeer, the Taj Mahal and a rocket ship that commemorates
John Glenn's return to space.
</P>
<P>
   This is no small project: Shanta Kuhl, executive vice president
of the local Chamber of Commerce, said 300 volunteers had spent
four weeks putting up lights in Taylor, a city of 14,700 residents
northeast of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just love it,'' Ms. Kuhl said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, holiday lights are taken for granted as almost every
city in America puts up some type of display. And more than 80
million households in the United States use them to decorate each
year, according to the Minami International Corp., one of the
largest manufacturers of holiday lights.
</P>
<P>
   Today's holiday lights may be a far cry from the traditional
candles that were once used to celebrate the winter solstice or, in
the Christian faith, to represent Jesus as the light of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But in one sense, the lights still have a similar purpose. They
are intended to lighten the mood, raise the spirits. Today, it is
the holiday spirit. Years ago, it was the spirits of Northern
Europeans during the long dark winters.
</P>
<P>
   The first recorded use of lights on a Christmas tree was in
1658, when candles were used in southern Germany, according to
``Christmas Ornaments, Lights and Decorations: A Collector's
Identification and Value Guide,'' by George Johnson (Collector
Books, 1987). The candles were attached to trees by melting them
directly onto the branches, attaching them with pins or clipping
them on with special holders.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1850s, gas tubes were added to real trees in provide
lighting. In 1878, a British company unsuccessfully marketed an
iron Christmas tree that contained channels for gas, which could be
lighted through tiny holes in the branches.
</P>
<P>
   The first electric Christmas lights were developed in 1882,
shortly after the advent of commercial electricity. Each light had
to be individually wired, however, which made the tree very
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1920s, the cost of electric lights had dropped, and
electricity was readily available.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, fashions in holiday lights have come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   In the early part of the century, lights of glass or plastic
with figures of animals, fruits, Santas and even Uncle Sam were
often used to decorate Christmas trees. In the 1950s, many used
bubble lights, which have colored liquid and a special chemical
that sends bubbles up the glass when the light heats up. Rotating
color wheels, twinkling lights and miniature lights followed.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Ritzer Ross, who covers trends in Christmas lights for
Selling Christmas Decorations magazine in Randolph, N.J., said
clear or white lights were still popular for indoor lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers say they are selling more colored lights than in the
past. And bubble lights are making something of a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday lighting has also seen a large swing toward outdoor
lighting. ``People are getting increasingly competitive about
outdoing their neighbors with outdoor decorating,'' Ms. Ritzer Ross
said. ``People are putting more lights outdoors _ trees, bushes,
hanging on eaves, wherever they can put them.''
</P>
<P>
   Outdoors, ``icicles are still very big,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While retailers might think that outdoor lighting fanatics are
just trying to outdo their neighbors, they may have it wrong. For
many enthusiasts, decorations are about Christmas cheer, no matter
how much wattage is required.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Jezioro, of Manassas, Va., decorates his house with about
40,000 lights. Jezioro, who takes 10 days off work around
Thanksgiving to set up his display, explained: ``I've been doing
this for about eight years. It's kind of a childhood fantasy to
have a house with lights on it _ my parents would take us to see
the houses with lights, and we never had the opportunity to
decorate our house because we always rented.''
</P>
<P>
   Jezioro said the 400 strands of lights (which his wife, Barbara,
tests before he hangs them) added about $350 to his electricity
bill in December. He has also revamped his house's wiring. ``All
told with the electronics, I have about five or six thousand
dollars invested,'' he said. When a display has at least 20,000
lights, it can be considered ``very serious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the lights are up at the Jezioros' house, people start
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love seeing the families in their cars with the kids and the
blankets in the back seat,'' Jezioro said. ``It makes it all
worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
