<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    European underdogs have bite
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A club's ticket to the European Champions League depends on its
league finish from the previous season. But three clubs mired in
the lower half of their respective domestic leagues so far are
finding continental play to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorentina, in 10th place in Italy's Serie A, was outplayed by
Manchester United but won 2-0 on Tuesday, as the second round of
group play began.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia, a preseason favorite in the Spanish Primera Division,
is in 10th place, but it thrashed Girodins de Bordeaux 3-0. Another
early flop, Hertha Berlin, in 14th place in the Bundesliga, forged
a 1-1 draw with Barcelona in foggy conditions in the German
capital. For Manchester United, the defending champions, the phrase
``back pass'' will bring a chill down the spines of the normally
reliable Roy Keane and Henning Berg, whose dreadful defending
mistakes led to both Fiorentina goals. In the first case, Gabriel
Batistuta pounced on Keane's effort and slammed home an 18th-minute
goal. In the second half, he intercepted a weak offering from Berg,
then passed over to Adel Balbo, who wasted no time putting home the
second score.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to admire the finish _ that is what the man is good
at,'' United manager Alex Ferguson, said, referring to Batistuta.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia dispatched the French champions in the final 30
minutes, getting all three goals in that time from Francisco
Farrios, Adrian Ilie and Kily Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   And in Berlin, neither team scored in the first half before the
fog rolled in, prompting play to continue with an orange ball.
Barcelona manager Louis van Gaal angrily argued that the game
should have been suspended, while a German television announcer had
to rely on another set of eyes: ``Somebody has just hit the post.
At least that's what I've been told.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Ronaldo out two months
</P>
<P>
   Inter Milan striker Ronaldo will be out at least until February
after suffering another injury to his right knee. Ronaldo, 23, tore
tendons when his cleats got stuck in a muddy patch in Inter's 6-0
rout of Lecce on Sunday. . . . Lazio lost its first Serie A match
in 17 games and had its overall unbeaten string snapped at 23 in a
4-1 drubbing by city rivals AS Roma. Some fans took the result
rather hard. Several Lazio supporters scaled a fence during the
club's training session on Monday and hurled abuse at players,
delaying practice for 20 minutes. Two goals apiece by Marco
Delvecchio and Vincenzo Montella lifted AS Roma into third place,
two points behind Lazio and Juventus.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: New coach, same result
</P>
<P>
   A 77th-minute goal from Jose Antonio Pikabea spoiled the debut
of Real Madrid manager Vicente del Bosque as struggling Real
Sociedad pulled out a 1-1 draw on Saturday. Madrid, which fired
John Toshack last week, went ahead in the 66th minute on a goal by
Savio but had to settle for a draw for the fourth time in its last
six outings. Del Bosque, Real's fourth manager in the past seven
years, also served in a caretaking role in 1993 and 1996. . . .
Deportivo La Coruna took the lead in the Primera Division with a
5-2 win over Sevilla, as Pauleta scored a hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   England: TV stakes get higher
</P>
<P>
   Published reports in London claim that British Telecom is
prepared to bid $2.1 billion to acquire Premier League television
rights starting in 2001, more than double what British Sky
Broadcasting Corp. reportedly is proposing to extend its current
deal. Microsoft Corp. chairman Bill Gates is spearheading a
consortium that might offer a $1.6 billion price tag. . . . BSkyB
was told by the Premier League this week that it would have to sell
off a fraction of its interest in Manchester United. Rupert
Murdoch's U.K. satellite concern holds an 11 percent stake in the
defending champions, and would have to get under 10 percent.
Earlier this season, BSkyB bought a 9.9 percent share in Leeds
United.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Matthaus injured
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich trounced Freiburg 6-1 Saturday for its fifth
consecutive win in the Bundesliga but lost defender Lothar Matthaus
for at least a week with a strained leg muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Torneo playoffs
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the Torneo Invierno playoffs begin tonight
when Pachuca and Morelia meet to fill the eighth and last
postseason slot. Sunday's second leg will be televised (1 p.m.,
Telemundo), with the quarterfinals getting under way next week.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil: Cruzeiro ousted
</P>
<P>
   Playoff upsets continued in the national championship postseason
Sunday, when Atletico Mineiro got two goals from Guilherme to
eliminate favored Cruzeiro 3-2. Mineiro, the last team to qualify
for the eight-team playoffs, is the first to reach the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
