<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, Nov. 25. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-PILOT (Cairo) _ Back in Kafr al-Dabusi, a farming
community set against the lush fields and irrigation canals of the
Nile delta, the villagers still remember the dashing young airman,
Gamil al-Batouti, who would circle in his small plane, scaring the
pigeons from their roosts and sending the women trilling in wonder.
Today, all of Egypt knows about Batouti, but it is an awful
prominence he has suddenly gained, one that has nothing to do with
his life of accomplishment and modest hometown stardom. American
investigators believe Batouti may have deliberately caused the
crash of EgyptAir Flight 990. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   OPERATION-SMILE-II (Beijing) _ Early last August, an
impoverished farmer brought his young son to the Plastic Surgery
Hospital in Beijing to take advantage of a once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity: For one week, plastic surgeons from the American
charity Operation Smile were operating for free on poor Chinese
children with cleft lips and palates, the congenital condition that
afflicted his boy. But that elation quickly turned to anguish when
his son returned from surgery and he discovered that the wrong
operation had been performed. A Special Report, the second of two
parts, by Elisabeth Rosenthal and Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-TREASON (Jerusalem) _ A newspaper's publication of
partial transcripts from the treason trial of Mordechai Vanunu,
arrested in 1986 for alleged disclosures of Israel's nuclear
program, is reopening the debate on the country's policy of nuclear
ambiguity. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ASSISI-BASILICA (Assisi, Italy) _ When a powerful earthquake
crushed the vaulted ceiling of the basilica of St. Francis of
Assisi two years ago, the damage seemed irreparable. Instead, on
Sunday, the early Renaissance masterpiece will be entirely
re-opened to the public.But another expected miracle _ a free
market experiment in disaster relief that was supposed to rehouse
thousands of victims within two years _ has not materialized. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SUBWAY (Tokyo) _ After waiting decades for a new
underground rail line that would relieve the over crowding on the
above-ground train that now encircles the central city, it now
seems like Tokyo has produced yet another boondoggle. The problem:
The new subway does not run in a complete circle. ``It's like a
Rolls-Royce that you can't shift into reverse,'' said Shintaro
Ishihara, Tokyo's outspoken governor. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-GORE (Undated) _ The two most famous students of the
Bill Clinton political school _ Hillary Rodham Clinton and Al Gore
_ have graduated. But now that they are finally out on their own
politically, they seem to be sticking to the same text. It should
not come as a surprise that Mrs. Clinton and Gore should be
approaching their races in like-minded ways. They are both
incredibly smart, ambitious and determined. Yet they can be a bit
tone deaf politically. So why wouldn't they soak up the wisdom of
their mentor, a world class instinctive politician and tactician?
By Richard Berke.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-RITALIN-SCHOOLS (Denver) _ The Colorado Board of Education
has become the first in the nation to adopt a policy against
teachers urging parents to put their children on behavior
controlling drugs like Ritalin and Luvox, rekindling a national
debate over the growing use of such drugs by school children. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   GIVING-THANKS-I (New York) _ A factory worker walked by a
homeless man near the Port Authority for years; once, he tossed a
couple of quarters his way. Thus is set in motion a remarkable
story of charity, kinship, coincidence and reunion. The worker
befriended the homeless man, cleaned him up, discovered he was from
same part of Virginia and vowed to take him home to his mother,
whose church had been praying for him for three years. Now back
home, the homeless man, Raymond, is playing the organ for the
church choir. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The American economy rolled into autumn
with even more momentum than had been thought, its rapid and widely
envied growth poised to set a record for longevity. ``How can you
not be thankful,'' said James Glassman, chief U.S. economist at
Chase Securities. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-KIDNEY-TREATMENT (Undated) _ Two new studies suggest that
flaws in the treatment of kidney failure may compromise the care of
thousands of people in the United States. The first report revealed
that people with kidney failure who had dialysis at for-profit
treatment centers were 20 percent more likely to die and 26 percent
less likely to be referred for a transplant than patients treated
at not-for-profit centers. The finding has broad implications,
because two-thirds of the 200,000 Americans on dialysis are treated
at for-profit centers. By Denise Grady.
</P>
