<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT PRESIDENT WILL BE AN INTERNATIONALIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When George W. Bush plunged headlong into the
simmering debate over America's role in the world as a foe of
isolationism and protectionism, he probably guaranteed that the
next president of the United States will be an internationalist who
advocates free trade.
</P>
<P>
   That is true because the man who takes the presidential oath of
office on Jan. 20, 2001, will very likely be one of four
candidates: Bush or John McCain, who are seeking the Republican
presidential nomination; Al Gore or Bill Bradley, the Democratic
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   All four are allied with the twin pillars of foreign policy that
have guided America since World War II: internationalism and free
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Once Patrick Buchanan severed his ties with the Republican Party
and announced plans to seek the presidential nomination of the
Reform Party, the GOP lost its most powerful and bombastic public
advocate of isolationism and protectionism, the discredited
principles that once dominated the party.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush was critical of President Clinton's handling of
certain aspects of foreign policy, including his dealings with
Russia and China, he said little in his Nov. 19 speech at the
Ronald Reagan Library in Simi Valley, Calif., that many Democrats
would find disagreeable.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a bow to bipartisanship, Bush contended that fears
raised by those who favor isolationism and protectionism have no
place ``in the party of Reagan or the party of Truman.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Russian brutality in Chechnya, Bush said that international
lending institutions should suspend aid to Moscow if it continues
``killing women and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Of China, he said that nation should be seen ``as a competitor
not a strategic partner.''
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty that Clinton
favors and that was defeated recently in the Republican-controlled
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But since Bush is only a candidate for president and not yet the
holder of that exalted office, his views on specific relationships
and issues can change drastically in the months and years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor's criticism of Clinton's handling of foreign
affairs was made in the same week that Clinton and other leaders at
a 54-nation summit in Turkey chastised Russia for its conduct in
Chechnya. At the same time, the United States and China reached an
agreement that will pave the way for China's entry into the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   It was anticipated that Bush would find fault with Clinton's
conduct of foreign policy. But the most important aspect of Bush's
speech was his unequivocal alignment with internationalism and free
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The views he expressed were very much like those of his father,
who as president put together a remarkable coalition of countries
to counter Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   If the Texas governor's position could be summed up in a single
sentence, it was contained in his own words: ``America must be
involved in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Republicans would agree with that declaration, because
there still is a pocket of steadfast isolationism in the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout much of the 20th century, Republican
internationalists have had to battle Republican isolationists. At
the end of World War I, Woodrow Wilson ran headlong into the
opposition of Massachusetts Sen. Henry Cabot Lodge _ the Republican
chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee _ when the
president tried unsuccessfully to win Senate approval of the Treaty
of Versailles and American participation in the League of Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, after World War II had begun in Europe,
Republicans, with the support of some Democrats, clung to
isolationism. But at the 1940 GOP national convention, a miracle
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   When they gathered in Philadelphia to nominate a presidential
candidate, their chief contenders were isolationists, Sen. Robert
A. Taft of Ohio, District Attorney (and later governor) Thomas E.
Dewey of New York, and Sen. Arthur Vandenberg of Michigan. But as
delegates roamed through hotel lobbies in silly hats, Adolf
Hitler's conquest of continental Europe became complete with the
fall of France.
</P>
<P>
   Britain then stood alone against Nazi aggression.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Republicans began to pay attention to a colorful
Hoosier lawyer who had been a Democrat and as head of the
Commonwealth and Southern utility company had defeated the
Roosevelt administration's Tennessee Valley Authority in a key
court case.
</P>
<P>
   His name was Wendell Willkie and he won the nomination but lost
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   An internationalist who favored aid to the victims of German
aggression, he later carried a message from Franklin Roosevelt to
British Prime Minister Winston Churchill and wrote a popular book
about his wartime travels called ``One World.''
</P>
<P>
   The next big battle within the GOP over foreign policy occurred
in 1952, when Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower defeated Taft for the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1964, Sen. Barry Goldwater of Arizona, who was skeptical
of foreign commitments, won the GOP nomination over Gov. Nelson
Rockefeller of New York and was badly defeated in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have had their own internecine battles over
protectionism and the war in Vietnam, but, for the most part,
internationalists have dominated the party since the days of
Woodrow Wilson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
