<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0507 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-INTERNET-HATER-2TAKES     11-24 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HATER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITOR EXPLORES UNINTENDED, AND NEGATIVE, SIDE OF TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephen L. Talbott, a former software programmer and technical
writer, has always been wary of computers and their effect on the
human psyche. Even as he made a living editing books on computer
programming, he wondered aloud whether the machines were making
people's lives worse, not better.
</P>
<P>
   But when colleagues and outsiders would needle him about his own
choices _ particularly the fact that he used a word processor to
write _ he would shake his head in resignation. It seemed almost
physically impossible, he said, to return to the old days of
molding thoughts using pen and paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really nervous about it,'' Talbott said. ``I asked
myself, `Will I be able to write on a pad?'''
</P>
<P>
   Today Talbott, 53, has transformed that feeling of inertia, of
not being able to shake off the grip of technology, into the focal
point of his life's work. He is the editor of a small but
influential e-mail newsletter called NetFuture, which is an effort
to open people's minds to what he sees as the unintended, and
usually negative, impact of technology on society. His 4,500
subscribers include people involved with the Internet, nationally
recognized computer scientists and other people who are typically
champions of technology, not skeptical about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a largely undiscovered national treasure,'' wrote Peter
J. Denning, a computer science professor at George Mason University
in Virginia, in an e-mail message about the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Articles in NetFuture, which usually comes out every few weeks
and is often forwarded to other e-mail lists, go beyond immediate
concerns of privacy and censorship. They look instead at the ripple
effects of technology, like how people's lives have changed as
tasks are automated and how communities have fared since the dawn
of the automobile.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Talbott embarked on publishing his newsletter, in
1995, he continued to depend on technology for his writing. And he
hated it. Working on a computer, he said, caused eyestrain, neck
aches and the feeling that his brain was ``turning to mush.'' A
year before he started NetFuture, he and his family had moved to
rural upstate New York, near the tiny town of Harlemville, where
they bought a house with a wraparound porch, nestled in a wooded
hillside. Yet he was withdrawing from those surroundings whenever
sat down to write.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1998, he resolved to make a drastic change. He
would sit in front of his computer for no more than 50 percent of
his workday. He would try writing without a word processor.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, in his modest office a mile down the road from
his home, Talbott opened a file cabinet to retrieve some of the
fruits of that decision. He drew out four sheets of yellow note
paper. They showed the slight slant of his handwritten sentences,
cascading down the page on every other line, in pencil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not write any other way now,'' he said. Having the
simplicity of a notepad and a pencil enables him to do his writing
while sitting anywhere in his house, he said, usually in front of
huge picture windows that overlook the foothills of the Berkshire
Mountains. Every so often, perhaps if a red-tailed hawk swoops by,
he puts down his pencil and grabs his binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm  &UR; in &LR;  the writing more, birds notwithstanding,'' he said,
smiling. ``It's been a real pleasure to discover my own error.''
</P>
<P>
   That discovery is one of many that appears to have honed
Talbott's philosophy regarding technology. He sums it up with these
words: ``The computer is our hope if we can accept it as our enemy.
As our friend, it will destroy us.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott, a slim balding man with white hair and a trim beard,
has the air of a philosopher when he talks. His voice has a natural
hoarseness; his deep-set gray eyes are wide and clear. Talk of
turning computers into enemies may sound extreme to some people.
But to Talbott, his statement is a riddle he delights in
unwrapping.
</P>
<P>
   Only when people consider the computer their enemy, he
explained, do they pull away from it. That act of pulling away can
bring a feeling of freedom, he said, and a new appreciation of the
personal, the creative, the natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer gives us the opportunity to assert ourselves
against it,'' Talbott said. ``That is a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott first touched a computer in 1980. Before then, he had
tried to make a living as an organic farmer and as the founder of a
scientific magazine called Pensee, which focused on theories of how
natural catastrophic events have played a role in Earth's history.
But the magazine folded within three years and farming failed to
pay the bills. So Talbott taught himself how to program computers
and got a technical-writing job at Tektronix, a computer company in
Portland, Ore., where his brother-in-law worked.
</P>
<P>
   That job led Talbott to other computer work, and he was hired in
1991 by Tim O'Reilly, the founder of a publishing and consulting
company that soon became highly regarded among academics and
software engineers for its no-nonsense approach to technology. In
1992, O'Reilly published one of the most influential books about
the early Internet, ``The Whole Internet User's Guide and
Catalog,'' which described how to find resources on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
