<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0509 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-INTERNET-HATER-2NDTAK     11-24 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HATER-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the Internet. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   O'Reilly has often embraced new ways of thinking about the
Internet. So when Talbott told him that he wanted to start an
e-mail list and write a book designed to shake up traditional
thinking about computers, O'Reilly gave him the computer resources
he needed and the time to write.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it's one of the most important books I've ever
published,'' O'Reilly said of the finished project, ``The Future
Does Not Compute: Transcending the Machines in Our Midst,''
Talbott's 1995 book that elaborated on many of the ideas that come
through in his newsletter. NetFuture's Web page
(www.oreilly.com/stevet/netfuture) is still maintained on O'Reilly
&AMP; Associates computers, though Talbott left the company in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The belief that people have a responsibility to think critically
about technology pervades Talbott's writing and the work of other
contributors to NetFuture. One topic that is often covered, for
example, is agriculture: growing genetically engineered crops , he
and other contributors have written, will have a devastating impact
on ecosystems. Another perennial is education: universities that
focus on computerized instruction and distance education, Talbott
has argued, have resorted to ``fact shoveling.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott even questions the free and democratic digital culture
that Wired magazine salutes. The fact that Internet users tend to
be more educated and politically involved is not necessarily
something to applaud, Talbott wrote in 1997; those qualities are
merely byproducts of the fact that people with access to computers
tend to come from privileged backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   His newsletter has brought praise from readers, even those who
do not always agree with everything he writes. A note from Lance
McKee, a vice president in the Open GIS Consortium, a group that
promotes technology for the creation of online maps, , is among
several messages from subscribers that Talbott has posted on the
NetFuture Web site. ``I earn my living in the computer industry,
and I'm not sorry I do,'' McKee wrote. But he continued, ``I am
drawn to NetFuture by both my curiosity and my desire to make
choices I won't regret.''
</P>
<P>
   A few incoming messages are less approving. A few weeks ago,
Talbott got an e-mail message from a reader who compared him to the
Unabomber, Theodore Kaczynski, who railed against technology and
sent mail-bombs that killed 3 people and injured 22 between 1978
and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott said he was slightly puzzled by the comparison. He said
he had not read more than a few paragraphs of Kaczynski's writings,
did not feel the need to read more and condemned such violence. But
regarding Kaczynski's ideas, Talbott said, ``I'm not worried if
there is some overlap there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Talbott rejects the label of Luddite. His wife, Phyllis,
also dismisses such a characterization. ``He is not
anti-technology,'' she said. ``You can be aware of the
repercussions of something and not get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott is keenly aware that he is able to survive and support
his family _ the couple have three sons _ because he devoted 18
years of his life to writing about computer programming. Two of the
books he edited while at O'Reilly &AMP; Associates were how-to manuals
on programming with Perl, a language that has proliferated on the
Web. Royalties from those books, along with income from his wife's
work as a part-time home-care nurse, have fed his family and paid
his mortgage. Now, as the royalties dwindle, he is asking his
readers for donations and seeking other sources of income. He has
received about $4,500 in donations so far.
</P>
<P>
   A fledgling nonprofit organization called the Nature Institute
has helped as well. The institute is dedicated to research that
focuses on how elements of nature are interconnected. It was
founded last summer by Craig Holdrege, a biologist, schoolteacher
and neighbor of the Talbotts. Talbott joined the Nature Institute
as a senior researcher, and his newsletter is now one of the
institute's publications. A few rooms on the first floor of a house
in Harlemville make up the group's office.
</P>
<P>
   If you walk up to that office on any afternoon, you might see
Talbott through the window, typing on his computer. He still uses
it almost every weekday, sometimes typing in sentences written on
his yellow note pad. And he still pores through computer manuals to
work through glitches or figure out some of the more obscure
qualities of Linux, the operating system he uses.
</P>
<P>
   His newsletter, in fact, does not have a print counterpart; it
exists only online for reasons of both financing and distribution.
In that way, Talbott embodies his riddle: his lifework springs from
his computer, as long as he makes it his enemy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1654EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
