<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0520 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-TURKEY-TEXAS-TEX     11-24 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY, TEXAS, POP. 500
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TURKEY, Texas _ A full-body turkey costume, complete from feet
to wattle, is uncomfortable to wear, particularly on a hot evening
when not a breeze stirs the nearly empty streets of this Panhandle
town.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Johnson, owner of the bed and breakfast Hotel Turkey, had
just bought the turkey costume in Amarillo, 100 miles north, in
anticipation of the CBS camera crew that had called to say it would
be arriving to film a segment about Turkey, Texas, to air on ``Late
Night With David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   So Johnson put on the turkey costume to surprise the
``Letterman'' crew. He waited in the lobby of the 1927-vintage
Hotel Turkey. And he waited. And waited. The crew was late. He
couldn't sit because of the tail feathers. Johnson paced the
parlor, which is decorated in Victorian frill, punctuated with a
few mementos of Turkey's famous native son, western swing king Bob
Wills.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, also a Turkey native, said some folks in town didn't
believe that Letterman's crew would show up.
</P>
<P>
   But that's Turkey for you. About half the 500 Turkey residents
believe that the cotton-and-peanut farming town will someday be
known as a tourist destination, partly because of its western swing
music heritage, partly because of its wonderful name, and partly
because of its proximity to Caprock Canyons State Park.
</P>
<P>
   The other half aren't convinced.
</P>
<P>
   Hot and frustrated, Johnson took off the turkey suit. Will
Turkey's fortunes ever change?
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Biff Henderson and the ``Letterman'' crew
pulled up, ready for two days of filming for a few-minutes-long
segment that aired Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson now says he should have known the crew would show. He's
one of the believers who are working to change the future of this
town abandoned by two-thirds of its population in the 1950s after
the railroad quit running on the Estelline-to-Lubbock spur and
after farming became the province of only those with thousands of
acres. A generation of farm children left for work in the cities.
Roofs fell in on Main Street. Henderson told the nation on
``Letterman'' that Turkey is one sleepy little town.
</P>
<P>
   A few plucky folks are working to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the justice of the peace, and his wife, Suzie, the
mayor, host an annual reservations-only Thanksgiving dinner for
more than 100 paying guests at Hotel Turkey. Oftentimes, the meals
are interrupted by telephone calls from radio talk show hosts from
around the nation who want to have a Thanksgiving-Day chat about
the quaint life in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, son of Clema Johnson, who ran a Turkey beauty shop for
more than 70 years, cutting hair and giving perms until she was in
her 90s, can tell them this:
</P>
<P>
   Wild turkeys still roost in the cottonwood trees along the
creeks, and they mingle with cattle herds, trying to steal the
feed. Cotton and peanut and sweet potato and watermelon farmers
still gather at the Turkey Cafe and Drive-In at the intersection of
Texas 86 and 70, where they talk about crop-dusting, road paving
and rattlesnakes that refuse to die, no matter how many times you
run over them with a pickup. Those snakes just sink into the red
dirt of the unpaved farm roads and manage to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Farms still flourish. Trucks _ sometimes 20 a day _ have been
leaving the peanut harvest in recent weeks, each hauling 50,000
pounds of peanuts to distributors who ship them out as seed or
edible peanuts for candy. Hershey's is a big buyer of Turkey
peanuts, according to the weekly newspaper ``The Valley Tribune''
of Quitaque, another small town down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The farms are far larger than they used to be, and there are far
fewer of them, said Tom Eudy, who retired after 47 years raising
cotton. And farm owners require far fewer workers than they did
some 40 years ago, when Turkey was a bustling center that drew
crowds to The Gem movie theater and the drugstore on Saturday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   The Gem has been closed for about 40 years. Lawana Cruse and her
sister-in-law, Marie Cruse, bought it for $10,000 four years ago, a
high price tag in a town with buildings that sometimes sell for
about $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters-in-law persuaded the Turkey Volunteer Fire
Department to bring two pump trucks to the theater and hose out 35
years' worth of Panhandle dust from the interior. The Cruses have
been successfully applying for grants and renovating the theater
for use as a performing arts center.
</P>
<P>
   Lawana Cruse also wants to open a museum of local farming
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good museum for Bob Wills, but we also ought to have
a museum to honor the people who stayed and worked,'' Lawana Cruse
said.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of economic development, fiddle player Bob Wills is
Turkey's real cash crop. Born March 6, 1905, in Turkey, Wills
learned how to barber at Ham's Barbershop, which is still operating
after 88 years as a family business on Main Street. Wills went on
to form the band sponsored by Fort Worth's Burris Flour Mills, the
Light Crust Doughboys, and then the Texas Playboys. Wills moved to
Fort Worth in 1963 and died there in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's Bob Wills Foundation puts on Jim Bob Wills Days the
last Saturday of every April. For two weeks, the town is packed
with the recreational vehicles of 10,000 or so western swing fans
and bands that play in the music festival, watch the parade and
attend the annual barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder why so many come, what with the dust and
wind,'' says Wilma Eudy, wife of Tom Eudy.
</P>
<P>
   The festival also raises money for community projects, including
the purchase of the old Turkey High School _ former home of the
Turks _ and elementary school, both abandoned in the 1970s for lack
of students. The schools now house City Hall and the Bob Wills
Museum. The museum is Turkey's main year-round attraction. In
October, 50 visitors had signed the guest book. They came from
Texas but also Missouri, Kansas, Alabama, Michigan, Ohio, New
Mexico, Nevada and California to see the hometown of the man known
for ``San Antonio Rose, Faded Love'' and other classics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of people do want to see Turkey grow, but I like it like
it is,'' says museum volunteer Lorene Setliff, a third-generation
Turkey resident. ``It's quiet and safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, there's plenty of turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The old schools also house a community center where each year
for the past 20 years, the Turkey Proud Committee has put together
a Turkey turkey dinner the Sunday before Thanksgiving. About 200 to
300 people are served.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Baptists bring the salads, the Church of Christ brings the
mashed potatoes and the Methodists bring something else. The
foundation brings the turkey,'' Gary Johnson says. ``Then everyone
eats until they run out of food.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson donned his turkey costume for the ``Letterman'' crew
before they left the bed and breakfast. The camera was packed by
the time he got the wattle and tail feathers on and straight, but
that's OK with Johnson. He knows he has a lot of promoting to do,
and that turkey costume is bound to come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0521 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1128-COX     11-24 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1128-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: BUSH FINDS THE SWEET SPOT
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Glass.
 &HT;    Moving in both (k) Commentary and (i) International categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Nov. 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``I'm going to be the next president of the United
States,'' Texas Gov. George W. Bush recently told foreign policy
guru Richard Perle. ``I don't need your help to be elected,'' Bush
went on to say. ``I know how to get that done. But I do need your
help to be a good president.''
</P>
<P>
   We see a candidate who is at once arrogant and humble, disarming
and demanding. Judging by the company he keeps and what he has to
say, Bush seems to have found a political sweet spot.
</P>
<P>
   Perle is a veteran conservative Democrat who held a key Pentagon
job in the Republican 1980s. He has since become rich and says he
doesn't want to return to government. Bush says he's running a
``positive campaign,'' which means he doesn't want to wallop
President Clinton on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Perle does. ``The current crowd is the least component to
hold office in the last half of the 20th century,'' he says. ``They
view every foreign policy issue in terms of how things will look.
Lots of people have died as a result of their concentration on
appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidents hold wide latitude in how they act abroad. History
shows that specific foreign policy issues raised in campaigns are
rarely the same ones that officeholders must confront. So evidence
of strong character and good judgment are key tests of what to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great deal he has to learn,'' Perle says, speaking
of Bush's general lack of expertise with big global and military
issues. ``But,'' he adds, ``he's a challenging student who in my
encounters with him has demonstrated a tough-mindedness that I find
encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Bush political calendar called for a high-profile
foreign policy rollout, the advisers Bush chose and where he chose
to speak were as helpful to his prospects as anything he had to
say.
</P>
<P>
   His eight core advisers worked mostly in second-level but
nevertheless pivotal government posts, either for his father or for
Ronald Reagan. One of them, Condoleeza Rice, a National Security
Council aide under Bush I, could well follow yet another fluent
Russian speaker into the Cabinet: Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Bush II selected as his venue the Reagan Library in Yorba Linda,
Calif. Nancy Reagan sat beaming beside former Secretary of State
George P. Schultz, the campaign's elder statesman, whom Bush
thanked ``for your decades of service, for your kindness, (and) for
your counsel over the past few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the uniform hard-line foreign policy views of his chief
counselors, it's hard to see how Bush could be credibly attacked
from the right.
</P>
<P>
   But he promptly was by Californian Bruce Herschensohn, who held
that Steve Forbes is the only candidate who has made it clear that
``we will defend Taiwan from a Chinese attack.'' Herschensohn spoke
at the National Press Club, along with several other well-known
conservative activists, including Richard Viguerie and Paul
Weyrich.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is fortunate to have these heavy-hitters running around
Iowa and New Hampshire on his behalf. But Bush is even more
fortunate since their attacks help define him as a centrist figure
_ the kind of ``compassionate conservative'' whom voters are apt to
favor.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
