<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1128-COX     11-24 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1128-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: BUSH FINDS THE SWEET SPOT
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Glass.
 &HT;    Moving in both (k) Commentary and (i) International categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Nov. 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``I'm going to be the next president of the United
States,'' Texas Gov. George W. Bush recently told foreign policy
guru Richard Perle. ``I don't need your help to be elected,'' Bush
went on to say. ``I know how to get that done. But I do need your
help to be a good president.''
</P>
<P>
   We see a candidate who is at once arrogant and humble, disarming
and demanding. Judging by the company he keeps and what he has to
say, Bush seems to have found a political sweet spot.
</P>
<P>
   Perle is a veteran conservative Democrat who held a key Pentagon
job in the Republican 1980s. He has since become rich and says he
doesn't want to return to government. Bush says he's running a
``positive campaign,'' which means he doesn't want to wallop
President Clinton on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Perle does. ``The current crowd is the least component to
hold office in the last half of the 20th century,'' he says. ``They
view every foreign policy issue in terms of how things will look.
Lots of people have died as a result of their concentration on
appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidents hold wide latitude in how they act abroad. History
shows that specific foreign policy issues raised in campaigns are
rarely the same ones that officeholders must confront. So evidence
of strong character and good judgment are key tests of what to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great deal he has to learn,'' Perle says, speaking
of Bush's general lack of expertise with big global and military
issues. ``But,'' he adds, ``he's a challenging student who in my
encounters with him has demonstrated a tough-mindedness that I find
encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Bush political calendar called for a high-profile
foreign policy rollout, the advisers Bush chose and where he chose
to speak were as helpful to his prospects as anything he had to
say.
</P>
<P>
   His eight core advisers worked mostly in second-level but
nevertheless pivotal government posts, either for his father or for
Ronald Reagan. One of them, Condoleeza Rice, a National Security
Council aide under Bush I, could well follow yet another fluent
Russian speaker into the Cabinet: Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Bush II selected as his venue the Reagan Library in Yorba Linda,
Calif. Nancy Reagan sat beaming beside former Secretary of State
George P. Schultz, the campaign's elder statesman, whom Bush
thanked ``for your decades of service, for your kindness, (and) for
your counsel over the past few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the uniform hard-line foreign policy views of his chief
counselors, it's hard to see how Bush could be credibly attacked
from the right.
</P>
<P>
   But he promptly was by Californian Bruce Herschensohn, who held
that Steve Forbes is the only candidate who has made it clear that
``we will defend Taiwan from a Chinese attack.'' Herschensohn spoke
at the National Press Club, along with several other well-known
conservative activists, including Richard Viguerie and Paul
Weyrich.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is fortunate to have these heavy-hitters running around
Iowa and New Hampshire on his behalf. But Bush is even more
fortunate since their attacks help define him as a centrist figure
_ the kind of ``compassionate conservative'' whom voters are apt to
favor.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
