<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0525 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-TEACHING-HOSPITALS-HN     11-24 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-HOSPITALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING HOSPITALS URGE CONGRESS TO REQUIRE INSURERS TO PAY FEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release over the Thanksgiving holiday weekend)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By JUDY HOLLAND and DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Teaching hospitals intend to press Congress to
require managed care providers, private insurers and large
employers to pay a special fee to help cover the costs of training
medical residents.
</P>
<P>
   The new lobbying campaign was being cranked up after the
teaching hospitals won a big victory earlier this month when
Congress restored to teaching hospitals more than $1 billion in
Medicare cuts made in the 1997 Balanced Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not enough to cover the cost of training medical
residents, conducting medical research, and caring for the
traditionally sicker and poorer patients that these institutions
attract, according to Dr. Jordan Cohen, president of the
Association of American Medical Colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare is one payer,'' Cohen said. ``Other payers, all of
whom benefit from teaching hospitals, should pay their fair
share.'' The time has come for Congress to require that other
insurers also pony up, he said, because the training of medical
residents is a ``societal good not paid for by the competitive
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Private insurers once covered much of the extra costs at
teaching hospitals. After managed care providers squeezed those
payments, the institutions came to rely more on Medicare payments,
until those also were cut back.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Congress now must find a way to pay for teaching
hospitals' services ``without having to depend upon patient
revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, a long-time champion of teaching hospitals, wants
Congress to create a Medical Education Trust Fund to finance the
costs of training medical residents. That fund would be financed by
a 1.5 percent tax on health insurance premiums for private
insurers. The bill would also transfer to the newly created fund
the existing Medicare and Medicaid contributions for medical
education.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan's legislation is co-sponsored by Sens. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., and Barbara A. Mikulski and was introduced on
the House side by Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y. Rep. Ben Cardin, D-Md.,
has proposed a similar measure that would place a 1 percent tax on
health care insurance plan premiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing the funding source for graduate medical education
from primarily Medicare funds to multiple layers would protect
graduate medical education for the long term,'' Moynihan told the
Senate earlier this month. ``Teaching hospitals are national
treasures; they are the very best in the world. Yet today they find
themselves in a precarious financial situation as market forces
reshape the health care delivery system in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Muller, president and CEO of the University of Chicago
Hospitals and Health Systems, who chairs the Association of
American Medical Colleges, said he is confident that Congress will
act favorably on the Moynihan legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of Congress and the administration saw that some
teaching hospitals were in real trouble,'' Muller said. ``We think
we can help shape the debate next fall. People feel some
substantial changes have to go forth in the health care system.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Spencer Foreman, president of Montefiore Medical Center in
Bronx, N.Y., said teaching hospitals are ``in an environment in
which everyone, including us, is just hanging on by our
fingernails.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreman said teaching hospitals and health insurance payers
``are caught in a tug of war in which the payers are winning _ and
that is causing a substantial amount of disruption for the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Montefiore stands to lose $10 million in Medicare payments over
five years _ more than any other teaching hospital _ under a new
payment system approved this month by Congress that would more
evenly distribute Medicare money for resident training.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new system, 121 teaching hospitals will get less than
they received in the past. Those hospitals previously received more
per resident than other hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, about 300 hospitals will receive more
Medicare funding under the new formula.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Coombs, vice president for medical affairs at the
University of Washington Medical Center in Seattle, said all
insurers, Medicare and Medicaid must be required to pay for the
training of young doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medical education is a public commodity,'' Coombs said. ``It's
something that everyone benefits from. It's a very expensive and
scarce resource and the public demands high quality.'' The issue of
how to pay for it, he said, ``needs to be right on the top of our
political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judy Holland and Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or
at judy &LR; hearstdc.com and dan &LR; hearstdc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
