<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES DEAL EMERGING ON VIEQUES BOMBING RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By STEWART M. POWELL   
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Wednesday the Pentagon and
Puerto Rico are ``making real headway'' toward a compromise to
reopen a Navy bombing range on the island of Vieques, with an
announcement possible ``in the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, fresh from a 10-day trip to Southeastern Europe
and Turkey, told reporters in the White House Rose Garden that he
and his administration have ``worked very hard'' to balance the
combat training requirements of the Navy and Marine Corps at the
island bombing range with the demands of Puerto Rico to permanently
end bombardment that has occurred on Vieques since the outset of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting there,'' Clinton said in remarks following a
traditional presidential pardon to spare a Thanksgiving turkey.
``And I hope in the next few days we'll have something to say about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Pentagon and the government of Puerto Rico
``have been working together'' in closed-door discussions. He
praised the ``good faith'' efforts to seek an agreement designed to
end a seven month standoff between Puerto Rico and the Navy over
future use of the target range. The discussions have involved Gov.
Pedro Rossello of Puerto Rico; Carlos Romero-Barcelo, Puerto Rico's
nonvoting representative in Congress; Defense Secretary William
Cohen; and Navy Secretary Richard Danzig.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, assigned by Clinton to seek a compromise, is expected to
brief the president on the results of the discussions as early as
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he faces a decision trying to balance ``two
legitimate issues'' _ the concerns of Puerto Rico's 3.8 million
residents and the 9,300 civilians living on Vieques, and the Navy's
``absolutely legitimate concern of sending all of our units out
combat ready.''
</P>
<P>
   On Vieques, eight miles east of the main island of Puerto Rico,
an 899-acre bombing range and an adjacent 11,000-acre buffer and
maneuver zone have been closed since April 19 when a Marine pilot
mistakenly targeted a range observation post atop a 450-foot hill.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot dropped two 500 pound bombs, killing Navy contract
security guard David Sanes Rodriguez, 35, and wounding four
civilian employees on the bombing range. Several dozen protesters
are encamped on the range hoping to prevent resumption of bombing
or naval gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really worked hard on this in a good spirit and like I
said, I've spent an awful lot of time on it myself,'' Clinton said.
``And I hope we can get it worked out. I'm not sure. I can't say
for sure we will. But we're making real headway and we're working
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision carries potential political repercussions for
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate campaign in New York and
for Vice President Al Gore's bid to succeed Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans, who are U.S. citizens by birth, are an
influential constituency in New York, where about 60 percent of the
state's 2.6 million Hispanics are Puerto Rican. Hispanic voters
also exercise growing political influence in electorally important
states that are represented in Congress by members of the Hispanic
Congressional Caucus, including California, Florida, Illinois, New
Jersey and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the timing of his decision is being driven by the
looming training schedule of the Navy-Marine Corps battle group,
led by the aircraft carrier USS Dwight D. Eisenhower, that is due
to train on Vieques in early December.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials said Wednesday that ships in the Eisenhower
battle group are scheduled to leave Norfolk, Va., and other East
Coast ports around Dec. 2 to begin a 10-day training exercise that
will include bombing practice by carrier-based warplanes, an
amphibious landing by Marines and naval gunfire by some of all of
the eight destroyers, frigates and cruisers that will accompany the
Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
dispute over the Vieques training range has prompted the Navy to
prepare to carry out live-fire training at other locations without
the combined land, sea and air attacks that traditionally have been
carried out at Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Navy warplanes plan to fly simulated combat missions from the
carrier to attack bombing ranges at Eglin Air Force Base on the
Gulf Coast of Florida and the Pine Castle range north of Orlando.
Marine forces plan to stage an amphibious landing at Camp Lejeune,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Navy warships are preparing to fire 5-inch guns from as far away
as 15 miles against shore targets at the range on Vieques, using
inert, non-explosive shells filled with sand or concrete rather
than traditional training rounds that use between seven and nine
pounds of high explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The gunfire training is designed to overcome a gap in combat
preparations that the Navy says it cannot remedy anywhere else on
the East Coast. Without the planned gunfire training on Vieques, as
many as five of the eight surface warships scheduled to accompany
the Eisenhower to the Persian Gulf in February would be forced to
operate during all or part of their six month deployment without
the gunfire qualification needed to be certified as combat ready.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
