<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0540 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WEB-SOFTWARE-ART-     11-24 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-SOFTWARE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORING YOUR LIFE IN A VIRTUAL DESKTOP ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Colin Brady is one of those executives whose office is a
computer screen, whether it is the one on his home computer, his
work computer or his laptop. So last July, when both his laptop and
his home computer crashed irreparably within a four-day period, it
was as if two-thirds of his office had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   By all measures, Brady should have been in a panic.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he remained calm. His work had been saved in what he
called his ``safe deposit box in the sky,'' an online area that had
been serving as his virtual desktop. Within a few days, after
getting a new laptop, he logged into a Web site called Visto.com
and retrieved his documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a professional lifesaver,'' said Brady, a recruiter for
TMP Worldwide Executive Search.
</P>
<P>
   If last year's buzzword was Web portal, this year it is virtual
desktop, also known as the roaming desktop, the Internet desktop,
and, in some circles, pervasive computing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, portals were heralded for their ability to give people
a central place to find personalized news, sports and stock quotes
from any computer on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, virtual desktops are being promoted for their centrality
and convenience, but they take ``personal'' a step further: users
have constant access to their content _ their files, their address
books, their calendars.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the information you ever wanted to look at will be
available at any time, anywhere,'' said Kevin Herrboldt, director
of engineering for Cyrus InterSoft of Minneapolis, which is
offering virtual desktop software called Speiros. ``You will no
longer say, `I have to go home and download that information from
my computer.'''
</P>
<P>
   So far, virtual-desktop services are mostly available in bits
and pieces. Some companies offer online storage while others
provide Web-based calendars or photo albums. A few companies, such
as MyFamily.com and Bungo.com, have tried to put those services in
one package.
</P>
<P>
   The newest services, which are still being tested, provide
spreadsheet or word-processing programs. The programs do not need
to be loaded onto a computer's hard drive. They can simply be
``borrowed'' or ``rented'' from companies such as Cyrus InterSoft
or Desktop.com that keep the applications on servers and operate
them over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   So far, that concept seems to appeal mostly to users who have
lightning-fast connections.
</P>
<P>
   But just as portals have not become essential for most computer
users, virtual desktops may not live up to their promise either.
How many people, for example, actually manage to keep the
 &UR; physical &LR;  elements of their work and their private lives _ to-do
lists, calendars, projects, phone numbers _ in one place?
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are of the viewpoint: this is where you'll put your
stuff, and that's what people will want to do,'' said Keith Dawson,
editor of an e-mail newsletter, Tasty Bits from the Technology
Front. But ``it's not clear at all that that's what people want to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about security, reliability and privacy, not to mention
bandwidth, may keep some people from adopting the virtual desktop,
Dawson said. ``I don't think it's the next big thing,'' he added.
``I think it's a small thing that may not work.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people say they do not want to be dependent on just one
computer. Many users, in fact, are already using an ad-hoc version
of the virtual desktop: They send documents to their home computer
as e-mail attachments and then use e-mail to transfer them back to
work. Or they set up roaming e-mail accounts, like Hotmail, that
allow them to check their messages from any Web-connected computer,
like those at airport kiosks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is sometimes difficult to maintain a ``home base'' _
that one place that contains the latest version of files. Some
newly updated documents, for example, might be sitting on the
computer at home when they are needed on the laptop or at work.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine, say the advocates of virtual desktops, if those
files could always reside in something like Brady's ``safe deposit
box in the sky.'' The latest changes would always be retrievable;
the documents would be stored on servers maintained by companies
that make a business of keeping that data safe.
</P>
<P>
   That vision has been bandied about for years among computer
manufacturers and information-technology enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Computer historians would argue that the vision was a reality
before the days of personal computers, when people worked on dumb
terminals that were connected to mainframes. In the consumer
market, the idea is more recent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Oracle began developing a device it called the network
computer, a stripped-down machine that tapped into a more powerful
network.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle chief executive Larry Ellison predicted in 1997 that
network computers would outsell PCs by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most analysts agree that the network computer is as good
as dead. But the companies jumping into the virtual desktop
movement are not discouraged. In fact, many of them argue that as
soon as their software gains acceptance among consumers, the idea
of a network computer will probably take off. This time it will be
called a ``Net appliance,'' a device like a cell phone or handheld
computer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only can you go to any computer, you'll have a handheld
device that has a consistent interface'' with the desktop you are
accustomed to seeing on your computer screen, said Sam Fahmy,
president of Bungo.com, one of the virtual-desktop companies.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most of the virtual desktops run on a typical Web
browser, like Netscape or Internet Explorer. Users create
``desktops'' by setting up a user ID and password. Then they upload
files from their computers into the servers maintained by the
desktop companies. Entering data into Web-based calendars and
address books can often be done on the fly, using fill-in-the-blank
forms. Desktop.com provides online calculators, applications that
make graphs of stock quotes and notepads that act as word
processors.
</P>
<P>
   Cyrus InterSoft, the company making Speiros, is taking a
different approach. It is abandoning the Web interface and
marketing a standalone product that acts something like a browser,
except that is designed specifically to maintain the security of
personal documents and run applications like spreadsheet programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web was meant to be a place to broadcast public
information,'' said Herrboldt of Cyrus InterSoft. ``It was never
meant to provide a secure location for storing information.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is hoping to add Speiros to Internet computers that
are in airport kiosks. It believes that people would be willing to
download Speiros onto their laptops and computers, since they are
already accustomed to downloading the latest version of Netscape
for Web browsing.
</P>
<P>
   But dial-up users, beware: Trying to maneuver around a
full-service virtual desktop, whether using a Web browser or
another piece of software, can be a chore. If loading a simple Web
page can take minutes using a dial-up modem, imagine the agony of
using a word-processing program that runs over the Web from a
server thousands of miles away. Even over a speedy T-1 line, the
process can be like typing underwater .
</P>
<P>
   Those who have adopted some form of virtual desktop (often those
in areas with broadband Internet access) use them as communal
spaces as much as personal ones. Once data resides on a networked
server, outside a private hard drive, anyone with a password can
gain access. The online desktop becomes part virtual bulletin
board, part virtual conference room.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Stuart Fullinwider, an investor in Bungo.com who
lives in Denver, uses the service to publish a schedule of his
son's ice hockey games, which other team members can tap into. John
Blair, a 40-year-old resident of Longview, Wash., puts photographs
of his late father on a virtual desktop he built using
MyFamily.com. His 10 brothers and sisters, who are scattered around
the country, can log in and add their own. Last summer, the group
planned a reunion using the service. ``It's caused a lot more
interaction,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   The family-and-friends benefit is not lost on virtual-desktop
companies. Capturing an audience, particularly one that multiplies
with every group enlisted, can translate into lucrative advertising
revenues and commissions on e-commerce products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service can wrap you in more closely and make you loyal,''
said Dawson, the newsletter editor. ``If your stuff is there, you
are going to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much stuff a person will put in their virtual desktops
is an open question. Marlene Cupit, a 60-year-old resident of
Hurst, Texas, stores family stories on a MyFamily.com site that
nearly 80 family members can enter. Because of the password
protection, she said she was confident that no one else can gain
access. The family even talks about financial matters using the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Others may be less trusting. ``I think people will use these for
nonsensitive data,'' said Bob Rankin, an editor of Tourbus, an
e-mail newsletter. But they will demand high levels of security, he
said, for more private materials. ``Especially,'' he added, ``after
the first highly publicized hacking incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Each virtual desktop company promises that their customers'
documents are safe; many have encrypted the materials and most of
them boast about their back-up procedures. But often the files are
only as private as people's passwords, which are often not as safe
as people think. ``It's very difficult to make these services
bullet-proof,'' said Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   Human psychology comes into play as well. Some observers argue
that people want to be able to point to a machine, Zip disk or
floppy disk and say: Here is where the information resides. ``I
LIKE having MY data on MY hard drive,'' Rankin wrote in an e-mail
message.
</P>
<P>
   Even Brady, the executive who swears by his ``safe deposit box
in the sky,'' backs up his data. He uses a Visto.com utility that
automatically synchronizes his data every day and then sends copies
to Visto.com for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have the latest stuff on all three machines
regardless of which machine on which I originally did the work,''
Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, virtual-desktop companies may say that their services
are available ``anytime, anywhere,'' but that ``anywhere'' comes
with a caveat: you must be connected to the Internet. Until it
becomes practical to log on for hours while flying at 30,000 feet,
Brady will work off line, from a document stored on his hard drive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   VIRTUAL STORAGE SERVICES
</P>
<P>
   It started with e-mail: Companies like Hotmail.com and Yahoo
offered people an online space to keep their e-mail so they could
gain access from any Web browser. Now the concept has moved to
other desktop services, from online calendars to word-processing
programs that run over the Web. Companies are sprouting up to offer
the services, which are free in exchange for your glances at their
advertisements. Here are a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   CALENDARS &QL;
</P>
