<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Nov. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gusty winds will buffet the central and northern Rockies on
Thursday as a strong difference in pressure between a high over the
Great Basin and a low near Lake Winnipeg develops. As the fast flow
of air weaves through the rugged terrain, local pockets of
exceptionally strong winds will affect portions of the Front Range.
Indeed, speeds may briefly exceed 70 mph from western Montana to
north-central Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   A plume of moisture-laden air from the Pacific will take aim on
portions of the Northwest coast, bringing heavy rain to northwest
Oregon and western Washington. As the eastward-bound damp air
ascends the Cascades, heavy snow will fall near and above pass
level. Foothill showers and high altitude snow will also affect
northeastern Oregon and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Subsiding currents of air associated with high pressure near
Utah will bring mainly sunny and milder conditions to the interior
Southwest. Offshore breezes will promote sunny and warm weather
near the southern and central California coast where afternoon
readings will approach 80 degrees near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The day will dawn dry with sunshine from the eastern Great Lakes
to the central New England coast, but an approaching jet stream
disturbance from the Gulf States will cause clouds to increase and
thicken during the day. Farther south, showers will develop in the
southern and central Appalachians as the disturbance intercepts a
moistening flow of air from the Atlantic Ocean. The rain will
quickly advance north, reaching New England Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Forms of Fog
</P>
<P>
   Many forms of fog have shrouded areas of the East this week. All
fogs form when moist air is cooled to its saturation point. Early
this week, some valleys of East filled with fog when clear skies
allowed the days warmth to dissipate quickly. The resulting mist
that developed is called radiation fog. As the air mass over the
Appalachians moistened during midweek, upslope fog formed as the
humid air was cooled upon ascending the sloping terrain. Also, a
dense sea fog plagued parts of Long Island when the mild air was
cooled to saturation as it passed over the chilly waters of the
North Atlantic.
</P>
</TEXT>
