<HEADER>
A0547 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ORIGAMI-SITES-NYT     11-24 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ORIGAMI-SITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIGAMI SITES SHOW HOW TO FOLD THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By JOYCE COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the world of origami, all links lead to Joseph Wu.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Wu's Origami Page (www.origami.vancouver.bc.ca), is the
definitive online source of information on origami, the art of
paper folding. Wu tries to connect to every origami site he can and
actively solicits feedback via e-mail; he estimates that he has
about 300 origami links.
</P>
<P>
   Wu's site brings order to the dizzying array of origami
information available on the Web, which includes origami history
and trivia, diagrams for figures of every kind, lists of origami
books and videos, addresses of stores that stock supplies and all
sorts of resources for connecting with fellow folders.
</P>
<P>
   Wu, 29, attributes his Web site's prominence to longevity. It
has been up since 1994, when he was a graduate student in computer
science and he and his classmates started Web sites about their
hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   His site includes diagrams for basic figures, like frogs and
fishes, plus some exceedingly complex creations of his own, like a
great white shark and a three-banded armadillo. But he finds
instructional diagrams tedious, he said, so he has not done that
for many of his own designs.
</P>
<P>
   His site also has pictures of unique folded things, like a devil
made from the wrapper of a bite-size Reese's peanut butter cup.
``The candy wrapper is difficult to work with due to its small size
and to the unforgivingness of the foil,'' Wu said. ``A mistaken
crease is there forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Other origami enthusiasts are happy to take advantage of Wu's
links when building their sites. ``We didn't know how to handle the
links, so we just linked to his page,'' said Jan Polish, treasurer
of OrigamiUSA (www.origami-usa.org).
</P>
<P>
   Members of OrigamiUSA, a national group with headquarters at the
American Museum of Natural History in Manhattan, create the origami
tree that decorates the museum's lobby every holiday season.
Volunteers are on hand to show children how to fold.
</P>
<P>
   The OrigamiUSA site contains a calendar for the group's Folding
Sundays, which are usually held on the fourth Sunday of the month
from 1 to 4 p.m. at the museum. A large shopping section offers
books, videos, kits and special paper, including one kind that
glows in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Other extensive regional sites are those for the Chicago Area
Origami Society (www.suba.com/blonnie/chaos.html) and the Bay Area
Rapid Folders in San Francisco (www.krmusic.com/barf.htm).
</P>
<P>
   The British Origami Society (www.rpmrecords.co.uk/bos) lists
meetings around England and also runs a sale and exchange board
under the heading Adverts. Most of the requests are from people
seeking out-of-print origami books.
</P>
<P>
   Origami.com is operated by Alex Barber, who has a section
entitled Folders on the Net, with e-mail addresses of nearly 400
origami fans plus a form for signing up to be added to the list
(origami.com). Paperfolding.com, run by Eric Andersen, includes a
detailed history of origami and links to several discussion groups
and to an origami e-mail list (paperfolding.com).
</P>
<P>
   A unique site at web.merrimack.edu/thull belongs to Tom Hull, a
math professor at Merrimack College in North Andover, Mass. He
focuses on the geometry of origami, which becomes apparent in the
pattern of creases when a figure is unfolded. Hull's site includes
a comprehensive origami-math bibliography, links to other
origami-math sites and instructions for making challenging figures
like ``five intersecting tetrahedra.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to OrigamiUSA, two other large sites sell origami
materials by mail. Kim's Crane Origami Supplies, at
www.kimscrane.com, lets people search the online catalog by
category as well as by word. A search for ``dinosaur'' turned up 10
items, including ``Dinosaurs and Fellows,'' an $11 book in English
and Hungarian, which shows how to fold 22 prehistoric figures. (The
author, Peter Budai _ as Wu's site notes _ was 12 when his first
books were published, in 1993.)
</P>
<P>
   The retail site Fascinating Folds (fascinating-folds.com)
features special categories, like materials for beginners and books
in several languages. The site offers things like foot-long dollar
bills, 50 for $6.95, that are, of course, proportional to the real
thing. These are used for ``money folds,'' also called `dollar
folds'' or ``bill folds'' _ shapes made from greenbacks, often
featuring George Washington's portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Wu's site links to sites dealing with money folds and other
origami topics. These include paper airplanes, origami
tessellations (geometric patterns made from a single sheet of
paper), unit or modular origami (simple shapes assembled into more
intricate ones) and wet folding (a technique using damp paper).
</P>
<P>
   There are also plenty of sites by origami enthusiasts, who post
whatever diagrams, articles and arcana strike their fancy. At the
Mark's Origami Olio site (www.eskimo.com/marmonk/origami.htm), Mark
Morden has a section on origami in the funny pages. In a
``Peanuts'' strip, Charlie Brown stands on a pitcher's mound in a
downpour, surrounded by paper sailboats.
</P>
<P>
   And Janet Hamilton has compiled an extensive list of origami
references in the news and entertainment media. (It is posted in
the Information section on Wu's site.) She recounts an episode of
``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch'' in which students learn to fold
napkins. Later, one girl tries to impress a football player by
folding a napkin into a bird. He's oblivious, of course, and ends
up using the napkin to wipe his mouth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
