<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0550 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-WHISTLE-HNS &LR;      11-24 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-WHISTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT'S DECISION IN VERMONT CASE COULD AFFECT LAWSUIT AGAINST TEXAS
HOSPITAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court will hear arguments Monday in a
Vermont case that might make or break a nurse's whistle-blower
lawsuit against Houston's St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Riley, a nurse in the hospital's heart-transplant unit,
claims the facility conspired to defraud the federal Medicare
program by unnecessarily admitting patients and needlessly
upgrading the level of services. Riley sued St. Luke's in 1994
under the federal False Claims Act, which permits private citizens
to sue companies on the U.S. government's behalf to recover
ill-gotten gains owed to the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   But a three-judge panel of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
this month blocked Riley's lawsuit from proceeding, ruling that
whistle-blowers who have suffered no direct harm from the alleged
fraud have no standing to sue under the Constitution. The U.S.
government, on whose behalf whistle-blower lawsuits are filed, may
sue because it has sustained an injury, the alleged fraud, the 5th
Circuit ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, for reasons it has not disclosed, has
chosen not to intervene in Riley's lawsuit against St. Luke's.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital has denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's attorney, Jim Perdue Jr. of Houston, appealed the
panel's decision to the full 5th Circuit, which has agreed to hear
the case the week of Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
   But, in an unusual turn of events, the Supreme Court on Friday
told the parties in an unrelated False Claims Act case from Vermont
to address a question like the one pending before the 5th Circuit:
``Does a private person have standing ... to litigate claims of
fraud upon the government?''
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision on that issue, expected by July, could have
serious ramifications for Riley's lawsuit against St. Luke's. A
ruling that private people have standing would contradict the 5th
Circuit and resurrect Riley's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, who gave no explanation for adding the standing
question, told the Vermont whistle-blower and the state agency
being accused of fraud to submit by Tuesday afternoon legal briefs
to the court addressing the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Perdue, Riley's attorney, said he suspects the justices added
the question to the Vermont case to allow them to express their
disagreement with the 5th Circuit's decision. The 5th Circuit's
ruling marked the first time an appellate court has held that
whistle-blowers may not sue on behalf of the United States, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's any coincidence that it came (just) four
days after the 5th Circuit's decision,'' Perdue said, referring to
the high court's question regarding standing.
</P>
<P>
   Judges can address the issue of standing, that is whether a
person has a legal basis for suing in the first place, at anytime.
Hence, it is not without precedent that the justices have told
parties to a case to argue the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But it is rare for the high court to ask litigants to submit
additional briefs in a case it has already scheduled for argument.
</P>
<P>
   Perdue said he will not file a brief with the justices in the
Vermont case, opting instead to focus his energy on preparing his
argument on Riley's behalf before the 5th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Perdue's brief in that case is due Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   But St. Luke's attorney, L. Boyd Smith Jr. of Houston, disputed
Perdue's theory that the justices raised the standing issue in an
effort to tell the 5th Circuit that its decision was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure the Supreme Court has better things to do than seek
out opportunities to head off issues before one of the circuit
courts,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Perdue, Smith said he will focus not on the high court but
on his pending arguments before the full 5th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hands are full'' in trying to meet a Jan. 3 deadline for
filing briefs with the circuit court, he added. ``We'll be spending
the Christmas holiday reading the Constitution.``
</P>
<P>
   Under the False Claims Act's ``qui tam'' provisions, a private
citizen may sue a company receiving federal funds, even if the U.S.
government decides not to pursue the case. Companies found liable
for defrauding the government can be ordered to pay up to three
times the amount of their fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The citizen, who sues on behalf of the federal government, is
entitled to up to 30 percent of the court's award, with the rest
going to the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The act's supporters say it allows the attorney general to
maximize Justice Department resources by not requiring her staff to
file suit for every perceived violation of law.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court had agreed to hear the Vermont case to address
whether states are subject to liability under the False Claims Act.
The justices also said they would use the case to decide if states
can in fact can be sued in light of their general constitutional
immunity from lawsuits for money damages.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Vermont Agency of Natural Resources nor
whistle-blower Jonathan Stevens addressed the question of standing
in their initial briefs to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   In her lawsuit against St. Luke's, Riley says she can prove that
hospital officials allowed an unlicensed doctor to practice
medicine as part of a scheme to defraud the government on Medicare
claims.
</P>
<P>
   She also alleges that officials conspired to move
heart-transplant patients to intensive-care units sooner than
necessary, thus inflating hospital profits.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Kenneth Hoyt of Houston dismissed the
lawsuit in 1997, saying Riley was an uninjured party with no
standing to recover government money that has been lost to fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit panel agreed in a 2-1 decision Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
