<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LEGEND1900-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LEGEND' TAKES A HO-HUM MUSICAL JOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Midway through The Legend of 1900 is a scene that appears to
have crossed over from another movie. The title character _ yes,
his name is 1900, a good sign that this movie will have its cloying
moments _ engages in a piano duel with Jelly Roll Morton, the
self-proclaimed founder of jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The duel is plotted like points on a graph; you not only know
how it will end, but you have a pretty good idea of the steps it
will take to get there. But it's filmed with such vigor and flair
that although it may be predictable, it's a lot of fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of The Legend of 1900 isn't so much fun. As much as the
piano duel moves, the rest of the movie meanders. During the
Depression, down-and-out trumpeter Max (Pruitt Taylor Vince,
narrating with perhaps more world-weariness than is necessary)
hocks his horn but asks the pawnbroker to let him play it one last
time. When the shopkeeper recognizes the rare, melancholy tune, Max
begins telling him the legend of 1900, Max's best buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that 1900 was born _ or at least abandoned as a baby _
on a cruise ship and raised by one of the ship's workers (Bill
Nunn), who named the tyke for the year in which he was born. The
turn-of-the-century tot grows into a piano prodigy, playing as if
he'd been studying all his life. He grows further into Tim Roth,
who downplays his usual snottiness to play the role with a more
wistful touch. Until he's an adult, 1900 never even thinks about
setting foot on land, which becomes a key plot point after 1900
meets an attractive young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Director Giuseppe Tornatore _ who has yet to match Cinema
Paradiso, his wonderful breakthrough film from about a decade ago _
adapted this story from a monologue by an Italian novelist. He
supplies it with an elegiac beauty, helped in no small part by a
winsome Ennio Morricone score (for some, reason enough to see the
film) and Lajos Koltai's empathic cinematography.
</P>
<P>
   But when Clarence Williams III's haughty-then-humbled Morton
leaves the scene, the movie's energy departs with him, although
Roth does his best to keep it flowing. Tornatore calls The Legend
of 1900 a fable, but it turns out to be sentimental much ado about
not very much.
</P>
<P>
   The Legend of 1900 is rated R for language.
The Legend of 1900 21/2 stars (on a scale of 5) Director: Giuseppe
Tornatore Stars: Tim Roth, Pruitt Taylor Vince Length: 119 min.
Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Filpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
