<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FLAWLESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FLAWLESS' LOOKS LIKE A VERY ROUGH DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can tell why Robert De Niro and Philip Seymour Hoffman
wanted to be in ``Flawless.'' Their roles _ an ultraconservative
former security guard recovering from a stroke and a morose but
flamboyant drag queen, respectively _ are the type that whisper
``Oscar nominations'' before the ink dries on the screenplay. It
doesn't matter that the ink dried before this was a fully formed
movie.
</P>
<P>
   De Niro's character, Walt Koontz, appears to have picked his
shabby apartment building because it houses everything he loathes,
especially a group of drag queens who love to taunt Koontz because
of his homophobia. When thugs attack one of Koontz's neighbors, he
tries to come to her rescue but suffers a stroke before he can
prevent her slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Koontz's rehabilitation includes singing lessons as voice
therapy, and who better to give the lessons than the mother hen of
the drag queens, Rusty Zimmerman? Rusty, played by Hoffman, was a
friend of the woman Koontz couldn't save. You don't need a
screenwriting degree to know that Koontz and Rusty bond, although
it's a rocky road.
</P>
<P>
   De Niro is typically meticulous (he even designed special shoes
and arm weights to help him mimic the effects of the stroke) and
the result is a mixed blessing. His performance is all technical,
obscuring the character's soul. De Niro has done a lot of good work
in the past few years _ ``Wag the Dog, Jackie Brown,'' even
``Analyze This'' _ without having to resort to such devices.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for Hoffman, who appears to be channeling
William Hurt in ``Kiss of the Spider Woman,'' right down to the
wounded musicality of his voice. In ``Boogie Nights'' and
especially ``Happiness,'' Hoffman _ one of our most interesting
young actors _ made us care about some dislikable characters. Here,
he's trying too hard.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Joel Schumacher gives the movie a moody look,
with lots of help from cinematographer Declan Quinn and production
designer Jan Roelfs. But he doesn't seem to have known what story
he wanted to tell. Consequently, ``Flawless'' is a hodgepodge: part
buddy movie, part disease-of-the-week movie, part gay serio-comedy,
part crime drama. By trying to make it all of the above, Schumacher
has made it none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flawless'''' is rated R for language and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Flawless''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Joel Schumacher
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Robert De Niro, Philip Seymour Hoffman
</P>
<P>
   Length: 111 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
