<SLUG> BC-FILM-''TOYSTORY-2''-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SEQUELS GO, ``TS2'' IS WORTHY SUCCESSOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With 1995's ``Toy Story,'' Walt Disney Pictures had a number of
hurdles to clear: A collaboration with a new company, Pixar
Animation Studios. A director, John Lasseter, whose only experience
to that point was with short subjects (albeit Oscar-winning ones).
And, most challenging of all, the task of bringing warmth and
character to computer animation, a medium long known for its
detachment and sterility.
</P>
<P>
   The results were stunning and wildly successful, leaving the
inevitable sequel, ``Toy Story 2,'' only one major hurdle _ namely
competing with ``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the followup may not be as good as the original _ a
feat that's nearly impossible considering ``Toy Story's'' stunning
innovations, not to mention its first-of-its-kind status _ Part Two
comes about as close to besting its predecessor as any sequel in
recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly from an animation standpoint, ``Toy Story 2'' is
light-years beyond the technical capabilities of Part One. Pixar's
``A Bug's Life'' seemed like an unbelievable technical marvel, and
``Toy Story 2'' does it one better. The film's colors, use of
light, tactile textures and inventive camera work overcome the
restrictions of live-action movies and add a hyper-reality absent
in cell animation.
</P>
<P>
   The story picks up where the original left off. Spaceman action
figure Buzz Lightyear (Tim Allen) and cowboy pull-string toy Woody
(Tom Hanks), along with the rest of the toys, have adapted nicely
to the household's new dachshund. But when a garage sale threatens
to do away with one of the toys, it's Woody to the rescue.
Unfortunately, he's stolen by Al (Wayne Knight), an unscrupulous
collector and toy-store owner who recognizes Woody as the final
missing piece of an elaborate collection of spinoff merchandise
from an old marionette TV show called ``Woody's Roundup.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Woody had his own TV posse, including his trusty horse
Bullseye, his gal pal Jessie (Joan Cusack) and his sidekick, Stinky
Pete the Prospector (Kelsey Grammer). Al plans to ship the whole
kit and caboodle to a Japanese toy museum unless Buzz and the gang
can find their way across town in time to save Woody.
</P>
<P>
   The entire ``Toy Story'' toy box returns with Mr. Potato Head
(Don Rickles); Slinky Dog (Jim Varney); Rex (Wallace Shawn); and
Hamm (John Ratzenberger), along with a few new faces. They include
Mrs. Potato Head (Seinfeld's Estelle Harris); a squeaky penguin toy
called Wheezy (Joe Ranft); Emperor Zurg (Andrew Stanton), a
hilarious new outerspace supervillain to challenge Buzz; and, of
course, Barbie (Jodi Benson). After Mattel refused to allow Barbie
to appear in the first movie, it's easy to see why they were
clamoring to be involved with the sequel.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, ``Toy Story 2'' avoids solely cashing in on the
best bits of the first film, and the familiar references that do
appear (the Pizza Planet delivery truck makes a brief appearance)
seem like surprises instead of contrivances. It also fires so many
in-jokes, one-liners and subtle movie references (from ``The Empire
Strikes Back'' to ``Jurassic Park)'') that repeated visits are
essential.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Toy Story's'' message was aimed more at teaching kids to
take care of their toys, the sequel chews on something a little
more meaty _ when kids outgrow their toys. When Jessie sings to
Woody (Sarah McLachlan's heart-tugging song ``When She Loved Me'')
about carefree days spent with her little girl owner _ until she
was donated to charity with that girl's other childish things _
there will be nary a dry eye in the house. And doggone it if this
movie doesn't make you feel guilty for every toy with which you
ever parted ways. It makes you want to leave the theater and rush
home to play.
Toy Story 2 4 stars (on a scale of 5) Director: John Lasseter
Stars: Voices of Tom Hanks, Tim Allen Length: 88 min. Rated: G
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
