<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ENDOFDAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END DOESN'T COME FAST ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sounds like a great idea for a comedy: Arnold Schwarzenegger
vs. Satan. At the very least, like a sequel to the Jesus/Santa
Claus death match from the ``South Park'' pilot. (Imagine, the
devil squaring off against Schwarzenegger's muscle-bound waddle.)
But, no, ``End of Days'' is as serious as a heart attack, and twice
as in need of life support.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of playing an ex-cop named Jack, as he did in ``Last
Action Hero,'' Schwarzenegger plays an ex-cop named Jericho. That,
and the fact that he's unshaven, makes this role a real stretch for
the action star. He's suffering a crisis of faith because his wife
and daughter were killed. At the beginning of the film, as New York
prepares for the New Year, Jericho is suicidal. In other words,
it's like the first ``Lethal Weapon,'' except that Jericho works
for some super security agency. It's the kinda place the Terminator
would retire to, armed with stealth helicopters and projectile
launchers. (He's a complicated man, Jericho; he's suicidal and yet
wears a bulletproof vest.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Days'' takes place over three days and seems to occur in real
time. Satan occupies the body of Gabriel Byrne, who's conveniently
wearing all black. The Man, as he's called, has to consummate a
union with a young girl, Christine (Robin Tunney), and sire a child
in the last hour of the year. Jericho and his partner (Kevin
Pollak, playing the sacrificial comic relief) get involved and try
to stop Satan from getting his groove on, which will mean the end
of life as we know it, etc., if it takes place. Y'know, the ``End
of Days.'' Although, based on the lack of sunlight in the movie, it
looks like the end of days has already happened.
</P>
<P>
   If there's anything remarkable about ``Days,'' it's that it's
like a thousand other movies. It's cobbled together like a ransom
note from pieces of other B-movies. (The only way to keep yourself
involved, in lieu of actual drama, is to tick off the influences.)
Director Peter Hyams gives much of the film the look of ``Seven,''
which is fast on its way to becoming the most influential _ that
is, copied _ thriller of the past few years. Byrne, the guy who was
not Keyser Soze in ``The Usual Suspects,'' plays the devil. Pollak
was also in ``Suspects,'' and in addition, ``Days'' features a
character saying ``Satan's greatest trick was convincing Man he
didn't exist'' _ a line right out of ``Suspects.'' And Satan's
Party Central, filled with worshippers and candles _ apparently,
the devil doesn't find overhead lighting flattering _ looks like
the set of a Korn video.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Schwarzenegger try a serious role is like watching Fred
Flintstone star in ``The Iceman Cometh.'' As Jericho tries to wrap
his mouth around the biblical prophecy, you may be reminded of his
first turn as Conan the Barbarian, where he talked about
slaughtering men and hearing ``der lamentations of dair vimmen.''
He's supposed to be a sufferer, and, in the painfully cheap irony
of the movie, a man of no faith who has to battle the ultimate
evil. But his plight is overexplained _ like the prologue that sets
up the movie, showing the birth of Christine and a pack of devil
worshippers spilling the blood of a rattlesnake over the newborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Days'' sets up rules only to violate them. Byrne's performance
consists mostly of smirking over corpses. And Tunney does the
crying and running required of a young woman in danger. The most
original thing about the movie is, when the inevitable 666 is
invoked, it turns out to have been a typo. You may find yourself
running home to scan the Bible, if only to see if it warns against
movies like this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``End of Days'' is rated R for baroque and plentiful violence,
including a crucifixion and adult language and subject matter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``End of Days'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Peter Hyams &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Arnold Schwarzenegger, Robin Tunney, Gabriel Byrne &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 118 min &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
