<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE IN SEATTLE BANS MAN FROM A NEWSGROUP  
 YOU CAN GET ANYTHING YOU WANT; PAY A VISIT TO ARLO'S HOME PAGE  
 COULD THAT BE A HUMAN VOICE COMING OUT OF THE COMPUTER?  
 PUTTING A MULTIMEDIA SPIN ON THE ORDINARY BUSINESS CARD  
 PC'S ARE ADOPTING NEW SHAPES, ONE JUST A BIT TOO FAMILIAR  
 FOR ONLINE BUYERS, IT'S CAVEAT EMPTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Wash., Mass., Nev., Calif.) (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A county judge in Seattle has raised eyebrows among civil
liberties groups by applying anti-harassment law to the realm of
cyberspace. Last week, as part of a restraining order, the judge
barred a man from posting messages to a public newsgroup.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Scott Abraham, was accused of threatening another
newsgroup participant, David Hobbs, on an online bulletin board
called rec.skiing.alpine. The source of the dispute is unclear _
some reports suggest that it started over a squabble about ski
passes. But messages lingering in the newsgroup's archives show
that whatever the root of the problem, the electronic exchanges did
get nasty: Vicious messages, from Abraham and from others acting
anonymously, were riddled with veiled threats to take up arms or
commit assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham has denied threatening Hobbs and says that he is the one
who has been threatened. But on Friday, at Hobbs' request, Judge
Pro Tempore Marcine Anderson of King County District Court issued a
restraining order against Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   The order is a three-page form, filled out and signed. Added to
it, in longhand, are the judge's words: ``Respondent is further
restrained from making or responding to postings at the Internet
site rec.skiing.alpine either directly or indirectly, in person or
through others.''
</P>
<P>
   Some civil rights groups say that those words are the equivalent
of barring Abraham from speaking freely in a public forum. ``It's
too broad,'' said Tara Lemmey, president of the Electronic Frontier
Foundation. To halt Abraham from sending messages about his
accusers is one thing, Ms. Lemmey said. ``But what if he wanted to
talk about skiing?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham was not available for comment, but a friend who has come
to his defense, Bert Hoff, said that Abraham had not decided
whether to appeal the order. The Washington office of the American
Civil Liberties Union is also reviewing the case.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   You Can Get Anything You Want; Pay a Visit to Arlo's Home Page
</P>
<P>
   One of the more memorable events in the history of Thanksgiving
occurred in Stockbridge, Mass., on Nov. 25, 1965, when Arlo Guthrie
dumped trash where he wasn't supposed to (the town dump having been
closed for the holiday). Guthrie was arrested the next day for
littering, and the arrest and its ramifications were immortalized
in Guthrie's 18-minute song, ``Alice's Restaurant Massacree.''
</P>
<P>
   The playing of that song has become a Thanksgiving tradition at
some radio stations. Anyone wishing to sing along should visit
Guthrie's official home page, www.arlo.net, where the lyrics
(``transcript'' might be a better word) are available.
</P>
<P>
   The site has a chat room, a concert schedule, and photographs
and news of Guthrie and his fans. There is also a link to the
Guthrie Center, an interfaith foundation in the former church where
Alice (whose last name was Brock) lived with her husband, Ray.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the site would not be complete without viewing the
tribute to William J. Obanhein, otherwise known as Officer Obie,
the man who put the handcuffs on Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Could That Be a Human Voice Coming Out of the Computer?
</P>
<P>
   Text-to-speech technology has been around for nearly 20 years as
a way for the blind to use computers. What has been elusive has
been the ability to make the computer voice sound human rather than
tinny and robotic.
</P>
<P>
   Lernout &AMP; Hauspie recently demonstrated its solution to that
problem, RealSpeak, at a trade show in Manhattan. Lernout &AMP; Hauspie
contends that the program is the first commercially available
text-to-speech product that sounds human and will run on a standard
PC or laptop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of interest in using the product on
PC's,'' said Pam Ravesi, senior director of product development at
Lernout &AMP; Hauspie, ``and we've been working hard to downsize the
program and compress it so that it can run on a standard Pentium
machine.'' One major application for RealSpeak on PC's will
probably be the translation of documents from one language to
another.
</P>
<P>
   RealSpeak for the PC will be available before the end of the
year. The first version will be in American English, followed by
versions in German, French and Italian. The system is not perfect;
there can still be slight variations in tone and inflection that
remind you that the voice is generated by a computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Stephen C. Miller.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Putting a Multimedia Spin On the Ordinary Business Card
</P>
<P>
   At the Comdex computer show in Las Vegas last week, one of the
hot items was business cards. Not ordinary cards, but CD-ROM's cut
to the size of business cards.
</P>
<P>
   The cards, which are made by several companies and cost about
$1.25 each, depending upon quantity, have a label that can feature
a company logo, a person's name and title, and all the other
information on the typical business card. But they also function as
CD-ROM's and can contain up to 100 megabytes of multimedia data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see these cards as a great tool for introducing our
product,'' said a user, Reba Rosenbluth, vice president of
marketing for One Voice Technologies of San Diego. Ms. Rosenbluth
said the CD-ROM cards were effective because people considered them
to be novelties.
</P>
<P>
   While the business-card size will be most common, BizNetCard,
one of the manufacturers, was displaying a heart-shaped disc. The
reason that CD-ROM's can be cut to odd shapes is that data is read
from the center outward. A data area that is a half-inch wide can
hold 40 megabytes of information, enough space for product photos
or demonstration versions of software.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Stephen C. Miller
</P>
<P>
   PC's Are Adopting New Shapes, One Just a Bit Too Familiar
</P>
<P>
   After Apple's iMac broke the ``any color as long as it's beige''
and ``any shape as long as it's a box'' molds, personal computer
makers have been showing off odd-shaped and colorful computers.
</P>
<P>
   There were a spate of them at Comdex, the big computer industry
trade show, in Las Vegas last week. Advanced Micro Devices was
showing a new design, called EasyNow, which looks like the
cross-section of a football and features a flip-top CD drive. PC
manufacturers are starting to produce systems based on the design,
under license from AMD.
</P>
<P>
   Intel persuaded a number of top design firms to come up with PC
designs for its new line of motherboards, which are intended for
family and specialty PC use.
</P>
<P>
   The unqualified hit was the Ottoman PC from Sozo Designs of
Burlingame, Calif. The all-in-one unit looks like an ottoman when
it is closed.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, when the lid is opened to reveal the monitor, the
unit resembles something else.
</P>
<P>
   The whispered question that circulated among some of the more
than 200,000 Comdex attendees was, ``Have you seen the toilet seat
PC?''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Stephen C. Miller.
</P>
<P>
   For Online Buyers, It's Caveat Emptor
</P>
<P>
   If you believe all the television commercials, online shopping
will be an effortless and satisfying experience this holiday
season. But a couple of recent reports suggest that dealing with
Web-based stores can be anything but.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey conducted by Jupiter Communications, an Internet
research company, at least 40 percent of retail Web sites did not
respond to e-mail requests for help. Another survey, which polled
consumer agencies, showed that many Internet-based shops had
disappointed and angered customers by sending goods late or not
shipping them at all.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are worse than in earlier years, analysts say. In
the third quarter of 1998, the Jupiter survey found, only 28
percent of Web retailers failed to respond to e-mail requests that
had been sent, anonymously, from Jupiter researchers. And the
National Association of Consumer Agency Administrators, which based
its conclusions on data collected through the end of 1998, said
that the number of complaints related to Internet transactions or
Internet service had increased by 39 percent since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter found a gulf between the companies that are ready for
the holiday rush and those that aren't. Of 25 online shops the
company tested, 15 responded to e-mail messages within one day,
while 10 took longer than five days to respond. (Among 100 Web
sites outside retail sales, 46 percent failed to respond to e-mail
requests.)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the problems encountered by consumer agencies went much
further than a lack of response to e-mail. Wendy Weinberg, a
spokeswoman for the national consumer group, said that people had
complained about undisclosed shipping charges, packages that
arrived weeks later than expected and purchases that turned out to
be fraudulent. She advises people to look for traces of the
nonvirtual world before pulling out the credit card: ``At least
check if there is a phone number listed on the Web site first,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
</TEXT>
