<HEADER>
A0567 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BEMELMANS-WEB-NYT &LR;      11-24 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEMELMANS-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUDWIG BEMELMANS: A NEW FOCUS ON THE CREATOR OF A CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDEN ROSS LIPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Madeline must be the only famous French orphan born
in a tavern near Gramercy Park. It was there, 60 years ago, that
Ludwig Bemelmans, her creator, jotted on the back of a menu the
famous phrases, ``In an old house in Paris that was covered with
vines lived 12 little girls in two straight lines.''
</P>
<P>
   A plaque honoring Bemelmans, who died in 1962, was dedicated at
that bar, Pete's Tavern, in late September. The small crowd that
gathered for the occasion included his widow, Madeleine (known as
Mimi), and his daughter, Barbara, who were inspirations for
Madeline, and two of his three grandsons.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Madeline'' (pronounced MAD-a-line) was published in 1939,
it was an immediate success, becoming a Caldecott Honor book. Five
more Madeline books followed, forever sealing his identification
with the fearless young girl who was not afraid of mice.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bemelmans explained how her parents lived in the Hotel
Irving nearby and ate dinner at Pete's, ``oh, almost every night.''
She told of being bored and restless as the adults lingered over
coffee, liqueurs, cigarettes and cigars, and how at the age of 5 or
so she would wander off, ending up downstairs wrapped in an apron,
washing dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps her early industriousness was inherited. Ludwig
Bemelmans, who was born in the Austrian Tyrol in 1898, was sent to
New York at 16 and went to work at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel. He
stayed there intermittently, rising in the hierarchy to the
position of assistant manager and living luxuriously on the
premises until he left to become a professional artist just as the
Depression began.
</P>
<P>
   His facility in so many mediums, his extravagant ways and his
entrepreneurial instincts were both a strength and a curse. He
traveled ceaselessly on assignment for magazines and publishers,
writing 20 books for adults, including four novels and 16
children's books, always calling or cabling for money. Most of his
correspondence with the Viking Press, one of his principal
publishers, is on hotel stationery, postmarked from seemingly
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s, Victor Hammer of the Hammer Gallery developed
a steady source of income for Bemelmans, his client, by selling
random sketches and drawings as well as many of his completed
illustrations and paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bemelmans, who lives on a horse farm in Three Rivers,
N.J., with her mother living nearby, said ruefully that ``talent
skips a generation.'' When the film rights to Madeline were sold a
dozen years ago to a company that is now a part of Disney, they
included merchandise rights that, her son James Ludwig Marciano
said, she blithely thought were ``balloons and T-shirts.'' There
are now more than 30 lines of franchised Madeline merchandise,
including a very successful line of dolls, made by Eden toys.
</P>
<P>
   Her three sons, however, have some of their grandfather's
entrepreneurial gifts. John Bemelmans Marciano's new books,
``Bemelmans: The Life and Art of Madeline's Creator,'' and
``Madeline in America: And Other Holiday Tales,'' can both be found
on Madeline.com, the Web site set up by his brother James. It was
James who bought the domain name for his mother and grandmother in
anticipation of rising interest in Madeline before the appearance
of the live-action Tri-Star movie in 1998. Already, he says, almost
10,000 parents have joined a Madeline fan club. Barbara Bemelmans'
third son, Paul Lorenzo Marciano, teaches philosophy at Davidson
College in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   James, 33, recently sold the Referit.com Web site, which creates
links to fulfillment agents like Amazon.com for products sold on
the Internet. He is also, he said, ``the guru of affiliate programs
for Webmasters,'' runs TheSquare.com, a Web site for Ivy League
graduates, as well as an online dating service for divorced people.
</P>
<P>
   John, 30, who studied art history and studio art at Columbia
College, spent months going through his grandfather's copious but
disorganized files, finding correspondence, notes, drafts and
corrections for the lavish book published by the Viking Press. Like
his mother, he chooses to be nearly oblivious to the Web site and
e-commerce, devoting himself to restoring and reviving Bemelmans on
the printed page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life and Art'' is a lavish volume including more than 400
examples of Bemelmans' work in an impressive range of mediums,
including comic strips, pen and ink sketches, watercolors, gouache
and finally, oil paintings. The oils are intensely colored,
abstracted views of New York City done in the late 1950s. They were
shown at the Museum of the City of New York in 1959 and have not
been displayed since.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig Bemelmans was an artist who made an art of recycling,
turning Madeline into other income-producing forms. A series of 15
Madeline murals he painted in the children's salon on Aristotle
Onassis' yacht Christina in 1953 will be sold at auction by
Sotheby's on Dec. 1; estimates for the group range from $200,000 to
340,000. (The original cover painting for ``Madeline'' was sold
this year at an auction for $131,000.) At the invitation of Stanley
Marcus, Bemelmans took Madeline, Miss Clavel and the other girls to
Texas for the Neiman Marcus Christmas catalog in 1955, a story that
has been republished this fall as part of ``Madeline in America:
And Other Holiday Tales.''
</P>
<P>
   John signed up with Arthur A. Levine and Scholastic Press (the
editor and publisher of the Harry Potter books) to enlarge some
forgotten and out-of-print projects. For ``Madeline in America,''
he applied color gouache to his grandfather's drawings and added a
few new illustrations to the full text of the Neiman Marcus story.
</P>
<P>
   Bemelmans painted on landlocked walls as well, decorating what
is now known as the Bemelmans Bar at the Hotel Carlyle in exchange
for 18 months' free rent. (Sotheby's held a party in the bar last
week to promote interest in the Madeline murals. Girls in party
dresses drank Madeline cocktails: blueberry juice, sparkling apple
cider and grenadine, served in champagne flutes with a slice of
clementine.)
</P>
<P>
   The cover of ``Life and Art'' is a detail from the only oil
painting that includes Madeline. The little girl in her boater hat
and her dog, Genevieve, with a bow in her bangs are standing to one
side of a Parisian flower market, lush with lilies and other
blossoms. The original hangs in Mimi Bemelmans' bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   As lighthearted as the finished books and covers for The New
Yorker or Town &AMP; Country appeared, Bemelmans carefully researched
and drafted his prose and his pictures. Indeed, literally thousands
of sketches and several dummies went into each Madeline book. The
epigraph to the section of ``Life and Art'' explaining the process
is from a note Bemelmans sent his longtime editor, May Massee: ``We
are writing for Children but not for Idiots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
