<HEADER>
A0568 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      11-24 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' DEFENSIVE COORDINATOR THE BEST, SWITZER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Barry Switzer is on the run these days _
managing his interest in four restaurants, spending time with two
younger children, and one grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Not too busy to defend Ernie Zampese, his friend and former
offensive coordinator with the Dallas Cowboys, who has been accused
of the ``P'' word: predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' said Switzer, who led the Cowboys to a victory in
Super Bowl XXX with Zampese. ``When you're losing, you hear it. You
don't hear it from football people because they know better. You
hear it from people who have never played the game and people who
have never coached. That's who you hear it from.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's total (expletive). Everybody tries to put a word on why
you're failing at something. They think it can be labeled and once
you label it well you ought to be able to correct it. You correct
it on the football field. You work at it, practice it, do what you
have to do to get it back. You don't snap your fingers and it
appears again.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictability is a word Switzer hates to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the best football teams I ever played against were
predictable,'' said Switzer, who won three national titles in his
16 years leading the Oklahoma Sooners. ``Let me give you an
example: Tom Osborne's Nebraska teams. Talk about predicatability.
You don't think I knew what was coming every time they had the
ball? Could I stop it? That was the challenge. If you execute
right, it doesn't matter how predictable you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Switzer, 62, is now out of the game and about to move back to
Norman, Okla., from Dallas. He said he watches the NFL, two years
after he was fired by Dallas owner Jerry Jones. He still pays close
attention to the people he considers friends in the league. He
watches the Cowboys, and keeps up with Zampese and the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched that game Sunday,'' said Switzer, referring to the
Patriots' 27-17 loss in Miami. ``You blame that on Ernie? How many
times did the quarterback get hit? How many times did he throw it
to the other team's player? If people are blaming Ernie, their
blame is misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole offense is designed to protect the quarterback.
Three-step dropback and make your reads, 1-2-3, and get rid of it.
You're supposed to avoid sacks by doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then why does Bledsoe lead the league in knockdowns and sacks?
</P>
<P>
   ``Either he's holding the ball too long or the receivers aren't
getting open,'' said Switzer. ``That's all correctable.''
</P>
<P>
   Switzer said he's angered by criticism of Zampese, as he was
when he was the Dallas head coach. Switzer and most of his staff
were fired following a 6-10 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That man is one of the best offensive minds in the game,''
said Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer said that predictability comes when a team is having
problems on first down. If it can't move the ball on first down and
gain a good hunk of yards, then they become predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get third and long, you pass,'' said Switzer.
``Quarterbacks go back in the shotguns and they look to complete a
pass for first down. That's predictable. When a team has only one
back in the backfield, that's predictable. There are so many things
in this game that are predictable. Every team has things they do
even if they know the other team knows they're going to do them. If
there's a confidence in what you're doing, it doesn't matter if the
other team knows it's coming. You just execute it because you know
you're better than the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Switzer-Zampese offense worked, it worked well enough
to win the Super Bowl after a stellar 1995 season. It was the
second year of the Zampese regime, and by then Troy Aikman, Michael
Irvin, Emmitt Smith and Co. had figured it all out. Aikman was
sacked only 19 times as the system worked with great precision.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Zampese system is out of sync. The pass routes are no
longer crisp and sure. Bledsoe is holding on to the ball far too
long. Zampese himself has lengethened the routes for whatever
reason. The 10-15-yard passes are now becoming 30-35 yards long.
</P>
<P>
   When coach Pete Carroll says the Patriots have to improve on
what they're doing and execute, it sounds hollow in the minds of
the fans. But that's the way football people think. That's the way
Switzer thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to believe in what you're doing and that your system
works,'' said Switzer. ``Ernie's system is proven. It's won a Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys system also had a huge offensive line that ran block
as well as anyone this decade. The running game was prevelant.
Balance was possible. But the Zampese system is built around
controlling the ball with short passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with executing our stuff,'' said Carroll. ``There
isn't a mystery here.''
</P>
<P>
   When the great Green Bay Packer teams were on top, everyone knew
what they were going to do, but nobody could stop them. It's an
attitude. It's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer said he misses some of the people in the game, but not
Jones, the Monday morning quarterback who made his last season in
Dallas miserable. Switzer says he still loves the game, but doesn't
expect to get back in unless someone makes a great case for why he
should.
</P>
<P>
   If he made a different decision in 1972, he might have been a
coach with the Patriots, and perhaps eventually the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Chuck (Fairbanks) left Oklahoma, he asked me to go with
him to New England,'' said Switzer. ``I could have been the
backfield coach there and who knows what that would have led to.
But I told Chuck that I wanted to stay behind and have the chance
to be the head coach at Oklahoma. I never regretted that
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he ever regret making Zampese his offensive coordinator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
