<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-CHEAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANT TO SKI FOR LESS? ASK MR. CHEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People complain about it, but no one does anything about it.
This Twainism may pertain to weather, but it also describes most
skiers' attitudes about lift ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anyone who hasn't gasped now and then at the sticker
shock at the ticket window? But has anyone ever tried to change it?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, and you can just call him Mr. Cheap from Chester,
Vt., a guy who stockpiles cereal and Diet Coke by the case just to
take advantage of bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   How cheap is Chris Estes? Well, there was that discounted
shampoo he bought three years ago? He's still using the stuff. And
50 boxes of cereal? He got them for less than a buck a box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' says the 32-year-old former Killington ski bum, ``I
really am cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does all this have to do with skiing? For starters, in
this age of $50-plus tickets, Mr. Cheap feels it an offense to pay
more than $25 for a day on the lifts, and prefers $15.
</P>
<P>
   He sizes up advertised bargains such as New Hampshire's offer of
40 ski days for $995 at 17 state resorts, including some biggies _
Attitash/Bear Peak, Cannon, Loon, Waterville Valley, Bretton Woods,
and Sunapee. That's less than $25 per day. That, says Mr. Cheap, is
not a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it a great deal. In fact, it's dangerously close to the
$30 mark at which point a price may not be included in Estes
newsletter called, what else: ``Ski Cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the price of a lift ticket at Stratton _ $59, and
that's just unreal. I would never pay that money to go skiing,''
says Estes, ``and there's no need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his driving passion to save money, Estes two years
ago began his newsletter, which is crammed full of money-saving
tips for skiers and boarders in Vermont, New Hampshire, and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   As a ski bum at Killington for a few years, Estes, who now works
for Newsbank in Chester, became accustomed to the deals and free
skiing that area employees receive as perks. When he left
Killington for his new job, the very thought of paying for
expensive lift tickets was too painful to contemplate. ``I suddenly
had to pay and I don't like to pay for anything,'' says Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Living in Vermont, he notes, necessitates learning to save
money, since wage scales are lower than in the areas from which
most skiers drive north on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many white collar jobs in Vermont,'' he says.
``To have a middle class existence here you have to be very
frugal.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, develop a business around the concept of frugality. Hence
the newsletter, which received about 2,000 inquiries last season
and 150 subscribers. A modest beginning, perhaps, but Estes still
firmly believes in his idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smaller resorts are places to find good deals,'' he says,
rattling some off from memory. ``For example, at Black you can get
a family ticket for four for 89 bucks. That's not too bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gunstock has (the same package) for $99, and at Shawnee, it's
$100. That's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, but not nearly as cheap as Estes likes. ``I like to ski for
$15,'' he says, and has last year's figures to prove it. He skied
30 days and spent a total of $435. That's $14.50, right in Estes's
comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   With his driving interest in frugality, the newsletter was a
natural development. He charges $15 for a yearly subscription, and
lets folks see a couple of pages on his Web site:
www:ski-ridecheap.com.
</P>
<P>
   Estes will send out one free copy of his newsletter in hopes
that skiers/riders will quickly figure out that their $15 outlay
can be made up several times in one ski season.
</P>
<P>
   With his home computer, Estes does the writing, design, and
layout of his newsletter, and runs off about 750 copies at this
point. He hopes it will take off and hit at least 20 percent of the
50,000 New England subscribers to Ski Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for high ticket prices are easy to trace, says Estes.
The biggest expense is the cost of snowmaking. When he began skiing
in 1973, snowmaking was in its infancy compared with today's white
paved boulevards of manmade snow. For this, he praises ski areas,
despite his belief that the costs are just too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at skiing as a product,'' he says, ``it has really
changed. Everyone complains about the high cost of skiing, but
skiing is so much better than it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But $59?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' says Mr. Cheap.'' No way. It's a good product, but it's
not worth $50 for a lift ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   A typical headline in Ski Cheap gives such information teases
as: ``Probably the best deals of the season are the ski passes
offered by state ski associations that offer multiple tickets for
one price. See below . . . for four unbeatable statewide ski
passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Two elements in the psyche of Chris Estes seem to conflict,
making it his life's work, he says, to reconcile them: ``I love to
ski. I think people have to get out there as much as they can. But
I am really, really cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Estes's newsletter address is Ski Cheap/PO Box 429/Chester, VT
05143. Or respond to his website: www.ski-ridecheap.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
