<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHINA-PEONY-PAVILION-     11-24 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PEONY-PAVILION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE DRAMA, A SHANGHAI `PEONY'? YES, WITH CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ _ One of the few predictable postscripts to
last year's drama over the blocking of a production of ``The Peony
Pavilion'' from a New York performance was that cultural officials
here would come up with their own version of the classic Chinese
opera. The Communist Party-approved ``Pavilion'' was recently
performed in a run-down auditorium here. It won few plaudits
outside the official press, and even in a relatively modest-size
performance hall plenty of seats remained empty.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the production of ``The Peony Pavilion'' that
finally reached New York's Lincoln Center Festival in July and won
praise for Chen Shi-Zheng's creative interpretation and inventive
staging, Shanghai's production was considered flat and lifeless by
many operagoers. At least there were efforts to spruce up the
presentation with rhinestone-studded gowns, flowery backdrops and
flashing lights, which offered an element of kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   It was presented in 30 scenes over three nights, for a total of
seven hours, notably shorter than the full 55-scene, 19-hour show
in New York. The Shanghai production did not have the asset of Qian
Yi, the actress who chose to perform her lead role of Du Liniang in
the New York version. Three pairs of actors performed the lead
roles on separate nights. After the furor on the eve of President
Clinton's visit to China in June 1998, when cultural officials
inexplicably blocked Chen's production, the tepid welcome that the
new version got here may have seemed to be just desserts.
</P>
<P>
   To many in the audience, the seeming weakness of Shanghai's
``Peony Pavilion'' epitomized what is wrong with the arts in China,
where artistic creativity seems to be smothered by the country's
vast bureaucracy, which determines what the public should be
allowed to see.
</P>
<P>
   Communist Party officials might be expected to be on the lookout
for art that is politically subversive. This often inflexible
nature of Chinese officialdom can place a crushing burden on any
artist who attempts to come up with anything fresh or inventive.
</P>
<P>
   To an outsider living here, one of China's enduring mysteries is
why the world's most populous nation, brimming with talent and
backed by an illustrious cultural history, should have made such a
relatively meager contribution to this century's art. For instance,
in the last 100 years, including the half century before the
Communist Party came to power, China has failed to produce its
share of internationally renowned writers, composers or painters.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers, on the other hand, although they battle Communist
bureaucrats as any other artists do, work in a relatively new art
form and are free from the constraints of ancient traditions. So
despite tight restrictions on what they can do, they have produced
an impressive array of world-class films in the last 15 years. But
in Chinese opera the burden of the past is heavy. A bevy of
cultural officials and critics and directors jealously guard that
art form ensuring that any new interpretation that would modernized
it is kept firmly at bay.
</P>
<P>
   It took an outsider with a special ability, Chen, with both the
education inside Chinese theater and the perspective of someone who
had lived and worked outside China for 10 years, to tackle a
complex classic like ``The Peony Pavilion'' with success. Drawn to
the work (which has stirred controversy since it was written in
1754 by Tang Xianzu), Chen wanted to stage it in its original full
form of 55 scenes, and he hoped to make it engaging and accessible
with an innovative staging.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Chen's production rehearsed in China for a year with
the sole intention of performing outside China, cultural officials
became deeply irritated by his refusal to act as submissive as most
other directors in China.
</P>
<P>
   He ignored suggestions by officials about how to improve his
production, but the authorities showed him who was boss by blocking
the Shanghai Kunqu Opera Company altogether. Officially, the
bureaucrats denounced Chen's version as feudal, pornographic and
superstitious, an odd thing to call an opera written in a feudal
and superstitious era and displaying no nudity. It was clear to
those involved in the production that Chen's bold creativity and
artistic intransigence were really at issue.
</P>
<P>
   Chen must take responsibility for failing to anticipate
bureaucratic obstacles to his production. When they arose, he could
have agreed to whatever the officials wanted to change, only to
shift it back once he got the company to New York. Instead, he
tried logic, pointing out that the Shanghai Municipal Bureau of
Culture had signed a contract with Lincoln Center, which had paid
for the entire production and had given him full artistic
discretion. Yet logic does not always work in politics. In this
case not even the risk of tarnishing President Clinton's reception
in China could deter the officials involved.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the adverse publicity generated by the incident, it
was embarrassing to China's culture czars that it took a director
from the United States to revive ``The Peony Pavilion'' in its full
form.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they immediately copied the idea and ordered the actors
Chen had worked with to participate. It apparently took months
before officials could find a director who was willing to take on
the project, and it was not hard to understand why.
</P>
<P>
   During rehearsals, both Ma Bomin, the director of the culture
bureau who carried out the decision to block last year's
production, and Shanghai's deputy mayor, Gong Xueping, offered
suggestions about what changes should be made to the staging.
Perhaps the greatest tragedy was for the performers themselves,
many of whom have spent a lifetime studying Kunqu Opera but were
denied a singular chance last year to perform a fresh
interpretation of a fragile and long-neglected work and to take it
to New York and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a rare, rare opportunity,'' said one of the actors
who participated, expressing admiration for Chen's version. ``It
tore my heart to lose it. But we live in China, and that's life in
China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
