<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOUSES-SUNLIGHT-NYT &LR;      11-24 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSES-SUNLIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANNELING THE SUN TO CREATE A PAINTING OF LIGHT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH GIOVANNINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACCOKEEK, Md. _ Some houses are built around a view, some around
a hearth, some around the kitchen, but rare is the home predicated
on celestial events. In architectural history, the buildings that
channel sunlight are usually religious structures that materialize
light, as though the finger of God were making a divine point by
marking space at a designated time.
</P>
<P>
   At Josephine Withers' house in this forested area across the
Potomac River from Mount Vernon, the star of the show, for the six
months starting in September and ending in March, is the sun, which
peers in through the long, high clerestory windows on the south
side of her two-story living room and strikes coated glass and
mirrored metals suspended from the ceiling. The work, by Janet
Saad-Cook, sends back a ``light painting'' across the south wall.
</P>
<P>
   In early September, the angle of the sun makes the painting
flicker. By now, the painting is in full stride, fluttering as the
remaining leaves filter the sunlight. At the winter solstice, with
the leaves gone and the sun at its nadir, the chromatic apparitions
achieve full bloom. Then, over the following months, the show fades
and gradually expires.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Withers asked McInturff Architects of Bethesda, Md., to
design a modest, 1,500-square-foot house on a rural site in
Maryland, she spelled out her many requirements in a letter. She
wanted the house to follow feng shui principles; it should face and
frame the forest out back, with its oak, beech and holly, and it
should have a horizontality to complement the contours of the land.
</P>
<P>
   She stipulated its character _ informal, calm and serene _
without specifying any architectural style. In addition, she asked
the architects to collaborate with Ms. Saad-Cook, who works in
Arlington, Va., to create a wall that would serve as a canvas for a
projected light piece.
</P>
<P>
   The two women have been friends for many years, and Ms. Withers
has seen Ms. Saad-Cook's work evolve from 1970s sculptures composed
of gauze, bamboo reeds and sisal (earthy materials that interact
with direct sunlight) to work that uses light, itself. Ms.
Saad-Cook uses optical instruments to reflect, refract, split,
shape and throw light onto nearby surfaces in moving washes of
color.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tradition of using natural light to interact with a
space is ancient, Ms. Withers, an associate professor of art
history at the University of Maryland at College Park, places her
friend's work in a Modernist tradition. (Other contemporary light
artists include Robert Irwin, James Turrell and Doug Wheeler.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Saad-Cook's shifting color fields set off chromatic events
that have a life of their own, the colors mixing unpredictably in
intensities that depend on the weather, time of day and angle. One
of Ms. Saad-Cook's pieces is at the Haystack Observatory outside
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always thinking about light in architecture _ that's
fundamental to our work,'' said Mark McInturff, the principal in
McInturff Architects. ``But we'd never worked with a light
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Lawlor, the project architect, said that he and
McInturff first met Ms. Saad-Cook in her loft, where she bends
metal or glass reflectors and coats them with chemicals to absorb
or reflect light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her whole studio was devoted to tracking the movement of the
sun, with chalked notations traced all over the floor,'' he said.
``We were blown away. It looked like something out of Copernicus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Saad-Cook has visited the great 18th-century observatories
in Jaipur and Delhi, India; the pyramids of Mexico; and the kivas
of Chaco Canyon in New Mexico, to ponder their solar mysteries. In
India, she recalls being in a dark astronomical tower and seeing an
intense beam of light slipping off a curved table and shattering on
the floor. ``An unforgettable experience, right up there with
childbirth,'' said Ms. Saad-Cook, the mother of three.
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Light, it's like a fickle lover. He's not there
when you need him; he's all over the place when it doesn't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The sun drove decisions at Ms. Withers' bucolic 11-acre site.
``The sun told us approximately where the house wanted to be
located, because there was a clearing, and we needed southern
light,'' Lawlor said.
</P>
<P>
   The architects sited the house in a clearing on a saddle sloping
down to two ravines and a stream, and worked with an astronomer,
Peter Boyce Sr., Ms. Saad-Cook's mentor. Boyce made a printout
showing architectural sections of the building and windows, and he
worked up a chart following the path of the sun to show what months
the sun would be active with respect to the proposed light piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and Janet are really able to hash out anything,'' Lawlor
said. ``I remember a whole discussion about how a special gimbel
mount would maximize the amount of sun. He had one opinion, she had
the opposite, and it was a battle between art and science right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Withers' most demanding requirement was the cost. ``I
definitely had a budget,'' she said. The result was architectural
simplicity _ a two-story gabled structure as rudimentary as a
Monopoly-board house but split into halves spanned by a covered
bridging structure. The flat-roofed bridge is glazed on the north
side facing the forest, and is clad in corrugated metal on the
south side, where Ms. Saad-Cook's light piece is projected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget encouraged us to keep the square footage down and
to minimize foundations, which led us to think of spanning from one
side of the house to the other,'' Lawlor said. The cost for the
house worked out to $100 a square foot, or $150,000, without road
and septic work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it a `Case Study House' in inexpensive construction
on the drawings that we gave out to the contractors for bids,''
McInturff said.
</P>
<P>
   The architects cut costs by deploying generic details and
materials, like asphalt shingle siding, Ikea cabinets and $8
exterior light fixtures used throughout the interiors.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the two-story volume looks like a loft and acts like a
plaza between the two bookend structures, where two bedrooms and a
study are located. An interior bridge, whose rails act as a truss,
connects the two halves of the upper story. The architects designed
the two metal struts suspended from the ceiling, which hold up the
reflective instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simplicity of the interior is disciplining me,'' said Ms.
Withers, who moved into the house last year after living in a
Victorian environment where clutter looked good. ``It did cross my
mind to move paintings onto the south wall during the other half of
the year, but now that I'm here, I like it plain.''
</P>
<P>
   The house has had a profound effect on her consciousness. ``It's
been cleansing to get rid of stuff,'' she said. ``It lightens me
up. I could cram it full of books, but I don't do that because this
house demands a cleanness. The house is speaking to me, and I'm
willing to submit to that discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides becoming more aware of the light, Ms. Withers says she
notices the forested setting because of the way the windows frame
the trees. ``Those are the gifts of the house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The sun drawing has become a local landmark: on sunny days
during the darker and colder months, neighbors bring friends to see
the south wall.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Withers was surprised by the first glimmerings of the sun
drawing in early September. ``I wasn't waiting for it,'' she said.
``It's ephemeral. You can't nail it on the wall, and yet it returns
tomorrow, it returns next year.'' Next September, she said, she
will be waiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0583 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-DISNEYQUEST-TE     11-24 1585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DISNEYQUEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A NEW GAME IN CHICAGO _ DISNEYQUEST 
(ACCOMPANIED BY BC-TRAVEL-DISNEYQUEST-REVIEW-TEX)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A middle-aged ``hausfrau,'' speaking from a
wall-mounted television, implores us to ``Save the colonists!'' It
seems our merry band of tourists are the colonists' only hope.
</P>
<P>
   The universal mom figure has issued her orders. We all nod our
heads, lemmings prepared to do her bidding. She sends us into the
rescue ship simulator with a rousing, ``Now, let's go kick some
alien butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK. I'm not really sure I know how to apply pedal-force to
the posterior of an alien's anatomy, but I'm confident that my
children do.
</P>
<P>
   The two teens are the reason we're spending a long weekend in
Chicago at DisneyQuest, the most recent device of the Walt Disney
Co. to separate indulgent parents from their dollars.
</P>
<P>
   This second location of DisneyQuest, an indoor interactive game
arcade, is packed with virtual reality games, simulated rides and
computer stations. It is Disney's answer to Sega GameWorks.
</P>
<P>
   But where DisneyQuests are heavily orchestrated to reflect
Disney films and family entertainment, GameWorks are thrill bars _
dark, raucous and filled with teens. At DisneyQuest, a virtual
reality game is Aladdin's Magic Carpet Ride; at GameWorks, it is a
simulation of hang-gliding. And where Sega likes to put its indoor
parks close to megaplex movie theaters, DisneyQuests can stand
alone. The Disney name is the draw.
</P>
<P>
   The family has spent many days and many dollars at various
Disney venues, and we've never been disappointed. And DisneyQuest
is a bargain in today's high-cost entertainment arena; all-day
passes that cost $34 each give you unlimited access to every
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Disney experiences, there is never a tear in the fabric
of the fantasy. The mechanics are always disguised. At DisneyQuest,
every nook, every mural, each and every wall, even the carpet, is
designed to entertain.
</P>
<P>
   I am enchanted by the staging. As I try to find a manufacturer's
name on the chairs that look just like the enchanted ones from
``Beauty and the Beast,'' my children remind me why we have come.
</P>
<P>
   We are here for the virtual reality games. We are willing to don
helmets that give us the profile of a platypus, just to
Ride-the-Comix. We use our light sabers to slash in huge lunging
sweeps, trying to rid the world of evil bikers. Well, everyone
except my daughter, who refuses to look silly. At 13, she is quite
sensitive about perceived dorkiness.
</P>
<P>
   This hypersensitivity to coolosity vs. dorkdom can mean success
or death in the business of family entertainment _ and it explains
a lot about the existence of DisneyQuest.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, my daughter thought she was Ariel, the little
mermaid. Thanks to Disney's movie, she wore Ariel clothes, slept on
Ariel sheets and jumped rope in Ariel-bedecked shoes. Her father
and I could predict the box-office business of each new Disney
release by my daughter's desire for the clothing (millions) or
matching accessories (double-digit millions).
</P>
<P>
   If she wanted the sheets, the movie was going to be really big.
</P>
<P>
   Then, abruptly pre-''Pocahontas,'' all things Disney became
``baby.'' This saves us some money _ not having to buy new linens
for each new animated film _ but it is a big problem for Disney and
its spinoff product lines. The Disney brand appeals to parents and
children. Preteens and teens are SO not interested.
</P>
<P>
   DisneyQuest appeals to this fickle audience with high-tech game
arcades. DisneyQuests also fill the geographic void between Japan
and France, Orlando and Anaheim. The Quests are quick Disney fixes
that can be scattered across the globe; 15 to 20 locations are
planned, though cities have not been named.
</P>
<P>
   The first DisneyQuest, in Orlando, Fla., was followed this
summer by the opening of the Chicago location, a block off the
heavily trafficked Michigan Avenue. Philadelphia will be the site
of the third park in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the full-scale theme parks that ramble over rural acres,
and take at least a full day to experience, DisneyQuests are built
in the inner city. The Chicago location is in a five-story downtown
building. Up to one thousand visitors are expected each day, but
only for a few hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Quick and changeable is the business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent theme-park rides are a huge investment, but
DisneyQuest games and virtual rides are meant to be impermanent.
About one-quarter of them will be changed each year so the company
can quickly respond to the transient interests of teens.
</P>
<P>
   On our visit, the design-your-own roller coaster was a big draw.
Standing in front of a computer screen at Cyber Space Mountain,
Michael, 15, and Katy, 13, choose from among a long list of coaster
thrills _ double loops, barrel rolls, jumps, spirals, camelbacks,
banked curves and high hills _ putting as many upchuck features as
possible in 10,000 feet of track.
</P>
<P>
   They climb aboard the simulator, a large tuna can built for two,
to test their design. I decline to enter what looks like a
claustrophobic vomitorium. Instead, I watch my children's
expressions on the video screen outside the capsule enclosure.
Their smiles and screams are recorded by a tiny video camera.
</P>
<P>
   The simulator operator, Christopher, assures me there are two
cut-off buttons, one inside the compartment, another outside. He
adds: ``I shut it down if I see their eyes roll back in their
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   I, too, design a coaster. It is nothing but a series of huge
hills. The computer informs me one out of five people would think
it scary. I refuse a trial ride. Which is perfectly OK, I explain
to the kids. There is no shame in knowing one's limitations and
tolerance for G-forces.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to save some face, I suggest we check out the Magic
Mirrors. This computer station will take a photo of your face, put
it on a monitor and allow you to manipulate your image. You can
twist and turn, nip and tuck, melt and wave, or rotate your face
into something funny. I opt for cosmetic surgery instead of comic
surgery. A little off the dewlaps, plump up the lips, enlarge the
eyes a tad, and VOILA, I look just like Carol Channing. Eeek.
</P>
<P>
   On to Living Easels, which is Disney Animation for Dummies.
Sitting in front of a monitor mounted in an easel, you pick from a
selection of lusciously rendered backgrounds and add animated
creatures and effects by simply touching the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the Stone Age background with the characters from the
Sweet Stuff page makes a surreal world of geysers, molten lava
fields, swooping pterodactyls and dancing gingerbread couples.
</P>
<P>
   This, beguilingly, was my chance to create a Disney-quality
piece of animation. To be honest, it has been prepackaged by Disney
artists, so it's already a Disney product. The results are
``Fantasia''-like, and I am thoroughly impressed with my facility
for animation.
</P>
<P>
   Too soon, my children come to drag me away. They want to play
the old games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old games?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, in the arcade they have Miss Pac Man,'' trills my
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Tron,'' adds my son in reverential tones.
</P>
<P>
   I realize that in only three decades we have come from binary,
black-and- white, back-and-forth Pong to the magnificent Living
Easels. Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   The children wax me at each old game _ cars, motorcycles and
boats. They are ecstatic. I challenge them to Mighty Ducks Pinball
Slam, an interactive game in which you physically become the
pinball. It's an aerobic workout, and I ponder the possibilities of
combining Nautilus equipment with virtual gaming. The kids beat me
at this game too, by a huge margin. I plead weariness and slink
away to Food Quest, where I nurse my injured pride over a soda.
</P>
<P>
   Food is important at entertainment venues; it's the big
revenue-raiser. Gaming gurus say it's where Discovery Zone failed;
the indoor party-playgrounds bellied up this past summer, after two
bankruptcy reorganizations in as many years. They learned too late
what McDonald's learned early with Leaps and Bounds, a Discovery
Zone competitor _ the profits are in the pizza, not the entrance
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Disney enlisted the Cheesecake Factory, a very popular
California-based restaurant chain, to set up a cafeteria and a
sweet shop called Wonderland Cafe. The food stretches beyond
burgers. There are kid-pleasing cheese and PB&AMP;J sandwiches, plus
more exotic fare and wraps. Our bill for lunch comes to $23. And
that is the last penny I spend inside DisneyQuest.
</P>
<P>
   Disney expects us to stay a few hours. We log eight. Because we
are there on a weekday, one that is not a holiday for Chicago
schools, we have the place to ourselves for several hours. Many
times, if we want a second ride, we don't have to return to the
line, because there isn't one. By the time we leave at 7 that
evening, DisneyQuest is packed, and we have experienced our
favorite games and virtual reality rides three or four times. We
have heard that on weekend nights it can become unbearably crowded.
We leave with a smug look on our faces. We feel like our hours of
line-free playing were a glorious gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they build a DisneyQuest in our area, would you want to
go?'' I ask. The kids, in unison, make that indignant coughing
sound that indicates they are about to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uuh....... ye-ah.''
.MDUL/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
