<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-CARLIN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EVOLUTION OF GEORGE CARLIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL DeYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recently on ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' Regis Philbin
asked his contestant this brain-buster: Who was the very first
guest host on ``Saturday Night Live,'' in October 1975?
</P>
<P>
   George Carlin _ the host in question _ happened to be in front
of a TV, watching. ``The (expletive) didn't know the answer,''
Carlin chuckles. ``And his friend in Albany didn't get it, either.
But I kind of like it, that they didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that money was lost. The George Carlin who
schmoozed that long-ago NBC audience with his hippy-dippy
weatherman routine is barely recognizable in today's Carlin, whose
standup comedy is raw, edgy, angry.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin has been in show business for 43 years, and although he
first gained notoriety as a ``counterculture comic'' in the early
'70s, that particular Carlin was just a morph on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he riffs on religion, advertising, sex and society with a
palpable contempt for almost all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an element in it of true anger, but there's an awful
lot of theatrical exaggeration,'' Carlin explains in a telephone
interview. ``So it's a bit of an adversarial and a confrontational
thing, and it plays as anger. I don't live angrily. I'm very
accessible to fans, I'm easygoing, I root for the little guy. I
defer to the least powerful person in the room, usually.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't feel positive and optimistic about my species and
my culture.''
</P>
<P>
   His verbal attacks, he explains, are ``intended to show
discontent, and to try to shame and embarrass the audience, as
members of the human race, as members of the United States culture,
for what they've done. And what they've allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlin, 62, is a native of New York City who never made it
through the ninth grade. He joined the Air Force in his late teens,
and it was during his hitch that he started developing his talent
for voices and mimicry. He became a disc jockey, and then a standup
comedian.
</P>
<P>
   Many years and mainstream TV appearances later, Carlin began to
resent the blandness of his time-tested material. He threw in with
the burgeoning counterculture, grew a beard and began writing and
performing more unconventional stuff, including jokes about
sexuality and casual drug use.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, he got fired from a prestigious Las Vegas hotel for
using the ``s'' word in his act. There was no turning back.
</P>
<P>
   America took him to its bosom through a series of appearances on
``The Flip Wilson Show'' in 1971. Wilson was co-owner of a record
label, Little David, which released in quick succession a series of
Carlin albums. They all went gold.
</P>
<P>
   He was a comedian like no other. One of his most famous bits was
called ``The Seven Words You Can't Say on Television.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlin, of course, expanded the list, and by the time of his
first HBO special in 1977, he was too much for the networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole structure had changed,'' he explains. ``And I had
completely outgrown it anyway, not just with the language I use,
but the kind of topics I choose.''
</P>
<P>
   His basic philosophy these days is that the world is hopelessly,
irredeemably screwed up. He doesn't say ``screwed,'' either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be only standup comedy, and I know that, I'm not
ashamed of that,'' he says. ``But it's art. It's writing. It's
interpreting the world through your own prism, and that's the
writer's job. And a writer is an artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are my thoughts and ideas. Of course, it is rhetoric, so
there's a great deal of overstatement and exaggeration. You have to
paint with a broad brush in rhetoric and in comedy, not only to
make your point but to make it in an absurd way.''
</P>
<P>
   Evolution, he explains, is only natural. ``A person who's 20
years old, who sees a particular phenomenon in society, sees it
against a kind of thin backdrop,'' he says. ``But a person who's 65
has a long experience, and whatever it is they're seeing, the
comparison with what they already know is much richer. So their
conclusions can be richer and have more texture to them. I've been
lucky enough to live this long, and have my faculties, and whatever
I've done has just been through accumulating information on my own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a far from perfect job. They say a self-made man is a
good example of unskilled labor, and that might be true of me, but
I'm very happy with the result of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, this self-made man and high school dropout sold
600,000 copies of a book of musings called ``Brain Droppings.'' The
book spent 18 weeks on the New York Times bestseller list. A six-CD
box set of his Little David recordings has just been released. ``It
makes a wonderful First Communion gift,'' he says, with a winking
trace of the old Carlin charm.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin may be finding a new audience thanks to his appearance as
Cardinal Glick in the movie ``Dogma,'' which lampoons Catholicism
in much the same way Carlin himself has for years. In fact, the
comedian says, writer/director Kevin Smith created the role with
Carlin in mind. No one else was ever considered.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
