<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sentimentality strikes a chord with readers
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Literary critics decry sentimentality, but apparently it sells.
How else can you explain the success of ``The Notebook'' and
``Message in a Bottle'' by Nicholas Sparks or ``The Christmas Box''
by Richard Paul Evans?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're gentle books that help us feel things we haven't felt
in a while,'' said Evans, whose self-published story of a young
family that moves in with an elderly widow became a phenomenon four
years ago. Simon &AMP; Schuster paid $4.2 million for the hardback
rights, and Maureen O'Hara and Richard Thomas starred in the
made-for-TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four years and 10 million copies of his books later, Evans
is back with ``The Looking Glass'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17.95),
another inspiring tear-jerker. Set in the 1850s Southwest, the
novel is the story of a reclusive gold prospector who still grieves
for his dead wife. All that changes when he meets a young woman who
has been brutally abused by her husband and attacked by ravenous
wolves.
</P>
<P>
   As melodramatic as Evans' plots sound, they touch a chord with
readers. ``They want to believe in the redemptive power of love,''
he said. ``At nearly every book signing for `The Christmas Box,'
people who have lost loved ones came up to me to say they had heard
of the healing power of the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans says the books have changed him, too. A former advertising
executive intent on getting rich, the Salt Lake City father of five
found that success can bring problems. When he made millions from
``The Christmas Box,'' many of his friends and some of his family
members turned against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd heard lottery winners talk about this, but I didn't
believe it until it happened. In America, we love success but hate
the successful. Eventually most of our friends came back. They said
they distanced themselves because they thought I would change.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, for a time. But now the family has moved back into it's
old neighborhood into the small starter house. Evans also has
funded the Christmas Box House, an assessment center and shelter
for abused children in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been exciting to be involved with this project,'' he
said. ``We wanted to show our children that you can do good with
money rather than letting it ruin your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans will sign books 4-6 p.m. Sunday at Hobbit Hall in Roswell
(120 Bulloch Ave., 770-587-0907), 6-8 p.m. Monday at Barnes &AMP; Noble
Booksellers in Morrow (1939 Mount Zion Road, 770-471-2227), noon
Tuesday at Chapter 11 Discount Bookstore (3509 Northside Parkway
N.W., 404-841-6338), and 7 p.m. Tuesday at Chapter 11 at Snellville
Plaza (2280 U.S. 78, 770-736-0502).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Millennium poll: J.R.R. Tolkien's ``The Lord of the Rings''
barely beat out Margaret Mitchell's ``Gone With the Wind'' as the
favorite book of the millennium in an Amazon.com poll. Rounding out
the Top 10, in order, are: ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' by Harper Lee;
``The Catcher in the Rye'' by J.D. Salinger; ``Harry Potter and the
Sorcerer's Stone'' by J.K. Rowling; ``The Stand'' by Stephen King;
``Ulysses'' by James Joyce; ``Atlas Shrugged'' by Ayn Rand; ``The
Grapes of Wrath'' by John Steinbeck; and ``1984'' by George Orwell.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Bible received the most votes, but since it wasn't
written in the past 1,000 years, it wasn't eligible. Amazon.com
received more than 250,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And more lists: Christopher Caldwell of Talk magazine used no
polls to compile the most talked-about books of the century. Maybe
that's why Tom Wolfe's ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' and Jim
Bouton's ``Ball Four'' are lumped in with ``Ulysses'' and ``Lady
Chatterley's Lover.'' Caldwell justifies his choices by pointing
out that Bouton's book made Americans take a more realistic look at
sports heroes, while he describes ``Bonfire'' as ``the last big
novel everyone read.'' Other books included are: ``Introductory
Lectures on Psycho-Analysis'' by Sigmund Freud; ``Invisible Man''
by Ralph Ellison; ``Sexual Behavior in the Human Male'' and
``Sexual Behavior in the Human Female'' by Alfred C. Kinsey;
``Eichmann in Jerusalem'' by Hannah Arendt; ``Quotations From
Chairman Mao'' by Mao Zedong; and ``The Bell Curve'' by Richard
Herrnstein and Charles Murray.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
