<SLUG> BC-BUYER'S-EDGE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tree trimming for the holidays
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas tree without ornaments is, well, just a a tree. Even
the gangliest evergreen can stand tall and proud when its boughs
are bedecked with jolly Santas and plump snowmen, some shiny red
balls, a crystal icicle or two and maybe a few silver bells.
</P>
<P>
   If there's anything more fun than decorating the tree, it's
unpacking the boxes filled with the memories that each ornament
evokes. But maybe it's time to add a few baubles to your
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the '80s, interest in Christmas ornaments was
waning,'' says Kathy Cook, a home decor expert for Enesco Home
Gallery, ``but in the last part of this decade we've seen a renewed
attraction in them.''
</P>
<P>
   We're seeing more wonderful designs than ever before in gift
stores and Christmas shops around the area. We've gathered what we
consider some of the season's merriest ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   And we offer these ideas on collecting these special keepsakes:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Think of ornaments as collectibles. Either go for an eclectic
look or focus on one designer, such as Christopher Radko, Kurt S.
Adler or Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   And why put them up after the holidays? They'll be special
additions to your china cabinet or curio chest all year long.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Give ornaments as gifts. Start a tradition such as giving a
beloved child an ornament each year so that she will have an
impressive collection by the time she has her own tree to decorate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy ornaments (or souvenirs that can be adapted for use as an
ornament) when you go on vacation and hang them on the tree. Shells
make great decorations; just glue on a hanger.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy small toys to place on tree boughs. Little plastic horns,
tiny teddy bears and soft-stuffed dolls work well.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hang ornaments in unexpected places: on a chandelier, on a
door wreath or pine bough or in a window, suggests Home Gallery's
Kathy Cook. Or group several in glass or silver bowls throughout
the house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If your hometown or favorite organization produces an annual
ornament, start collecting.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you have more ornaments than you can cram on the tree, give
some of your extras to the kids to decorate a small tree for their
room or play space.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Place food-themed ornaments on a small tree for the kitchen.
We've seen candy canes, gingerbread people, tiny fruitcakes and
even blown-glass fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
