<HEADER>
A0595 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION2     11-24 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A civil town worthy of Norman Rockwell
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKLIN, Tenn. _ If Norman Rockwell were around today and
looking for a perfect little Southern town to paint, he couldn't
find a better place than Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   Located about 20 miles from Nashville, Franklin is a Main Street
type of town built around a 15-block Victorian commercial district
with a towering statue of a Confederate soldier at its center.
</P>
<P>
   The town was the site of one of the bloodiest battles in the
Civil War _ the Battle of Franklin in 1864 _ when Confederate
forces charged entrenched Union troops near the Carter House. The
fierce, five-hour fighting resulted in Confederate losses of 6,000
and Union losses of more than 2,000. Bullet holes can still be seen
in the clapboards of the nearby farm office.
</P>
<P>
   It is much quieter here now. Throngs of visitors and residents
stroll along shady, brick-paved streets that lead past an eclectic
mix of antique shops, gift stores and bookstores, art galleries and
businesses. Just off the square are a number of historic homes,
churches and bed-and-breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fastest-growing towns in Tennessee, Franklin has
become a haven for busloads of tour groups eager to soak up its
historic atmosphere and browse through the quaint shops.
</P>
<P>
   But things weren't always this prosperous.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the late '60s, the main businesses in town were discount
furniture stores, a Ben Franklin five-and-dime and other
nondescript shops whose old brick facades were obscured by aluminum
storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants watched helplessly as most of the shoppers flocked to
new shopping centers and residents abandoned older downtown homes
for the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point occurred in the early 1980s, when a group of
local investors saw the potential in the historic buildings on Main
Street. The aluminum fronts were ripped off to expose the old
brick, businesses moved in, the rundown Merchant's Hotel was
converted into a restaurant and the upper floors of a 19th century
building at Fourth and Main were turned into elegant apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the downtown got a $2.6 million Streetscape face
lift of brick sidewalks, lighting and tree plantings.
</P>
<P>
   The improvements drew young entrepreneurs such as Paul and
Angela Barrett, who opened a fragrant soap and cosmetics shop
called Bliss two years ago. Barrett, a native of London, was
enthralled by the charm of the town. ``My wife is a Southerner,''
he says, ``and she liked to make different kinds of soap as a
hobby. So we decided to set up shop here and make a clean break
from big-city life, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   If the aromas of the soaps do not bring in customers, the clouds
of bubbles floating out the door will.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the street, Strange and Wonderful Things proves to
be an accurate name for Barbara Kurland's unusual shop. From
sterling silver eating utensils shaped like human bones to an
assortment of bamboo Vietnamese musical instruments, the store is
irresistible to the curious.
</P>
<P>
   Just as inviting is Yarrow Acres, Sheri and Mike Gramer's shop
of garden accessories, herbs, country antiques and folk art. The
crowded shelves and narrow aisles evoke the charm of an
old-fashioned hardware store without the unpleasant smells of
fertilizer and chewing tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Other interesting shops on the square include Heart and Hands,
Ellen Forster's shop of pottery, stoneware and other handcrafted
items; Patchwork Palace, which specializes in vintage quilts dating
from 1800 to 1940; and the Heirloom Shop, a colorful store filled
with collectibles and hand-blown glass Christmas ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   And, speaking of the holidays, the whole town becomes one big
Victorian Christmas scene Dec. 11-12, when Franklin celebrates a
Dickens of a Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Five blocks of main street are blocked to traffic, some
residents dress up as characters from ``A Christmas Carol'' and
other Dickens stories and others in costume demonstrate Victorian
crafts in the store windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have horse-drawn carriage rides, carolers and hand-bell
choirs,'' says Nancy Williams of the Downtown Franklin Association.
``We'll even have a Fagin and a little pickpocket running around.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-75 north from Atlanta to Chattanooga. At
I-24 junction, take I-24 west for 108 miles to Murfreesboro. Exit
at Tenn. 96 west to Franklin. It's about 30 miles from I-24 and 244
miles from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most shops are open 9 a.m.-6 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays;
1-6 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Plenty of free on-street parking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most stores are accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: In shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Downtown Franklin Association, 615-790-7094; or
Franklin-Williamson County Chamber of Commerce, 615-794-1225.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dotson's. This classic meat-and-three restaurant has
comfortable booths, friendly waitresses and walls covered with
signed photographs of country music stars. Daily specials vary from
smothered pork chops and fried chicken to country fried steak and
meatloaf for $5.50. Most days' choices include eight meats and 17
different vegetables. And don't skip dessert. Specials are
chocolate pies or Coca-Cola cake for $1.85 a slice. 99 E. Main St.,
615-794-2805. Open 6 a.m.-8 p.m. Mondays-Fridays; 6 a.m.-3 p.m.
Saturdays; 7 a.m.-3 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Also recommended: 4th &AMP; Main, an upscale restaurant on the
square that serves lunch specials such as cantaloupe stuffed with
chicken salad ($7.49) and Hazelnut Pecan Chicken ($6.99). Dinner is
fancier, with Cajun trout and pork chops stuffed with braised
spinach and blue cheese ($12-$16). Fourth and Main streets,
615-791-0001. Five Points Place 1923 has the ambience of an
old-fashioned soda fountain. Lunch specials such as baked ham and
sweet potatoes ($4.95-$5.95) are served as well as chicken salad
with walnuts on a croissant ($5.50) and homemade vegetable soup
($2.25). The house specialty is a pimento cheese with bacon
croissant sandwich ($5.50). 438 Main St., 615-591-4787.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Magnolia House Bed &AMP; Breakfast. This 1905 Craftsman-style
home, operated by Jimmy and Robbie Smithson, was built on land that
was the site of the Civil War Battle of Franklin. It's within two
blocks of the historic Carter House and the Lotz House Civil War
Museum, and a short walk to downtown Franklin. Each of the four
guestrooms is furnished with antiques and has a private bath. A
full Southern-style breakfast is served at 8:30 a.m. $80-$95. No
smoking or pets. 1317 Columbia Ave., 615-794-8178.
</P>
<P>
   Other places to stay near downtown include the Franklin House
Bed and Breakfast, 302 Third Ave. South, 615-591-0808, with rooms
for $85 per night, and Rebel's Roost Bed and Breakfast, 305 Third
Ave. South, 615-790-8346, in the heart of the antiques district.
Two-bedroom suites with fully equipped kitchen, $100-$175.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dickens of a Christmas. If you visit Franklin on the second
weekend in December, you may think you have stepped back into
Victorian England. Every year, five blocks of the downtown area are
closed to automobile traffic and open to horse-drawn carriages and
strolling carolers dressed in period costumes. Scrooge and Father
Christmas will participate in the celebration as local residents
set up shop in the storefront windows to demonstrate Victorian
crafts. Plum pudding, hot chocolate and traditional British treats
will be sold, and a high tea will be held each afternoon at the
Franklin Episcopal Church. The celebration, which runs from 10
a.m.-5 p.m. Dec. 11 and 1-5 p.m. Dec. 12, is free. Information:
615-790-7094.
</P>
