<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where to get hard itemsBy Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But due to the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It, Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com (please
include yur name, the city you live in and daytime phone number);
or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Yardley of London's Rose bar soap and bath
powder.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carole Schneider, Ball Ground, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Another Yardley request: I have been in the Atlanta area 10
years and only recently lost my kitchen and guest powder room
mainstay _Yardley English Lavender liquid soap. I still see the
solid bars and liquid body wash. It came in a round pump dispenser
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Donna Sue Hettick, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Yet another Yardley plea: For several years, I have tried to
locate Yardley's Musk men's cologne. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Helene Camp, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: You Yardley fans are a loyal bunch. Since 1770, this English
company has been turning out nostalgic scents including rose and
lavender. Here's the latest scoop: Some items have been
discontinued, such as Yardley smelling salts. Other Yardley
products are sold only in Europe and South Africa, including the
men's Musk cologne and Bond Street cologne, the Black Label shaving
cream, after shave and deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   The English Lavender liquid soap is around, but can be hard to
find. We spotted a 16-ounce bottle for $2.29 at Drug Emporium, 2953
N. Druid Hills Road N.E. (404-636-6108). The liquid soap (16
ounces, $5.99) is also available through the catalog Beauty
Boutique (1-800-497-7463). Or you can order via the company at
1-800-528-3036. One 16-ounce bottle is $2.35.
</P>
<P>
   Good news for fans of Yardley's English Rose scent. It had been
discontinued but because of customer demand, the company is
bringing it back. English Rose will be available in March. A
1-ounce cologne will be $9.75, a trio of bar soaps will be $9.75
and a tin of talc will sell for $7.50. You can also order products
on the company's Web site: www.yardleylondon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q:I am looking for an old-fashioned wire rug beater.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sharon Myers, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Another old-fashioned request: I have looked everywhere for a
manually operated cookie press. The only kind I can find are
electric or run on batteries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mary Faster, Carrollton
</P>
<P>
   A: You both will appreciate the Lehman's retail operation. For
over 40 years, this family has operated hardware and appliances
stores in northeastern Ohio, selling nonelectric products to their
Amish neighbors who shun modern conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Amish have shown us that nonelectric products can give us
the ability to complete a task more efficiently than commonly
accepted modern methods,'' says founder Jay Lehman. Among the
inventory: oil lamps and gas refrigerators, wood and cook stoves,
glass-jar butter churns and, yes, a wire rug beater ($11.50) and a
manually operated cookie and pastry press with storage tray
($20.99).
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,500 items are in the catalog and two retail stores
in Kidron and Mt. Hope. Lehman's Non-Electric catalog is available
online at www.lehmans.com. You can also order at: 1-877-438-5346.
For a catalog ($4), call customer service: 1-888-438-5346.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for Dickinson's fruit preserves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jennifer Webber, Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another Dickinson's request: I've searched all over and
can't find Dickinson's jam. I tasted it at a resort in Lake Geneva,
Wis., and it was wonderful. The label said it was made in Oregon. I
would love to find it in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Judi Schildts, Gainesville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Toast, biscuits and muffins will soon be tastier with
Dickinson's preserves, which have been made in Oregon since 1897.
We found a 10-ounce jar of red raspberry ($2.99) at Cracker Barrel
Old Country Store, 6175 McDonough Drive, Norcross. Most Cracker
Barrel stores carry a wide assortment of flavors, including bing
cherry ($2.79), grape ($1.89) and honey ($3.99). Other stores also
carry the line. A sampling: Cub Foods, all stores, has plum and
seedless boysenberry ($3.38) and Ingles at 675 Buford Drive,
Lawrenceville, has several flavors, including orange marmalade and
peach ($2.69); strawberry ($3.19) and red raspberry and blackberry
($3.39).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you find Christmas ribbon candy? It is old-fashioned
hard candy, shaped like pieces of ribbon. I remember it from my
grandmother's house.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendy Messick, Grayson, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Tie one on this holiday season by indulging in Sevigny's Thin
Ribbon Candy. These colorful _ and fragile _ candies have just made
their annual appearance on store shelves. We found our 9-ounce box
($1.97) at Wal-Mart, 1630 Pleasant Hill Road, Duluth. The
manufacturer recommends you do not refrigerate the candy. To keep
it fresh, place in a covered glass dish or in a tightly covered
tin. Best of all, one piece of candy contains 60 calories but no
fat, cholesterol or salt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you locate Buf-Puf products for me? These cleaning
sponges are great for removing makeup. Many thanks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gloria T. Borders, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: These light-as-air sponges, according to manufacturer 3M
Health Care, lift off dry skin cells and gently take off makeup,
dirt and excess oil. Your skin should feel smooth and prepped for
moisturizer and makeup. A Buf-Puf with cleanser is $3.99 for 40
single sponges. Use a fresh sponge every time you wash. One regular
(also known as original) facial sponge is $3.69, and can be used
daily. It should be replaced every 4-6 weeks. We found ours at
Ulta, 3855 Venture Drive N.W., Duluth (770-232-0606).
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
