<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0597 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOK28-COX     11-24 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cooke takes true measure of character
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 28.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have enough to lay at the feet of President Clinton and
Kenneth Starr as it is, but an unwelcome mutation has redefined the
word ``character.'' Where it once implied _ not exclusively, but
primarily _ the essential attributes of a person's makeup, it's now
shorthand for undisclosed moral deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   My own profession, to be sure, has not been derelict in doing
its part. It never is. When reporters write about ``the character
issue,'' they hint at the scandalous and titillating without regard
to what in fact a person's character might be. If you doubt it,
consider this: The word is not used unless someone is under
suspicion of wrongdoing, usually of a sexual nature. The
implication is that if one's done nothing to embarrass himself, his
character is a moot issue _ nondescript, of no interest, secondary
to anything else that might be said about him.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, the older and more interesting meaning of the
word goes to the person's core. Novelists and playwrights
understand this, even if the press corps doesn't. There was a time
when it did. Alistair Cooke has spent six decades portraying public
people _ politicians, movie stars, writers and artists _ by
delineating their character. Years ago he wrote of Adlai
Stevenson's innate, and politically fatal, sense of noblesse
oblige:
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving among wretched people in mean places, as I often saw
him do, he had the humility of a saint but not the serenity. He was
acutely sensitive to poverty, sickness, disability and grief. But
when he was among his poorer worshipers, he could not improvise the
politician's spread-eagle stance and manic grin. He ambled
nervously among them, spoke gently, hoping to convey by a look that
he was grateful they did not hold their plight against him.''
</P>
<P>
   An artist's intuition
</P>
<P>
   Anyone reasonably competent can report the week-to-week
movements of the polls, parrot back a candidate's canned comments
and secure a quote or two from the crowd. It requires an artist's
intuition to see behind the public mask. Cooke wrote of Bertrand
Russell: ``He raged against the dying of the light of reason in
human affairs, but more against the greed, cowardice, hatreds and
injustices of his fellow man, of whom, from time to time, he
greatly feared he might be one.''
</P>
<P>
   Over several generations, Americans have known Cooke as the
witty and urbane narrator of such television programs as
``Omnibus,'' ``Alistair Cooke's America'' and ``Masterpiece
Theatre.'' But a sizable proportion of today's television audience
would scarcely know the name or the voice. And only a few would
know him as a correspondent for the British Broadcasting Corp. and
The Guardian, or as a skilled portraitist in prose. His most recent
book, ``Memories of the Great &AMP; the Good'' (Arcade, $24.95),
features commentaries on 23 public personalities _ from Frank Lloyd
Wright and Duke Ellington to Erma Bombeck and Bobby Jones _ and
demonstrates his particular gift for seizing on the character of a
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Enviable turns of phrase
</P>
<P>
   Cooke did this best in his book ``Six Men,'' from which the
descriptions of Adlai Stevenson and Bertrand Russell are drawn. But
``Memories of the Great &AMP; the Good,'' even if it has the feel of a
valedictory volume, sparkles with enviable turns of phrase and
Cooke's keen perceptions of personality. Cooke _ 91 years old this
month _ cobbled the collection together from pieces he wrote for
The New Yorker, from BBC broadcasts and from earlier books, and
added to the mix new pieces on George Bernard Shaw, Franklin D.
Roosevelt and James Reston.
</P>
<P>
   Of Bobby Jones in old age he writes: ``My first impression was
the shock of seeing the extent of his disability, the fine strong
hands, twisted like the branches of a cypress, gamely clutching a
tumbler or one of his perpetual cigarettes in a holder. ... (B)ut
the embarrassment a stranger might feel about this was tempered by
the quizzical eyes and the warmth his presence gave off.''
</P>
<P>
   When Barry Goldwater died a few years ago, respected by
Democrats and resented by the Republican far right, Cooke recalled
his impressions during Goldwater's presidential campaign in 1964.
The candidate and his constituency, he wrote, did not yet know they
were opposites: ``He has no strain of demagoguery in him. He
detests racial discrimination, but the ingrate South listens and
sees the Negro foiled. He thinks of Jefferson, and his audience
looks on Caesar.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooke's instinct was to appreciate more than to debunk, and it
could sometimes be a weakness. But when he felt the need to
criticize, he could do so deftly. Of Edward VIII, he wrote: ``He
was at his best only when the going was good.'' It was his style to
see complicated people whole, and he did so by identifying the
character that marked them as clearly as thumb prints.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
