<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE STOCKS   SIZZLE ON TURKEY DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to travel very far to find at least 61 reasons to
celebrate a very happy Thanksgiving today.
</P>
<P>
   That is the number of publicly traded Massachusetts companies
whose stocks have at least doubled so far in 1999, a figure that
does not include a number of wildly successful initial public
offerings launched this year.
</P>
<P>
   More important than the sheer sizzle of triple-digit gains,
their price appreciation represents the leading edge of what has
turned out to be a banner year to date for public Massachusetts
companies as a broad group.
</P>
<P>
   The Bloomberg Massachusetts index, which tracks the stock market
fortunes of 330 local companies, has surged by 40 percent so far
this year and reached a record high Monday. That gain outpaces
advances by nearly all major stock market indexes with the
exception of the Nasdaq Composite index, which has hurtled forward
by 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But here is the most striking comparison of all: the
Massachusetts index has moved up on a percentage basis as much this
year as it had over the previous three years combined.
</P>
<P>
   Over past years and in 1999, Massachusetts stocks have been
swayed by larger stock market trends. For now, the wind is firmly
at their backs.
</P>
<P>
   The index includes many large, nontechnical companies like
FleetBoston Financial Corp., Gillette Co., Raytheon Co., and
Staples Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But it consists mostly of scores of smaller and midsized
companies dedicated to a wide range of high-tech businesses. The
index is chock full of much less familiar names like Vicor Corp.,
Alpha Industries Inc., and Project Software &AMP; Development Inc. that
have boomed so far in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those stocks have tended to drift in recent years, amid
a market that seemed to be completely uninterested in anything but
very large companies. This year, the boom in technology investments
has spread to stocks of all sizes.
</P>
<P>
   As big technology stocks became very expensive, many
institutional investors have bought the cheaper shares of smaller
companies that offer similar kinds of high-growth or prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fund has seen its capitalization decline radically during
the course of the year,'' said Marc Klee, manager of the John
Hancock Global Technology fund. ``It's reflected the fact that we
saw better valuations there.''
</P>
<P>
   For the smaller issues with limited liquidity, demand on the
part of shareholders can have a disproportionate impact on prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's money coming into the small-cap growth
sector,'' said Brian Stack, who manages $3.5 billion at MFS
Investment Management in Boston. ``The illiquidity of the names
really starts to be your friend instead of the bane of your
existence.''
</P>
<P>
   The most successful Massachusetts companies so far this year
typically embrace one of several favorite technology investing
themes: high-speed telecommunications, biotechnology,
semiconductors, and anything that works the Internet in any way.
</P>
<P>
   Interleaf Inc. of Cambridge, easily the biggest winner of all,
has gained 1,968 percent to date this year. For years a
down-and-out publishing software company, it's riding high on new
products that may make it easier for devices other than your
standard personal computer to access the Web.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI Inc., the Internet investing hot house based in Andover,
continues to pile up huge 1999 gains after spectacular gains the
year before.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies among the best performers, LTX Corp. of Westwood
and Helix Corp. of Mansfield, are tied into the boom in the
semiconductor industry. So is Teradyne Inc. of Boston, which has
soared 113 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   EMC Corp. of Hopkinton, the big manufacturer of computer storage
equipment, has gained 110 percent in 1999 so far. Just this spring,
EMC surpassed Gillette Co. to become the most valuable public
company in the state. Today, EMC's $90 billion market value is
slightly more than twice the value of Gillette shares.
</P>
<P>
   An entire class of new IPO stocks based in Massachusetts have
boomed also, thanks to unquenchable and sometimes unexplainable
demand for Internet and telecommunications investments.
</P>
<P>
   This year's two biggest local new issues, Sycamore Networks Inc.
of Chemlsford and Akamai Technologies Inc. of Cambridge, have
traded at six to eight times their IPO price.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there's a list of losers among the state's public
companies, including 19 that have been cut by half or worse this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The worst performing stock of all: assisted-living manager
Carematrix Corp. of Needham, which has lost a crushing 93 percent
of its value in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
