<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0612 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CASSIDY-MERGER-BOS &LR;      11-24 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASSIDY-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LOBBYIST CASSIDY, IT WAS TIME FOR   MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There was a time when the photographs in Gerald
Cassidy's office advertised his dazzling success as a Capitol Hill
lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   There was Cassidy fishing with US Representative Silvio O.
Conte, the late, longtime ranking Republican on the House
Appropriations Committee. There he was again, beaming, standing
alongside the late House speaker, Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time when being a lobbyist meant chiefly knowing how to
schmooze. Cassidy was an expert, and his cozy ties with leaders in
Congress helped bring about beneficial legislation or funnel
millions in federal funds to clients from academia to aerospace _
with an emphasis on New England.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, the photographs seem as dated as the
three-martini lunch. Searching for a new look, the lobbying
industry is in transformation. Clients today want one-stop shopping
for all their clients' government-relations needs, from polling and
public relations to representation on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   So nearly 25 years after hanging out his shingle as ``Cassidy &AMP;
Associates,'' Cassidy this month sold his lobbying business to
Shandwick International, a public relations firm with offices in 52
countries and a subsidiary of Interpublic Group, a New York-based
global media and public relations conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   The selling price was reportedly just under $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy, 59, remains in charge of the four units of his firm
that specialized in lobbying and polling. Each keeps its old name,
but as part of a new office, Shandwick Washington. The fifth unit,
Powell Tate public relations, now becomes part of Shandwick's PR
operation.
</P>
<P>
   But Cassidy has gone from being kingpin of the firm that he
built from just two people in 1975 to 300 today to being a cog in
the works of a ``full service company'' devoted to performing every
public-relations and lobbying function under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his 13th Street office recently, Cassidy
reflected on the transformation. ``When I came here, a couple of
dozen people were the decision-makers in D.C.,'' he said. `'There
was a seniority system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 26 years, I've watched the way in which communications
and public affairs has changed. There's been a growth in the number
of media outlets. There's been a spreading of the power. There's
been the globalization of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fundamentally, ``everybody's become more sophisticated,''
Cassidy said.
</P>
<P>
   John R. Silber, the chancellor of Boston University, which has
been a big beneficiary of Cassidy's lobbying prowess over the
years, agreed. ``I suppose what's happening here is similar to
what's happening with banks and what's happening to hardware stores
and retail stores and the Internet,'' Silber said. ``These
corporations find they can work more effectively on a global basis
than they can on a local basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of this metamorphosis are the aquisition nearly a
decade ago of Gray &AMP; Co., a lobbying office, by Hill &AMP; Knowlton,
the public relations firm, and the more recent acquisition of
lobbying units by two big Washington law firms. Other, smaller
lobbying firms have also been in merger negotiations recently,
including podesta.com, run by Tony Podesta, a former aide to
Senator Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a huge level of consolidation in the industry,
because the industries we serve are consolidating,'' said Nancy
Sterling, a vice president for the Boston-based firm of Mintz,
Levin, which has a Washington office that houses lawyers, a
lobbying unit, and a public relations team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connections are still important,'' Sterling said, ``but I
don't know anyone who has even a one-martini lunch these days.
People are looking for a final product, and what we do is end up
putting together a network of products for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy's history is illustrative. The Brooklyn, N.Y, native
earned a Cornell University law degree in 1967 and, after briefly
working for a legal services program, took a staff job in
Washington with the Senate Select Committee on Nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   There he met George McGovern, the unsuccessful Democratic
candidate for president in 1972, and other influential Democrats
including O'Neill and Kennedy, followed.
</P>
<P>
   When he decided lobbying was his future, those contacts led to a
ready-made big client, Jean Mayer, the president of Tufts
University, who six years earlier headed a White House Conference
on Food, Nutrition and Health and wanted to build a government
supported nutritional institute in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy went to work and the result is the $32 million US
Department of Agriculture Jean Mayer Center for Human Nutrition and
Aging, next to the Tufts Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Boston University, with Silber then its new president, soon
signed on for help in pursuing funds for an engineering school. The
relationship continues; Cassidy more recently helped win
congressional support for BU's new Photonics Center.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy kept his firm's Capitol Hill connections fresh by hiring
from the ranks of congressional committee staffs and by buying out
smaller lobbying firms, including Boland &AMP; Madigan, which had
Republican Party ties. He also acquired Powell Tate, a public
realtions firm founded by Jody Powell, who was former President
Jimmy Carter's press secretary, and Shiela Tate, press aide to
Nancy Reagan and former President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other college clients _ Boston College, Columbia
University, and Northwestern University among them _ Cassidy also
signed up corporate interests _ Ocean Spray, the cranberry growers
cooperative; General Dynamics Corp., which builds nuclear
submarines in Connecticut; Crane &AMP; Co., the western Massachusetts
company that makes paper for US currency. Therre were national
clients, too _ the Boeing Co. is one.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues grew: last year Cassidy &AMP; Associates took in $40
million from all operations. Lobbying brought in $19.8 million of
that, making the firm Washington's most lucrative lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   What the change of ownership will mean for Cassidy is still
being worked out. He is still getting used to the new company name
and two weeks after the acquisition was still waiting for new
business cards.
</P>
<P>
   What it means for some clients, though, is easier to predict _
an international public relations network at their disposal _
without losing the services and connections of Cassidy himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that we want to project Boston University
worldwide, they are in a better position to do that now than they
were before,'' Silber said. ``We have wealthy alumni in Thailand,
Taiwan, Hong Kong, and for them to be more aware of Boston
University helps us in terms of fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be flattering myself,'' Silber continued, ``but I think
Boston University has a very special relationship to the Cassidy
firm, and I think I have a very important relationship to Gerry
Cassidy, which means they aren't going to forget Boston University.
If in the future they do as well as they've done in the past,
they're going to do very damn well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1828EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
