<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0613 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-MACMUGGERS-     11-24 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-MACMUGGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE THANKFUL FOR THE MACINTOSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SIMSON L. GARFINKLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Two weeks ago, I reviewed Apple's new iBook computer. Although
I praised the computer's industrial design and Apple's marketing
prowess, I couldn't resist taking a swipe at the Macintosh
operating system. Out on the Internet, I said, I had run into
problems _ particularly with Web sites that had been designed with
Windows users in mind, or those which required me to use programs
such as ``telnet'' or ``ftp.'' I also criticized the computer's
browsing speed, saying the iBook ran more slowly with my cable
modem than did my Pentium III desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   I should have known better than to say anything negative about
the Macintosh computer in print. Less than three hours after my
column hit the pavement, my in-box was filling up with hostile
e-mail from the Macintosh Faithful. People criticized my analysis,
said I had an inherent anti-Mac bias, and said I shouldn't blame
the MacOS system for the failings of Windows-centric Web designers.
One angry reader tried to organize a letter-writing campaign to the
Globe's ombudsman.
</P>
<P>
   This reaction from Macintosh users is somewhat typical. Unlike
Windows users, Mac-heads are quick to circle their wagons and
attack the messenger whenever someone criticizes their beloved
system. Apple evangelists have even organized harassment campaigns
to ``reeducate'' journalists who have written unfavorable Macintosh
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than engage in another war of words, I want to call a
truce. On this Thanksgiving Day, I want to give public thanks for
the Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, the Macintosh is the friendliest,
easiest-to-use, and the most colorful computer on the market today.
The Mac is a pleasure to operate. It's a computer that respects its
user.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment you turn it on, the Mac brings a smile to your
face. Press the ``on'' switch of a typical Windows computer and
you'll hear a nasty ``beep.'' The Mac, in contrast, plays a
pleasant chord. One of the things that I hate about my Windows
computer is the way it is always interrupting me. I can be in the
middle of typing something in my word processor, but if another
program needs my attention, it pops a window up in my face,
demanding immediate attention. Unfortunately, if I don't
immediately stop typing, it's quite likely that one of my
keystrokes will inadvertantly trigger one of the buttons on the
pop-up, and before I know it I've told the computer to go off and
do something else _ what I'm not sure. Mac programs, on the other
hand, get your attention by pulsing the Apple icon in the
computer's upper-left hand corner. There they will wait patiently
until you decide to see what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   Many readers wanted to know why I reviewed Apple's MacOS 8.5
operating system, when Apple had just released version 9.0. The
reason, as I explained in my column, was that the iBook came with
MacOS 8.5 installed. It was only the day after my column ran in the
paper that Apple provided me with MacOS 9.0.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, that same day I received a second operating system
in the mail: a copy of Windows 98 Second Edition. So that
afternoon, I upgraded both my iBook and my Windows desktop. The
experience gave me another reason to be thankful for the Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   The Macintosh upgrade was fast and painless. Following the
instructions on the CD, I put the CD in the iBook's CD-ROM drive,
held down the ``C'' key, and turned the computer on. The computer
booted from the CDROM. Next I ran the MacOS upgrader and was given
the choice of upgrading my current operating system or performing a
``clean install.'' (The clean install is useful if you have damaged
your computer and it will no longer boot.) I chose the upgrade
option; the job was finished in less than 10 minutes. When my
computer rebooted, it was running MacOS 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows upgrade was far more complicated. First, I had to
boot my computer into Windows and run the upgrade program from the
CD-ROM. Then I had to manually kill the ``MS-DOS'' box that I had
used to start up the upgrade program. Then I had to type an
activation key. Finally, I had to watch numerous Microsoft
advertisements for the next 40 minutes, and wait through two
reboots, until my computer was usable again. Microsoft has copied
so much from Apple _ it would be nice if they could copy the Mac's
ease-of-upgrading.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's new operating system gives us a lot to be thankful for,
as well. Just as with Windows 95, the Mac now supports multiple
users, with different levels of privilege assignable to each. And
it has a cool ``auto-update'' feature that lets you download
operating system updates automatically over the Internet by
clicking a button. Although there is a similar feature built into
Windows 98, I've tried both and the Mac's is far easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   Although programs such as ``ftp'' and ``telnet'' don't come with
the iBook, these programs are readily available on the Internet for
people who want to download them. And while it is true some Web
sites require ActiveX or Windows-specific helper-programs, most
don't. I'm thankful the Internet is equalizing many of the
differences between Mac users and PC users.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thankful for the stability of the Macintosh operating
system. Gone are the days when the Mac crashed every few hours.
These days the Mac is an incredibly reliable operating system _ far
more reliable than my Windows PC.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I'm thankful for the Macintosh user community _ a vocal
group of computer enthusiasts who are always quick to criticize any
person or company that does not properly support their computer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Simson Garfinkel can be reached at http://chat.simson.net/)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1829EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0614 &Cx1f; taf-z
a l BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV02-     11-24 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DO YOU HEAR WHAT YOUR KIDS ARE SAYING? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)   (For release Thursday, Dec. 2)  
 (bl)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I live disconcertingly close to Rockdale County, Ga., the
subject of a PBS recent ``Frontline'' documentary that has become a
national parable about promiscuous suburban teens.
</P>
<P>
   The documentarians chose Rockdale due to the surprising
incidence of syphilis in the teen-agers of the affluent community.
</P>
<P>
   What they discovered was a group of kids, some as young as 13,
living shockingly hedonistic lives _ multiple sex partners, group
sex, unsupervised parties, drugs and alcohol _ while still at home
under their parents' supposed supervision.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many things that are disturbing about the
documentary, it's hard to single one out. (For a transcript, visit
the PBS ``Frontline'' Web site at www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/
and click on ``The Lost Children of Rockdale County'' under past
offerings.)
</P>
<P>
   Some are teens who had been set adrift by divorce; parents so
distracted by their own dramas, careers or naivete that they either
didn't care what their child was doing, or had no clue.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these children were given every financial advantage _
mansion-style houses, BMWs to drive to school, lots of cash _ and
the freedom to indulge. Other teens who were involved came from
loving homes, whose parents gave them plenty of time and attention
when they were young, then stepped back to allow some independence
during the teen years.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: A group of schoolmates gathered weekly in an
upstairs bedroom not to finish a science project, but to watch _
and reenact _ the Playboy channel.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent of two young children, I watched the show with the
same anxiety most parents did. Is Rockdale any different than any
other upscale American suburb?
</P>
<P>
   How can we inoculate our own children against going too far,
experiencing too much at far too young an age, without clamping
down so hard that they rebel or never learn to think for
themselves?
</P>
<P>
   Then I read an article in The Family Therapy Networker's
November/December issue, ``Discovering our Children,'' that I
believe captures what's going on with our sons and daughters and
provides some answers for how we can reverse the course.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Taffel, director of the family and couples treatment program
at the Institute for Contemporary Psychotherapy in New York and the
author of the book ``Parenting by Heart,'' believes that today's
children lack emotional literacy, a passion for something other
than the pop culture, and the ability to delay immediate
gratification.
</P>
<P>
   This adds up to aggressive, glibly sophisticated children unable
to control their moods, act respectfully or talk about what really
matters _ their feelings, dreams, wishes and frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   The first problem, Taffel proposes, is a moral ambiguity that
has swept over modern families. Seeing more and more children at
younger and younger ages explode with defiance and talk and act
with increasing disrespect has led him to believe that parents are
not giving clear signals as to what is acceptable behavior and what
is not _ and carrying through with consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Too many wishy-washy answers, compounded by contradictory advice
and threats without substance have resulted in children who see
parents not as leaders in the family, but ineffectual guides
incapable of providing moral direction.
</P>
<P>
   This allows a child's second family _ the kiddie culture of
peers and the media _ to become more important and more persuasive
than parents, siblings and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again in his conversations with school children,
Taffel heard the refrain, ``We don't spend much time together _
we're always so busy in my house.'' He has concluded that,
``stretched to the limits as we are, we do not really know the
children we have ... we just do not spend enough direct, one-on-one
time with them.''
</P>
<P>
   True, research indicates that parents today spend the same, if
not more, time with their children than ``June and Ward Cleaver
did,'' he says. ``Yet, family members may be spending time near
each other, in the same house, (but) engaged in parallel but
separate activities, and not remotely doing things together.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, mom might check her e-mail while listening to the
5-year-old take a bath, and dad might conduct business on his cell
phone while riding in the car with his son to school. Prime
opportunities for one-on-one attention and conversation lost by the
modern habit of multitasking every minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overwhelmingly, what the kids want most, is (their parents')
undivided attention,'' says Taffel.
</P>
<P>
   To go bowling, to lie down together for a bed-time story, to sit
at the kitchen table together during breakfast and tell silly
jokes, to do a jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature abhors a vacuum, and for American children, the great,
roaring hurricane of the mass media culture _ particularly the
culture of celebrity _ rushes in to fill the psychic void that
family used to fill,'' Taffel says.
</P>
<P>
   This blind admiration for celebrities even extends to a desire
to become celebrities themselves _ and there are many ways to
achieve this, as evidenced by the Littleton shootings. ``Violence
becomes the perfect antidote to ... anonymity,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   What can we do? Taffel says parents should strengthen certain
core attributes in their children to raise sons and daughters with
a strong sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   These include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mood mastery _ Model specific ways to soothe intense emotional
states, such as anger and fear, that fit their child's temperament.
</P>
<P>
   _ Respect _ Be clear about expectations and follow through with
reasonable consequences.
</P>
<P>
   _ Passion _ Encourage love of learning and teach how to deal
with disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Peer smarts _ Help a child recognize a true friend, and teach
negotiation styles for maintaining a friendship.
</P>
<P>
   _ Body comfort _ Help a child value and accept the way he or she
looks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gratitude _ Instill a healthy appreciation for the good things
in life. And, most of all, pay attention. Really look at, and
listen to, your children. As 11-year-old Amanda told Taffel when he
visited her classroom, ``If the adults don't know what's going on,
it all turns into chaos. The adults need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
