<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0618 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV02-     11-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVING THE COOL FROM CIGARETTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Dec. 2)  
(js) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because it's cool, is what kids say when you ask them why they
smoke cigarettes. Cool, they say, a word older than their
grandfathers, even their great grandfathers, but an image that
spans the generations to indicate a certain attitude and style _
assured, loose, above it all.
</P>
<P>
   So, you have 14-year-olds or younger _ for this is when more
than half of all smokers begin _ in pursuit of coolness and
believing the way to it is to stick a paper wad of lit tobacco in
their mouths. You just wish they could get the same cool factor
from baggy jeans or acing a science quiz.
</P>
<P>
   If coolness is everything, then it follows that the only way to
get kids to not smoke is to make smoking not cool. And how do we do
that?
</P>
<P>
   Cool is separate from healthy and wise. It's a look. You see the
way kids bend over a cigarette, the way they let it dangle from
their fingers. They're like little actors, posing as sophisticates.
So how do we make that look unappealing, something not at all worth
imitating?
</P>
<P>
   The other strategies, well-intended and based on fact, don't
work against coolness. Cancer statistics, secondhand smoke dangers,
the specter of yellow teeth and stinky clothes work on adults but
not on kids.
</P>
<P>
   And that includes California kids, who more than kids in most
parts of the country, and certainly the world, live in smoke-free
environments where smoking is not only antisocial but against the
law, except in private homes or outside far away from any air duct
or another's breathing space. A lot of adults finally quit smoking
when they find themselves outside at the party feeling like a
desperate loner trying to get a match to light in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Kids don't seem to mind the inconvenience. It's part of being a
kid smoker to sneak a smoke where adults can't see you. If you have
to hang out in an alley in the rain to light up, that's kind of,
you know, cool. Even more so to take your chewing tobacco to
school, stuff some in your mouth before class and carry a Diet Coke
can to spit into.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Kerfoot is a nurse and prevention specialist for high
school tobacco programs in Sonoma County, Calif. She works with
kids who've been busted for smoking on campus or who are trying to
quit, and some of the older kids do penance by talking to
fourth-and fifth-grade classes about smoking.
</P>
<P>
   When they ask the younger kids, 9- and 10-year-olds, why they'd
want to smoke, they hear back that ``it's cool.'' The older kids
then explain that by the time you're in high school it's not cool
anymore, but you've got the craving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even kids in middle school want to look cool,'' Denise says.
``And they want to look older and they want to fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't everyone who ever smoked know that one? We smoked
because we were at a party and feeling awkward, or when we got to
college and someone showed us how to light a cigarette by holding
the hand of a man with a match and staring into his eyes. We were
all little actors, too, and it was our passport into grownup-land.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a sign of getting into middle school.
</P>
<P>
   People whose jobs are to get people to stop smoking and who
proudly show a drop in adult users are at a loss to explain why
kids are smoking more than they did 10 years ago. They blame it on
magazine advertising that seduces kids with messages of
independence, and, of course, looking cool and fashionably thin.
</P>
<P>
   Or they say it's the way of kids, to indulge in what's bad for
them and believe they're invincible. But these kids have grown up
with antismoking messages. Guest speakers connected to oxygen tanks
come to their school and lecture. They've watched their own parents
struggle to get through a bad day without tumbling back to their
habit.
</P>
<P>
   When a state report showed that the three-county region of
Sonoma-Marin-Napa has the highest percentage of teen smokers in the
state, health professionals could only come up with a weak
suggestion that kids in this largely middle-class population can
better afford the high price of cigarettes than kids in poorer
parts of the state. Most said they don't have a clue.
</P>
<P>
   There are no more mysteries about tobacco itself. It has been
proven to be a major health risk, a public menace and an insidious
drug. In the movie ``The Insider,'' the whistle-blowing tobacco
researcher calls cigarettes a nicotine-delivery device, designed to
hook people. Meanwhile, high school kids go into middle schools and
tell kids that 1,300 Americans die a day because of tobacco, more
than the number dying in car accidents, plane crashes, house fires,
murders, AIDS and suicide combined. And to please, please not do
what they did. That's cool.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
