<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0619 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TA     11-24 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIMELESS MOMENT GROUNDED IN IMPERMANENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 28)  
 (af)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``This,'' said William Carden, the director, ``is
theatrical tough love.'' The audience in the cavernous Majestic
Theater roared its approval.
</P>
<P>
   He was standing on the nearly bare stage, backed only by the
black drops that help to create the atmosphere of subterranean
melodrama in ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' the theater's current
tenant.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sunday night two weeks ago. We were there to see
something a good deal less rococo than ``Phantom'' and, as it
turned out, more historic: a staged reading of ``Who's Afraid of
Virginia Woolf?,'' Edward Albee's epic consideration of one
American marriage, in which Uta Hagen would recreate the role in
which she triumphed when ``Virginia Woolf'' first arrived on
Broadway 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Carden's ``tough love'' was a reference not only to the ferocity
of the play and the minimal production values given the staged
reading (a table, four chairs, the outlines of a doorway), but also
to Ms. Hagen. The night was designed to be a tribute to the actress
on her 80th birthday, and to benefit the HB Playwrights Foundation
and Theater, which she heads. Yet all the work was being done by
Ms. Hagen and her colleagues in the cast: Jonathan Pryce, Mia
Farrow and Matthew Broderick.
</P>
<P>
   ``She honors us,'' Carden went on, anticipating what he
described as ``this leap in time.'' True enough, but nothing anyone
might have said in advance could have been adequate preparation for
the performance that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Most actors loathe staged readings. They don't have time to
learn the text, so they must juggle their scripts, reading their
lines while also being required to make entrances and exits and to
perform a lot of the basic stage business. Actors feel all thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   A staged reading is even tougher than a plain, unadorned sight
reading, done without rehearsal, when the lines need not be acted
as much as heard while someone reads the stage directions, a de
facto storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as directed by Carden, who is also the artistic director of
the HB Theater, this ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' had a
seamless dramatic intensity that suggested virtually a new way of
making theater.
</P>
<P>
   After witnessing three hours of desperate marital combat, the
members of the audience emerged from the Majestic aware that they
had just experienced something available nowhere but in this great
ailing tradition we call the theater. It wasn't conventional
theater, but it's as good as theater gets.
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, time is inflexible and cruel, a wearing out of
resources, a diminishment of powers. But when time bends, as the
title of Arthur Miller's memoir suggests, it can, among other
things, accommodate, deepen and make possible the sort of one-of-
a-kind performances of which theatrical legends are made.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hagen's great, bawdy one-night stand with the role of Martha
now becomes one of those legends, her physical and psychological
presence possibly even enriched by everything that has happened
since the first time she played the role.
</P>
<P>
   Such legends are unique to theater. They are an impossibility in
any of the performing arts that have been frozen in time on film or
tape. Movies have enormous power but, being representations of
something already completed, they are fixed and quite dead. Only
memory keeps the living theater alive, recalling the particular
circumstances in which time wasn't stopped but, instead, its
passage celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   It is only in an acute awareness of the finite, during a
performance you know will never be exactly duplicated, that you
glimpse the meaning of the infinite. That was the effect of this
revivifying production.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hagen was, in fact, too young _ 43 _ when she first played
Martha, a college professor's voracious, disappointed wife who is
supposed to be 52. She now says she is too old, and you might
agree, but only if you had not seen this performance. You didn't
hear her as she brayed with the indignation of a fastidious
fishwife: ``I do (italics)not(end italics) bray!'' You didn't see
her as she charged out of the room to attend to poor drunk Honey,
passed out on the bathroom floor clutching a brandy bottle. Loud or
soft, the voice is rich and strong, the body lithe and the brain as
strong and quick as a bear trap. At moments of doomy
self-awareness, she reminded us of Groucho Marx when he said he
wouldn't join any country club that would let him in.
</P>
<P>
   Though the company rehearsed together only a week, there seemed
an easy balance in the casting. Pryce was sneakily strong as
George, Martha's husband, a history professor whose wimpishness is
only one of the various guises he assumes to make their marriage
work.
</P>
<P>
   George and Martha were equals here. During the long night of
boozy game-playing and failed infidelities, George remained laid
back. He collected his injustices quietly, hoarding them, letting
his outrage accumulate so that the final explosion, when it came,
was devastating.
</P>
<P>
   The roles of Nick and Honey usually seem more important as
functions of the plot than as characters in their own right. They
are the new, young and very ambitious biology professor and his
mousy wife, whom Martha and George welcome into the faculty family
with a late-night party they'll never forget.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as performed by Broderick and Ms. Farrow, Nick and Honey
took on dimensions I have never seen before. He was alternately
bewildered and opportunistic. She was sweet, dangerously stupid and
sly. She was also very, very funny.
</P>
<P>
   Though I have long admired her performances in Woody Allen's
films, especially in ``Broadway Danny Rose,'' ``Radio Days'' and
``The Purple Rose of Cairo,'' I had no inkling that she could take
hold of the stage in this manner. And as there was no consciousness
of the age difference between Ms. Hagen and Pryce, there was none
between Ms. Farrow and Broderick.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The HB Playwrights Foundation and Theater, which was served by
this remarkable evening, includes an 80-seat theater where the
productions of the HB Playwrights Foundation are presented. It is
physically attached to but is an entity separate from the HB
Studio.
</P>
<P>
   The studio, founded by Herbert Berghof in 1945, some years
before he and Ms. Hagen were married, is the acting school where
Ms. Hagen still teaches and Berghof taught until his death in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The theater was his special project, however, as I found out in
1985 when I worked with him on the production of a play I had
written. Berghof, who had a horror of the commercial theater, made
sure that the HB Theater became the kind of sanctuary where people
can make plays unmolested by philistines. Critics are not invited.
Risks can be taken without fear of failure. Admission is free
(donations are accepted). Patrons come from the neighborhood, the
city, California and, sometimes, abroad.
</P>
<P>
   At first I felt Berghof was curious about me as an eccentric
movie critic who had written a play, but then I realized he had
more or less the same contempt for the movie business as he did for
the commercial theater. He delighted in recalling how the Elizabeth
Taylor ``Cleopatra'' had financed the HB Theater. Its cost was
covered by the overtime he received for playing the role of
Theodotos in the picture, whose shooting delays kept him in Rome
for the better part of a year, instead of a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Berghof planned all of his productions well in advance. There
was a feeling of roominess _ of space _ about his methods. He was
civilized. When we worked together, the schedule included almost a
year of meetings once or twice a month before we went into
rehearsals. Sometimes we would discuss the play, sometimes the
history and state of the theater in general, sometimes life. After
several months it came as a shock to realize that he knew the
script word for word, far better than I did.
</P>
<P>
   Our talks weren't idle chat. He was getting my measure and
putting his own ideas in order. An extraordinary actor, director
and man of the theater. Not long after his death, I also had the
opportunity to work with Ms. Hagen, again before I began covering
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Like hundreds of other people in this country, I feel as if I
had studied with Herbert and Uta, but without ever realizing it was
work. It was always life. The work grows out of that. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not quite in the same league with the performance of ``Who's
Afraid of Virginia Woolf?,'' but a complete entertainment
nevertheless, was Gerald Gutierrez's recent staged reading (staged
singing?) of ``Sail Away'' with Elaine Stritch, a fine Broadway
cast and a full orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 1961 Noel Coward musical in which Ms. Stritch, the
show's original star who is now 74, reprised her role of a
wisecracking cruise director for 10 performances at the Weill
Recital Hall in Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sail Away'' is scarcely comparable to Albee's seminal drama.
It would be difficult to imagine anyone seriously wanting to revive
it today. It would cost a fortune, what with all of the singers and
dancers, sets, costumes, lights, fancy sound amplification system
and other technical marvels required.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sail Away'' is not a memorable show. Coward's score has some
of his wittiest satirical numbers, including ``Useful Phrases,'' a
sendup of the contents of one of those ``How to Get Along in
Italy'' books, and ``Why Do the Wrong People Travel?'' (which
speaks for itself), but the other numbers are mostly reminders of
earlier, better Coward songs.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the exemplary revivals of musical comedies produced in
concert form by Encores at City Center, there was no dancing in
``Sail Away,'' no costumes except for Ms. Stritch's sailor hat.
There were few entrances or exits. The performers sat on the stage
and came forward only when they were doing a scene.
</P>
<P>
   The excellent supporting cast was headed by Marian Seldes, Jane
White, Jerry Lanning, Jane Connell and Gordon Connell. Ms. Seldes
was especially welcome as an outrageously self-dramatizing writer
of best-selling novels in which loins grow hot and breasts heave.
</P>
<P>
   The production pared away much of the hokum of the original
show, allowing us to savor Coward's multiple moods and charms
without demanding that they justify the expense of a full staging.
More important, it returned Ms. Stritch to the world of musical
comedy, where she is revered as an icon comparable to Ethel Merman.
Her voice and quickness of mind can still pierce and enchant. The
fizz is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Her Tony-winning performance in the 1996 revival of Albee's
``Delicate Balance,'' also directed by Gutierrez, is much
appreciated. Yet there are those who believe that a Stritch who has
no chance to belt, to sashay and to let go with a juicy
double-entendre is hiding something large and fabulous under a
bushel.
</P>
<P>
   That qualifies as criminal negligence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1837EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
