<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0621 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHYA-BOS &LR;      11-24 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN CHOICE TO LEAD CHECHNYA HAS CRIMINAL PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's leaders believe they have found the man to
help them put an end to years of lawlessness in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But first, they had to spring him from jail.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin says the Islamic militants it is fighting in
Chechnya are ``terrorists'' and ``bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Moscow needed a Chechen leader to help win public
support among civilians for Russia's latest campaign in the region,
it turned to Beslan Gantamirov, who was serving a six-year sentence
for embezzling federal funds earmarked for rebuilding the
war-devastated region.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian troops, tanks, and warplanes bombarding their way
through Chechnya, Moscow has ruled out negotiations with the
separatists' elected leader, President Aslan Maskhadov. Instead,
Russia is trying to set up a pro-Moscow administration in Chechnya
and to squeeze out Maskhadov, who the Kremlin says has lost control
of Islamic commanders.
</P>
<P>
   To replace him, the Kremlin wants Gantamirov, who goes by the
nickname ``The Demon.'' Last week, he was appointed head of the
pro-Moscow Chechen State Council.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's choice underscores just how difficult it is for
Russia to find influential allies in its campaign in Chechnya,
which has few fans among Chechens because of the indiscriminate
bombardment that rebel leaders say has killed 4,000 civilians and
sent at least 200,000 more fleeing from the region.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Gantamirov was convicted on charges that he embezzled
more than $6 million while a member of the Chechen government
during Russia's occupation of the city in 1995 and 1996. The money
had been earmarked for rebuilding the city, which was nearly
flattened during the 1994-1996 war between Moscow and Chechen
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov was set free last month thanks to a rare pardon by
President Boris N. Yeltsin, as Russia sought to create a new
pro-Moscow regime in areas of Chechnya its troops have occupied.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Demon was more useful to us outside jail than inside,''
said one government analyst, explaining the pardon. ``Gantamirov
sees Chechnya as a part of the Russian Federation and will fight on
our side. Today that is the most important thing. . . The Demon is
no day at the beach, but he's our man.''
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov, 36, left Moscow for the Caucasus Tuesday, saying he
would raise and command a loyalist militia that would help fight
the separatists. Some Russian press reports said he could raise a
force of some 2,000 men.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to fight, and we don't know who of us will be
coming back,'' Gantamirov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The release from prison of Beslan Gantamirov and the formation
of some new Chechen authority under his leadership demonstrate
quite clearly that the Russian Government has no rational plan of
action for Chechnya,'' said Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of the
centrist Yabloko opposition party in the Duma, or parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers say Gantamirov will not make Moscow's campaign to
win the hearts and minds of Chechens any easier. His first tour of
a refugee camp near the Chechen frontier appeared to stir little
enthusiam among Chechens there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent a bandit to find other bandits. They will reach a
deal and divide the money sent from Moscow, like they did during
the last war,'' the Associated Press quoted a 34-year-old Grozny
resident as saying. ``As long as Russia keeps sending criminals to
lead us, we will remain criminals ourselves, since we will have to
live in a criminal state.''
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov's mission comes amid signs that Russia's military
campaign against Islamic militants in Chechnya may be bogging down.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders have claimed a series of military successes,
including the capture of Chechnya's second-largest city, Gudermes.
Russia's defense minister, Igor Sergeyev, said Tuesday that federal
troops had Grozny 80 per cent surrounded. He said its residents
would soon force rebels to leave the city, which has been under
heavy bombardment since late September.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Chechen military official Wednesday denied
Sergeyev's claims, saying that the approaches to the city from the
south and east remained open. Mumadi Saydayev, the military
commander of the breakaway republic, also brushed aside Russian
reports that Chechen fighters were leaving the capital en masse and
taking refuge in the southern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``All are in their positions,'' he was quoted as saying by the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces have suffered heavy casualties but have moved
quickly across the northern plains to the outskirts of Grozny. Some
analysts say the military has been exaggerating its successes to
retain public support for the war among Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``All talk about how people are tired of the bandits' arbitrary
rule and meet our paratroopers with open arms is a bluff,'' said
Andrei Rykhlin, who writes for the news magazine Itogi.
``Surrendering towns without battle is a part of Maskhadov's
strategy, and town elders who enter talks with military are trying
to gain one goal _ to save the lives of civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov was originally an ally of Dzhokhar Dudayev, the
Chechen president who declared independence from Russia in 1991 and
led the uprising until his death in a Russian rocket attack in
April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1994, an internal struggle put Gantemirov and Dudayev on
opposite sides. Gantemirov became a key leader in a failed
Kremlin-backed attempt to overthrow Dudayev in November, 1994, and
later joined the puppet government Moscow installed when its troops
took the city in February 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in May 1996, three months before the separatists retook
Grozny and the loyalist government fled, Gantamirov was arrested in
Moscow. He spent three years in prison awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov never denied he misspent the money, but said he was
paying for weapons for his fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course that is true, but he did not forget about himself,''
the weekly Obshaya Gazeta quoted a Gantamirov supporter as saying
last week. ``How could it be otherwise?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
