<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEECH RECOGNITION SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is speech recognition software another alternative to the
mouse? How powerful a computer do you need to run one of these
programs?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, a good speech recognition program can take a load off
your mouse if you are willing to work with the software. Although
the most advanced programs on the market today won't let you
interact as effortlessly with your machine as characters on
science-fiction shows do, the technology has become a lot more
accurate and reliable in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   These natural language programs (so called because they allow
you to speak in normal conversational patterns instead of pausing
between each word, as with the older programs) will let you control
your computer and its applications through vocal commands.
</P>
<P>
   You can also dictate text that you would normally type, and some
programs will let you speak up to 140 to 160 words per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Specific system requirements depend on the program that you
choose, but most require your PC to have a 16-bit sound card
installed. Your computer will probably need a minimum of 48
megabytes of RAM installed to run the latest versions of popular
speech recognition programs, and you will probably need 200 to 300
megabytes of free hard drive space.
</P>
<P>
   A fast processor, at least 200 megahertz, is also essential for
smooth performance of the software. Two popular programs in this
category are Dragon NaturallySpeaking by Dragon Systems
(www.dragonsystems.com) and Via Voice, from IBM
(www.ibm.com/software/speech).
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are developing Macintosh versions of the programs
as well for release in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
