<HEADER>
A0627 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-BOSCOLL-WILLETTS-     11-24 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSCOLL-WILLETTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLETS ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE BC-VA. TECH SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been a Thanksgiving tradition at the Willetts household
in Alexandria, Va. There was turkey and stuffin' on Thursday,
followed on Friday by a four-hour car ride south to Blacksburg to
watch Virginia Tech knock the stuffin' out of the University of
Virginia, the Hokies' archrival.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way Thanksgiving was always went for Mike Willetts.
His parents, Randy and Susan, were Virginia Tech graduates and they
delighted in taking their eldest of two sons back to their alma
mater to watch the Hokies. Deep down, they dreamed one day of
making the same trip to watch their son play for Virginia Tech and
chant:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoki, Hoki, Hoki Hy!
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech! Tech! VPI!
</P>
<P>
   ``Sola-Rex Sola-Rah
</P>
<P>
   ``Polytech-Vir-gin-ia!
</P>
<P>
   ``Rae, Ri, VPI!''
</P>
<P>
   Friday Willetts will take part in his family tradition of turkey
and football. About 15 members of his family and 50 more high
school friends from West Potomac High will reunite to watch
Willetts play at Lane Stadium/Worsham Field.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be one important twist.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of suiting up for the Hokies, Willetts will don a Boston
College jersey (No. 98) when the No. 20 Eagles (8-2 overall, 4-2
Big East) arrive for a Big East showdown against the second-ranked
Hokies (10-0, 6-0). It is a game that will have national
championship ramifications for Virginia Tech, which will be playing
for a slot in the Bowl Championship Series title game against
top-ranked Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much grew up around Virginia Tech football,'' said
Willetts. ``I would watch it, but they were never really any good.
I remember I would always go down for the UVa-Virginia Tech game,
which was usually played the day after Thanksgiving, but somehow
they always seemed to struggle. It's funny, but once I got to
college it seems that's when Virginia Tech really became good.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he had been exposed to Virginia Tech football all his
life, Willetts never really was excited about the prospect of
continuing the family legacy. Willetts had been recruited by
Tennessee and Florida, as well as the in-state schools, after he
wound up his senior season at West Potomac as Virginia's Defensive
Player of the Year. Practically everyone in his high school went to
Tech, but Willetts refused to follow the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to set myself apart from other people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he followed a path that eventually landed him in Chestnut
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from Virginia, the city was different and I had a great
time coming here to visit,'' Willetts said. ``It was something new
and it was what I was looking for. Plus, at the time, we had just
beaten Notre Dame twice in a row and the D-Line was leading the
nation in sacks. So all those things played a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Willetts said his parents never really attempted to steer him to
Virginia Tech, except for one notable exception when his father
took a detour to Blacksburg on the way back from a recruiting visit
to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the drive back from Tennessee, I was sleeping, and my dad
was driving through Virginia Tech and trying to show me around the
campus and stuff,'' Willetts said with a chuckle. ``But I'd been
there before when I was in high school to go down to visit buddies.
So, I kind of gave my dad a little attitude, I was like, `Dad, I'm
sleeping! I don't want to see the campus.' After that, my parents
were really good about it. The second I came here, they were no
longer Virginia Tech fans.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Willetts clan isn't likely to be torn when Mike lines up
with BC and attempts to knock the Hokies out of the national
championship race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's a great player and he makes plays when he needs to make
plays,'' said senior defensive tackle Chris Hovan. ``When he gets
single-blocked, I know that Mike is going to make that tackle. I
know Mike is going to make that sack. I have total trust in Mike.
He's a great player and he's got the instincts to make the big
plays when he needs to.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4-inch, 281-pound senior defensive tackle is BC's
sixth-leading tackler with 58 stops, including 36 solo and four
sacks for 20 yards in losses.In last week's 31-29 victory at Notre
Dame, Willetts did his part by making six tackles (including one
sack), breaking up a pass, and blocking one very huge extra-point
attempt by Jim Sanson that enabled BC to preserve a 3-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   He would like nothing more than to have an impact on the outcome
of the game against the Hokies, who shifted their traditional game
against Virginia to Oct. 2 in order to accommodate BC in the season
finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if we'd go to a bowl game or not, but I thought
we'd have a good shot at it,'' Willetts said. ``The way I looked at
it, I was like, `Man that could be my last game, you know?' It's
definitely going to be a nice way to end up _ a win over Virginia
Tech, with a 9-2 record, and a bowl game _ in front of everyone
whose close to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
