<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0638 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-DISNEYQUEST-RE     11-24 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DISNEYQUEST-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OK, MOM, HERE'S THE REAL DEAL 
(ACCOMPANIES BC-TRAVEL-DISNEYQUEST-TEX)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Editor's note: Michael Robinson, 15, and Katy Robinson, 13,
graciously agreed to visit DisneyQuest with their mother, reporter
Gaile Robinson. Here are their reviews.) ---
</P>
<P>
   By Katy Robinson &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The best thing at DisneyQuest? Designing my very own roller
coaster.
</P>
<P>
   The coasters can only be a certain length, and you pick the
speed _ slow, fast and, my choice, Hang On For Your Life. Then you
get to pick the setting of your coaster, in space, on a volcano, or
on an ice planet.
</P>
<P>
   Next you design it on a computer; you have tons of loops, barrel
rolls, twists and hills to pick from. When you're finished, your
coaster appears on the screen and gets tested for its scariness: If
five out of five people won't ride your coaster, then it's great,
but if everyone will ride it, then that's a pretty lame coaster.
Next, you choose words from two lists to come up with a wacky name.
Mine was the Astro Riot.
</P>
<P>
   Then you get to ride it. You get into a cylinder that has two
chairs with a bar that goes over your head, so it seems like you
are really on a roller coaster. You start moving along with the
ride; you go upside down, twist, turn or whatever you put in.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I thought riding the ride wasn't as much fun as
designing it. I didn't feel as if I were on a real roller coaster;
it wasn't as bumpy or as scary. I still think this ride was a very
good idea and I enjoyed every second of it.
</P>
<P>
   Other stuff I liked:
</P>
<P>
   Buzz Lightyear's Astro Blaster: Now, this isn't some kiddie
ride. This is just like bumper cars, except there are asteroids
flying at you. If one of them hits a spot on your car, your car
goes spinning in a tight circle. You need two people to play this:
one to drive and one to fire the asteroids.
</P>
<P>
   Midway on the Moon: This section is filled with fun arcade games
like Basketball, Skee-Ball, Whack-an-Alien (similar to
Whack-a-Mole), and old games like Tron and Ms Pac Man.
</P>
<P>
   Sid's Create-A-Toy: Sid was the character from the movie ``Toy
Story'' who messed with the toys and tried to make new designs. In
this game, you look around Sid's room for bodies, heads, arms and
legs to create your very own toy. After you are done, you can even
buy the toy you just created.
</P>
<P>
   Animation Academy: Here you learn how to draw Disney characters.
The lesson takes about half an hour, and after you are finished you
get your picture and your diploma. You do draw on a computer, so it
is a little harder to do than on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Overall rating: When you're 13, you don't recommend anything.
But I'd go back. ---
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Robinson &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The best virtual reality game was ``Invasion! An Alien
Encounter.'' This game is for four people _ three gunners and one
driver. You start out on this world in a spider walker, trying to
save colonists who are being threatened by aliens. You have about
three and a half minutes to save 27 colonists; the driver must
execute jumps over lava rivers or move platform to platform.
</P>
<P>
   You will never save all the colonists; there is just not enough
time. Plus, the walker goes extremely slow, and the aliens move
fast. If you have good gunners, you may save most of the colonists.
But if you are playing with your mother, like I was, then you're
lucky if you get 15.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this game, you have to enter a transporter before
the world explodes. Then your percentage of kills or the number of
colonists you saved pops up on the screen, and you're given a
ranking. Overall, I give it five out of five stars.
</P>
<P>
   Other stuff I liked, and some I didn't:
</P>
<P>
   Ride the Comix: This is a virtual reality game where you and six
other people fight with these ``swords of light'' and defeat comic
monsters such as a mutant dog or a sewer gang on hover-bikes. I
hated the sword. You couldn't hit any of the enemies because you
couldn't swing far enough to hit them unless they got so close you
could feel their breath, even though you can't feel their breath.
One out of five stars.
</P>
<P>
   Cheesecake Factory: The restaurant actually had good food, such
as pizza and hot sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Jungle Cruise: The setting is a prehistoric river. You
sit in a raft on an air bed and you get cheap paddles with rollers
on the ends. It was hard to steer the raft throughout the ride, and
your arms immediately got tired. There were squirts of water to add
to the effect, but all that did was make little spots on your
shirt. Two out of five stars.
</P>
<P>
   Hercules in the Underworld: Amusing and incredibly easy to play.
All you have to do is collect the lightning bolts scattered about
the game. This is played in a cramped closet where you stand in a
corner in front of your character's joystick. The story wasn't very
appealing to me, but then, it was designed for those who saw the
movie, and I didn't. Two out of five stars.
</P>
<P>
   Overall rating: If I could afford to go back I would, a couple
of times. But the plane trip and other transportation from Texas
was expensive.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
