<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0641 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     11-24 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SICKLE CELL TAKES ANOTHER VICTIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if she never said as much, you knew Kelley Lewis hated this
dance with death, even as you knew she hoped that sickle cell
disease would someday be curable.
</P>
<P>
   Not in time for her, perhaps, but for the thousands of others
who know the disease's debilitating pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not in my life,'' she told me in September during
National Sickle Cell Disease Awareness Month. ``But it'll happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's how it is when you've spent your life in and out of
the hospital, struggling to get through another crisis, feeling
each time as if you've been run over by a truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only way I know how to describe it,'' Lewis said.
``One day I'm feeling OK, and the next I may be in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   That might sound depressing to most of us, but Lewis discussed
her plight as if she were on her way to a vacation spot in the
Caribbean, not the sterile environs of a hospital ward.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, hope isn't enough. Kelley Lewis died Oct. 29. She
was 30 years old.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure for sickle cell disease, an inherited chronic
anemia in which oxygen-deprived blood cells become sickle-shaped.
</P>
<P>
   The syndrome varies considerably in severity and often results
in extreme fatigue and widespread, life-threatening organ damage.
Some people live long and nearly normal lives; others, like Lewis,
are plagued by strokes and painful crises.
</P>
<P>
   One in 12 people in Tarrant and Denton counties carries the
sickle cell trait, according to Pearl Jones, executive director of
the Sickle Cell Disease Association of America/Greater Fort Worth.
And contrary to popular belief, the disease is not limited to
African-Americans such as Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   But many contend that funding for research would be more
generous if the disease did not primarily affect blacks and a small
percentage of people of Mediterranean, East Indian and Middle
Eastern descent.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kelley Lewis believed. Her mother, Sandra, still
does. She wants us to help, to begin to donate to sickle cell
research so that no one else has to endure the pain her daughter
did, so that no one else has to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to try,'' she said recently.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time after Kelley and I talked that day in September,
I thought about her. One moment she was telling me she was sure
she'd die before a cure came, and the next she talked about her
hope for other sickle cell sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   A good friend of hers told me that that's how Kelley Lewis was.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was more worried about everybody else than herself,''
Caryn Perry said. ``This last time she went in the hospital, I told
her I was coming to see her and she said no, to take care of my
kids, I didn't need to be worrying about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry's memory is filled with such stories about her friend.
There was the time they went to a thrift shop and Kelley bought
clothes for Perry's youngest daughter; and the time she gave Perry
$20 for a pregnancy test even though her illness prevented her from
holding a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just a wonderful, wonderful human being,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis' body grew tired. She spent Oct. 11, her 30th
birthday, at home, surrounded by friends and relatives. The next 17
days were spent in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Then, finally, her dance with death was over.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
