<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOYS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS     11-24 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POKEMAN CRAZE EXPECTED TO LEAD REBOUND IN HOLIDAY TOY SALES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Adriana Reyneri and her two young sons, Jake and
Luke, were exploring FAO Schwartz in Manhattan on Wednesday when
they stopped in front of a display for ``Toy Story 2,'' the sequel
to the 1995 animated movie.
</P>
<P>
   The toys tied to the movie are expected to be big sellers this
holiday season, but Ms. Reyneri of Northbrook, Ill., gave them a
thumbs down. ``This is the Pokemon Christmas for us,'' she said
resolutely as her boys nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out, Furby. Get a life, Beanie Babies. Pokemon now rules.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to another hit movie, Pokemon items are
disappearing from the shelves faster than you can say, ``I choose
you, Pikachu.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as one in five of the toys, games and books given to
children this holiday season _ which the industry counts on for its
profits _ will be based on Pokemon, said Chris Byrne, the editor of
The Toy Report, a weekly newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Susan McLaughlin, a spokeswoman for Toys `R' Us, said, ``Kids
can't seem to get enough of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But they may not get exactly what they want. Some of the most
popular Pokemon items, like trading cards and Pikachu dolls that
also say their name, are in short supply in some places. ``We're
making them as quickly as we can,'' said Wayne S. Charness, a
spokesman for Hasbro, the company that is expected to clean up on
Pokemon this year, along with its Tiger Electronics and Wizards of
the Coast subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by last year's disappointing season and ever optimistic
when it comes to projections, the Toy Manufacturers of America
expects sales of toys and video games to jump 6 percent this year,
to a record $28 billion. Sales were virtually flat last year, after
early predictions of 4 percent gains, in part because behemoth Toys
`R' Us lost its footing, and action figures and dolls did poorly.
</P>
<P>
   This year, merchants and toy makers seem to be counting on
growth fed by a widespread selection of technologically advanced
merchandise, appealing because, at least in theory, it stands a
better chance of holding a child's interest beyond Christmas
morning.
</P>
<P>
   These items are intended for jaded children like Jared Carr, 6,
of Chicago, who has not been smitten by Pokemon, a craze that
evolved from a Japanese cartoon series. ``It's really popular, but
they don't do anything,'' said Jared, who had his eye on a
radio-controlled toy bulldozer.
</P>
<P>
   The big sellers are expected to include some familiar names in
new incarnations. Among them will be Rock and Roll Elmo and Rock
and Roll Ernie ($30), well known ``Sesame Street'' characters
licensed by Fisher-Price, part of Mattel Corp.. Then there is
Flight Control Buzz Lightyear ($40) and Strumming' Singing' Woody
($25) from ``Toy Story 2,'' all made by Mattel. The popularity of
televised wrestling has also spawned a collection of figures that
would make Jesse Ventura proud.
</P>
<P>
   Not every television and movie tie-in is a sure thing, though.
Star Wars toys, introduced by Hasbro earlier this year to accompany
``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' have been
disappointing. ``Toys are really a fashion business,'' said Michael
L. Glazer, the chief executive of KayBee Toys, the chain of 1,400
stores owned by Consolidated Stores Corp. ``The life cycle is
really short.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro, which makes the Star Wars items, has smartly diversified
in recent years so it is not dependent on the big tie-in. Furby and
Pokemon products should more than make up for the Star Wars
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft effectively admitted defeat in the toy business
earlier this year by discontinuing its $60 line of Actimate
Teletubbies, which proved to be high priced for toddlers, who do
not necessarily need such indulgences. ``If they don't talk, they
can't ask for it,'' said Sean McGowan, an analyst at Gerard Klauer
Mattison. ``A 1-year-old will take whatever you give him.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Among the more promising offerings are Furby Babies ($30), which
were spawned by last year's Furby craze and have ``20 percent more
vocabulary and 200 percent more interactivity'' than their
progenitors, said Charness of Hasbro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The babies speak more words, and they're cuter,'' said
Margaret Morgan, 12, of Memphis. Better still, there is no sign of
shortage. ``Furby,'' said McGowan, ``is going to do five times the
volume of last year because it's available.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A Yoda toy, inspired by Furby, was supposed to reach stores for
the holidays but will not appear until next year because of
production delays stemming from the Taiwan earthquake, Charness
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Beanie Babies appear to have run their course and are being
discontinued after this year, which could, of course, lead to a
spike in holiday sales, and which could be just a prelude to
another line extension, a la Furby Babies.
</P>
<P>
   After losing ground in recent years, Barbie is making a comeback
_ a turnaround that Jim Silver, one of the publishers of Toy
Wishes, a new consumer buying guide, said is directly linked to the
waning popularity of Beanie Babies, even though the two items do
not share the same store aisles.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A miscalculation by Mattel led to a glut of Holiday Barbies in
past years and turned off consumers, especially collectors who
expect prices of their limited editions to rise. Millennium Barbie
($30), dressed in a blue velvet gown with silver trim, was the
second best-selling toy in the country in October after Furby,
according to the NPD Group, a company that compiles sales figures
for the Toy Manufacturers of America. The sales are especially
important to Mattel, which is reeling from a series of missteps,
including a disappointing acquisition of the Learning Company and
inventory management problems last year.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing Ally, big sister to last year's Amazing Amy, is another
heavily promoted doll, this one from Playmates. Ally, whose mouth
moves when she is talking, tells stories and jokes and can remember
birthdays. But her ``friendship'' costs $60. ``It's for the
grandparent who wants to buy a granddaughter a toy that is really
elaborate,'' said Jill Bilzi, the editor of Playthings, an industry
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Those girls' brothers may be asking for wrestling figures with
infrared sensors that can recognize and taunt one another (WCW Tuff
Talkin' Wrestlers at $40 by Toy Biz) or others (WWF Titan Tron Live
Series at $32 by Jakks Pacific) that can recite dialogue downloaded
from the Internet. For kids (or parents) who prefer more polite
conversation, Mattel makes Chat Pals ($40), based on characters
from ``Winnie-the-Pooh.'' Other popular toys are likely to include
Toy Biz's Kindergarten Babies ($20), aromatic descendants of the
Cabbage Patch dolls who would rather be sniffed than heard.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As no parent needs to be told, with 5,000 new toys produced each
year, demand is usually fueled by advertising dollars. FamilyFun
magazine tested 66 toys by giving several hundred children across
the country three weeks to play with them. Only a handful of the
toys preferred by the children have been named as hot prospects by
people in the toy industry.
</P>
<P>
   In video games, however, no such test was needed to determine
that the cutting-edge Sega Dreamcast (especially with the Sega
Sports NFL 2 game) is everyone's favorite. Despite the $200 price
tag, the consoles are hard to find. ``We sold out the first day,''
said Ms. McLaughlin of Toys `R' Us.
</P>
<P>
   Given the price, some shrewd parents are advising their children
to wait until next year, when the next generation of the popular
Sony Playstation comes out, said Silver of Toy Wishes. ``They're
telling them it's going to be better,'' he said of Playstation 2.
</P>
<P>
   Spending Saturday afternoon at a toy store may not be every
parent's idea of a good time, but buying over the Internet is
expected to account for just 1 percent of total toy and game sales
this year, according to several stock analysts who specialize in
e-commerce. ``A lot of people are just not going to entrust their
kids' holiday gifts to the Net,'' said Seema Williams, an analyst
with Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. And many shoppers still
have security concerns, Ms. Williams said, about providing credit
card numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, reports of service, inventory and delivery problems
with the online toy sites could scare last-minute shoppers away.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has been a source of frustration for Toys `R' Us as
it tries to recover from poor performance last year at its stores
and the surge in sales and publicity that went to its new online
rival, Etoys.com. Earlier this month, after Toys `R' Us distributed
62 million catalogs praising its online capability, its Web site
was overwhelmed. A company spokeswoman, Leeann Lavin, acknowledged
that the company experienced a ``site slowdown due to the volume of
visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lavin said toyrus.com had responded by increasing its
Internet capacity and extending its holiday discount through the
end of November. The promotion enabled Toys `R' Us to pull ahead of
Etoy.com in number of visitors for the week ended Nov. 14 (the most
recent week for which figures are available), according to Media
Metrix, an Internet measurement company that uses a panel of people
to gauge traffic.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Small as it is, Internet sales are expected to account for much
of the future growth in the toy industry. Ms. Williams predicted
that Internet toy sales would rise to $3.7 billion by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   While adults may want to see a product before buying it,
children's selections can be as simple as a click. ``Kids know
exactly what they want,'' said Christopher E. Vroom, a toy stocks
analyst at Thomas Weisel Partners, in San Francisco. ``They're a
very focused customer group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
