<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE COURAGE TO LEARN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The education of young girls was supposed to have ceased when
the Taliban took power in Afghanistan a few years ago. It was
outlawed. The stifling cloak of ignorance was to have been thrown
like a burqa over the country's females.
</P>
<P>
   But quietly, and with very little in the way of resources, brave
groups of Afghan women have been conducting underground classes for
girls in private homes and other secret locations.
</P>
<P>
   I've been in touch with women who are running at least 30 home
schools in Herat, Kabul and Jalalabad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot say that we are scared,'' said one. ``Not for
ourselves. But, of course, there is the fear the program may be
stopped. We have that fear every day that we go to work. So we
don't want to make a huge noise about it. The community is behind
us, protecting us. They know what we are doing. We operate quietly
and all day long we keep the classes going.''
</P>
<P>
   The teachers get a small salary and are specially trained for
their delicate mission. Most had at least five years of classroom
experience before the Taliban banned schooling for girls. The
number of grades that are taught varies with each operation, but
the schools seldom go beyond the sixth grade. Books and other
supplies are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   A home school typically gets started as follows: A female
teacher, now barred from working, decides she wants to somehow
continue teaching. She discusses this with members of her extended
family, usually over tea. If the family supports the effort, then
neighbors begin to be included. Word spreads. Pupils who are
considered ``safe,'' who can be trusted not to reveal the existence
of the school to those who might betray it, are recruited. A home
in which classes can be conducted is selected.
</P>
<P>
   These efforts, initially uncoordinated, are now getting a small
measure of professional support from organizations committed to
relieving the misery imposed by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   A leader of one of those organizations told me she had mixed
feelings about talking to the press. She asked that neither her
name nor the name of her group be mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need publicity, but at the same time we have to be very
careful,'' she said. ``Right now there are so many people coming to
us, so many people who want schools to open that it's overwhelming.
But it is impossible for us to respond to them because we don't
have enough funding. We are teaching about 1,000 girls now but the
funding is so limited we cannot provide them with even the books
that they need. We tell the teachers to try to teach in a way that
doesn't depend so much on books.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing breaks my heart. These kids are like any
other kids. We had one little girl, she was 12, who said, `I love
this school!' Her father had died and she was very lonely and a
school was started right next door to her. These kids want to learn
like any other kids want to learn. They are desperate, so we have
to help them. And we need help in order to do that. But at the same
time I'm afraid for the life of my personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the teachers were reminded repeatedly to draw as little
attention to themselves as possible. ``They go according to Islamic
rule and Islamic law. We accept it. We encourage them to remain
covered. We are not defiant.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the schools, while clearly a form of resistance, had
not been created with that in mind. ``When we give the policies and
procedures to our teachers, we say, `OK, what is our objective
here?' And the answer is to educate our children, to keep the door
of education open.''
</P>
<P>
   I first learned of the home schools from Ruth Messinger, the
president of American Jewish World Service, an organization in New
York that is providing some of the funding for the 30 schools in
Herat, Kabul and Jalalabad. The Global Fund for Children is also
providing funding. The money is routed, for technical and security
reasons, through a human rights group in Dearborn, Mich., called
Creating Hope International.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Messinger said of the women and girls in Afghanistan: ``This
is a community that is facing oppression and violence beyond our
imagination, and they have nevertheless taken their future into
their own hands. We are very proud to stand with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
