<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0666 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-VIGIL-HNS &LR;      11-24 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-VIGIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS EXPECTED TO ATTEND VIGIL AT TEXAS A&AMP;M 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims, optional ending) 
 
By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid growing concerns about lax safety standards in the
construction of the Aggie Bonfire, tens of thousands of Texas A&AMP;M
students and alumni will gather on campus Thursday night for a
``remembrance'' of the 12 who died in last week's collapse of the
massive log pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have said 50,000, some have said twice that,''
said A&AMP;M spokesman Jonathan Kraatz, referring to the potential size
of the crowd. ``We don't really know.''
</P>
<P>
   The university has about 43,000 students, but graduates and
others are expected to swell attendance at the unstructured vigil
near Kyle Field.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M is about 90 miles northwest of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The vigil will begin at sundown on the field where the Bonfire
would have been ignited in a ritual dating back nearly a century.
There is no planned program, no scheduled speakers and no time
limit for the vigil.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can stay as long as they want to stay,'' Kraatz said.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 p.m. CST, however, a ``yell practice'' will begin at Kyle
Field, walking distance from the Bonfire site, and most of the
crowd is expected to attend that, Kraatz said. In the past, the
``yell practice'' has begun at midnight, following the Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   After the collapse of the woodpile last Thursday morning, the
Bonfire was canceled for only the second time since 1909, the first
being after the assassination of President Kennedy in 1963. But,
criticism of the event following the fatal tragedy has threatened
to cancel it for good.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the university administration began laying the
groundwork for an investigation into the collapse of the log
structure. A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen was expected to announce by
week's end the names of those appointed to a commission to study
what caused the accident.
</P>
<P>
   And the Texas Board of Professional Engineers disclosed plans to
determine if the Texas Engineering Practices Act applies to the
Aggie Bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires state and local governments to file plans with
the engineering board and provide for a licensed professional
engineer to oversee construction of building projects that could
affect public safety or welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law does not mention anything about a pile of logs that
are going to be burned,'' said Jimmy Smith, interim director of the
engineering board. ``There is no precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, the Aggie Bonfire was just a pile of logs and
other trash wood. In the 1940s and 1950s, it became much more
sophisticated _ a multitiered structure of bundled logs stacked on
end to a height of 55 feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some engineering professors raised questions
about the safety of the pile and a construction handbook was
developed.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Larry Grosse, a former A&AMP;M construction science
professor and Bonfire adviser for 13 years, said he believes the
structure collapsed because safety and design features spelled out
in that handbook were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Among the safety measures he helped develop: interlocking the
tiers of logs, driving some of the bottom level logs into the
ground, and lashing the first two levels with steel cables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, there was not someone overseeing all of this to make
sure it was being done,'' Grosse, now a professor at Colorado State
University in Fort Collins, told WFAA-TV in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that the tiers were simply placed one on top of
another and the logs were held together by wire.
</P>
<P>
   Grosse said the handbook also specified that only students with
two years experience in building the Bonfire would be allowed above
the first level. That condition also was not enforced this year.
Some freshmen have told reporters that they were working as high as
the fourth tier.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Thompson, an administrator who has been Bonfire adviser
for two years, acknowledged that all of the handbook procedures had
not been followed, but he told reporters he was comfortable with
the safety measures that were enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson could not be reached for comment Wednesday, but earlier
he was quoted by The Associated Press as saying: ``I don't think
the fact that there were freshmen or sophomores on the stack was
the reason it fell. Something went wrong somewhere within that
stack.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the final plans for the memorial vigil were being made, about
120 passengers of a charter flight to California, where one of the
victims was being buried, returned to Texas after a lengthy delay
caused by mysterious damage to their airplane.
</P>
<P>
   After the plane landed in Stockton and the Aggie delegation, led
by Bowen, had departed for nearby Turlock, maintenance crews found
a hole in the wing flap of the chartered Boeing 737. The cause of
the damage was not immediately determined, but lightning was a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The plane had been scheduled to return Tuesday evening to
College Station, but it wasn't until Wednesday afternoon that a
replacement jet was found, according to an airport official in
Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, three students remained hospitalized Wednesday, while
another was released.
</P>
<P>
   John Comstock of Richardson and Dominic Braus of Hallettsville
were still in critical and fair condition, respectively, at College
Station Medical Center. William Davis of Bellaire was listed in
fair condition at St. Joseph's Regional Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   Milton ``Chip'' Thiel of Livingston was released from St.
Joseph's on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
