</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLOWELL-CONNECTING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING THANKFUL FOR IMPOSSIBLE FAMILIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PERRI KLASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ On a Saturday morning here, there is only one
possible place to be, at least for parents with children under 10.
Dr. Edward M. Hallowell is at a soccer game. His son Jack, 7, is
playing for the Maroon team; his wife, Sue Hallowell, is team
manager. Because this is Cambridge, ground zero for self-conscious
parenting, every soccer team has been taught to chant, ``One, two,
three, four _ We don't care about the score!''
</P>
<P>
   Hallowell, 49, a child and adult psychiatrist, is the author of
``Connect,'' a book that argues the necessity of human
connectedness in the interest of health and happiness. So how does
he square connecting and competing? Even 8-and-under soccer, he
would argue, is more than little boys in shorts and shin guards
running themselves breathless on a bright fall morning; it, too, is
a form of connection.
</P>
<P>
   As the game starts, the woman who coaches the Maroon team
admonishes the adults, ``Parents _ we don't scream orders! We just
say good things!'' When Jack gets subbed in, and his mother and
father (``we don't care about the score'' momentarily set aside) go
on instant parent alert, leaning forward when he has the ball,
following him with their body language: ``Go on! Get it! Shoot,
Shoot, Shoot!''
</P>
<P>
   When talking to the avatar of family connection amid the falling
leaves of a Massachusetts autumn, when hearing about the vital
importance of establishing, re-establishing, deepening and
maintaining ties with immediate and extended family, a person
cannot but think: Oh-oh. Thanksgiving!
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, Thanksgiving is the zinger of family
connectedness,'' he admitted. ``There always is conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to his theories, there is still hope. That's
because it is better to fight over which tablecloth to use and who
last spoke to cousin Robin, than not to gather around the table at
all. Yes, he believes there is connectedness even in conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, the extended family is there for the connecting.
``Instead of holding your nose and getting through it, which is
what most of us do,'' said Hallowell, ``try saying, `Maybe I'll
plant a few seeds this Thanksgiving.' And maybe by next
Thanksgiving, you won't have to hold your nose that hard.''
</P>
<P>
   No. He does not mean planting a few seeds of envy, about the new
car you are getting, or spite, about your sister-in-law losing her
job. He means facing each other and hashing out the problems that
stand between you.
</P>
<P>
   Hallowell will say things like ``It's better to connect than to
make $1 million dollars.'' But don't we all know that? Isn't it the
Hollywood cliche (think Bedford Falls at Christmas), the greeting
card truth we all subscribe to and then ignore?
</P>
<P>
   Exactly, Hallowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Hallowell, a senior lecturer at the Harvard Medical School and
an expert on attention deficit disorder, has turned his focus on
the squishy area of feelings and found that feeling good is good
for you.
</P>
<P>
   Most people are unaware of the body of scientific data he cites.
``Social isolation is as much a risk factor for dying as cigarette
smoking,'' he said. ``This is not a `Well, people have a lot of
feelings left over from the '60s, hearts and flowers thing.'' In
other words, there's a reason to go to Thanksgiving dinner besides
the gravy and pumpkin pie.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Hallowell combines the data on social isolation and
family connection with a large body of practical, homey advice. He
is not unlike the family nag _ or sage _ you ignored for years,
until you realized she had been right all along.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that his advice is hard to follow. Common sense
or not, this is no quick route to feeling good about yourself. What
it often comes down to on Thanksgiving is dealing with what
Hallowell calls one's family of origin. Make sure you see everyone
in your family of origin at least once a year, he writes. Speak to
everyone at least once a month, make up with family members from
whom you are estranged, don't take no for an answer, discuss how
they feel about the family.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but what about the alcoholics and the nasties and the just
plain crazies? What about those people who are genuinely difficult?
Do people have to connect to them?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what every family is like!'' he said. ``The norm for
families is rage, conflict, irresolvable difficulty. Instead of
just trying to avoid explosions and survive, which is what most of
us do, try to go deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it will mean a big fight and more conflict,'' he said.
``Maybe it will get messy and dirty. It's just that simple and just
that hard. Everybody has a reason why their situation is
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   He's on a roll now. ``Life is impossible. Families are
impossible.'' He paused dramatically. ``But it isn't. If you're
willing to shed some blood and swallow some pride, you can get to a
better place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallowell's common-sense advice is grounded in real family life,
both his own and his patients'. The message is not delivered as a
sermon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not be the first to identify the missing ingredient in
many lives,'' said Publisher's Weekly, ``but he can claim authority
of a splendid articulation.'' That authority often comes from
self-exposure.
</P>
<P>
   In order to write his books, Hallowell goes into sometimes
harrowing detail about himself and his family. His father was
manic-depressive, his mother married an alcoholic and abusive
stepfather, whom he called Uncle Noble.
</P>
<P>
   How abusive?
</P>
<P>
   In the chapter ``Speaking Personally,'' he writes, ``Things
happened back then that shouldn't have.'' He describes his father
taking him downstairs in the middle of the night in the family home
in Charleston, S.C., to see his mother, lying naked on the bed,
surrounded by three of his father's friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never seen my mother naked, so that in itself was a
shock.'' Even more upsetting was what they were doing: shooting
craps against his mother's bare backside. ``Uncle Noble asked me if
I wanted to play,'' he writes. He was not yet 10.
</P>
<P>
   He says in ``Connect'' that he had always felt that if people
knew his story they would think less of him, and that he felt
tainted. He writes about all this to show the human connections
that saved him, the teachers at boarding school who recognized him
and helped him through. After fifth grade, those boarding schools
``became my home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he made his peace with Charleston. ``I went back to
the city where I had learned how to hate,'' he writes. His mother
and stepfather are both dead, as is his real father. But he went
back to the big brick house he remembered as a font of sadness and
worry in his childhood, and he made his peace with that. ``It is a
mistake to disconnect yourself from who you were and where you've
been,'' he writes. ``It's better to reconcile.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Arlington, in a large sunny house on a hill, the
Hallowell family is connecting through chaos in a kitchen filled
with soccer trophies, children's art supplies, school schedules.
Jack and the other Hallowell son, Tucker, 4, are eating lunch,
along with their 10-year-old sister, Lucy. Lucy is named for her
distinguished foremother, Lucretia Mott, a heroine in the battle
for women's suffrage and Hallowell's direct ancestor. One child is
doing acrobatics on a kitchen chair while eating a bowl of Ramen
noodle soup; the daughter clearly feels she knows much more than
her parents. Their keeshond dog, Pippi, is running around the
kitchen, hoping for spilled food.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hallowell and his wife seem unguarded about letting a
visitor see the squabbling and the bumps of family life. ``This is
who we are,'' he said. ``We don't feel we have to be the Partridge
family. I can't be a perfect parent.'' He and his wife seem, in
fact, most delighted when their children fail to toe the party
line: ``Oh, Dad, not this again!''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hallowell is probably best known for ``Driven to Distraction,''
the 1995 book he wrote with Dr. John J. Ratey about attention
deficit disorder. It is the kind of book that changes people's
thinking. People read it and say, this explains my child, this
explains my whole life.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem a leap from attention deficit to the subject of
connectedness, but Hallowell does not think so. He reached a point
where he saw the world becoming distracting for everyone. ``I was
seeing all this worry, the combination of this speeded-up,
electronically superconnected age, and the way we're
interpersonally disconnected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one is more speeded up and electronically superconnected than
Hallowell. In his travels and lecture tours, he has visited every
state except Alaska. His wife, Sue, 43, a social worker with a
part-time practice in Cambridge, said that because of his travels
``it's important for me to be at home more.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows there is an obvious question coming. ``I write a book
about `connect,' how connected am I at home?'' He makes an obvious
effort to be as connected as possible, and when he's on the road,
he stays in touch through e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Note: his book cites a Carnegie-Mellon study that found
correlations between depression and loneliness and the amount of
time people spent on the computer. Yet he is a ferocious e-mailer.
He seems to make a habit of e-mailing people to tell them to e-mail
other people _ an electronic daisy chain of connections. The
paradox of the modern age, he says, is that the same technology
that speeds life up and smothers us in information makes it
possible to respond to each other through e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   He relies on his wife to remind him of things like potluck
dinners. They both try to make sure that family life doesn't get
lost in the shuffle. That's because, he said, ``what we did this
morning, both parents going to a game, never happened for me in my
childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Lucy, interrupted. ``Enough with the sad stuff,
Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's the sad stuff that ends up motivating me,'' her
father answered.
</P>
<P>
   The Hallowells assembled for a photograph; all five members of
the family piled onto a couch plus Pippi. Five pairs of sneakers,
large and small, were kicked off on the floor. There was no
possible way to keep everyone on the couch and not poking one
another and not blocking one another and not making a stupid face.
It is a happy chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are the issues of the prophet in his own home,
where connection is Daddy's hobbyhorse, and Lucy pronounces,
``Connect, connect, connect,'' with the I've-heard-all-this-before
intonation of a bored 10-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having kids keeps me humble, teaches me I don't have the
answers, teaches me how surprising life can be,'' Hallowell said.
``Jack once observed, `I don't know why anyone would want to hear
you talk,''' his father recounts proudly.
</P>
<P>
   People have asked him, he goes on, somewhat ruefully, ``Ned,
when are you going to run out of personal problems you can write
books about?''
</P>
<P>
   But that misses the point: ``I'm trying to normalize having
problems,'' he said. ``Life is problems, life is conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy Thanksgiving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
