<HEADER>
A0671 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-HITLER'S-NIECE-T     11-24 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HITLER'S-NIECE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WOMAN HITLER LOVED _ NO, NOT EVA BRAUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hitler's Niece''
</P>
<P>
   by Ron Hansen
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $25
</P>
<P>
   Before Eva Braun there was Angelika Raubal, known affectionately
as Geli by Adolf Hitler and members of his family and inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   In his splendid historical novel, ``Hitler's Niece,''
distinguished novelist Ron Hansen makes a compelling case that Geli
was the great love of the Fuhrer's life, although he married Eva
just before ending her life and his as the curtain descended on the
Third Reich ``Gotterdammerung'' in a Berlin bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Although Eva Braun was to Hitler the ``girl at my disposal in
Munchen'' for 14 years, Hansen, in an afterword to his compelling
story, quotes Hitler as having told his secretary a few months
before the end: ``Eva is very nice, but only Geli could have
inspired in me genuine passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Geli died Sept. 18, 1931, of a gunshot wound. Her death was
officially ruled a suicide. But rumors have abounded that the
Fuhrer either killed her or had it done. Through the years, many
books and magazine articles have speculated about Hitler's
relationship with a woman 19 years younger than he was, and about
the tragic end of the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Although the preponderance of that speculation weighs in against
Hitler's version, the issue is now moot. But Hansen does not allow
that inconclusiveness to stand in the way of a good story.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of spinning a fascinating yarn out of a historical
footnote, Hansen casts the Fuhrer and his cronies in an almost
comedic light. They are still monsters. But they are flawed,
pathetic characters, who have to be taken seriously only because of
the enormity of their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   A short dialogue captures the glaring irony in the way those
megalomaniacal mediocrities saw themselves, and the way they really
were.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she got in, he (Heinrich Hoffman) said, `I've just heard
a good one. What is an Aryan's Nordic ideal?'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Tell me.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `To be thin like Goring, tall like Goebbels, and blond like
Hitler.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The story is set against the background of jarring political
upheaval in Germany between the end of World War I and Hitler's
climb to the threshold of dictatorial power. That greater story
elevates to a higher significance the smaller drama of Hitler's
relationship with the daughter of his half-sister.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps the worst-kept secret in Germany. She shares an
apartment with him in Munich. She and her mother live with him and
keep house for him in Obersaltzburg in Bavaria. He spends lavishly
on Geli's clothes and education, and she accompanies her uncle to
many social events, where his possessiveness is much in evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A young man spends too much time dancing and conversing with
Geli on one of those occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clenching his jaw, Hitler held the large twenty-two-year-old
in his scalding eyes until Schirach's fortitude, his friendliness,
the flush in his feminine cheeks were all gone,'' Hansen writes. ``
`She is with me,' Hitler said, and she followed him as he went to
where Rudolf Hess was holding the coats.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret that no one knows, except some of his closest inner
circle, is that Hitler is impotent. His sexual encounters with
women, including Geli, are bizarre and unnatural.
</P>
<P>
   Geli's disgust with Hitler's sexual perverseness and his
smothering domination ultimately leads to her death at age 23.
</P>
<P>
   Although the reader suspects early on how the strange
relationship between Hitler and his beautiful niece will end, that
predictability does not ruin the climax, which is handled
masterfully.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sex in the novel is graphic, it is not
pornographic. To his great credit, Hansen resists the temptation to
produce an exploitative piece of sexual titillation. Instead, he
has delivered a jewel of fact-based fiction that explores important
moral and political issues, and teases the reader into thinking:
``Yes, it could have happened that way.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
