<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-NUKES (Washington) _ A small group of U.S. and Russian
military officers won't be doing much cork-popping on New Year's
Eve as the new millennium nears at midnight. Instead, they will be
guarding against the end of the world. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHING-HOSPITALS (Washington) _ Teaching hospitals, which are
struggling to cover the cost of training the nation's young
doctors, intend to lobby Congress to force managed care providers,
private insurers and large employers to pick up more of the tab. By
JUDY HOLLAND and DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   UNDERINSURE-HEALTH (Washington) _ Apart from the 44 million
Americans with no health insurance, there are an estimated 31
million who are underinsured. These are people with insurance who
nevertheless risk spending 10 percent or more of their own annual
income if a major illness strikes. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-WHISTLE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court will hear
arguments Monday in a case that could make or break a nurse's
whistle-blower lawsuit against St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital in
Houston. Joyce Riley, a nurse in the heart-transplant unit, alleges
that the hospital conspired to defraud the Medicare program by
unnecessarily admitting patients and needless upgrading the level
of services. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIEQUES (Washington) _ President Clinton says the
Pentagon and Puerto Rico are ``making real headway'' toward a
compromise to reopen a Navy target range on the island of Vieques.
Defense officials say an emerging compromise calls for surface
warships accompanying the aircraft carrier USS Dwight D. Eisenhower
to the Persian Gulf on Feb. 18 to fire non-explosive rounds on the
island target range in December while combat aircraft rehearse
bombing on ranges in Florida. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE-VIGIL (College Station, Texas) _ Tens of thousands of
Texas A&AMP;M Aggies are expected to turn out Thursday night at the
bonfire site for a candlelight memorial to the 12 people who were
killed when a tower of logs collapsed earlier this month. By JIM
HENDERSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GIANT-MARTINI (San Francisco) _ Towering above crowds at a New
Year's Eve interfaith worship service in Union Square will be a
giant martini, complete with a 10-foot olive that will drop at the
stroke of midnight. But some religious leaders are shaken by the
prospect of the symbol being used at an event that will ring in the
new year with piety and reflection. By RYAN KIM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-A&AMP;M-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ It has been a sudden and
stunning transformation. Texas and Texas A&AMP;M, two of the college
football programs best known for their running-oriented offenses,
have both had record-setting passing seasons in 1999. With
sophomore Major Applewhite leading the high-powered Longhorns and
senior Randy McCown directing the Aggies, the annual A&AMP;M-Texas game
promises to be a real shootout this weekend. By JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS (Irving, Texas) _ Advance on the Dallas Cowboys'
Thanksgiving Day matchup against Jimmy Johnson and the Miami
Dolphins. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The campaign finance reform issue is
working for Sen. John McCain. But with former Sen. Bill Bradley,
it's not working. Why not? By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ It's clear now, particularly in
the wake of George W. Bush's recent speech on foreign policy, that
the next president of the United States will be a free-trader and
an internationalist. Bush and his main rivals _ Vice President Al
Gore, former Sen. Bill Bradley and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. _ all
agree on that viewpoint. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
