<SLUG> BC-WORKING-TUNA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   WORKING COOK: Tuna and Pasta Combine in One Big Smile  
   
   
   
 By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  There are some nights of the week when the
refrigerator shelves are bare, but going grocery shopping requires
way too much effort. The reality of it hits you with a dull thud _
dinner is coming straight out of a can.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luckily, others have grappled with this dilemma as well. As many
a harried Italian mother knows, a wonderful tasting and
protein-rich pasta sauce can be made from canned tuna and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   This is the idea behind Fusilli with Tuna, Capers and Chickpeas,
the 30-Minute Main Dish, and truly dinner out of a can. Make that
three cans and a jar of capers, a box of pasta and an onion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, using the best ingredients makes this dish even
better. Regular water-packed tuna works fine, but olive oil-packed
tuna is even better. The boxed Pomi brand chopped tomatoes, which
contain neither salt nor preservatives, have a fresher flavor than
most canned varieties.
</P>
<P>
   This week's Fast&AMP;Fresh entree derives from a Vietnamese dish of
grilled pork with rice noodles. Thin slices of tender pork are
grilled and then layered, hot, on a bed of light-as-a-feather
noodles, under which hide rings of cucumber and other raw
vegetables. Garnish it with a tangy dipping sauce and peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of sweet and salty, warm and cold, and crunchy
and soft makes the noodles one of my favorite dishes. This recipe
has similar components but is constructed more like a salad, with
all of the ingredients tossed together.
</P>
<P>
   For a homey Sunday dinner, try the Now&AMP;Later recipe, Chicken and
Rice Pilaf Casserole. It is actually easy enough for a weeknight
dinner _ all it takes is browning the chicken and sauteing bell
peppers and onions. Then add the rice to saute with the vegetables,
and bake all the ingredients together. Fresh lemon zest and juice
make a bright note.
</P>
<P>
   The quantity of liquid makes this dish more like a comforting
stew, and more suitable for freezing extra portions. Be sure to let
it rest for about 10 minutes before serving so the rice fully
softens and absorbs more of the juices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; RICE STICK NOODLES WITH GRILLED PORK &AMP; LIME VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to heat up a grill, use a grill pan or quickly
stir-fry the pork in a hot wok or a large nonstick skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup lime juice (the juice of about 3 limes)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup rice vinegar + 1 tablespoon for the cucumber
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup peanut or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pork tenderloin, cut into thin rounds
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces rice stick noodles (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber, sliced into half moons
</P>
<P>
   6 green onions, trimmed and sliced on the bias
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup roasted and lightly salted peanuts, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat a grill before beginning preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Put a large pot of water on to boil for the noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the lime juice, 1/4 cup vinegar and the fish sauce.
Add the sugar and salt; stir until dissolved. Whisk in the oils.
Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Season the pork pieces liberally with salt and pepper. Cook the
pork on the grill until just cooked through, about 1 to 2 minutes
per side. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the noodles according to package directions. Drain and
rinse briefly to cool, then drain well, shaking the colander
vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the sliced cucumber with 1 tablespoon rice vinegar. Combine
the cucumber, pork, noodles and most of the green onions and
chopped peanuts in a large bowl; toss to combine. Add the
vinaigrette and toss again.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with the remaining green onions and peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; If rice stick noodles are unavailable, substitute glass
noodles or angel hair pasta.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 713 calories, &LR;   &LR; 34 g protein, 83 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 27 g fat (5 g saturated), 74 mg cholesterol, 1,224
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
30-MINUTE &QL; 
MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FUSILLI WITH TUNA, CAPERS &AMP; CHICKPEAS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fusilli pasta
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) can high-quality tuna (preferabled packed in olive
oil), drained
</P>
<P>
   1 (7-ounce) can chickpeas, drained and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1 (15-ounce) can chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers, drained and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Put a large pot of salted water on to boil for the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large skillet. Add the red pepper flakes
and saute briefly over medium heat. Add the onion and saute until
translucent, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, begin cooking the pasta according to package
directions.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tuna to the onion in the skillet, smashing it into small
pieces with a wooden spoon. Add the chickpeas and tomatoes. Season
with salt and pepper and cook, stirring occasionally, for 10 to 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the pasta is done, drain it and return it to the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Add the capers to the sauce in the skillet and taste for
seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the sauce over the pasta and stir together briefly over low
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 670 calories, &LR;   &LR; 32 g protein, 105 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 13 g fat (2 g saturated), 14 mg cholesterol, 373 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 5 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOW &AMP; LATER &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN &AMP; RICE PILAF CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 chickens (31/2-4 pounds each), each cut into 10 pieces
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 to 4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons minced lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 onions, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 red bell peppers, deribbed and diced
</P>
<P>
   41/2 cups basmati or other long-grain white rice
</P>
<P>
   3 quarts chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Season the chicken pieces with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large skillet. When hot, add enough of the oil to cover
the bottom of the pan. Heat the oil to almost smoking. Add the
chicken pieces in batches and brown over medium-high heat until
golden, about 5 minutes per side, adding more oil as needed. As the
chicken browns, transfer the finished pieces to 2 large baking
pans. Drizzle liberally with lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, carefully drain some of the oil from the skillet,
leaving about 1 or 2 tablespoons in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Reheat the oil, and add the lemon zest, oregano and onions,
scraping up browned bits from the bottom of the pan. Saute the
onions for 5 minutes, then add the bell peppers and saute until
softened, about 5 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Add the rice and cook, stirring, until all of the grains are
coated with oil, about 1 minute. Stir in the broth and water and
bring to a boil. (If using unsalted broth, season with salt to
taste at this point or the cooked rice will be bland.)
</P>
<P>
   Pour the broth and rice mixture evenly over the chicken. Cover
tightly and bake until the chicken is cooked through and the rice
is tender, 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and let rest, still covered, at least 10
minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 650 calories, &LR;   &LR; 43 g protein, 62 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 24 g fat (6 g saturated), 135 mg cholesterol, 134 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
