<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0690 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BESTWAY-PIE-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTWAY-PIE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 BEST WAY: Thanksgiving Pie Crust   By Lynne Bennett  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _    Baking a pie crust is like playing golf: You
can't think about it too much or it will drive you crazy. Just
relax and do it without overanalyzing _ the results are usually
better, ideally a crust that is tender, crisp and flaky.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chronicle Food department tested piecrusts to determine
which type of fat, liquid and mixing method made the best crust. We
chose a basic piecrust recipe from the ``Fannie Farmer Baking
Book'' that made ample dough for a single, 9-inch crust. The
crusts, made with all-purpose flour, were either blind-baked (baked
without any filling) at 425 degrees for 25-30 minutes or made with
a pumpkin pie filling.
</P>
<P>
   Our first task was to select the type of fat that was best for
flavor and texture. We blind-baked crusts made with all shortening,
all butter, all lard, and half butter-half shortening. The winner:
the 50-50 combination of Crisco vegetable shortening and unsalted
butter. The lard crust was by far the flakiest and most tender,
although it was rich; it took second place. The butter crust had
the best flavor but was not as flaky.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure we would like the crust as much in a pie as we did by
itself, we baked the 50-50 crust and the lard crust with pumpkin
pie fillings. While both pies were yummy, the 50-50 crust was best
again.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we tried various methods of blending the dough _ with a
hand-held pastry blender, in a food processor and with our
fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   The crust made with a pastry blender was acceptable but the food
processor crust _ we were careful not to overprocess it _ was more
tender. It also took the least amount of ice water _ 3 tablespoons
_ to get the dough to come together. But the crust made with the
fingertips to blend the fat into the flour was the best. It needed
a little over 31/2 tablespoons of ice water. This version was the
most tender and was extremely flaky.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we determined the best fat and mixing method, we tried
replacing part of the ice water with vinegar to see if that
ingredient made the crust more tender. If it did, it wasn't
noticeable. We couldn't discern a substantial difference.
</P>
<P>
   Our final try at improving the crust was to rest it for 45-60
minutes in the refrigerator before rolling it out. Again, the extra
time and effort did not make a noticeable difference. But resting
the dough (it lets the gluten in the dough relax) may be more
important if you are using a food processor, which mixes the dough
vigorously. Letting the piecrust rest in the refrigerator for 2
hours after it is rolled out and fitted in the pan is supposed to
minimize shrinkage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE BEST WAY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
We found the best piecrust is one that is made with half shortening
and half unsalted butter and mixed with your fingertips. Handle it
lightly and keep it cold so the fats don't melt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A PLEASING ALTERNATIVE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
If your hands tend to be hot or you aren't comfortable about making
pie dough with the snap of your fingers, try a food processor or
hand-held pastry blender. Both produce good results. Process the
dough minimally, and be sure to use ice water as the liquid to help
keep the dough cool.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we learned one more thing about making piecrusts. It
improves with practice, unlike many people's golf game.
</P>
<P>
   (Lynne Bennett is a student at the California Culinary Academy.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST WAY PIECRUST RECIPE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the ``Fannie Farmer Baking Book,'' by Marion
Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup (4 tablespoons) unsalted butter, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   3-4 tablespoons ice water
</P>
<P>
   additional flour for rolling
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Mix the flour and salt together in a bowl, add the shortening
and butter, and work it into the flour with your fingertips or a
pastry blender until the mixture resembles fresh bread crumbs.
Sprinkle on the water, 1 tablespoon at a time, stirring
(``fluffing'') lightly with a fork after each addition. Use enough
water so the dough holds together.
</P>
<P>
   Form the dough into a ball and flatten the top to form a disk.
If you use a food processor, wrap the dough completely in plastic
wrap and allow it to rest in the refrigerator for 45 minutes to 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out the dough on a lightly floured surface or between 2
sheets of wax paper until it is about 1/8-inch thick and 2 inches
larger than your inverted pie pan.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the dough to the pan, then trim the edges to even them
out. Roll the cut edge under and crimp edges.
</P>
<P>
   If your filling recipe calls for a prebaked shell, use a piece
of aluminum foil, shiny side toward the dough and fill the shell
with dried beans or rice. Place in a preheated 425 oven for 15
minutes then remove foil and beans. Return piecrust to the oven to
more evenly brown the bottom of the crust. Continue baking and
rotating in the oven until golden, about 10-15 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Yields one 9-inch pie shell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER RECIPE: &LR;   &LR; 1,490 calories, &LR;   &LR; 19 g protein, 131 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 99 g fat (42 g saturated), 124 mg cholesterol, &LR; 
 &LR; 1,076 mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
