<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0691 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-LEFTOVERS-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 1992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEFTOVERS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: This story is not only for a holiday, but also
for  its aftermath. It's followed by recipes for using the
leftover 
 bird.   For the Holidays: Turkey Survival Guide 
 &HT;       
 By Sean Forsha and Lynne Bennett  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  The honorable Thanksgiving turkey. It's been
selected and purchased. It's been stuffed, seasoned and roasted.
It's been carved and enjoyed. And now the leftovers remain _
refrigerated zip-close plastic bags bulging with white and dark
meat that will most likely end up on sandwiches or eaten by
snacking fingers.
<P>
   For the culinary die-hards, the ones who remain willing to cook
following the Thanksgiving task, we have provided six recipes that
will turn those leftovers into exciting meals.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey proves its versatility. In one dish it's tossed in a
bright pasta with currants and butternut squash; in another it's
stir-fried Cantonese-style with onions and green beans. A curried
turkey salad teamed with radish sprouts makes for a new take on the
day-after sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   We have kept in mind that simplicity is the key to post-holiday
cooking so these offerings feature ingredients that will be readily
available and substitutions can be made easily.
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Forsha and Lynne Bennett are students at the California
Culinary Academy.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TURKEY, CORN &AMP; ROASTED PEPPER ENCHILADAS WITH CHIPOTLE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Chipotle Sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dried Mexican oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 (28-ounce) can diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 chipotle in adobo, seeded
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon adobo sauce from can of chipotles
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   The Filling
</P>
<P>
   3 red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 onion, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced roasted turkey
</P>
<P>
   1 can (83/4 ounces) corn
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Assembly
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   12 corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   Black or green olive slices for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The chipotle sauce:  &LR; Pour the oil into a medium pot and place
over medium-high heat. When the oil is hot, add the onion and saute
until translucent, about 3 minutes. Add the garlic and saute for 2
minutes. Add the cumin, oregano, tomatoes, chipotle, adobo sauce
and water. Bring to a simmer, reduce heat to low and simmer for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Puree the sauce in a blender (work in small batches) and return
to the pot. Add the sugar and season with salt and pepper. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The filling:  &LR; Preheat the broiler. Roast the bell peppers under
the broiler until the skins blister and blacken, about 5 minutes,
turning often. Place the roasted peppers in a paper bag; fold over
the top to seal and set aside for 15 minutes. Peel, seed and dice
the peppers and place in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce oven temperature to 375.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a small pan. Add the onion and saute over
medium-high heat until translucent, about 3 minutes. Add the garlic
and saute for 2 minutes, stirring frequently. Transfer the onions
and garlic to the roasted bell peppers. Add the turkey, corn,
cilantro, 3 tablespoons of the chipotle sauce, the cheese and lime
juice; stir to combine. Season with the cumin, salt and pepper; set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Assembling the enchiladas:  &LR; Heat the oil in a heavy skillet
over medium heat. Fry the corn tortillas one at a time in the oil
for 2 to 3 seconds on each side. Transfer to paper towels to drain.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle a thin layer of chipotle sauce in an 11x7-inch oven-proof
casserole dish. Working with one tortilla at a time, dip into the
pot of chipotle sauce and place on a cutting board. Spoon 2
tablespoons of the filling down the center of the tortilla and roll
it up. Place seam-side down in the casserole dish.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with the remaining tortillas, packing the enchiladas
tightly in the dish. Pour the remaining sauce over the enchiladas
and sprinkle with the grated cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 20 minutes, until heated through. Garnish with olives.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 12 enchiladas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER ENCHILADA: &LR;   &LR; 250 calories, &LR;   &LR; 14 g protein, 23 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 12 g fat (4 g saturated), 33 mg cholesterol, 229 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CURRIED TURKEY SALAD WITH APPLE &AMP; WALNUTS
</P>
<P>
   This makes a wonderful filling for pita breads. To add textural
and color interest, garnish each sandwich with alfalfa or radish
sprouts, tomato and cucumber slices.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   21/2 teaspoons curry powder, toasted (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cubed roasted turkey
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peeled, cored and diced red apple
</P>
<P>
   1 celery stalk, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup peeled, seeded and diced cucumber
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped toasted walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instruction:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the mayonnaise, curry powder, lemon juice and cayenne
pepper; stir to blend.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the turkey, apple, celery, cucumber and walnuts. Fold in
the dressing. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yields enough for 6 pita breads.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Toast the curry powder in a small nonstick pan over low
heat for 1 minute, or until just fragrant, stir often. This will
help remove the raw flavor from the curry powder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 215 calories, &LR;   &LR; 15 g protein, 5 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 15 g fat (3 g saturated), 43 mg cholesterol, 109 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
PENNE WITH BUTTERNUT SQUASH, CURRANTS &AMP; SPINACH
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Butternut Squash
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds butternut squash, peeled and cut in medium dice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   The Pasta
</P>
<P>
   1 pound penne or rigatoni
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups turkey stock (made from carcass), or low-sodium
chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped fresh sage
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup currants, plumped in warm water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   6 cups stemmed and cleaned spinach leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded roasted turkey, white meat preferred
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup toasted and roughly chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Combine the butternut squash, olive
oil, garlic and salt and pepper in a large bowl; toss to combine.
Transfer to a baking pan and bake for 30 minutes, or until the
squash is tender but not mushy.
</P>
<P>
   While the squash is roasting, bring a large pot of salted water
to a boil. Add the pasta and cook until al dente, about 7 minutes.
Drain, return to the pot, cover and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat olive oil in a large pan over medium heat. Add the shallot
and cook until softened, about 3 minutes. Add the wine and cook
until reduced by half. Add the stock, parsley, sage and drained
currants and cook for 2 minutes. Swirl in the butter, then add the
spinach, turkey and squash. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the sauce with the cooked pasta and top with toasted
pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 815 calories, &LR;   &LR; 41 g protein, 115 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 20 g fat (4 g saturated), 62 mg cholesterol, 150 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 7 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TURKEY SOUP WITH WILD RICE &AMP; ESCAROLE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   11/2 quarts turkey stock (made from carcass), or unsalted
chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup wild rice, rinsed
</P>
<P>
   8 cups escarole leaves, chopped into 1-inch pieces (about 1/2
head)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups roughly chopped roasted turkey (white and dark meat)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated Parmesan for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large pot over medium heat. Add the
onion and cook slowly until translucent, about 5 minutes. Add the
garlic and pepper flakes and cook until fragrant. Add the stock and
bring to a boil. Reduce heat to a simmer, then stir in the wild
rice. Simmer uncovered for 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the escarole and simmer for 20 minutes, until the rice is
tender. Stir in the turkey, season with salt and pepper, and cook
until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle into bowls and garnish with grated Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 310 calories, &LR;   &LR; 30 g protein, 32 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 7 g fat (2 g saturated), 55 mg cholesterol, 68 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GREEN BEANS &AMP; TURKEY IN ASIAN BLACK BEAN SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   This recipe cooks quickly with most of the time spent in
preparing the ingredients. It provides a savory option for your
turkey leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces green beans, trimmed and cut into 11/2-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons black bean paste or dried fermented black beans,
rinsed and crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 small yellow onion, peeled and cut lengthwise into 1/4-inch
slices
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup turkey or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 can (6-ounce can) of sliced water chestnuts, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cup turkey (cut into 11/2-inch lengths and similar size to the
beans)
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of sugar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Blanch the beans in boiling salted water; drain and rinse under
cold running water. Drain again. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place a nonstick saute pan or wok over medium-high heat. When
hot, add the oil, then add the black beans and garlic. Stir-fry
until aromatic but do not let the garlic brown. Add the ginger,
onion and white wine. Stir-fry until the onion starts to lose its
crispness, about 1 minute. Add the stock, then soy and oyster
sauces. Add the blanched green beans, water chestnuts and turkey.
Stir-fry until heated through. Stir in the sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with steamed rice or noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as a side dish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 150 calories, &LR;   &LR; 13 g protein, 11 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 6 g fat (1 g saturated), 27 mg cholesterol, 699 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SPICY ASIAN-STYLE CABBAGE &AMP; TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   The spiciness of this Asian-style dish can be adjusted by using
more or less of the chile paste. The turkey adds a meaty texture,
but the vegetables are definitely the main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 yellow onion, thinly sliced lengthwise (about 1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound green cabbage, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup turkey or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, peeled and julienned
</P>
<P>
   1/2 large red bell pepper, deribbed and julienned
</P>
<P>
   1 cup julienned roasted turkey
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Asian chile paste (or to taste)
</P>
<P>
   1 green onion (green part only), thinly sliced on the diagonal
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place a nonstick frying pan or wok over medium-high heat. When
hot, add the oil. When the oil is hot, add the garlic and ginger.
Stir-fry until fragrant but do not let the garlic brown. Add the
onion and stir-fry until it starts to turn translucent, about 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cabbage, wine and stock. Continue to cook, stirring
occasionally, until the cabbage begins to soften, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the carrots, bell pepper and turkey, then the oyster sauce,
fish sauce and soy sauce. Cook 1 minute longer, or until the turkey
is heated through and the carrots and pepper are still slightly
crisp. Season with salt, then add the chile paste, stirring to
combine well.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with green onions. Serve with white rice.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 155 calories, &LR;   &LR; 13 g protein, 12 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 6 g fat (1 g saturated), 27 mg cholesterol, 631 &LR;   &LR; mg
sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
