<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0696 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BOTTOM-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 2013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTTOM-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Two sidebars follow the main story --
well-known  cooks' least favorite gizmos and a few unlikely gadgets
that 
 work.   BOTTOM-DRAWER BLUES: Gadgets, gizmos and gewgaws nobody loves  
   
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Cookware guru Chuck Williams held up a slim,
three-pronged kitchen gadget and sighed. He was certain the French
tool, designed to make it easier to peel a hot, boiled potato,
would be a hit at his Williams-Sonoma stores.
 &HT;    Instead, it bombed.
 &HT;    ``I don't understand it,'' he said, a wistful look crossing his
84-year-old eyes. ``Maybe it's because we don't eat as many boiled
potatoes as the Europeans do.''
 &HT;    Or maybe it's because peeling the darn thing with a knife is
easier.
 &HT;    So it goes in the mercurial world of kitchen gadgets. More often
than not, tools that offer a clever solution to a vexing kitchen
problem are used once or twice and then relegated to the place all
bad kitchen gadgets go to die _ the bottom drawer.
 &HT;    Don't look so smug. You know you have one. Likely, it's filled
with olive grabbers, cherry pitters, butter curlers and bundt pans.
 &HT;    The bottom drawer has a corollary _ the bottom shelf. That's
reserved for kitchen appliances that once held the promise of
certain culinary glory, only to be shoved in the pantry after a few
uses. The items are often so heavy and bulky, their sheer weight
keeps them from being pulled out for use. Count among the
candidates food processors, electric juicers, yogurt makers and
electric pasta machines.
 &HT;    Although we ought to know better, cooks just can't stop buying
gadgets, ever hopeful that the olive will be easier to pit, the
cheese easier to grate. Last year, according to the National
Housewares Manufacturers Association, Americans spent almost $15.75
billion on kitchen cookware _ including pots and pans and basic
tools like spatulas _ but also including more esoteric items. And
the trend shows no sign of slowing.
 &HT;    So what makes a gadget go bad? Why does an item that seems so
promising in the store end up in the bottom drawer? After
interviewing dozens of cooks and sellers of kitchen tools, some
broad _ albeit completeley unscientific _ theories emerged:
 &HT;     It's simply easier to do the task by hand. 
 &HT;    Williams' boiled potato holder falls into this category. So do
egg separators. Remember when tasting spoons were popular? They had
a hollowed handle so soup or sauce could cool as it flowed from the
bowl down the handle to your lips. Somehow, just using a regular
spoon seems a lot easier.
 &HT;    Stephanie Connelly, an avid San Francisco home cook, offers a
perfect example. ``The one gadget that I bought that I tried to use
to no avail was a shrimp deveiner _ a little plastic thing with a
metal prong that you are supposed to scrape along the bottom of the
shrimp to remove the vein. The thing was more trouble than it was
worth. Just stick with your fingers; they work better.''
 &HT;     Food fashion changes. 
 &HT;    Still have your larding needles? How about that terra cotta
garlic roaster or your sea salt grinder? Food trends change as fast
as fashion trends, and the bottom drawer is a mini-museum of the
way we once cooked.
 &HT;    Williams doesn't sell many of those two-piece wire baskets used
make deep-fried shredded potato nests anymore. Nor does he sell a
lot of escargot equipment or vertical chicken roasters. He does
sell truckloads of oil misters, a gadget that reflect today's
lighter cooking styles .
 &HT;    But like bell-bottoms, keep a gadget in the drawer long enough
and it might come back in fashion. Just look at the crepe pan and
the fondue pot.
 &HT;     It's easier to buy the food than to make it. 
 &HT;    Many a cook has discovered this truth after buying a pasta
maker, bread machine, beef jerky maker or counter-top potato chip
fryer.
 &HT;    Allex Gruman, a division merchandising director for Macy's, puts
pizza stones in this category. ``Pizza stones were big when
thin-crust Italian pizza became fashionable five or six years ago.
But people realized it was a pain to roll out the crust and it
never tasted like the pizzas from the wood ovens anyway.''
 &HT;    But that wasn't the worst entry in this category, he says. ``The
total ultimate dog was the seltzer maker. I'll never forget it. It
was 1989. We found out nobody wants to make seltzer water at
home.''
 &HT;     You rarely or never make the food for which the tool is 
 designed. 
 &HT;    Holiday-specific cooking gadgets comprise much of this category.
Just shuffle through a drawer full of Pilgrim-shaped cookie
cutters, heart-shaped gelatin molds and cast-iron rosette irons.
Alongside, you'll find zuchinni ballers, soft-boiled egg cups,
turkey roasting accessories and donut making equipment.
 &HT;    Maybe it's time you admit you're never going to curl butter.
 &HT;     Cleaning the tool is too much work .
 &HT;    Although some people swear by them, garlic presses might be the
poster children for this problem. Spend time with a toothpick
trying to get garlic bits out of the holes and you'll be back to
using a knife in no time.
 &HT;    Home cook Jon Dickson of Oakland offers the combination pasta
and sausage maker as an example of a kitchen tool that got
consigned to the bottom shelf not only because cleanup was a
hassle, but because making the food wasn't worth the trouble.
 &HT;    ``I bought it, used it twice for pasta and once to make
sausages. It took more time to use than if I'd made pasta and
sausages by hand,'' he says. ``And the cleanup ... let's not even
go there.''
 &HT;     You can't resist the pitch. 
 &HT;    It slices, it dices _ and it usually doesn't work. This is the
universe of gadget sellers like Ron Popeil, and likely where bottom
drawer items are likely to be born.
 &HT;    Whether as complex as a half-hour infomercial or as simple as a
well-written packaging claim, the pitch on some kitchen items can
be too strong to resist. Of course you want a simple way to get
garlic odors off your fingers. But is a piece of polished stainless
steel really the answer?
 &HT;    Instant frothers, little glass disks that keep pots from boiling
over, in-the-shell egg scramblers, devices to make hard-boiled eggs
square, counter-top hamburger grills and knives that can cut a
soft-drink can then slice a tomato _ they all sound so promising,
so necessary. And how about those machines that cut segments of
citrus with the turn of a handle or slice onions into perfect
blossoms, just like you see in restaurants. Brilliant _ until you
find out that they don't work, they're too much hassle or you never
really liked those deep-fried onions anyway.
 &HT;    Clearly, weak moments fill bottom drawers. But good tools are as
essential to cooking as fresh ingredients. So how can a smart cook
balance the temptation to buy time-saving gadgets against the need
to have the right tools?
 &HT;    Easy. Be a smart shopper and go for solid kitchenware that will
endure.
 &HT;    ``The basic tools are what you'll always use,'' Williams says.
``Good knives, slicers and vegetable peelers, a zester, a whisk.''
 &HT;    Of course, that doesn't mean his stores will never stock
candidates for the bottom drawer. Among the kitchen items stacked
in his office for consideration recently was a wide-bladed knife
designed specifically to cut and serve cottage cheese.
 &HT;    Williams admitted it was a rather esoteric item. But then he got
a twinkle in his eye. ``Well,'' he said, ``you can get a lot of
cottage cheese up with it.''
 &HT;     
 
 
SIDEBAR: Chef's Least Chosen 
 
Here's what some Bay Area chefs, food writers and personalities
keep in their bottom drawers: &HT;     Nancy Oakes, chef/owner Boulevard . A garlic peeler shaped like
a rubber tube. ``Some things are just too much trouble to clean.''
 &HT;     Emily Luchetti, pastry chef, Farallon . A Mason jar lid opener.
``I have no idea where it came from. I think it has always been
with me.''
 &HT;     Craig Stoll, chef/owner, Delfina . A Parisian scoop. ``What am
I going to do? Take a beautiful vegetable from the farmer's market
and make little balls out of it?''
 &HT;     Mollie Katzen, cookbook author . A double cherry pitter. ``The
first time I used it I almost injured someone.''
 &HT;     Robert Helstrom, chef, Kuleto's . A sushi maker. ``I've had it
for 10 years and it has never been out of the box.''
 &HT;     Dan Scherotter, chef, Palio d' Asti.  A metal bar that removes
onion and garlic odor from hands. ``The French chef that was
selling them swore by them.''
 &HT;     Kevin Godes, chef, Cafe Pescatore.  A sandwich press. ``My
roommate from college had it. I brought it all the way from
Wisconsin.''
 &HT;     
_ Stephen Baker, San Francisco Chronicle 
 
 
 
SIDEBAR: A FEW UNLIKELY GIZMOS THAT WORK 
 
By Rebecca Markowitz 
c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ We asked experts from Williams-Sonoma, Home Chef
and Sur La Table cookware stores to list gadgets they expect to be
hot sellers for holiday gifts. Which will endure as favorite
kitchen tools and which will end up in the bottom drawer? Only time
will tell.
<P>
   &UR; Razor-sharp graters and zesters. &LR;  This line from Microplane, a
company that makes extraordinarily sharp woodworking tools, has
entered the cookware market. Kit Dombrowski from Sur La Table calls
the graters ``amazing.'' They come in five sizes, and retail from
$13-$19.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Potato ricers and food mills.  &LR; These tools are far from new,
but Home Chef founder Judith Ets-Hokin says they are _ and predicts
they will continue to be _ strong sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Potato ricers create fluffy, lump-free mashed potatoes and
retail for around $20.
</P>
<P>
   Food mills are much more versatile; they work as a masher,
strainer, blender and ricer _ but they can be expensive. Home
Chef's most popular food mill retails for $85 and comes with
exchangeable disks for additional versatility. Prices range from
$30-$100.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nonstick baking sheet liners.  &LR; Ets-Hokin says these are a great
gift choice for bakers. The silicon-coated liners allow cookies and
candies to easily slide off and are making a move from the
professional to home kitchen. Home Chef's eight stores sold 61 of
them in one recent business day. The liners come in two sizes and
retail for around $26.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Instant-Marinator.  &LR; Vacuvin makes this piece of equipment
that reduces the time it takes to marinate meat from one hour to 17
seconds. The meat is placed in a pouch with the marinade &UR;  &LR; and the
device removes the air, causing the pores to open. &UR;  &LR; After 17
seconds, the air is let back into the pouch. The pores close,
holding flavor inside. The Instant-Marinator retails for $29.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A gravy/stock strainer.  &LR; These measuring cups, with a long
pouring spout coming off the bottom, are not new but are remarkably
useful to get rid of fat in stock and pan drippings. Since fat
rises to the top, when liquids are poured out of the cup through
the bottom spout, the fat remains and can be discarded. The
strainer retails around $15.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OXO Good Grips turkey lifter.  &LR; This gadget eases the chore of
getting the heavy holiday bird out of the pan. Slip the hook into
the turkey cavity and pull. It retails for about $10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Camerons Smoker. &LR;  No need to wait for summer barbecue season if
you enjoy smoked foods. This smoker is designed to be used indoors.
It sits on any stovetop and imparts smoke flavor into meat,
poultry, fish or vegetables as they cook. It retails for around
$60.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Popeil Showtime Rotissierie and Grill ($179.99) and George &LR; 
 &UR; Forman Grill ($99.95).  &LR; Both are ``as seen on TV'' items, bringing
outdoor cooking into the kitchen. The table-top rotissiere is large
enough to hold two chickens. The Foreman ``lean, mean grilling
machine'' is an electric grilling pan that allows fat to run off
into a tray. At Macy's, these two items have been outselling the
classic Cuisinart food processor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Millennium-themed items.  &LR; Stores are heavily promoting
everything from caviar spoons to monogrammed Champagne stoppers for
end-of-the-year celebrations. But what will happen to these come
Jan. 2, 2000?
</P>
<P>
   (Rebecca Markowitz is a student at the California Culinary
Academy.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
