<HEADER>
A0697 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SOURCE-DUCK-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-DUCK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California
growers,  anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary 
 wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field 
 to forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients 
 stocking our larders.   AT THE SOURCE: These Ducks Are Birds of a Different Feather  
   
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 PETALUMA, Calif. _  The client list of fourth-generation duck
farmer Jim Reichardt reads like a Gault-Millau guide.
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Spago and Jiraffe in Los Angeles to Sorento in Seattle to
the Bay Area's Postrio, La Folie, Jardini &LR; e &LR; re, Hawthorne Lane,
Chez Panisse, Bay Wolf and Cafe Rouge, to name a few, top
restaurants use Reichardt's birds to make the likes of port-cured
duck confit, duck with Armagnac sauce and dried apricots, and duck
liver flan with green peppercorns and Marsala.
</P>
<P>
   Descended from a long line of Bay Area duck farmers _
great-grandfather Otto Reichardt started his business in 1901 in
San Francisco _ Jim Reichardt almost didn't make it into the
thinning ranks of independent poultry farmers.
</P>
<P>
   When he graduated from high school, his family, who had
relocated to Petaluma in the late '50s, felt the outlook for
independents like themselves was so dicey that their youngsters
needed to learn another profession. So Jim Reichardt dutifully got
a degree in architecture and, after finding draughting thoroughly
unsatisfactory, studied photography at the California College of
Arts and Crafts.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 29, he returned to the family business,
Reichardt Duck Farm. Seven years ago, he struck out on his own,
calling his business Sonoma County Poultry, Liberty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   By the standards of an industry dominated by giant producers,
Reichardt's farm is a boutique operation. ``We bring about 1,500
ducks to market in a week,'' he says. ``Compare that to Foster
Farms with at least 300,000 chickens  &LR; a day &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Reichardt and such faithful customers as Bay
Wolf's Michael Wild, Liberty ducks are birds of a different feather
from mass-produced poultry. Reichardt ducks, they assert, are
exceptionally meaty and have excellent flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The duck farmer says there are several reasons for these
qualities. He raises a strain of Pekin (CQ) &LR; ducks from a Danish
bloodline he considers outstanding, feeds them corn and other
grains (no hormones or antibiotics) and slaughters them at eight to
nine weeks, rather than the six to seven weeks that are standard in
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Reichardt alerts consumers that a bird promoted as not having
been fed antibiotics may still be inoculated with them. His are
not. He says he does lose some birds to disease but that his losses
are small because he keeps his flock healthy by natural means.
</P>
<P>
   Cleanliness, obviously is a factor, but so is space. In
large-scale poultry farming, a chicken may be allotted as little as
one square-foot of space. By comparison, Reichardt's ducks can
positively roam, with 50 to 75 square-feet of space allowed per
duck.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that they can move around, the farmer says, means more
blood circulating, which translates into meat with more flavor.
</P>
<P>
   And it keeps them healthy. Being able to exercise, says
Reichardt, they are not under the stress experienced by tightly
caged birds, ``and it's stress that makes (any creature) vulnerable
to disease.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHERE TO FIND &QL; 
THE DUCKS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Liberty Ducks from Jim Reichardt's Sonoma County Poultry are
mostly sold to top-flight restaurants in the Bay Area, Los Angeles
and the Pacific Northwest, though they are available retail _ or
can be ordered _ from Food For Thought in Santa Rosa, Sunshine and
Keller's markets in St. Helena and Enzo's in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no salesroom at either the farm or the
processing plant in Petaluma, individual customers can order birds
and pick them up at the plant (by prearrangement only) or have them
shipped.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are $1.90 per pound dressed (although prices are subject
to change). Sizes average 5 to 6 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The phone number for Liberty Ducks is (800) 953-8257 or (707)
795-3797. You can visit the company online at
 &LR; www.libertyducks.com &LR;  or e-mail the farm at  &LR; scpducks &LR; aol.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
