<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0699 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRETS-SALA-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRETS-SALA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the
recipe  for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the 
 chef's secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow 
 in optional trim.   SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Humble and Haute Hobnot in a Posh Portobello 
 Salad  
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Nancy Oakes, chef/owner of the wildly popular
Boulevard, loves the restaurant's Shaved Portobello with Fennel and
Radish Salad. She says, ``It allows the celery and radishes, which
often are ignored, to step out on the town with their more
glamorous friends: endive, fennel and portobello mushrooms.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the features that makes this bright winter salad
different is the fact that all the ingredients are sliced very
thinly, making for a delicious melding of tastes and textures. It
also makes it easy to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The vegetables are crowned with shavings of Spanish Manchego
cheese and dressed with a roasted lemon vinaigrette, another
unusual feature. This is a spectacular salad _ you won't find it
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Oakes is one of the most original cooks in the Bay Area, and
this belle epoque-style restaurant designed by Pat Kuleto is an
appropriate stage for her talents.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Boulevard, 1 Mission St. (at Steuart Street), San Francisco; &LR; 
 &LR; (415) 543-6084. Open for lunch weekdays, dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Bauer is The Chronicle's food editor.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; The dressing ingredients. &LR;  The roasted lemon adds a mellow flavor.
The acidic tomatoes help to emulsify the dressing. The white
balsamic vinegar adds a smooth richness, and the sugar helps to
balance the acid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shaving the ingredients. &LR;  This allows the dressing to cover
more surface, intensifying and unifying the flavors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An ice-water bath. &LR;  This ensures that the vegetables will be
cold and crisp, which helps them retain their individual character.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHAVED PORTOBELLO, FENNEL &AMP; RADISH SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 large head fennel, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   12 large red radishes, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   5 stalks celery, (preferably with pale green leaves)
</P>
<P>
   1 head frisee
</P>
<P>
   3 heads white or red endive
</P>
<P>
   1 large portobello mushroom, stemmed, gills removed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Manchego cheese
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Lemon Vinaigrette (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped mixed fresh herbs, such as Italian parsley,
tarragon and chervil (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Fill a large bowl with ice and add water to cover. Place the
fennel on a cutting board and cut in half lengthwise. Using a
Japanese or French mandoline, slice the fennel as thinly as
possible. Drop into the ice water.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the radishes into rounds and add to the ice water. Repeat
with the celery stalks. Add celery leaves to the ice water as well.
</P>
<P>
   Trim the frisee by cutting off all tough green leaves down to
the white part. Then cut away the root. Add the frisee to the ice
water.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the large leaves from the endive; try to get 18 large
leaves. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the heads of endive in half lengthwise. Carefully cut a
``V'' shape in the root end of each half. This core is bitter;
discard it. Place the endive halves on a cutting board and thinly
slice crosswise. Add to the ice water.
</P>
<P>
   Let the vegetables soak in the ice water for 10 minutes. Drain
and spin in a lettuce dryer.
</P>
<P>
   Using the mandoline, slice the portobello mushroom and Manchego
cheese very thinly.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place 3 large endive leaves on each salad plate
forming a loose triangle. Drizzle with a little of the Roasted
Lemon Vinaigrette. Combine the drained vegetables in a large bowl.
Drizzle with enough of the remaining vinaigrette to coat. Toss.
Season with salt and pepper. Add the optional herbs, the shaved
cheese and portobello. Toss to combine. Place a handful of salad in
the middle of each endive triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER SERVING (without dressing): &LR;   &LR; 280 calories, &LR;   &LR; 15 g &LR; 
 &LR; protein, 42 g carbohydrate, 13 g fat (6 g saturated), 33 mg &LR; 
 &LR; cholesterol, 672 mg sodium, 18 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROASTED LEMON VINAIGRETTE &QL; 
Any leftover dressing keeps well in the refrigerator for up to a
week. It may be used to dress other salads or to spoon onto grilled
chicken, fish or pork.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 lemons
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   10 yellow cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pierce each lemon with a paring knife. Place the lemons in a
microwave-safe container and cover with plastic wrap. Microwave on
HIGH for 10 minutes. Remove cover and let cool. (If you do not have
a microwave, pierce lemons and wrap in several layers of aluminum
foil, making sure no liquid can escape. Place in a pan and roast in
a 325-degree oven for 45 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   When the lemons have cooled to room temperature, gently squeeze
them to release the juices, but not so hard as to force out the
seeds. Put the juice in a blender; add the sugar, vinegar and
tomatoes. Puree until smooth. Transfer to a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually whisk in the olive oil until the vinaigrette is well
blended. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 11/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 85 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 1 g carbohydrate,
9 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 1 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
