r d BC-BESTBIRD-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTBIRD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST WAY: COOK THAT BIRD  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: The Best Way, a regular feature in the San  Francisco
Chronicle, describes the best methods for cooking 
 particular foods. This week, we talk about turkey. Descriptions 
 of the methods are followed by a recipe for brining _ the 
 staff's favorite.   c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Last week, The Chronicle Food section gave you the
four best ways to cook the Thanksgiving turkey _ a traditional
roasted method, roasted and brined, barbecued and smoked, and the
best big bird _ which we determined after two weeks of cooking and
tasting 28 turkeys.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a re-cap. These methods are for a 12- to 16-pound, or a
22-pound, unstuffed turkey. For the best way to roast a stuffed
turkey, see the chart elsewhere in this section.
</P>
<P>
   In all cases, roasting times may vary depending on the
temperature of the turkey when it goes in the oven and the accuracy
of the oven thermostat. To be sure the bird is done, the internal
temperature should read 165 degrees at the thickest part of the
thigh. When pricked with a fork, the juices should run clear. Let
the turkey rest 20-30 minutes after taking it out of the oven
before carving, during which time the internal temperature will
rise several degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BEST WAY TRADITIONAL
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Spread 2 tablespoons of softened
butter over the skin and sprinkle 41/2 teaspoons of kosher salt and
11/2 teaspoons of ground pepper over the skin and in the cavity.
Tuck the wing tips under, truss the legs and place the turkey on a
v-shaped rack in a roasting pan. Tent the breast with foil and
place the turkey in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   After about 1 hour, remove the foil and baste the turkey with
1/2 cup stock. Re-baste it with pan drippings and any remaining
stock every 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Roast the turkey until the internal thigh temperature reaches
165 degrees, 13/4-21/4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST WAY BRINED
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  This was the Food staff's favorite turkey. Brine the turkey for
12 to 24 hours, using the accompanying recipe for the brine.
</P>
<P>
   Before roasting, rinse and dry the turkey well, and follow the
directions for the Best Way Traditional turkey, but do not sprinkle
the turkey with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Start checking the internal temperature after about 11/2 hours
of roasting time. If the legs begin to overbrown, cover them
loosely with foil. Roast until the internal thigh temperature
reaches 165 degrees, 2-23/4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST WAY NON-ROASTED
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Brine the turkey according to the accompanying recipe, then rinse
and dry the turkey well, rub the skin with 2 tablespoons of
softened butter and sprinkle with 11/2 teaspoons of pepper on the
skin and inside the cavities.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a covered grill with a charcoal fire, centering an
aluminum or metal drip pan directly under the grill and arranging
the coals on either side. Soak applewood chips as directed on the
package, then sprinkle a handful over the hot coals.
</P>
<P>
   Place the prepared turkey on the grill, close the cover and cook
the turkey until the internal thigh temperature registers 165
degrees, about 21/4-3 hours. Add additional coals and soaked chips
as needed to maintain an even temperature and smokiness. Cover the
turkey with aluminum foil if it begins to overbrown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST WAY BIG BIRD
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Prepare a 20-22 pound turkey as
directed for the Best Way Traditional bird, but double the amount
of softened butter, salt and pepper, then roast and baste (using
about 1 cup stock) according to the Best Way Traditional
directions. Cover the legs with foil if they begin to overbrown.
Roast until the internal thigh temperature registers 165 degrees,
about 31/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   CHEZ PANISSE'S BRINE FOR TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   21/2 gallons cold water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves, torn into pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh thyme, or 4 tablespoons dried
</P>
<P>
   1 whole head of garlic, cloves separated and peeled
</P>
<P>
   5 whole allspice berries, crushed
</P>
<P>
   4 juniper berries, smashed
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the water in a large pot that can easily hold the liquid
and the turkey you intend to brine. Add all ingredients and stir
for a minute or two until the sugar and salt dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   Put your turkey into the brine and refrigerate for 24 hours. If
the turkey floats to the top, use a plate or other weight to keep
it completely submerged in the brine.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Note: &LR;  The recipe may be halved or doubled; the important
thing is to have enough brine to completely cover the turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Before roasting, remove the bird from the brine and drain well.
Pat dry.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1941EST &QL; 
