<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0705 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BOOKHARLOW-SFCHRON &LR;      11-24 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKHARLOW-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   COOK'S BOOKS : ``West Coast Seafood'' 
 
 
By Karola Saekel 
c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle 
 
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ A young professional cook of our acquaintance spent
an hour or so perusing ``West Coast Seafood'' the other day and
said that if you had no other book on seafood, this would tell you
all you needed to know _ from basic facts to techniques to recipes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's a pretty strong endorsement, but it's right on the mark.
Veteran chef/food writer Jay Harlow leaves no fin unturned in this
just-published volume. And while there are some excellent books on
fish and seafood cookery on the market, most are geared to East
Coast catches. Harlow is West Coast specific.
</P>
<P>
   As a cookbook author, Harlow is eminently practical. He doesn't
just state that a certain fish is great for barbecuing, poaching or
sauteing, he explains why, so the reader gains an understanding of
the inherent nature of different fish and can make informed
choices.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the book explains how tuna is graded and why it's a
waste of money to buy grade one (sashimi-grade) fish unless you
intend to eat it raw.
</P>
<P>
   Even seafood novices should have no problem preparing great
meals from this book _ and may even tackle intimidating tasks such
as boning and filleting a fish or cooking live crab and lobster.
(Harlow details the most humane manner of dispatching the
crustaceans.)
</P>
<P>
   All of Harlow's recipes meet the three essential C's: They're
clear, concise and consumer-friendly. In flavor combinations, they
roam the globe, with much inspiration from the Pacific Rim _ Shrimp
and Vegetable Curry with Tamarind, a soupy dish to be spooned over
rice; Real Sweet and Sour Fish with a choice of two sauces; and
Stir-Fried Oysters With Black Bean Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   These Asian-inspired preparations share billing with Italian,
French, Caribbean, Creole and good &LR; all-American dishes such as
Beer-Steamed Clams and Basic Buttermilk Fried Catfish.
</P>
<P>
   The catfish is a superbly budget-pampering dish. If you want to
go to the other side of the cost spectrum, go for the Abalone and
Chanterelle Salad. I intend to make it as soon as the NASDAQ goes
up another 500 points.
</P>
<P>
   Harlow puts the appropriate finish on dishes _ and the book _
with a selection of sauces as familiar as tartar sauce and as
interesting as charmoula, the garlicky Moroccan preparation that
doubles as marinade and sauce. In Harlow's processor/blender
version, it's a snap to make.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``West Coast Seafood: The Complete Cookbook,'' by Jay Harlow &LR; 
 &LR; (Sasquatch Books; 366 pages, trade paperback; $23.95). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; FISH DIEPPOISE
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; This is a festive, rich dish, inspired by the fish-shellfish
combinations favored in the French port of Dieppe.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soft butter
</P>
<P>
   1 heaping tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   12 mussels, cleaned
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   12 medium-size raw shrimp, peeled, deveined, shells reserved
</P>
<P>
   3 green onions, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   4 sole or flounder fillets, about 3 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Blend the butter and flour thoroughly; set aside at room
temperature. Combine the mussels, shallots and half of the wine in
a saucepan. Cover, bring to a boil and steam until the mussel
shells open, 3 to 5 minutes. Remove the mussels and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce the heat to a simmer, add the shrimp and simmer just
until they turn opaque. Remove the shrimp with a slotted spoon and
set aside. Add the shrimp shells to the pan and leave at a simmer.
Shuck the mussels, discard the shells and add the mussels to the
bowl with the shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the remaining wine and the green onions in a nonstick
skillet just large enough to hold the fish. Add water to a depth
equal to the thickness of the fillets, bring almost to a boil,
reduce the heat and simmer 5 minutes. Season the fish fillets
lightly with salt, add them to the skillet and poach until just
done. Transfer to a warm platter or individual plates.
</P>
<P>
   Discard the green onions and strain the contents of the
shellfish pan into the skillet. Bring to a boil, reduce by
two-thirds and add the cream, cayenne and a large pinch of salt.
Reduce until lightly thickened, whisk in the butter-flour mixture
and simmer another minute or so. Taste for seasoning and adjust to
taste. Add the shellfish to the sauce to reheat briefly, then spoon
the sauce and shellfish over the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 275 calories, &LR;   &LR; 24 g protein, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 16 g fat (9 g saturated), 149 mg cholesterol, 277 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
