<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIMELINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BACK TO THE FUTURE, BUT IT'S BEEN DONE BEFORE
</HEADLINE>
 (for use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timeline
</P>
<P>
   by Michael Crichton
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $26.95
</P>
<P>
   Um.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to write a review that essentially trashes a
sure-fire bestseller, a book that will be made into summer 2000's
smash hit film and, not coincidentally, earn its already flush
author another few million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Timeline,'' Michael Crichton's latest potboiler,
exemplifies the kind of novel that ought, properly, to be a comic
book. It's crammed with one-dimensional characters and improbable
plot twists, and it features a plot that has been exhausted by
previous generations of writers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Timeline'' is going to sell at least a million copies
in hardcover _ that means hopeful publisher Knopf, shipping 1.5
million to bookstores as its first printing, can have 500,000 left
over for remainder bins and still turn a tidy profit. The movie
sale is already made, and Crichton's so certain of ``Jurassic
Park''-type success that he's cut himself in for a box-office
percentage instead of a sure-thing one-time rights sale.
</P>
<P>
   So what is ``Timeline'' about? Time travel, natch. Scientists
working for a nasty boy-genius billionaire figure out how to send
people back to medieval times. Things don't always work perfectly,
and one key team member, a revered professor, gets stuck smack in
the middle of some contretemps in 14th-century France. Some other
people are sent to fetch him back, but they must somehow do this
``without radically affecting the course of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Crichton serves up the present/past literary cocktail with
ingredients that taste good but don't provide much intellectual
nourishment; let's call it the fictional equivalent of Pop-Tarts.
The author spews out just enough scientific stuff to give the false
impression that readers are learning a lot about quantum physics,
and his descriptions of castle life are just vivid enough to fill
in frames of a TV cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   The jousts and sword fights are appropriately grisly. Rotting
teeth are described perhaps more frequently than necessary. We
learn what sort of drawers the knights wore under their armor.
</P>
<P>
   The suspense, such as it is, is cartoonish, too. Believe it or
not, things go wrong for the rescue team, and their modern-day
means of getting back to the present hang in the scientific
balance. Will the scientists battling present-day technology
disasters fix things in time to rescue their friends battling enemy
knights in the past? Gee, take a wild guess.
</P>
<P>
   But Crichton has succeeded as a novelist any time he has
provided predictable cartoon entertainment. There was nothing
particularly innovative about ``Jurassic Park,'' ``Congo'' or ``The
Andromeda Strain,'' to name his other fiction megasuccesses.
Writers from H.G. Wells to Edgar Rice Burroughs had plowed those
literary fields before. The familiar sells; just consider those
clone-like TV sitcoms that top the Nielsen ratings every week.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton's sales have tumbled when he has tried to deal with
real-life issues. ``Rising Sun'' (Japanese-bashing), ``Disclosure''
(sexual harassment) and ``Airframe'' (air safety) all flopped, at
least compared with ``Jurassic Park.'' Cartoon characters work only
with appropriately cartoonish subjects, like dinosaurs in the
modern world or scientists in the 14th century.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be blunt: ``Timeline'' is not a very good book, but, for
its purposes and audience, it doesn't have to be. It is the
frothiest kind of mind candy, spiffed up with a few scientific
terms here and there to give the impression that it's delivering
more information than it really is. Professional wrestling pretends
to be real, too, and calls itself ``sports entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, ``Timeline'' is entertainment. Just don't kid yourselves
you're getting the literary equivalent of the Olympics. You're
getting pro wrestling..MDUL/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
