<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0717 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-DARKTHICKET-TEX     11-24 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DARKTHICKET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLES RAGE ON THE HOME FRONT, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dark Thicket''
</P>
<P>
   by Elmer Kelton
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   TCU Press, $21.95
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Kelton fans generally have to wait a year or so between
his highly crafted stories. The last was ``The Buckskin Line,'' a
Civil War-era tale of Texas Rangers and a young man's growth to
manhood.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just months from that book's release, comes the rerelease
of ``Dark Thicket,'' a 1985 book that also centers on Texas during
the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   There is much in common between the two Kelton novels. A young
boy must mature amid family discord, battling neighbors and
differing political views.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a young woman involved. Kelton always seems
to soften the hardships of the Texas frontier with the presence of
a woman to turn a man's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Thicket'' is a tightly written story. Owen Danforth has
gone off to war, to fight for the Confederacy against his father's
wishes. The two men were estranged, and now Owen is coming home
with a deep saber wound across his arm.
</P>
<P>
   He is to rest, recuperate, then rejoin his gray-uniformed
outfit.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to convalesce at his home, where he and his father can
heal their relationship as well.
</P>
<P>
   But in their way stands the ``heel flies,'' a band of ``home
guards'' who have taken the war as an opportunity to steal land and
livestock. They get their nickname by buzzing around the heels of
anyone who doesn't believe in the Confederacy. They are devoted to
the Confederacy, and property belonging to Union sympathizers is
free for the taking. Texas is filled with Union sympathizers, and
being a heel fly can be lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   Owen's father believes that the Union should be preserved, and
the heel flies constantly swirl around his place. He keeps the
flies stirring by aiding others who flee rebel conscription,
sending them to the safety of the dark, deep East Texas thicket.
</P>
<P>
   Owen arrives in this mess, protected only slightly by his
threadbare uniform and his orders to return to duty. He is
mistrusted, though, because of his father's sympathies.
</P>
<P>
   He is quickly tossed into conflict that makes him reassess his
feelings for his country and his father. He reluctantly ends up in
the thicket, hiding from the heel flies and protecting families
that also mistrust him because of his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   He is still a Confederate soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Thicket'' is a typical Kelton novel. Stories come full
circle, details are attended to, and the dialogue is as real as
Kelton's West Texas upbringing can allow. It is enjoyable reading
in which good always overcomes bad, and the boy always gets the
girl.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
