<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROTZ IN THE KNOW WHEN IT COMES TO BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Of all the NHL coaches, few are more familiar with
the Bruins' personnel _ recent past and present _ than Nashville
Predators coach Barry Trotz.
</P>
<P>
   Trotz nurtured many talented players while at the helm of the
Portland Pirates of the American Hockey League. Among those he
coached were Bruins centers Jason Allison and Anson Carter and
goaltender Byron Dafoe. Trotz also coached former Bruins goalie Jim
Carey, ex-Bruins forward Dmitri Khristich, and Olaf Kolzig,
Washington's No. 1 netminder.
</P>
<P>
   Trotz, whose team took on the Bruins here Wednesday night, said
he was sure Carter would find success at the NHL level, but wasn't
as certain about Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anson was an easier read than Jason. Anson was a guy who was
naturally a gifted athlete. He was very powerful, very quick. He
was very smooth on the ice. He had a good work ethic and he was
quite mature for being in the AHL,'' said Trotz. ``He stuck out
like a sore thumb. It was obvious he was going to do fine. Jason
was a guy who, because of his awkward skating, was a tougher guy to
get a read on. You knew if he was consistent in his work ethic and
he would listen and he would pay attention to both parts of the
game, that with his hands and size and reach that he could do some
good things.''
</P>
<P>
   Trotz said it took a little while for Allison to whittle off
some of his rough edges. ``He was a young 18-year-old when we
drafted him and he was sort of set in his ways,'' said Trotz.
``When he played in London (Ontario of the OHL), he played 40
minutes a game. He just sort of ended up standing around but
because of his hand skills and his vision, he could do some good
things in junior and score a lot of points. But he wasn't skating,
he wasn't moving his feet. He wasn't having success when he came up
to Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Trotz said Allison was caught between being too good for the
junior leagues and too young for the NHL, and he wasn't eligible to
go to the minors so it made for a quandary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed that adjustment period,'' said Trotz. ``He played
very well for Portland when he played for us on the offensive side.
He was a little bit stubborn in how he saw the game, but he loves
the game. You could talk to Jason about hockey and he'd talk to you
for hours, but he was set in his ways, a little stubborn. I think
as he's matured, he's seen he has to do different things to be
successful. He's got the work ethic. He's not the most graceful
guy. But as he got strong, he got better.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you knew he could do is dish the puck and he could
see the ice. He's got great patience. He's tough to contain. We
knew he was going to be a good player. Anson was a guy you'd knew
would be a consistently 50-60 point guy on your first line or your
checking line. And both those kids are good guys.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After missing one game with a bruised knee, Joe Thornton was
back in the lineup against the Predators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good (Wednesday) morning,'' said Thornton, who sat out
Monday's game in Carolina. ``So, I'm ready to go. (Trainer Don Del
Negro) has done a great job. It was a little sore after practice
(Tuesday) because it was the first time skating in a couple of
days, but it felt good. I'm ready to go. It's tough not being in
the lineup. It's nice to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison joked that Thornton just hated the trapping, obnoxiously
tough style of the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the Carolina flu,'' kidded Allison. ``Make sure you put
that in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Brandon Smith arrived early evening on Tuesday and
was in the lineup Wednesday. Smith, who was paired with Darren Van
Impe, was recalled from Providence after Mattias Timander was
sidelined by a separated left shoulder he suffered against
Carolina. Smith was a victim of a numbers game at the end of
training camp with the Bruins' decision to keep rookie Jonathan
Girard. Had they not, Smith would've likely been in Boston all
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of caught me off guard because I had the feeling I was
going to be around for the start of the season, so it kind of came
as a surprise,'' said Smith. ``But it's all part of the game. I'm
kind of used to it, but it was very disappointing. To see what
happened to Johnny Grahame was kind of surprising also but it's all
part of the game. All we can do is go out and play and they make
the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Smith wasn't thrown off by being demoted.
After going down, it took him some time to find his game. ``It was
a little struggle the first couple of weeks because it was really
disappointing and my head wasn't into it,'' he said. ``But things
were starting to come around the last couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember all the activity back in June? The Bruins exposed
forward Peter Ferraro and goaltender Rob Tallas in the expansion
draft. Tallas was scheduled to be taken by Atlanta, but in exchange
for not taking him, the Bruins got Ferraro back and gave up center
Randy Robitaille. Robitaille's rights were then traded to Nashville
for Denny Lambert two months later.
</P>
<P>
   Now Robitaille is trying to carve out a niche with the
Predators.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played fine,'' said general manager David Poile. ``And in
fairness to him, in a very limited role. He doesn't dress in all
the games. Some games he's played on the fourth line. I think we're
a little ahead of the Bruins in terms of giving him an opportunity.
Still, we haven't put him in a top three line position for any
number of games. I think that's what we have to do if we're going
to be committed to him and vice versa. Maybe he's not showing
enough to warrant that. But it's real close. Statistically, he's
done not bad for the amount of ice time he has. He has some real
good skills offensively. When all is said and done, we should know
whether he's going to be a long-term player here or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1954EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
