<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0721 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-JAPAN-SUBWAY-ART-2TAK     11-24 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SUBWAY-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC WORKS AND POINTLESS WASTE GO HAND-IN-HAND IN JAPAN
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 of the new subway is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In its ceaseless effort to prod its maddeningly lifeless
economy into action, Japan has spent more than $1 trillion, much of
it on bridges, tunnels, airports, concert halls and pavement aimed
at propping up the economy and satisfying political promises.
</P>
<P>
   The goal has been old-fashioned pump priming in the manner of
John Maynard Keynes, whose prescription for reviving an economy
was, more or less, dig a hole and fill it up, again and again if
need be. That is an oversimplification, but he was the leading
proponent of government spending as a means of restarting economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   So in Japan, airport runways have been added when an extension
would suffice. Tunnels are dug instead of simple roads. The
cobblestone sidewalks in a graceful old graveyard have been dug up
_ and relaid. Many a town is getting a multimillion-dollar concert
hall that would be the envy of Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the new Tokyo subway line. After waiting decades
for a new underground rail line that would relieve overcrowding on
the above-ground train that encircles the central city, Tokyo now
seems to have produced yet another boondoggle.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when local population and subway ridership trends are
flat, it will cost taxpayers a stunning $10 billion _ 50 percent
more than originally projected in 1989 _ and it is two years behind
schedule. By one estimate, tickets will have to cost about $9.50
for the city to recoup its investment, a price that makes Tokyo's
infamously expensive taxis look like a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   But that is just the half of it. What has really raised tempers
here is the fact that the new line will not live up to its billing
when it opens because it does not run in a complete circle. Riders
seeking the most direct route from the northern part of the city to
the southwest, or vice versa, will have to get off the train at one
point, walk across the platform to another track and wait for
another train.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Rolls-Royce that you can't shift into reverse,''
Shintaro Ishihara, Tokyo's outspoken governor, said recently in one
of his milder critiques of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Route 12, as the line is known, is just one of many public works
projects here that seem extravagant, wasteful, pointless or just
plain dumb, especially if one is unfamiliar with the complicated
politics that brought them to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least 50 percent of the spending has been useless at
stimulating further economic activity beyond the initial
investment,'' said Tadashi Nakamae, a prominent economist here.
``And maintenance costs for it all will be huge.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, the government announced yet another stimulus
package, its ninth, which included a minimum of $24 billion to
$28.5 billion at current exchange rates for traditional public
works.
</P>
<P>
   No one is certain how many jobs or how much economic growth has
been created by such lavish spending, but economists generally
agree that it has kept the Japanese economy from slipping into a
severe recession or even a depression. Indeed, a good portion of it
has come at the behest of the U.S. Treasury, which believes that a
healthy Japan is good for the world and certainly for the United
States. Never mind that in today's political climate, Washington
would never be allowed to spend so freely were the U.S. economy to
slip.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many economists argue, much of the money has been
spent profligately, staving off inevitable and necessary changes in
the economy but failing to put it back on its feet so that it can
move ahead. Some also have suggested that Japan would have been
better served if the money had been used to help more start-up
companies or to create a better safety net for the unemployed
instead of propping up failing construction companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not totally against public works,'' said Masaaki Kanno,
chief economist at J.P. Morgan Securities. After all, he notes, it
is hard to find a pothole in Tokyo's streets, and most public
facilities are clean and in good condition. ``But the government
should focus on projects whose returns on investment would be much
higher, like encouraging the construction of taller buildings in
Tokyo to enhance land usage.''
</P>
<P>
   That would require changes in the tax code, which penalizes
those who replace small ramshackle buildings with skyscrapers, as
opposed to outright spending. Instead, money keeps getting spent,
often in places where it seems to make no sense.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Consider the colored asphalt that is now used to keep Tokyo's
streets flawlessly paved. The roads are beginning to resemble
patchwork quilts, with stretches of red and green pavement
alternating with ordinary gray.
</P>
<P>
   A square yard or so of the green asphalt used by the Minato
Ward, Tokyo's wealthiest district, costs about $238, compared with
$146 for regular asphalt, said a ward spokesman. The green
pavement's rough surface helps keep cars from slipping, he said,
and is also used to distinguish the part of the road intended for
pedestrian use.
</P>
<P>
   But in an adjacent ward, a green stretch of pavement means there
is a school nearby and red pavement is used to prevent slippage and
warn drivers of blind curves.
</P>
<P>
   Given the stop-and-start nature of Tokyo traffic, drivers can
hardly be bothered to remember that in one district green pavement
means one thing while in another it means something else.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Officials are also under pressure to spend all of the money
allocated to them for public works within a fiscal year. If they do
not, they get less the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Japanese system of single-year budgets, budget
organizers only think about the completion of roads and so forth
and do not consider future usage or maintenance costs,'' said
Atsushi Miyawaki, a professor of law at Hokkaido University who
specializes in government finance. ``Political pork barreling
becomes much easier if you disregard future costs.''
</P>
<P>
   And public works here, as in many other places, are nothing if
not political pork. Most involve construction, because that
industry directly and indirectly employs 10 million Japanese
workers and voters, said Takayoshi Igarashi, a professor at Hosei
University who has been an especially outspoken critic of public
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public works benefit the general contractors, their
subcontractors and so on, so that the eventual list of
beneficiaries, including the politicians who receive contributions
from the construction companies, is a long one,'' he said. ``It's a
very strong network.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new underground subway, there are 58 general contractors,
a fact that, coupled with the cost overruns and delays, led
Ishihara to charge earlier this year that the whole project was
ridden with ``dango,'' or price collusion.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal bureaucrats denied his accusations, and Ishihara has
since chosen his words more carefully by criticizing the difference
between what the government agreed to pay and the actual cost of
the line. ``I don't know that dango is involved,'' he said. ``I
don't think so, but it's very strange, isn't it, very mysterious
that such discrepancies in cost would arise, considering there were
so many smart people here working on the bidding.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The planning of many public works projects also seems inept.
Take the airport in Fukushima Prefecture. The prefecture, about 100
miles north of Tokyo, was less than a year into the construction
when it decided that the airport needed a longer runway.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than merely adding several hundred feet, the
prefecture successfully appealed to the national government for
funding for a new runway.
</P>
<P>
   Makoto Kano, a prefectural official, said a new runway was the
obvious answer. Forecasts suggested there would be a demand for
jumbo jet service, he said, and they require not only a longer
runway, but also a path for jets to enter it. The original runway
was too close to the terminal building to construct one, he said,
so a new runway was built. The cost: about $267 million at current
exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   But even before construction could be completed last December,
the prefecture decided that the new runway also would have to be
extended, and it received national government approval for that,
too. Fukushima Ombudsman, a citizens' watchdog group that opposes
extending the new runway, estimates that the extension will cost
anywhere from $380 million to $667 million.
</P>
<P>
   Why is the extension more expensive than building the runway in
the first place? Kano did not have an answer, other than to say
that the prefecture was still debating the total length. He said he
expects the extension to cost a little more than $380 million.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The urge to spend certainly seems to take precedence over
planning. In Hokkaido, the northernmost of the four main Japanese
islands, authorities decided to build the Doto Jidoshado, a toll
road that will eventually cross the island.
</P>
<P>
   About 32 miles of the new 160-mile highway has been completed,
at a cost of about $1.9 billion at current exchange rates. But it
has failed to attract drivers largely because an existing highway
running parallel to it is free.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have tried to attract drivers by offering prizes, golf
competitions and the chance to drive a snowplow. The campaign
succeeded in increasing the average number of cars using the toll
road to 862 a day but it still has the distinction of being the
least used road in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   All this spending, too, has led to a tremendously expensive game
of one-upmanship. In Hamamatsu, a city of about 555,000 people
southwest of Tokyo, almost $1.9 billion of public and private money
was spent to build a concert hall and performance center.
</P>
<P>
   Act City Hamamatsu, which opened in 1994, features a $3 million
organ and a high-tech, four-stage performance hall. ``It is
expensive,'' a spokesman for the hall said. ``There are few stages
in the world that use a four-panel stage because of the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   So grand is Act City that its cross-prefecture rival, Shizuoka
City, with a population of about 471,000 decided it needed one too.
The Granship Shizuoka, designed by the leading Japanese architect,
Arata Isozaki, has a meeting hall with a view of Mount Fuji and six
booths for simultaneous translators, and its main hall can be used
for sporting events because all of its 4,600 seats are removable.
</P>
<P>
   It opened last March, about 40 miles from its competitor. The
price: $672 million in public money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-KIDNEY-TREATMENT-     11-24 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-KIDNEY-TREATMENT-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATMENT OF KIDNEY FAILURE IS FLAWED, 2 STUDIES SUGGEST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two studies being published Thursday suggest that flaws in the
treatment of kidney failure may endanger thousands of Americans.
Both studies concern dialysis, the treatment given several times a
week to cleanse the blood of waste products that build up when the
kidneys do not work.
</P>
<P>
   The first report, by researchers at Johns Hopkins University and
Harvard Medical School, found that people with kidney failure who
had dialysis at for-profit treatment centers were 20 percent more
likely to die and 26 percent less likely to be referred for a
transplant than patients treated at nonprofit centers. Two-thirds
of the 200,000 Americans on dialysis are treated at for-profit
centers, which have come to dominate the dialysis industry in the
last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said they did not know the reasons for the
disparities, but speculated that for-profit centers might be
cutting corners in ways that harmed patients, and failing to
recommend transplants in order to hang on to customers and keep
dialysis payments coming in.
</P>
<P>
   The second study, also by Harvard researchers, found that blacks
with kidney failure were considerably less likely than whites to be
referred for the best treatment, a transplant _ a difference that
could not be explained by medical differences between blacks and
whites or on blacks' wanting transplants less than whites. More
likely, the authors said, the difference was in doctors' failure to
inform blacks properly about the advantages of the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Both studies are being published in Thursday's New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The first, directed by Dr. Pushkal P. Garg, an instructor in
medicine and health care policy at Harvard Medical School, included
3,569 patients who began dialysis in 1990 or 1993, and studied them
for three to six years; 2,168 were treated at for-profit dialysis
centers.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that for every 100 patients treated per
year, 21.2 died at for-profit centers, as against 17.1 at nonprofit
centers _ a 20 percent higher risk of death. The study also found
that patients at those centers were 26 percent less likely to be
referred to transplant centers and placed on waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   Garg and his colleagues suggested that the root of the problem
was the Medicare program, which pays for dialysis for all patients
but has not raised the price it pays since 1973. The shrinking
value of the payments, they said, might have led centers needing to
show a profit to skimp on patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts viewed Garg's findings with caution, and several
noted that earlier studies had examined similar data and found no
difference in death or transplant referral rates between for-profit
and nonprofit centers.
</P>
<P>
   The National Kidney Foundation, a patient advocacy group that
receives some of its financing from dialysis centers, issued a
statement saying that Garg's data was several years old and that
treatment of dialysis patients had improved in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   The new study did not look for cost-cutting tactics at dialysis
centers, but previous studies by other researchers have found that
some centers had tried to save money by shortening the time each
patient spent on dialysis, giving smaller doses of expensive drugs,
reducing staff size, replacing nurses with lower-paid technicians
and reusing disposable equipment. It is not known whether those
practices took place in the new study.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the likeliest explanation but there is no direct proof,''
said Dr. Norman Levinsky, a kidney specialist and professor of
medicine at Boston University, who wrote an editorial about the
studies in the same issue of the journal.
</P>
<P>
   Garg acknowledged that dialysis patients might be alarmed by the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual patients will be concerned about what's happening
at their corner dialysis center, but our study doesn't address
that,'' Garg said. ``We try to emphasize that this is an average
effect across all facilities in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, he added, that some for-profit centers may provide
excellent care and some nonprofit centers may give poor care.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, when asked which type of center he would choose if
he suddenly needed dialysis, Garg said, ``The odds would be in my
favor if I went to a nonprofit center.''
</P>
<P>
   Levinsky said, ``Neither patients nor relatives should be
frightened that they're in danger of imminent death. But they can
use this as an occasion for a dialogue with their nephrologists.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be a good idea for patients in both kinds of
units to ask their kidney specialists if their center was providing
enough dialysis and if it had enough technicians, nurses and social
workers to provide good care.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Josephine Briggs, director of the kidney, urologic and
hematologic division of the National Institute of Diabetes,
Digestive and Kidney Diseases, said that because other researchers
had not made findings similar to Garg's, ``this kind of analysis
needs to be done again and followed over time,'' and added, ``If
it's a persistent trend, it will have to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eli Friedman, who runs a nonprofit dialysis unit for Kings
County Hospital and the State University Medical Center in
Brooklyn, said: ``Though I doubt it is true that proprietary units
are increasing the mortality in patients to increase their profits,
I'm happy to see the discussion provoked.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman added that it would make no sense for dialysis centers
to provide poor care, because if patients died they would be losing
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be dumb business, bad medicine and inhumane, and I
don't think that combination exists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the second study, a team led by Dr. John Z. Ayanian, an
assistant professor of medicine and health care policy at Harvard
Medical School, conducted a survey of 1,392 dialysis patients,
slightly more than half of whom were black.
</P>
<P>
   It was already known that blacks were less likely than whites to
have transplants, as well as other effective medical procedures
like bypass surgery, knee and hip replacement, and cataract
surgery. The reasons for the differences are not known, but it has
been suggested that blacks simply did not want the procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Ayanian and his colleagues found that blacks were slightly less
likely than whites to want transplants. But the small difference in
interest could not begin to account for the large difference in
referrals by doctors to transplant centers. Among black women, 50.4
percent were referred to a transplant center, but with white women
the figure was 70.5 percent. For black men, 53.9 percent were
referred, as opposed to 76.2 percent for white men.
</P>
<P>
   Ayanian said he did not think the differences reflected overt
prejudice on the part of doctors, who are mostly white. ``I think
primarily we're talking about deficits in communication and
trust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, citing Ayanian's study, the federal Health Care
Financing Administration, which oversees Medicare, announced that
it would take new steps to make sure that everyone on dialysis is
evaluated for a kidney transplant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
