<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0730 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-EGYPTAIR-CRASH-BOS &LR;      11-24 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIPLOMATIC CONCERNS CLOUD PROBE OF EGYPTAIR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ FBI Director Louis Freeh was hoping to get started
on the investigation of EgyptAir Flight 990 when he went in to see
Attorney General Janet Reno nine days ago. She favored the move,
but with one caveat: All other interested parties must sign on,
including the US State Department and the Egyptian government.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the National Transportation Safety Board, which had
been poised to turn over the investigation to the FBI, has pulled
back. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has been walking a
diplomatic tightrope, attempting to prevent the investigation from
harming relations with an important Middle East ally while also
making sure that the Egyptians do not hinder the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   While news reports have already exhaustively examined the
sequence of events in the Oct. 31 crash and the performance of the
EgyptAir crew, the investigation officially remains in an early
stage. And US officials say progress is being complicated by
diplomatic and cultural clashes of two countries that sometimes
appear to have conflicting goals, and by the variety of US agencies
involved.
</P>
<P>
   US government and law enforcement officials say the situation
has not reached the level of an international crisis, but several
concede that the dispute with Egypt may eventually require
President Clinton's decision on how to handle the investigaton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's eventually going to reach the White House,
because of the diplomatic sensitivity'' said a law enforcement
official.
</P>
<P>
   As for transferring the case to the FBI, a Justice Department
official said: ``I don't think it's possible to ever put a real
timeline on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The fluidity of the timetable is apparent in the comment of
Abdel El Abyad, a spokesman for the Egyptian Embassy in Washington.
a decision on making the investigation a criminal probe cannot be
made until Egyptian investigators examine all the flight data, he
said, which could take days, weeks, or even months.
</P>
<P>
   The first real test of America's patience and Egypt's
willingness to concede that something other than mechanical failure
caused the crash, which the NTSB had initially ruled out, may come
as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   US officials say that by then, Egyptian investigators should
have finished transcribing data from the cockpit voice recorder and
matching it with the flight data recorder. But those same officials
also don't rule out that Egypt may want to take their examination a
step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to go as far as we need to go with Egypt,'' a
State Department official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of the conflict within the US government, the law
enforcement official said, ``Politics shouldn't play a role in
solving tragic events like this. The only thing that everyone
should be interested in is finding the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflicts between the two countries' approach was also
apparent Wednesday, when a senior Egyptian Transportation Ministry
official said that an explosion caused the crash, in which all 217
people aboard were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario differs sharply with the preliminary assessment
of NTSB Chairman James Hall, who said early this week that data
from the aircraft's ``black boxes'' suggest that mechanical
problems or bad weather did not cause the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's remarks by General Issam Ahmed, who heads the
government's flight-training program at the ministry, marked the
first time any senior Egyptian official publicly said an explosion
was the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed, who previously headed the Transportation Ministry's plane
accidents committee, said the Egyptian experts in the United States
should concentrate on investigating the tail of the plane, which
``carries the mystery of the accident,'' the Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
   He said the cases carrying the flight data and cockpit voice
recorders, the ``black boxes'' in the plane's tail, were severely
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This confirms that the tail of the plane, where the two boxes
are located, was subjected to an explosion at the height of 33,000
feet. It was either an internal or external explosion,'' Ahmed, who
is not involved in investigating the Flight 990 crash, said in the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Such differences of interpretation have been evident since the
crash. In the United States, much has been made of the fact that
co-pilot Gamil El Batouty uttered the phrase ``I put my phrase in
God's hands.'' That phrase, combined such evidence as the shutting
off of the autopilot and the wild movements of the plane, have led
some to construct a scenario in which Batouty was saying a prayer
before deliberately putting the plane into a dive.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptians have angrily responded that the phrase is a common
saying among Arabs and has no special significance. They argue that
Americans have stereotyped Arabs as religious fanatics and rushed
to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Though NTSB Chairman Hall has said the crash might be result of
a ``deliberate act,'' he has noted the ``differences in cultural
interpretation'' over El Batouty's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of the crash, the NTSB was operating on two
levels _ informing Egyptian officials of their concern that the
accident was the result of deliberate pilot action, while Hall
discussed with Freeh the possibility of having the bureau take over
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   One high-ranking government source said the State Department's
concern is two-fold. On the one hand, the diplomats do not want to
see an erosion of relations with a key nation in the Middle East.
In addition, there is concern that fundamentalists in Egypt could
use the US investigation as a trigger to an attempt to unseat Hosni
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is trying hard to the Egyptians as much room and time
as they need to see the case the way we do,'' the government source
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, a spokesman for the National Security Council, said
Clinton is being kept informed of the investigation through his
National Security Adviser Samuel R. Berger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a very strategically important ally that
is cooperating fully in a very difficult investigation,'' Leavy
said of Egypt. ``It was their carrier, their pilot, and there are
the obvious diplomatic sensitivities that have to be taken into
account, but it's a far cry from an international crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdel El Abyad of the Egyptian Embassy in Washington said
Egyptian crash investigators had done nothing to interrupt the
probe. When asked about the involvement of the FBI, he said, ``The
leading role is played by the NTSB, and they are still playing that
role. I wouldn't inject the FBI in this at all.''
</P>
<P>
   While control of the inquiry remains in flux, evidence continues
to be collected. According to NTSB spokesman Jamie Finch, the FBI
is still working with crash investigators, and ``we're just
maintaining the evidence as it needs to be properly maintained
until a final decison is made on the status of the type of
investigation it will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COKE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      11-24 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE REJECTS COCA-COLA'S BID FOR ORANGINA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a two-year struggle with French regulators, the Coca-Cola
Co.'s bid to buy the Orangina soft-drink brand from Pernod Ricard
SA was rejected Wednesday for the second time, and a spokesman for
Coca-Cola said the company regarded the decision as final.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement from the French government came as a surprise
because Coca-Cola had carefully reconstructed its original offer to
satisfy officials of the competition council, who had turned the
deal down in September of last year. The government's concern was
that if Coke bought Orangina, it would control too much of the
distribution network in France that other soft-drink makers use.
Among the companies that might have been affected is Pepsico, which
had lodged a complaint with the government.
</P>
<P>
   The French finance minister, Christian Sautter, said the terms
of the revised $733 million bid, in which Coca-Cola offered to
exclude the distribution of Orangina in restaurants and other
public places, did not do enough to allay concerns about market
dominance. ``The modifications of Coca-Cola's bid were not judged
sufficient to meet all the guarantees needed in terms of
competition,'' he said in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement provided by a spokesman in Paris, Thierry
Jacquillat, president of Pernod Ricard, said: ``We share the
disappointment of the entire staff of the Orangina company. This
decision deprives them of legitimate ambitions and considerable
means of development on the global market, and it is detrimental to
the national economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pernod Ricard must now seek a new buyer for Orangina, which it
has said many times it wants to sell in order to concentrate on its
other businesses, which include wine and spirits as well as fruit
processing. A Pepsico spokesman, Jeff Brown, refused to say whether
the company would try to buy it, although he did applaud the French
government for having ``again established itself as one of the
foremost defenders of fair competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decision will help preserve choice and fair pricing
for French consumers,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Coca-Cola said the company accepted the
decision. ``We're disappointed that the ministry has rejected the
sale of Orangina, but we respect the government's final decision,''
said the spokesman, Rob Baskin. ``We would have preferred a
different outcome, but the minister's decision does not diminish
our commitment to French consumers and our core French business.''
</P>
<P>
   Several industry experts noted that in the time that had elapsed
since December 1997, when Coca-Cola's chairman and chief executive,
M. Douglas Ivester, announced the Orangina acquisition for about
$780 million, Coca-Cola has made other acquisitions that seem like
better bargains. In particular, the purchase of the Cadbury
Schweppes brands in most of the world outside the United States,
for $1.1 billion, added far more volume to the Coca-Cola system
than the Orangina deal would have. Orangina would have represented
about 55 million cases a year; the Cadbury purchase accounts for
about 400 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice for Coke to complete this
transaction,'' said John D. Sicher, editor of Beverage Digest, a
trade newsletter. ``But losing it is no big deal, by a long shot.
The Cadbury deal is a lot bigger and a lot more consistent with
Coke's strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the loss of Orangina was seen by one analyst as a blow to
the image of Coca-Cola and its chairman, as well as to plans to
expand Coca-Cola's influence in France, which has one of the lowest
per-capita consumptions of Coke in Europe. ``The curse on the
Continent continues,'' said Jennifer Solomon, a beverage analyst
for Salomon Smith Barney, referring to what has been a difficult
year for Coca-Cola in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A huge recall in June cost the company and its bottler,
Coca-Cola Enterprises, more than $100 million in revenue. Coca-Cola
is also spending heavily on marketing to rebuild its reputation
with consumers. There have also been problems with European
Commission regulators that eroded part of the Cadbury deal, and
there are continuing investigations of Coca-Cola's dealings in
Italy, Germany and other parts of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years is a long time for investors to wait for something
to happen,'' Ms. Solomon said, noting that many investors had
stopped worrying about whether the Orangina purchase would be
completed. ``But it's one more frustration for Ivester.'' Ivester
announced the deal barely two months after taking over the top job
from Roberto Goizueta, who died of cancer in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, with more than $700 million now freed up,
Coca-Cola may resume its share buyback program, said another
beverage analyst, Andrew J. Conway of Morgan Stanley. ``The French
competitive council's decision implies that Coke won't be able to
significantly expand its brand in the next five years there,'' he
said. ``But this opens up more share repurchase opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola halted the share buyback program earlier this year
after credit agencies expressed worry about the company's profits
in light of its other acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's earnings have declined since last summer, when
economic crises around the world and other issues slowed the
company's growth. After a sharp selloff this fall, its shares have
risen drastically over the last week after announcements of much
higher concentrate prices at both Coca-Cola and Pepsico. The stock
has also been helped by a Merrill Lynch analyst's report that
predicted impressive earnings growth next year. Shares of Coca-Cola
rose $1.25 Wednesday, to $67.9375.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 1959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
