<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH ERRED IN NBC REMARKS, SAYS ASSOCIATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   News Corp. chairman Rupert Murdoch's suggestion that NBC had
been offered for sale to Time Warner was ``a bit of a mistake,'' an
executive close to Murdoch said Wednesday. The executive also
sought to counter any criticism that Murdoch, with his remarks, had
been seeking to affect the Time Warner stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the executive said, Murdoch had simply reacted to a
television interviewer's unexpected question by repeating reports
he had heard about Time Warner vice chairman Ted Turner's interest
in acquiring NBC from General Electric. ``Rupert misspoke,'' said
the executive, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's comments came Tuesday evening, after the close of the
stock market, on a financial news program on the Fox News cable
channel, which his company owns. He was responding to a question
about whether he was interested in buying NBC. He said that General
Electric had already offered NBC's television operations to Time
Warner for $25 billion and that some Time Warner board members were
very interested in the deal while others were strongly opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Both NBC and Time Warner reacted with unusually rapid and
adamant denials. Within hours, representatives of both Time Warner
and GE issued strong statements. GE spokeswoman Beth Comstock said,
``We don't usually comment on the musings of others, but this is
flat-out denial.'' Beyond dismissing Murdoch's remarks as musings,
Ms. Comstock's specific denial carried unusual weight because GE
and NBC routinely respond to questions of the possible sale of the
network with a pro forma response: ``We don't comment on rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal reason for the caution is that the companies could
face sanctions by the Securities and Exchange Commission if they
deny such talks but are in fact discussing a sale. With both Time
Warner and GE on record with formal denials, any such deal between
them could not now legally be in the works.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Initially, some executives at Time Warner had speculated about
Murdoch's motives for making the remarks about the sale by
questioning whether he was trying to undermine the company's stock
price. That price had already been negatively affected this week
after a media analyst, Jessica Reif-Cohen of Merrill Lynch,
downgraded her evaluation of the company from a buy to an
accumulate rating. Wednesday, Time Warner shares gained $3.1875,
closing at $62.875.
</P>
<P>
   The executive close to Murdoch said Wednesday that this was not
at all his intention. ``There was no grand scheme,'' the executive
said. ``Rupert is an executive who is very much in the flow of
information. He has heard that Ted Turner is pushing Time Warner to
buy NBC.'' The executive noted, as did many other executives
Wednesday, that Murdoch has had a longstanding personal feud with
Turner.
</P>
<P>
   One other executive familiar with Time Warner's corporate
strategy confirmed that ``some executives in the company are
extremely interested in seeing if something could be done with NBC,
but nothing is going on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring NBC would entail enormous complications for Time
Warner. It would create a company with two broadcast networks _ NBC
and WB _ as well as a company with cable systems in the same cities
as television stations (in New York, for example, NBC owns Channel
4 and Time Warner owns most of the cable systems). Both of those
cross-ownership situations are barred by the Federal Communications
Commission, though media companies are lobbying to have the rules
changed.
</P>
</TEXT>
