<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEFT OF A YOUNG SUPERSTAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There are 16 green-and-white championship banners
hanging from the rafters of the huge house. The first one was
raised in 1957. The last one found its place in 1986. The 17th
banner, which would have been earned last June, was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. The Celtics had a title stolen from them one
Sunday afternoon two years ago in New Jersey. They were betrayed by
a plastic ball in a bin. They wanted the ball to bounce left and it
went right. In those few inches, the Celtics and their fans would
say goodbye and hello to players that they never would have said
hello or goodbye to if the larceny hadn't occurred. You've heard of
being a year or two away from a title? The Celtics were an inch or
two away.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the worst news: In those few seconds, the Celtics
had their 17th championship delayed by, at least, one year. They
would have won it last season, not the San Antonio Spurs, if their
pockets hadn't been picked. Even the main character in our play,
Tim Duncan, understands the details of the robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to Boston,'' Duncan said Wednesday. ``I
had articles pinned up in my dorm room. Everyone said the Celtics
were going to be the worst team and that they would pick me first.
I had people in Boston trying to find a place for me to live.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics were the worst team in the East. They won 15 games,
only one of them in their division and finished a staggering 46
games out of first place. Duncan probably had his bags packed
before watching the 1997 lottery on television. His life changed
when he sat in front of his TV and, ``I saw that the Celtics got
(draft picks) 3 and 6. I was thinking, `Oh (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only one thinking that. Another character in our
play, M.L. Carr, was the Celtics' representative that afternoon in
Secaucus, N.J. I watched Carr's reaction when the picks were
announced and, to this day, I have never seen a man of color lose
his color as fast as Carr did. He didn't even look real as he sat
there. He appeared to be a life-sized portrait with an anguished
half-smile painted on his face (that day, ``M.L.'' could have stood
for ``Mona Lisa'').
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and the Spurs played the Celtics Wednesday night at the
FleetCenter. The 7-foot forward-center is averaging 21 points, 14
rebounds, and 3.3 assists. He is 23 years old. There are only two
players in the league _ Kevin Garnett and Shaquille O'Neal _ who
can even think about shutting him down. He and a remixed band of
Celtics certainly would have won a title last season. This will be
detailed in our play.
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Tim, 'Toine, and Rick: A Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Key Characters: Tim Duncan (a young superstar), Antoine Walker,
Rick Pitino, The Renounced Free Agents, Kenny Anderson, Walter
McCarty, Tom Heinsohn, Chauncey Billups, David Wesley, Tony Battie,
Travis Knight, Chris Mills, Andrew DeClercq, Paul Pierce, Dino
Radja, Eric Williams, a pro-Celtics plastic ball.
</P>
<P>
   Potential Understudies: Ruben Patterson, Michael Dickerson,
Bryce Drew, Matt Harpring, Pat Garrity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We join the play in progress. The pro-Celtics plastic ball has
just bounced left instead of right. Boston has the first and sixth
picks in the NBA draft. Carr surprises no one and announces that
the Celtics will draft Duncan No.1. Sources confirm that the
Celtics have reached an agreement with Bill Russell. The legendary
center has one assignment: tutor Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   June and July are heavy personnel times for new Celtics coach
Pitino. He knows he will have Duncan as his center and Antoine
Walker at either small or power forward. He has a roster loaded
with 10 free agents, most of them marginal pros. But he does have a
veteran free agent swingman in Rick Fox and a good free agent point
guard in Wesley.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino knows that Fox and Wesley are both solid in the locker
room, and you need that for a young team. He also understands that
both are above-average defensive players. He plans to draft Ron
Mercer with the sixth pick. A player such as Mercer _ one who can
consistently make 17-foot jumpers _ makes Duncan even more
dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggest that Pitino will renounce all of his free agents to
sign Lakers free agent center Travis Knight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitino: Why would I sign Travis Knight? I've got Tim Duncan.
Next thing you know, someone will say I want to sign Tyus Edney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The coach signs Fox and Wesley and renounces the remaining eight
free agents to create salary-cap room. The one man he regrets
cutting is Marty Conlon. He and owner Paul Gaston agree to buy out
the contract of Radja, who does not fit in the team's plans. With
additional cap space, the Celtics sign Warriors free agent DeClercq
to back up Duncan. If the Celtics can get 12-17 minutes per game
out of him, they will be happy.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone can see it: The Celtics are definitely going to make
the playoffs in 1997-98. They made great decisions in the draft.
They passed on Colorado guard Billups and Texas Tech forward Battie
so they could take Mercer. They laughed at Mills' agent, Arn
Tellem, when he suggested that they sign his client to a seven-year
contract worth more than $35 million. They hung up on the Denver
Nuggets when the team asked about Eric Williams . . . for a
second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the season, the Celtics wondered why Trail Blazers
guard Anderson did not report to the Raptors when he was traded
there. They teased broadcaster Heinsohn about his special
relationship with Knicks forward McCarty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heinsohn: I love Walter!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics won 43 games and made the playoffs. The only
negative thing about that is they watched a fine player from the
University of Kansas, forward Pierce, taken by the Nets (who won 36
games and had the 10th pick) in the 1998 draft. The Celtics,
instead of drafting from among guards Dickerson and Drew and
forwards Harpring and Garrity, traded out of the first round. They
moved Greg Minor's contract in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Their 1998-99 lineup: Wesley and Mercer in the backcourt, Duncan
at center, and Fox and Walker at forward. Bench: Dana Barros,
Williams, DeClercq, Adrian Griffin (why not?), Dee Brown, Patterson
(free-agent signee), and Pervis Ellison.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998-99 Spur starters: Avery Johnson and Mario Elie at
guard, David Robinson at center, and forwards Duncan and Sean
Elliott. Top Reserves: Antonio Daniels, Steve Kerr, Malik Rose, Wil
Perdue, Jerome Kersey . . .
</P>
<P>
   There was no Michael Jordan last season. There was no one in the
playoffs who could stop Duncan. As he showed Wednesday night, most
people cannot stop him. He would have won a title in Boston if the
team had not been robbed in the New Jersey daylight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
