<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-ART     11-24 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., N.J.)  
 SPORTS COLUMN: WITH THANKS FROM LeSHON JOHNSON  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, he had two young children to preoccupy his thoughts
and his wife to assist him in keeping his faith. Thanksgiving was
spent quietly, pensively, in his Jersey City, N.J., apartment,
supposedly a convenient ride to where he was receiving treatment
for the cancer that so rudely had rerouted his life.
</P>
<P>
   LeShon Johnson was not familiar with New Jersey. He barely knew
the Giants. The traffic and the tunnel and the cacophony that
awaited him on the Manhattan end were really the environment he
found forbidding, and strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord knows I wouldn't drive in the city,'' Johnson said
recently. ``Even though I hadn't played a down for them, the Giants
were nice enough to send a car.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in the inevitable crawl of crosstown traffic, during
those frightening collisions with mortality's terms, that Johnson
found himself experiencing cravings for the rural Oklahoma
countryside he once zealously swore was no longer home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never coming back to a small town,'' he recalls saying
when he left Haskell, Okla., for junior college.
</P>
<P>
   In those dark days of chemotherapy for non-Hodgkin's lymphoma,
when his weight was down and his hair was gone, a town of 2,200
people suddenly was the most inviting place on the face of the
earth. Haskell, without a stoplight or stop sign, was where traffic
flowed like the adjacent Arkansas River. It was where LeShon
Johnson had carried the football to statewide prominence, where he
had graduated in his high school's largest-ever class, 53 students.
It was where life once felt like an open road.
</P>
<P>
   It was where a call to the Chamber of Commerce was answered
Wednesday by Rocky Purdom, at his town convenience store. ``Oh, we
don't really have an office,'' Purdom said. ``We just set it up so
that if anyone calls, it'll be to a place where the phone is
manned.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, of course he knew LeShon Johnson, the way he knew most
everyone in the rural hamlet that is 35 miles south of Tulsa. As a
matter of fact, LeShon's cousin, Chris, was the current talk of the
town, what with Haskell High School still alive in the state
football tournament and Chris Johnson 33 yards short of 5,000 for
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Chris, Purdom said, runs with the same abandon as LeShon, son of
Luther, one of the country's most successful black ranchers. In
addition to raising horses on his Five Bar Ranch, Luther Johnson
had been a professional bull rider. LeShon, one of three children,
began riding at the age of 8, competing in rodeos until he was 17.
</P>
<P>
   Running a football, riding a bull. These were trade hazards that
could never seem as perilous as those interminable journeys across
the Hudson, the car creeping toward the Cornell Medical Center at
New York Hospital for another round of radiation, another drain on
the body that no longer was as sturdy as a bull's.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's cancer was diagnosed in May 1998, the result of a
minicamp physical after he had signed with the Giants as a veteran
free agent. An X-ray detected the malignancy, in his chest. He was
27 years old, married all of eight days to his college sweetheart,
Nalani.
</P>
<P>
   By last Thanksgiving, Johnson was nearing the end of his seven
chemotherapy treatments. He didn't know if he would play football
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know where I was headed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He just knew he didn't want to go for any more rides to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   By February, doctors were giving him a clean bill of health. By
July, he was back on the field, if not altogether physically whole.
His recuperating muscles still need massages many nights from his
wife. His season, in which he has averaged roughly 2.5 yards a
carry, has been less a revelation than he originally hoped. Yet how
can he voice frustration?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Thanksgiving,'' he said, ``and when I look back to where
I was at this time last year, I know I have so much to be thankful
for.''
</P>
<P>
   At this time last year, he didn't know any Giants well enough to
ask over for a home-cooked meal. This year, he has extended
invitations to a few. This year, regardless of where football may
yet take him, he has a far better idea of where he is headed.
</P>
<P>
   With his next examination set for Dec. 5, Johnson is starting to
look down the distant road. He has begun the process of building a
home on the outskirts of Haskell. That is where he wants to raise
Kaleo, 5, and Klayton, 2. That is where he sees his hopes, his
dreams. That is where he imagines giving future thanks, for many
more years of serenity and life.
</P>
</TEXT>
