<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0741 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BONFIRE-THEORIES-COX     11-24 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-THEORIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Runs with BONFIRE
 &HT;    Cause of bonfire collapse still uncertain
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Imagine shoving one end of a yardstick
into the ground and then pushing sideways on the other end. Before
long, the yardstick will snap.
</P>
<P>
   The same forces might explain how a giant woodpile collapsed at
Texas A&AMP;M University last week, according to engineers in Texas and
around the nation. The engineers, who are not involved in
investigations into the collapse, said in interviews that it was
too early and information was too sketchy to reach any firm
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   But based on details that have emerged, they say, one likely
scenario is that some of the logs making up the teepee-like
structure shifted. That, in turn, could have caused lateral
pressure that snapped the 100-foot-long center pole of
pressure-treated pine, bringing down the entire structure.
</P>
<P>
   This theory seems consistent with the sequence of events
described by many students working on the bonfire, which was
intended to be burned tonight before Friday's football game between
Texas A&AMP;M and the University of Texas. The students said they
noticed a shift in the load, followed by a loud crack and the
collapse of the woodpile. Twelve people were killed, and 27 others
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The woodpile, which was 40 to 45 feet tall at the time it
collapsed, consisted of four cake-style layers of logs lashed to
each other and leaning against the center pole. The center pole,
which was made of two logs spliced together, broke in at least two
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is balancing the load,'' said Hal Watson Jr., a
professor of mechanical engineering at Southern Methodist
University who has testified many times in court cases involving
accident reconstruction. ``It was evident from aerial helicopter
views that the center pole did snap somewhere close to its base.
That, more than likely, plus an unbalanced load, was the reason it
fell over.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible that an unbalanced load alone caused the
woodpile to collapse and that the fracturing of the center pole was
a result of the collapse and not an initiating factor, said William
Bulleit, a professor of civil engineering at Michigan Technological
University and a specialist in structural and wood engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The load could have become unbalanced in myriad ways, Bulleit
said. A gap in the layers of logs could have allowed one or more to
shift and the other logs followed suit. Logs might not have been
added evenly, causing the woodpile to lean to one side. Or logs
might have started to slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or it could be that one of the layers shifted enough to break
the center pole, and that caused other layers to come down,''
Bulleit said. ``Or perhaps the center pole didn't break at first
but deformed, allowing a layer of logs to shift, and then the pole
broke. You could probably dream up possibilities all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   Still another possibility is that the center pole had a weakness
or defect in it. An internal flaw would not be detectable without
special nondestructive testing.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a structure of this type is a complex system, with the
strength of the wood, the strength of connections and the design
all figuring into its stability, said Franz-Josef Ulm, a professor
of civil engineering at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Accident investigators ought to be able to pinpoint a weak link by
running various simulations on a computerized model, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One focus of inquiry undoubtedly will be whether a shift in the
woodpile was sufficient to produce what engineers call a ``bending
moment.'' That is the technical term for sideways pressure causing
the center pole to snap, much like the hypothetical yardstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound like a very stable structure,'' said James
Ricles, an associate professor of civil engineering and a
specialist in structures at Lehigh University in Bethlehem, Pa. ``I
don't know if I would stand on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he was horrified at the lack of safety precautions
for construction of the bonfire, with scores of students atop it at
one time. ``Having them crawl all over the structure like they were
_ I think that was an accident waiting to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How could basic engineering and safety principles possibly be
compromised at an institution known for top-flight engineering
faculty and programs?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think their engineering people were that much
involved with it,'' Watson said. ``It was an Aggie tradition. I
think the tradition overpowered any strict control.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
