<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0742 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BONFIRE25-COX     11-24 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas bonfire: Students tales consistent
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer and Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION _ Eric Etheridge climbed off the huge pile of
logs, looked up and noticed a slight tilt. Derek Woodley, hanging
from the centerpole and working on the fourth level, felt his swing
dip suddenly. Both heard a deafening crack, and the 90th Aggie
Bonfire fell in a heap, killing 12 people and injuring 27.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a week later, no one can say for sure why. However,
interviews conducted by the American-Statesman with a dozen
students who worked on the bonfire early Nov. 18, including
Etheridge and Woodley, reveal a number of consistencies:
</P>
<P>
   Students from ground level to the stack's peak say the entire
structure shifted and swayed mere seconds before the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, several students sitting in harnesses hanging
from the center pole say, they felt their swings dip suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the loud crack of splitting timber.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, a task force appointed by the university
will investigate the collapse and issue a report by March 31. In
the meantime, university officials caution against jumping to
conclusions, including one offered by a former A&AMP;M professor who
says the bonfire likely collapsed because students failed to follow
engineering safety procedures he developed in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas A&AMP;M welcomes any and all individuals who have the
expertise and background to offer substantive opinions about what
may have happened to cause this tragic accident,'' the university
press office said in a statement Wednesday. ``It is way too early
to know what factor or factors contributed to this accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Among students present when the stacks crashed to the ground at
2:40 a.m. last Thursday, a few theories on what caused the collapse
have developed: a weak center pole, loose wiring a lopsided stack,
unstable soil. But they concede their explanations are guesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two seconds before it fell, it kind of sank, like the center
pole might have leaned,'' said Woodley, who is from Georgetown.
``The center pole shifted somehow.'' Woodley suffered several
broken bones, cuts and bruises in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, freshman Rachael Hines, 18, of Katy, noticed the
stack shift as she wired logs into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The logs started to move, so I looked up to my swing man to
tell him to stop the log from moving, and then I realized it wasn't
just my log moving,'' Hines said.
</P>
<P>
   Etheridge, an 18-year-old freshman from Richardson, had just
climbed off the stack when he noticed something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking it was leaning a little and right as I
ended that thought, it fell over,'' he said. ``It looked like it
cracked on the top half, right above the first stack. That part
started to go over to the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Brittny Allison, a sophomore, was hanging in a swing waiting for
another log to wire to the second stack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was staring at the log in front of me when it suddenly
looked like it was moving,'' Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   She looked up and saw the logs on the third and fourth stack
starting to lean before toppling away from her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Oh God! It's falling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her swing tethered to the center pole, Allison was jerked onto
the top of the collapsing pile.
</P>
<P>
   A log fell onto her left arm and her left foot was caught
between two logs. Yet somehow Allison escaped with only a scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wiggled out and crawled off the pile,'' Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the pile toppled, she had heard someone complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said, `Stack isn't tight enough,''' Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   No one else interviewed reported hearing those complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Grosse, a professor who headed A&AMP;M's construction science
department from 1992 to 1996 and who now works at Colorado State
University in Fort Collins, said he believes the accident may have
happened because students working on the bonfire ignored proven
safety measures he helped develop.
</P>
<P>
   Those design modifications called for driving logs into the
ground every 15 to 20 feet along the outside of the first level,
wrapping a steel cable around the two bottom stacks, and
interlocking logs between all levels.
</P>
<P>
   The system proved effective in 1994, when heavy rains softened
the ground beneath the unfinished stack, causing the structure to
tilt toward the ground but remain intact, Grosse said.
</P>
<P>
   Grosse said he served as an unofficial technical adviser to the
Red Pots _ the students in charge of building the bonfire _ for 13
years before leaving the university for a post at Colorado State.
His design changes were adopted in 1988, Grosse said. When he heard
of the bonfire collapse, Grosse wondered what could have gone
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a moment to study the photographs of the collapsed
structure and it raised some questions. Structurally, it was not
sound, and I think that led to the problems,'' Grosse said. ``It's
pretty obvious (the upgraded design plans) were not being
followed.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, one of the Red Pots gave a copy of the revised plans to
then-bonfire adviser Bill Kibler, now A&AMP;M's vice president of
student affairs, said Grosse. He criticized A&AMP;M officials for not
providing more guidance to the Red Pots and making sure they were
using the most up-to-date techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should have been somebody out there carrying the ball
and continuing it on, and it's pretty obvious there wasn't,''
Grosse said.
</P>
<P>
   If the three strengthening measures he recommended were not
used, the result would be too much stress on the center pole,
Grosse said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The center pole should be used primarily for attaching ropes
to and a guide to build the stacks by,'' he said. ``The center pole
cannot be expected to provide the structural integrity of the
bonfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Kibler, who was the official bonfire adviser from 1983 to 1992,
said he recalls receiving bonfire-related documents from a student
but does not remember whether those documents addressed the design
modifications Grosse mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware of the specific recommendations that were made.
I think all of those things will come out as a result of the
investigation the university has commissioned,'' Kibler said. A&AMP;M
administrators assumed each class of Red Pots had passed down their
construction diagrams to the next, Kibler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't someone external to the students who was assuring
that the precise techniques of this part or that part of the
bonfire were passed along,'' Kibler said. ``That was the
responsibility of the students.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysis of the photographs indicate that aside from the center
pole, no posts were driven into the ground and the steel wires were
not in place to hold the bottom two stacks together, Grosse said.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Thompson, the current bonfire adviser, partially disputed
Grosse's claim, a university spokeswoman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked to Mr. Thompson, who has spoken this morning
with some of the students most directly involved in the
construction of the bonfire this year. Our best information, based
on that feedback, indicates that what Larry Grosse described as
'should have happened' did happen,'' said Cynthia Lawson,. ``That
includes sinking the poles into the ground and interlocking the
layers. However, we obviously want to investigate this further,
just as we're doing with the many theories, suggestions and
speculations that have been forthcoming since the time of the
accident. Photographs and videos that are being collected should
help tell the real story.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts by the American-Statesman to interview the Red Pots in
charge of building the 1999 bonfire were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Robbins, a sophomore, said he attended the raising of
the center pole and helped with the beginning of the first stack.
</P>
<P>
   He did not see any of the first-stack logs buried in the ground
for added support.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be too hard,'' he said. ``All the first-stack logs
sit flat on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins also said the first two stacks were not surrounded by
large cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't make sense since we weren't done with the first
and second stacks,'' he said. But he agreed with university
officials who said there were interlocking logs between the bottom
two stacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want that to happen because it makes it stronger,''
Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Egenes, the head student medic in charge that night,
watched the stack crumble from just outside the construction zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like three picture frames; starting, half-way
down and then on the ground. A lot of dirt and dust was kicked up
at that point,'' he said. ``I knew right away that I needed other
help out there. At that point, there were so many people that were
hurt, we had to triage the patients and go through and determine
the priority patients. That's the saddest thing for an (emergency
technician) to do. You have to leave them and say, 'I'll be back
for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
