<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERINI-SHARES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERINI PLANS SALE OF $40 MILLION IN NEW SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE BUTTERFIELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking an infusion of capital after a string of heavy real
estate losses, Perini Corp. has signed a letter of intent to sell
new shares valued at $40 million to the Tutor Group.
</P>
<P>
   The investment group is headed by Ronald N. Tutor, who has
already invested $3 million in Perini and was named its chairman
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials stressed that the action _ a move that would
give Tutor a far bigger stake in the Framingham, Mass. construction
company _ is subject to, among other things, Perini's ability to
negotiate new bank credit agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Perini, which employs more than 2,000 workers and has commercial
construction projects worldwide, said Wednesday it has hired
Houlihan Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin as financial advisers. It has
authorized them to explore alternative ways to recapitalize, should
the Tutor negotiations break down.
</P>
<P>
   Perini needs an infusion of money to restore positive net worth,
company officals say, after being forced earlier this year to write
off $99.6 million in real estate holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also had setbacks in some of its construction
projects in past years, but officials say the core construction
business remains strong, with more than $1 billion in sales
annually. After several difficult years, the company has again
begun to post modest after-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has turned around,'' insists Robert Band, Perini's
chief financial officer. He said it has now shed all of its
troubled real estate and is concentrating solely on its
international construction business.
</P>
<P>
   He said the proposed recapitalization with Tutor Group was not a
step toward selling the company. ``I tend to call it an investment
at this point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has previously ruled out an outright sale, and
observers say it faces no liquidity crisis or interruption of work.
But the huge real estate loss has left it short of the capital it
needs to meet bank debt.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deal with Tutor would involved common and preferred
shares valued at a total of $40 million, with the common stock
valued at $4.25 a share. Although the company cautioned that it was
not a binding agreement, Perini will have to pay Tutor $750,000 if
it cuts a deal with a different group.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had little to say about the latest move by Perini to
get its house in order. ``This is way too tentative for us to
comment. It's contigent on a lot of other things happening,'' said
Walter J. Kirchberger, who follows Perini for PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Perini stock closed Wednesday at 3 7/8, up 3/8, on the American
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
