<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MANNESMANN-VODAPHONE-     11-24 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANNESMANN-VODAPHONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR FROM BATTLE OVER EUROPE'S PHONES, A HONG KONG TYCOON COUNTS HIS
BILLIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Germany, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Panama, Australia,
India and Israel)   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ As Mannesmann of Germany and the British company
Vodafone Airtouch roll out the heavy artillery for their bitter
takeover battle, there is already one undisputed victor: a Hong
Kong tycoon who is watching Europe's great corporate war from the
penthouse of a skyscraper half a world away.
</P>
<P>
   He is Li Ka-shing, the billionaire developer and chairman of the
Hong Kong conglomerate Hutchison Whampoa. With the closing of a
deal to sell its British mobile-phone operation, Orange PLC, to
Mannesmann, Li's company has become the largest single shareholder
in the German company.
</P>
<P>
   Li has made an enormous profit because of the Orange-Mannesmann
deal and could make more if Vodafone buys Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the latest of many shrewd moves for Li, 71, who
has amassed a $12 billion fortune since he came to this former
British colony in the 1940s as a penniless refugee from mainland
China.
</P>
<P>
   As Vodafone seeks to entice Mannesmann's shareholders with its
$127.7 billion hostile bid, analysts said the British company would
have to win over Hutchison, which in addition to its 10.1 percent
stake has a seat on Mannesmann's supervisory board. That will not
be easy, since Li said on Tuesday that he would back Mannesmann's
chief executive, Klaus Esser, in rebuffing Vodafone's advances.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and bankers noted, however, that Hutchison's loyalty
stemmed at least partly from a legal obligation to hold its shares
in Mannesmann for 18 months after the mobile-phone deal. Should
Vodafone further sweeten its offer, Mannesmann would likely feel
obliged to let Hutchison sell its shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been incredibly lucky,'' said Peter Milliken, an
analyst who follows Hutchison for DBS Securities here. ``But Li
Ka-shing isn't just a lucky guy. Some of it is foresight.''
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann paid $14 billion in cash and stock to buy Hutchison's
controlling stake in Orange _ a sky-high price that analysts said
was driven by Mannesmann's urge to protect itself from a predatory
Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   When Vodafone started its hostile bid for Mannesmann, the value
of Hutchison's shares soared 25 percent. If Mannesmann accepted the
current bid, Li would make more than a 40 percent return in barely
a month.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Vodafone has indicated that if it won control of
Mannesmann, it would spin off Orange to the German company's
existing shareholders. Although that move would be aimed at
mollifying British regulators, it would also leave Hutchison with a
stake in the same company it just sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``First they sold Orange at a huge premium,'' said an executive
close to Hutchison who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Now
they're getting a double-dip with the Vodafone bid for Mannesmann.
If Vodafone were to spin off Orange, it would be a triple-dip.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Li nor his lieutenants would comment beyond a statement
on Tuesday in which Hutchison said it viewed its stake in
Mannesmann as a long-term strategic investment. ``Jointly with
Orange, Mannesmann will be an outstanding company and better
positioned than Vodafone for the future opportunities in the
telecom sector,'' said Canning Fok, the managing director of
Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that reaction was not surprising. If Vodafone took
over Mannesmann, Hutchison's stake in the new company would be
diluted to 4.5 percent. Though that might be enough to secure a
board seat, Li would clearly not enjoy as much influence.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison cannot stand in the way of a takeover. Under
Mannesmann's bylaws, no single shareholder exercises more than 5
percent of the vote. Mannesmann's fate will be determined more by
Vodafone's next move _ it has declared it will not raise its bid _
than by the wishes of an Asian tycoon.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of Li's position, according to analysts, is that
regardless of the outcome, Hutchison will continue to be a player
in the global mobile-phone business. In addition to its interest in
Mannesmann, Hutchison controls cellular companies in Australia,
India and Israel. The company is also active in wireless in the
United States, through an investment in the VoiceStream Wireless
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, a city where nobody leaves home without a cellular
phone, Hutchison is the leading service provider, with 1.6 million
subscribers. The company also competes with the dominant local
phone company, Cable and Wireless HKT, in fixed-line telephone
service.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Hutchison announced a $1.2 billion joint venture with
Global Crossing Ltd., the operator of a worldwide fiber-optic
network, that will further expand its presence in its home market.
The new venture, to be called Hutchison Global Crossing, will build
a high-speed fiber-optic voice and data network. Global Crossing
will contribute $400 million in stock and $50 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a classic Hutchison deal,'' said Tim Dattels, the
head of investment banking in Asia for Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., which
advised the company. ``They've chosen their partners well.''
</P>
<P>
   Li took over Hutchison Whampoa in 1981, becoming the first
Chinese businessman to control a traditionally British trading
company in Hong Kong. The company's roots are in ports, and it now
runs container ports in Hong Kong, mainland canal. That last
franchise recently landed Hutchison in a tempest in Washington. The
Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, said the canal would fall under
Chinese influence after the United States departs in December
because Li had links to the Chinese Army.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have dismissed Lott's claims, though nobody
denies that Li has cultivated close ties to China's leaders. That
could come in handy in the aftermath of a landmark trade deal
between the United States and China. As part of the agreement,
Beijing has pledged to open its telecommunications market to
foreign companies. Few are better positioned than Hutchison
Whampoa.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reason Global Crossing was willing to pay so
much,'' Milliken said. ``They were paying for Li's connections _
and not just telephone connections.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
