<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CZECH-GYPSIES-ART-470     11-24 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-GYPSIES-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN REMOVES WALL DIVIDING GYPSIES AND CZECHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ A wall put up six weeks ago to separate
Gypsies from their Czech neighbors in a town in northern Bohemia
was torn down Wednesday, to the relief of an embarrassed Czech
government and foreigners who had suggested that racism might
thwart the country's bid to join the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The government, unable to prevent local authorities from
building the wall in the depressed industrial town of Usti nad
Labem, negotiated its removal after agreeing to give the city
government $286,000 to improve social conditions in the town.
</P>
<P>
   For the Gypsies and human rights activists, it was a Pyrrhic
victory: The city council announced it would use at least one-third
of the money to buy the houses of Czechs who refused to live next
to Gypsies. ``Now, it will be a real ghetto,'' said Tibor Bada, a
local Gypsy activist.
</P>
<P>
   The concrete barrier, 65 yards long and 6 feet high, was built
overnight on Oct. 13, with about 80 police officers present to
prevent any violence. It was supposed to separate Gypsy residents
from three houses owned by Czechs who had claimed that the Gypsies,
most of them rent defaulters who had been moved into substandard
municipal housing, produced disturbing amounts of noise and waste.
</P>
<P>
   Local authorities said the wall was intended to prevent Gypsy
children from coming to the street and playing in front of houses
owned by residents who wanted no contact with Gypsies. It quickly
became a symbol of racism and segregation in the Czech Republic and
of the new social divisions that have emerged in Europe in the
decade since the fall of the Berlin wall and the end of communist
rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy that this tragic symbol of separation
disappeared,'' the U.S. ambassador, John Shattuck, said in a radio
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Both President Vaclav Havel and Guenter Verheugen, the European
Union official overseeing efforts to enlarge the 15-nation economic
bloc, applauded the destruction of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Verheugen, who had indicated that the wall might impede the
Czechs' bid to enter the European Union, said the demolition would
``enhance the image of the Czech Republic and its human rights
record.'' He added that he hoped it would be followed by a dialogue
aimed at solving the social problems of Gypsies in the Czech
Republic, who call themselves Romany or Roma.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Gypsy community expressed scant hope of such a
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Ladislav Bily, the executive secretary of the Romany Board, said
the Czech government, ``when confronted face to face with racism,
has allowed itself to be dragged into a game played by the Usti
town hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Buying up family houses on the street will end any coexistence
of Gypsy and non-Gypsy neighbors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gypsies in the Czech Republic often complain about racial
discrimination and ask for asylum abroad.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last weekend seven Gypsies in a music band were injured when
they were attacked by skinheads in Ceske Budejovice, south of
Prague. Seventeen youths have been charged with racially motivated
violence and hooliganism and could face up to three years in jail
if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The band leader, Gejza Ladic, told the daily newspaper Pravo
that the group had written to the Canadian and British embassies in
Prague asking for asylum. Thousands of Gypsies in the Czech
Republic have sought asylum in Britain in recent months, usually
unsuccessfully, prompting the British government to threaten to
re-introduce visa requirements for Czechs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
