<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-THANKSGIVING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKSGIVING EPISODES NEEDN'T BE HALF-BAKED TURKEYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanksgiving episodes often fall flat because they're more
maudlin than the PaxTV prime-time lineup. Producers are feverishly
working to remedy that by encouraging writers to create
cutting-edge scripts. However, change comes slowly to the TV
industry, so the proposed Thanksgiving episodes outlined here
didn't make it this year. But stay tuned. There's always next year.
And the year after that. And the year after ...
</P>
<P>
   ``ER.'' The County General staff is stunned when Nurse Hathaway
gives birth to a 22-pound Butterball named Tommy. Dr. Weaver chides
Hathaway for not following a more healthful, free-range pregnancy.
Meanwhile, Dr. Carter falls in love with a young woman he is
treating for pecan-pie addiction. George Clooney makes a special
appearance when his character, Dr. Ross, is called in for a
pediatric consult on a case involving a little boy who accidentally
inhales his pet cranberry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging Amy.'' A custody battle gets ugly when a mother has to
choose between her daughter and her secret recipe for
sausage-and-raisin stuffing. Judge Amy resolves the matter by
recessing until after the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order.'' Detectives Lennie Briscoe and Ed Green happen
upon a mess of smashed pumpkins in Central Park. There are no
witnesses to the senseless gourdage, but a canvass of the area
uncovers a small-caliber food processor in a trash can near Sheep
Meadow. Fingerprints on the Cuisinart lead to the Hamptons and the
summertime home of Martha Stewart. During a vigorous interrogation
at Riker's Island, Stewart tearfully admits she doesn't always get
her pumpkin flan to come out right on the first try and has to go
through a lot of pumpkins. Assistant D.A. Jack McCoy decides to
prosecute her for fraud and conspiracy to commit froufrou. But
Stewart walks when the judge rules that the food processor is
inadmissible as evidence because police violated the trash can's
constitutional right to privacy and Stewart's confession can't be
used because anyone who would gold-leaf a doorknob has no
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing.'' President Josiah Bartlet issues the customary
pardon to the White House turkey, but on the way to the fowl
retirement home the turkey is brutally slain by a rogue band of
animatronic pigs unemployed since the filming of TNT's ``Animal
Farm.'' They claim that every pardoned turkey requires an increase
in the senseless slaughter of swine to facilitate production of
more honey-baked, spiral-cut hams. Bartlet defuses the situation by
outlawing the sale of ham guns in November and declaring the
chalupa an official Thanksgiving table alternative, provided Taco
Bell stops running those commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace.'' Grace is depressed during Thanksgiving dinner
because her chest is smaller than the turkey's. Will assures her
it's only because turkeys are corn-fed to enhance their appeal to
shoppers, and that a man would never be attracted to a woman simply
because she had her measurements enhanced. Grace doesn't buy it and
begins power-noshing corn niblets, which explains why the episode
is titled ``Maize in Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Waltons.'' The whole clan, minus those who are dead,
returns to the homestead for one last holiday gathering and is
startled to discover that a distant relative, Gym-Bag Walton, has
moved in and is using cheap Southern labor to manufacture Nike
footwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'' Giles attempts to embrace quaint
American customs by hosting his first Thanksgiving dinner. Things
go awry when the sage for the stuffing combines with the nutmeg for
the pumpkin pie, causing a chemical reaction that summons from the
netherworld a long-dormant demon/vamp of the kids' table named
Nomogravy. It can only be subdued if all the kids seated at kids'
tables in Sunnydale eat their white meat without benefit of
lubrication. Of course, this will cause the entire child population
to die of turkey-stuck-in-the-throat-itis. (Also, if a child whines
for a drop of gravy from the adult table, Nomogravy invades the
child's soul and disconnects the dessert reflex, replacing it with
a yearning for candied yams.) Buffy, Willow and Xander save the day
by luring Nomogravy to a dark alley with a plate of garlic mashed
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal.'' Ally dreams she is having sex in a cranberry
bog with a Massachusetts farmer. John Cage dreams he is having sex
in a Winnebago with a randy Pilgrim. The two dreams come together
in reality when Billy tells Georgia he wants to have sex with her
on Plymouth Rock, but only if she'll wear a buckskin bustier and
burlap thong. Meanwhile, Richard Fish goes out to a turkey farm
where he collapses from exhaustion after caressing 4,000 wattles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
