<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Thursday, November 25, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   ASBESTOS-GOVERNOR (Libby, Mont.) _ As a child, the governor of
Montana played in piles of asbestos-contaminated vermiculite ore
that some residents here say has caused death and disease. Now,
after the Post-Intelligencer last week documented dozens of deaths
related to the contamination, Gov. Marc Racicot is vowing to take
action.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   IMMUNE-DISEASE (Seattle) _ Kevin Parsons is a doctor who knows
what it's like be so sick you ask your wife to kiss you goodbye for
the last time, who knows what it's like to be told no one knows
what's wrong, who knows what it's like to be racing for a cure for
a disease that few people have and even fewer care about. He knows
these things because he's living them.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-THANKSGIVING (Undated) _ Thanksgiving episodes often fall
flat because they're more maudlin than the PaxTV prime-time lineup.
Producers are feverishly working to remedy that by encouraging
writers to create cutting-edge scripts. However, change comes
slowly to the TV industry, so the proposed Thanksgiving episodes
outlined here didn't make it this year. But stay tuned. There's
always next year.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
