<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0787 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-GEORGEWBUSH-TEX     11-24 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GEORGEWBUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE `DUB-YA' TELLS ALL _ THAT HE WANTS YOU TO KNOW
</HEADLINE>
 (for use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Charge to Keep
</P>
<P>
   By George W. Bush
</P>
<P>
   (ghostwritten by Karen Hughes)
</P>
<P>
   Memoir
</P>
<P>
   Morrow, $23
</P>
<P>
   Before evaluating a campaign-related autobiography, let's agree
on its purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jimmy Carter's ``Why Not the Best?'' and other engagingly
self-serving, ghostwritten ``memoirs'' before it, ``A Charge to
Keep'' is not meant to give interested readers the real lowdown on
its subject. ``A Charge to Keep'' was written in the name of _
although not by _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush to cement his high
standing with those who've already decided they want him to be the
next president.
</P>
<P>
   It is intended to seduce some fence-sitters who aren't quite
certain ``Dub-ya'' is qualified for the highest U.S. office, and _
perhaps most important _ to neutralize extreme Republican
conservatives who might otherwise sit out the 2000 election instead
of supporting Bush against Al Gore or Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, ``A Charge to Keep'' addresses devout
Christians who wonder about Bush's level of commitment to their
religious agenda. The first chapter immediately identifies one of
his life's ``defining moments'' _ a stirring sermon delivered just
before Bush's swearing-in for his second term as governor. Bush
also lists other inspiring sermons he has heard over the years.
</P>
<P>
   There are remembrances of loving family moments, excerpts from
Bush's inaugural address, some meditations on the importance of
raising kids right ... and we're scarcely a dozen pages into a book
Bush says he reluctantly wrote after deciding it would be wrong,
with so many other books about him being published, ``to let others
define me.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he's right about that. So far, the Bush biography
receiving the most attention, ``Fortunate Son'' by J.H. Hatfield,
claimed to reveal details of a Bush cocaine arrest in 1972. That
headline-grabbing charge was quickly discredited with news about
Hatfield's criminal past, which involved hiring a hit man in a
failed attempt to kill his boss. So who can blame Bush for wanting
to get his own sanitized, spin-friendly life story on bookstore
shelves?
</P>
<P>
   But ``A Charge to Keep'' suffers from typical campaign blurb
disease. Every word seems too carefully considered _ how much can
be said on any topic without inviting criticism? Did the governor
help pass a concealed-gun law vehemently opposed by gun-control
spokesmen? Well, there's a page or two about how Bush says that
responsible Texans ought to be able to carry arms for self-defense,
followed by another page insisting he wants some sort of generic
prosecution for those who tote guns for nefarious reasons. For
every opinion, there's a subsequent qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seems truly definite only when discussing his love for his
family _ wife, daughters, parents, in-laws, brothers, sisters,
cousins, friends who are as close as blood relatives ... and this
is comforting. Even Bush-detractors will tear up when reading about
the death of Bush's little sister from leukemia (he was 7, she was
almost 4). He obviously is someone capable of loving and being
loved in return. That's an important gift.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the political chapters are, as the Scots say, pap.
Who doesn't believe in good schools, fair taxes, respect between
races and honest government? Mickey Herskowitz, the well-known
journalist whose ghostwriting credits include books for Nolan Ryan,
Mickey Mantle and John Connally, says he quit/was fired from ``A
Charge to Keep'' when he insisted that there ought to be some
substance in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Bush replaced Herskowitz with communications director Karen
Hughes, who includes her own ``Reflections'' section that says Bush
insisted she skip some important campaign events to attend her
son's baseball games. (Herskowitz is thanked by Bush for ``his help
and work in getting the project started.'')
</P>
<P>
   To make certain that ``A Charge to Keep'' attracts no undue
criticism, Bush mentions in several places that all royalties
earned by the book will be donated to the Boy Scouts, Girl Scouts,
Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs of America and Girls, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   If you really want to learn about George W. Bush, ``A Charge to
Keep'' is interesting, but not enlightening. Several other Bush
biographies are being published now or will be in the next few
months. Bear in mind that the authors of these books also have
agendas. Some will want to be objective, some will want to take
cheap shots. ``A Charge to Keep'' is a reasonably well-presented
effort to protect whatever political territory George W. Bush has
already won.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
