<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMUNE-DISEASE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR HAS SPECIAL INCENTIVE TO FIND CURE FOR RARE DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Kevin Parsons is a doctor who knows what it's like be
so sick you ask your wife to kiss you goodbye for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Parsons is a doctor who knows what it's like to be told no
one knows what's wrong, even as your body weakens and your will
wavers.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Parsons is a doctor who knows what it's like to be racing
for a cure for a disease that few people have and even fewer care
about.
</P>
<P>
   He knows these things because he's living them.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, 46, has Lambert-Eaton Syndrome, an extremely rare
autoimmune disease that interrupts the transmission of signals
between nerves and muscles, causing crippling, sometimes fatal,
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people just lay in bed and die,'' said Parsons, 46, who
was diagnosed with the disease at age 37.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers don't know yet what triggers the disease, but
something causes the body to make antibodies to a protein on the
surface of nerve endings. The antibodies block the nerves from
releasing chemical messengers, called neurotransmitters, that
communicate with muscles to cause movement.
</P>
<P>
   The muscle weakness can be so profound, it's difficult to even
blink an eye. Or breathe.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of neurotransmitters across the neuromuscular junction
is like a firehose for most people, said Parsons. ``For me, it's
more like a drip.''
</P>
<P>
   Only about 300 people in the world have the disease. Parsons has
emerged as their leader, a man who not only knows what it feels
like to have Lambert-Eaton, but is trying to cure it as well.
Fourteen months ago, with the backing of Virginia Mason Medical
Research Center, he set up a research lab to investigate new
strategies for treating his own disease.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago Parsons never dreamed he would be making the
journey from doctor to patient to medical researcher, or that his
life would depend on it.
</P>
<P>
   Trained in internal medicine with a specialty in geriatrics, the
irony of his situation is not lost on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt like an old man for the last 10 years,'' he said. He
has been bedridden, used a wheelchair, a walker and a cane.
</P>
<P>
   Today he takes an experimental medication called 3,4
diaminopyradine (DAP), which temporarily restores his muscle
strength for a few hours at a time. Although he now walks without a
cane, he still has the careful gait of an old man with a fear of
falling. He can't run or jump, and has trouble with hills. He has
to take a pill an hour before getting out of bed, just to have
enough strength to sit up.
</P>
<P>
   The experience has changed the way he practices medicine, and
the way he views the role of a doctor. No longer able to maintain a
full-time patient load, he now spends most of his days teaching
himself immunology, communicating with other Lambert-Eaton patients
and searching for a cure.
</P>
<P>
   It's a quest that began with a routine flu.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons was newly married and working at a medical center in
Texas in 1983 when he and his wife, Hillary, came down with a
severe influenza. His wifegot better, but Parsons never quite
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to know whether the flu triggered the autoimmune
response that caused his disease, but Parsons suspects his body's
normal response to fighting an illness somehow got derailed, and
ended up turning on itself.
</P>
<P>
   With his health continuing to deteriorate, he and Hillary moved
to Southern California to be closer to his family. But the move
didn't help. At one point, he got a series of painful infections so
severe they put him in the hospital. It was during that
hospitalization that doctors discovered he had almost no white
cells _ the body's front-line defense against disease.
</P>
<P>
   The low white cell count indicated leukemia. But none of the
other tests they ran could detect any cancer in his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't figure out what was wrong with me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A former tennis player, who worked weights and loved to ski, it
was all Parsons could do to continue seeing his own patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be looking in people's ears and throats and everything
would go double,'' he said. His vertigo, another symptom of
Lambert-Eaton, got so severe, he would have to lie down to keep the
room from spinning.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually got so weak, he stopped taking stairs at work. He
brought a camping cot to his office and spent his lunch hours
sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   He lost 30 pounds off an already trim frame from vertigo-induced
vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't figure out what was wrong with me, either,'' he
said. ``I looked like a cancer patient, but I didn't have cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons relates his own medical history matter-of-factly, with a
clinician's detachment and a touch of the surgeon's gallows humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never that interested in rare diseases,'' he admits.
``Until I got one.''
</P>
<P>
   He chuckles and draws a sip from a slanted mug that says
``Nobody's Perfect.'' He glances at his watch, but not because he's
impatient. He's gauging how long before he has to pop the next
batch of little yellow pills that turbo charge his muscles enough
to get him through the day. The pills only work for two or three
hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others with Lambert-Eaton, it took Parsons about four
years before he finally got a diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching my husband die, literally before my eyes,''
Hillary Parsons said. ``I couldn't figure out what to do anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   One day in 1991, Kevin Parsons collapsed at the Veteran's
Administration Hospital where he was working. In desperation,
Hillary grabbed all his medical records from where she worked,
drove him to UCLA Medical Center emergency room and begged doctors
to admit him one more time.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up in the intensive care unit, too weak to turn over or
to cough. Hillary could see he was trying to tell her something.
She bent near to his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss me goodbye,'' he said. ``I'm dying.``
</P>
<P>
   ``I got really angry,'' she said. ``I said, `No you're not.
You're not leaving me with two small children.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, doctors finally diagnosed Lambert-Eaton
Syndrome using an electrical test that shocks the nerves and traces
the resulting impulses. It was the first case UCLA had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   But having a diagnosis didn't solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news was no one knew much about the disease, or how to
treat it. That plunged Parsons into a depression even more
debilitating than his illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just lying in bed all day,'' said Hillary Parsons. ``It
was like talking to a blank wall.
</P>
<P>
   One day she took him in a wheelchair to a busy mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' she told him. ``They're living. You're not. You may
have nothing left of a body, and you may be unhappy about that, but
your brain is still there, and it's a hell of a brain. You can help
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she gave him an ultimatum. If he didn't try to get out of
bed, she would put him in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very next day, he said, `Give me a walker,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got on the phone, calling around the world to speak to
anyone who had any insight into Lambert-Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he moved his family to Seattle to be treated by Dr.
John Ravits at Virginia Mason Medical Center, one of only a handful
of neurologists in the country who know anything about the disease.
Ravits helped him get started on DAP, the drug that allows him to
function.
</P>
<P>
   But DAP has drawbacks. At the high doses Parsons takes, it can
cause seizures. And because it wears off quickly, his energy levels
fluctuate like a roller coaster through the day.
</P>
<P>
   If there was ever going to be a better solution, Parsons figured
he was going to have to find it himself. Because there are so few
patients involved, few other scientists, let alone drug companies,
were attracted to the idea of doing research on Lambert-Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have such a rare disease, there's no money in drug
development for it,'' said Ravits. ``It leaves us (clinicians) high
and dry trying to treat patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons approached Jerry Nepom, director of Virginia Mason
Research Center, who gave him lab space and technical support to
get going.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Parsons is trying to find a way to block the binding
of the antibodies and restore normal communication between the
nerves and muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a large black box that I'm diving into alone,''
Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his research, Parsons also acts as the de facto
doctor for the small community of Lambert-Eaton patients he's
gathered through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He follows about 40 patients worldwide, including 30 in North
America and a handful in the Pacific Northwest. They call him day
and night. He talks to their personal physicians. He gives them
suggestions about medications, and strategies for coping with the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The patients also help him with his research, sending him their
blood to use in his experiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wonderful man,'' said Mildred Schiro, 67, who lives in
Illinois and has never met Parsons. But by phone and by e-mail, she
credits Parsons with giving her hope and getting her on medication
that has given her back some independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for him I probably wouldn't be here,'' she said.
Two years ago, she couldn't lift her head from her pillow, used a
wheelchair, and had to have assistance for daily living. Today, she
can walk a hallway by herself, crochet, take care of her animals
and bathe herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't appreciate those little things until you lose
them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons believes his experiences as a patient have made him a
better doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians really don't understand patients that well because
most have never been sick, especially with a chronic illness,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more interested now in their emotional states, in
educating them about the disease, and in (building) communication
between patients,'' he said. And he spends more time thinking about
ways to help restore patient functionality, even if it means
risking side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about what I would do if the patient were my father
rather than worrying about malpractice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he thinks about a cure, even on the days when he comes home
so exhausted, his wife has to beg him to not to push himself so
hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be smart,'' he said. ``But it's worth it to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
