<SLUG> BC-GORE-TRADE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR'S SUPPORT FOR GORE TESTED BY U.S. TRADE AGREEMENT WITH
CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 was sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE with STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration's trade agreement with
China, hailed by President Clinton as one of his greatest foreign
policy achievements, is complicating Vice President Al Gore's
efforts to energize labor behind his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With the Iowa presidential caucuses only two months away, the
Gore campaign is counting on his endorsement last month by the
AFL-CIO to translate into intensive door-to-door political work
there and in other early primary states.
</P>
<P>
   But the labor federation is focused more immediately on the
global trade talks set to begin next week in Seattle, where it
plans huge demonstrations against the World Trade Organization and
the Clinton administration's eagerness to strike pro-business trade
accords, like the deal with China.
</P>
<P>
   Labor is worried that lowering trade barriers _ a goal of the
Seattle talks _ will make U.S. products less competitive and
encourage businesses to build plants overseas to take advantage of
cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   In one early sign of potential problems for Gore, the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees has delayed
distributing pro-Gore literature to its hundreds of members in
factories because of anger toward the administration about the
China deal.
</P>
<P>
   The accelerated primary schedule is also putting pressure on
Gore, and all candidates, to hurriedly organize petition drives for
their slates of delegates. For example, in Pennsylvania, which just
set its primary for April 4, three weeks earlier than usual,
presidential candidates must file their delegate slates by Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That gives labor leaders, who have ready-made networks of people
who can circulate petitions for presidential delegates, just more
than a month to gather signatures. And compounding Gore's problem
in Pennsylvania, most political attention there is focused on the
U.S. Senate race in which 11 Democrats, five of them pro-labor, are
competing for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential race hasn't penetrated down to the rank and
file,'' said Rick Bloomingdale, treasurer of the Pennsylvania
AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   While two of the biggest AFL-CIO affiliates objected to the Gore
endorsement and are among the strongest voices opposing the
administration's steps on trade, even important Gore backers in
organized labor recognize that rank-and-file enthusiasm for the
vice president is in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a job and a half to educate our membership
what this is all about,'' John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO,
said. ``Of course he's got a problem. We all have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said very little about the sweeping agreement,
referring to it in passing on the day it was sealed as ``good news
indeed.'' And when the talks get underway in Seattle, he will be
campaigning in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But he has said that any trade pacts in a Gore administration
would include labor and environmental agreements, not as side deals
but as part of the pacts. And he has told union officials that he
in fact pushed labor's cause in the China negotiations, fighting
for an anti-dumping clause to block low-cost imports and calling on
all 135 member-nations of the world organization to meet certain
standards on matters such as wages, job safety and child labor.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not the only Democrat caught in a political bind over
the trade pact.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the Democratic leader in the House, who has
long been labor's champion against trade deals, is also aware of
the potential political benefits of this agreement to other
important constituencies, including business and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic and labor officials say that labor's active
opposition to the China agreement could stir up the same kind of
animus that prevailed in 1993 over the North American Free Trade
Agreement. It is gospel within organized labor that anger over
NAFTA suppressed union support for Democrats and helped the
Republicans to take the House for the first time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the fate of the House, with its slim Republican
majority, once again up for grabs, and with the opportunity to
become speaker in sight, Gephardt has taken a lower profile on the
China agreement than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   He has muffled his concerns, saying he is not sure how he will
vote when the matter, in the form of permanent normal
trade-relations status, comes before the House next year. But since
the deal is overwhelmingly supported by business and farmers, whose
financial contributions to the Democrats are vital to their success
next year, it is widely expected to pass. And Gephardt is trying to
make the best of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some in labor are very much concerned about China just coming
into the WTO and not having attention paid to labor and human
rights,'' Gephardt said. ``But we're in a different place than we
were in '93. Labor has begun to change its message and its stance
on trade. At one time, labor was protectionist; I don't believe
that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Some labor leaders seem willing to forgive both Gore and
Gephardt this time because they believe that electing Gore
president and giving Gephardt a majority in the House would serve
their longer-term purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Upton, a spokesman for the International Association of
Machinists, which abstained from endorsing Gore last month but did
so last weekend, said that his union had been persuaded by Gore's
support for core labor standards in trade agreements and that this
had outweighed his backing of China's entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade is one issue that we're going to disagree very strongly
about, but you have to look at other issues,'' Upton said. ``The
vice president was very adamant about the need for a larger
percentage of the U.S. workforce to be organized. He's been there
on fights against gutting Medicare and gutting OSHA and gutting
NLRB funding. So you have to look at the whole thing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Sweeney said that firing up the unions on Gore's behalf
would entail some work, he also said that the leaders planned to
``educate'' the membership on where the other candidates stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley says he's proud of his vote on NAFTA and would
support it again,'' Sweeney said of Gore's only rival for the
Democratic nomination. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, the leading Republican candidates, have given
their qualified endorsement to the China deal.
</P>
<P>
   In giving Gore a pass, the labor leaders are acquiescing in
Gore's effort to distance himself from the Clinton administration.
They intend to focus their anger at the global trade talks in
Seattle against Clinton and the World Trade Organization, not Gore.
``The vice president is much stronger on the issue of core labor
standards than the president is,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald McEntee, president of the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees, and chairman of the AFL-CIO's
political committee, also emphasized that Gore is vice president,
not president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of unions that are going to be really
upset, angry with everybody about this,'' McEntee said. ``But I
think most unions recognize the fact that this is Clinton's China
policy.'' He added: ``There has also been a very deliberate
disengagement on behalf of Gore in relations to the administration.
They have held a number of meetings with groups lately and they've
been telling Gore what's happening because he's intentionally
disengaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the question is less what labor leaders think than what
their membership does. ``In the end,'' said Greg Tarpinian,
president of the Labor Relations Association, a New York-based
consulting group to unions, ``what the top leadership does is one
thing _ the level of involvement and activities of the membership
is another. Anything that detracts from the unions' being able to
thoroughly say `This is our guy,' doesn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Some union officials say that Gore was sacrificed to Clinton's
desire to establish a strong foreign-policy legacy. They charge
that the president deliberately held off on the China deal until
after Gore won labor's endorsement and then took the endorsement as
a green light to proceed with the China negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   William Klinefelter, political director of the United
Steelworkers of America, said, ``Once again, Clinton has thought
only of his own legacy and has driven home a deal that didn't have
to be done at this point in time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
