<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0792 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ECON-REPORT-800&AMP;ADD-N     11-24 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY PROVING IT'S MORE ROBUST THAN ANTICIPATED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich)  (rk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long-running expansion of the American economy rolled into
autumn with even more momentum than had been thought, and is poised
to set a record for longevity with the arrival of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With employment, incomes, confidence and major stock-market
averages at or near peaks, the Commerce Department raised its
estimate Wednesday of economic growth from July to September to an
annual pace of 5.5 percent from 4.8 percent, surpassing nearly all
predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you not be thankful?'' asked James Glassman, chief
U.S. economist at Chase Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce report arrives with few signs of revived inflation.
``This is not something you expect to see this late in the game,''
Glassman said.
</P>
<P>
   But unless growth slows dramatically, analysts fear the Federal
Reserve could be forced to raise interest rates again and dampen
the expansion, which is now 8 and a half years old.
</P>
<P>
   One source of anxiety is the fact that inflation is creeping up
in the early stages of production, before products reach consumers.
But consumers are already seeing the highest oil prices since the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The latest consensus, according to Blue Chip Economic
Indicators, a monthly survey of economic forecasters, is for gross
domestic product to rise at a 4.1 percent pace in the current
quarter and by 3 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth is going to be well above historical averages,'' said
John M. Youngdahl, a senior economist at Goldman Sachs, which is
forecasting a 4.5 percent growth rate in the final three months of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   And stock prices keep rising. Wednesday, the technology-laden
Nasdaq market sailed to a new peak that puts it 56 percent ahead
for the year while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and the Dow Jones
industrial averages hovered near records.
</P>
<P>
   While the government's latest snapshot of the $8.9 trillion
economy covers only the third quarter, the growth rate and other
data for October and November were said to bode well for the
holiday shopping season. Consumer spending, which makes up about
two-thirds of overall economic activity, rose at a 4.6 percent
annual rate in the third quarter, initially reported as an increase
of 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The latest figures also advanced the likelihood that January
will become the 107th consecutive month of economic growth,
breaking the mark set between 1961 and 1969, when national output
was spurred by the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report Wednesday, the Labor Department said
first-time claims for unemployment insurance tumbled by 13,000 last
week, to 274,000, the third decline in the past five weeks. With
stores gearing up for Christmas, this was further evidence that
little or no slack has yet developed in the tautest labor market _
an unemployment rate of only 4.1 percent _ in a generation. On a
four-week moving average, initial claims have now totaled less than
300,000 for 18 straight weeks, the longest string since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer optimism is also high, with the University of
Michigan's confidence index climbing to 107.2 in November from
103.2 in October, according to subscribers to its polling service.
The index reflects consumers' positive assessment of current
economic conditions and their optimism about the future.
</P>
<P>
   What accounts for the extraordinary longevity of the 1990s
expansion, which has seemed little affected so far by the Federal
Reserve's three quarter-point increases in its interest-rate target
since midyear?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is accelerated productivity, which Chase economists
say is translating into compensation gains that exceed the
expectations of workers who had become accustomed to increases
averaging only about 1 percentage point more than inflation. This,
the bank said, fostered ``a general level of satisfaction'' that
has helped spur major increases in spending by consumers, which
grew at a 4.6 percent pace in the summer quarter, according to data
released Wednesday by the government, up from the initial estimate
of 4.3 percent in late October.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor, analysts said, was the foreign economic crisis
in Asia and Russia in the second half of 1998, which funneled
overseas capital to the safety of the American securities markets,
helping to keep interest rates low.
</P>
<P>
   This, in turn, contributed to the rise in American stock, bond
and home prices, all of which sustained confidence and buying
power.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty over possible disruptions from the so-called year
2000 computer problem has prompted some producers and consumers to
stockpile products, such as medicines, or to replace hardware or
software they otherwise might only have fixed. This accounts for at
least some of the surge in capital investment and inventories, the
latter one of the biggest factors in Wednesday's upward revision in
gross domestic product.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Economists said that while they could not quantify the year 2000
effect, they suggested it might turn out to be less than expected.
If so, there would presumably be little falloff in such demand
early next year, as some have feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to disentangle Y2K from other rebuilding'' of
depleted inventories, said Youngdahl of Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   The largest positive factor in the upward revision of the gross
domestic product was fewer imports, the Commerce Department report
also showed, while the biggest drag was less production of
equipment and software than first estimated.
</P>
<P>
   As for inflation, the price index for gross domestic purchases
edged up to 1.7 percent from 1.6 percent last month, which analysts
disregarded as trivial.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's report also included the government's first estimate
of corporate profits for the quarter, which on a current production
basis rose $8.2 billion in the summer after falling $6.5 billion in
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Current production cash flow, which adjusts for inventory
valuation and capital consumption, rose $16 billion following a
$6.7 billion decline in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Profits were reduced by about $8 billion because of the effects
of Hurricane Floyd, the department said, $6 billion of this in
benefits paid by insurance companies and $2 billion from uninsured
losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
