<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-TRAVEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWDS TAKE TO THE ROADS, SKY AND TABLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A record number of travelers jammed airports and highways across
the nation Wednesday to celebrate Thanksgiving with family and
friends. Despite the crowds, the day went off with no more than the
usual frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Snow in some Rocky Mountain states earlier in the week did not
help matters for motorists or airline passengers there, but it was
a godsend for ski resorts and for huddling around the fireplace
after Thursday's dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people here are staying in town to take advantage of
the snow,'' said Robyn Robinson, an architect in Aspen, Colo. But
she herself was scheduled to fly to Portland, Ore., Wednesday
afternoon to have Thanksgiving dinner at a friend's house, before
flying home Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Robinson can expect plenty of company on that return trip,
when a record 2.2 million people _ almost 1 million more passengers
than Wednesday _ are expected to fill just about every seat on
every flight.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the biggest share of the record 28 million vehicles
expected to be on the road this holiday will also be heading home.
</P>
<P>
   Police will also be out in force during the holiday, not just to
deal with speeders and drunk drivers, but also to ticket motorists
whose child passengers are not properly buckled up. The latter
campaign is part of a nationwide effort to enforce child passenger
and seat belt laws, which go unheeded an estimated 25 percent of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices are up 22.8 cents a gallon this holiday from the
same period last year. But the 3 percent fare increase announced by
American Airlines and Delta Air Lines late Tuesday night will have
little if any effect this holiday, since most passengers will have
booked their flights well in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a home-cooked turkey dinner with all the trimmings
for 10 people will average $33.83, 74 cents less than last year,
according to the annual survey by the American Farm Bureau
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   The 24,000 people expected at the Raul Jimenez Thanksgiving
Dinner in San Antonio on Thursday will not have to pay a cent.
Started 20 years ago by a local businessman to honor elderly
people, the dinner quickly became an annual event to feed anyone in
need. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 7,000 people that first year,'' said Alice Guerra, who
coordinated the event for the first 19 years, ``and now 5,000
volunteers, including lots of tourists to San Antonio, serve all
day long in the city's convention center. We just set the tables
and open the doors, no questions asked.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, there will be no sleeping-in Thursday morning for
Vincent Gravelli. A detective with the New York City Police
Department, Gravelli was scheduled to report for duty at 6 a.m.,
and to work the Macy's Thanksgiving Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the afternoon I'll go to Mom's house in Brooklyn,'' he
said, for a reunion with his sister and eight or nine relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he added, ``for a traditional Thanksgiving dinner with
a lot of food.''
</P>
</TEXT>
