<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN25-COX     11-24 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES
 &HT;    Fifth in a series
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paris potpourri ...
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) No matter how many times I visit, the Paris version of
the Statue of Liberty always takes me by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scale model of the gift France made to the United States
in 1885. You'll find it at Pont de Grenelle in the middle of the
River Seine, facing west toward New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Farther up the Seine is the Liberty Flame, a replica of the
statue's torch, given to France by the International Herald Tribune
after World War II, in memory of the fighters of the French
Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays it's better known for its location, directly above the
Right Bank entrance to the tunnel where Princess Diana was killed
in a car crash.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers and other remembrances are placed there daily by
visitors who mistake the Liberty Flame for a memorial to Diana.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) The French and the English will never be able to come
to an understanding, not as long as one speaks French and the
other, English.
</P>
<P>
   An English translation on one particular marker, recalling a
visit by one of England's future kings, identified him as the
``Prince of Whales.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) Phone cards can be tricky, and it's almost impossible
to find a pay phone that works with coins.
</P>
<P>
   I kept shoving the card into the appropriate slot, but to no
avail. Finally a nice young woman came to my aid.
</P>
<P>
   It seems you still need a coin - one to scratch off the gray
stripe on the back of the card to reveal a code number. You punch
in those numbers and the phone will work. C'est le French
technology.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) It's hard to find a bad meal in this town, but it's not
always easy to find a quick, satisfying snack.
</P>
<P>
   Four-course, sit-down dinners for $50 apiece are memorable.
Sometimes, though, you just want to grab a sandwich on the run. The
French, who take their food very seriously, will have none of it.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, MacDonald's and the French equivalent, Le
Quick. Better you should stop at a neighborhood pastry shop.
</P>
<P>
   Try a hot dog, French style - a weenie baked inside a small loaf
of bread and topped with melted cheese. Just don't go asking for
onions and chili. Dijon mustard, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) The French are as particular, and peculiar, about
fashion as they are food.
</P>
<P>
   I was there in late October, early November. For that time of
year, the weather should have been chilly and damp. Instead, Paris
was enjoying balmy days when you go about in your shirt sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Not the French. They were bundled up in coats, sweaters and
mufflers, their shoulders hunched as if against the cold as they
trudged the boulevards. Never mind what the thermometer says. They
seem to dress according to the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) Personally, I have no problem with the language, since
I seldom attempt it. Things usually work out OK anyway.
</P>
<P>
   I was riding in a cab. The sun was shining, and rain was
falling. The taxi driver explained that the French have an
expression to describe that kind of weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say-tan bot le femme,'' he recited, or something that sounded
like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The devil is beating his wife?'' I responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah!'' he exclaimed, taking both hands from the steering wheel
of the moving car and waving them about. ``You speak French!''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher of the Lufkin Daily News, is
senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108; email, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
