<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0806 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-THEATER-NOTHING-BUT-B     11-24 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTHING-BUT-BLUES-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
  
L.A. gets the `Blues'  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:   2.5 stars 
(Eds:  Not for use before Friday, Nov. 26) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By Reed Johnson 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spirit of the blues soars heavenward, but its flesh is
notoriously weak. It's music that hankers after transcendence, yet
revels in its raw humanity. The blues is about lust followed by
loss, repenting on Sunday morning after raising hell on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' the patchy and overly
earnest, but ultimately rewarding, new musical theater piece at the
Geffen Playhouse, those contradictions are strikingly personified
by co-author/performer Ron Taylor, a man of ample soulfulness and
ample corporeal substance.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's defining moment occurs in the second act, when he
throws himself into the raunchy standard ``I'm Your Hoochie Coochie
Man,'' one of 40 songs that make up the kinetic score. Filling
practically every inch of his vintage earth-toned suit, Taylor
gathers his heroic bulk, summons his rich, loamy baritone and
flashes the audience a look of evil playfulness. Then, savoring the
song's insinuating lyrics like a mouthful of good whiskey, he
extends an incantatory hand, as if beckoning us to plunge with him
into some lascivious musical underworld.
</P>
<P>
   This number is among the high points of a loosely structured
evening in which musical insight and narrative context come
together only about half the time. Even when the tunes are
beautifully sung, as they mostly are, the performers don't always
do an adequate job of selling them dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when everything clicks under Randal Myler's direction, the
show provides a kind of generous, uptempo lift now rare in the
American theater. In this season that celebrates gratitude, that's
a lot to be thankful for.
</P>
<P>
   Making generous use of sepia-toned rear-screen projections of
photos, drawings and other images, ``It Ain't Nothin' but the
Blues'' tells the story of how African American slaves cultivated a
sacred and profane singing style that gave rise to a uniquely
American art form.
</P>
<P>
   Dividing itself into two acts _ the first representing blues in
the Old South, the second its migratory manifestations in early
20th-century Chicago _ the show traces the evolution of blues from
African call-and-response chanting to the sweetly mournful
spirituals of slaves, sharecroppers and chain gang members and on
through the rise of jazz and the birth of rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   It's an inspiring story, told with great conviction by Taylor
and fellow performers Eloise Laws, Janiva Magness, Jewel Tompkins,
Billy Valentine, Mark Leroy Jackson and Dan Wheetman, a fine guitar
player who also is one of the show's five co-authors and its
musical director. A crack backup band keeps the sound shapely and
funky throughout.
</P>
<P>
   In telling this epic tale, however, ``It Ain't Nothin' but the
Blues'' frequently betrays its roots as a 45-minute touring revue
that was developed as part of Denver Center Theatre's outreach
program and later expanded into a Tony-nominated Broadway musical.
The authors demonstrate greater sophistication in their handling of
music than in the chatty between-numbers dialogue, which sometimes
has the feel of a well-meaning civics lesson.
</P>
<P>
   What the show does best is what the blues does best: tell a
story of everyday living through deceptively simple metaphors and
chord progressions. Listening to Valentine's gently resigned ``I
Can't Stop Lovin' You,'' Tompkins' smoky ``St. Louis Blues'' or the
company's rousing Act 1 gospel closer, ``Catch on Fire,'' you may
find yourself wondering why it took so long to bring this music to
Broadway in its pure form. Make that one less historical injustice
left to be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What: &LR;  ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Where: &LR;  The Geffen Playhouse, 10886 Le Conte Ave., Westwood
Village.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; When: &LR;  Through Jan. 2. Performances at 7:30 p.m. Tuesdays,
Wednesdays and Thursdays; 8 p.m. Fridays; 4 and 8:30 p.m.
Saturdays; 2 and 7 p.m. Sundays. Special 2 p.m. Wednesday matinees
Dec. 8, 22, 29. No performances Dec. 24, 25 and Jan. 1. New Year's
Eve performance at 8 p.m. Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tickets: &LR;  $20-$42; $10 student rush 15 minutes prior to
curtain. Call (310) 208-5454.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Our rating: &LR;  2.5 stars
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
