<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENTLE-GIANT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOY STORY' TOYS' STORY BEGINS WITH A GIANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Every action figure, toothbrush holder and
pencil topper tied to ``Toy Story 2'' has its own story, and many
of those stories took place in an obscure Southern California
facility called Gentle Giant Studios Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Although children will never see its name on ``Toy Story 2''
merchandise, Burbank-based Gentle Giant designed many of the Buzz
Lightyear and Woody products that will grace toy store shelves this
season. The 30-employee company sculpted about 200 ``Toy Story 2''
pieces in all, capping off the best year in its five-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably as big as anything we've ever done,'' said Karl
Meyer, founder, president and sole owner of Gentle Giant. ``Woody
and Buzz Lightyear are as recognizable to kids as any other
character out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer credited close ties to Pixar and the Walt Disney Co. for
its ``Toy Story 2'' contracts with industry powerhouses such as
Mattel and Thinkway Toys.
</P>
<P>
   Toy industry analyst Sean McGowan of New York-based Gerard
Klauer Mattison, estimated ``Toy Story 2'' merchandise will pull in
$100 million in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation is that `Toy Story 2' will be very big, very
quickly,'' he said. ``I think there is going to be a lot of
merchandise.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Toy Story 2'' contracts are no fluke for Gentle Giant, a
little company with a long list of clients.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently produced 250 pieces for ``Star Wars _
Episode One: The Phantom Menace,'' including action figures and
cup-toppers. Gentle Giant also sculpted many of the Pokemon toys
that fast-food chain Burger King Corp. hopes will help it close the
gap with McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Gentle Giant's work is at the core of the merchandising process,
giving toys the proportion and detail they need to be believable
replicas of the genuine article. The company's artists use both
traditional and high-tech tools, everything from clay sculpting to
advanced 3-D imaging that can make a perfect digital replica of a
human, or non-human, face.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-D technology used by Gentle Giant and others has boosted
the toy industry by creating a new generation of toys that actually
look like the characters they represent, said McGowan, the toy
industry analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Digital technology also speeds up the sculpting process. Instead
of creating clay models from scratch, Gentle Giant artists can
often import 3-D digital animation data and use that information to
change a character's pose or size.
</P>
<P>
   Then, using printers that produce 3-D models, artists can
quickly create prototypes that are later reproduced in wax and
hand-finished.
</P>
<P>
   John Barton, director of marketing for Thinkway Toys, said his
company chose Gentle Giant for ``Toy Story 2'' design work because
of the company's technological innovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saves an incredible amount of time,'' Barton said. ``On top
of that, you get a great looking product.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, a former aspiring rock star, said he made the move to
digital design and computer graphic work about 2{ years ago, ``when
I realized where the industry was headed.''
</P>
<P>
   The move paid off. Since starting the company in his garage five
years ago, Meyer has nabbed contracts for scores of projects with
about 150 different clients, including a contract for some products
tied to the original ``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   When he moved the operation from his garage to a Burbank office,
Meyer dubbed his company Gentle Giant, a name that he said reminded
him of Eric ``Hoss'' Cartwright from ``Bonanza,'' a television
series set in the old West.
</P>
<P>
   Hoss was the biggest and brawniest of the Cartwright brothers,
but he also was the most gentle, Meyer explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoss was able to bend a horseshoe in one hand and hold a
butterfly in the other,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Gentle Giant has a similar philosophy, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're able to handle hard things and still have finesse,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   True to its roots, the company remains self-contained, with its
own machine shop, paint room, and even a backyard basketball court.
Artists work on advanced computers or simple clay amid a forest of
action figures, posters and other toys.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its core toy prototype business, Gentle Giant
also does 3-D scanning, computer assisted drafting and video game
work, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough to keep the office humming, but Meyer said it
pales in comparison to the company's early years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first three years of business, I worked seven days a
weeks, 16 to 20 hours a day,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company just doubled, and then doubled, and then doubled
again,'' he said. ``It has been a blur.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
