<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 25
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Nov. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Nov. 9,
about prospective remedies being sought by the plaintiffs in the
Microsoft antitrust trial omitted a first name and title in some
editions for the government official who said he thought Microsoft
could live within the law without being broken up. He is Bill
Lockyer, the attorney general of California.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CASPIAN-PIPELINE-NYT (moved on Saturday, Nov. 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Nov. 20,
about an agreement to build a pipeline across Turkey to carry oil
from the Caspian Sea region included one country erroneously among
the signers and omitted one. Along with the United States,
Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan and Turkey, the list includes Georgia but
not Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LIVING-WAGE-LAWS-NYT (moved on Thursday, Nov. 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Nov. 18,
about ``living wage'' ordinances, which raise pay for low-wage
workers and grant them benefits, misstated the name of an
organization involved in the movement. It is the Industrial Areas
Foundation, not the Independent Areas Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
