<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0813 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ALVIN-AILEY-DANCE-$AD     11-24 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALVIN-AILEY-DANCE-$ADV28-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN WIDE THE DOORS: MEMORIES OF A MENTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 28)  
 (af)  
 Robert Tracy, a former ballet dancer, is the author of ``Goddess:
Martha Graham's Dancers Remember.''  
 By ROBERT TRACY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to believe that Judith Jamison is already celebrating
her 10th anniversary as artistic director of the Alvin Ailey
American Dance Theater. Next month, she will receive a Kennedy
Center Honor for her contribution to 20th-century dance. At the
same time, working within the Ailey tradition, Ms. Jamison has
envisioned the direction the company will take in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to constantly feed the repertory with people who are on
the cusp and ready to put their feet into the future,'' Ms. Jamison
said a decade ago. ``I want to also pay loyal respect to our
choreographers Talley Beatty, Donny McKayle, John Butler, Geoffrey
Holder and Louis Johnson, who were Alvin's contemporaries. Those
people made it possible for us to be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   As arguably the most popular modern-dance company in the world
prepares for its monthlong season, Wednesday (the 10th anniversary
of Ailey's death) through Jan. 2 at City Center, Ailey's mission to
keep modern dance alive through an eclectic repertory by a variety
of choreographers has been largely accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Ailey democratized dance by providing a showcase for the wealth
and diversity of vernacular dance that already existed in America.
He thought these dances should belong to the whole world. To
accomplish this, he blended styles in his repertory, borrowing
ideas from Lester Horton, Katherine Dunham, Jack Cole and Jose
Limon and incorporating the theatricality of Denishawn.
</P>
<P>
   He was also indebted to the modern-dance pioneers Martha Graham,
Doris Humphrey, Charles Weidman and Anna Sokolow. According to Joe
Nash, the African-American dance historian, ``Alvin's goal from the
very beginning was for his dancers to be able to move from one
style to another with ease, grace, passion and conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   That ideal is achieved in the current season in which there are
21 ballets by 12 choreographers. These include three world
premieres: ``Danger Run,'' choreographed by Donald McKayle; ``C
Sharp Street _ B Flat Avenue,'' by Urban Bush Women's Jawole Willa
Jo Zollar, and ``Grace,'' by Ronald K. Brown. There will also be
three revivals: Ms. Jamison's ``Divining,'' John Butler's ``After
Eden'' and a revisitation of Bill T. Jones' ``Fever Swamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently 10 choreographers whose work will be danced by the
Ailey company this year and next discussed how Ailey inspired them
personally and artistically.
</P>
<P>
   Ailey danced in the company of Donald McKayle for a few years
before he started his own in 1958. ``Alvin spoke to me a lot,''
says McKayle, who is 69. ``He asked a ton of questions because he
was a curious, inquisitive, brilliant man. We had a marvelous
exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   McKayle observes that the Ailey repertory was based on Alvin's
own works, which revealed his personal style yet was strongly
influenced from the time he apprenticed under Horton in the early
'50s. He says the technique of the company has changed over the
years and thinks that if you can't dance every style, you aren't
valuable to the troupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danger Run'' is McKayle's seventh work for the Ailey company
and is set to folk material by the radical contemporary American
composer Frederic Rzewski, with costumes by the Nigerian Omatayo
Wunni Olaiya. Although the dance is not locked into a time frame,
it depicts the odyssey of Africa's Middle Passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ailey dancers are so giving to me,'' says McKayle. ``It is
important for us as choreographers, but also for the company. It's
a very grounding experience, and the statements we are making
together are unique because, you see, it is very important for us
to realize our identity.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jawole Willa Jo Zollar, 48, first saw the Ailey company in
the early '70s she was impressed by the individuality of the
artists, particularly Ms. Jamison, John Parks and Sylvia Waters
(who has directed the junior company, Ailey II, for 25 years).
After seeing an all-Ulysses Dove program danced by the Ailey
company last year, and although she adores Dove's choreography, she
found his dances tense, she said.
</P>
<P>
   So, as a contrast, Ms. Zollar went on to choreograph a
light-hearted dance for 15 Ailey dancers, ``C Sharp Street _ B Flat
Avenue,'' set to a jazz score by Michael Wemberly and David Murray.
Inspired by a line from a Ntozake Shange poem, ``I live on C-Sharp
Street and my friend lives on B Flat Avenue,'' Ms. Zollar says, ``I
fell in love in that moment _ the funkiness of living in music.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zollar points out that theatergoing habits have changed for
African-Americans. ``What we are interested in, what our mission
is, is to make the work more accessible to black audiences,'' she
says. ``What we have found is that the majority of our audiences
are white, which is great. But we want to try and get our work to
the people who don't have the tradition of going to the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Many black choreographers didn't have a home for their dances,
and that was something Ailey was able to provide. ``Certainly,
having my choreography danced by Ailey, the top modern-dance
company, is exciting,'' says Ms. Zollar. ``I'm having my work seen
from Germany to Iowa City.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald K. Brown, who is 33 and directs his own company,
Evidence, says it is a special honor for someone who never belonged
to the Ailey troupe to be choreographing for the Ailey dancers. He
didn't attend the Ailey school, so his first interaction with Ailey
was in the late '80s, at a rehearsal with Barry Martin's company,
for which he was making a work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alvin turned to me and said, `Are you one of mine?''' recalls
Brown. ``I felt immediately that he had this large heart, and that
he would have a company that would be bigger than himself.'' Brown
immersed himself in what Ailey was creating and strove to do his
work following the lead, instructions and lessons that artists like
Ailey and McKayle set down. ``It is kind of an acceptance or
approval by them to have my work danced in the repertory with
theirs,'' Brown says.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's ``Grace'' is set to Duke Ellington's ``Come Sunday,''
juxtaposed with contemporary dance music by Roy Davis and Afro-pop
by the Nigerian composer Fela Anikulapo Kuti. In the piece, the
dancers take the audience on a vicarious physical and spiritual
journey to the ``grace'' that surrounds individual existence.
</P>
<P>
   Ailey always wanted to give his dancers the opportunity to
experience the process of choreographing. Exceptional members of
his company like George Faison, Hope Clarke, Kelvin Kotardier, John
Parks and Milton Myers began by choreographing solos for Judith
Jamison, the Ailey icon, now 56.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite a challenge because of the type-casting of myself
as goddess, earth mother, bold, strong, forceful woman,'' Ms.
Jamison recalls. ``Those specific choreographic dancers knew me
very well and were able to go past that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a dancer I don't ever remember being interested in or eager
to choreograph,'' Ms. Jamison continues. ``Alvin pulled me out of
the Connecticut woods to create my first piece, `Divining,' for the
company in 1984. I'm very happy to recreate it this year.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Troy Powell, 30, a current Ailey dancer, was encouraged
by Ms. Jamison to create his first piece, ``Ascension,'' last year
to the music of Michael Wemberly. Powell is already at work on his
second ballet. Somehow it all seems connected to Ailey's legacy.
``As far as being a choreographer, of being a black man in dance,
I've always identified with Alvin,'' says Powell. ``It is what
Alvin started out and Judy is continuing: opening the doors up for
a lot of people. She has done a wonderful job in keeping Alvin
alive, true and honest-Aileyfied.''
</P>
<P>
   John Butler, who died at 74 in 1993, spoke in the early '90s
about his collaborations with Ailey. He recalled Ailey's saying,
``Any piece of yours that you want I will take, because I would
like to have John Butler's repertory danced by the Ailey company.''
Ailey eventually took six of Butler's dances because he felt that
Butler had never received proper recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generosity of the man, of one choreographer to another,
was truly amazing,'' said Butler. ``Naturally I would kill myself
for him. Alvin was someone who gave me respect, freedom,
encouragement and belief.'' Butler's ``After Eden,'' about Adam and
Eve's expulsion from the biblical garden, to the music of Lee
Hoiby, was initially recreated for the Ailey company in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Bill T. Jones, 47, the downtown choreographer, had a different
scenario with his first collaboration, ``Fever Swamp,'' with Ailey.
Everyone used to say to Jones, ``Why don't you let Ailey polish
you?'' At the time, Jones was totally against what he considered
``classical modern dance.'' ``When I met Alvin I was in awe of
him,'' says Jones. ``He had this astounding persona as a black
person, black artist, black man. I said, `What do you think of the
postmodern choreographers?' And he said, `I like them when they
dance.' That was our first exchange. I was prepared for him not to
like me and not to like what I do, but it was just the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Ailey then went out of his way to give visibility to the
avant-garde choreographer by putting ``Fever Swamp,'' on a
television special documenting the Ailey company. Jones thinks
Ailey's triumph is that he created a significantly integrated
audience. ``At this point I feel Alvin was way ahead of any racial
discourse,'' Jones says. ``Ailey claimed all styles and traditions
of dance to be his own as an American citizen. That is a pretty big
claim and part of his great contribution to dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Holder, 69, a peer of Ailey's, revived his ``Prodigal
Prince,'' about Hector Hyppolite, the father of Haitian folk art,
in 1998 after 30 years. It had its premiere with the Ailey company
in 1968. ``I'm glad Judy asked me to redo it,'' says Holder. ``I
did it really as a salute to the incredible artistry of Miguel
Godreau,'' the original Hector Hyppolite. ``He was a gem who could
fly.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Ailey company went to the USSR in the early '70s, the
Soviets asked them to cover the men in ``Prodigal Prince'' because
they thought they were too naked. Of course, they weren't nude;
they wore loin cloths. ``I'm not afraid of exposing the beautiful
black derriere,'' says Holder. ``We never tell the Russians, `Don't
bring your ballet here where a man is trying to have sex with a
swan in three acts.' My ballet is set in Africa. The Africans are
naked, and they don't wear tights when they dance.'' (Ultimately he
suugested that Ailey take another ballet.)
</P>
<P>
   Holder says that Ailey was very clever in creating a repertory
company because it gave ``Alvin time to work on and develop his own
choreography.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmen de Lavallade, 68, the golden American beauty who also
happens to be Holder's wife, remembers the early influences that
enlarged Ailey's choreographic statements and vision. It was, after
all, Ms. de Lavallade who inspired Ailey to dance in the first
place. And for Ailey the choreographer, Ms. de Lavallade was his
first muse. ``We were in Lester Horton's mixed-race company, which
was unheard of in the early '50s,'' she recalls. ``In Los Angeles
during the conservative McCarthy period we were artists of all
races dancing together. That was truly Hollyweird, but quite
courageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Lavallade thinks that, because of working with Horton,
Ailey had the will to kick off his extraordinary success with the
1960 masterpiece, ``Revelations,'' only his 10th ballet. After this
enormous triumph, Ailey was able to create a gigantic repertory
with all the choreographers whom he valued and admired. For the
2000 season, Ms. de Lavallade has been commissioned by Ms. Jamison
to create her first ballet for Ailey's main company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancers are attracted to the Ailey repertory beyond Alvin's
spirituality, because it is so diverse,'' says Dwight Rhoden, 36,
who directs the Ailey-inspired company Complexions with the former
Ailey star, Desmond Richardson, 30. ``One has to be versed in all
dance techniques and at the same time have some sense of
theatricality,'' Rhoden says. ``Particularly in Alvin's work you
have to be mature enough to bring something to it, because he gives
you a lot of room as an individual artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jamison commissioned Rhoden's ``Frames,'' while he was
dancing with Ailey in 1992. He will also choreograph a new work for
the company next year. Rhoden thinks Ms. Jamison's eclecticism is
different from Ailey's, but still within the same spirit of
diversity and adventure in terms of taking chances. ``Alvin was
never safe,'' Rhoden says. ``Judy is sharp and intelligent when it
comes to selecting choreographers. She is not taking the secure
route, which is part of the appeal of the company. The reality is,
people who come to see the Ailey company perform will, in one way
or another, be entertained and provoked beyond the edge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
