</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NEGEV-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIMITLESS DREAM FOR THE DESERT OF TOMORROW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NITZANA, Israel _ Standing at the edge of the Negev, overlooking
a border crossing into Egypt, Lova Eliav swept a hand across the
expanse and summoned up his vision of a new Israeli city in the
sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here there will be high-tech industries, here desert research
centers, over there residential areas, desert agriculture, and out
there an airport,'' he said on a recent clear morning, the air
scrubbed clean by an overnight rain.
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous 77-year-old who looks younger, Eliav _ a former
regional developer, a secret emissary, a peace advocate, a member
of parliament and an inveterate visionary _ has reinvented himself
at the place that he considers Israel's new frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Negev is the future of Israel,'' he said of the wide
spaces of the desolate southern region, an area that makes up more
than half of Israel's territory but where just 5 percent of the
population lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate is excellent, the soil is excellent,'' Eliav said.
``There won't be any of that intolerable overcrowding of the
central part of the country. Nitzana can be a bridge of peace into
the Arab world and Israel's calling card in science and research. I
don't think it's entirely imaginary.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliav's vision is a new version of the largely ignored call of
David Ben-Gurion, Israel's first prime minister, to settle the
Negev. Although Ben-Gurion saw pioneer farmers sweating to make the
desert bloom, Eliav sees high-technology industry and agriculture
sprouting up, backed by research centers that investigate the
desert and offer solutions to combat desertification and to promote
arid-zone farming and the use of solar energy.
</P>
<P>
   At Nitzana, Eliav envisions a ``peace city'' of 50,000 built
around the border crossing, a hub of regional development at a
historical crossroads linked by highways leading to Egypt and
central Israel, the West Bank, Jordan and Syria. The area would be
self-sufficient in water, he said, drawing on a large aquifer of
salt water that is already being used for irrigation and can be
desalted for home use.
</P>
<P>
   The core of a community is already here. With the help of the
Jewish Agency and foreign Jewish contributors, Eliav founded a
live-in educational center at Nitzana 12 years ago. Israeli high
school students and Jewish youth groups from abroad learn about the
Negev, and immigrants study Hebrew and prepare to enter Israeli
universities.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Through trips to the dunes and hills, and on bicycle rides along
the border, the teenagers are taught about desert ecology and
experience life along a peaceful border. They take part in
experimental projects that grow crops and trees irrigated with salt
water pumped from underground.
</P>
<P>
   At neighboring Tel Nitzana, students have helped excavate
ancient Nabatean and Byzantine cities that straddled a crossroads
of caravan routes linking Africa and the Fertile Crescent and the
Red Sea with the Mediterranean. Eliav hopes that the site will
become a national park that would draw tourists to what he believes
should be Israel's most rapidly developing area.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although he is still trying to persuade the government to adopt
his plan _ considered by the Housing Ministry three years ago but
largely neglected since _ Eliav has a track record of improbable
accomplishments that suggests that his dream could become reality.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Russia and brought by his parents to British-ruled
Palestine in 1924, his personal history mirrors Israel's.
</P>
<P>
   In the '40s he commanded ships packed with illegal Jewish
immigrants from Europe that ran British blockades on Palestine's
shore. Under his direction, the town of Kiryat Gat and dozens of
agricultural communities were built in southern Israel in the
1950s, settling a flood of immigrants across a wide area that had
been previously unpopulated by Israelis. In the 1960s, he directed
the planning and construction of the desert town of Arad,
overlooking the Dead Sea.
</P>
<P>
   As an emissary of the Mossad, the overseas intelligence service,
in the late 1950s and '60s, he built a network of covert ties with
Jews in the Soviet Union and led a secret mission to Morocco to
assist in regional development and another mission to northern Iraq
to help a rebel Kurdish leader. In the 1956 Arab-Israeli war, he
led an air and sea operation to remove Jews from Port Said, Egypt,
to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, his strong advocacy of a Palestinian state as the
solution to the Arab-Israeli conflict led him to break with the
Labor Party, where he had risen to secretary-general. He held
meetings abroad with representatives of the Palestine Liberation
Organization when such contacts were banned, founded a dovish
political party with other peace advocates and mediated a prisoner
exchange between Israel and the PLO in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   After years of estrangement from the Labor Party because of his
views, Eliav conceded that he had some sense of vindication now
that the government was negotiating with Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, about a possible Palestinian state. But he said
precious time and many lives had been lost to arrive at what he
advocated more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Weary, he is investing his energy in Nitzana. In his mind's eye
he sees a city surrounded by dozens of smaller communities and
farms, rekindling an idealism that seems to have faded under the
consumer culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the political desert, and I've paid a price for
my opinions,'' he said. ``What I've done here is an antithesis to
the superegoism and materialism that are so rampant. We want to
show that things can be different. The future of the country, of
the people, is here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
