<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY EIGHT CLIPPERS ABLE TO PRACTICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Today's potential struggle between the calendar
and sporting clich has been preempted by Clippers coach Chris Ford,
who has quit worrying about what his players bring to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, whose team has managed to win three of its last four
games, simply is thankful when his players actually (ital) make it
(end ital) to the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only so much you can do with eight guys,'' he said,
referring to the number of able bodies suited up for Wednesday's
practice, the same number of players Ford used in Tuesday's 100-95
victory over the similarly depleted New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Before knocking off early to participate in the team's annual
charitable distribution of food and clothing at St. Joseph's Center
in Venice, the Clippers went to work with several employees on the
mend.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Taylor (foot sprain), who has missed the last five
games, didn't participate and will sit out Friday's game at
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Anderson (concussion) scored 23 points Tuesday in his
return from a three-game rest for cobweb removal, but absorbed a
few more big hits from the Knicks. He had Wednesday off, as did
power forward Brian Skinner (various aches and pains) and Keith
Closs (excused absence for personal business).
</P>
<P>
   For a little irony on the menu, it should be noted that point
guard Eric Murdock (sore right knee) didn't play against New York,
but did participate in Wednesday's workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric is good at stabilizing and settling down the offense,''
Ford said of Murdock, who had several important contributions
during last week's five-game trip. ``He's a calming influence.''
</P>
<P>
   That calm might have come in handy Tuesday, when his young
teammates helped the Knicks kill their 28-point, first-half lead by
unloading 31 3-pointers, including a 3-for-16 performance in the
second half. Ford said the Knicks fell in love with the standard
double-team tactic against Lamar Odom. With Odom under
surveillance, many subsequent 3-point opportunities for his pals
seemed worthy and inviting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after you've missed that many, a light bulb has to go
on,'' Ford said. ``During every timeout, we told 'em to start
taking the ball to the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Wednesday's crowded list of wounded preventing any
offensive upgrades, the Clippers worked on ``closing out,'' a
defensive maneuver used to prevent an open shooter from being open
for very long.
</P>
<P>
   Improvement in that area would come in handy vs. the
SuperSonics, who led by the top gunning of sub Vernon Maxwell (29
points) - defeated the Clippers, 104-92, in the season-opener at
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   (subhead) Kandi not dandy
</P>
<P>
   Center Michael Olowokandi spent another night in frequent-fouler
oblivion, picking up two personals in the first 30 seconds of
Tuesday's victory over the Knicks. He was on the floor for a
not-so-grand total of 16 minutes 60 seconds more than Olowokandi
clocked in last Friday's flop at Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, because I want to be out there
contributing,'' said the capable Olowokandi, who posted
double-doubles (points, rebounds) at Vancouver and Minnesota. ``You
can't let it get you down. But with the new rules, there has to be
some consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ford: ``Everybody's playing with the same rules. He's got
to work his way out of that. I'm not blowing the whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   But Olowokandi, in something miles short of a revelation, said
leniency for the NBA's star players means the rules may not be the
same for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it would be consistent, then I'd be happy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
