<HEADER>
A0837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ISMAIL-NY     11-24 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ISMAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROCKET IS RECLAIMING HIS BIRTHRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Originally skedded as FBN-COWBOYS-MANDELA) 
(jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It was a joyous mood recently in the Dallas locker room
because the Cowboys had once again toppled the rival Washington
Redskins. It was also a regal room because Nelson Mandela, the
South African social and political icon, and Prince Bandar of Saudi
Arabia were in the Cowboys' midst.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones, the Dallas owner, rushed to an area near the
showers where Raghib Ismail and Deion Sanders were standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jones said, `Deion, Rocket, come here!''' Ismail recalled in a
recent interview. ```I want you to meet Nelson Mandela and Prince
Bandar!' Nelson Mandela? I thought he must have meant Willie
Nelson. What would Nelson Mandela be doing at a Cowboys game? But I
went over and there was the prince. Deion already knew him. Mandela
was talking to a young boy and then he turned around. We said hello
and took a picture. To be totally honest with you, I was in such
shock that I can't remember what I said or what he said. I couldn't
focus. Wow, I hope he didn't say anything too important.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans used to shudder the same way upon meeting Ismail when he
was a college football star at Notre Dame before leaving in 1991.
Ismail was a spellbinding kick returner and an elusive, fleet
receiver, runner and marvel. Rocket became his universal identity.
People often became shocked and speechless in his presence. Mothers
often approached asking him to help raise their children. Others
would beg him to autograph their programs, or their shirts, nearly
fainting at simply the touch of his hand.
</P>
<P>
   But the seven years that followed Notre Dame became a
circuitous, complex, disheartening odyssey for Ismail. He left
Notre Dame after his junior year for two seasons in the Canadian
Football League and, thus, became obscure in the United States. He
then joined the Oakland Raiders for three nondescript seasons
during which he never caught more than 34 passes in any season and
scored a total of nine touchdowns. That was followed by two woeful
seasons with the Carolina Panthers, where he labored with injuries
and internal struggles over his spirituality and the recognition
that he missed stardom, the football success he once possessed.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, last year with the Panthers, Ismail enjoyed a breakout
National Football League season.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the Cowboys (5-5), Ismail continues his climb back to
what the calls his birthright. He does so Thursday in a
Thanksgiving Day battle with the Miami Dolphins (8-2), a
circus-like game where the controversial former Dallas Coach Jimmy
Johnson, now the Miami coach, makes a blustery return to Texas
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can have something all of your life, take it for
granted and not see it as a gift,'' Ismail said. ``In high school,
college and Canada, I saw my gift as a burden. If there was a big
play, I was always in the picture. I used to think of this as a
curse. It was not what I desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just before I was traded by the Raiders to Carolina, something
in me wanted me to be recognized as a ballplayer again. It was like
I had given up my birthright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reminded of the biblical story of Esau and Jacob. I
asked the Lord if it was too late to get it back. He said no,
because I didn't give it up knowingly. I repented. I wanted to get
back to where I knew I should be. But every time over my first two
years in Carolina when I thought I was able to handle being a
special player, I got knocked on my rear. I wanted my birthright
back, but I was being molded, shaped, renewed so that when I did
get it back, I'd be able to handle it in the proper way. Like going
through the fire.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His first two season in Carolina were full of fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my first year there, my attitude was garbage,'' Ismail
said. ``I came into a team meeting once and I was rushing, nearly
late. So, I had my boxers on and my pants and shoes in my hands. I
was hustling to my seat and I planned to put them on there. One of
the coaches leading the meeting was furious. He cursed at me in
front of everyone. I saw red. I literally could have jumped up and
bit his throat off. I was enraged and talked back. Stuff like that
was going on the whole year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up having to apologize to the entire staff. It showed
me I was not anywhere close to being where I wanted to be as a man
of God. The Lord showed me to trust in him. Once I would find that
out, I wouldn't let go. I learned to trust him through the fire. I
kept apologizing to everybody my second year, had a great minicamp
and then injured my knee. My confidence, out of the blue, was
shattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I was riding home and my mind began to map out how
much money I had in the bank and if I could just move to an island
and live there until the money ran out. And then I would get a job
shoveling sand if I had to. And then the Lord spoke to me and said,
look around you. And I looked up and there was a billboard with my
face on it smiling. And it said: `Rocket Ismail believes in the
Lord.' I cried all the way to the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season in Carolina, he finally caught fire. He caught 69
balls and scored eight touchdowns. He signed with Dallas as a free
agent this year and now has become a focal point of the Cowboys'
offense. Through 10 games, he leads the Cowboys in receptions and
is second in touchdowns scored. He has caught 52 passes for 749
yards and scored four touchdowns. He has rushed nine times for 83
yards. He turned 30 last Thursday, yet maintains superior speed and
skills. He is a tougher receiver. His peers say that now he takes
more hits with his 5-foot-11-inch, 175-pound frame and then readily
returns for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always circumstances that surround each player
you're interested in acquiring and we try not to put people in a
box and say this is only him,'' Cowboys Coach Chan Gailey said.
``You can talk yourself out of anybody. We thought he would be a
big part of us becoming a championship team. Rocket has tangibles
and intangibles. The tangibles are his speed, quickness and ability
to run after the catch. The intangibles are he is a very
high-character person who will do what it takes to help us to win.
We want diversity in our offense. But he is going to have a very
big year and be a big part of our season. The players here respect
who he is and respect him as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismail used to fear injury, fear that his teammates and coaches
thought he was dogging it, fear that trainers might prescribe him
the wrong treatment. His wife, Melani, and three children _ Raghib,
3, Imani, 1, and Kianna, 3 months _ have helped him to clear his
vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had come to Dallas right after Notre Dame, I probably
would have been overwhelmed by the football stuff and life here
because I wasn't grounded spiritually,'' Ismail said. ``I might
have been good football-wise but off the field I could have been
smashed. People might have seen me as an upstanding guy who could
handle a lot, but they were judging me by man's standard and not by
God's standard.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
