<HEADLINE>
USC'S WIN PAYS DOUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As expected, there were plenty of the top recruits in Southern
California sitting in the Coliseum stands last Saturday, watching
USC end eight years of frustration with a victory over UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   None of them burst into the victorious locker room and gave USC
coach Paul Hackett an oral commitment. But, the win as well as the
frantic postgame celebration on the Coliseum turf was certainly a
nice recruiting tool for the Trojan coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passion and energy level that existed after the game was
wonderful for the team,'' Hackett said. ``And it didn't hurt that
we had 25 recruits there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the USC locker room after the game included
offensive linemen Blair Jones of Newport Harbor, Travis Watkins of
San Diego Helix and Joe McGuire of Servite; defensive linemen
Nathan Goodson of Temescal Canyon, Steve Nevarrez of San Fernando
and Traison Lewis of Rancho Cucamonga; linebackers Amon Gordon of
San Diego Mira Mesa and A.J. Single of Bonita Vista; quarterback
Matt Cassell of Chatsworth;, running back Chris Howard of Banning,
and Brookside Christian teammates Willie Dixon and Jason Girley,
who are both receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game began, recruiting coordinator Larry Petroff took
Howard onto the field for a short conversation with Hackett. A few
of the Trojan players also stopped by to talk to Howard, who is a
recent USC commitment. Other commitments among the locker room
visitors were Lewis, McGuire, Cassell and Single.
</P>
<P>
   Also in attendance was former Los Alamitos defensive lineman
Sagan Atuatasi, a 1998 Trojan commitment, who is spending the
semester at Cypress College taking care of academic deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Southern California's most desired recruits Teyo
Johnson, Alex Holmes and Travis Johnson weren't at the game, but
each is slated to visit USC on Dec.3.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, a tight end from Harvard-Westlake, and Travis Johnson, a
defensive end from Sherman Oaks Notre Dame, were on a visit to
Michigan to watch a rivalry game of different stripes when the
Wolverines played Ohio State. And, San Diego Mira Mesa
football-basketball standout Teyo Johnson was in Palo Alto watching
his brother, Riall, and the Stanford Cardinal clinch a Rose Bowl
berth with a victory over Cal.
</P>
<P>
   (subhead) The recruiting trail
</P>
<P>
   Former Capistrano Valley quarterback Austin Moherman is leaving
Ohio State after three seasons. Moherman, who began the season
fighting for the starting spot, could end up at Division I-AA
Northern Arizona. ... Arizona and Arizona State will battle on the
field next week with a bowl bid on the line. The teams also battled
for the services of offensive lineman Ralph Zarate, and the
Wildcats won. Zarate, a 6-foot-5, 305-pounder from Scottsdale
Community College, had committed to Arizona State out of high
school but changed his mind following two junior college seasons.
... Florida State could have another dependable kicker on the way
with the commitment of Tampa's Brett Cimorelli. The 6-foot-4,
220-pound Cimorelli, who is similar to current Seminole kicker
Sebastain Janikowski in size, has three kicks of 50 yards or longer
this season, and will also play baseball in college.
</P>
</TEXT>
