<SLUG> BC-WARNER-EATS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER BROS. STUDIO SETS TO GRACE LAS VEGAS EATERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK -- In an offbeat use of its well-known name,
entertainment giant Warner Bros. is allowing the re-creation of
four studio sets in a restaurant that will open in Las Vegas in
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The WB Stage 16 eatery will open at the Venetian casino, which
rolled out earlier this year, with a menu aimed at movie buffs and
upscale diners. The facility will include backdrops based on
soundstages for ``Gold Diggers of 1933,'' ``Casablanca,'' ``Ocean's
11'' and ``Batman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sets create a dramatic backdrop for an amazing dining
experience,'' said John Baydale, director of operations for the
restaurant, which will serve lobster and wild mushroom strudel
along with healthy doses of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, under which the studio has licensed its logo to
European sports/entertainment concern ENIC, gives Warner a low-risk
opportunity to try out the dining concept at one of the most
prominent new casinos in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant is the first project to emerge from an alliance
announced in April 1998 between the studio and ENIC, under which
Warner sold an 80percent interest in its 10 Warner Studio Stores in
the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes three months after Warner announced a joint
marketing agreement with General Motors giving the automaker broad
access to the studio's properties, leading to a GM minivan bearing
WB and Bugs Bunny logos. It also said last week that it was
considering closing down some of the under-performing locations
among its 140 Studio Stores in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Batman'' section will include sound and lighting effects;
the ``Gold Diggers'' set will re-create the ``We're in the Money''
interior; the ``Casablanca'' set includes Rick's Cafe American; and
the ``Ocean's 11'' component will offer a re-creation of the lounge
of the Sands Hotel, which was blown up to make way for the
Venetian.
</P>
<P>
   Warner rival Walt Disney Co. experimented with a pair of themed
fast-food outlets in the early 1990s that closed after a few years.
Industry trackers believe its fledgling chain of themed ESPN Zone
restaurants has potential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 2102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
