A0843 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-CENTURYOFCOUNTRY     11-24 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CENTURYOFCOUNTRY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTRY MUSIC CHRONICLER MAY BE THE LAST NASHVILLE OPTIMIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Century of Country: An Illustrated History of Country
Music''
</P>
<P>
   by Robert K. Oermann
</P>
<P>
   TV Books, by HarperCollins publishers
</P>
<P>
   320 pages, 200 color and black-and-white photos.
</P>
<P>
   $39.95 hardback
</P>
<P>
   Robert K. Oermann, veteran Nashville music journalist and
industry observer, is that rarest of all songbirds currently
nesting on Music Row: an optimist.
</P>
<P>
   More or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like more things than I don't,'' Oermann said during a
recent stopover in Arlington to promote his new book, ``A Century
of Country: An Illustrated History of Country Music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually look forward to the millennium to see what's going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to be in direct contrast to the Chicken Little,
sky-is-falling mode currently gripping Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think country is going through an identity crisis right
now,'' he allowed, adding that the innovative artists who came up
10 years ago, such as Clint Black, Garth Brooks, Alan Jackson,
Vince Gill and Travis Tritt, have all peaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of the Dixie Chicks and Shania, nobody's shining the
light on where to go next,'' he said. ``They're pursuing the
13-year-old market, and that's very short-term.''
</P>
<P>
   Oermann's coffee-table creation is, of course, a
Nashville-centric view of the genre, but he does deal with the
Texas and Oklahoma-led western swing and progressive country
movements.
</P>
<P>
   And he gives Milton Brown as much ink as Bob Wills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of goes from alpha to omega, with everything in
between,'' Oermann said.
</P>
<P>
   He includes topics such as the history of country songwriting
(no, it doesn't begin and end with Hank Williams) and country music
on television and in the movies (that's where you'll find Bob
Wills).
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly, he says, a collection of personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have packaged or invented a Jimmy Dickens or a
Willie Nelson,'' he said. ``That's the downfall of Music Row today:
They're trying to package that.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to Nashville 22 years ago, ``when it was still a small
town and country music was still a cottage industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Oermann said he was thrilled with the look of the book, which
includes rare photos from his collection and oddball artifacts such
as a Roy Acuff flour-sack doll, a Gene Autry picture puzzle, even a
Brooks &AMP; Dunn cornflakes box.
</P>
<P>
   The pop culture aspect ``didn't all start with Clint and
Garth,'' Oermann said. He traces modern country's origins to
vaudeville and Wild West shows, which, he pointed out, have always
been commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I always try to give the culture the dignity it
deserves,'' he said. ``It's such a rich culture. I think if you
look at the richness of the culture, you don't get so depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   He worries about young fans, who he says should be seeking out
the earlier country stars to gain ``a sense of rootedness. They
don't know who Lefty Frizzell was, or who Ray Price is.''
</P>
<P>
   Oermann's personal favorites are the Jimmie Rodgers-Carter
Family era of the '20s and early '30s, and Dolly Parton as an
interview (''to greet each day with such wit, grace and candor,
after 35 years,'' he enthuses).
</P>
<P>
   His personal quest? To find a 1923 silent newsreel of Fiddlin'
John Carson that was supposedly so compelling as to convince one
music industry pioneer that he should record him.
</P>
<P>
   Oermann will argue all day with those who question country music
as an art form, he said, because of the inherent musical honesty of
the artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is what you get,'' he said. ``That's why these
people are artists. They say, `Here I am. I hope you like it.' An
entertainer says, `What do you want me to do, and I'll do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With the higher profile of the business and recent corporate
takeovers of record company structure, there is less individual
vision now, he says, ``and then it becomes harder to turn the
Titanic around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's confused,'' Oermann said. ``Fans listen to the
radio and think, `That's not country.' It's very easy to get lost
in the moment and not see that those 20 records are not all that is
being produced.''
</P>
<P>
   Cajun, western swing, bluegrass and cowboy music are all popular
subgenres in their own right, Oermann says, and that will help save
country's soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a very diverse format, and it's still
diverse,'' he said. ``I have yet to meet the person who can't be
seduced by Jimmie Rodgers, or the person who can listen to Bob
Wills and not get it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Oermann chose to start the book with the first printed
use of the term ``hillbilly'' to denote country music (April 23,
1900, ``The New York Journal),'' a debatable jumping-off point but
a Nashville-friendly one.
</P>
<P>
   He concludes at the same spot, with a blunt Marty Stuart
observation that ``at the end of the day, we're (all) hillbilly
pickers.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not Shania.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
