<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-TRAVEL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY TRAFFIC IS EXPECTED TO SET A RECORD THIS WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Those who helped people Wednesday get home
for the Thanksgiving holiday will have earned their dinner today.
</P>
<P>
   The American Automobile Association estimates that 33.8 million
people will travel over the Thanksgiving holiday weekend, setting a
record _ with about 200,000 more travelers than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday normally is the busiest travel day of the Thanksgiving
weekend, and Kansas City International Airport was no exception.
Despite the bustle, airport and airline officials reported that
flight schedules generally stayed on time.
</P>
<P>
   Fog on the East Coast early Wednesday had only a minimal effect
on flights out of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terminals are pretty crazy with the big crowds, but the
weather's been great,'' said Erica Hupp, a spokeswoman for the
Kansas City Aviation Department. ``There were a few in the morning
for flights going to Newark, but that was earlier (Wednesday
morning). Everything else has been running pretty smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   The most activity at KCI took place at the ticket counter and
gates of Southwest Airlines, which has the most daily departures of
all the carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our highest bookings ever in Kansas City'' on
Wednesday, said Jill Raines, Southwest's marketing manager. ``But
we have staffed accordingly, and the lines have moved quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines said Southwest had one fog-related delay at KCI on
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard Airlines, which has the second-most flights at the
airport, also had a busy day. Rocky Spane, the carrier's president
and chief executive officer, even spent some time talking to
customers and checking in bags, said Rana Walker, a Vanguard
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had high levels of traffic, but everything seems to be
running smoothly,'' she said. ``We haven't seen a lot of delays.''
</P>
<P>
   While the nation's airports were busy, the majority of travelers
will get to their destination on the road. AAA estimates that 27.8
million people, or 82 percent of this weekend's travelers, will
travel using a personal vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Those taking to the road will have to pay more for gasoline than
they did last year, according to a AAA survey. In Kansas City, the
average price of gasoline is $1.16 a gallon, up 28 cents from last
year's holiday period.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, higher prices have not deterred the nation's
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prices are higher than last year, but you're still looking
at gasoline prices slightly lower than in 1996,'' said Mike Right,
a spokesman for AAA in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Observers also noted that generally milder weather throughout
the country had prompted more people to drive to their destinations
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
