<HEADLINE>
SPRINT SCRAPS PLAN FOR ITS OWN DIGITAL-AGE TELEPHONE SWITCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Sprint Corp. has scrapped a pioneering project to
develop its own digital-age telephone switches, part of a $500
million initiative to revamp its network and replace the
100-year-old technology that it uses to route long-distance voice
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Employees on the project, who asked not to be identified because
of future employment prospects, said they were frustrated by the
move. They think it represents the first casualty of the company's
planned merger with MCI WorldCom, a move that could presage the
loss of the company's culture of technical innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Vendors who worked on parts of the project also expressed
disappointment and said they would carry on their work despite
Sprint's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain confident that next-generation switching ... will be
the vehicle by which carriers migrate from today's circuit-switched
world to a new public network,'' said Brian Jackman, president of
global products and technologies at Tellabs Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint officials say the company simply had lost its early lead
in developing the technology and plans to buy packet switches from
vendors instead of developing its own.
</P>
<P>
   The company intends to license the proprietary technology it
developed during the project to vendors such as Cisco Systems. Most
employees will be reassigned, the company said, and the contractors
involved will have the chance to work on other projects.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, a team of 120 Sprint employees and contractors
working in conjunction with at least two vendors _ Cisco and
Tellabs _ had spent the better part of three years developing the
telephone switch, the JCS 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Named after the engineer who developed the idea, Joe Christie's
System 2000 was designed to route voice calls over the company's
fiberoptic network in the same fashion as data _ in bursts of
fixed-length digital cells, or packets _ using a technology known
as asynchronous transfer mode, or ATM.
</P>
<P>
   Packet switching, which allows many calls to share the same
path, uses network capacity far more efficiently than traditional
circuit switching, which opens up a dedicated circuit between
callers for the duration of a call.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint made much ado about the JCS 2000 when announcing its
Integrated On-Demand Network in June 1998. The company boasted that
``packetized'' voice traffic would allow it to generate almost
unlimited capacity in its network; eliminate its reliance on older,
overpriced circuit switches; and reduce the cost of carrying a
long-distance call by 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This week, it downplayed the significance of the switch in its
plans and said there were other solutions that would allow it to
accomplish the same goals.
</P>
<P>
   They also stressed that the decision to abandon the JCS 2000
would not delay the deployment of the Integrated On-Demand Network,
a service that will bundle local, long-distance and data on the
same connection to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going back to the old model,'' said Russ Robinson, a
Sprint spokesman, ``but we are abandoning this development
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Migrating to a purely packet-switched network is still Sprint's
plan, Robinson said. Indeed, all carriers have such plans as they
cope with exploding amounts of data traffic generated by the
Internet and try to deliver integrated communications services to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   But given an anticipated surge in voice traffic next year,
Sprint will continue to rely on and buy the workhorse circuit
switches it has traditionally used from Nortel Networks, known as
the DMS 250.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're projecting a pretty significant increase in voice
traffic next year,'' Robinson said. ``Nortel switches will be in
place longer than we thought because of the growth in voice
traffic. We need the DMS 250. The data switches weren't there
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said the decision made sense in light of the merger
with MCI WorldCom, as it would be easier to meld networks with
similar architectures than one based on packet switching and
another on circuit switching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that if you look down the road, this could make our
network more compatible with theirs, but this was not a merger
decision,'' Robinson said. ``We're not at the point of merging
networks yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the move would not involve any write-offs, as much
of the technology developed in JCS 2000 would ultimately be
deployed in the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a marketing tragedy than an engineering
tragedy,'' said Maribel Lopez, an analyst with Forrester Research.
``They spent so long pushing the ION vision'' with their own
switches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
