<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-GUILTY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR OF MISSOURI TOWN PLEADS GUILTY IN SEX, BRIBERY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and ED FLETCHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The 68-year-old mayor of tiny Reeds Spring,
Mo., pleaded guilty in federal court Wednesday to bringing a
15-year-old girl across state lines for illegal sex and then paying
thousands of dollars in bribes to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in prison blaze orange, but without his trademark
toupee, Joe Dan Dwyer confessed to nine felony counts that stemmed
from a sexual encounter he had with a Manhattan, Kan., girl in a
St. Louis motel room in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he provided money and paid for a shopping trip to
Neiman Marcus as a reward to the girl and his 25-year-old friend
who drove the girl from Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm guilty, sir,'' Dwyer told U.S. District Judge Ortrie
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and defense lawyers have agreed to ask Smith to
sentence Dwyer to seven years in prison. Smith, who is not bound by
that recommendation, set Dwyer's sentencing for April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Laird, the woman who drove the girl from Kansas, pleaded
guilty earlier this week to accepting more than $20,000 from Dwyer
in exchange for a promise to testify falsely on his behalf
regarding the sex case.
</P>
<P>
   Following Dwyer's hearing, a second woman, Dorothy Shipley,
pleaded guilty to helping him find other women whom he offered
thousands of dollars to testify on his behalf after his initial
indictment on the sex charges.
</P>
<P>
   Shipley acknowledged setting up a meeting just after Dwyer was
indicted in the sex case in January 1999 at which he discussed the
need to find witnesses willing to give false statements and
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Dwyer said he needed help and that he would take care of
people to get that help,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Katharine
Fincham, summarizing the government's case. ``He said he needed
adults to testify on his behalf since most of the witnesses against
him at the time were juveniles.''
</P>
<P>
   Fincham urged Smith to accept the guilty pleas. She noted that
if Dwyer went to trial, she would call several girls to testify,
and the prosecutor wanted to avoid subjecting them to that
experience.
</P>
<P>
   As word of their mayor's guilty plea trickled back to Reeds
Spring, a town of 411 about 30 miles south of Springfield, reaction
varied from disbelief to a realization the town needs to make new
plans for its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is time to find a new mayor if he is guilty of this
stuff,'' said Doug Patrick, co-owner of Bass Pro Shop. ``We can't
have a mayor who's a convicted felon.''
</P>
<P>
   City Clerk Kacee Anderson, who has managed the city's day-to-day
business in the mayor's absence, was saddened and shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pled guilty to these things?'' she asked. ``Are you sure he
wasn't coerced into pleading guilty?''
</P>
<P>
   During his hearing, Dwyer assured the judge that no one had
coerced or threatened him to plead guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Barb Meeker, owner of the Spring House doll shop, said attempts
by Dwyer's lawyers in pretrial hearings to suppress evidence
gradually convinced her there might be some truth behind the
accusations. Still, she said, people there wanted to believe that
someone who did a lot for Reeds Spring was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   During the hourlong hearing, Dwyer spoke in a firm, courtly
voice and praised his defense lawyers _ James Wyrsch, Charles
Rogers and David Kelly. They fought to bar prosecutors from using
tape recordings of phone calls in which Dwyer offered witnesses
money for favorable testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are the most outstanding attorneys in all of
America,'' Dwyer said. ``They're perfect. I'm very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about Dwyer's behavior first surfaced in August 1998
when authorities raided his home and carted off several cases
filled with sexually explicit videotapes and sex toys.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury indicted Dwyer and Laird in January on the
sex case, and he was released on bond.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a second grand jury issued a new indictment that
accused Dwyer and Shipley of obstruction of justice, including
offering money to the 15-year-old victim and her mother.
</P>
<P>
   A magistrate then revoked Dwyer's bond, putting him in federal
custody pending trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
