u a BC-CONFEDERATE-FLAG-NYT &LR;      11-24 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATE-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFEDERATE BATTLE FLAG IS LOSING MORE BATTLES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Md., Va., Ala.)   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It may not be as bad as the winter of 1865, but this
year has not been kind to the Sons of Confederate Veterans and
their desperate defense of their ancestors' most beloved emblems.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate battle flag that flies over the South Carolina
Statehouse has been under renewed siege for months, this time by
the combined forces of the NAACP and the state Chamber of Commerce.
A portrait of Robert E. Lee was removed from Richmond's centerpiece
Canal Walk in June after a black councilman objected. Virginia and
Tennessee refused to allow the Sons' logo, which includes the
battle flag, on personalized license plates, and Oklahoma would not
fly the flag on a history plaza in Oklahoma City. A character in a
new Tom Clancy novel, of all places, equates the group with the Ku
Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   But what may have been the most piercing blow of all came
earlier this month, when the Adam's Mark hotel chain told the Sons
of Confederate Veterans not to schedule any more meetings at its
hotels, which rise above 12 Southern cities. The company's chief
executive said the Sons' displays of the Confederate battle flag
were excessive, and offensive to the largely black service staff at
the hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wear the flag on their T-shirts, and they put it in their
windows,'' said Fred Kummer, chief executive of the 21-hotel chain
and of its parent, HBE Corp., based in St. Louis. ``They tried to
get us to fly it on our flagpole. You know, we operate mostly in
urban areas, and we have a large number of Afro-Americans who work
in our hotels. For them, it's like waving a red cloth in front of a
bull.''
</P>
<P>
   Kummer's decision has infuriated the Sons, many of whom resent
any notion that the very existence of a group like theirs is a
belligerent tribute to the era of slavery. Leaders of the
organization, which has about 27,000 members around the country,
say their intention is to honor their fallen ancestors and preserve
a memory of Confederate gallantry. But they admit to a certain
weariness at their many fallen ramparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem like things are really stepping up against us,''
said Collin G. Pulley Jr., a furniture salesman in Courtland, Va.,
who leads the organization's Heritage Defense Committee. ``These
groups like the NAACP want to destroy everything Confederate, from
the flags to the monuments on courthouse lawns. I guess it's
because the lot of black people in this country has improved so
much in the last 30 years that now they need something else to keep
themselves occupied, and keep their organizations in the
forefront.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulley, who is in charge of keeping track of what the group
calls ``heritage violations,'' has been busy maintaining lists of
insults to the battle flag and the Confederacy's reputation and
posting them on the Sons' Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes any number of instances in which schools have
disciplined students for wearing Confederate insignia; an order by
Coast Guard officials in Elizabeth City, N.C., that employees
remove Confederate decals and bumper stickers from their cars, and
one incident described as follows:
</P>
<P>
   ``The SCV camp in Tazewell, Va., recently placed a wreath and a
small flag at the Confederate monument by the courthouse, but the
circuit court judge took it upon himself to remove the decorations.
The Virginia Division heritage coordinator is currently
investigating the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, which says its membership tends to grow with each
such incident, is planning a large march around the South Carolina
Statehouse on Jan. 8 and has organized a postcard protest campaign
directed at Penguin Putnam, the publishers of the Tom Clancy novel,
``Hidden Agendas.''
</P>
<P>
   It has also obtained the help of the Rutherford Institute, a
conservative advocacy group, in a drive to change the decision on
the Virginia license tags. (Similar efforts were successful in
Maryland and North Carolina.) Of course it is telling its members
not to spend a dime at any Adam's Mark hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't appreciate being painted as a troublesome
organization,'' said the group's commander in chief, Patrick J.
Griffin III, a general contractor in Darnstown, Md. ``The symbols
we use are well known, and it's unfortunate there are racist groups
out there that misuse them. We are not anti-African-American or
anything like that. But we do honor the people who suffered and
died under that banner for what they believed, which was Southern
independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Kummer, of Adam's Mark, said he made his decision after some 500
members of the group's Alabama chapter met in September in Mobile,
the third time the Sons had gathered at any of the company's
hotels. There were so many displays of the battle flag, he said,
that many hotel employees refused to serve the group, and some
called in sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the environment was respectful of our
employees,'' he said. ``They didn't feel they could provide service
to the guests. So we had managers all over the hotel making beds.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that while there were some minor confrontations during
the meeting, it was the overall atmosphere that led to his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, who attended the Mobile meeting, said his group was a
victim of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that those employees work in a service
industry, and if they don't find everything to their personal
liking, they should just take a deep breath and carry on,'' he
said. ``There was nothing that occurred in Mobile that would have
caused any employee any concern. But I guess Kummer has a problem
with any group his employees don't like. Things must be different
with the politically-correct crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Sons say, there are plenty of other hotels
where they can meet, and they will continue trying to eke out small
victories. The credit card used by the members _ which was at first
mistakenly printed with the American flag _ now sports the Rebel
banner. The town of Rosa, Ala., population 149, has agreed to fly
the battle flag three times a year. Two weeks ago, after months of
hand-wringing and debate, the Richmond City Council voted to
restore Lee's portrait to the Canal Walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe they went after Robert E. Lee?'' Pulley said
with a sigh of exasperation. ``Well, at least we've got him back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
