<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHANGING-RELIGIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANITY LEADS IRANIAN WOMAN ALONG NEW PATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAIME JORDAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soraya had always been one of the beautiful people. The kind
with money, who had nothing to worry about in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Iranian Revolution of 1979 racked her land, and she
found herself in the United States _ broke, ashamed and hurting.
</P>
<P>
   But she found Jesus, and now none of those material things
matters to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lots of problems and difficulties in my life, but I am
truly happy,'' said Soraya, whose full name has not been used for
privacy reasons. ``I really feel like my desires have changed
completely. I'm not interested in the way I had. I put everything
on his shoulders and let him show me the way ... because I failed
in whatever I did.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her 17-year-old son are the only members of her family
who believe in Christ. But she said that while growing up she had
always received positive messages about Christians, even in a
country that preached a negative message about Christianity. Her
father always talked highly about Christians, and it planted a seed
in her heart, she said. Before her father died in 1982, he told
Soraya he was no longer a Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Soraya's journey to Christianity began with the Iranian
Revolution. Until then her family, born into Islam, had not been
devout. But after the revolution, Islam became a more dominant
force in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Soraya says she didn't like the way she saw women being treated,
and she didn't see compassion or love in the traditions. It was
inconsistent with the God she had been taught about.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is fair for Christian people,'' she said. ``They are
equal, but in Muslim world, God discriminates against people.''
</P>
<P>
   After fleeing Iran and briefly living in England, Soraya moved
in 1985 to Rockwall, Texas, where she lived with a sister. While
she was there, a woman from Church on the Rock knocked on Soraya's
door one day, inviting her to the church.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, she was at Bible study. As she studied the
Bible, she said, she began to see a new way. Immediately she saw
changes in herself. She discovered sins she hadn't known were sins,
and she began to live to serve God, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult aspect of becoming a Christian has been
accepting Jesus as her savior, she said. As a Muslim, she believed
that Jesus was a prophet. But the more she read the Bible and the
more she attended church, the more she opened her heart to the
concept of Jesus as her savior, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But other things have been difficult, as well. There was a time
when Soraya's mother refused to have a relationship with her
because of her conversion. Her mother visited in 1996, but for two
months would not talk to her, Soraya said. But then, while Soraya's
mother was in the hospital awaiting a difficult surgery, Soraya's
constant prayers broke down the barrier. Soraya said she begged her
mother to accept Christ. Her mother never made that leap, but she
did accept her daughter into her life again.
</P>
<P>
   And Soraya, a Dallas loan officer, says she feels fortunate
because her husband has not discouraged her in her faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees the changes, but he's so stubborn he doesn't want to
admit they come from Christianity,'' she said. ``Because of those
changes, he doesn't want to stop me from going.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost 10 years after accepting Jesus, Soraya has never
regretted her conversion. She attends an Iranian Church in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy. Every day, that's my first thing when I open my
eyes,'' she said. ``I'm glad that I know the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she only wishes she could spread the Gospel in her
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lots of wishes for my country when the door opens,''
she said. ``They are really hungry. This is the best time for
Iranian people to hear the Gospel, because they really are hungry,
thirsty and ready for the Gospel.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
