u s BC-BKN-SPREWELL-1STLD-WR     11-24 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPREWELL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL IS FINED $10,000 BY THE NBA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Clarifies reference to Sprewell being unable to appeal) 
(jt) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association all but ordered Latrell
Sprewell to wash his mouth out with soap by fining him $10,000
Wednesday for directing profanity toward fans during his emotional
return to Golden State in Oakland on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was traveling to New York from Los Angeles on Wednesday
with the Knicks after their five-game road trip and was unavailable
for comment. Because the fine was less than $25,000, Sprewell will
not be able to appeal On Tuesday Sprewell said he was surprised by
a morning phone call from a league security official asking him
about the obscenities he shouted toward his hecklers at the Arena
in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have dialogue with the fans,'' Sprewell said,
explaining his actions. ``I think because it was Golden State,
there was the hype about me and P.J. Carlesimo and a bigger focus
on the game. That made it more of an issue. But I like talking to
the fans. I'm not the type to back down from that. Frankly, I think
the fans like that back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Thorn, the league's vice president of basketball operations,
reviewed Sprewell's conduct during the game and determined that the
Knicks' impulsive guard went too far.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game even began, Sprewell confronted a detractor and
used profanity to tell the man to ``shut up.'' During the game,
when three men sitting in corner court-side seats were chiding
Sprewell for his attack on Carlesimo, then his coach, two years
ago, Sprewell used more obscene language to address them. Near the
end of the game, Sprewell could be seen shouting profanities into
the air as he left the court during a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really recall saying that much, except to the three
guys in the corner,'' Sprewell said. When asked what the league's
intentions were in investigating the incident, Sprewell, who was
suspended by Commissioner David Stern after choking Carlesimo, said
if he was being used as an example, ``it wouldn't be the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sprewell is not the first player to be fined $10,000 for
directing profanity at fans, which is a violation of the league's
code of conduct. In April 1998, Houston's Charles Barkley was fined
the same amount for directing obscene gestures and profanity at a
Utah fan in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, Sprewell has been financially punished on
several occasions. In 1997, he lost $6 million because of his
four-month suspension after choking Carlesimo. Last season, after
critical comments made by his agent, he was fined $25,000 by the
Knicks, although that fine was later rescinded by the team.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, the team fined him $130,000, which included a
penalty for missing training camp and a one-game suspension for the
first game of the preseason. Throughout this past week, Coach Jeff
Van Gundy has defended Sprewell's response during the Golden State
game and blamed the escalated tension on unruly fans.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks General Manager Scott Layden issued a statement
Wednesday, saying: ``The league investigated the situation and felt
it necessary to fine Latrell. The league is objective; it made a
decision that should bring closure to an emotional situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
