<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-TOOLATE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY THAT LOST CHILD TO ASTHMA FOUND OUT ABOUT HELP TOO LATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARTELLARO  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ Pupils at Benton Elementary School in
Independence are approaching the holidays with an empty space in
their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   It is a space that once was filled by the second-grader her
teacher called ``the perfect student'' _ the bright, happy little
girl who was always willing to help and never complained about the
chronic disease that eventually took her life.
</P>
<P>
   Joslynne Clark, 8, died this month of asthma, leaving her family
and friends in sorrow, shock and pain. Her hard work in school and
at home, her uncomplaining nature and the devotion to others that
made her ``everybody's best friend'' showed that Joslynne was
anything but typical.
</P>
<P>
   But as a child from an urban family that has struggled
financially, she was in a sense a typical victim of asthma _ a
disease that does not subscribe to the belief that all children are
created equal.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma rates are highest in low-income urban neighborhoods,
experts in the field agree. Many suspect that urban neighborhoods
present the greatest exposure to substances that can trigger the
disease _ dust, smoke, air pollutants and latex particles from car
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Joslynne and her mother, Michelle Clark, were uninsured. They
had been on Medicaid intermittently for years, but lately the
family had been taking in just enough money to prevent qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   The family was able to get medical care for Joslynne through a
public hospital, and she had a breathing machine that administered
medication at home. But in the early morning hours of Nov. 10, as
Joslynne struggled for breath, asthma claimed another life.
</P>
<P>
   ``She went into an attack, and she just went,'' Clark said. ``I
called 911, but I think she was gone by the time they got here. Her
lips were blue. They said she died at the hospital but....''
</P>
<P>
   It was only after the child's death that Clark learned about the
additional help for asthma patients available through the Greater
Kansas City chapter of the Asthma and Allergy Foundation of
America.
</P>
<P>
   The local chapter of the asthma foundation has programs designed
to help disadvantaged patients get the medications and equipment
they need, said Noel Albert, executive director of the chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have prescription assistance programs. We have free
breathing machines,'' Albert said. ``It breaks my heart when I hear
that people don't know that we have these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Wald, a physician and asthma allergy specialist, serves
on the national and local chapter boards of directors of the asthma
foundation. He said that 7 percent to 10 percent of the Greater
Kansas City population suffers asthma, which causes about 50 local
deaths a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People often don't know the resources that exist in the
community that they can turn to,'' Wald said. ``Most pharmaceutical
companies have a program under which they provide free medications
to the poor, and doctors know how to access that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wald said the most important sign for asthmatics to watch for
was the time period of relief given by a bronchodilator drug, such
as albuterol. If a dose does not provide four full hours of relief,
he said, it is a sign that the disease is in a severe stage, and
the patient should see a doctor or visit an emergency room right
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more than 5,000 deaths (nationally) a year from
asthma,'' Wald said. ``The deaths are increasing despite more and
better medications for asthma.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of those deaths is leaving a very large mark at Benton
Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   Deena Graham, Joslynne's second-grade teacher, said the little
girl was impressive in the way she handled her illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't even know she was sick, because she wouldn't
complain,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always was willing to help her peers,'' said Graham, who
often asked Joslynne to help explain concepts to other pupils.
``She could be a peer who could give a peer's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everybody would say she was their best friend.
Everybody loved her. ... Life is not the same around here for our
class.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
