<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAZA-LIGHTS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING CENTER PREPARES TO USHER IN HOLIDAY SEASON WITH CEREMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOYCE E. SMITH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In November 1929, the country was reeling
from the recent stock market crash and President Herbert Hoover was
trying to assure Americans that prosperity was just around the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   But on the fledgling Country Club Plaza, things already were
looking a little brighter. For the first time, merchants lighted
every Spanish tower and balcony with sparkling colored lights. A
year later the first formal ceremony was held.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the 70th Plaza lighting ceremony is expected to
draw more than 250,000 people and be seen around the world on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   George and Leslie Brett, along with their children, will flip
the switch at 7:30 p.m., turning on 200,000 jewel-colored lights.
The lights will glow nightly until mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, the Plaza had only five buildings. Now more than 75
miles of lights are strung on the Plaza's 14 city blocks.
</P>
<P>
   The lighting ceremony kicks off the holiday season for many area
residents. During the seasonal boomlet of consumer spending, the
Plaza lights offer an extra attraction for area businesses and a
public relations windfall for Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds to the stature of the city; it gives a cosmopolitan
feel,'' said Ken McCormack, vice president of Halls. ``What the
arch is to St. Louis, the bridge is to San Francisco, the Plaza
lights are to Kansas City. It is something that is noted
nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of the Plaza lights are in virtually every publication
about Kansas City, said Pete Levi, president of the Greater Kansas
City Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us an image of being very alive and different from
other cities,'' Levi said. ``Shoppers come from all over the
Midwest, if not the country, boosting the economy of Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Haddad Restaurant Group said the fourth quarter was always the
strongest for the company's Plaza restaurants, which include Plaza
III and Fedora Cafe &AMP; Bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see double-digit increases,'' said Bruce Campbell, director
of marketing and purchasing for Haddad. ``More and more people are
coming down _ large groups of families, business cocktail parties,
holiday parties. The lights definitely bring people down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks after the lighting ceremony, Campbell said,
families often come down for dinner and then head out for holiday
shopping. Every year, one group of 15 or so women meets for
cocktails at Fedora and draws names for gifts. Each woman then
spends an hour buying a gift for the friend she picked and returns
to Fedora for dinner and the gift exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Raphael Hotel also has its best month of the year in
December, about 20 percent higher in revenue than other months.
Almost every one of the 123 rooms are booked. Some customers have
made the lighting ceremony an annual event for more than 25 years,
and they book rooms a year in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum continues through the holidays; it continues as
long as the lights are on,'' said Beth Morrison, executive director
of the Plaza Merchants Association. ``All the hotels fill up.
People are dining, shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pottery Barn notes a large increase in evening shoppers
during December as people come to enjoy the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Hoffman, co-owner of Panache Chocolatier, said her Plaza
shop did one-third of its annual business during December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights are a real draw for people from all over the city
and from a five-state area,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Plaza lights also give Kansas City two distinct tourist
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate to have the summer and the holidays, and a
pivotal part of that is the Plaza,'' said Maxine Odell of the
Convention and Visitors Bureau of Greater Kansas City. ``We get
6,000 motor coach tours a year, and a good portion of those come in
December.''
</P>
<P>
   Motor coaches carry... MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
