<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING CENTER PREPARES TO USHER IN HOLIDAY SEASON WITH CEREMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOYCE E. SMITH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...those come in December.''
</P>
<P>
   Motor coaches carry an average of 35 to 40 persons, spending an
estimated $130 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Several tours now offer a package trip to Branson in December,
with a stopover in Kansas City to see the Plaza lights and the
mayor's Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1925 that Charles S. Pitrat, head of maintenance for
the J.C. Nichols Co., first hung a humble string of 16 colored
bulbs on the Suydam Building on the northwest corner of 47th Street
and J.C. Nichols Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   The merchants in the other Plaza buildings, all north of 47th
Street, added to Pitrat's lights by putting Christmas trees along
the sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, Pitrat extended a string of lights from those buildings
across 47th Street to the theater building. The extended lights
were an unusual step for the times and one that caused much
comment.
</P>
<P>
   More lights were added each year as new buildings went up.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 70 years, the lights have gone out only during World
War II and for two weeks in 1973, when President Richard Nixon
asked Americans to conserve energy.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the wiring is at least 35 years old. The 10-foot
papier-mache replica of Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer, with
lighted nose and moving tail, hasn't survived, but the 8-foot stars
are still mainstays.
</P>
<P>
   One year the Plaza tried all blue lights, but the concept failed
because the lights couldn't be seen well.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the lights begins in the spring, when Broadway
Electrical Construction Inc. starts inspecting miles of streamers
in a storage room.
</P>
<P>
   In late July, the crew climbs the roofs of the Plaza to inspect
fuse boxes and streamer feeders. They begin hanging lights in
September.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 workhours later, the crew puts the finishing
touches on the project on Thanksgiving Day, working right up to
show time at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A timer turns on the lights at 5 p.m. every day and turns them
off at 3 a.m. during the holiday season. On darker days a switch
can be flipped to turn the lights on earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The lights will be on until Jan. 16. Workers will then start
taking the lights down, a project that will be completed in March,
weather permitting. The lights can't be left up through the summer
because the high temperatures would cause them to deteriorate much
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Hendrickson, who has worked on the lights for more than
three decades and is project foreman, will retire this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other shopping districts are picking up on the public relations
and economic boost that holiday lights bring.
</P>
<P>
   Omaha, Neb., plans to turn on 1 million lights around the Gene
Leahy Mall during its Millennium Lights celebration on New Year's
Eve. Although the Greater Omaha Convention and Visitors Bureau
isn't expecting much tourist traffic for the event, it does expect
Omaha residents in outlying areas to book hotel rooms near the
mall.
</P>
<P>
   An Arkansas millionaire recently donated 2 million Christmas
lights to Graceland in Memphis, Tenn., including a 40-foot wall of
lights with 100 angels and 20 lighted trees. One 120-foot tree is
topped by a 12-foot replica of Elvis with a guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Graceland traditionally boasts a blue-lighted driveway, Nativity
scene and reindeer display from the day after Thanksgiving until
Elvis' Jan. 8 birthday. The new lights will be divided between a
pasture behind Graceland and the large souvenir shopping center
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``November through February is the slowest time of year for
us,'' said Todd Morgan, spokesman for Graceland. ``We expect the
new lights to jolt our visitorship a little bit, but by how much we
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   New York also has expanded its holiday events to continue to
draw bus tours and day-trippers from the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has become the place to be on the holidays,'' said
Nell Barrett, spokeswoman for NYC &AMP; Co., the Convention &AMP; Visitors
Bureau. ``We do $2 billion in the winter months, and most of that
is in December. It's a festive, happy climate that is so good for
attracting visitors and so great for a city's image.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
