<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-SCOUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY SCOUTS IN DETROIT IN DRIVE FOR FUNDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ohio, Ind.)  (rk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ In this city of more than a million people, there are
just 20,000 boy scouts. But there is an unusual, $17 million effort
afoot to increase that number.
</P>
<P>
   With an executive at General Motors who was an eagle scout
leading the charge, the Detroit Area Council of the Boy Scouts of
America has begun a drive to raise $10 million for inner-city Scout
troops and another $7 million to build a new camp for Cub Scouts
and make improvements on a Boy Scout camp in nearby Metamora, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising drive is notable not only for its size, but
also because it would earmark most of the money for long-term
goals. If successful, the campaign would create a $10 million trust
fund for inner-city troops. Interest and investment income from the
fund would pay for costs like camping gear and uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Philanthropy experts say the drive is ambitious. ``For scouts in
Detroit, that's a lot of money,'' said Stacy E. Palmer, editor of
The Chronicle of Philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit groups are increasingly taking advantage of the strong
economy to build nest eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is figuring out that this is the smartest way to
raise money and not have to keep going back to your donors,'' Ms.
Palmer said. ``The general prosperity is making people think of the
long term.''
</P>
<P>
   People, as well as money, are being solicited as part of the
drive to increase the number of inner-city scouts here. Detroit's
1,200 Baptist churches and its 73 Roman Catholic parishes have
pledged to use scouting as part of their youth ministries. And the
Detroit branch is looking for up to 500 volunteers from businesses
and community groups to serve as assistant troop leaders, said
Chuck J. Lang, senior director of development for the Detroit Area
Council.
</P>
<P>
   While Lang knew of no larger initiative targeting inner-city
youths for Boy Scout membership, and a national spokesman for the
Scouts was unable to provide any information about fund-raising
drives in other cities, Detroit's is not the only
multimillion-dollar drive for donations. Scouting organizations in
Houston, Cincinnati and Indianapolis have held large fund-raising
drives in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   There are slightly more than 100,000 scouts in the Detroit
metropolitan area, with about 80,000 in the suburbs and 20,000 in
the inner city, Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses have been receptive so far. General Motors has
pledged $1 million toward the $17 million goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids who are involved in scouting get exposed to skills and
values in scouting,'' said John F. Smith, general manager of GM's
Cadillac division and a former eagle scout, who is one of the
organizers of the drive. ``Lots of surveys indicate they are
changed and changed for the better by that experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith added: ``If you are a business interest, you could
selfishly look at this as early-on training for employees. We know
it makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are likely to pledge money later, when the
fund-raising effort gets into full swing next month.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler ``definitely will participate, but right now we
are still considering the contribution amount,'' said a
spokeswoman, Curtrise Garner, who added that the company had given
$50,000 to the Scouts in Detroit so far this year. A spokeswoman
for the Ford Motor Co., Gwynne Irvin, said that ``news from Ford
may be forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Some billboard owners have donated advertising space on
billboards along some of Detroit's highways, and the advertising
agency D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles has designed the
advertisements without charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
