A0870 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-BLUECROSS-DOCTORS-2TA     11-24 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUECROSS-DOCTORS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Many physicians resisting Blue Cross and Blue Shield contracts  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE and JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In a rare show of protest, at least 1,000
area physicians have declined to sign or delayed signing Blue Cross
and Blue Shield of Kansas City contracts that they say unfairly
restrict their medical practices.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross officials confirmed this week that about one-third of
the 3,200 physicians had not signed contracts by the Nov. 19
deadline. Physicians who haven't signed will receive termination
notices on Dec. 1, which will become effective in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance to the contracts reflects actions taken around
the nation as physicians increasingly protest the control wielded
by the managed-care industry.
</P>
<P>
   Key issues involve who defines when care is medically necessary,
how physicians are reimbursed for treating patients and the
liability insurers owe to a physician's patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've ever seen doctors in the Kansas
City area show this much concern over contracts,'' said Rebecca
Gaughan, an Olathe, Kan., ear, nose and throat specialist who is
chairwoman of the carrier relations task force for the Medical
Society of Johnson and Wyandotte Counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the hottest issue in the nation. Doctors are fed up,''
said Gaughan, who has yet to sign her contract with Blue Cross and
is negotiating changes.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the Blue Cross contracts could influence how
doctors respond to contracts with other area insurance carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross officials, who spent this week meeting with
influential physicians, say they are not worried yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly acknowledge the frustrations of physicians, and
we're grateful for their willingness to work with us as much as
they have,'' said Tom Bowser, executive vice president and chief
operating officer of Blue Cross and Blue Shield.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing an impasse, Kansas Insurance Commissioner Kathleen
Sebelius has offered to mediate.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Metropolitan Medical Society of Greater
Kansas City, Sebelius said she was concerned that the situation
might affect ``the ability of consumers in the Kansas City area to
receive the health care they need and have purchased in their
insurance contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical officials also took their complaints to Missouri
Insurance Commissioner Keith Wenzel and Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan.
State insurance officials have limited regulatory powers, but they
can take action to prevent a disruption of services.
</P>
<P>
   Disruption might occur if Blue Cross cannot meet its obligations
to employers and consumers to build a network of health-care
providers for a wide variety of specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians who don't sign could lose considerable income,
because Blue Cross is the biggest area health insurer. And patients
could be forced to find new physicians if their caregivers leave
Blue Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Activism has grown in the last year as physicians _ prevented by
antitrust laws from organizing to protest insurance contracts _
have shared their complaints over the Internet. Feelings have run
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been burned by these contracts,'' said Kansas City
surgeon Charles W. Van Way III.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Medical Society of Greater Kansas City hired
attorneys to dissect insurance contracts, then posted the critiques
on a special Web page, metromedkc.org.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Jantsch, president of the organization, said:
``Traditionally, doctors just signed any managed care contract that
came across their desks. It looked like a bunch of legalese, and
they didn't delve into it.''
</P>
<P>
   But as physicians studied... MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
