<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-OIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIA DELAYS FUEL SHIPMENT SENT TO HELP ITS OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESEVO, Yugoslavia _ Serbian customs officials have held up the
European Union's first effort to donate heating fuel to Serbian
towns controlled by the political opposition, impounding the 14
fuel trucks overnight at this border town.
</P>
<P>
   The oil tankers are headed for the southern Serbian towns of Nis
and Pirot as part of a program called Fuel for Democracy, which is
intended to provide help directly to the Serbian people and the
democratic opposition, bypassing the government of President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia while keeping sanctions in place
against it.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian officials implied in recent weeks that the shipments
would not be hindered, but Wednesday customs officials delayed the
trucks for about seven hours, before finally postponing a decision
on whether to let them pass until the following day.
</P>
<P>
   They kept four senior European diplomats, and the two mayors of
Nis and Pirot, waiting in near-freezing temperatures at the border,
forcing them to seek shelter in a small truckers cafe down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only express surprise and disappointment,'' said Michael
Graham, the head of the European Commission's delegation in
Belgrade, who is organizing the program. ``I see no reason why
anybody should wish to delay heating fuel for the citizens of Nis
and Pirot.''
</P>
<P>
   Nis Mayor Zoran Zivkovic, who is vice president of the
opposition Democratic Party, said the customs officials had allowed
the trucks into Serbia from neighboring Macedonia but were throwing
up bureaucratic obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely that the government will let the shipment into
Yugoslavia, since blocking would be unpopular with a population
already suffering with extensive power cuts because NATO's bombing
of Yugoslavia last spring damaged the power grid, and sanctions
have sliced shipments of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's fuel, even if it only goes to certain
towns, will ease the national energy crisis Serbia is facing. For
the 15 European Union nations, which had to amend the oil embargo
placed upon Serbia in order to make the shipment, its humanitarian
benefits and message to Serbs that they are not being punished for
the faults of their government outweigh any immediate effects it
will have on Milosevic's regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show the European Union cares for the people of
Serbia,'' said Hannu Mantyvaara, the ambassador of Finland, which
now holds the rotating presidency of the European Union. ``Heating
is one of the basic needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Zivkovic, and Mayor Tomislav Panajotovic of Pirot heralded
Wednesday's developments as Serbia's chance to open itself up to
Europe and to begin to end its isolation. They are pinning much on
the success of the first shipments of fuel oil to their towns. The
European Union is looking to extend the program to other towns in
Serbia if the pilot program, worth about $4 million, is successful.
</P>
</TEXT>
