A0872 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-BLUECROSS-DOCTORS-2ND     11-24 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUECROSS-DOCTORS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Many physicians resisting Blue Cross and Blue Shield contracts  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE and JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...didn't delve into it.''
</P>
<P>
   But as physicians studied their contracts more closely, she
said, they became irate because insurers _ and not physicians _ had
the discretion to decide what constituted medically necessary care.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant the plan medical director or an administrator was
making a decision about what is medically necessary,'' Jantsch
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since their role is to save on costs, it's a conflict of
interest for them to say what's medically necessary and then to say
whether they'll pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Patzman, an attorney for the medical society, said
physicians were seeking ``to make the Blues think twice about
shoving a printed contract under their nose for a signature without
any input from doctors _ without any chance to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross' Bowser contends that a lot of the friction stems
from the size and complexity of the new contracts.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 contracts were sent to 3,200 physicians,
covering three health maintenance organizations, two preferred
provider organizations and fee-for-service programs. A physician
who wants to be in every plan must wade through 92 pages.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Blue Cross contracted with physicians separately on
each of its plans. This year, contracts were all sent out at once,
largely to comply with state and federal laws, Bowser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are requirements that apply to all carriers, not just
Blue Cross Blue Shield,'' Bowser said.
</P>
<P>
   But physicians say the contracts give Blue Cross and other
insurers too much control over medical decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question but that doctors are resisting more,''
said Richard Hellman, president-elect of the Metropolitan Medical
Society of Greater Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the debate over who should decide medical necessity,
physicians are rankled by other requirements.
</P>
<P>
   They bristle that contracts give insurers the right to set and
then change reimbursement fees whenever they want but do not
guarantee prompt payment to physicians for care given.
</P>
<P>
   They complain that ``hold harmless'' clauses exempt insurance
companies, but not physicians, from liability if an insurer's
decision to withhold care results in injuries to a patient.
</P>
<P>
   And they criticize a policy that allows Blue Cross to lease its
network to other insurance companies, obligating a physician to
care for patients of the other insurance company, even if it goes
broke.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians say adherence to the bottom line forces them to be
more loyal to insurance companies than to their Hippocratic oath,
treating larger volumes of patients but for lower rates of
reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it's like Wal-Mart,'' Gaughan said. ``I can't see
more patients in an hour without spending less time with each
patient, and I don't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is often not enough time to explore all of a patient's
symptoms, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross is seeking to respond to these concerns, Bowser said.
``This medical necessity issue is one that is of great concern to
physicians and patients and the health insurance industry,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have a very good track record in working with
physicians on this front. We will continue to look at it to make it
as acceptable as it can be in the months ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicians say that whatever happens with Blue Cross will
greatly influence their relations with other insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Dillard, a spokeswoman for HealthNet, said her company
had modified its reimbursement formula in response to physicians'
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're (doctors) an important part of our structure, and
their input is essential on this and other operational matters,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowser said Blue Cross planned to meet further with physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very frustrating times for physicians,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
