<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST SPRING'S INSPIRATION IS BUT A MEMORY FOR KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team that ended up being loathed by parts of middle America
last season for its brazen arrogance and outlaw roster has emerged
this season with an identity as indistinguishable as a blade of
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about the New York Knicks stands out. No character
traits separate them. The same Knicks who finished last year with a
dynamic personality have fallen back into the kind of mediocre
state that nearly ruined them before they awoke for an electric
springtime playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly despondent, the Knicks shrugged their shoulders as to why
they have reverted to their bad habits and shuffled out of the
Staples Center in Los Angeles embarrassed on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Here were the defending Eastern Conference champions, trailing
by 28 points before losing, 100-95, to the Clippers, of all teams.
A mystified Coach Jeff Van Gundy warned that he would have to
``make changes and do something'' to break a pattern that left the
Knicks 2-3 on their road trip and 6-7 on the season. He didn't say
what changes _ lineup moves, a trade or a four-hour practice _ but
Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell suggested that the only
alterations necessary were from within each player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all saying the right things, but it's just lip
service,'' Sprewell said. ``You'd think we would learn from last
year. We've gone through this type thing already, so we should be
beyond that. We definitely don't want to wait until the All-Star
break, half the season, before it finally hits home. We're much
better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Knicks aren't as good as they think. It's too early to
flip on a red alert _ particularly after the team just finished its
most difficult 13-game stretch of its season _ but there are
troubling issues. While there have been devastating injuries to the
front line, leaving the team without Marcus Camby, Larry Johnson
and Patrick Ewing on Tuesday night, the future is uncertain for all
of them. How much tendinitis can Camby withstand? How long before
Johnson's back pain eases? What will Ewing look like upon his
return?
</P>
<P>
   With a little luck and a lot of passion, the Knicks survived
each critical injury and thrived last season on their way to the
finals. They trumped reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think we're still living off last year,''
Houston said. ``In reality, the eighth seed doesn't make it. We got
hot and got on a roll, and I think a lot of us are living off last
year. This is a whole new year. We have to do the things it took to
get us to where we were last year. We're not doing it. We're not
working.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a problem Van Gundy can trace back to August. Very few
Knicks came into the team's practice facility to work out in
preparation for training camp. Once camp began, Sprewell chose to
go on a cross-country drive instead of hustling to join the team.
When the preseason began, the Knicks hardly showed urgency and
finished 2-6.
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove preseason meant nothing, the Knicks popped out to
a 3-0 record before losing seven out of their last 10 games. During
the last two weeks, there has been little practice time because of
a crammed schedule, but on days off, only a handful of Knicks have
come in for extra work.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration has been difficult to come by. Along the way, the
Knicks have lost their rebounding edge, their desire to dive for
loose balls and their intensity on defense. Players from the
Western Conference have fattened their statistics by running right
by the hustle-challenged Knicks, who have been atrocious in
transition. That was glaringly evident against a Clippers team that
scored 39 points on the Knicks in the first quarter and shot 54.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, for one, was embarrassed by Lamar Odom and then Derek
Anderson during the team's miserable start. ``I wasn't ready,''
said Sprewell, who made up for his initial laziness on defense with
a 32-point finish. ``I wasn't into the game early. I think that's
why I'm really upset right now. In that first quarter, it just
wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   A blank look has replaced the defiant stare the Knicks once had.
In the 99 days between Game 5 of the finals and the beginning of
training camp, the Knicks have been searching for something to
provoke them. After falling behind teams like Utah, Boston, Phoenix
and the Clippers by double digits in the first quarter, their pride
has kicked in but only closed the gap so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can get into the game once you've been humiliated,''
Van Gundy said. ``It's no coincidence that all of our road wins
have been when we've jumped out to good starts.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those starts came against Golden State. Now that
emotionally-charged game motivated them. And yet, playing the Miami
Heat a week earlier did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not fired up,'' said a struggling Chris Childs, who was
0 for 3 against the Clippers and is shooting about 31 percent on
the season. ``If someone makes a good play, it's like, OK,
whatever. Being a team means when someone makes a play, it's a team
play. You go and slap the guy on the back, give him a high five and
let him know that you're with him. We're not doing that. It's like
playing is a chore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a personality. We've got to get mean and nasty
again. That's the way this team has always been. Right now, it's
not even close.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
