r a BC-KIND-ACTS-3TAKES-KAN &LR;      11-24 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIND-ACTS-3TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Kindness of strangers helps ease sorrow and hardship  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At first, the question stunned Raymonette
Cole.
</P>
<P>
   David Brown and his wife, Brenda, wanted to know if Cole's son
could live with them for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Not forever, they said, just long enough to give him a little
``tough love.'' Maybe it would help.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Cole, then 12, was beginning to have problems. He
wouldn't do his homework. He was skipping classes. And he was
fighting classmates on a daily basis. His mother felt helpless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe that someone would offer to do that,''
recalls Cole, a single mother of three children.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe she shouldn't have been surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Most stories of kindness pass unnoticed, invisible in a world
full of trauma and despair. But ordinary people do extraordinary
things every day. People like the Browns. Or a nurse named Zahra
Raki, who helped a family thousands of miles away. Or Kansas City
firefighters who saved one family's lifetime of memories.
</P>
<P>
   For Raymonette Cole, the Browns were an answer to a mother's
prayers.
</P>
<P>
   She knew her bright little boy was losing his way. The Browns
knew it, too. They are youth coordinators at the Coles' church.
David is a security officer at Marcus' school, Southeast K-8 Zoo
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns liked Marcus. Perhaps a strong male presence in his
life would turn him around.
</P>
<P>
   Cole rejoiced at their offer. Her son's problems at school were
making life too hard for her and her other two children at home.
</P>
<P>
   This might be the answer.
</P>
<P>
   It was late March when Marcus moved in with the Browns. Their
first priority was for him to learn some rules: Do your chores
before you play outside; do your homework before you play outside,
too. They also gave him a library card and took him to the library.
</P>
<P>
   And they challenged him to raise his grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know all those book reports you haven't done, Marcus?
They're going to be finished now,'' they told him.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus had to show them his homework before he could play. They
showed him what he did wrong and what he did right. But Marcus
admits that he tried to fool them _ especially when it came to
those book reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I copied the stuff at the back of the book without
reading it,'' he says. ``But David is smart. He caught me, and made
me read the book and do it again. I couldn't get away with
nothin'.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote 25 book reports in one month. And his grade point
average zoomed from a 1.1 to a 3.0. He made the honor roll and was
in the 95 percent attendance club.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of May, he moved back home _ changed now from a boy
into a young man.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Marcus, now 13, is on the student council, in a
leadership class and plays football for the Marauders, an
after-school league. He's the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like science now,'' he says, ``and, oh yeah, I haven't got
in one fight this year....David is still guiding me. If he left the
school, I don't know what I'd do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole smiles as her son tells his story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of my child,'' she says. ``He wanted to change
and he had an opportunity to do it. Tell all those single parents
out there not to give up on their children. God brings people to
you that can help. I believe the Browns were our gift from God.
</P>
<P>
   (BREAK)
</P>
<P>
   Zahra Raki looked at the face of the comatose young man in
critical condition at Overland Park (Kan.) Regional Medical
Center's intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, a car crash almost took his life. Now, medical
science was giving him a little more time on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   A ventilator raised and lowered his chest for breath. A cranial
catheter was in his skull relieving pressure on his brain. Four
chest tubes snaked out of his bandaged chest, with more tubes
tethered to his wrists.
</P>
<P>
   He is so handsome and so young, she thought sadly. Raki, an
intensive care nurse at Baptist Medical Center since 1985, knew
from experience that this patient would die.
</P>
<P>
   She learned about him after reading an article in the newspaper.
It was a brief story about a car crash of a 19-year-old with an
Iranian name: Amirarash Mofidi.
</P>
<P>
   His name leapt out at Raki, who was born in Iran. If Mofidi was
Iranian, she thought, perhaps I could help him.
</P>
<P>
   Raki went to the hospital. She learned that Mofidi was a student
at Johnson County Community College from Iran. His parents could
not travel here.
</P>
<P>
   But in the waiting room was an aunt from Texas, and uncles from
Canada and London. All three, however, spoke little English. Raki
immediately stepped in, explaining complicated medical procedures
to them in Farsi.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   Mofidi was in a coma.... MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
