<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIND-ACTS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Kindness of strangers helps ease sorrow and hardship  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...she didn't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   Mofidi was in a coma. As a nurse, Raki thinks comatose patients
can still hear. Amid the whirr of monitors and the foosh of
ventilators, she spoke Farsi to him, too. Sometimes joking with
him. Sometimes telling him stories.
</P>
<P>
   She invited his aunt and uncles to her Overland Park home and
cooked dinners for them. More than once she sat with them in the
waiting room, including one all-night vigil when Mofidi was not
expected to survive.
</P>
<P>
   For 11 days she tried to prepare the family for the inevitable,
but ``they were in complete denial,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That troubled her.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim custom for the dead is that burial must occur
quickly, within 24 hours. No embalming is permitted. How much more
pain would this family endure if their loved one could not be
buried at home? Raki thought. A plan emerged.
</P>
<P>
   She worked the telephone, calling officials in Washington and
Iran. Then 11 days after his crash, Mofidi died on the morning of
his birthday.
</P>
<P>
   His family was stunned. Across the miles, Mofidi's mother and
father were devastated at losing their only child. Added to their
grief was that they could not give him a Muslim burial.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Raki gave them her precious gift: ``It's all taken
care of,'' she told them. ``His body will be there tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Raki, who had never known Mofidi, had pre-paid the numerous
expenses and arranged for his body to be shipped home. It cost her
$5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mofidi died two years ago, Raki is still good friends
with his family, planning to attend his aunt's wedding this summer.
A scholarship was also set up in his name at the college.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did is something anyone else would do for another,''
she says, embarrassed. ``I would have paid for him to get home even
if they never paid me back. I didn't care about that. ICU nurses go
out of their way to treat the families of patients like their own.
We do it on a daily basis. It's why I wanted to be a nurse.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his death, she dreamed she was at a party. There, a
healthy, smiling Amirarash Mofidi approached her, joked with her
and thanked her.
</P>
<P>
   (BREAK)
</P>
<P>
   Brett Henne, 33, always considered himself an animal person. He
once stopped a car driving down the street because a bunch of
children were hanging a kitten out the side window. Almost every
pet he had as a boy was a dog or cat adopted from an animal
shelter. In fact, there wasn't a time in his life when he didn't
have a pet.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the Raytown man read a story about a no-kill animal
shelter in Savannah, Mo., named M'Shoogy's, that rescues hundreds
of stray and abused pets; pets that sometimes don't have legs or
eyes or ears. After reading the story, he called his mother, Sharon
Henne, to make sure she had read it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great what those people are doing for animals,'' he told
her. ``I'd really like to help them somehow. Maybe volunteer
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brett Henne never got that chance.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later he complained of chest pains to his girlfriend
and lay down. His dog, Sandy, was acting even more friendly than
usual, refusing to leave his side, even when Brett's girlfriend
called to her.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Henne died.
</P>
<P>
   As his grieving family arranged for his funeral and obituary,
his mother remembered her conversation with her son about
M'Shoogy's. She decided to ask people to send a donation to
M'Shoogy's in lieu of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after Brett Henne's funeral, Sharon and Kenneth Henne
drove to Savannah. They met M'Shoogy's founders, Gary and Lisa
Silverglat, and handed them more than $850 in donations from Brett
Henne's family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flowers are nice,'' Sharon Henne says, ``but this is something
that will do a lot more good.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Brett really did get to help them after all.''
</P>
<P>
   (BREAK)
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 30, 1998, was Judy and Bill Hidy's 40th wedding
anniversary. To celebrate, they went out to a nice restaurant for
dinner. Then came the phone call: ``Your house is on fire!''
</P>
<P>
   As the Hidys neared their Kansas City home, they could see smoke
curling skyward. Their street was blocked with fire trucks and
police cars.
</P>
<P>
   Their front door was broken in. Glass was shattering. Smoke and
fire alarms were shrieking. Inside, an eerie glow flickered.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Hidys didn't care about the house's contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cry for people, not things,'' Judy Hidy says. They were
more worried about their pet schnauzer, Sybil, whom they'd left in
the basement.
</P>
<P>
   When they saw her in the arms of their neighbor, they sighed
with relief. But then new worries emerged: Where will we sleep?
What about food? Our clothes? All our Christmas decorations?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before a Red Cross volunteer handed them a check
for a week's worth of food. A neighbor offered to house them for
``as long as it took to rebuild.'' Their church organized delivery
of homecooked meals for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People made this easier,'' Judy Hidy says. ``They shared our
burdens. You could feel the prayers for us. Whenever we saw
something sad, we'd see something positive and it helped us get
past it. The average person has no idea what it means to suffer
through a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The full reality didn't hit until dawn. Daylight illuminated a
surrealistic scene. Every step in the house meant wading through
knee-deep charred muck. Even part of Judy Hidy's car had melted in
the blaze. Blackened wood beams hung from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the shock wears off, you think about the familiar
furniture, antique lamps and clocks,'' Hidy says. ``Then you think
about all the stuff you used to have and all the photos.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the fire destroyed...MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
