<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0884 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-GIVING-THANKS-I-1STLD     11-24 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIVING-THANKS-I-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH GOOD SAMARITAN'S HELP, A SHATTERED MAN RETURNS TO HOME, FAMILY
AND HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., N.Y.)  (EDS: Subs 2nd take grafs 4 and 11 for chronological and other
clarifications) 
(ART ADV: Photo (NYT8) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vincent Jones cannot forget the first time he saw the
homeless man, so skinny he was ``holding up his pants with one hand
and holding onto the wall with the other.''
</P>
<P>
   A police officer was rousting the man from his regular square of
sidewalk on 39th Street near Seventh Avenue. And Jones walked past
as he had walked past so many men like him over the years, drinking
and drugging themselves into the grave in the dismal orbit of the
Port Authority bus terminal.
</P>
<P>
   But something _ Jones still finds it hard to explain _ drew him
back. ``The look on that man's face,'' he says now.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Raymond Lawrence, asked Jones for a quarter. Jones gave
him two. He bought him a cup of coffee and a bacon-and-egg
sandwich. He asked the man _ please _ not to spend his money on
alcohol, and then he walked away, sure that he would never see him
again.
</P>
<P>
   That was three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, Jones pulled his battered gray minivan up to a
tiny white, shingled house in Portsmouth, Va., where he stepped out
and then Lawrence stepped out and then Lawrence's 73-year-old
mother, Alberta, walked slowly onto the lawn with her arms in the
air, crying.
</P>
<P>
   It had been three years since she had heard from her son, and,
despite her prayers and those of every parishioner in two Virginia
Baptist churches during that time, she had given him up for dead.
</P>
<P>
   The act of charity that brought about the reunion that October
evening was unlikely enough. But in its details, the story of the
bond that developed between a stocky, easy-going 56-year-old
Garment District delivery man from Queens Village and a troubled,
51-year-old alcoholic becomes even more so.
</P>
<P>
   In the months after the chance encounter on 39th Street, Jones
began to slowly and doggedly work his way into Lawrence's life and
discovered several things: that the homeless man who usually had
trouble opening a bottle of Thunderbird had once been an
accomplished jazz pianist and attended the Berklee College of Music
in Boston. That one of Lawrence's sisters worked in midtown
Manhattan and regularly took the bus in from New Jersey to the Port
Authority, never knowing that her lost brother was usually lying on
the sidewalk one block away.
</P>
<P>
   And that Lawrence's mother, still working as a nurse, lived only
5 miles from where Jones himself had been born and raised, in
segregation-era Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   To Jones, a deeply religious man, few of these things were
particularly surprising and none were coincidences. ``I truly
believe that God led me to Raymond,'' he says. ``Sometimes I would
even say to him, `Lord, why do I keep running into this man?'''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, with his faith and scriptures at the ready, even Jones
finds it hard to believe that today, the same Raymond Lawrence he
knew on the streets of New York will sit down with his mother, and
his nephew's family in Newport News, for his first Thanksgiving
dinner in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In truth,'' Jones said, ``there were times when I said to
myself: I am going to watch this man die out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month, the story of what the handtruck delivery
man did for the homeless man has spread slowly through the Garment
District like a kind of urban legend. Lawrence has taken on the
dimensions of a samaritan too good to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McDonald, a homeless outreach worker who had struggled to
help Lawrence for three years, said, ``I was suspicious at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Randall, executive director of the Fashion Center
Business Improvement District _ who heard about it from the
agency's security guards and later mentioned it to a newspaper
editor _ said she had decided that Jones must be ``totally crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy was a fixture in this district for so long, and he
was not just a nuisance; he was offensive,'' she said of Lawrence,
who was often covered in urine and feces, bellowing at passersby
when he was drunk. Ms. Randall added: ``We were always kind of
hoping that something would happen to him. We didn't think it would
be anything good.''
</P>
<P>
   But when people stop Jones to marvel at what he did he will
usually only pause for a moment and concede: ``I guess it is a
little unusual, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, even this never seemed to occur to
him. At first, he would seek the homeless man out in the middle of
his fabric deliveries and offer a dollar here and there and food
whenever he asked for it.
</P>
<P>
   On a couple of occasions, when he could not stand to see
Lawrence shaking so uncontrollably, Jones would break down and buy
him a bottle of cheap wine. But he soon vowed never to do it again.
And he stopped giving money altogether, because he knew it would
end up in the cash register of the Athens Liquor Store on 40th
Street near the Port Authority. (By all accounts, Lawrence never
used drugs.)
</P>
<P>
   But alcohol was all Lawrence wanted, and it was often not easy
for Jones to refuse him when he saw the frail man _ Lawrence is
5-foot-9 but weighed only 125 pounds; he is 51 but looks 70 _
beaten by fellow homeless men or crying because they had robbed him
in the night.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence's shoes were stolen so often that through the winters,
the toes on his left foot became unbearably painful and one night
in 1998, he said, ``I guess I dialed 911 because I couldn't walk no
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons amputated all of the toes on his left foot and the
little toe on his right foot. For several months, he stayed in a
nursing home in the Bronx, but then, as he always did, he made his
way back to his old haunt, rolling down Seventh Avenue and calling
out to Jones from a shiny new wheelchair. It was stolen within a
week.
</P>
<P>
   The longer Jones knew Lawrence, he said, the more he would try
to keep track of him, enlisting Fashion Center security guards to
let him know when they spotted the homeless man. He also began
slowly trying to pry loose some of Lawrence's past, which usually
came out confused or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, the outreach worker for the Partnership for the
Homeless, said that over his three years' acquaintance with
Lawrence _ even as he helped place him in several detoxification
programs and get him medical care _ he could never win his trust.
``Every time I saw him _ every time,'' said McDonald, ``he would
act like he didn't remember my name.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But where McDonald and others failed to get through to him,
Jones became like a kind of older brother, at times protective and
compassionate, and at other times argumentative and overbearing
like an older brother can be.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With incredible patience, Jones began to piece together a
picture of a lost life. Lawrence had been in the Navy, serving in
San Diego during the Vietnam War; at some point, it seemed, he had
been court-martialed for being AWOL and drunk; he had moved to
Boston and in the 1970s had auditioned for the Berklee College of
Music, playing a jazz piece and a Bach prelude; he was accepted and
lasted for a year before the drinking destroyed his resolve.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two decades, he bounced almost everywhere _ Alaska,
Arizona, New York, California, the Carolinas and back to New York _
but he can now summon few memories of those years.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in early October, Jones extracted the details he
needed: Lawrence had a sister, Mary Helen, somewhere in New Jersey;
a mother somewhere in Virginia and another sister near Boston. In
May 1996, the last time anyone in his family had heard his voice,
he had called that sister to wish her happy Mother's Day. And
somehow, he still remembered her number.
</P>
<P>
   It was with this scrap of the past _ 10 digits _ that Jones' set
himself in motion.
</P>
<P>
   He called Lawrence's sister Cathaleen, who got him in touch with
their mother. On a morning soon after, Jones held a cell phone up
to the homeless man's ear and told him his mother was on the other
end.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence looked at the phone and then said into it, tears
welling in his eyes: ``Is this really my mother?''
</P>
<P>
   The voice of a woman, crying, shot back: ``On October 3, 1948,
they handed me a baby and told me it was you, so I guess it's your
mother, Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   In a life that had seemed on an unswerving trajectory toward
death, that was the turning point.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lawrence said she was asked by friends later: ``How long
have you known this Vincent fellow? And I said, `I've never met the
man before in my life!' They asked what he wanted, and I said, `He
doesn't want anything. He won't take anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was so excited that he wanted to drive Lawrence to
Virginia the next day, but was persuaded to wait until he had gone
though a five-day detoxification program. And so on the afternoon
of Oct. 20, Jones picked up his trembling charge from a midtown
office of the Partnerghip for the Homeless and drove him back to
his own cramped house in Queens Village, which Jones shares with
his longtime girlfriend, Lillie Whitmore.
</P>
<P>
   It was, to say the least, an unusual scene, but Ms. Whitmore was
not exactly surprised. Once, several years earlier, Jones had taken
off time to care for an elderly neighbor in Sullivan County, where
he often goes with friends to hunt. Over the years he knew
Lawrence, he would often come home and tell her how worried he was
about the man. And Jones tried to act on the advice his mother had
given him just before she died: ``Never look down on a person
unless you are picking them up.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the huge differences between Jones and Lawrence, Ms.
Whitmore could also see the similarities between the two men. They
both grew up essentially without fathers and both had principled,
strong-willed mothers. And when Lawrence was not drinking, he was
as humble and hard-working as Jones.
</P>
<P>
   That night, they all dined on baked chicken, corn, peas and
potatoes. Jones asked his girlfriend's son, Brent Whitmore _ a hair
stylist who goes by the monicker Sharnteek, and who has worked for
Mike Tyson, Puff Daddy and Johnnie Cochran _ to come over and see
what he could do about Lawrence's matted hair and beard. Whitmore
pulled out his clippers, took off most of the hair and left
Lawrence with a small, stylish mustache. ``I reconstructed his
whole look,'' he recalled the other day, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence slept in the spare bedroom. And the next morning,
Lawrence and Jones and Jones' howling Walker hound, Max, piled into
the van for a 10-hour drive to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Whitmore watched them leave that morning, she looked at
her beaming boyfriend, whom everyone in his family calls Butch, and
she thought to herself: ``That's Butch, bless his heart. He will do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But before it was all over that day, one final thing happened to
reassure Jones once again that there are no coincidences: half an
hour after they arrived in Portsmouth from their long road trip,
Lawrence suffered a grand mal seizure, brought on by his withdrawal
from alcohol. His mother, a nurse, knew exactly what to do before
he was taken to the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   He spent three weeks in a veterans' hospital. He is now back
home with his mother and has an appetite for the first time in a
year. He has not had a drink in more than a month. But those around
him say they know he wants one, and worry that he will try to get
back to the sidewalks where Jones found him.
</P>
<P>
   He says he thinks often about Jones and is not sure how to feel:
``I don't know why he did that for me,'' he says. ``Maybe I remind
him of somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence has begun to find a new sense of purpose in playing the
piano at his mother's church, the Noble Street Baptist Church in
Portsmouth, where the parishioners had prayed for him for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, he found himself sitting in a clean, grey
thrift-store suit at the other church that prayed for his return,
the Life-Line Full Gospel Baptist Church in Newport News, where his
nephew is the music minister.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had traveled down with a reporter once again to visit the
Lawrence family and check up on his friend Raymond. Before the
service began, he pulled Lawrence close to him and held on to his
thin arm like an older brother. ``Raymond,'' he said, ``you can't
come back to New York City. It's not the same up there, man.
Giuliani is putting all the homeless people in jail. You stay
here.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pews began to fill, he made another request. Would
Lawrence and the choir play his favorite hymn, ``Pass Me Not, Oh
Gentle Savior''?
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the service, Lawrence sat almost hidden behind the
black baby grand piano. Closing his eyes tightly shut and placing
his shaking fingers above the keys, he began to play. The voices of
Mrs. Lawrence and her daughter, Mary Helen Hollins, rose and joined
with the choir and filled the church with sound.
</P>
<P>
   The song ended. Jones rose and smiled and said to no one in
particular: ``That's my buddy Raymond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
