<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIND-ACTS-3RDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Kindness of strangers helps ease sorrow and hardship  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...and all the photos.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the fire destroyed the main sections of the house,
oddly, a hall closet seemed almost untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Hidy opened its door and peered inside. A brown tarp was draped
over something. She lifted it up and saw her daughter's baby
picture staring back.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, stacked neatly and very deliberately was every family
photo and album that the Hidys thought were lost forever. Somehow,
firefighters in the midst of battling the blaze had removed every
photo on every wall, dresser and desk in the house.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Judy Hidy sat down and cried _ tears of joy for the
kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   She cried once more, too, when Floyd Dupree, battalion chief of
Fire Station 35 in Kansas City, arrived with a book for fire
victims.
</P>
<P>
   On its second page was this quote:
</P>
<P>
   ``I shall pass through this way but once; if, therefore, there
can be any kindness I can show or any good thing that I can do, let
me do it now...for I shall never pass this way again....''
</P>
<P>
   (BREAK)
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, a spring storm had pummeled Susan Hall's Raytown
patio. She knew her son's gravestone would need cleaning today.
</P>
<P>
   Her 19-year-old son, Isreal Houk, died in a car crash a week
after Mother's Day 1994. Hall visits his grave often. It gives her
peace.
</P>
<P>
   At his grave she reconnects with Isreal just a little, she says.
Sometimes she talks to him. Sometimes she places flowers there.
Sometimes, she just washes away grass and mud from his headstone.
She's even placed cheery pinwheels at his grave that twirl with
each zippy breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Pinwheels are silly, she said, just like he was.
</P>
<P>
   No one asks her anymore if she still misses him. She still cries
for him when she's alone, remembering and thinking about what might
have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one else can know what I feel,'' she says. ``Oh, I don't
blame anyone. I mean, it has been five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Society tends to give time limits on grief, she says.
</P>
<P>
   But to a grieving mother, the loss of a child hurts as if it
were yesterday, especially so on May 15, the anniversary of her
child's death.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular May afternoon, with the anniversary still a
few days away, Hall visited his grave once more. That's when she
saw it _ a note, fluttering in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Pinned beneath one whirling pinwheel was a crumpled piece of
blue paper. Rain-soaked and dirty, the handwriting was still
legible. As she read it, Hall began to cry:
</P>
<P>
   I have watched the flowers change here for five years. I have
also changed my daughter's for five years. She died May 8, 1994, a
few days before Isreal....My prayers are with you this week. _
Anita Huffman.
</P>
<P>
   Hall read, re-read, then read once more the note, whispering
each word out loud. Somewhere, a stranger and also a mother _ in
fact, a grieving mother _ had taken the time to write her a note.
And somewhere this stranger was praying for her.
</P>
<P>
   Hall stood up, now smiling, holding the message as if it were
precious gold.
</P>
<P>
   She found the gravesite of Anita Huffman's daughter, placed a
pinwheel there, ``one with feminine colors,'' she says, and a
reciprocal note for Huffman. The two mothers finally met one summer
day, when both were at the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hall keeps the note in a corner drawer of her
grandmother's oak dresser, sandwiched inside special greeting cards
from friends and family. The three-by-five inch paper is wrinkled,
with dirt smearing over a few words. Its corners curl where a hole
was once punched through it. But it's still legible. And very
precious.
</P>
<P>
   (BREAK)
</P>
<P>
   Missy Hetland's car quit on Missouri 7 near Garden City.
</P>
<P>
   Hetland, a freshman at College of the Ozarks near Branson, was
on her way to visit family in Kansas. But her car, a lemon yellow
1978 Ford Festiva, wasn't up to it.
</P>
<P>
   She walked to the nearest house, the home of Paul and Rennie
Statham, and asked to call some friends. Paul Statham, who works on
cars, thought maybe he could help. Hetland reminded him of his
grown daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, her friends arrived, James and Mary Taylor of
Harrisonville. But the Taylors, grandparents of her college
roommate, knew nothing about repairing cars.
</P>
<P>
   Statham stepped in. He recharged the car's battery, but it
promptly sputtered out a few feet down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's the alternator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He went back to his house and returned, driving his tractor to
tow her car to his garage. Then he went to the auto parts store,
bought an alternator and installed it.
</P>
<P>
   An hour and a half later, Hetland was on her way again. But
again, the car died.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I know it's the voltage regulator,'' he told them. But the
auto parts store had now closed, so Hetland spent the night with
the Taylors in Harrisonville. They would meet Statham at the auto
store at 8 a.m. the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Statham just knew he had a spare voltage regulator in
his barn loft. He rummaged through his box of car parts. At
midnight, he found it and worked on the car before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   This time the car hummed.
</P>
<P>
   He drove it to a nearby parking lot, then drove his own car to
the parts store. As the Taylors and Hetland drove up, he met them,
grinning wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already fixed,'' he told them. Statham wouldn't accept
any money for his work, but he did ask Hetland to promise not to
set out driving on a long trip without checking out her car first.
</P>
<P>
   As Hetland slid into the driver's seat, a note was on the
steering wheel: God Bless and good-luck.
</P>
<P>
   Statham says he helped Hetland to pay back a personal debt he
owed a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chance to return a favor that someone once did for
me,'' he says. ``It used to be a nicer world...Maybe it still is,
sometimes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
