<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      11-24 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: GORE, RUNNING IN IOWA, RUNS HARD FROM CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Pa.)  (rk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COUNCIL BLUFFS, Iowa _ As Vice President Al Gore tries to sell
himself as his own man, unencumbered by President Clinton and his
scandals, it is hardly a surprise that he plays down his ties to
the politician he hopes to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore may be taking things to an extreme. He has has
practically banned the dreaded ``C word'' from his vocabulary. In a
campaign swing on Monday and Tuesday that brought him before
several partisan audiences in southeastern and western Iowa and in
a quick flight to Chicago for a fund-raising dinner, Gore mentioned
the president only once _ and only because he did not have much
choice.
</P>
<P>
   At the event in Chicago, he was listing the administrations that
had advocated a nuclear test ban treaty _ ``Clinton, Carter, Bush
and Reagan administrations'' _ so he could not easily have excluded
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Gore goes through verbal contortions to avoid
mentioning Clinton. At an open meeting of undecided Democratic
voters Tuesday in this town on the western border of Iowa, one
person stood up and asked Gore to describe the best thing that has
happen to this country in his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's instinct was to blow the Clinton administration's horn _
and his own. But that was no easy trick given that he did not dare
mention the president.
</P>
<P>
   So, using fractured sentences and odd tenses, the vice president
cited the administration's economic accomplishments but did not
cite the administration. It was as if he took his old talking
points and excised any mention of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have the strongest economy in the history of the
United States,'' Gore said, citing the ``end of the recession of
the Reagan-Bush years'' and ``having 20 million new jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The pretend-Clinton-does-not-exist approach seemed to work. Gore
received a hearty applause.
</P>
<P>
   A Chairman on a Tightrope
</P>
<P>
   When Mayor Edward Rendell of Philadelphia was installed as
general chairman of the Democratic National Committee several weeks
ago, some who back Gore's rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New
Jersey, groused that Rendell had been a bit too friendly with the
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The concern was that Rendell's past relationship with Gore would
interfere with the custom that a party chairman is supposed to be
neutral in a contested primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's backers would not have been heartened when Rendell
introduced the vice president on Monday at a lavish fund-raising
dinner in Chicago that raised about $700,000 for the national
party.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Rendell was even-handed. ``We have two candidates who
could both stand up and be president of the United States today,''
he said. ``And they are right on the issues!''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Rendell edged toward the Gore camp: ``We also
have, as I said, two good candidates _ but one who has served this
country in a way that I think is unparalleled.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell went on to recall that he had once described Gore as the
best vice president in history. But then, not wanting to be accused
of hyperbole, he scaled back his praise a bit, saying that ``no
question about it,'' he was the best No. 2 ``in our lifetimes.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pop Quiz on Football
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hansen, a retired civilian employee for the military,
ambled up to Gore at the open meeting here and announced, ``I have
a pop quiz for you, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president visibly winced before managing a meek,
``OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Who could blame him? After Gov. George W. Bush of Texas flunked
a pop quiz on foreign leaders earlier this month from a Boston
television reporter, politicians are on the lookout.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Gore, Hansen was only teasing. He asked him which
team he favored for the national college football championship:
Florida State, Nebraska or Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly a stumper. When Hansen mentioned Nebraska, he
stomped his foot. And Nebraska, of course, borders Iowa, so it was
no surprise which team is the favorite in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   It was an easy pander for the vice president. ``Nebraska's
looking good,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   A Bridge to Local Issues
</P>
<P>
   Except when he steps off the stairs from Air Force Two, it is
easy to forget these days that Al Gore is the understudy to the
leader of the free world. On trips, he eschews the
vice-presidential seal. And he eschews a tie (except at big-money
fund-raisers like the one in Chicago).
</P>
<P>
   But Gore may have gotten carried away with his
I'm-just-a-man-of-the-people theme when he addressed members of a
senior citizens center in Fort Madison, in the southeast corner of
Iowa. He sounded like Mayor Gore when he mentioned how he and the
local congressman, Leonard Boswell, had been chatting about repairs
needed on a nearby bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incidentally, Leonard's been talking to me about this
bridge,'' Gore said. After describing how the lanes curved, Gore
asked his audience, ``Does that need to be changed?''
</P>
<P>
   By tailoring his remarks for the locals, the vice president may
have won some converts. But he also gave more fodder to Bradley,
who likes to portray himself as the purveyor of big ideas.
</P>
<P>
   An Absent Star Next Door
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising dinner on Monday at the sprawling home of Lou
and Ruth Weisbach in the Chicago suburbs was a success.
</P>
<P>
   But while Gore was a big draw, several of the Weisbach's guests
seemed more interested in the man who lives next door: Michael
Jordan, the basketball star. In case there was any doubt, the gate
to the star's driveway was decorated with a huge number 23, the
number on his Chicago Bulls uniform. (No one could spot a basket in
the driveway, though.)
</P>
<P>
   It is not likely that Jordan was invited. He has already given
money to his fellow veteran of the NBA, the former senator from New
Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
