<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AIRCRASH-PILOT-730(2T     11-24 2038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-PILOT-730(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPTAIR PILOT, FROM PRIVILEGED BACKGROUND TO A TERRIBLE
PROMINENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AIRCRASH) 
(js) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL with JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Back in Kafr el-Dabusi, a farming community set
against the lush fields and irrigation canals of the Nile delta,
the villagers still remember the dashing young airman who would
circle in his small plane, scaring the pigeons from their roosts
and sending the women trilling in wonder.
</P>
<P>
   It was the early 1960s, an era of great national pride, when the
1952 revolution that toppled King Farouk and Gamal Abdel Nasser's
1956 nationalization of the Suez Canal still fueled a contagious
headiness. The airman, Gameel el-Batouty, was a kind of local hero,
the youngest son of the village's most prominent family, seen as
part of a new generation coming of age in Egypt, eager to explore
new horizons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget how proud we all were of him,'' said a
brother, Fakhri el-Batouty, 70.
</P>
<P>
   There was reason for that pride to endure. Batouty went on to
serve in the military during a time of war with Israel. He was a
flight instructor, and many of the pilots he trained, like him,
later joined one of Egypt's national companies, EgyptAir, assuming
a place in that great state-run enclave of privilege.
</P>
<P>
   In the chaos of modern Egypt, friends, relatives and other
associates said, Batouty over the course of his life seemed to
embody stability _ as a good Muslim, a devoted family man who kept
in touch with his rural roots to the point that he had promised to
finance the construction of a new village mosque back in Kafr
el-Dabusi.
</P>
<P>
   Today, all of Egypt knows about Batouty, but it is an awful
prominence he has suddenly gained, one that has nothing to do with
his life of accomplishment and modest hometown stardom. Batouty was
among 217 people who plunged to their deaths aboard EgyptAir Flight
990 on Oct. 31, and U.S. investigators, in their best theory of
what happened at 33,000 feet, suspect that Batouty may have caused
the crash deliberately, by pointing the Boeing 767 and everyone
aboard on a fatal path toward the sea.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators, who have come to no formal conclusions, have
based their working theory of the crash on several facts: there is
no evidence of mechanical trouble before the plane began its
descent; the cockpit voice recorder appears to show that Batouty,
who was not scheduled to fly the plane until later in the flight,
was in fact in command of the plane when, after the pilot had
briefly left his seat, several fatal actions were taken, starting
with the autopilot being disengaged and the plane's nose being
pushed down in a steep dive. Those actions, the investigators
believe, are hard to explain other than by attributing them to an
intentional desire to doom the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, including agents with the FBI, have only recently
begun a meticulous examination of Batouty's life, and there is no
way to forecast what, if anything, they might find in the way of
evidence or explanations to support or discredit their suspicions.
And no one, investigators included, has offered anything
approaching a rationale for why Batouty might have crashed the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Egyptian authorities have made available no
detailed information about Batouty, who was a relief pilot aboard
the flight and died at the age of 59, just months away from
retirement. They have said only that they know of nothing unusual
in his personal and medical background.
</P>
<P>
   But the picture painted of Batouty by those who knew him best
seems, absent a secret life yet to be uncovered, starkly at odds
with any notion of someone who might have done what the U.S.
investigators suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew Batouty remember him as a generous friend
untouched by greed. He moved easily, they said, between two worlds
_ the familiar one of Egypt and the new frontier of the United
States, his regular destination as a co-pilot. He regularly piloted
the plane himself on the prestigious Cairo-New York-Los Angeles
route.
</P>
<P>
   On long layovers in America, he arranged first-class medical
treatment for his ailing youngest daughter.
</P>
<P>
   From his salary, and by selling land inherited from his father,
Batouty also managed to acquire the badges of prosperity of Egypt's
urban upper middle-class. He owned a late-model car and three
residences, including a villa on the sea and another outside Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud that Captain Gameel is from this village,'' said
Said Harb, a farmer in Kafr el-Dubusi.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   u axxnt22 nt26 nt06 nt11 nt33 &QL; 
uaxx &QL; 
 &UR; BC-AIRCRASH-PILOT-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CAIRO, Egypt: Kafr el-Dubusi. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Batouty was born March 4, 1940, the seventh and last child of a
prosperous landowning family in Kafr el-Dabusi, not far from the
provincial capital of Mansoura, near the eastern branch of the
Nile. Even today, the village has no telephone service and only one
paved road.
</P>
<P>
   As mayor, and as head of the dominant family, his father, Hamed
Batouty, was something of a feudal lord, overseeing the local
villagers who grew corn, bananas, rice and other crops on the
family's 60 acres of farmland.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty attended the Lycee in Mansoura, an elite school where
classes were taught in both French and Arabic, living there with an
elder sister and her husband. A cousin, Dr. Fathi Batouty, who
attended the school with him, remembered Gameel as a happy-go-lucky
but good student, who was handsome and not averse to chasing after
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Like other family members of his generation, Batouty saw his
future in Cairo, where two of his three older brothers, one of them
Fakhri, had already gravitated in pursuit of university degrees and
professional careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came to Cairo, we liked it,'' said Fakhri el-Batouty,
a retired executive in Egypt's state-owned Hotel Tourism Company.
``We did not want to return to the village because there were no
careers for us there.''
</P>
<P>
   Such individual journeys from countryside to city had already
begun to transform post-revolutionary Egypt. Leaders like Anwar
el-Sadat and Hosni Mubarak made their way from the black-earthed
farmland of the Nile delta.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike those men and their closest associates, Batouty did
not enter the army or air force. Instead, he moved in with another
sister in Cairo and persuaded his father to pay for his training in
a civilian career.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty would become a pilot.
</P>
<P>
   When Batouty did move to the air force in the mid-1960s, friends
said, it was not by choice. With tension building again between
Israel and its Arab neighbors, Nasser had embarked on a
pilot-training program, part of a military buildup that preceded
the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty was assigned to the air force academy, where Mubarak,
the fighter pilot who would later become president, was the
commandant. But as an instructor, Batouty had no place among the
combat aviators and their Russian-made MiG jets; his job was with
students, in single-engine propeller planes.
</P>
<P>
   Even as an air force major, Batouty continued to work at a
civilian aviation institute. He returned there full time as a
senior flight instructor in 1983. In one way or another, his
colleagues estimate, he served as teacher to men who make up fully
half of EgyptAir's 533 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, some of those former students persuaded Batouty that
he ought to seize an opportunity to see the world. At their urging,
and at the age of 47, he joined EgyptAir in 1987 as a first
officer. He would eventually earn a salary of more than $6,000 a
month _ more than 40 times the average salary in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty also became eligible for a wide range of benefits, the
kinds of hidden luxuries that Egypt's state-run institutions have
historically provided to high-ranking employees to substitute for
generally substandard pay _ free flights for family members and
free medical care at the company's own hospital.
</P>
<P>
   By 1989, he was winning assignments flying the Boeing 767-300,
whose long range had only that year enabled EgyptAir to begin
nonstop service between Cairo and New York. Still, Batouty remained
a first officer, outranked and outpaid by younger men who had
joined EgyptAir earlier in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Batouty's friends, including Mark Abdelazim, a concierge
in a Manhattan apartment building who knew Batouty for 10 years,
said that he had been disappointed not to have been promoted. But
Walid Murad, head of the EgyptAir pilots' association, said that,
because of his relatively advanced age and limited airline
experience, Batouty had never expected to become a full pilot and
had never taken the airline pilots' test required to secure
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his colleagues say, Batouty was respected and treated as
an equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called him captain,'' said Hamza Emeira, a fellow EgyptAir
pilot. ``Always.''
</P>
<P>
   As a husband and a father, Batouty straddled several worlds, his
friends and neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people like him come to the city, they keep their good,
conservative rural traditions and mingle with city life, and
mostly, they are the best,'' said Sawsan Kamal, a close family
friend who is the wife of an EgyptAir pilot.
</P>
<P>
   An observant Muslim, Batouty prayed five times a day, in
accordance with Islamic teachings, his relatives said. He made a
pilgrimage last winter to Mecca, accompanied by his wife, Umayma
Dahi, whom he had married in 1965 and is the mother of the couple's
five children.
</P>
<P>
   Only occasionally did he return to his home village, but he
usually did so during Ramadan, when he would distribute cash to the
poor in accordance with Islamic tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In Cairo, using money from the sale of his inherited hometown
property, he put aside funds to help smooth the Batouty children's
way into marriage; he bought apartments for the two eldest, Amr,
now 29, and Sally, 27, after they found spouses.
</P>
<P>
   In his religious beliefs, Batouty showed no sign of extremism,
his friends said.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, he blocked his son Mohammed's choice of a bride,
exercising traditional veto power. But he relented earlier this
year, and gave an engagement party for his son, now 22 and a recent
graduate of Egypt's police academy.
</P>
<P>
   But the trials he experienced with his youngest child, Aya, who
was born in 1990, may have presented Batouty with his biggest
personal test.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, whom he called ``my blessing,'' was diagnosed at
the age of 5 with skin cancer. She was treated with chemotherapy by
Egyptian doctors, lost her hair and good humor, and still showed no
sign of getting better.
</P>
<P>
   Not until three years later, when Batouty, in despair, brought
his daughter with him to the United States, did he learn that Aya
had been misdiagnosed. She was suffering not from cancer but lupus,
an immune system disorder that cannot be cured but responds
favorably to treatment.
</P>
<P>
   After an intervention by Hamdi el-Tahan, a friend and member of
the Egyptian parliament, EgyptAir's chairman, Mohammed Fahim Rayan,
approved a loan of about $6,000 for Batouty to help pay for Aya's
medical treatment in the United States. Batouty nevertheless felt
compelled to sell more land to cover the medical bills, Tahan said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that he was in financial trouble was disputed by Dr.
Mohsen Hamza, a Beverly Hills neurologist who is married to
Batouty's niece and who helped arrange the daughter's treatment at
the University of California at Los Angeles Medical Center. Hamza
insisted that the treatment had not imposed a financial burden on
Batouty, and that the girl had recently been pronounced well on her
way to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Cairo on what would be his final flight, Batouty
seemed to have been busily preparing himself for retirement, which
would have become mandatory in March.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Batouty told friends, he intended to spend time with
his family. And knowing that free trips to the United States would
soon become a thing of the past, he had promised to take his wife
to New York with him in December, to celebrate their 35th wedding
anniversary. They had been hoping for the celebration to be on New
Year's Eve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
