<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-AIRLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO GROUNDS ENTIRE FLEET OF AIRLINE INVOLVED IN CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Texas)   (bl)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Citing safety concerns about aircraft operated by
Mexico's third-largest airline, known as Taesa, aviation
authorities have ordered the airline to ground its fleet and
suspend operations.
</P>
<P>
   The government order came late Tuesday, two weeks after a Taesa
commuter plane crashed west of Mexico City, killing all 18
passengers and crew members.
</P>
<P>
   The order grounded the 27 aircraft operated by Transportes
Aereos Ejecutivos SA, a low-cost operator founded in 1988, and left
thousands of passengers scrambling to exchange Taesa tickets for
seats on aircraft run by Mexico's two larger airlines, Aeromexico
and Mexicana.
</P>
<P>
   Taesa flights were suspended between several Mexican cities and
three U.S. destinations: Oakland, Calif.; Chicago; and Laredo,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Taesa is heavily in debt and has been trying a financial
restructuring. The intervention raised questions about whether the
airline could survive financially, even if the government
inspectors who were swarming over the carrier's aircraft and books
Wednesday were eventually to recertify the company to operate new
flights.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by Mexican officials, with participation by
U.S. technicians, is continuing into the causes of the Nov. 9 crash
of a Taesa DC9-31. After the crash, Mexican inspectors also stepped
up inspections of all Taesa aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``A series of anomalies and incidents have come to light, which
the airline has been correcting but have occurred repeatedly,''
Aaron Dychter Poltarek, Mexico's deputy secretary of communications
and transport, told reporters as he announced his suspension order.
``This measure will let us verify all the airline's systems and
procedures, in its business and in its aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1.7 million passengers flew on Taesa flights in the
first three quarters of 1999, Dychter said. The company has
controlled about 10 percent of Mexico's air passenger market,
specializing in destinations between Mexico City and Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Taesa considers safety to be the No. 1 priority, it will
abide by this decision, gladly collaborating with authorities so
that all these doubts can be cleared up,'' the company said in a
statement faxed to news organizations Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Taesa has 3,000 employees, 300 of whom are flight attendants.
Some of the flight attendants have been trying to decertify their
union, which is allied with Mexico's governing party, and to
affiliate with a more aggressive independent union. After the Nov.
9 crash, Alejandra Barrales, the leader of the independent union,
accused Taesa of filing deceptive maintenance logs about several of
its aircraft to cover up what she called recurring mechanical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   A Lear jet operated by Taesa on a charter flight crashed in June
1994 at Dulles International Airport, killing all 10 passengers and
two crew members. The National Transportation Safety Board reported
after an investigation that the probable causes of the accident
were ``poor decision making, poor airmanship and relative
inexperience of the captain.''
</P>
<P>
   Orders to ground an airline's entire fleet for safety reasons
are rare. John Macdonald, a partner at Aviation Management
Services, a company in Miami that services Latin America's airline
industry, said he could not recall any other time when the entire
fleet of an airline in the region had been grounded for safety
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. aviation regulators temporarily grounded Valujet Airlines
on concerns about safety after one of its jets crashed in the
Everglades in May 1996, killing all 110 people aboard. That airline
subsequently renamed itself Airtran Airways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
