<HEADLINE>
EAST CAPE'S TACKLE MAN A REEL CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENAVISTA, Mexico _ Rent tackle in this isolated East Cape
mecca for saltwater anglers and you'll encounter Steve Chism.
</P>
<P>
   And when you do you may well think to yourself, like I did,
``I'll bet you there's a real character.''
</P>
<P>
   Chism is the first to agree: ``I'm sure some people come away
with that notion, and some of them know it's for a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the type of wry humor one can expect from a man who spends
his workday in a sparse, fenced-in hut that resembles a cage. But
the tiny facility is as close to paradise as the owner of the
tackle concession at the 60-room Hotel Buenavista Beach Resort has
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different way of life; it's not just a job,''
Chism said in a frail voice that emits drawn-out words. ``There is
not a whole lot of pressure or anything. The guys come through,
they get the tackle, you talk to the people a little bit, then
they're gone and you do whatever else there you have to do for the
day. Maybe go do something else (errands) you want to do and be
back in time to pick (the tackle) up.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Bay Area native first became enamored with the
East Cape during a fishing trip in 1976. Soon he was overcome by
the draw of angling and the quaint, docile community _ so much so
that by 1981 he up and quit his job gunsmithing and selling
firearms and fishing tackle in Oakland and moved down. Shortly
afterward he was offered a job by the hotel's owner, ``Chuy''
Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time there were 13 rooms, so (my duties included)
anything that was necessary _ from doing the payroll to washing the
dishes,'' the 57-year-old Chism explained. ``Whatever, you name it;
if it had to be done, somebody did it and a lot of times it was
me.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1985 he was able to purchase property and a home two miles up
the highway. Today his sole income is derived from the tackle
concession, which also rents kayaks and snorkel gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's enough that I can do pretty much what I want to do,'' he
said. ``All the toys are mine. I don't owe anybody money or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   From hired hand to business owner, Chism is somewhat of an
institution in these parts. ``He's like the old man,'' said the
hotel's manager Axel Valdez, 26, son of the proprietor.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't get a hint of the respect he garners from the title
or job description on Chism's business card; he doesn't have one.
Heck, his rental operation isn't even named.
</P>
<P>
   However, one can't miss that inimitable beard, which only
further belies his reverence. Blond on the outside, salt and pepper
in the middle, the wiry, largely unkempt affair hasn't been trimmed
since Christmas Eve 1997. ``Nobody confuses me with Santa Claus,''
Chism clarified.
</P>
<P>
   Yet image is of little concern in Southern Baja California, as
one can tell by his broken shoes and a watchband that has seen much
better days. ``You don't have to keep up with the Joneses or
anything like that,'' he said. ``I probably haven't bought a hat or
a T-shirt since I've been here; (visitors) are always giving you
hats or something. And I just keep the raggedy shoes around till
they fall off.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Chism gets ribbed about his appearance _ and his
demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He observes things in a different manner,'' Axel Valdez said.
``When he sees something's wrong, he'll be sure to tell you it's
wrong, but he won't tell you how to fix it, so that's a big help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
