<SLUG> BC-BROKERAGE-DISCUSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRUDENTIAL SECURITIES CLOSE TO CASH DEAL TO BUY WEST COAST
INVESTMENT BANK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   By PATRICK McGEEHAN with LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The brokerage unit of Prudential Insurance Co. of
America is in the final stages of negotiations to buy Volpe Brown
Whelan &AMP; Co., one of the last independent investment banks on the
West Coast, people close to the talks said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential Securities, the nation's fifth-largest securities
firm, is expected to announce the cash acquisition soon, possibly
next week, these people said. Executives of the two firms are
expected to continue discussions this weekend, but as with any
deal, talks could still fall apart until an agreement is signed.
The purchase price, which Prudential does not plan to disclose,
could not be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Volpe, a private firm, would give Prudential a bigger
presence in the hottest investment sector, emerging technology
companies. It would also mark the end of an era, of sorts. After
commercial banks gobbled up its competitors, Volpe is the last of a
breed of San Francisco-based investment banking boutiques that
specialized in financing young companies in Silicon Valley and the
San Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal that was announced last month, Chase Manhattan is
buying one of Volpe's larger local competitors, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist,
for $1.35 billion. Chase hopes to complete that transaction before
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Volpe was chief executive of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist before he
founded Volpe in 1986. Volpe could not be reached for comment; a
spokesman for Volpe declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Prudential Securities also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential, which has about 6,500 brokers nationwide, has been
trying to raise its profile as a stock underwriter. In June, it
paid an undisclosed amount to acquire Vector Securities
International, a small investment bank that specializes in health
care financing. Vector's founder, D. Theodore Berghorst, was named
Prudential's top health care banker
</P>
<P>
   Prudential has been looking for somebody to head its technology
banking business since last month when David Weild left that
position to run Prudential Securities.com, the firm's online
operations. Weild's successor would most likely come from Volpe if
a deal is completed, said one person inside Prudential.
</P>
<P>
   An acquisition by Prudential would end an alliance between Volpe
and another Wall Street firm, Credit Suisse First Boston. Since
March 1997, Credit Suisse First Boston has owned 25 percent of
Volpe through a venture that was intended to give it an entry into
the technology industry on the West Coast. At the time, Credit
Suisse First Boston and other big Wall Street firms were struggling
to make inroads in Silicon Valley, which has been the prime
breeding ground for the most popular stocks in the long bull market
of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, First Boston has spent huge sums to hire two teams
of investment bankers and research analysts that have made the
alliance with Volpe much less important to the firm. Early this
year, Credit Suisse First Boston hired the entire technology
banking team away from Deutsche Bank, the giant German bank. In
July, Credit Suisse First Boston followed up by hiring about 35
members of Deutsche Bank's health care investment banking team.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves have helped Credit Suisse First Boston establish
itself as a major underwriter of first-time stock offerings this
year. Last quarter, no investment bank underwrote more initial
offerings than Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, which has operated largely independent of First Boston,
has played a smaller and less lucrative role in the Internet stock
boom. This year, it has been the lead underwriter of a few initial
offerings and a co-manager of many others, including one this month
for Next Level Communications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
