r n BC-CARO-SLAYING-LADN     11-24 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARO-SLAYING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOUNDED MOTHER WON'T TALK TO POLICE ABOUT SONS' SLAYINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY KRYSTN SHRIEVE WITH LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORPARK, Calif. -- The mother of three boys fatally shot in
their hilltop mansion was recovering from a bullet wound to the
head but declined to talk to investigators, who said no arrest was
expected for at least a week.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies by the Ventura County coroner determined that each of
the youngsters died from a single gunshot wound to the head.
Officials refused to divulge the caliber of the gun used or whether
the bullets recovered during the autopsies could have matched a
handgun found in the victims' house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we collect the bullets we have to ship them to
forensics,'' sheriff's Deputy Eric Nishimoto said. ``It's not a
15-minute test. Those tests will take a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys' father, Dr. Xavier J. Caro, a prominent rheumatologist
with a practice in suburban Los Angeles, called 911 about 11:20
p.m. Monday to report the shootings in his Presilla Drive home.
When emergency personnel arrived at his home, he answered the door
holding his infant son, who was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Caro spent most of Tuesday being questioned by police and
remained in seclusion Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County sheriff's investigators continued to gather
evidence in the slayings of Xavier ``Joey'' Caro Jr., 11, who was
found dead in his bedroom, and Michael Anthony Caro, 8, and
Christopher Laurence Caro, 5, who were killed in the room they
shared.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, Socorro ``Cora'' Caro, was found in another room
with a gunshot wound to the upper right side of her head. She
underwent surgery at Los Robles Regional Medical Center, and her
condition was upgraded Wednesday from critical to serious, said
spokeswoman Kris Carraway-Bowman. She also was taken off a
ventilator that had helped her to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Officials tried to interview Cora Caro but she ``chose not to
speak with them,'' Nishimoto said. A lack of a statement from Cora
Caro would force authorities to rely more heavily on the physical
evidence and slow down the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three bodies here,'' sheriff's Sgt. Steve Bourke
said. ``Conceivably, the investigation could take three times as
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials refused again to identify any suspects in the case,
but reiterated earlier statements they are not focusing on anyone
outside the Caro home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at all the different alternatives still,''
Nishimoto said Wednesday. ``Yesterday we did the gathering and
today we're doing the sifting. We have hundreds of statements to go
out and validate.''
</P>
<P>
   Cora Caro's mother and husband had called the hospital Tuesday
to check on her progress, and she received calls from friends and
her family priest on Wednesday, Carraway-Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Helmstedter, principal at Santa Rosa Elementary School,
where all three slain boys attended classes, released a statement
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Caro volunteered in each of the boys' classrooms.
Teachers described her as eager and ready to help,'' the statement
said. ``She was willing to do what it takes from running off papers
to listening to students read. She stopped first thing each time
she came in to hug Joey. She was positive and helpful to the
students.''
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 50 or 60 parents at the school _ where the boys
were in kindergarten, second and fifth grades _ attended a meeting
Wednesday with district psychologist Candra Shiney-Norris, who
talked with them about how to address their child's emotional
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Parents were mostly concerned about how how to talk with their
children about the shootings, and wanted to know how much to reveal
about the incident. Some parents said their children had trouble
sleeping Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have complete knowledge of who did this, so some
children were worried that there was someone out there who might
attack their house,'' Shiny-Norris said. ``They need to be
reassured that they are safe. What to say depends on the age of the
child. Kids are going to have a lot of questions and their parents
are a good resource and should listen and take the cue from their
child.''
</P>
<P>
   At Dr. Caro's office on Wednesday, workers fielded calls from
concerned patients who mostly offered their sympathy, said an
employee who did not identify herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of calls expressing sympathy,'' the
employee said. ``He's a great doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The employee recalled how Caro would sometimes spend time in the
office with his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always laughing with them, always cheerful with the
kids when they'd stop by sometimes with their mom or
grandparents,'' the employee said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
