<SLUG> BC-OUT-BASICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP THE FISH FRESH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY BRIGHTENBURG  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ OK, so you've made your catch, and it's a keeper.
What's the best way to prepare and preserve it to ensure the best
quality at the kitchen table?
</P>
<P>
   Bleed the fish _ especially tuna, bonito and yellowtail _ to
minimize foul taste by clipping the gill or making an incision
around the base of the tail.
</P>
<P>
   Then ice the fish, if possible; private boaters have the
advantage here. If ice is not available, keep the fish cool by
stashing it in the shade and periodically wetting the gunnysack.
</P>
<P>
   Determine who will fillet the fish. You can take the fish home
and do it yourself; private boaters can fillet it on board. Party
boaters can pay crew members to perform the task.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, make certain the fillet is placed into a plastic,
zip-fastened bag and nearly sealed close. Then dip the entire bag
into water _ the baitwell in many cases _ to release all air and
reduce the risk of freezer burn. Air is the culprit and must be
kept clear of the meal if it is to be frozen.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternate to filleting, some landings _ frequently those
that cater to multiday and long-range passengers _ offer canning or
smoking services. Determine those options before embarking on the
journey.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, release anything that is more than you can use or give
away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saltwater fishing tips are offered occasionally by San Diego
calico-bass angler and plastic-lure tactician Barry
Brightenburg. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
