<HEADER>
A0907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      11-24 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: RECOVERING FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The government announced that it has recovered more than $120
million stolen when the previous military government was in power
and that it has frozen $600 million in overseas banks. Since the
inauguration of a civilian government in May, President Olusegun
Obasanjo has made the recuperation of stolen assets a priority.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: AID FOR THE DELTA
</P>
<P>
   The government announced emergency projects totaling more than
$50 million to develop the oil-rich Niger Delta. Soldiers were
deployed last weekend to the area, which has remained mired in
desperate poverty, after 12 police officers were killed during a
surge of violence.
</P>
<P>
   KENYA: PRESIDENT DENIES CORRUPTION
</P>
<P>
   President Daniel arap Moi, in a rare interview, denied to a
radio journalist that he had invested large sums of money in a
Swiss bank. A recent issue of the influential British newsletter
Africa Confidential said Moi and his family had invested ``suspect
funds'' in Switzerland. Moi is under rising pressure from foreign
lenders to curb corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: CROWD CONTROL
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese announced new rules for public gatherings, requiring
assemblies larger than 200 to obtain approval from local public
security authorities. Gatherings larger than 3,000 will require the
approval of security offices at a higher level. The rules follow
efforts to stamp out the Falun Gong spiritual movement, which
shocked officials by gathering 10,000 members for a protest in
Beijing in April.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: CO-DEFENDANT ACCUSES OUSTED LEADER
</P>
<P>
   The former head of the Civil Aviation Authority, Aminullah
Chaudhry, has agreed to testify against Pakistan's ousted prime
minister, Nawaz Sharif. According to a prosecutor, Chaudhry has
said that he was acting on Sharif's orders when he attempted to
keep an airliner from landing in Karachi in October, endangering
the lives of 198 passengers, including the army chief, Gen. Perez
Musharraf, who then took power in a coup.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: ADVISER ON TOBACCO ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Health Minister Allan Rock has appointed Dr. Jeffrey
Wigand, the whistle-blower on a U.S. tobacco company, as his
special adviser on tobacco issues. Rock, said Wigand, a former head
of research for Brown &AMP; Williamson, the tobacco company, will help
interpret tobacco industry documents, which the minister says could
bolster the legal claims of provinces seeking to recover
smoking-related health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: CUTTING THE DEFICIT
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Fernando de la Rua has selected a cabinet of 10
men and one woman that includes four economists that is meant to
signal that he will be serious about cutting a spreading g deficit.
The appointment of Juan Jose Llach, a conservative economist, as
education minister has provoked dissent among liberals in his
Alianza coalition.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: PROTECTION FOR RIGHTS CENTER
</P>
<P>
   The Inter-American Court of Human Rights, a branch of the
Organization of American States, ordered Mexico to provide
protection for four members of the Miguel Agustin Pro Juarez Human
Rights Center in Mexico City. In the latest of a series of
harassment actions, a lawyer for the center, Digna Ochoa, was
assaulted Oct. 28 in her home by unknown assailants. The
announcement came as Mary Robinson, the U.N. high commissioner for
human rights, began a five-day visit to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: ID CARDS FOR IMMIGRANTS
</P>
<P>
   The far-right Freedom Party said immigrants from outside the
European Union should carry a special identity card. Joerg Haider,
the party's leader, said the card would help the authorities tackle
illegal immigration and black-market employment. The call provoked
protests from other parties, which compared it to the yellow star
that Jews were forced to wear by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: ASYLUM FOR KURDISH REBEL
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch foreign ministry announced that a veteran commander of
Kurdish rebels in Turkey, Murat Karayilan, has applied for
political asylum. He is reported to have opposed peace calls by the
imprisoned rebel leader, Abdullah Ocalan, and to favor a
continuation of armed struggle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
