u f BC-EBAY-NAZIS-NYT &LR;      11-24 0301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-NAZIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBAY IS TOLD THAT IT SELLS NAZI MEMORABILIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The online auction service eBay Inc. has come under fire
previously for letting people bid on pornography and firearms.
Wednesday, it encountered more problems when a group that monitors
anti-Semitism complained about the sale of Nazi memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   A letter sent to the company by the Simon Wiesenthal Center in
Los Angeles said items that ``glorify Nazism'' were being auctioned
and noted that the sale of such items was illegal in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal here is not to get eBay indicted,'' said Rabbi Abraham
Cooper, associate dean of the center. ``My goal is to keep eBay
from selling Nazi memorabilia in Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for eBay, which is based in San Jose, Calif., said
that the company already prohibited the sale of such items in
Germany because they are outlawed there. But he said it generally
polices the sales of banned items only after receiving complaints
from users. In addition, the spokesman said, the service expects
users in Germany not to violate their country's laws and thus would
not technologically block such sales.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Amazon.com said it would stop selling Hitler's ``Mein
Kampf'' to customers in Germany, citing German laws prohibiting
sales of hate literature. The move came after the Wiesenthal Center
filed legal complaints against Amazon and other Internet
booksellers in August.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Amazon, eBay does not handle or ship the items sold on
its site.
</P>
<P>
   A search for listings containing the word ``Nazi'' on eBay on
Wednesday returned nearly 3,000 items. They included a Nuremberg
rally postcard for $24, items described as ``Five Beautiful Large
Nazi Death Notices!!'' for $40, and a Nuremberg rally flag for
$550. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
