<HEADLINE>
DODGERS COACHES TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _When the season ended, Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said he wanted the coaching staff to return intact, and he
got that wish. The Dodgers announced Wednesday there would be no
changes in the major-league staff.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question was whether pitching coach Claude Osteen,
who replaced the fired Charlie Hough on May 26, would be given the
opportunity to work a full year with the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Claude's great,'' Johnson said. ``He's a great guy and has a
great relationship with the pitchers. I'm confident with Claude. I
think it's a very talented staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Tracy (bench), Rick Down (hitting) and Rick Dempsey will
return for their second seasons. Glenn Hoffman (third base) and
John Shelby (first base), who joined the Dodgers' major-league
staff during the 1998 season, will remain with the club.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the club signed infielder Craig Counsell to a one-year
contract and the lefty-hitting second baseman accepted an outright
assignment to Triple-A Albuquerque. Infielder Tripp Cromer,
outrighted a week ago to the minor leagues, elected to become a
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Ricky Stone and Luke Prokopec and infielder Adam Riggs,
all recently removed from the club's protected 40-man roster, each
accepted minor assignments. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
