   (NYT28) TOKYO -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- JAPAN-SUBWAY-2, 11-24 --
Commuters on Tokyo's new Route No. 12 subway line wait to board an
incoming train. The construction of the route, which is
infrequently used by commuters, is part of Japan's ceaseless effort
to prod its maddeningly lifeless economy into action. (Stuart
Isett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) BOSTON -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- COLO-RITALIN-SCHOOLS, 11-24
-- Mary Jane Kemper, a school nurse, carries a tray of medication
for students at McKay School in East Boston in January. As a debate
over the growing use of behavioral drugs for children intensifies
across the country, the Colorado Board of Education has passed a
resolution meant to discourage teachers from recommending
prescription drugs like Ritalin and Luvox. (Ed Quinn/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- THANKSGIVING-BALLOONS,
11-24 -- Cloe the Clown, one of the balloons which will be paraded
in Friday's Thanksgiving Day parade, is inflated Wednesday night in
Manhattan's Central Park West. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- WORLDBANK-RESIGN, 11-24
-- Joseph Stiglitz, chief economist for the World Bank, in his
office Wednesday afternoon. Stiglitz said today that he would
resign after using the position for nearly three years to raise
pointed questions about the effectiveness of conventional
approaches to helping poor countries. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) ALBANY, N.Y. -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- FBN-ARATON-COLUMN,
11-24 -- LeShon Johnson during a practice session in August. A year
ago, he had two young children to preoccupy his thoughts and his
wife to assist him in keeping his faith. Thanksgiving was spent
quietly, pensively, in his Jersey City apartment, supposedly a
convenient ride to where he was receiving treatment for the cancer
that so rudely had rerouted his life. ``It's Thanksgiving,'' he
said recently. ``And when I look back to where I was at this time
last year, I know I have so much to be thankful for.'' (David
Jennings/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- THANKSGIVING-BAND, 11-24 --
South Street Seaport. Trinity Valley Community College Jazz
Wildcards Band of Athens, Texas, performs for an audience at the
South Street Seaport on Wednesday. Nicole Barrett, the woman hit in
the head by a brick several weeks ago in Midtown, was once a dancer
for the band. Band members will will pin her favorite color,
purple, onto their red-and-white uniforms in her honor. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- TOYS, 11-24 -- Aside from
Pokemon, the big sellers will no doubt include some familiar names
in new incarnations --among them, Rock and Roll Elmo and Rock and
Roll Ernie ($30) from ``Sesame Street'' and Flight Control Buzz
Lightyear ($40). But not every television tie-in is a sure thing.
Star Wars toys, introduced by Hasbro earlier this year when ``Star
Wars: Episode I - The Phantom Menace'' was released, are not huge
sellers. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BOSTON -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- BOSTON-ACADEMY-2, 11-24 --
Sister Mary Dooley watches her students jump rope at Mother
Caroline Academy last week. The four-story building which houses
the school was once a place where generations of women from the
neighborhood waited for their checks and were made to feel that
they would never amount to anything. Now, the building is a Roman
Catholic middle school that strives to make 60 girls from poor
families believe that their futures are limitless. (Evan
Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- GORE-TRADE, 11-24 --
Vice President Al Gore adresses the A.F.L-C.I.O. after the union
offered its endorsement during the organization's convention in
October. With the Iowa caucuses only two months away, the Gore
campaign is counting on the labor organization's endorsement to
translate into intensive door-to-door political work there and in
other early primary states. But the union's most immediate
attention right now is focusing on Seattle, where it plans huge
demonstrations during global trade talks which get underway next
week. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEWPORT NEWS, Va. -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- GIVING-THANKS-I-3,
11-24 -- Vincent Jones is blessed by Pastor Herbert A. Hill Jr., as
Raymond Lawrence looks on at left during services at the Life Line
Full Gospel Baptist Church. Lawrence, homeless and living on the
streets of Manhattan, was returned home by Jones, a garment center
worker, who saw Lawrence on the streerts and couldn't get him off
his mind. (Richard Perry/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) PORTSMOUTH, Va. -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- GIVING-THANKS-I-2,
11-24 -- Alberta Lawrence hugs her son Raymond in front of her
house. Raymond Lawrence, homeless and living on the streets of
Manhattan, was returned home by Vincent Jones, a garment center
worker, who couldn't get Raymond off his mind. (Richard Perry/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) PORTSMOUTH, Va. -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- GIVING-THANKS-I,
11-24 -- Vincent Jones, left, tells Raymond Lawrence to stay away
from the streets on New York and stay with his mother. Lawrence,
homeless and living on the streets of Manhattan, was returned home
by Jones, a garment center worker who couldn't get Raymond off his
mind. (Richard Perry/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TOKYO -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- JAPAN-SUBWAY, 11-24 -- A lone
commuter exits the new Tochomae Station after arriving on the Route
12 subway. The construction of the route, which is infrequently
used by commuters, is part of Japan's ceaseless effort to prod its
maddeningly lifeless economy into action. (Stuart Isett/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ISLIP, N.Y. -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- NY-COPTER-CRASH, 11-24
-- An unidentified woman places roses on the fence near where an
Army National Guard helicopter crashed at Long Island-MacArthur
Aiport on Wednesday. Investigators were seeking the cause of the
crash that killed two Army National Guard members and injured two
others Tuesday night. (Vic Delucia/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 11-24
-- A variety of Japanese saws and their uses. (Edward R.
Lipinski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WESTFORD, Mass. -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- CIR-WEB-SOFTWARE-2,
11-24 --Keith Dawson, editor of ``Tasty Bits,'' an e-mail
newsletter, holds what he characterizes as his life; his computer's
valuable files in a portable format which includes magnetic disks,
Zips, etc. Voicing his reservations about security on virtual
desktops, Dawson says that reliability and privacy, not to mention
bandwidth, may keep some people from adopting the option as a way
to backup files online. (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- THANKSGIVING-FLOATER-2,
11-24 -- The words spoken and the ceremony over, Harry the turkey
waits for handlers to return him to his cage after a ceremony in
the White House Rose Garden on Wednesday. Harry, a native of
Minnesota, was ``pardoned'' from becoming a Thanksgiving dinner by
President Clinton and will be sent to a petting zoo at Kidwell Farm
in Herdon, Va. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- BOSTON-ACADEMY, 11-24 --
Sister Susan Thornell greets students arriving at the Mother
Caroline Academy last week. The four-story building which houses
the school was once a place where generations of women from the
neighborhood waited for their checks and were made to feel that
they would never amount to anything. Now, the building is a Roman
Catholic middle school that strives to make 60 girls from poor
families believe that their futures are limitless. (Evan
Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- THANKSGIVING-FLOATER, 11-24
-- Joseph Destephano holds his sleeping two-year old son Joseph
while Dave Greco, of Mike's Deli in the Bronx, tends to customers
on Wednesday. A roasted turkey, center, is available to customers
who prefer to avoid the whole cooking process and go right to the
finished product. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- WORKSHOP-WALLPAPER-COX, 11-24
-- Dee Harris demonstrates how to remove wallpaper by first
spraying wall paper remover, scraping the surface off, and then
removing the backing. Removing wallpaper doesn't have to be an
overwhelming task. With the right supplies and a little
preparation, the job can be completed in a few hours. (Louie
Favorite/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- GIVING-THANKS-III, 11-24 --
Iris Sanchez with bags of food she and her colleagues have prepared
to distribute over the Thanksgiving Holiday. Ten Thanksgivings ago,
Ms. Sanchez, on strike from a low-paying job, made 30 turkey
sandwiches and gave them to the homeless in her Brooklyn
neighborhood. Now she feeds 1,000 hungry, often homeless people
each week, and organizes language classes and health exams for
them. For her it's about gratitude: on successive Thanksgivings,
years earlier, her ex-husband almost succeeded in murdering her.
(Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- CIR-WINDOWS-CE-2,
11-24 -- Blake Patterson holds up a Visor, which uses the Palm
operating system. On his desk is a Nino, which uses Microsoft's
Windows CE, that Patterson uses less frequently. When Microsoft
first announced Windows CE three years ago, hardware manufacturers
were quick to start producing handheld devices to compete against
the popular Palm organizer, which has its own operating system.
Industry analysts' projections were so rosy they implied that Palm
Computing should run for cover. But a very different picture has
emerged since then. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- CIR-WINDOWS-CE, 11-24 --
Rogers Weed, director of marketing for Windows CE, a compact
version of the Windows operating system for small computers and
handhelds, shows some of the products that use the software. When
Microsoft first announced Windows CE three years ago, hardware
manufacturers were quick to start producing handheld devices to
compete against the popular Palm organizer, which has its own
operating system. Industry analysts' projections were so rosy they
implied that Palm Computing should run for cover. But a very
different picture has emerged since then. (Larry Davis/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEWARK, N.J. -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- CIR-WEB-SOFTWARE, 11-24
-- Colin Brady works on his computer at the Delta Crown Room in the
Delta Terminal at Newark Airport. Last July, Brady's laptop and
desktop computers crashed. However Brady was able to rebuild his
files with a new computer by downloanding his documents from
Visto.com, an online site which he uses as his virtual desktop.
(Richard Perry/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PORTLAND, Maine -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- MAINE-AIDS-ACTIVIST,
11-24 --Frances Peabody, 96, sits in the parlor of Peabody House.
The death of Mrs. Peabody's grandson, who died of AIDS in 1984,
turned her into an activist. She started the first AIDS information
hot line in Maine, which grew into the AIDS Project, a network of
social services. In 1994. She also opened Peabody House, the
state's first and only AIDS hospice. (Herb Swanson/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- DUGDALE-FARM-2, 11-24 -- In
interior of John Dugdale's studio appartment. Dugdale, 39, a fine
art photographer, lost almost all his sight following an
AIDS-related stroke six years ago. His apartment, which doubles as
his photographic studio, is the top floor of an 1828 town house on
a picturesque tree-lined street in Greenwich Village. (Jeffery A.
Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- DUGDALE-FARM-1, 11-24 --
John Dugdale poses next to a large, unwieldy wooden-framed 19th
century camera that dominates a corner of his high-ceilinged studio
in Manhattan. Juno, a springer spaniel, relaxes on an Empire sofa.
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Nov. 24, 1999 -- MILLIONAIRE-PHONE, 11-23 --
Stan Kemper, shows the kind of frustration he felt when the 32
year-old, playwright/actor/French teacher was caught in an
telephonic nightmare. New York City residents and wannabe
contestants on the smash-hit quiz show ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' who forgot to dial the 1 before the 877-258-5808
were reaching Kemper instead. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
