<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE DELAYS THE TRINIDAD-REID BOUT 
TUA'S STATUS IN DISPUTE 
GRANT GAINS FROM FIGHT 
INDICTMENT WON'T STOP PAYMENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bout between Felix Trinidad and David Reid, the WBA
superwelterweight champion, has been postponed because the WBC has
mandated that Trinidad defend the welterweight championship against
the No. 1 contender Derrell Coley within 90 days or vacate the
title.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Goossen of America Presents, promoter for both Coley and
Reid, said Wednesday that Coley had been offered ``a substantial
amount'' of money to step aside and allow the Trinidad-Reid match
to take place on March 4. But Coley did not want the money; he
wanted to fight Trinidad for the WBC welterweight title instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had an oral agreement with our fighters and all the
parties were satisfied, we were prepared to go forward with the
fight between David and Trinidad,'' Goossen said. ``We did the
right thing with Coley with the step aside, but at the end of the
day he wanted to fight for the title.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Trinidad did not want to give up the WBC welterweight
title, which he won from Oscar De La Hoya on Sept. 18 in a split
decision in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   When the Trinidad-Reid fight was announced two weeks ago,
Trinidad laid out an ambitious strategy to fight for titles in
weight classes from welterweight to middleweight next year. He had
no clear-cut plan for holding on to all the titles in the various
weight classes because in most cases a fighter must give up a world
title in one weight class once he wins one in another.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen said he did not know when the Reid-Trinidad bout would
happen, but said that Trinidad-Coley would be held within the next
90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, HBO/TVKO had informed Goossen that under its
contract with Reid, it had a right to bid on the Reid-Trinidad
bout, despite the fact that Don King, the co-promoter for the bout
had said it would be broadcast on pay-per-view by Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Tua's Status in Dispute
</P>
<P>
   David Tua, the No. 1 ranked heavyweight in the IB F, could be
trying to change management and promoters just as his chances of
fighting Lennox Lewis for the undisputed heavyweight championship
have heated up.
</P>
<P>
   Tua is currently managed by Shelly Finkel and promoted by Main
Events, but there is a disagreement over whether Tua's contract
with both has expired. Tua believes it has. Finkel doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick English, a lawyer for Main Events, said Tua was still
under contract with his promotion company, but English would not
say how much time was remaining on the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Finkel said there were extensions in his contract with Tua for
time taken off because of injury and inactivity. Finkel said Tua
had elbow surgery two years ago and took four months off to
recuperate. To Finkel's way of thinking that has extended Tua's
contract by four months.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Finkel said he was trying to work on a new contract
with Tua.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Gains From Fight
</P>
<P>
   Don Turner, the trainer of Michael Grant, said that Grant's
knockout victory against Andrew Golota last Saturday night could be
worth as much as two or three fights' worth of experience for the
young heavyweight. But the major benefits for Turner is that the
two first-round knockdowns Golota scored against Grant will instill
a greater sense of urgency in Grant, who is a slow starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future he'll work harder to dispatch his guys much
sooner,'' Turner said. ``And now maybe it will be much easier for
me to reach him in the gym. Michael's been doing everything in his
whole life at 80 percent. He had to give 100 percent to get out of
this fight. From now on, he'll know he has to give 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Indictment Won't Stop Payments
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Lee, Sr., president of the IBF, said he does not
foresee any problems collecting the sanctioning fees for the Dec. 5
bout between Fernando Vargas, the IBF junior-middleweight champion,
and Winky Wright. Lee and three other executives of the
organization are under federal indictment on conspiracy and
racketeering charges and federal prosecutors are trying to freeze
two IBF bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Bob Arum withheld the $450,000 sanctioning fee for the
Oscar De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad bout, and has placed it in an
escrow account. The promoters for Lennox Lewis tried to put the
$300,000 sanctioning fee in escrow to keep from paying it directly
to the IBF, but later relented and paid the fee to the nonprofit
arm of the organization, so Lewis could get the IBF championship
belt.
</P>
<P>
   English, the lawyer for Main Events, one of Lewis' promoters and
also Vargas' promoter, said they would pay the $20,000 sanctioning
fee to the IBF nonprofit entity for the Vargas fight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
