<SLUG> BC-GIVING-THANKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUICK TALKER,   UNLIKE GRANDFATHER; A QUICK CONCESSION FROM AN
IRISH BAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ireland, Switzerland )  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The actress Dolores Chaplin was talking about the
making of ``The Ice Rink,'' a film about the making of a film that
was made last year and will open in New York next year.
Specifically, she was talking about how she got her part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lied,'' she said. ``Of course I said I could ice skate.''
</P>
<P>
   She learned to skate by learning in-line skating. ``I was
Rollerblading on parking lots'' in France, where the film was shot,
she said. ``I didn't have to do any crazy acrobatic tricks. I only
fell once, the last day. I got carried away, overconfident. I was
wearing this overlong red dress, which got tangled up in my
skates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ice Rink'' is scheduled to open in New York on a double
bill with ``Modern Times,'' the 1936 classic that starred her
grandfather, Charlie Chaplin. This prompted the question: How many
times has she seen ``Modern Times''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't count,'' she said. ``There are many reels of his films
I've never seen, but I still enjoy `Modern Times.' I'll probably
stay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   A NAME ISN'T WORTH A FIGHT FOR THIS IRISH BAND
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gregory Grene, who plays the button-key accordian in
an Irish folk band called the Prodigals, was ambitious _ he wanted
his own record label. ``We have a CD coming out,'' he said. ``So we
set up West Side Music as the publishing end of the band.'' The
name ``West Side Music'' had personal significance _ ``I live in
Chelsea on the West Side.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a city where the Bronx is up and the Battery's down, the
names of neighborhoods have long since been copyrighted, registered
as trademarks or claimed as service marks. Grene soon received a
letter from a lawyer for Leonard Bernstein's estate, who said that
the name ``West Side Music'' infringed on Bernstein's rights to the
phrase ``West Side Story.''
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement could have turned into a David-and-Goliath
clash, except that Grene decided not to play David.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the finances of a band that, touch wood, is going in the
right direction but is still pretty young versus the established
power of Leonard Bernstein's law firm,'' he said, ``we couldn't
afford the legal fees.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Bernstein estate, it registered ``West Side Story''
as a service mark years ago. ``We just felt that `West Side Music'
was too close,'' said Craig Urquhart, a spokesman. ``That's that.
We're trying to keep people from getting confused.'' Referring to
Grene and the Prodigals, he added, ``We're grateful they changed
it.''
</P>
<P>
   They became Grab Entertainment, using an acronym from their
names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
