<SLUG> BC-NAKED-POLICE-NYT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESA COPS GET NAKED FOR STINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBBIE SHERWOOD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - At least twice in the past six months, undercover
Mesa police officers have gotten naked to convince massage parlor
prostitution suspects that they aren't really cops.
</P>
<P>
   And in both cases, officers allowed the suspects to touch their
genitals.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa's unwritten policy giving officers the go-ahead to disrobe
and allow themselves to be touched, short of sex, goes further than
any law enforcement agency in the Phoenix area, and most agencies
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no sex acts,'' said Lt. Ron Kirby, who runs the
special investigations unit that goes after prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to do an illegal act to get these people. But
we are going to throw things out there to get them to bite.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers had the option to take their clothes off in each of the
department's 15 massage parlor prostitution arrests in the past
year, but police refused to say how far officers went in each case.
</P>
<P>
   But in response a public records request by The Arizona
Republic, the department released two reports where officers felt
it necessary to get naked.
</P>
<P>
   In the delicate dance between police and prostitutes, law
enforcement agencies across the nation have wrestled with how far
undercover officers can go behind massage parlor doors to disguise
the fact that they are cops.
</P>
<P>
   Most seasoned escorts or prostitutes masquerading as massage
therapists won't even discuss a sex act unless the customer is
nude; and for some, the threshold is contact with the genitals.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, Scottsdale, Tempe, Glendale and Maricopa County are
among the police agencies that have made it clear to their vice
officers that disrobing beyond a towel or underwear is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Justice studies Professor Jon Kavanagh said completely disrobing
is unnecessary to prostitution stings, and that's why most police
departments around the country don't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A clever cop can get an offer for sex for money without
exposing himself,'' said Kavanagh, who retired from the New York
police force in 1993 and now leads the justice studies department
at Scottsdale Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``You run into big problems ethically and procedurally when you
allow police officers to disrobe,'' he said. ``It's obscene and
immoral and could open up an officer to allegations that he's
acting for his own pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Police Chief Jan Strauss said the policy has been in effect
for about six years, but the public has known little about it
because nearly all of the massage parlor prostitution arrests have
been plea-bargained before trial.
</P>
<P>
   She said the recent scandal involving officers having sex with
each other on duty had nothing to do with her department's
reluctance to release the massage parlor policy.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss said her concern was that releasing details of
investigative techniques could jeopardize future investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how far will Mesa cops go? Officers wouldn't say, only
that the line is somewhere between nudity and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she would say to taxpayers who had a problem with
police going this far, Strauss said, ``These are the same people
who would be shocked at what is going on in massage parlors.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Kirby said that his detectives will not disrobe if they can
avoid it, and that his detectives get regular training on how to
conduct themselves during massage parlor stings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something these guys enjoy doing,'' Kirby said.
``And I don't force anybody to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added police Cmdr. Rodney Johnston, ``You have to evolve with
the nature of the crime. . . . You have to do certain things to rid
the community of a certain element.''
</P>
<P>
   According to police report of the November investigation of the
O.K. Garden Spa at 1911 W. Broadway Road, the proprietor, Frances
Chong, never gave the undercover Mesa detective the option of
covering up with a towel.
</P>
<P>
   After paying $50 for a massage, the officer was led into a room
and told, ``Take your clothes off.''
</P>
<P>
   The officer wrote in the report that Chong touched his genitals
while giving him a bath.
</P>
<P>
   During the ensuing massage, Chong exposed herself and offered to
perform a sex act, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer declined, but then discussed prices to have sex with
Chong. She said she would have sex for $100 and then grabbed the
officer's hand and placed it on her breast, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The officer made an excuse to leave before the massage
progressed any further. Chong has been indicted on two felony
counts: operating a house of prostitution and receiving earnings of
a prostitute. She is awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa police were met with a similar situation nine days later
when the investigated Spa Nouveau at 706 W. Southern Ave.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, part of a continuing investigation, the officer
wrote in his report that he paid $50 for a massage and was given a
robe to wear after taking off his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   But the suspect told the officer to take off the robe when it
came time for the massage and gave him nothing else to cover
himself.
</P>
<P>
   When discussing the appropriate amount for a ``tip'' to pay for
a sex act, she reportedly told the officer he must first place her
hand on his genitals ``to prove that you're not a cop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I then took her hand and placed it on my upper thigh and she
said it was not good enough, so I placed it low on my stomach,
which seemed to satisfy her suspicions of my being an officer as
she moved her hand onto my penis,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Again the officer made an excuse to leave before completing a
sex act.
</P>
<P>
   Other police agencies say Mesa is venturing into an area they
will not go.
</P>
<P>
   ``By our policy, completely disrobing is strictly prohibited,''
said Lt. Larry Jacobs, head of the Phoenix Police Department's vice
enforcement unit. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robbie Sherwood can be reached at (602) 444-7938 or at
robbie.sherwood(at)pni.com. &QL; 
Republic writer Jim Walsh contributed to this article. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
