<HEADLINE>
A BULLET RICOCHETS OFF A CELL PHONE AND AN OFFICER IS ONLY GRAZED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A plainclothes officer who was shot at during an
undercover drug operation in the Bronx late Tuesday night escaped
serious injury when a bullet ricocheted off his cellular telephone
and grazed his stomach, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Sgt. Robert Delamey, 38, was wounded when three men
tried to rob him and another officer during an undercover sale of
cocaine that the police had hoped would help build a case against a
drug organization, officials said. Delamey was listed in stable
condition at Jacobi Medical Center last night, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Three men were arrested on attempted murder and attempted
robbery charges, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred at about 11:50 p.m. in an apartment in the
South Bronx. Police officials said that three suspected drug
dealers began firing in an apparent attempt to rob the two
officers.
</P>
<P>
   A bullet that probably would have struck Delamey in the stomach
bounced off his cellular telephone and only grazed him, Police
Commissioner Howard Safir said outside the hospital Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant's partner, Wilbert Morales, 32, was struck over the
head with a pistol, but was able to fire eight shots with his
9-millimeter handgun, striking one of the assailants, officials
said. Delamey fired two rounds from his Glock handgun before backup
officers arrived and arrested the suspects, officials added.
Investigators said it was unclear Wednesday who shot Delamey.
</P>
<P>
   The three Bronx men who were arrested were identified by the
police as Shane Palmer, 28; Raymond Thomas, 22; and Shawn Howell,
21, who was shot in the left leg.
</P>
<P>
   Howell was in stable condition at Lincoln Hospital, officials
added. Investigators said that a 9-millimeter handgun and a knife
were found at the scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991124.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-THANKSGIVING-BAND-NYT     11-24 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIVING-BAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SPOTLIGHT, TEXAS BAND JUGGLES THRILL AND FEAR
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among the hundreds of performers in the crowded
Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade, the Trinity Valley Community
College marching band and dance team would probably not have drawn
an extraordinary amount of attention, except perhaps in its
hometown of Athens, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But a glaring spotlight turned on that small town last week
after one of its natives, Nicole Barrett, was struck down with a
brick in a random attack on a midtown Manhattan street. Eight years
ago, Ms. Barrett had the time of her life in the Thanksgiving
parade as a member of the school's Cardettes dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity's 118 band members and dancers had been anticipating
that same sort of once-in-a-lifetime excitement before Ms.
Barrett's attack. And Wednesday, many said they were still thrilled
to represent their college in a national tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But, for some, there was also concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared us that she was attacked, but that could have
happened anywhere, even in our small town,'' said Misty Mosley, 20
a dancer from New Waverly, Texas, who has watched the Macy's parade
on television since she was 3 years old. ``I was so excited about
coming to New York that no way was I having second thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the incident will not be far from their minds. The band
members will pin purple ribbons _ Ms. Barrett's favorite color _ to
their red-and-white uniforms and dedicate their performance to Ms.
Barrett, who is recovering at Bellevue Hospital Center. She has
improved in recent days, and the hospital listed her in serious but
stable condition Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know her, but it still hurts,'' said Stephen Estes,
19, a bass drum player in the band. ``Her being from Athens and
being so close, you would never think that something like that will
happen, but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Although several students acknowledged, like Estes, that the
attack on Ms. Barrett was a random act, they said they were more
concerned about their safety because of it. A few refused to leave
their hotel, the Milford Plaza in Times Square, after dark when
they arrived on Tuesday, and Wednesday others said they would
venture out only with a group of people during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Others say they have been careful not to look at strangers or
talk to them. ``It's different,'' said Crystal Martin, 20, a drum
major from Eustace, Texas. ``We come from a small town so we
usually talk to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one student said that she was so excited to be in
the city that she rushed out at midnight Tuesday to take in the
night life in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw all these lights, I almost lost my concentration,'' said
the student, Starr Brown, 21, a flute player from Athens who is
mostly blind. ``It was just as crowded as it was at 5 in the
afternoon. I come from this Podunk town where the restaurants close
at 8 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Baker, who directs the dance team, said the Trinity
Valley students had applied for a coveted spot in the Macy's parade
last spring. They sent in videotapes and photographs, and after
being picked, they sold raffle tickets to raise money for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   After all that hard work, Ms. Baker said, there was never any
question of canceling the trip after the attack on Ms. Barrett.
``Nikki had such a great time, she would have hated to think that
we missed out on this because of something that happened to her,''
said Ms. Baker, who said she cried when she visited her former
student in the hospital Tuesday night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The students, who are accompanied by 28 faculty members and
parents, will stay through Saturday. On Wednesday, 20 band members
played jazz on Liberty Island and at South Street Seaport.
</P>
<P>
   For other students, the highlight of the trip will be Thursday's
parade. Ms. Mosley said it was important for her to march _ not
just for herself but also for Ms. Barrett. ``I feel like she's part
of me because she did this before me,'' she said. ``This is out of
respect for her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
