<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOSTON-ACADEMY-ART-NY     11-24 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-ACADEMY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A PLACE FOR WELFARE TO ONE FOR FOSTERING PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In cities, buildings are constructed and gutted and
torn down and rebuilt all the time. Rarely does a single structure
come to embody for one group of people both a moment of indignity
and defeat, and one of pride and possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But such is the story of the yellow brick building at 515 Blue
Hill Ave., once a city welfare office and now, through the
determination of three nuns and two volunteer fund-raisers, the
Mother Caroline Academy and Education Center.
</P>
<P>
   The four-story building where generations of women once waited
for their checks and were made to feel that they would never amount
to anything is now a Roman Catholic middle school that strives to
make 60 girls from poor families _ African-American, Hispanic,
Haitian and Cape Verdean _ believe that their futures are
limitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``A life is not defined by circumstance,'' said the executive
director, Sister Mary Dooley. ``It's defined by hope.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall Maria Montefusco, 14, whose family was homeless when
she was in the third grade, has been telling everyone, ``I'm going
to Harvard.'' Dulce DePina, 13, whose mother is a hospital aide, is
talking about becoming a doctor. Lisa Barbosa, 12, has declared her
intention to become a historian.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Lisa has been grilling her social studies teacher,
Manon Beaudrie, about ancient Rome: ``What did they dress like?
What did they eat? What about the government? How did it work? Who
were all the people in it? Why did they blame Cleopatra for the
fall of Rome?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask a lot of questions,'' said Lisa, whose persistent
curiosity was rewarded last semester with an A-plus in social
studies.
</P>
<P>
   With only 14 people in her class _ all the classes at the school
are small _ Ms. Beaudrie has plenty of time to answer Lisa's
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa's school day is 12 hours long, but Ms. Beaudrie, who left
her job as a bookstore manager for Mother Caroline, stays longer.
She and her nine fellow teachers, all in their 20s, are volunteers.
With room and board provided by Mother Caroline, they live at the
school, on the fourth floor.
</P>
<P>
   In its former incarnation, the building, which opened in 1952 at
the center of an African-American community, in the Dorchester
neighborhood, was a place where the caseworkers were the ones who
asked the questions. Sharon Cox, 54, was 14 and a new mother when
she walked inside to apply for welfare. ``Everyone said you were a
loser just to be there,'' recalled Ms. Cox, who went on to become a
writer and wrote a poem about the building for the school's
opening. ``They didn't expect you to have anything to offer. You
needed the help, you were grateful for the help, but you paid for
it in humiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1967, resentments and hostilities inside the building
spilled over into a race riot. By 1983, the welfare office had
moved and the building was boarded up, an ugly symbol of a past
that made no one proud.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Sister Mary, Sister Frances and Sister Barbara Dewey,
from the School Sisters of Notre Dame, opened Mother Caroline
Academy for 30 girls in a rented convent in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But the school needed more space, and in 1994 the nuns looked
inside the old welfare office. ``We walked through and there was
garbage everywhere,'' Sister Mary recalled. ``The hallways were
flooded. There were no lights. It was awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she returned with an architect, Tom McGrath. ``He said
the building had great potential, wonderful possibilities, a strong
foundation,'' Sister Mary said. ``Those were the same words as we
use for the girls. I said, `You know, I think we're being
called.'''
</P>
<P>
   The nuns bought the building from the city for $1 but they
needed more than $2 million to renovate it.
</P>
<P>
   And, Sister Mary said, ``We had no major donors.'' Nor did
Mother Caroline Academy receive any money from the archdiocese, or
from the Sisters of Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Mary asked two women who had been volunteering at the
school, Beth Floor and Barrie Landry, if they would lead a capital
campaign. ``We both said, `No, we can't ask for money,''' Ms. Floor
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But they raised $2.6 million in 14 months. The new Mother
Caroline school opened in June 1998, adding to a growing revival of
its neighborhood. Tuition is only $100 a year, and the school also
helps puts its graduates through private high schools. In addition,
it offered classes in computers, reading and English as a second
language to adults and children in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the women who once waited for checks in the old welfare
office are now taking classes at Mother Caroline. One, Lois Lee, is
a member of the board of the school. The women also come back to
meet the girls and to talk with Sister Mary and Sister Frances, the
principal, about the power of one building.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is vindication to me,'' Ms. Cox said. ``There are young
people in this community who have what it takes to deal with a
rigorous academic program. No matter where the girls come from,
they bring something to the building. Just like me, they have
something to offer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
