<SLUG> BC-NY-BUILDING-COLLAPSE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACTOR WHERE BUILDING FELL IS SAID TO VIOLATE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after an accident killed a worker at a Brooklyn
building site, local and federal investigators said Wednesday that
the contractor had a history of safety problems and violations at
its projects.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that both the Brooklyn district attorney's office
and the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn were examining whether
criminal charges would be warranted in the accident, which sent
several construction workers falling three stories. The workers
were pouring concrete at 50 Middleton Avenue in Williamsburg when
the upper floors of the structure collapsed, apparently because of
shoddy construction.
</P>
<P>
   An immigrant laborer, Daniel Eduardo, 23, was crushed by
concrete blocks; three other workers remained in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Wednesday that the accident
and the history of the contractor, Industrial Enterprise Ltd., were
a case study of why city guidelines regulating contractors are
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   As several agencies pursued investigations into the collapse,
the contracting firm's chairman and owner, Chaim Ostreicher, had
apparently left for Israel, making it much harder for investigators
to question him about the accident, according to two law
enforcement officials who cited comments by his wife as well as
other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The firm appears to have a troubled history. The federal
Occupational Safety and Health Administration has documented at
least seven previous violations by the company for such problems as
faulty wiring that could lead to fires and failure to protect
workers at job sites, according OSHA spokesman Randy Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   And at one residence the contractor built, the city's Buildings
Department ordered part of the structure vacated _ even though it
was already inhabited _ because it did not have enough fire exits,
said department spokesman Paul Wein.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Industrial Enterprises, Jeffrey Buss, said he could
not comment on the accident until his client had further
investigated it, but he said another company was responsible for
pouring the cement Tuesday. He would not comment on Ostreicher's
whereabouts, or the company's history of violations, but he said,
``my client wants to express his sympathy to the families and the
people that were injured.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they have been hampered in their inquiry
because the contractor involved has operated under different names.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's accident, Eduardo plunged to his death after the
unfinished fourth level of the structure collapsed while workers
were pouring concrete on top of it. Acting Buildings Commissioner
Richard Visconti said the collapse was apparently caused by
improper bracing on a joist supporting the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that if either poor construction
or violations of workplace regulations are found to have
contributed to the accident, and thereby the death of Eduardo, the
company, or individual managers, could face separate state and
federal homicide charges.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that preliminary indications are that the
builder's failure to follow the approved plans, something they had
been cited for at other sites, may have contributed to the
accident. Builders must submit such plans to the city, which detail
essential components of construction, and then are generally
required to adhere to them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Federal investigators are also probing whether Ostreicher paid
workers the appropriate ``prevailing'' union wage, and federal
officials said that they are continuing to explore whether the
company used illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   While investigators focused on the contractor, the city itself
was coming under scrutiny for its oversight of such projects.
</P>
<P>
   Buildings Department officials Wednesday sought to deflect
criticism from labor advocates that they had mishandled a similar
accident Aug. 10 at a separate building on the same site. After a
collapse that day, inspectors received amended building plans and
did not return to inspect the site before allowing work to resume.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said that city guidelines did not require them to
return to the site, an issue that has raised concern among some
legislators who say the city's rules governing such inspections are
too lax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
