<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-RENDERMAN--PIXAR-SFCH     11-24 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENDERMAN--PIXAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 RenderMan to the Rescue: Software Is Real Hero of Animation  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
When people hear ``Pixar,'' Woody, Buzz Lightyear, Flik and a host
of other likable characters from the company's bubbly animated
films inevitably spring to mind.
<P>
   But there's another name in the animation house's repertoire
that will never rescue a kidnapped toy or lead an ant colony's
rebellion, although ``he'' plays a key role in all of Pixar's
movies and shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Pixar, the Point Richmond film production company behind '``Toy
Story,'' ``A Bug's Life'' and now ``Toy Story 2,'' is also the
proud parent of RenderMan, an Academy Award-winning piece of
software that helps thousands of animators and special effects
wizards worldwide put the finishing touches on computer-generated
images for commercials, TV shows and movies.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``render'' refers to the process whereby a computer
takes all of the calculations embedded in a single frame's digital
models &LR;  and draws a complete picture, literally fleshing out a
bare-bones representation with texture and lighting. Without
rendering, viewers would see wire-frame models, the Erector
set-like representations that tell the computer what each object
looks like.
</P>
<P>
   In films like ``The Matrix,'' RenderMan helped fuse
computer-generated elements and live action. In the entirely
digital ``A Bug's Life,'' it created a wholly believable insect
world with the sheen of a classic illustrator's brush.
</P>
<P>
   ``RenderMan has been a key part of getting dazzling, realistic
images on the screen,'' said Darwyn Peachey, Pixar vice president
of research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does 450-employee Pixar use RenderMan in all of its
films, it licenses the technology to the likes of Sony Pictures
Imageworks (the force behind the upcoming ``Stuart Little'' movie)
and George Lucas' special effects powerhouse, Industrial Light &AMP;
Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Other animation firms like ILM often develop their own in-house
software, but it's unusual for one company to develop, sell,
support and use its own tools.
</P>
<P>
   And in the 11 years it's been on the market, RenderMan has
become a steady part of Pixar's business, Peachey said, though in
its financial filings, the company admits its focus on feature
films hasn't let it dedicate the resources to boost RenderMan sales
even more.
</P>
<P>
   As a percentage of overall revenues, RenderMan varies widely, as
do the company's sales, which tend to skyrocket after a movie
release then subside as interest in the film wanes.
</P>
<P>
   For the first nine months of this year, Pixar earned $39.6
million on revenues of $96.2 million _ much of it due to ``A Bug's
Life'' _ compared with $7.9 million in earnings on $14.3 million of
revenue for all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of RENDER25 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Software sales, mainly from RenderMan, totaled $4.6 million in
the first nine months of this year, a 70 percent jump over the $2.7
million posted for the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That increase reflects an industrywide trend. Snader &AMP;
Associates, a San Rafael reseller of hardware and software for
graphic artists, says the digital effects industry is in the middle
of an upswing after a sluggish 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good amount of demand (for software and hardware) in
the Bay Area and all over right now,'' said Dennis Payne, an
account executive at Snader. ``There's a lot of content creation in
film, the Web and on the games side of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an increase in projects using computer-generated
effects, RenderMan's success derives from clients' love of the
product. San Rafael's ILM used RenderMan on ``Terminator 2,''
``Jurassic Park'' and ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of features (in RenderMan) sustains a quality
level .. that is unsurpassed,'' said Christian Rouet, senior
technology officer at ILM.
</P>
<P>
   Rouet and others say the $5,000 (per license) RenderMan stands
apart from other rendering tools, which usually come as part of
broader animation and modeling software from companies such as
Softimage and Alias/Wavefront. Alias's Maya Complete, the company's
entry-level 3-D modeling, animation and rendering software, costs
about $7,500; and Softimage 3D, with roughly equivalent
capabilities, costs approximately $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rouet emphasizes that those products aren't substandard. It's
simply that RenderMan is mature _ in 11 years, Pixar has worked out
the bugs _ and it can handle a massive amount of data.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to create something that's photo-realistic,
you need a lot of detail ... and rendering really means creating
something that's extremely detailed,'' Rouet said. ``If the
renderer can't take it because of memory (limitations), it becomes
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   At $5,000 a pop just for a renderer, RenderMan is a little
pricey for the self-employed digital artist. But even tiny firms
say the software is worth every penny.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a very small studio and we couldn't do special effects
if we didn't use RenderMan, in terms of the quality of images we
can put out, the speed with which we can put them out,'' said
Annabella Serra, creative director of Rainsound Inc., a Seattle
visual effects company that has seven RenderMan licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Rainsound faced a major challenge several years ago on the
action-adventure flick ``Anaconda.'' Its artists needed to create
snake skin that wouldn't distort when the beast slithered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have the textures stretch,'' she said. ``With
RenderMan, we had no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Anaconda,'' as in other movies that use computer-generated
visuals, technicians started with a model. Modeling software
(separate from RenderMan) lets an artist create a virtual
doppelganger of a snake, person, tree, etc. Then the artists
manipulate the model to create the illusion of movement and
expression, or animation. Finally, they layer on cues for texture,
shading and other details that add dimension and realism.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the complexity of the image and the power of the
computer, rendering software will take anywhere from 1 to 50 hours
to spitting &LR;  out a final image that incorporates all of that data.
Pixar uses a network of computers called a ``render farm'' to speed
up the process) &LR; . But a team of about a dozen RenderMan developers
has dedicated themselves to further shrinking that time with each
RenderMan release _ version 3.9 is the latest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The performance of the renderer and the ability to deal with
complex shots has improved a lot,'' said Peachey. ``We can do
scenes with an enormous amount of material.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``Buster,'' a dog in ``Toy Story 2,'' has 4 million
hairs on his body, and each has to be textured and lit. Such
minutiae ``wouldn't have been possible with the renderer we used
for `Toy Story,''' said Peachey.
</P>
<P>
   And forget the company's earliest rendering tools, developed in
the mid-1980s when it was still the Computer Division of Lucasfilm
Ltd. Thirteen years ago, Steve Jobs bought the unit for $10 million
and incorporated it as Pixar. At the time, the company revolved
around the Pixar Image Computer, an early workstation for graphics
professionals. But even then, a faction of frustrated filmmakers
was branching out.
</P>
<P>
   As Pixar began producing shorts, it shifted away from hardware
and software development, but the core RenderMan technology
remained.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Pixar decided to sell the software commercially, in
part to establish an industrywide standard, ``to give people a way
to build on each other's work,'' Peachey said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite RenderMan's success over the past decade, Peachey says
there are no plans to spin it out into a separate company. The
software is simply too entwined with Pixar.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the nice thing about having the in-house film
production (at Pixar), is that they integrate things they need for
themselves into the software,'' Rainsound's Serra said. Other firms
making graphics software ``don't have the people in-house who push
the software; they don't live it day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
