<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 BY JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK:
</P>
<P>
   Lehigh (10-1) at Hofstra (10-1), Saturday
</P>
<P>
   Get to Long Island for this tremendous first-round match up in
the NCAA Division I-AA championship. The two quarterbacks _
Giovanni Carmazzi of Hofstra and Phil Stambaugh of Lehigh _ are
genuine National Football League prospects and have had scouts
measuring them all year. So perhaps is Lehigh's tiny running back,
5-4 Ronald Jean. A heart-rendering success story in his own right,
Jean has gained 1,358 yards and scored 23 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi (7-3) at Mississippi State (8-2), 8 p.m. ET, ESPN
</P>
<P>
   In-state bragging rights are more important than where these two
bowl-bound teams end up spending their holiday season: either
Atlanta and the Peach for the winner, or Florida and the Outback
for the loser.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   Texas (9-2) at Texas A&AMP;M (7-3), 11 a.m. ET, ABC
</P>
<P>
   This is perhaps the most emotional game of the college season
after A&AMP;M's bonfire collapse, in which 12 students died. The
Longhorns have already sewn up a spot in the Big XII Championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska (9-1) at Colorado (6-4), 2:30 p.m. ET, ABC
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1990 have the Cornhuskers lost to the Buffalos. The
streak needs to continue if Nebraska is to keep its slim national
title hopes alive. If they lose, Kansas State plays Texas in the
Big XII title game.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College (8-2) at Virginia Tech (10-0), 2:30 p.m. ET, CBS
</P>
<P>
   The Golden's Eagles surprising season is just what the Hokies
needed to boost their strength of schedule in the Bowl Championship
Series rankings. A Virginia Tech victory caps a remarkable season;
if the Hokies pound BC, it shouldn't matter how Nebraska finishes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   On television, there are a couple of entertaining matchups that
really don't mean much:
</P>
<P>
   Georgia (7-3) at Georgia Tech (7-3), 1 p.m. ET, ABC
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton won't win the Heisman Trophy, but
you will witness why he will make the trip to New York as a
finalist.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame (5-6) at Stanford (7-3), 8 p.m. ET, ABC
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal are in the Rose Bowl. This is the Fighting Irish's
bowl game.
</P>
</TEXT>
