<SLUG> BC-OLY-RECOMMENDATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC ANNOUNCES 50-POINT REFORM CAMPAIGN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With less than a month before a crucial meeting of its members,
the International Olympic Committee Wednesday released 50
recommendations that will form the centerpiece of the beleaguered
Swiss-based organization's reform campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms suggested by the IOC 2000 Commission focus on
changing the IOC structure, the selection of host cities for future
Olympics and financial reporting are to be submitted when the full
membership meets in Lausanne from Dec. 11-12.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the scandal involving the awarding of the
2002 Winter Olympics to Salt Lake City _ which led to the expulsion
or resignation of 10 IOC members _ the committee has pointed to
next month's meeting as the ultimate proof of its desire to reform
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reforms we advertised are the ones we will deliver,'' said
Richard Pound, an IOC vice president who served on the commission.
``I hope it reflects our desire to be as open as we can in all
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC released its slate of reform in a report that said,
loftily: ``The IOC 2000 Commission supported the notion that the
IOC should be the moral authority for world sport. To obtain even
greater credit, the IOC must now be more representative of the
sports world.''
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Reducing the retirement age of new members from 80 to 70, and
establishing eight-year, renewable term limits. The age limit had
been raised several years ago to 80 to accommodate the wishes of
the longtime president, Juan Antonio Samaranch, who is to retire
next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establishing an eight-year term limit for future presidents
but with the possibility of re-election to an additional four or
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Setting a limit of 115 members, including 15 active athletes,
15 international federation presidents, 15 national Olympic
committee presidents, and 70 individuals.
</P>
<P>
   _ The elimination of IOC member visits to bid cities and of
visits to members by representatives of the cities. Olympic
candidate cities would be evaluated by a small commission, which
would include members of the IOC, international federations and
national Olympic committees as well as outside experts. A vigorous
campaign of gift-giving by Salt Lake City Olympic organizers to
visiting IOC members and their families animated the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sports that do not subscribe to the IOC's anti-doping code and
do not perform out-of-competition testing in accord with the
organization's new World Anti-Doping Agency will be excluded from
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   _ The World Anti-Doping Agency will require that each athlete
hold a ``passport'' that contains all the information needed to
carry out efficient doping controls and monitoring of the athlete's
health.
</P>
<P>
   _ The publication of financial reports that explicitly outline
the use of IOC funds, including the allocation of money to national
Olympic committees and international federations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
