<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-POLICE-HARTFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO MONITOR HARTFORD POLICE IS HAILED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD _ Longtime critics of the local police are hailing a
plan to hire a civilian monitor and resurrect a moribund police
review board to investigate all police shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford City Council approved both measures Tuesday in an
effort to temper the racial tension that has simmered for years and
has increased in the seven months since Aquan Salmon, an unarmed
14-year-old black youth, was fatally shot in the back by a white
police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Lauded by both sides as a huge step toward a more accountable
police force, the Council's unanimous vote does not break any new
ground: it essentially reaffirms the city's commitment to the terms
of a 1973 federal consent decree that required, among other things,
that the Police Department adopt strict rules governing its
officers' conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But it was seen as a major sign of a commitment to holding the
police accountable. In recent years, local Hispanic and black
groups have accused the city of failing to adhere to the goals of
that decree, and the April shooting of Salmon, now the subject of a
state investigation, has only heightened distrust of the city's
mostly white police force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department is in desperate need of new leadership; they
know there has to be a change,'' said Nicholas R. Carbone, a city
councilman in 1973 and the current president of the Connecticut
Institute for Municipal Studies, a nonprofit group that helped
pressure Hartford officials to approve the measure. ``The
department is now going to reach for a higher degree of
professionalism.''
</P>
<P>
   The outside police monitor, or ``special master,'' will probably
be someone from outside the city government and will not have any
authority over the Police Department, said the city manager,
Saundra Kee Borges. Rather, the monitor will act as the eyes of
U.S. District Court in New Haven, which issued the 1973 decree, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Council vote, approving the monitor and a reconstituted
seven-member Board of Inquiry for police shootings, should create
``a more customer friendly Police Department,'' Ms. Kee Borges
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a good resolution,'' she said. ``It was a good
opportunity for all sides to come together and come to some
agreement on how we move forward.'' But she stressed that the
Council resolution did not admit that the city had failed to adhere
to the 1973 federal order.
</P>
<P>
   But to most people who live here, including the 14 groups that
pressured Tuesday's resolution, problems within the police seem
deeply entrenched. Weeks after Salmon's death, for instance, Police
Chief Joseph F. Croughwell Jr., who is white, said publicly that
his department was riven with racism.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, police officials said they were encouraged by the
action. ``It's going to make us, hopefully, be a better police
department,'' said Assistant Police Chief James Berry.
</P>
<P>
   The 1973 decree was the result of a settlement between city
officials and Le Casa de Puerto Rico, an influential community
group that filed a civil rights suit in 1969 to force the police to
end abusive methods.
</P>
<P>
   The decree, which imposed a code of ethics governing how the
police interacted with citizens, required officers to give their
names and badge numbers to anyone who asked and forbade the use of
pepper spray on children. It also prohibited the shooting of
unarmed youths under 16, unarmed criminal suspects and anyone
fleeing the police, unless there was a deadly threat.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also established a Use of Firearms Board of
Inquiry, staffed mostly by police officials. The board, which often
went ignored over the years, will now get a new mandate, Berry
said. ``It's going to deem that we definitely start reviewing all
firearms discharges in the department,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rank-and-file police officers were not as enthusiastic about
Tuesday's Council vote. Sgt. Michael R. Wood, president of the
Hartford Police Union, which represents the city's 480 officers,
said he believed the community groups who pressured the city to
reconsider its commitment to the 1973 consent decree were ``taking
advantage'' of the Salmon shooting to gain more leverage over the
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure we are out of compliance with the consent
decree,'' Wood said Wednesday. ``I don't think there's any need for
an overseer. Senior management of this department is able to
determine if there is compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution agreed to Tuesday took months to forge. Though
Salmon's death in April prompted some Council members to press the
city manager to do something about the Police Department,
negotiations became more serious once a coalition of 14 community
groups here filed a suit in federal court seeking to have Hartford
held in contempt of court for ignoring the 1973 decree.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, more than two dozen black ministers, and
hundreds of their followers, flooded City Council chambers to press
city officials to adhere to the terms of the consent decree,
Carbone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
