<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FRANKEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 STANLEY FRANKEL, 80, WRITER AND CORPORATE OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stanley Frankel, a journalist, corporate executive
and speechwriter for Democratic presidential candidates, including
Adlai Stevenson, Robert F. Kennedy, Hubert H. Humphrey, George
McGovern and Walter Mondale, died on Nov. 12 in a New York City
hospital. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel, who lived in Scarsdale, died from complications from a
cerebral aneurysm, said his son Stephen Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   Long active in the Democratic Party, Frankel started by working
in Stevenson's campaign for Illinois governor in 1948, and later
worked on his unsuccessful presidential campaigns in 1952 and 1956.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Frankel won a Peabody Award as executive producer of
the television series ``Adlai Stevenson Reports,'' a network
television program.
</P>
<P>
   He then wrote speeches and recruited leading scholars to help
write speeches for other Democratic presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Born on Dec. 8, 1918, in Dayton, Ohio, Frankel attended
Northwestern University, graduating in 1940 as valedictorian.
</P>
<P>
   Serving with the 37th Infantry Division in the Pacific in World
War II, Frankel took part in the liberation of Manila and of about
2,000 U.S. prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to civilian life, Frankel worked for Esquire, Coronet
and This Week magazines before becoming a vice president of
McCall's magazine. He later spent 27 years as vice president for
Ogden Corp., an industrial conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son Stephen of Hastings-on-Hudson, N.Y.,
Frankel is survived by his wife, Irene Baskin Frankel; two other
children, Thomas, of Manhattan, and Nancy Joselson of Mamaroneck,
N.Y., and three grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel gleefully took credit for a stroke of political
gamesmanship at the Democratic National Convention in Atlantic City
in 1964. After a team of Republicans set up a billboard outside the
convention hall picturing their candidate, Barry Goldwater, with
the legend ``In Your Heart, You Know He's Right,'' Frankel and a
few fellow Democrats put up a huge sign directly under it reading,
``Yes _ Extreme Right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
