<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUSD-BELMONT-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. OFFICIALS LOOKING FOR ALTERNATIVES TO CONTAMINATED SCHOOL
SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDITORS: Daily News Staff Writer Rick Orlov contributed to this
story) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- With the fate of the Belmont Learning Center
still unresolved, Mayor Richard Riordan and school board members
have focused on converting a hulking empty post office building
into a downtown high school.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the padlocked Terminal Annex post office has
risen above a slew of other possibilities to become the mayor's and
school board's favored site for a campus in the Belmont attendance
area, district and mayoral sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The 480,000-square-foot historical landmark would provide about
as much classroom space as Belmont, which sits partially completed
atop an oil field seeping potentially deadly and explosive gases.
</P>
<P>
   The two properties are located less than five minutes away from
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been contacted by the mayor and members of the school
board, and they have expressed a significant interest in the
property,'' said Wayne Ratkovich, a partner in the development
consortium handling the complex for the U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is likely that in the near future, we will be offering the
Terminal Annex building and the land on which it sits for sale or
lease. ... We have an agreement with the mayor that there will be
continuing discussions about the school district's interest.''
</P>
<P>
   While Riordan did not respond to specific questions from the
Daily News about the post office building, the mayor said on
Wednesday he believes the school district should begin looking at
another site for a downtown high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complicated issue,'' Riordan said of the Belmont
situation on his monthly ``Ask the Mayor'' radio show on KFWB-AM
(980).
</P>
<P>
   ``In a pure and simple world, I would say yes (to building on
the current site). But, with the politics of this and the
environmental studies, it could be another three to five years to
even begin construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means kids will be waiting three to five years for a
school they need now,'' the mayor said. ``I think we should look
for another solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials close to the mayor confirmed he has been pushing the
idea of using the post office building as an alternative to
Belmont, along with scouting other locations around the city that
could be used as campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor supports the school board in considering all options
that will establish school sites sooner rather than later,''
spokeswoman Jessica Copen said.
</P>
<P>
   School board President Genethia Hayes referred to the Terminal
Annex building as a high priority option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been looking at that,'' Hayes said. ``It is definitely
a high priority proposal for the district in the event that we
decide not to go ahead with completing Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have many sites ready to go so the community around
Belmont gets a new school ASAP.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Ratkovich, there has been a great deal of interest
in the Terminal Annex in recent weeks, including proposals from a
Pasadena arts college and several information technology companies.
Ratkovich would not disclose how much money the Postal Service is
seeking for the property.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Terminal Annex building, LAUSD administrators are
considering converting the district's downtown administrative
headquarters into a campus. There also is preliminary interest in
building schools where the Ambassador Hotel now stands and at the
site of the Pacific Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle in the way of converting the Terminal Annex
building into a school appears to be its landmark status. The
building's designation as a National Historic Place could prevent
the district from making significant renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Constructed under the auspices of President Franklin D.
Roosevelt's New Deal, the Terminal Annex building was declared a
landmark in 1995, shortly before it was padlocked. The complex
served as the city's main post office from 1940 to 1989, when a new
facility opened in South Central Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service continues to use a portion of the 18-acre
property as a distribution and retail center.
</P>
<P>
   According to two board members, who asked not to be named, the
board's decision last week to delay its vote on Belmont until next
month was partially designed to give the district added time to
compile information on the annex.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the school board has indicated they are leaning
toward abandoning Belmont, the nation's costliest high school. By
the board's unanimous decree, the construction site was to be
closed on Tuesday, with no work to resume at least until state
officials can complete environmental testing on the parcel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to need to make some kind of decision on the
future of Belmont in early December,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(2nd take to follow) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
