<HEADER>
A1084 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAUSD-BELMONT-2nd-tak     11-24 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUSD-BELMONT-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  LOS ANGELES: December,'' Hayes said. 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But board member Victoria Castro, a vocal advocate of Belmont,
said she is seeking to put off a vote on the $282 million complex
until the district has worked out ``every last detail'' of building
another school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still support and believe we can construct the Belmont
Learning Center,'' Castro said. ``If the board decides not to go
forward, they cannot decouple that decision from the responsibility
of telling the community what the solution is. And it must be a
viable solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't have an alternative site, there is no rush for a
decision on Belmont. There should be no more false promises to this
community,'' Castro said, referring to the district's failed
attempts to build a high school in the inner city for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Belmont, the five-story Terminal Annex building has been
given a clean bill of health by state environmental officials,
Ratkovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Methane and hydrogen sulfide contamination at Belmont would
require the district to install a $60 million system of vents,
vacuums, blowers and liners under the complex and playing fields to
make the property safe.
</P>
<P>
   A citizens commission narrowly advised the school board last
month to complete construction of the $282 million high school with
the costly technical fix. Muddling the recommendation, the
commission also concluded it would take at least five years to open
Belmont and determined another school could be built on safe ground
for the same price as completing the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the final vote on Belmont, the board is expected
to pursue up to two alternative sites for new schools in the
downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, has told the district
that the state would pick up as much as 80 percent of the tab to
convert the district's headquarters, located at 450 N. Grand Ave.,
into a campus.
</P>
<P>
   Similar funding would likely be available to convert the
Terminal Annex building into a campus.
</P>
<P>
   The state has refused to give the district any more money to
complete Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Ambassador Hotel plan, the district would build a high
school on the rear portion of the abandoned historical landmark's
lot, and a private developer would build a movie theater and retail
shops along Wilshire Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   No details were immediately available with regard to the Pacific
Stock Exchange site, although that scenario is being championed by
state Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, LAUSD Chief Operating Officer Howard Miller, a
real estate attorney, is guiding the board. Miller did not respond
to requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Board member David Tokofsky said all of the options to replace
Belmont ``sound like good places to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Terminal Annex looks like a quick solution to the
overcrowding problems,'' Tokofsky said. ``Ideally, we could put
about 2,500 kids at two schools, rather than all 5,000 in one place
like Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   Any additional classroom space would help reduce massive
overcrowding in the Belmont attendance area and neighboring
inner-city communities. About 2,300 students who live near Belmont
are bused each school day to campuses more than 90 minutes away.
</P>
</TEXT>
