<HEADLINE>
USC'S JUMPY LINE ALSO UNHEALTHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC is approaching its 12th game of the season,
but the offensive line remains full of issues heading into Friday's
contest with Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, it isn't healthy. Starting center Eric Denmon is less
than 100 percent with a sprained ankle. Left tackle Brent McCaffrey
and left guard Donta Kendrick missed Wednesday's practice with the
flu.
</P>
<P>
   If that weren't enough, the line is coming off an atrocious
performance _ from a penalty standpoint _ that included eight false
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, our poise will be better in this game,'' offensive
line coach Steve Greatwood said. ``There was no excuse for it. The
thing that is disappointing is we did a nice job against Washington
State.''
</P>
<P>
   Greatwood was also disappointed because the line was often
fooled offsides by UCLA's voice signals along the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, we worked on that last week,'' Greatwood
said.
</P>
<P>
   Busy secondary: Freshman cornerbacks Darrell Rideaux and Kevin
Arbet should both start against Louisiana Tech because the Bulldogs
often use four or five wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation that Arbet relishes, even with his
inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to pick on me and Darrell,'' Arbet said. ``I
look forward to it. It's a challenge I'll meet head up.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbet did not allow any completions against UCLA, even though he
switched off defending Danny Farmer, Freddie Mitchell and Brad
Melsby.
</P>
<P>
   USC is also preparing to use cornerback Eric Reese and free
safety Troy Polamalu as reserves in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bouncing back: So far, USC coach Paul Hackett has been pleased
with the way the Trojans responded from their victory over UCLA,
and isn't overly concerned about a letdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The practices have been really good,'' Hackett said. ``But now
you spend all the time with your family. All everybody will be
talking about is UCLA. A big part will be how we handle the next 24
hours. I thought we had really good focus and were zeroed in
(Wednesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury's kicking: Hackett said sophomore David Newbury (11 for
19 this season) will kick against Louisiana Tech, although he has
split practice time with junior David Bell this week. But Hackett
also mentioned that the Trojans will have to consider whether to
recruit another kicker, and perhaps a punter, for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to study it real carefully,'' Hackett said. ``We
cannot go through another year with this inconsistency in the
kicking game.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele update: Outside linebacker Markus Steele (bruised stomach
muscle) practiced Wednesday and should be OK, although he will
split playing time with Darryl Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the quarterback: It's not enough that Louisiana Tech
quarterback Tim Rattay is the NCAA's second all-time leading passer
with 12,341 yards, but Bulldog quarterbacks have only been sacked
27 times this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we can get enough pressure on them,'' Hackett
said. ``He doesn't stand there and throw the ball and they've got a
veteran offensive line.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight straight: USC has to deal with another eight-game winning
streak, and it has nothing to do with playing UCLA. Louisiana Tech
(8-2) has won eight straight games since season-opening losses to
No. 1-ranked Florida State (41-7) and No. 24 Texas A&AMP;M (37-17).
</P>
<P>
   It's the fourth-longest winning streak in the nation, and
includes a 29-28 victory over eighth-ranked Alabama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
