<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1086 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-OPERATION-SMILE-II-1S     11-24 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERATION-SMILE-II-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHIRLWIND OF FACIAL SURGERY BY FOREIGN CHARITY LEAVES CHINESE
UPSET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   (CORRECTS ``should'' to ``could'' in 11th graf; ADDS attribution to
5th graf of 2nd take) 
(bl)  
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL with REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ ``I am the father of Patient 088, and I'd like to
express my gratitude but also say I am very dissatisfied,'' wrote
Zhao Kang in a letter to the Plastic Surgery Hospital in Beijing.
Instead of fixing his son's disfiguring cleft lip, as he had
wanted, the surgeons fixed the son's cleft palate, which had not
affected his speech and was not visible.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not Chinese surgeons the farmer was complaining
about. It was a team from the American charity Operation Smile, who
had raised the hopes of many parents like Zhao by bringing in
doctors and offering free surgery for children with cleft palates
and lips.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao's son was among the 245 patients to be chosen, a great
stroke of fortune for a poor farmer who could never afford elective
surgery like this. Most emerged with the normal smile that is
promised by Operation Smile's name. But Zhao's son was among those
whose experience has raised serious questions, in China and in the
United States, about the program's practices.
</P>
<P>
   For the Zhao boy, the problem was the wrong operation; his lip
was only repaired, by Chinese doctors, after the Operation Smile
team left China. But there were many other and often more serious
problems when the 45 volunteers ended six frantic days of surgery,
in which they operated on 188 of the selected children. The
problems included heavy bleeding, repairs that split open, and even
the death of a patient that might have been avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that the operations were crude and hasty and the
surgical skill was _ dare I say _ below that of the surgeons
here,'' said Dr. Li Senkai, vice president of the hospital, China's
pre-eminent plastic surgery hospital, who was in charge of hosting
the group. The high-volume, ``assembly-line'' approach so worried
the hospital's honorary director, Song Ruyao, a well-known expert
on cleft lip and palate surgery, that he refused to come to work
after the first day of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We admire and want to work with Dr. Magee and a project whose
spirit is so full of love and good will,'' said Li. ``But people
still have complaints and we have many ideas of how to improve
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Magee, the plastic surgeon who founded Operation
Smile and serves as its chairman, said in a telephone interview in
Norfolk, Va., where the charity has its headquarters, that he had
no knowledge of the case involving Zhao's son. He said the charity
had not discussed the other problems with the Chinese doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Magee defended the quality of the care being provided. ``It is
not an assembly-line product,'' he said. ``It never has been.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to the Chinese doctors, when Operation Smile
departed, it volunteers left a famous but poor hospital with large
new debts, and its doctors with the task of following up
complications, redoing faulty operations, and calming some angry
families.
</P>
<P>
   The experiences of the Plastic Surgery Hospital, an affiliate of
the Chinese Academy of Medicine, prompted the Ministry of Health to
convene a conference of directors from all six hospitals in China
that had hosted the charity over a decade, only to discover that
many had similar complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors agreed that Chinese hospitals could continue working
with Operation Smile and accepting its charity; one mission went to
Yunnan province earlier this month. But the meeting also concluded
that the charity should coordinate more with local surgeons and be
far more closely supervised by the Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``To ensure the quality of treatment, the level of Operation
Smile's scientific knowledge and expertise should be improved,''
said a 1998 report by Chinese doctors who worked with Operation
Smile. ``Responsibility to the patient should come first. The
quality of the treatment should not be sacrificed to
self-promotion,'' said the report, which was made available to The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Smile said it had not seen the report. ``We have a
long, long history in China in many, many sites,'' said Magee, who
said he had not heard of any Health Ministry meeting or about any
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Cleft lips and palate deformities are relatively common in
China, especially in the countryside, where the condition may
result from marriage of close relatives as well as pollution, say
doctors. Having a cleft lip or palate is rarely life-threatening,
and corrective surgery is generally considered an elective
procedure _ although one that can greatly improve a child's
appearance and speech.
</P>
<P>
   Risks associated with the surgery are low, although they exist.
``In the United States it's extremely uncommon to lose a child, for
a child to die, from cleft lip or palate surgery,'' said Dr.
Marilyn Jones, the president of the American Cleft Palate and
Craniofacial Association.
</P>
<P>
   But Operation Smile has had 16 deaths during its history, three
of them in China. In Beijing a child died just after anesthesia was
induced, without proper monitoring. In the mid-'90s, two children
died during an Operation Smile mission in Shantou in southern
China, said Dr. Li Yu, a surgeon at the university hospital there.
</P>
<P>
   The Plastic Surgery Hospital in Beijing had never had a child
die during cleft lip or palate surgery until Operation Smile,
doctors there said. The hospital's staff was shaken by an egregious
error: Although the hospital possesses and requires the use of
modern equipment to monitor anesthesia during surgery, Operation
Smile decided not to use it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw American-trained anesthesiologists using these
primitive methods, our impression was that they must have developed
these methods for use in remote rural areas,'' said the hospital's
professor of anesthesia. ``We would never use them here, and my
guess is that they would never be used at an American hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   The professor said it is still not clear what killed the
3-year-old adopted boy, from rural Shaanxi Province, although he
said the child's heart was normal and that he suspected an
anesthesia overdose. He added that whatever the cause, a modern
monitoring system would have detected the problem long before the
child went into cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother, who was infertile and recently married for the
second time, had taken the extremely rare step in China of adopting
a handicapped child. She was devastated by his death, doctors said,
and, like several other patients, wanted to sue. Operation Smile
offered her the equivalent of about $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   Magee said he did not know about any offer from the group but
said any gesture was well-meaning. ``Any distortion of that is
ludicrous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the death, the hospital directors shut down the Operation
Smile program for a day and then reluctantly allowed the charity to
re-start surgery, once full monitoring was assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that this is tragic,'' said Magee. He said
that Operation Smile took several measures to improve safety after
the Beijing mission, as it does after all of its missions. ``We are
constantly improving the services we give,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our respect for life and dignity is paramount,'' Magee said.
</P>
<P>
   But death in surgery can be unpredictable, and it is the high
rate of complications of Operation Smile in Beijing that stands
out.
</P>
<P>
   Always thinking big, Operation Smile had planned so many
surgeries during its brief stay in Beijing, that the Plastic
Surgery Hospital decided to provide its own staff for two of the
nine operating rooms to accommodate the overflow. Over five days,
Operation Smile did 188 operations in rooms 1 through 7; Chinese
doctors did 61 operations in rooms 8 and 9. The results were very
different.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study done at the hospital, of the 61 operations
with Chinese surgeons, only two caused any post-operative problems,
in both cases minor bleeding. But over 40 patients under the care
of Operation Smile had serious complications.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the death, more than 30 children's palates split
open; suffered tissue death, or had other problems healing. Of
these, two children went into shock from massive bleeding and, in
the case of 6-month-old Wang Qing, nurses had to donate their own
blood for transfusions, since blood typing had not been performed.
The nurses were universal donors, and the girl was not harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medical textbooks have never recorded such a high complication
rate for this surgery'' said Li of the Plastic Surgery Hospital.
``It is unacceptable from the perspective of both medicine and
modern society.'' And at the meeting called by the Health Ministry,
other hospitals, like the one in Zhaoqing, reported rates that were
higher still.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese doctors also complained that surgeons and
anesthesiologists from Operation Smile rarely saw their young
patients or the parents of the patients outside of the operating
room, creating a situation that led to mishaps like the wrong
surgery being performed on Zhao's son, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child has an examination by a surgeon before,'' said
Magee.
</P>
<P>
   Many surgeons at the hospital felt that Operation Smile failed
to deliver on important promises.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Plastic Surgery Hospital gladly emptied 6 normally
teeming wards to accommodate the program, scheduling little surgery
of their own during the visit. It seemed a worthy cause and an
opportunity to learn from foreign experts.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. charity had promised the hospital professional and
highly qualified plastic surgeons. Instead the seven doctors it
sent proved to be mostly young, inexperienced and non-American,
according to the report the hospital compiled on the mission. In
addition to the two American surgeons, there was one each from
Colombia, Singapore, the Philippines, China and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, hospital officials have calculated that its
association with the well-financed U.S. charity cost it over
$200,000 _ a small fortune to a struggling state hospital which,
despite modern equipment, still houses patients on metal cots in
crumbling wards.
</P>
<P>
   To complete more than 200 operations in such a short time, the
hospital had to call in its own staff to work overtime. After the
volunteers left, it was left to Chinese doctors to take care of the
patients and to re-operate on those like Zhao's son, who had
botched or unsatisfactory operations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated requests for more money, Operation Smile
reimbursed the hospital about $25,000. The hospital failed to meet
the next month's payroll. China's hospitals have lost much of their
state subsidies and have to rely on patient charges to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Magee said he did not know about the specifics of the finances.
``We were there with hard-earned fund-raising dollars,'' he said,
and the vast majority of children were given a chance at a new
life.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hospital's dozens of trained plastic surgeons hope
to collaborate again with Operation Smile, but on very different
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of delegation of 45, which included many
non-professionals, they would like to see a small team of experts,
who would teach their Chinese counterparts new techniques.
</P>
<P>
   They would also like some help with equipment purchases and
financial support for developing a permanent home-grown team of
Chinese surgeons who could offer free surgery themselves. They note
that the hospital surgeons already perform hundreds of cleft lips
and palate surgeries a year on paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that Operation Smile can bring us information on
contemporary medical science and examples of good surgeons,'' Li
said, adding with characteristic Chinese politeness: ``To an
extent, our Chinese surgeons are also qualified to do such work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
