<SLUG> BC-CT-HATE-CRIME-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS AND CIVIC LEADERS MEET TO CONFRONT REPORTS OF BIGOTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILFORD, Conn. _ In church and in City Hall, leaders and
residents of this middle-class shoreline suburb halfway between New
Haven and Bridgeport have been gathering over the last two weeks to
discuss what has become a too-familiar concern in southern
Connecticut: reports of bigotry in their community.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 people, including a panel of local elected
officials, clergy members and grade-school students, met Monday
night at City Hall to voice a variety of emotions stirred up by the
Nov. 11 arrest of a local white couple, who were charged with
making threats and racial slurs against their neighbors, a biracial
couple.
</P>
<P>
   The week before the arrest, a small group of men dressed in the
white robes of the Ku Klux Klan spent several days in town
disseminating literature about their white supremacist
organization, at one point, according to several accounts, stopping
outside the home of the biracial couple. While they broke no laws,
their presence added to a sense of menace here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot, will not tolerate bigotry,'' said Albert J. DeLuca,
minority leader of Milford's Board of Aldermen. He was among a
dozen officials who spoke at Monday night's forum, which was
organized by state Sen. Winthrop Smith Jr., a Republican, as a
chance for elected officials to express their feelings about the
incidents publicly. ``These actions made me angry,'' Smith said.
``This was not the town I was born and raised in.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 16, the Board of Aldermen passed a resolution condemning
acts of bigotry. Two days earlier, an ecumenical service at the
Woodmont United Church of Christ drew almost 300 residents in a
show of support against hate crimes. And a task force is being
organized through the church to examine ways residents can prevent
such incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt that it was important for the community to come
together and take a stand against hate and prejudice,'' said
Woodmont's pastor, the Rev. Paige Besse-Rankin, who organized the
church service. ``We do not want our city to be a place where the
Ku Klux Klan can recruit a single soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Frederick L. Lisman said that there was some touchiness in
Milford over racial issues, dating to 1995, when the federal
government, prompted by the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, sued the city, alleging that it had
discriminated against minorities when it abandoned a plan to build
low-income housing.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also lamented the vitriol that surfaced in several
local races during fall elections; though race was not an issue, he
said the campaigns had a hostile tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see our community end up like so many others,
where people are confrontational,'' he said. ``I want to see people
working to solve problems in a civil manner and treating people
with respect.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two other shoreline cities, Norwalk and Stamford, have also had
recent brushes with bigotry. In August, a bag of medical waste with
a note carrying an anti-Semitic message was left outside a
synagogue in each city, the incidents coming within several days of
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Norwalk has had three other incidents. In October, racist
graffiti was found outside a community center. On Halloween,
headstones at a Jewish cemetery were defaced with anti-Semitic
graffiti. And on Nov. 2, two men fled after a passer-by saw them
preparing to throw Molotov cocktails at the same synagogue where
the medical waste had been found.
</P>
<P>
   Norwalk's mayor, Frank J. Esposito, said that many civic
meetings had been held in response and that police officers had
been stationed around the clock at all synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Stamford, Dannel P. Malloy, said city officials had
taken a variety of steps, including meeting with concerned
citizens. The police are offering tips on security procedures for
any group that asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We react very seriously to this,'' Malloy said. But he and
others said they believed the incidents were unrelated and not part
of a trend.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Leikind, regional director of the Connecticut office of
the Anti-Defamation League, said that although recent incidents had
received wide notoriety, there was ``a steady drumbeat of incidents
that happen.'' He attributed these to a small minority that he said
nevertheless needed to be taken seriously. By and large, however,
he said a rough social consensus continued to make such acts
repellent to most.
</P>
<P>
   This year in Milford, all public school students are taking part
in a new, yearlong program about respecting differences in others.
</P>
<P>
   Savva Savvidis, 13, an eighth grader at East Shore Middle School
who joined in a poetry reading at Monday night's forum, said that
though racism was not an issue at his school, tolerating
differences sometimes was.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our schools,'' he said, ``there's a lot of kids making fun
of other kids because of the way they dress or the way they look,
and it's just dumb.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
