<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-24 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-AFFORDABLE-HOMES-N     11-24 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AFFORDABLE-HOMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG CITY COLUMN: BUMPER CROP OF BEDROOMS AND CLOSETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``It's a real blessing,'' Kathryn Sanders said more
than once as she conducted the tour of her new home. For 16 years,
Ms. Sanders, a special-education teacher at a public school in
Chelsea, had been living in a vintage Lower East Side tenement that
looked nothing like this place.
</P>
<P>
   She and her two children, 13 and 15, had been squeezed into a
railroad flat with one tiny bedroom that barely had room for Ms.
Sanders' bed. The children slept on bunk beds in the living room.
Their new home, a duplex apartment at 13th Street and Avenue A, has
1,300 square feet and three bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are so glad to be getting their own rooms,'' Ms.
Sanders said. ``They're teenagers. They need their space, and
sometimes I need them to have their space.'' She showed her
daughter's room on the first floor and stopped to admire the
closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old apartment there was only one closet for everyone _
one little closet,'' she said. ``When they built those tenements I
guess people had their one good dress and coat. I still can't get
used to all the space here. I walk around and have to pinch
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out the two bathrooms and the closet with the
washer-dryer _ ``No more schlepping to the corner for laundry'' _
and went on marveling at the kind of things that do not cause most
middle-class Americans to give thanks today. But it's easy for a
cramped New Yorker to understand her feelings, especially once you
hear another amazing feature of the apartment: it costs her less
than $1,300 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sanders was one of the 2,000 people in the lottery to buy
the 98 apartments in Del Este Village, a joint project of the city
and a nonprofit group, the New York City Housing Partnership, to
sell homes to people whose household income was less than $70,500
per year. Because the city donated the land and provided, together
with the state, a capital subsidy of $20,000 toward the
construction of her apartment, Ms. Sanders had to pay only $150,000
for it.
</P>
<P>
   As government housing programs go, this one is a bargain not
just for Ms. Sanders but for the city. A conservative might object
to the public subsidy, but it's a relatively cheap way to provide
affordable housing while also putting vacant lots back on the tax
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   A liberal might prefer devoting the money to housing for the
poor, but the result would be many fewer homes. And the
middle-class lottery winners are not the only beneficiaries,
because their old homes, like Ms. Sanders' tiny $500-a-month
rent-stabilized apartment, are freed for others.
</P>
<P>
   But building anything is never easy in New York, and this
project encountered fierce opposition because several community
gardens had to be bulldozed to make room for the apartments. The
neighborhood was plastered with posters showing pictures of an
earthworm and a real-estate developer under the question, ``Which
kind of worm would you rather have in the neighborhood?'' When the
developer, Donald Capoccia of BFC Partners, showed up at a public
hearing, he found his picture on signs emblazoned, ``Wanted for
Rape of Community Gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   The gardeners lost this fight, but they've been winning other
ones recently to keep vacant lots from being developed. The
green-versus-greed theme is good public relations, and there's some
truth to it: a well-maintained garden open to everyone is a
valuable communal good not always provided by the market. But many
community gardens are ramshackle lots, and many are essentially
personal fiefdoms of people who get free private yards during a
severe housing shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never understand some of the gardeners,'' said Capoccia,
who estimated it cost him $250,000 in legal fees to defeat them in
court. ``When it came time to clear the lots, they asked me if I
could delay a few weeks. They said they wanted to transplant some
specimens to their country homes. Their country homes! People with
country homes were fighting an affordable-housing project so they
could have a second garden in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The country squires may not have been representative of the
gardeners' side in the debate, but then, neither were the pictures
of developers representative of the other side. This dispute
ultimately wasn't a conflict between gardeners and developers. It
was a conflict between gardeners and people like the Sanders
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that living room,'' Ms. Sanders said at the end of the
tour. ``this year we'll finally have room for a Christmas tree.
It's funny, but our old apartment never felt like home. Even before
we've moved in, this one does. It's just a real blessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
