u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      11-24 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cowboys putting focus on winning, not Johnson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IRVING _ Miami Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson and Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones have been downplaying Johnson's return to Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   They both say there is mutual admiration and a lack of animosity
between the two. Both want today's focus to be on the Thanksgiving
Day game _ a matchup that means so much for two teams hoping to win
their respective divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect him a lot, and he really is a great coach,'' Jones
said. ``But this is an important game for us because of the
situation we find ourselves in. We've got to bounce back after a
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time Johnson will meet his former boss since
he left in 1994. In 1996, the Dolphins faced the Cowboys in Miami,
a game Dallas won.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of current Cowboys who played under Johnson.
All agree the theme of the day won't revolve around Johnson's
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it makes for a great story about Jimmy's tenure here
and how it all ended, but we're not playing Jimmy,'' quarterback
Troy Aikman said. ``Jimmy is on the sidelines, and I don't pay a
whole lot of attention to any of the coaches, no matter who we are
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Johnson be using this game to motivate the Dolphins, who
at 8-2 are tied for the second-best record in the league?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably telling them this is one team I don't want to
lose to,'' Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith said. ``I can hear him
now. `The trap is set. They're no 5-5 team.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys are a 5-5 team, tied with the New York Giants in
the NFC East. Both teams trail the 6-4 Redskins for the division
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want, you could use it as a mental boost,'' Cowboys
defensive lineman Chad Hennings said. ``Do I? No. I've got enough
on my mind besides worrying about who the opposing coach is.''
</P>
<P>
   Like how they can turn around their season. They've won only one
of their last four games and two of their last seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm worried. Who wouldn't be worried?'' Cowboys coach
Chan Gailey said. ``It's my job to worry. We are capable. We just
haven't done it yet. But I think we have a chance to be a very good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this season, the Cowboys are admitting to a
sense of desperation. After all, this team has lost leads in five
games. They've had to pull off defensive stops at the end in a
couple of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely desperate,'' Hennings said. ``We're in dire
straits right now. That's the attitude we have to take, that we
have to finish off games. I think we've been leading at the half in
almost every game we've played.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the focus won't be on coaches and owners once they step
on the field, it will most definitely be on two starting
quarterbacks who are expected to return from injuries. Aikman
missed the last two games and parts of the two previous after
suffering back-to-back concussions in Indianapolis and Minnesota.
The Cowboys went 1-1 with Jason Garrett as the starter and are 1-3
over that four-game span. Aikman hasn't experienced any headaches
or dizziness for more than a week. He was kept out of Sunday's loss
at Arizona as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins won't name their starting quarterback until just
before game time, but Dan Marino, who has had a pinched nerve in
his neck, has been throwing and analyzing game film for the first
time since getting injured Oct. 17 against New England. Damon
Huard, who suffered a deviated septum last week, led the Dolphins
to a 5-1 record while Marino was sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a pretty good chance,'' Marino said. ``I felt
pretty good. But to tell you that I felt like I have in the past
and at the level that I'm used to, I could say I'm not maybe quite
there yet. But I'm pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino doesn't know how his neck will react to a hit, and the
Cowboys are certain to dole some out. The Cowboys have had 27 sacks
this season, led by defensive end Greg Ellis' 6.5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important whether (Dan is) hurt or not to keep him
healthy,'' guard Kevin Gogan said. ``He's our meal ticket for what
we're trying to get done. I think we're improving as an offensive
line, but it's not just the offensive line, it's the backs and the
tight ends, too. Everyone's got to come together, even if we have
to keep an extra guy in to block to keep our quarterback healthy.
If that's what we have to do, that's what we should do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defense also ranks sixth against the pass and sixth
in total yards. Dallas has 16 interceptions this season, but the
secondary has been decimated by injuries. Cornerbacks Deion Sanders
(hamstring/groin) and Kevin Smith (hamstring), and safety George
Teague (shoulder) are all expected to play despite their injuries.
Cornerback Kevin Mathis (hamstring) is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What could happen is that the Cowboys treat Dan like a young
quarterback and blitz him all the time and see if he can make the
throws he's normally capable of making,'' Miami receiver Oronde
Gadsden said. ``Until he beats them _ then they would probably back
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offense is starting to look healthy again, though
they'll still be missing lineman Larry Allen (knee). The Cowboys
had the No. 1 rushing attack with a healthy Smith, but dropped to
fourth during his absence. Smith, who returned against Arizona less
than two weeks after surgery to repair a broken bone in his right
hand, missed most of two games with the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to me when Troy is out there, he's playing as well as
I've seen him play and, of course, Emmitt is still rushing for a
lot of yards,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest factor in this game could be the home-field
advantage. As Johnson knows, the Cowboys play well on their own
turf, good enough this year for a 4-0 record. They are 1-5 on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is not far from putting it all together,'' Smith
said. ``If we can put it together for four quarters and do it on a
consistent basis, we can get on one heck of a run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-24-99 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
